// AUTO-GENERATED for gi_final from the GI 31-34 + 35-38 delta docs (assemble_gi_final.py). Regenerate, don't hand-edit.

const QUIZ_CONFIG = {"id": "gi_final", "title": "GI Final", "emoji": "🩺"};
const IMAGES = {};
const LO_ANSWERS = {"31_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Dr. Blavo opens by deliberately downscoping the microbiology — \"we've given enough talks on those organisms\" — so the move he wants from you is not a memorized list but a pattern. Every organism collapses into one of three stool behaviors: inflammatory (EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter), secretory (ETEC, Vibrio cholerae), and osmotic (rotavirus, norovirus, EPEC, Giardia). Once you know the pattern, the workup and the fluids follow — so learn the buckets, not the encyclopedia.", "why": "E. coli O157:H7 — it causes HUS, and unlike the rest it is made worse by antibiotics, so the stakes of recognizing it are highest."}, "31_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. For diarrhea, the history is the diagnostic test — Blavo's whole \"rote-to-rationale\" message is that you ask each question for a reason. The single most useful question is the character of the stool: loose, watery, mucoid, bloody, oily, or foul-smelling. Each adjective points somewhere.", "why": "Blood/leukocytes (inflammatory), stool volume (voluminous = secretory), and fat/odor or response to fasting (osmotic/malabsorptive) sort almost every case."}, "31_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. There is no rigid formal classification, but the working schema gastroenterologists carry — and the one that organizes your whole differential — is inflammatory vs non-inflammatory, with non-inflammatory splitting into secretory and osmotic. The classification is the differential diagnosis.", "why": "Secretory — an enterotoxin is actively driving secretion, so the lumen stays wet even without ingested solute; an osmotic diarrhea would have slowed or stopped with fasting."}, "31_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Most diarrhea is mild, self-limited, and needs no workup at all — observation, fluids, and anticipatory guidance. You investigate only when a red flag raises the stakes: moderate/severe dehydration, an ill child or elderly patient, bloody or voluminous stool, duration >48 h, high fever, severe abdominal pain, recent antibiotics, or an immunocompromised host.", "why": "You choose the single study that confirms a named hypothesis (the red-flag pattern points to it), rather than ordering a broad panel and hoping something turns up."}, "31_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Management is mostly rehydration, because most infectious diarrhea is self-limited — the body heals itself if you keep it in a workable fluid and electrolyte state. Blavo's childhood memory of a cholera outbreak in Ghana, and his later cholera intervention in Haiti, anchor the stakes: secretory losses can kill through dehydration even when the patient doesn't look classically \"septic.\" Oral rehydration is first-line.", "why": "Glucose drives sodium-coupled absorption (SGLT1) so water is reabsorbed even while the gut secretes; Coca-Cola's glucose-to-sodium ratio is backwards and hyperosmolar, so it pulls water into the lumen instead."}, "33_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Endoscopy for a GI bleed turns on two questions: is the patient hemodynamically stable or unstable, and where is the source. Unstable patients (hypotensive, tachycardic, syncope) get volume and, if exsanguinating, unmatched blood — you resuscitate before you scope.", "why": "A fast upper bleed (e.g., duodenal ulcer) presents as maroon stool from below, and unlike most lower sources you can actually stop it endoscopically — so the top is scoped first."}, "33_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Beyond the standard EGD and colonoscopy, three scopes are each defined by what they can do. The trick is to tag each one diagnostic, therapeutic, or both.", "why": "EUS — it stages and biopsies the mass through the gastric wall, assesses vascular involvement and nodes in one step; percutaneous biopsy risks tract seeding and undersampling."}, "33_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Upper endoscopy (EGD) sees from the oropharynx to the second portion of the duodenum. The biggest indication is GERD — and the reason to scope reflux is to look for Barrett's esophagus, a silent change in the lining.", "why": "Whether liquids get stuck too: solids-only points to a structural narrowing; solids-and-liquids points to a motility disorder (work it up with barium first)."}, "33_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Colonoscopy diagnoses the colorectal differential and removes polyps, but for bleeding its therapeutic reach is limited. The high-yield separations are the diverticular pair and the IBD patterns.", "why": "Diverticulosis — acute, painless, significant hematochezia over 50 that self-limits ~80% of the time; endoscopic therapy for lower bleeds is limited, so management is largely supportive after excluding an upper source."}, "33_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Indications run through the other LOs; the complications and contraindications are the testable headlines. ERCP is the most dangerous procedure gastroenterologists perform, with an overall complication rate around 10%. Its signature complication is post-ERCP pancreatitis — you are working at the tiny opening where the bile and pancreatic ducts meet, so even a flawless operator can inflame the pancreas.", "why": "ERCP — about a 10% complication rate, and its signature complication is post-ERCP pancreatitis from manipulating the shared bile/pancreatic-duct opening."}, "33_6": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Schneider calls screening his primary responsibility — and the single highest-yield block. The logic is the adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence: precancerous adenomatous polyps become cancer over roughly a decade, so we scope to find and remove them.", "why": "Colonoscopy is offered FIRST and is the only test that also prevents cancer by removing polyps; a stool test (annual FIT) is for patients who decline colonoscopy — it detects cancer but doesn't prevent it, and Cologuard is not equivalent."}, "35_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar anchors the entire lecture on one picture: the parietal cell and the H⁺/K⁺-ATPase proton pump that does the actual work of secreting hydrogen ions into the gastric lumen in exchange for K⁺. Everything you study after this — every drug class — is just a different way of getting at that pump, so it pays to fix the wiring now. Four signals converge on it: three stimulate, one restrains.", "why": "ON: acetylcholine (M3), histamine (H2), and gastrin (CCK-B) all activate kinases that drive the H+/K+-ATPase. DOWN: PGE2 (EP receptors) inhibits secretion and is cytoprotective."}, "35_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This is the workhorse LO — Parmar marches one class per slide on a fixed template (mechanism / uses / adverse effects), and he is explicit that you should learn the class logic rather than memorize every interchangeable agent. The organizing spine is a potency ladder: antacids neutralize, H2RAs block a receptor, PPIs and PCABs hit the pump itself. Climb the ladder and acid suppression deepens.", "why": "Antacid (transient neutralization) < H2RA (~60-70%, tachyphylaxis) < PPI (>90%, irreversible) < PCAB (reversible K-competition). Signature AEs: Al/Mg bowel shift, cimetidine antiandrogen/CYP, PPI B12-Mg-fracture-C.diff, misoprostol pregnancy CI."}, "35_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The whole point of this LO is one comparison: H2RA versus PPI. Parmar drew the contrast explicitly in numbers, and the exam loves it because the two drugs sit on the same pathway but act at different points — a receptor versus the pump.", "why": "The PPI wins on potency (>90% vs ~60-70%) and durability (irreversible pump block, no tachyphylaxis). The long-term cost is decreased B12 bioavailability, because the acid that normally frees B12 from dietary protein is suppressed."}, "35_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar flagged the interaction material directly — “focus from exam point of view, this is important” — while warning that the full list reads as an unmemorizable laundry. The way through is to sort by mechanism: enzyme inhibition (CYP), a change in gastric pH, and physical binding/chelation. Get the three buckets and any specific pair is predictable.", "why": "CYP inhibition: cimetidine (warfarin/diazepam/eletriptan) and omeprazole/esomeprazole + clopidogrel (CYP2C19). Raised gastric pH: PPIs impairing digoxin/azole absorption. Binding: sucralfate + quinolones, and antacids chelating tetracyclines/iron — space dosing 2-4 h."}, "35_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar time-boxed this to a few minutes but framed it as high-stakes — H. pylori is a common infection linked to peptic ulcer disease and an established risk factor for gastric adenocarcinoma and MALT lymphoma. The cancer link is the reason eradication is taken seriously, and the reason the rules tightened in the 2024 guidelines.", "why": "14-day Optimized BQT (PPI + tetracycline + metronidazole + bismuth) is gold standard; clarithromycin was dropped for resistance, with PCAB-dual and rifabutin-triple as alternatives. After 14 days, confirmation of eradication (fecal antigen, urea breath test, or biopsy) is mandatory."}, "35_6": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar builds this whole lecture as a receptor map, so the first move is to learn the categories, not the individual drugs. Nausea and vomiting are integrated at the chemoreceptor trigger zone (CTZ) / area postrema and the vomiting center, and four neurotransmitter-receptor pairs feed them: ACh (M1), histamine (H1), substance P (NK1), and serotonin (5-HT3). Each pair has a drug class that blocks it. Two adjunct families — cannabinoids (CB1 agonists) and benzodiazepines (GABA-A modulators) — plus dexamethasone and olanzapine round out the rescue/adjuvant tier.", "why": "ACh/M1 (scopolamine), histamine/H1 (meclizine, dimenhydrinate), substance P/NK1 (the -pitants), and serotonin/5-HT3 (the -setrons) — the four receptors that organize the entire antiemetic toolkit."}, "35_7": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The mechanism story is the heart of the lecture, and Parmar tells it as one vomiting-reflex framework: stimuli converge on the CTZ/area postrema and the vomiting center in the floor of the fourth ventricle, and each antiemetic class simply blocks one input. Get the framework first and every drug's MOA is just \"which receptor does it sit on.\"", "why": "The immediate episode is serotonin acting at 5-HT3 (acute phase) — covered by a setron; the day-3 episode is substance P acting at NK1 (delayed phase) — covered by a -pitant. Highly emetogenic regimens combine both plus dexamethasone."}, "35_8": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Therapeutic uses cluster around a short vocabulary you'll see repeated on every slide — CINV (chemotherapy-induced), PONV (postoperative), RINV (radiation-induced), motion sickness, and gastroparesis. Because the indications overlap so heavily, the exam discriminates by adverse effect: each class has a signature toxicity, and that's where Parmar spends his emphasis.", "why": "Both block D2 and cause EPS, but metoclopramide's boxed warning is irreversible tardive dyskinesia (cap therapy at 12 weeks), while droperidol's is QT prolongation/torsades (mandatory 12-lead ECG before and 2-3 hours after dosing)."}, "35_9": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Two interaction themes carry this LO, and Parmar flags both as testable: the Parkinson's contraindication that follows every dopamine blocker, and the CYP-P450 interactions of the NK1 antagonists — which he ties directly to COMLEX drug-interaction questions after talking to a student who took the exam.", "why": "Aprepitant inhibits CYP3A4, the enzyme that clears dexamethasone, so dexamethasone accumulates and its dose must be reduced; rolapitant inhibits CYP2D6 instead, leaving CYP3A4-mediated dexamethasone metabolism untouched, so no adjustment is needed."}, "37_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Rose opens the way an old-school trauma surgeon does: before he lays a hand on the patient he pictures what's going on inside — skin, fascia, muscle, and peritoneum stripped away, the organs laid bare. The whole lecture rests on this. For trauma the single most useful map is the four quadrants, because the quadrant plus the mechanism tells you which organs are at risk. (The finer nine-region map — epigastric, umbilical, hypogastric, and the paired hypochondriac, lumbar, and iliac regions — is for localizing abdominal pain, not trauma.)", "why": "Picturing the organs by quadrant lets the mechanism predict the injury: knowing what is fixed vs mobile, and what sits in the struck quadrant, tells you which organs to look for before any imaging."}, "37_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. If Rose makes one point in this lecture, it is ultrasound: that's the thing that's going to make all the difference. The bedside FAST exam (Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma) is fast, cheap, repeatable, and increasingly done on a phone probe — he told the class to chase the ultrasound teams in the ED and learn it. FAST hunts for free fluid (blood), air, and gross organ injury in the liver, kidneys, and spleen, and the density of the fluid even distinguishes blood from serous fluid. The volume of blood in the abdomen can be estimated from it.", "why": "Because stability — not the FAST result — drives disposition: the unstable patient is exsanguinating and goes straight to the OR, while the one who responds to crystalloid has bought the time for a CT and a trial of observation."}, "37_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The mechanism tells you what to look for, so name it. Blunt / compression (the common one) drives organs against the spine and breaks ribs over the spleen and liver. Penetrating (stab, gunshot) injures along its trajectory — and the trajectory, not just the entry point, is what matters: a wound below the nipple line can cross the diaphragm into the abdomen because the diaphragm rides up to the nipples on expiration. Crush is severe compression (steering wheel, a wall). Iatrogenic injury is caused by us during an operation. Blast injury drives foreign bodies inward and combines penetrating with crush.", "why": "The path determines which organs the object actually crossed; a wound's entry point can be misleading, since a sub-nipple or angled trajectory may cross the diaphragm or track retroperitoneally and spare or strike organs far from the entry site."}, "37_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This is the heart of the lecture, and the spleen is its center. The spleen is the most frequently injured organ in blunt abdominal trauma and the most common reason for splenectomy in the U.S. Its capsule is paper-thin and its attachments (gastrosplenic ligament, attachments to the diaphragm) tear easily. Injury comes from penetrating, blunt, or iatrogenic mechanisms — and isolated splenic injury occurs in only about 30% of cases, so when you find a hurt spleen, look for the stomach, left kidney, pancreas, and ribs too.", "why": "The grade encodes laceration depth and parenchymal/vascular involvement, which is exactly what dictates management: splenic grades I–III can be repaired or observed (especially in stable patients and children, to avoid OPSI), while IV–V — crush, bisection, hilar, or shattered — are not repairable and require splenectomy."}, "37_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Rose closes fast and by anecdote, so keep this tight. The pancreas is a crush injury: lying retroperitoneally across the spine, a focal midline blow can crush or even transect it against the vertebral column — his garbage-truck case bisected the pancreas right over the spine, repaired with a Roux-en-Y pancreaticojejunostomy. Work it up with amylase and lipase (also checked in lavage fluid), see it on CT/ultrasound, and use ERCP to define the ductal anatomy; expect severe back pain because there's no room in the retroperitoneum. Thoracoabdominal and pelvic trauma in a crashing multi-trauma patient is a team approach through a thoracoabdominal incision, working chest and abdomen at once.", "why": ""}, "38_1": {"answer": "ANATOMY FIRST. Moljo built the whole lecture around a single ED vignette — a 68-year-old woman with three days of left-lower-quadrant pain, low-grade fever and chills — and her one repeated instruction is to start with anatomy: \"for the abdominal exam… always start with anatomy.\" Name what lives in the painful quadrant (sigmoid colon, ovary, bladder) and the history questions write themselves. The classic tell is constant LLQ pain with fever; ask too about timing, change in bowel habits, urinary symptoms, and — in a woman — gynecologic causes, which is why she argued the declined pelvic exam still leaves a real gap (an ovarian source can masquerade as colonic pain). Notice the exam targets recognition here, not deep recall — you are pattern-matching a presentation, not memorizing a checklist.", "why": ""}, "38_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The workup runs on one idea Moljo built into a quiz slide: each test answers a specific question, and you order it to confirm a suspicion rather than to fish. The lab panel sorts the differential — CBC (infection? anemia from a GI bleed?), CMP (diabetes, electrolytes, and crucially renal function before contrast), CRP/ESR (inflammation), urinalysis and culture (UTI, the LLQ mimic), HCG (pregnancy in any woman of childbearing age), and blood cultures if she looks septic. Two of those — the CMP renal check and the HCG — exist specifically to make it safe to give contrast.", "why": "Choose a water-soluble contrast medium. If it leaks through a perforation it is harmlessly absorbed, whereas leaked barium causes barium peritonitis — a severe chemical peritonitis."}, "38_3": {"answer": "THE DEFINITIONS LADDER. The whole LO turns on keeping four terms straight, so climb the ladder deliberately. A diverticulum is a single sac-like outpouching of colonic mucosa through a weak point in the muscular wall; diverticula is just the plural. DiverticulOSIS is the presence of diverticula — often asymptomatic. DiverticulITIS is inflammation of a diverticulum, which is then subdivided into uncomplicated versus complicated (abscess, fistula, obstruction, or free perforation). Diverticular disease is the umbrella term for clinically significant, symptomatic disease — including diverticulitis, diverticular bleeding, and segmental colitis. The exam loves to swap osis and itis on you, so anchor it: -osis = the pouches, -itis = the pouches inflamed.", "why": "Diverticulum = a single colonic outpouching; diverticulosis = their presence (often asymptomatic); diverticulitis = inflammation of one (uncomplicated/complicated); diverticular disease = the symptomatic umbrella. A colonic diverticulum is a pseudodiverticulum because it herniates only mucosa/submucosa, not all wall layers."}, "38_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW — UNCOMPLICATED VS COMPLICATED. Every management decision forks on one split: uncomplicated diverticulitis (inflammation only) is managed medically, often outpatient; complicated disease (abscess, perforation, obstruction, fistula) needs a more aggressive, usually inpatient and sometimes surgical approach. The modern, high-yield shift lives on the uncomplicated side — and the entire complication ladder lives on the other.", "why": "Antibiotics are reserved for complicated disease or high-risk hosts (major comorbidity, immunocompromise, immunomodulating drugs, systemic disturbance). A fluoroquinolone (or TMP-SMX) does not cover anaerobes, so it must be paired with metronidazole; amoxicillin-clavulanate covers both alone."}, "39_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Alcohol is the disease Schneider opens with because it is everywhere — implicated in over 50% of liver-related deaths, contributing to 250,000 deaths a year and $3 billion in health-care cost. But the paradox he wants you to hold is that most people who abuse alcohol never get severe liver disease — only about 20% develop alcoholic hepatitis, cirrhosis, or both. So the lecture is really about who tips over, how you spot them on labs, and how the body handles ethanol in the first place.", "why": "Low platelets and an elevated PT/INR together call cirrhosis off the labs: portal hypertension enlarges the spleen, and the hypersplenic spleen sequesters platelets, while the failing liver underproduces the vitamin-K-dependent clotting factors II, VII, IX, and X, prolonging the PT/INR."}, "39_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Schneider opens his 'Hit Parade' of chronic liver diseases by telling you exactly how to study them — sort each one by who gets it, how it presents, the one diagnostic serology if any, and the treatment. Primary biliary cholangitis is the easiest to pin down: a cholestatic disease of middle-aged women with a single near-perfect antibody. (A naming note: he learned it as primary biliary cirrhosis for a career and now teaches it as primary biliary cholangitis — the deck still shows both, but 'cholangitis' is the current name because most patients never reach cirrhosis.)", "why": "The antibody is the antimitochondrial antibody (AMA), positive in 95% of PBC. The rheumatologist gets there first because PBC travels with other autoimmune diseases (Sjögren, CREST, RA): chasing one of those, they order a broad panel, AMA lights up, and the patient arrives already labeled."}, "39_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Schneider promised this one would be 'super fun' and that 'you'll get pimped on it by everybody' — translation: high-yield, learn it cold. Hereditary hemochromatosis is the disease of too much iron absorbed. It is autosomal recessive on chromosome 6, carries two classic mutations — C282Y and H63D — and is the most common single-gene inherited disorder in the white US population (about 1 in 10 are carriers, 1 in 200–300 homozygous). A 1980s genetic survey of an entire Kodak factory turned up iron overload everywhere among old-stock Caucasians — that is how common the gene is.", "why": "Excess iron is absorbed in the gut (2–4 vs 1 mg/day), accumulates over decades with no excretory escape, and deposits in every organ. Before cirrhosis, phlebotomy clears the load and prognosis is excellent; once cirrhosis develops it is irreversible and carries a 120× HCC risk — so catching HHC pre-cirrhosis changes the whole outcome."}, "39_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Wilson disease is the copper twin of hemochromatosis — and Schneider builds the whole LO on the contrast. It is autosomal recessive on chromosome 13, with over 100 mutations, which makes genetic testing less useful and the clinical presentation highly variable. Where HHC is a disease of the 4th–5th decade, Wilson is the young person's disease (median presentation 12–23, oldest diagnosed at 58). Michael J. Fox, diagnosed with young-onset Parkinson's, was famously worked up for Wilson's — the right reflex, even though he did not have it.", "why": "The copper defect is in excretion, not deficiency: absorption is normal but biliary excretion is decreased, so copper backs up into blood and urine. Ceruloplasmin ends up low because it is consumed by the disordered copper handling — a consequence, not the cause; a high level actually excludes Wilson."}, "39_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Schneider closes the Hit Parade with three diseases at breadth, not depth — learn each by its one signature. Autoimmune hepatitis (AIH) attacks hepatocytes; primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) attacks large bile ducts and lives next to IBD; alpha-1 antitrypsin (A1AT) hits liver AND lung. He warned that fourth-year students chronically blur the bile-duct diseases and forget the antibodies — so the antibodies and the PBC-vs-PSC split are the durable discriminators here.", "why": "Autoimmune hepatitis needs urgent steroids (it mimics viral hepatitis but can be fatal); PSC is diagnosed by ERCP with no serology ('chain of lakes' in a man with IBD); alpha-1 antitrypsin makes you think lungs — early emphysema in a non-smoker — as much as liver."}, "39_6": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Schneider calls this the most common cause of liver disease you will see in your career — and he means it: an estimated 100 million Americans (~25% of the population) have fatty liver, and in the U.S. it is arguably the #1-2 cause of cirrhosis, hepatocellular carcinoma, and liver transplant. The nomenclature changed to reflect the real driver: NAFLD is now MASLD (metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease) and NASH is now MASH. The whole topic is the metabolic twin of the alcohol story — two roads to a fatty liver.", "why": "The diagnosis is MASLD (metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease, formerly NAFLD) in a textbook metabolic-syndrome patient; the single discriminator is the transaminase ratio — her ALT > AST (78 vs 55) is the non-alcoholic pattern, whereas alcohol would have shown AST > ALT."}, "41_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar runs this lecture as a two-part drug-class spine — laxatives first, antidiarrheals second — and the single most useful thing you can do is build the category map before you learn a single mechanism. He said it plainly and repeatedly: he is not expecting you to remember the doses; he wants you to know which class a drug belongs to, how it works, and its one signature adverse effect. Laxatives start with a definition — drugs that accelerate fecal passage or decrease fecal consistency, used primarily for constipation — and the recurring caution that they treat the symptom, not the underlying cause, so undiagnosed abdominal pain, IBD, or obstruction must be excluded first.", "why": "The spine is the two category maps: four laxative buckets (bulk-forming, softener/lubricant, osmotic, stimulant, plus the severe-constipation secretagogues) and four antidiarrheal buckets (opioid-antimotility, antisecretory, bile-salt resins, probiotics) — each agent slotted to its class with its mechanism and signature adverse effect."}, "41_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This is the deepest LO of the lecture — every drug slide leads with Mechanism of action, and Parmar spends most of his minutes here. The trick is to see that all the laxatives are variations on getting water into the stool and all the antidiarrheals on keeping it in the body; the testable detail is by what molecular route. Work down the laxative buckets first, then cross to the antidiarrheals.", "why": "Saline laxatives pull water in by poorly absorbed ions raising luminal osmotic pressure; lactulose by colonic bacteria fermenting it to organic acids (with ammonia trapping); linaclotide by agonizing guanylate cyclase-C to raise cGMP and secrete Cl-/HCO3-. The route is tested because it predicts the use and the adverse effects — lactulose's ammonia-trapping gives its hepatic-encephalopathy use, and GC-C secretion gives the diarrhea risk."}, "41_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Every drug slide carries therapeutic uses and adverse effects in parallel, and the exam pattern Parmar coaches is a drug-matching one: which agent for which condition, and which signature AE flags which agent. The organizing move is to learn one headline indication and one signature toxicity per drug, because that pairing is what a vignette keys off. Below, the high-emphasis ones.", "why": "Chronic stimulant-laxative (senna/anthraquinone) abuse is flagged by melanosis coli — benign brownish-black colonic-mucosa pigment from lipofuscin (plus cathartic colon, the lost-motility partner). The somatostatin analog octreotide is flagged by cholelithiasis, gallstones from the biliary stasis and fat malabsorption it causes."}, "41_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The contraindications here are flagged hard because they are the drug-matching traps a vignette is built to spring. The pattern to carry: for each agent, one setting where giving it is dangerous. A 'which drug do you withhold' question is far more likely than a dosing question. Below are the four that recur.", "why": "Antimotility agents are forbidden in infectious/inflammatory diarrhea (C. difficile, IBD, bloody/febrile stools) — risk of toxic megacolon and sepsis. Eluxadoline is forbidden in sphincter-of-Oddi dysfunction/pancreatitis/biliary obstruction (and >3 drinks/day). Bismuth is forbidden in children with viral illness (Reye, from the salicylate). Mineral oil is forbidden in aspiration-risk patients (aspiration pneumonia)."}, "41_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This LO is a discrete rationale trio, and the unifying idea is that these three agents control diarrhea by treating the underlying disease, not by braking the gut. Sulfasalazine and glucocorticoids quiet inflammatory bowel disease; octreotide shuts off tumor hormone secretion. Match each to the disease it actually treats and the question answers itself.", "why": "Sulfasalazine treats ulcerative colitis (its bacterially released 5-ASA is the anti-inflammatory); glucocorticoids treat moderate-to-severe IBD flares (UC and Crohn's) by reducing cytokine-driven inflammation; octreotide treats secretory diarrhea from neuroendocrine tumors (carcinoid, VIPoma) and refractory CID by inhibiting tumor hormone secretion. Each controls diarrhea by treating its disease driver."}, "42_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This is the high-yield heart of the lecture, and Machini handed you the organizing trick on a single slide he put in red and double-starred — he told the class 'I want you to know this slide' and that your board exam pulled two questions from it. The trick is one sort: conjugation. The first three diseases — Crigler-Najjar I, Crigler-Najjar II, and Gilbert — are UNCONJUGATED (a problem making bilirubin water-soluble), and the last two — Dubin-Johnson and Rotor — are CONJUGATED (a problem getting already-conjugated bilirubin out of the cell). Get that boundary and the rest is detail. All five are autosomal recessive.", "why": "The first sort is conjugation: CN-I, CN-II, and Gilbert are unconjugated UGT1A1 (gene 2q37) defects; Dubin-Johnson and Rotor are conjugated. The two conjugated ones are separated by the black liver and the inverted 1:3 coproporphyrin ratio of Dubin-Johnson versus Rotor's absent pigment and ~5x total coproporphyrin."}, "42_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The whole vascular block hangs on one anatomical fact Machini drilled — the liver has a dual blood supply, the portal vein plus the hepatic artery — so losing one channel is usually buffered by the other and the liver rarely truly infarcts. When flow does fail, it is the hepatocytes farthest from the oxygenated inflow — the centrilobular (zone 3) cells — that die first. Frame the disorders by where flow is compromised: impaired inflow (portal vein), intrahepatic (cirrhosis/sinusoidal), and outflow (hepatic vein, i.e. Budd-Chiari) — that Robbins grid predicts the whole presentation.", "why": "The dual supply (portal vein + hepatic artery) means loss of one channel is buffered, so true infarction is rare. When flow does fail, the centrilobular (zone 3) hepatocytes — farthest from the oxygenated periportal inflow — are most vulnerable and die first, which is why zone-3 necrosis is the hallmark of both shock liver and infarction."}, "42_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Machini compressed this into the last few minutes, but the anchor is simple: Budd-Chiari syndrome is hepatic-vein OUTFLOW obstruction — thrombosis of the major hepatic veins (AKA hepatic vein thrombosis, a congestive hepatopathy). Obstruct more than two hepatic veins and blood can't leave the liver, producing the triad of hepatomegaly, ascites, and liver dysfunction. It is the outflow end of the vascular spectrum — contrast it with portal vein thrombosis, the inflow end (LO 42.4).", "why": "Budd-Chiari obstructs the hepatic vein OUTFLOW (more than two major veins). That one fact predicts a dark, congested, enlarged liver with ascites grossly, and centrilobular (zone 3) congestion progressing to necrosis and fibrosis histologically — because blood backs up rather than failing to arrive."}, "42_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Portal vein thrombosis (PVT) is narrowing or blockage of the portal vein by clot — the INFLOW end of the vascular spectrum, the mirror image of Budd-Chiari's outflow block. Machini gave the class one anchor he called 'the only one point here you should know': there is NO necrosis — only inflammation, hepatocellular atrophy, and sinusoidal congestion. The reason is the recurring theme of this whole lecture — the liver's dual blood supply means the hepatic artery keeps the tissue perfused even when portal inflow is blocked, so cells atrophy but do not die.", "why": "The one point is that portal vein thrombosis produces NO necrosis — only inflammation, hepatocellular atrophy, and sinusoidal congestion. The liver's dual blood supply means the hepatic artery keeps the tissue perfused when portal inflow is blocked, so hepatocytes atrophy but do not die."}, "43_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Alcohol is the dominant liver disease Machini teaches — he said it causes more than 60% of chronic liver disease and that the US is one of the top three alcohol-consuming countries. The key is one arrow with three sequential lesions: steatosis (fatty change) -> alcoholic steatohepatitis -> fibrosis/cirrhosis. If the disease is from alcohol it is alcoholic liver disease (ALD); if the identical fatty morphology occurs without alcohol it is non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD), whose drivers are obesity, insulin resistance, type 2 diabetes, and metabolic syndrome. Alcohol also drives 40-50% of cirrhosis deaths, and the natural history thins out as it advances: ~95% of heavy drinkers develop fatty liver, ~20% alcoholic hepatitis, ~15% cirrhosis, and hepatocellular carcinoma eventually arises in about 15% of alcoholic cirrhotics.", "why": "The three lesions in order are steatosis (reversible fatty change), alcoholic steatohepatitis, and fibrosis/cirrhosis. The middle lesion, steatohepatitis, is defined on biopsy by the triad of hepatocyte ballooning (hydropic degeneration), Mallory-Denk bodies (twisted-rope cytokeratin 8/18 aggregates), and neutrophil infiltration."}, "43_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Machini flagged this slide explicitly — 'I saw a question in the board from it.' Two enzymes do the work and you must keep them straight. Alcohol dehydrogenase (ADH) handles step one in the cytosol: ethanol -> acetaldehyde. Then aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH) handles step two in the mitochondria: acetaldehyde -> acetate, finally oxidized to CO2 and water. The mnemonic order: alcohol dehydrogenase first, aldehyde dehydrogenase second — substrate names track the enzyme names.", "why": "ADH oxidizes ethanol to acetaldehyde, then ALDH oxidizes acetaldehyde to acetate (ultimately CO2 and water). Both steps generate NADH, raising the NADH/NAD ratio, which simultaneously increases fatty-acid synthesis and decreases fatty-acid oxidation, so triglyceride accumulates and the liver becomes fatty."}, "43_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Machini put the definition in red: hear cirrhosis and think three things — (1) abnormal nodule formation, (2) fibrosis, and (3) loss of the normal liver architecture. He framed it as a sequela, not a disease itself — the common endpoint of hepatitis, steatohepatitis, biliary disease, and others (alcohol in the US; schistosomiasis and parasites in much of the world). Pathologically it advances through fibrosis (excess collagen types I and III made by hepatic stellate/ITO cells, driven by TNF-alpha, TGF-beta, and IL-1 from Kupffer cells, with inflammation and regenerative nodules) and is partly reversible (regression) if the insult stops.", "why": "Cirrhosis is defined by three features: nodule formation, fibrosis, and loss of architecture. The two size subtypes are micronodular (Laennec/alcoholic) - uniform nodules up to ~3 mm separated by thin passive septa - and macronodular (post-necrotic, usually non-alcoholic) - larger nodules over 3 mm separated by wider scars."}, "43_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Machini said he color-coded the slide on purpose — 'I want you to remember in what disease, what color the liver will have.' The gross color of a cirrhotic liver is a direct recall handle for its cause. Yellow = alcoholic fatty cirrhosis (the fat itself tints the liver yellow and greasy). Rusty / dark brown = hemochromatosis (deposited iron). Enlarged and green = chronic biliary obstruction (retained bile pigment). One look at the specimen narrows the differential before any stain.", "why": "Yellow points to alcoholic fatty cirrhosis (triglyceride/fat). Rusty-brown points to hemochromatosis (deposited iron/hemosiderin). Enlarged and green points to chronic biliary obstruction (retained bile pigment)."}, "43_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Acute liver failure (ALF, fulminant) produces hepatic encephalopathy within ~6 months of diagnosis ('altered mental status and coagulopathies'); hepatocellular necrosis begins in the central zone and spreads toward the portal tracts. Chronic liver failure (CRF) follows repeated bouts and is mostly tied to cirrhosis (necrosis, inflammation, fibrosis), with HCC the usual cause of death. The morphologic clue that distinguishes them: in acute failure the liver is initially enlarged and then shrinks dramatically, and serum transaminases decline as viable hepatocytes are lost.", "why": "Zone 1 is periportal (phosphorus, eclampsia), zone 2 mid-zonal (yellow fever), zone 3 centrilobular (ischemia, acetaminophen, CCl4). Acetaminophen is the #1 US cause of acute liver failure (~50%) and hits zone 3 for its low oxygen and high P450. The acute-liver-failure triad is jaundice, coagulopathy (INR >1.5), and encephalopathy."}, "43_6": {"answer": "OVERVIEW (background — full LFT lecture is Lec 48). Machini gave a single orientation slide: order liver labs by what they ask. To check hepatocyte integrity (are the cells intact?) order the cytosolic enzymes that leak when cells die — AST, ALT, and LDH. To check biliary excretory function (is bile flowing?) order serum bilirubin (total = unconjugated + conjugated; direct = conjugated only), urine bilirubin, serum bile acids, and the canalicular enzymes alkaline phosphatase (ALP) and gamma-glutamyl transpeptidase (GGT). To check synthetic (hepatocyte) function order what the liver makes — serum albumin and the clotting times PT and PTT (the liver makes most coagulation factors — fibrinogen, prothrombin, factors V, VII, IX, X). Keep this as a filing system; the detail comes in Lec 48.", "why": ""}, "43_7": {"answer": "JAUNDICE — THREE PHASES, TWO CONJUGATION CLASSES. Jaundice is yellow discoloration of sclera/skin from elevated bilirubin; clinically visible when bilirubin reaches ~2.5 mg/dL (normal 0.3-1.2). Sort it by location: prehepatic (before the liver — excess RBC breakdown/hemolysis, unconjugated), hepatic (in the liver — hepatocellular dysfunction/intrahepatic cholestasis), and posthepatic (after the liver — obstruction of bile egress, conjugated). Unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia comes from increased production, decreased uptake, or decreased conjugation; conjugated from hepatocellular dysfunction or obstruction of intra-/extrahepatic bile flow.", "why": "Jaundice is prehepatic (hemolysis, unconjugated), hepatic (hepatocellular/cholestasis), or posthepatic (obstruction, conjugated), visible at ~2.5 mg/dL. The cascade: a failing hepatocyte cannot clear ammonia, so it crosses the BBB into astrocytes, becomes glutamine, raises osmotic pressure, and swells the astrocytes (Alzheimer type II) into cerebral edema - the cause of death."}, "43_8": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Portal hypertension is increased pressure in the portal venous system. Sort it by where the resistance sits: prehepatic (before the liver — portal vein thrombosis, splenic vein thrombosis, portal vein atresia); intrahepatic (within the liver — cirrhosis, the most common cause overall; presinusoidal; also schistosomiasis, PBC, fatty liver, Wilson); and post-sinusoidal / posthepatic (after the sinusoids — Budd-Chiari (hepatic vein thrombosis), IVC thrombosis, restrictive pericarditis, severe right-sided heart failure). In cirrhosis, fibrosis and nodularity raise sinusoidal resistance, slightly lowering portal-vein flow pressure and forcing blood into portosystemic collaterals.", "why": "The sites: prehepatic (portal/splenic vein thrombosis), intrahepatic (cirrhosis, most common), post-sinusoidal (Budd-Chiari, IVC thrombosis, RHF). One back-pressure drives all three: blood into portosystemic collaterals (varices, caput medusae, hemorrhoids), spleen congestion (splenomegaly -> pancytopenia), and - with hypoalbuminemia and Na/water retention - fluid into the peritoneum as ascites."}, "43_9": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The congenital block is three diseases that all obstruct the biliary tree from birth: biliary atresia (the duct that isn't there), the choledochal cyst (the duct that balloons), and Caroli disease (the intrahepatic ducts that go cystic). Machini's exam handle is to know the Latin root — 'atresia' means the tube is closed and does not exist, and if you miss the word you miss the question. All three present as obstructive cholestasis, and all three carry a long-tail risk of cholangiocarcinoma.", "why": "'Atresia' means the tube is closed/absent — biliary atresia is obliterative obstruction of the extrahepatic ducts, implicating GPC1 (glypican-1) deletion. Bile cannot leave the liver, so neonatal cholestasis drives rapid cirrhosis and failure — which is why biliary atresia is the #1 cause of pediatric liver transplantation in the US."}, "43_10": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The LO names PSC, but the only way to be safe is to author it against PBC, because the board lives on the contrast (Machini went straight to the comparison slide). Both are autoimmune cholestatic diseases that destroy bile ducts and end in cirrhosis and cholangiocarcinoma, but everything else is a mirror image: PBC = the AMA-positive woman with small intrahepatic ducts and a granulomatous florid duct lesion; PSC = the p-ANCA man with ulcerative colitis, large and small ducts, and onion-skin fibrosis.", "why": "PBC is the anti-mitochondrial-antibody (90-95%) disease of middle-aged women, nonsuppuratively destroying small/medium intrahepatic ducts (granulomatous florid duct lesion), tied to Sjögren (70%). PSC is the p-ANCA (~65%) disease of men with ulcerative colitis, scarring both intra- and extrahepatic ducts (onion-skin fibrosis → tombstone scar, beaded ERCP)."}, "43_11": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Cholelithiasis (gallstones) is the most common cause of biliary obstruction in the US, affecting ~10% of adult women and 6% of adult men. Stones are crystalline cholesterol, bile pigment, and calcium salts in a protein matrix, and the whole LO collapses into one sort: cholesterol (the yellow, ~90% majority) versus pigment (the black/brown minority). Get color, percentage, radiodensity, and location right and the stem answers itself.", "why": "Cholesterol stones (~90%) are yellow, mostly radiolucent, gallbladder-only, and hit the 4 F's (female, fat, forty, fertile); pigment stones carry unconjugated bilirubin — black (hemolysis/cirrhosis/TPN, radiopaque) vs brown (infection/stasis, radiolucent). The initiating step for a cholesterol stone is bile supersaturation, then nucleation from hypomotility and mucus."}, "43_12": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This is the gallbladder grab-bag: the two cholecystitides (acute and chronic, each with a calculous and acalculous flavor), plus three benign-to-watch lesions — cholesterolosis (strawberry gallbladder), polyps, and mucocele/hydrops — and the pre-malignant porcelain gallbladder. The unifying histologic thread is the Rokitansky-Aschoff sinus; the unifying gross lesson is telling the red strawberry gallbladder from the white porcelain one.", "why": "The Rokitansky-Aschoff sinus — mucosal herniation through the muscularis — ties the cholecystitides together, present ~90% in chronic cholecystitis. The two gross gallbladders to separate: the red strawberry (cholesterolosis: foamy cholesterol-laden macrophages, benign) and the bluish-white porcelain (calcified, carcinoma-in-situ epithelium, pre-malignant — resect)."}, "43_13": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Biliary tumors are nearly all adenocarcinoma of bile-duct (or gallbladder) epithelium, share a poor prognosis, and are tied to the lesions earlier in the lecture — gallstones, porcelain gallbladder, ulcerative colitis (PSC), and liver flukes. Sort them by site: the gallbladder, the bile ducts (cholangiocarcinoma, by location), and the ampulla of Vater.", "why": "The junction is where the right and left hepatic ducts unite to form the common hepatic duct; a perihilar cholangiocarcinoma there is a Klatskin tumor (Machini flagged a board question on it). At the ampulla of Vater, carcinoma follows the adenoma-carcinoma sequence, and 90% of the carcinomas are surrounded by adenoma."}, "45_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW (baseline anatomy/physiology). The gallbladder is a saccular organ on the inferior surface of the liver (fundus, body, infundibulum, neck) that stores bile (capacity ~50 mL). The liver makes ~600-700 mL of bile per day, which is ~90% water plus electrolytes and solutes (bile salts/acids, phospholipids, cholesterol, protein). After a meal, cholecystokinin (CCK) triggers gallbladder contraction. Bile matters for absorption of fat-soluble vitamins, elimination of bilirubin, and excretion of cholesterol and bile acids. The primary bile acids are cholic and chenodeoxycholic; the secondary bile acids are deoxycholic and lithocholic. Blood supply is the cystic artery, which runs in the triangle of Calot (hepatocystic triangle) and is a branch of the right hepatic artery.", "why": ""}, "45_2": {"answer": "STONE TYPES. Gallstones are pigment or non-pigment. Cholesterol stones are the non-pigment majority (most stones you see), forming from biliary stasis, calcium nucleation, and increased water absorption (risk: obesity, estrogen/OCPs, diabetes). Pigment stones are black or brown: black pigment stones are seen with hemolysis, cirrhosis, or chronic TPN; brown pigment stones are seen with biliary stasis, infection, and Asian descent. Calcium bilirubinate is the other pigment category.", "why": "Cholesterol = non-pigment majority (obesity, estrogen, diabetes); black = hemolysis/cirrhosis/TPN; brown = stasis/infection/Asian. An escaped stone causes cholecystitis in the cystic duct, cholangitis/jaundice in the CBD, pancreatitis at the ampulla of Vater, and gallstone ileus via a cholecystoduodenal fistula impacting the terminal ileum."}, "45_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW — THE OPENING AND CLOSING RULE. Sharieff bookended the whole lecture with one message: NOT all gallstones need to be removed. Asymptomatic cholelithiasis is common and is managed conservatively — observation / expectant management. The reasoning is risk-versus-benefit: the lifetime risk of complicated disease from initially silent stones is low (estimated ~8%), so a routine or incidentally found stone in a patient with no biliary colic and no symptoms is simply watched. Do not be in a hurry to take the gallbladder.", "why": "Observe - not all gallstones need removal. Asymptomatic cholelithiasis is common with a low (~8%) lifetime complicated-disease risk; prophylactic cholecystectomy is for individualized special cases. Higher-risk: female, immobile/numerous stones, large (>10 mm) or small (<5 mm). Gallstones are the #1 risk factor for GB cancer, but not all cause cancer, so observation stays default."}, "45_4": {"answer": "BILIARY COLIC. Biliary colic is RUQ or epigastric pain that develops after eating (postprandial), with or without nausea/vomiting, lasting ~30 minutes to ~5 hours (can radiate to the back or right scapula; classically after a fatty meal). The mechanism is a stone transiently impacting the gallbladder neck/cystic duct and then passing — so the pain comes, peaks, and resolves. Pain >5 hours suggests something more than colic (e.g., evolving cholecystitis). BOAS sign = referred pain/hyperesthesia at the right infrascapular region. Rome criteria describe the recurrent, steady, daily-living-disturbing pattern used clinically.", "why": "Biliary colic = postprandial RUQ/epigastric pain (+/- nausea), ~30 min to ~5 h, from a stone transiently impacting the GB neck/cystic duct; pain beyond 5 h suggests worse. Biliary dyskinesia is a functional GB disorder and diagnosis of exclusion: ultrasound shows no stones, then CCK-augmented HIDA measures ejection fraction, GbEF <35-40% confirms it, treated with cholecystectomy."}, "45_5": {"answer": "ACUTE CHOLECYSTITIS — CALCULOUS vs ACALCULOUS. Acute calculous cholecystitis is inflammation of the gallbladder from a stone impacted in the cystic duct (the common form). Acalculous cholecystitis is inflammation without stones, seen in the critically ill / low-perfusion / biliary-stasis setting — severe burns, prolonged TPN, trauma, major surgery. Clinically: RUQ pain (4-6 h), nausea/vomiting, fever, and a positive Murphy sign (inspiratory arrest on RUQ palpation). Infection is usually gram-negative aerobes (E. coli, Klebsiella, Enterococcus); always check LFTs to catch a CBD stone.", "why": "Acute calculous cholecystitis = cystic-duct stone; acalculous = no stones, critically ill/low-perfusion (burns, TPN, trauma, surgery). Ultrasound first (wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, stones); HIDA second-line: non-visualization at 60 min = acute, delayed by ~120 min = chronic. Management: NPO, IV fluids, antibiotics, cholecystectomy (open if emphysematous or cancer suspected)."}, "45_6": {"answer": "RECOGNITION — CHARCOT TO REYNOLDS. Acute cholangitis is infection of an obstructed biliary tree (stone — most often from choledocholithiasis — stricture, or tumor). Charcot triad = fever, RUQ pain, and jaundice -> think cholangitis. Add altered mental status and hypotension and you have Reynolds pentad (the 5: fever, RUQ pain, jaundice, AMS, hypotension), which signals suppurative cholangitis / septic shock — a surgical emergency needing immediate treatment. Infection is typically polymicrobial gram-negative gut flora (E. coli, Klebsiella).", "why": "Charcot triad = fever, RUQ pain, jaundice (cholangitis); Reynolds pentad adds AMS and hypotension = suppurative cholangitis/septic shock, a surgical emergency. Fixed sequence: broad-spectrum IV antibiotics + resuscitation FIRST, then drainage (ERCP + sphincterotomy, clears distal CBD stones >90%). If drainage fails, escalate to surgical drainage/CBD exploration removing the stone source."}, "45_7": {"answer": "GALLSTONE PANCREATITIS. When a stone impacts at the ampulla of Vater, it causes backflow into the pancreatic duct and acute pancreatitis (most stones in the common duct are cholesterol stones that came from the gallbladder; in ~20% of people the pancreatic duct inserts separately, but usually it joins the common duct before the duodenum — which is why gallstones so commonly cause pancreatitis). The good news: gallstone pancreatitis usually improves on its own once the stone passes. If obstruction persists, do an ERCP with stone removal; and to prevent recurrence, perform a cholecystectomy (interval cholecystectomy removes the stone source).", "why": "Gallstone pancreatitis = stone at the ampulla of Vater with pancreatic-duct backflow; resolves on passage (ERCP if it persists), cholecystectomy to prevent recurrence. Gallstone ileus = large stone eroding through a cholecystoduodenal fistula and impacting the terminal ileum (SBO with pneumobilia); treat with enterotomy proximal to the obstruction, usually leaving fistula and gallbladder."}, "45_8": {"answer": "BILIARY STRICTURES. Strictures of the biliary tree arise from stones, cancer, trauma, inflammation, or surgery — but the #1 cause of benign biliary strictures is IATROGENIC injury, classically a bile-duct injury during laparoscopic cholecystectomy in an inflamed field (often not apparent until edema subsides). A stricture causes obstruction and can lead to cholangitis, jaundice, sepsis. The board one-liner: a biliary stricture in the absence of prior pancreatitis or biliary surgery is CANCER until you prove otherwise — evaluate thoroughly (endoscopic evaluation), and most of these go to an operation (often a choledochojejunostomy / hepaticojejunostomy reconstruction).", "why": "The #1 cause of benign biliary strictures is iatrogenic injury - classically during laparoscopic cholecystectomy. A stricture without prior pancreatitis or biliary surgery is cancer until proven otherwise, evaluated and usually reconstructed operatively. Biliary (choledochal) cysts are biliary-tree dilatations in four types carrying ~15% cholangiocarcinoma risk, evaluated to rule out cancer."}, "45_9": {"answer": "WHAT GALLBLADDER CANCER IS. Gallbladder cancer (GBC) is rare but aggressive. Because the gallbladder lacks a submucosa, tumors spread early via lymphatics and into the liver, and survival is poor. Adenocarcinoma is the most common histology, most cancers arise in the fundus, and the #1 risk factor is gallstones/cholelithiasis (others: porcelain gallbladder, large/long-standing stones, gallbladder polyps, PSC, anomalous pancreaticobiliary junction). Nearly half are found incidentally at routine cholecystectomy. A fundal mass is a red flag — gallstone disease usually involves the infundibulum/cystic duct, so fundal involvement suggests a neoplastic process.", "why": "GB cancer is a rare, aggressive fundal adenocarcinoma; no submucosa = early lymphatic/liver spread, #1 risk gallstones. By T stage: T1a (lamina propria, not crossing muscularis) = simple cholecystectomy; T1b/T2 (invading muscularis) = extended cholecystectomy + lymphadenectomy + segment IVb/V resection. Suspected pre-op = open to avoid seeding; polyps ~10-18 mm = chole, >20 mm = open."}, "45_10": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Cholangiocarcinoma is cancer of the biliary tree other than the gallbladder, and the most common histology is adenocarcinoma. It can occur anywhere along the biliary tree; classification includes intrahepatic, extrahepatic, and perihilar (plus right/left distinctions). The classic and most-recognized variant is the perihilar tumor at the confluence of the hepatic ducts — the Klatskin tumor. About two-thirds of cholangiocarcinomas are extrahepatic. Presentations include a mass, stricture, jaundice, and weight loss; survival is poor.", "why": "Cholangiocarcinoma = adenocarcinoma of the biliary tree (not the gallbladder), arising intrahepatic, extrahepatic, or perihilar; the classic perihilar confluence tumor is the Klatskin tumor, ~two-thirds extrahepatic. Presents with a mass, stricture, jaundice, or weight loss; best survival chance is curative resection, though many are unresectable, leaving palliative drainage."}, "45_11": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Liver masses usually surface incidentally — found on imaging done for something else, noticed intraoperatively, picked up on screening of abnormal liver function tests, or during a metastatic workup (e.g., a colon-cancer patient with elevated LFTs). When you see one, you must hold both benign and malignant causes in mind. Sharieff's framework: benign = hemangioma (most common, usually asymptomatic), hepatic adenoma (the symptomatic one), focal nodular hyperplasia, simple cyst; malignant = metastasis (the most common, covered in LO 46.4), then the primaries hepatocellular carcinoma and cholangiocarcinoma.", "why": "Workup is triple-phase contrast CT (liver protocol) or MRI plus tumor markers; the test you avoid is biopsy, because imaging and markers almost always make the diagnosis (and biopsy adds bleeding/seeding risk). The combination that means hepatocellular carcinoma without tissue is cirrhosis + elevated alpha-fetoprotein + a hypervascular liver mass."}, "45_12": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Four benign liver lesions, each with its own behavior. Hemangioma is the most common benign tumor and is usually asymptomatic — follow it, don't biopsy, and resect only when large/symptomatic or at high rupture risk (e.g., giant hemangiomas, or Kasabach-Merritt syndrome, where hemangiomas reach ~10 cm with consumptive coagulopathy in children). Simple cysts (often with polycystic kidney/liver disease) are typically <3 cm and need nothing unless they bleed, infect, rupture, or look complex/suspicious for a mucinous cystadenoma/carcinoma.", "why": "Hemangioma is the most common - asymptomatic, no biopsy, watch (resect only if giant/symptomatic or Kasabach-Merritt). Hepatic adenoma carries rupture and malignant-transformation risk: resect ANY size in a man; in a woman watch if <4 cm (stop estrogen/steroids), resect if >4 cm. FNH (central stellate scar) is watched - NO malignant potential, very low bleeding. Simple cysts: watch unless complicated."}, "45_13": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) is the more common primary liver malignancy (cholangiocarcinoma is the other) and almost always arises in the background of cirrhosis. In the US the classic drivers are hepatitis C cirrhosis and, increasingly, alcoholic cirrhosis (also NASH/fatty liver). Diagnosis is by imaging + markers, not biopsy: a hypervascular mass on multiphase CT/MRI plus an elevated alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) in a cirrhotic is HCC. Sharieff's refrain — 'imaging, imaging, imaging', with MRI added when you need to define biliary-tree extension before any treatment.", "why": "HCC arises on cirrhosis (HCV, alcohol, NASH), diagnosed by a hypervascular mass on multiphase CT/MRI plus elevated AFP - no biopsy. The Milan criteria are a single nodule <=5 cm OR up to three nodules each <=3 cm, no macrovascular invasion and no distant disease; meeting them makes the patient the best transplant candidate. Transplant beats resection because it removes the tumor AND the diseased, cancer-prone liver - better outcomes, higher UNOS priority."}, "45_14": {"answer": "PYOGENIC ABSCESS — DRAIN IF >5 cm. Liver abscesses split into pyogenic (bacterial), amebic, and fungal. Pyogenic liver abscess is the most common in the US, involves the right hemiliver in ~75%, and classically presents with fever, jaundice, and right-upper-quadrant pain. Cover broadly (aerobes + anaerobes, gram-negatives). Size drives drainage: <3 cm -> IV antibiotics alone; >5 cm -> drain (percutaneous first; excise if percutaneous fails and the patient decompensates).", "why": "Pyogenic (most common in the US, right liver ~75%, fever/jaundice/RUQ pain; <3 cm antibiotics, >5 cm drain), amebic (Entamoeba - metronidazole, no aspiration), echinococcal (Echinococcus - albendazole + PAIR, then resection). Do NOT simply aspirate the amebic (unnecessary) or the echinococcal cyst - puncturing spills antigenic fluid -> anaphylaxis. The #1 malignant liver lesion is metastasis, colon (colorectal) the top primary, then pancreas/stomach."}, "45_15": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Unlike liver masses, most pancreatic masses are found incidentally; they are rarely identified intraoperatively because the pancreas is retroperitoneal and hard to see. The differential holds both benign and malignant lesions, but Sharieff's organizing rule is binary by consistency: every SOLID pancreatic lesion is considered malignant and treated as such (resect early — surgery is the only cure), while a CYSTIC lesion obligates you to rule out cancer. A key contrast with the liver: metastasis to the pancreas is rare (in the liver, metastasis is the #1 lesion), so a solid pancreatic mass is your own primary cancer until proven otherwise.", "why": "Solid = treat as malignant (resect early - surgery is the only cure); cystic = rule out cancer. Mucin is the cyst key: serous cysts and pseudocysts are benign, MCN ~15-25%, IPMN ~35-65% (main-duct worst). Workup is triple-phase CT (pancreas protocol) or MRI/MRCP plus CA 19-9; biopsy is avoided (EUS-FNA only for an indeterminate cyst) because it risks acute pancreatitis and delay. Unlike the liver, pancreatic metastasis is rare."}, "45_16": {"answer": "PSEUDOCYST — NO EPITHELIUM, EXPECTANT MANAGEMENT. A pancreatic pseudocyst is a well-defined peripancreatic fluid collection with a fibrotic wall but NO epithelial lining (that absent lining is what makes it a pseudocyst), filled with amylase-rich fluid from disruption of the main pancreatic duct after an acute inflammatory process; the common cause is chronic pancreatitis/alcohol. Most are discovered after pancreatitis with vague pain, nausea, and vomiting, and diagnosed by contrast CT/MRI. The board point Sharieff highlighted: pseudocysts are usually sterile (no antibiotics) and most resolve spontaneously, so initial management is expectant — pain control, nutritional support, and treating the pancreatitis — sometimes waiting >3-6 months.", "why": "A pseudocyst is an amylase-rich collection with a fibrotic wall and NO epithelial lining, usually after pancreatitis (alcohol). It is usually sterile and most resolve, so management is expectant (pain control, nutrition, treat the pancreatitis); drain only for persistence or complications. Splitting rule: a cyst from pancreatitis/trauma is a pseudocyst you watch; a cyst tied to neither means you MUST rule out cancer (MCN vs IPMN)."}, "45_17": {"answer": "PDAC — THE BIG BURDEN. Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC) is the most common pancreatic cancer and the one Sharieff most wants learned, because it carries a very poor prognosis (5-year survival <10%) — by the time it is found, many patients are unresectable. It is projected to become the 2nd-leading cause of cancer death by 2030 (stated three times), arises usually in the head of the pancreas (classic painless jaundice from biliary obstruction), and has a genetic contribution. Workup is the same triple-phase CT/MRI (define ductal/vascular invasion -> resectability) plus CA 19-9.", "why": "PDAC is the most common pancreatic cancer, worst prognosis (5-yr <10%), usually in the head (painless jaundice), projected 2nd-leading cause of cancer death by 2030; resectable head -> pancreaticoduodenectomy (Whipple). PNETs are mostly sporadic/nonfunctional but high malignant potential, so resect (especially >=2 cm); they metastasize to the liver. Whipple's triad - symptomatic hypoglycemia, low glucose, relief with glucose - names a functional insulinoma."}, "45_18": {"answer": "OVERVIEW + THE CT TRIAD. Chronic pancreatitis is irreversible injury to the pancreas, most often from alcohol (with tobacco), increasingly idiopathic/genetic. The classic patient is a long-time heavy drinker with epigastric pain radiating to the back, weight loss, and steatorrhea (bulky, foul-smelling, fatty stools) from malabsorption. The CT triad Sharieff wants read off the scan: pancreatic calcifications + an irregular, dilated pancreatic duct + parenchymal atrophy. Get a good CT (MRCP supplements ductal anatomy) to gauge how dilated the duct is and whether the patient needs an operation.", "why": "The CT triad is calcifications + an irregular dilated duct + parenchymal atrophy, in a long-time drinker with epigastric-to-back pain, steatorrhea, and weight loss. Because the injury is irreversible, management replaces lost function - pain control, pancreatic enzyme replacement, fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K), glucose control. When pain persists despite medical therapy and the duct is dilated, the operation is a Puestow (lateral pancreaticojejunostomy)."}, "47_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Jaundice (icterus) is the accumulation of unconjugated or conjugated bilirubin (UCB or CB) in tissues — chiefly skin, sclera, and mucous membranes — giving them a golden-yellow color. Bonfil built the whole lecture on one idea: 'whenever we talk about jaundice, bilirubin is going to take an important role.' Master the bilirubin pathway and every jaundice becomes the step that broke. Know the numbers first: normal total bilirubin is 0.2-1.2 mg/dL (above 1.2 = hyperbilirubinemia), normal direct (conjugated) is ≤0.3 mg/dL; clinically, scleral icterus appears > 2-3 mg/dL and skin yellowing > 4-5 mg/dL.", "why": "Heme oxygenase -> biliverdin reductase -> UCB (insoluble, rides albumin) -> UGT1A1 -> MRP2 into bile. Production, uptake, and conjugation breaks raise UNCONJUGATED; canalicular transport breaks raise CONJUGATED. Gilbert and Crigler-Najjar I/II are UGT1A1 (unconjugated); Dubin-Johnson (MRP2/ABCC2, black liver) and Rotor (OATP-1B1/1B3, no pigment) are conjugated."}, "47_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Cholestasis is a condition in which bile flow is markedly reduced or stopped, from either impaired hepatocyte secretion of bile or obstruction anywhere from the liver to the Ampulla of Vater. It splits two ways anatomically: intrahepatic cholestasis (within the parenchyma — impaired secretion of bile into canaliculi, or blockage of intrahepatic ducts) and extrahepatic cholestasis (the biliary tree — blockage of large ducts outside the liver). Intrahepatic causes are a wide spectrum — drugs (contraceptive pills, anabolic steroids), primary sclerosing cholangitis, infections, sepsis — while extrahepatic causes are primarily anatomic (the most common adult cause is a gallstone in the common bile duct; in infants/children, cystic fibrosis and biliary atresia).", "why": "Cholestasis is bile flow reduced/stopped, from impaired secretion or obstruction to the Ampulla of Vater; intrahepatic vs extrahepatic. ICP = an ABCB4/MDR3 phospholipid-translocator defect: third-trimester pruritus worst on palms/soles, resolving post-delivery, confirmed by high bile acids. Three canalicular mechanisms: contractility (RhoA/Rho-kinase), membrane (low Na+/K+-ATPase), transporter inhibition (estrogens)."}, "47_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This objective is the synthesis LO — the etiology, morphology, and effects of the jaundice/cholestasis picture. A note on sourcing: the deck's morphology slides are cholestasis morphology, so that is where the 'morphologic changes' come from; jaundice's own morphology is simpler — tissue bilirubin staining (the yellow sclera/skin) and, at the extreme, kernicterus (UCB in the basal ganglia). The etiologic factors are the four general causes from 47.1 plus the cholestatic obstructions of 47.2; the effects are the clinical and laboratory consequences below.", "why": "Morphology is cholestasis-sourced: both types show feathery degeneration (foamy bile-laden hepatocytes), bile plugs in dilated canaliculi, apoptotic hepatocytes with Kupffer phagocytosis; extrahepatic adds a ductular reaction (periductular neutrophils), bile lakes ringed by necrotic hepatocytes, periportal fibrosis to cirrhosis. Effects: jaundice, pruritus (bile salts in skin), xanthomas, pale stools, steatorrhea; labs elevated ALP and GGT."}, "48_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Rodriguez frames the whole lecture around a naming problem. The panel everyone calls liver function tests (LFTs) has five 'true LFT' components: serum aminotransferases (AST/ALT), alkaline phosphatase, serum bilirubin, serum albumin, and PT/INR. But the name is a misnomer — most of these do not actually test function. The slide banner spells it out: 'Health ≠ Function.'", "why": "Of the five 'true LFT' components, the enzymes (aminotransferases and alkaline phosphatase) test INJURY - they leak from damaged cells - while albumin, PT/INR, and bilirubin test FUNCTION (the liver makes albumin and clotting factors and processes bilirubin). 'Health does not equal Function': an injured liver can still function, and a normal enzyme panel does not prove a healthy liver."}, "48_2": {"answer": "AMINOTRANSFERASES (AST & ALT) — THE BREAD AND BUTTER. The aminotransferases (older term: transaminases) transfer the alpha-amino group of alanine or aspartate. ALT (alanine aminotransferase, a.k.a. SGPT) and AST (aspartate aminotransferase, a.k.a. SGOT) both report hepatocellular injury/inflammation — they leak when hepatocytes die. Both are useful, but ALT is more specific for liver pathology. Why? Location. ALT is present in the highest concentration in the liver (mnemonic: L for liver). AST, by contrast, is also abundant in cardiac muscle, skeletal muscle, kidney, brain, pancreas, lung, leukocytes, and erythrocytes — so much so that AST was used to detect MIs before troponin. A subcellular pearl Rodriguez flags: both enzymes are cytosolic, but AST is the ONLY one also found in the MITOCHONDRIAL MATRIX.", "why": "ALT and AST report hepatocellular injury; ALT is most concentrated in the liver (more specific), while AST is also in cardiac/skeletal muscle and the only one in the mitochondrial matrix. Alkaline phosphatase detects cholestasis (~4x ULN) but also rises from bone, pregnancy, and growing infants - so GGT or 5'-NT (neither affected by bone) confirms a hepatobiliary source (GGT in pregnancy; high GGT = alcohol)."}, "48_3": {"answer": "CAUSES OF AMINOTRANSFERASE ELEVATION. Essentially anything that harms the liver raises AST/ALT: acetaminophen toxicity (acetaminophen is hepatotoxic; NSAIDs are nephrotoxic), alcoholic hepatitis, MASH (metabolic dysfunction-associated steatohepatitis, formerly NASH), ischemic hepatitis, acute viral hepatitis (A-E, plus HSV, VZV, EBV, CMV — EBV causes mono and can bump LFTs), autoimmune hepatitis, malignancy (breast, small-cell lung, lymphoma, melanoma, myeloma), pre-eclampsia/eclampsia, and muscular disorders (recall AST lives in skeletal muscle, so muscular dystrophy can raise AST). Hemolysis can raise AST too (erythrocytes).", "why": "Aminotransferases rise from almost anything that harms the liver: acetaminophen (hepatotoxic), alcohol, MASH (ex-NASH), ischemia, viral (A-E plus EBV/CMV/HSV/VZV), autoimmune, malignancy, (pre)eclampsia, and muscle. Alcohol shows AST:ALT >= 2:1 (often high GGT). Magnitude ladder: MASH < 5x ULN, acute viral or toxin (e.g. acetaminophen) > 25x, ischemic hepatitis > 50x with an elevated LDH."}, "48_4": {"answer": "BILIRUBIN — DIRECT VS INDIRECT. Bilirubin is the yellow product of heme catabolism, excreted in bile and urine. Three tests: total, direct, and indirect. Direct = CONJUGATED (direct hyperbilirubinemia); indirect = UNCONJUGATED (indirect hyperbilirubinemia). Rodriguez's memory hook: bilirubin comes in unconjugated, and once conjugated it goes 'directly' out into the biliary/gut system. Indirect (unconjugated) hyperbilirubinemia arises from overproduction, impaired uptake, or impaired conjugation; direct (conjugated) hyperbilirubinemia from decreased excretion into the bile ductules. Bilirubin is the component that straddles both axes — it reflects liver function AND liver injury, in acute or chronic disease. (Full metabolism is detailed in the bilirubin/jaundice lecture.)", "why": "Bilirubin (a heme-catabolism product) is reported as total, direct (conjugated), and indirect (unconjugated): indirect comes from overproduction, impaired uptake, or impaired conjugation; direct from decreased excretion into the bile ductules. Albumin and clotting factors are made by the liver, so albumin falls (slow turnover, implying chronic disease) and PT/INR rises (fewer factors, longer to clot)."}, "48_5": {"answer": "THE FOUR PATTERNS. Step one in any abnormal panel is to see which value is disproportionately elevated. HEPATOCELLULAR = aminotransferases >> alkaline phosphatase (hepatocytes more affected; e.g., a transaminase of 2,000 with only a slightly high ALP). CHOLESTATIC = alkaline phosphatase >> aminotransferases (bile ducts more affected; e.g., cholecystitis). ISOLATED HYPERBILIRUBINEMIA = an isolated bilirubin rise with normal aminotransferases AND normal alkaline phosphatase (the congenital hyperbilirubinemias). INFILTRATIVE = a subtype of cholestatic (tumor/infiltrate): very high ALP with near-normal aminotransferases (the hepatocytes are replaced). Each pattern raises BOTH enzymes somewhat — the dominant one names the pattern. Rodriguez wants the hepatocellular-vs-cholestatic split cold.", "why": "Four patterns: hepatocellular (aminotransferases >> ALP), cholestatic (ALP >> aminotransferases), isolated hyperbilirubinemia (bilirubin only, normal enzymes), infiltrative (cholestatic subtype: very high ALP, near-normal aminotransferases). The best discriminator of acute failure is an elevated INR/PT (injury keeps it normal). Closing case: falling AST/ALT with rising bilirubin and PT/INR = a liver too destroyed to leak enzymes while function worsens - poor prognosis."}, "49_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW — HEPATITIS VS CHOLESTASIS FIRST. Before naming a virus, Soff sorts the injury two ways. Hepatitis is destruction/death of hepatocytes with inflammatory infiltrate of the parenchyma — the markers that leak are the transaminases AST and ALT (with bilirubin and PT-INR rising only if damage is extensive). Cholestasis is a problem of the biliary tree (canaliculi -> intrahepatic ducts -> extrahepatic ducts), and its marker is alkaline phosphatase. Because alk phos lives in both liver and bone, you confirm a liver source with GGT or 5'-nucleotidase — both liver/biliary-specific and not found in bone. One more practical split: imaging is minimal help in hepatitis but a major help in cholestasis.", "why": "Hepatitis raises AST/ALT from hepatocyte death; cholestasis raises alkaline phosphatase from a biliary problem, and GGT or 5'-nucleotidase confirm an elevated alk phos is hepatobiliary, not bony. The #1 cause of abnormal LFTs in the US is MASLD (fatty liver). On the ratio, ALT > AST points to viral hepatitis, AST > ALT to alcohol."}, "49_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW — FIVE VIRUSES, TWO ROUTES. The classic viral causes are hepatitis A, B, C, D, and E (plus other viruses — CMV, EBV/mono, COVID-19). The organizing split is transmission: HAV and HEV are fecal-oral and self-limited/acute; HBV, HCV, and HDV are blood/body-fluid (parenteral) and can become chronic. HAV is an RNA 'infectious hepatitis' (1.4 million cases/yr) spread person-to-person and by contaminated food/water — households, daycare, prisons, military — with no prenatal spread. US incidence has fallen since vaccination began (1996 high-risk, all infants 2006): from ~6 to ~0.4 cases per 100,000.", "why": "HAV is RNA, fecal-oral (food/water), ~1.4 million cases/yr, no chronic state. HBV is the only DNA hepatitis virus ('serum hepatitis'), spread vertically/parenterally/sexually, ~82% of US cases foreign-born. HCV is small RNA, parenteral; 1.3% of the US has/had it (~3.6 million, 'Boomers'), and ~85% of acute HCV becomes chronic vs only ~5% for adult HBV."}, "49_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW — THE THREE WORKING HBV MARKERS. The acute presentation is nonspecific (fever, N/V, RUQ pain, anorexia, jaundice, malaise; HBV adds a serum-sickness-like prodrome — fever, rash, painful joints), and AST/ALT run 1,000-2,000 with ALT>AST — so the serology, not the symptoms, makes the diagnosis. Three markers do the work. HBsAg (surface antigen) is the first to rise and means current infection. Anti-HBs (surface antibody) is the last to appear and means immunity. Anti-HBc (core antibody) sits between them and is the key to the window. Two more report infectivity: HBeAg (highly contagious) and anti-HBe (lower infectivity).", "why": "Acute HBV = HBsAg+ with anti-HBc IgM; chronic = HBsAg+ >6 mo with anti-HBc IgG, anti-HBs NEVER appears; resolved = anti-HBs AND anti-HBc both+; vaccinated = anti-HBs+ but anti-HBc NEGATIVE. In the window HBsAg has fallen, anti-HBs not yet up, so anti-HBc fills it and catches it. HAV: IgM = acute, IgG = immunity; HCV: anti-HCV screens, HCV RNA confirms chronic."}, "49_4": {"answer": "VACCINATED VS INFECTED — ONE MARKER DECIDES. A vaccine presents only the surface antigen, so the immune response is anti-HBs alone — the body never sees the core, so it never makes anti-HBc. That gives the decisive rule: vaccinated = anti-HBs POSITIVE + anti-HBc NEGATIVE; previously infected (recovered) = anti-HBs POSITIVE + anti-HBc POSITIVE. Two patients can both be immune (anti-HBs+); the one who is anti-HBc positive met the real virus, the one who is anti-HBc negative got there by vaccine. (This is the same anti-HBc that fills the window in LO 49.3 — it is the universal footprint of true exposure.)", "why": "The discriminator is anti-HBc: vaccinated = anti-HBs+ with anti-HBc NEGATIVE; previously infected = both positive (vaccine carries only surface antigen, so never raises anti-HBc). Perinatal HBV: give the newborn HBIG plus hepatitis B vaccine within 12 h of delivery, cutting the ~90% transmission risk by ~95%; breastfeeding is not a risk factor. HAV and HBV have vaccines; HCV has none - screen and cure."}, "49_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW — SUPPORTIVE CARE IS THE TREATMENT. Acute viral hepatitis is largely self-limited, so the mainstay is supportive care: fluids (assuring hydration), rest, reassurance, and time. There is no routine antiviral for uncomplicated acute disease — symptoms are nonspecific and resolve. The judgment call is recognizing when supportive outpatient care is not enough: hospitalize if the patient cannot tolerate fluids, or shows hepatic dysfunction — coagulopathy (elevated PT-INR), encephalopathy, or severe jaundice. If the course is fulminant (acute, severe liver destruction with organ failure), transfer to a transplant center. (Chronic-disease antiviral management is LO 49.6.)", "why": ""}, "49_6": {"answer": "CHRONIC HBV — WHO TO TREAT, WITH WHAT. Not every chronic HBV patient is treated; treat if ANY of: cirrhosis/advanced fibrosis, HBV DNA >2000, or AST >2x ULN. First-line oral nucleos(t)ide analogs are entecavir (Baraclude) and tenofovir (Viread/Vemlidy) (others: lamivudine, adefovir, telbivudine). The goals: eliminate HBsAg and HBeAg, suppress HBV DNA, and decrease long-term cirrhosis and HCC risk. Both treatment and HCC monitoring are LIFELONG — these drugs suppress, they do not cure HBV.", "why": "Treat chronic HBV for cirrhosis, HBV DNA >2000, or AST >2x ULN with entecavir or tenofovir; treatment and HCC surveillance are lifelong because these drugs suppress, not cure. HBV causes HCC without cirrhosis because its DNA integrates into the hepatocyte genome (directly oncogenic), so surveillance continues regardless of fibrosis. Chronic HCV is curable: anti-HCV, HCV RNA, stage, treat by genotype - ~95% cure, no vaccine."}, "50_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Hyperbilirubinemia is an excess of bilirubin in the blood; when it stains tissue it shows as jaundice (icterus) — yellow pigment in skin, sclera, nail beds, and oral mucosa. Blavo framed the whole hour as a biochem review aimed at one skill: 'this lecture is really about differential diagnosis.' Master the bilirubin pathway and every cause becomes the step that broke. Two definitions anchor everything: unconjugated bilirubin (UCB) is fat-soluble (crosses lipid membranes into tissues, is toxic, rides albumin, is not in urine), and conjugated bilirubin (CB) is water-soluble (non-toxic, excreted in urine).", "why": "Walk the pathway, then read each jaundice off the broken step and sort it twice -- by form (UNCONJUGATED vs CONJUGATED) and by site (pre-/hepatocellular/post-hepatic). That places the syndromes: Gilbert/Crigler-Najjar (the UGT pair) and Wilson are unconjugated; Dubin-Johnson (black liver) vs Rotor (no pigment) are the conjugated transport pair; PSC and biliary atresia are post-hepatic."}, "50_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Jaundice is the visible end of hyperbilirubinemia, and the first tell is the sclera: scleral icterus appears because fat-soluble UCB crosses lipid membranes and stains tissue, and the sclera is a sensitive, easily inspected site (skin, nail beds, and oral mucosa pick up the yellow too). Beyond the bilirubin itself, the exam is a hunt for signs of liver disease: hepatomegaly, splenomegaly (think hemolysis), caput medusae (dilated abdominal-wall veins from portal hypertension), ascites, palmar erythema, spider angiomas, xanthomas (dermal fat/cholesterol deposits), and Courvoisier's sign (a painless palpable enlarged gallbladder suggesting biliary obstruction).", "why": "Look for scleral icterus first (fat-soluble UCB stains tissue), then scan for the liver-disease signs (caput medusae, palmar erythema, spider angiomas, Courvoisier). Then fractionate: unconjugated raises indirect alone, conjugated raises both. The two add-on labs split the mechanism -- GGT for biliary obstruction, haptoglobin for hemolysis (and MRCP is the PSC test)."}, "50_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Neonatal hyperbilirubinemia is the one place this lecture talks treatments, and almost all of it is unconjugated — the newborn liver is immature, so its conjugating enzymes lag while red-cell turnover is high. The stakes are set by one fact: because UCB is fat-soluble, a high neonatal load crosses the blood-brain barrier and causes kernicterus — life-threatening bilirubin encephalopathy. Everything else here is about telling the benign causes apart and treating before bilirubin climbs that high.", "why": "Separate the three -- physiologic (immature liver, self-limited), breast-FEEDING (poor intake -> feed more), and breast-MILK (milk substances -> monitor). The dreaded complication is kernicterus: fat-soluble UCB crosses into the brain. Then match cause to treatment: phototherapy photo-isomerizes UCB water-soluble, phenobarbital lowers bilirubin in Crigler-Najjar type II (partial enzyme to induce) but not type I (no enzyme), Kasai is for biliary atresia."}, "51_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This LO is the heart of the lecture — a ladder from benign liver tumors up to hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC), and the trick is that each lesion has a signature you can name. The benign side sorts by morphology (a scar, a cavern, diffuse nodules); the hepatocellular adenoma sorts by molecular subtype; and HCC sorts by its driver-mutation triad. Bonfil built the block so that the adenoma's beta-catenin subtype literally feeds into HCC, so learn the benign molecules and the malignant ones answer themselves.", "why": "HNF1a-inactivated = HNF1a mutation, L-FABP loss on IHC + steatosis, low risk; beta-catenin-activated = CTNNB1, nuclear beta-catenin on IHC, very high malignant risk (resect); inflammatory = gp130/IL-6/JAK-STAT, CRP on IHC, small risk. The beta-catenin subtype feeds the HCC triad: aflatoxin B1 -> G:T transversion -> p53 (~60%), CTNNB1 (~40% non-HBV), and IL-6/JAK-STAT downregulating HNF4-alpha."}, "51_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Cholangiocarcinoma is an adenocarcinoma of the bile-duct epithelium — about one-sixth of all primary hepatic cancers. The three things to carry are the anatomic map (which tells you the Klatskin number), the etiologic risks (a fluke, a duct disease, and stones), and the desmoplastic morphology. Unlike HCC, intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma usually arises in a non-cirrhotic liver.", "why": "Most cholangiocarcinomas are perihilar Klatskin tumors at the confluence of the right and left hepatic ducts (~60%; intrahepatic ~10%, extrahepatic 20-30%). The classic SE-Asian risk is the Clonorchis sinensis liver fluke (also PSC, hepatolithiasis, biliary cysts). Biopsy shows a desmoplastic glandular adenocarcinoma with perineural and lymphovascular invasion."}, "51_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Bonfil bookended the lecture — intro and close — with the single high-yield fact of this LO: involvement of the liver by metastatic cancer is by far more common than primary hepatic tumors. About one-third of all carcinomas metastasize to the liver, so metastasis is the most common malignant liver tumor overall. Keep this distinct from the LO 51.1 superlatives: hemangioma is the most common primary tumor, HCC the most common primary cancer, but metastasis beats them all as a malignancy.", "why": "Metastatic cancer is by far the most common malignant liver tumor — about one-third of all carcinomas metastasize there. The leading primaries are colon, breast, and lung. Grossly, metastases appear as a few large lesions with central necrosis or as multiple small round nodules scattered through the liver — a multifocal pattern unlike the solitary scar of FNH or the diffuse fine nodules of nodular regenerative hyperplasia."}, "52_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The exocrine pancreas is 80-85% acinar cells packed with membrane-bound zymogen (proenzyme) granules — trypsinogen, chymotrypsinogen, procarboxypeptidase, proelastase, prophospholipase. Pancreatitis is what happens when those enzymes activate inside the gland and digest it. Acute pancreatitis is the acute onset of abdominal pain from enzymatic necrosis and inflammation; common triggers are gallstones, alcohol, and hyperlipidemia. Chronic pancreatitis is the irreversible end-state — fibrosis that follows repeated injury. Frame everything off the one idea: inappropriately activated digestive enzymes.", "why": "Three mechanisms — duct obstruction, acinar injury (Ca2+ triggers enzyme activation), and defective transport — all converge on ACTIVATED ENZYMES that autodigest the gland. Diagnose with lipase (over amylase) + contrast CT; Turner's = flank, Cullen = periumbilical hemorrhage. Chronic differs by being IRREVERSIBLE fibrosis (alcohol #1) with pathognomonic calcifications, ending in exocrine insufficiency + secondary diabetes."}, "52_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Pancreatic masses split into non-neoplastic (the post-inflammatory pseudocyst) and neoplastic cystic lesions. The Mayo schematic lays them out: serous cystadenoma, mucinous cystic neoplasm, main-duct and side-branch intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm (IPMN), cystic neuroendocrine tumor, and pseudocyst. The single most useful split is benign vs premalignant: serous is benign, the mucinous family is the one that turns into carcinoma. Diagnosis uses US/CT/MRI/PET, but biopsy is definitive.", "why": "The pseudocyst is the non-neoplastic mass: a post-pancreatitis fluid collection walled by fibrous tissue with no epithelial lining. The serous cystadenoma is benign — glycogen-rich cuboidal cells, clear straw-colored fluid, 2x in women. The mucinous cystic neoplasm is the worrisome one — women, tail, thick mucin, columnar epithelium, ~1/3 progressing to invasive carcinoma, KRAS/TP53/RNF43 (IPMN is its intraductal variant)."}, "52_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Infiltrating ductal adenocarcinoma is the 4th leading cause of cancer deaths in the US and has one of the highest mortality rates of any cancer. It is a disease of older adults — 80% of cases at 60-80 years, slightly more common in Black and in Ashkenazi-Jewish patients. Etiology: cigarette smoking is the strongest environmental influence and doubles the risk; a high-fat diet is implicated less consistently; chronic pancreatitis and diabetes are both risk factors AND complications. Inherited: germline BRCA2 ~10% (Ashkenazi Jews, even without a family history of breast/ovarian cancer/melanoma) and loss-of-function CDKN2A.", "why": "Smoking is the #1 risk (doubles it); BRCA2 (~10%, Ashkenazi Jews) and LOF CDKN2A are inherited. PanIN: KRAS early, p16/CDKN2A intermediate, TP53/SMAD4/BRCA2 late. ~60% arise in the head, obstructing the CBD with painless jaundice + Courvoisier; body/tail stay silent. Trousseau = migratory thrombophlebitis, Leser-Trelat = seborrheic keratoses. CA 19-9 monitors (not screening); the Whipple resects."}, "53_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Acute pancreatitis is an acute inflammatory process of the pancreas, driven by intracellular activation of digestive enzymes (trypsinogen → trypsin, which then autocatalyzes the other proenzymes) so the gland digests itself. Lamet built the etiology block around one pair you cannot miss: gallstones and alcohol together account for ~90% of cases. Everything else is a zebra worth recognizing but rarely the answer. Anatomically the set-up is the shared ampulla of Vater (main pancreatic duct + common bile duct, ringed by the sphincter of Oddi) — anything that obstructs it can back up pancreatic juice and ignite pancreatitis.", "why": "Gallstones (30-45%) and alcohol (30-45%) together cause ~90%. The zebras sort by category: metabolic (hypertriglyceridemia >1000, hypercalcemia), iatrogenic (post-ERCP, drugs), toxic/infectious (scorpion venom, HIV), inflammatory (autoimmune), and obstructive. The three obstructive figures: Ascaris at the ampulla (ascariasis), a periampullary diverticulum (Lemmel), and pancreas divisum (bud non-fusion)."}, "53_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW — THE HISTORY. The classic presentation is acute onset of persistent, severe epigastric pain that radiates to the back, often with nausea and vomiting; the pain may ease when the patient sits or leans forward. Severe acute pancreatitis can add dyspnea (diaphragmatic inflammation, pleural effusions, or ARDS); rarely a severe case presents with respiratory failure or altered mental status and no abdominal pain. Physical findings track severity — epigastric-to-generalized tenderness, a possible ileus with hypoactive bowel sounds, and in severe cases fever, tachycardia, hypoxemia, and hypotension.", "why": "Diagnosis requires 2 of 3: the clinical presentation (acute severe epigastric pain radiating to the back with n/v), lipase or amylase >3x ULN, or characteristic imaging (CT/MR/US). Because any two suffice, imaging is NOT required. Cullen's sign is periumbilical ecchymosis and Grey-Turner's is flank ecchymosis — both nonspecific markers of retroperitoneal bleeding in necrosis, in ~3% of patients."}, "53_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Ranson criteria were established to differentiate mild from severe (originally alcohol-induced) acute pancreatitis; higher scores mean higher morbidity and mortality. The score answers the clinical question on admission: is this patient going to improve on the floor, or head toward organ failure and the ICU? The catch is timing — 11 criteria scored across 48 hours (5 on admission, 6 at 48h). Lamet's exam rule: 'not that you have to calculate it, but you have to know what does and doesn't fall into Ranson criteria.'", "why": "On admission, the five are age >55, WBC >16,000, glucose >200, AST >250, and LDH >350. The 48-hour values include a hematocrit drop >10%, BUN rise >5, calcium <8, PaO2 <60, base deficit >4, and fluid sequestration >6L. Mortality runs from 2% at 0-2 criteria to ~40% at 5-6 and 100% at 7-8. Ranson stratifies mild vs severe — know what counts, not the calculation."}, "53_4": {"answer": "DIFFERENTIAL DIAGNOSIS. Sudden severe epigastric pain with n/v is shared by a row of acute-abdomen emergencies, so the differential is wide: peptic ulcer disease, choledocholithiasis / cholangitis, cholecystitis, perforated viscus (e.g., a large ulcer that perforated), intestinal obstruction, mesenteric ischemia, and hepatitis — with myocardial infarction the classic must-not-miss add. A CT on presentation is valuable precisely because it rules out several of these (free air, an inflamed gallbladder) at once.", "why": "Differentials: PUD, choledocholithiasis/cholangitis, cholecystitis, perforated viscus, obstruction, mesenteric ischemia, hepatitis, MI. Complications split local vs systemic: local = early peripancreatic fluid collection, pseudocyst (fibrous wall, no epithelial lining, ~4 weeks, ~10%), walled-off necrosis after 4 weeks; systemic = ARDS, shock, renal failure. Rule: hold invasive intervention >=4 weeks to let necrosis wall off."}, "53_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW — FLUIDS FIRST. The management of acute pancreatitis is largely supportive, and the first step is always aggressive isotonic crystalloid — normal saline or lactated Ringer's. Given in the first 12-24 hours, fluid resuscitation reduces morbidity and mortality. You then monitor: vital signs, urine output, and reduction in BUN/hematocrit. Lamet's bedside point — a pancreatitis patient lying tachycardic in bed is decompensating until proven otherwise; vitals are vital.", "why": "Step one is aggressive isotonic crystalloid (NS or LR), which in the first 12-24h reduces morbidity and mortality; monitor vitals and urine output. NJ enteral feeds are preferred over TPN, and prophylactic antibiotics are NOT recommended (reserve for proven infection). Always treat the cause. Pain: meperidine is the board answer over morphine (sphincter-of-Oddi myth), but no studies support it and morphine can be given."}, "53_6": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Chronic pancreatitis (CP) is a syndrome of progressive inflammatory change that produces permanent structural damage and impaired exocrine and endocrine function. It contrasts with acute pancreatitis (AP), an acute, usually non-progressive inflammatory response; recurrent episodes of AP may eventually lead to CP. Lamet built this hour on two anchors: the etiology (alcohol dominates) and the >90%-function-loss rule that gates every clinical finding.", "why": "Alcohol is the #1 cause (~70%); gallstones do NOT cause chronic pancreatitis. The alcoholic gets both steatorrhea and insulin-requiring diabetes because one advancing fibrosis destroys the exocrine acini and the endocrine islets together — and neither deficit appears until more than 90% of pancreatic function is lost."}, "53_7": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This objective is the diagnostic toolkit across acute pancreatitis, chronic pancreatitis, and pancreatic tumors — Lamet operationalized it through two case workups. The spine: serum enzymes are an acute test (not chronic), fecal elastase is the exocrine test of choice, and a handful of imaging/marker findings (double-duct sign, CA 19-9, cyst-fluid CEA) point at tumors.", "why": "Serum amylase/lipase (>3x ULN) diagnose ACUTE pancreatitis; in CHRONIC disease they may be high, normal, or low and are NOT diagnostic — use fecal elastase (<200 mcg/g). In painless jaundice, the double-duct sign (pancreatic duct + CBD dilated on CT/MRCP) signals a pancreatic-head mass: assume pancreatic cancer, with a rising serum CA 19-9."}, "53_8": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Sort pancreatic tumors into the exocrine (non-endocrine) majority and the endocrine (neuroendocrine, NET / islet-cell) minority. The exocrine group holds the common malignancies; the endocrine group is a dense eponym catalog Lamet flagged with gold stars — each functioning NET is named by the hormone it oversecretes and the syndrome that follows.", "why": "Exocrine: ductal adenocarcinoma (#1, CA 19-9), acinar, serous cystadenoma (low CEA), mucinous cystadenoma (CEA >=192-200, premalignant), IPMN, SPN. Endocrine NETs by eponym: insulinoma = Whipple's triad (most common); gastrinoma = Zollinger-Ellison, ~90% in the triangle (cystic/CBD, 2nd-3rd duodenum, neck-body); glucagonoma = necrolytic migratory erythema; VIPoma = WDHA; somatostatinoma = rare."}, "53_9": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The whole of LO 53.9 is one clean definitional contrast. Exocrine glands secrete a substance out through a duct; endocrine glands secrete a hormone into the bloodstream ('glands of external' vs 'internal' secretion). That single distinction sorts every pancreatic tumor.", "why": "Exocrine glands secrete out through a duct; endocrine glands secrete a hormone into blood. Exocrine (ductal/acinar) tumors are ~95% of pancreatic malignancies, led by aggressive ductal adenocarcinoma; endocrine NET/islet-cell tumors are rare (~5%), secrete peptide hormones, and tend to be more indolent."}, "53_10": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Cystic fibrosis (CF) is the most common life-shortening autosomal recessive disease among Caucasian populations, with a frequency of 1 in 2000-3000 live births. The underlying lesion is abnormal chloride and bicarbonate transport from mutations in the CFTR gene (CF transmembrane conductance regulator) on chromosome 7. The defect produces abnormally tenacious mucus in the lungs, GI tract, pancreas, and hepatobiliary system, so the lumens of these organs become obstructed.", "why": ""}};
