const LECTURE_CONTENT = {"31": {"prof": "Cyril Blavo, D.O.", "tldr": "Acute infectious diarrhea is usually self-limited — your job is to classify it (inflammatory vs secretory vs osmotic) and replace fluid and electrolytes, orally first and IV only when oral fails.", "mustKnows": ["Classify before you treat. Split every case into inflammatory (blood + fecal leukocytes + fever; EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter) vs non-inflammatory, then non-inflammatory into secretory (voluminous watery, ETEC/cholera) and osmotic (smaller volume; rotavirus, Giardia, EPEC). The bucket drives the workup and the fluids.", "Secretory diarrhea dehydrates fast. Secretory means an enterotoxin drives active secretion — voluminous watery non-bloody stools that persist even with fasting. ETEC (traveler's) and Vibrio cholerae are the archetypes; patients can lose enough fluid and electrolytes to die without looking 'septic.'", "The one bug you cannot miss: E. coli O157:H7. EHEC O157:H7 makes a Shiga-like cytotoxin → hemolytic uremic syndrome (azotemia, microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia). Do NOT give antibiotics — they increase HUS risk. Blavo flags HUS as a recurring board question.", "Know the toxin vocabulary. Exotoxins are secreted proteins: enterotoxin (gut — cholera, Staph), neurotoxin (C. botulinum), cytotoxin (C. difficile). Endotoxin is the LPS of gram-negative bacteria, released on cell death. C. diff is a cytotoxin, not a neurotoxin.", "Work up to validate, not to fish. Most diarrhea needs no testing. Work up only red flags (moderate/severe dehydration, bloody or voluminous stool, >48 h, high fever, recent antibiotics, immunocompromised). Calprotectin/lactoferrin beat fecal leukocytes; O&P ×3 for Giardia; osmotic gap >160 = osmotic diarrhea.", "ORS is glucose-sodium cotransport — and it is first-line. Oral rehydration solution works because glucose drags sodium and water across the gut (SGLT1). WHO ORS ≈ 245 mOsm/L, Na 75, glucose 75. Sodas and juices have glucose far exceeding sodium and can worsen losses. Use ORT whenever possible.", "Reserve IV — and avoid the drug traps. IV only when ORT is not feasible (persistent vomiting, severe dehydration, ileus, aspiration risk): NS, LR, or D5NS, individualized. Bismuth → Reye syndrome in <17. Antimotility and antiemetics with caution. BRAT diet is obsolete; zinc shortens duration."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Recognize the etiology of common infectious diarrheas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Dr. Blavo opens by deliberately downscoping the microbiology — \"we've given enough talks on those organisms\" — so the move he wants from you is not a memorized list but a pattern. Every organism collapses into one of three stool behaviors: inflammatory (EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter), secretory (ETEC, Vibrio cholerae), and osmotic (rotavirus, norovirus, EPEC, Giardia). Once you know the pattern, the workup and the fluids follow — so learn the buckets, not the encyclopedia."}, {"t": "p", "x": "TOXIN VOCABULARY. Exotoxins are secreted proteins and come in three flavors the exam keeps straight: enterotoxins act on the gut surface to drive secretion (Vibrio cholerae, Staph aureus); neurotoxins damage nerves (Clostridium botulinum); and cytotoxins damage cells in any tissue (Clostridioides difficile). Endotoxin is different — it is the lipopolysaccharide of gram-negative bacteria (E. coli, Salmonella), released when the organism dies, which is why those infections keep triggering inflammation even as bacteria are killed. Blavo briefly misspoke and corrected himself here, so pin it down: C. difficile is a cytotoxin; C. botulinum is the neurotoxin."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "C. difficile makes a cytotoxin; C. botulinum makes a neurotoxin."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Endotoxin is the LPS of gram-negative bacteria, released on bacterial death."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ONE YOU CANNOT MISS. Enterohemorrhagic E. coli (EHEC), serotype O157:H7, produces a Shiga-like cytotoxin and is the inflammatory, bloody diarrhea that progresses to hemolytic uremic syndrome — the triad of azotemia, microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, and thrombocytopenia. Blavo calls HUS out specifically as a recurring board question, and the high-yield twist lives in management: antibiotics increase the risk of HUS, so you withhold them (we return to this in LO 31.5)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "EHEC O157:H7 → Shiga-like cytotoxin → HUS (azotemia, MAHA, thrombocytopenia)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Cytotoxin vs neurotoxin: C. difficile = cytotoxin (colonic mucosa); C. botulinum = neurotoxin (nerves). Blavo misspoke and corrected this in lecture."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Reflexively giving antibiotics for \"bacterial\" bloody diarrhea — in O157:H7 they raise HUS risk. Withhold them."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Don't memorize the organism list — bucket every bug as inflammatory, secretory, or osmotic. The bucket drives workup and fluids."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Blavo says you can mostly skip memorizing the organism roll-call — so what is the one organism he tells you never to forget, and why?"}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Identify the clinical presentations of common infectious diarrheas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. For diarrhea, the history is the diagnostic test — Blavo's whole \"rote-to-rationale\" message is that you ask each question for a reason. The single most useful question is the character of the stool: loose, watery, mucoid, bloody, oily, or foul-smelling. Each adjective points somewhere."}, {"t": "p", "x": "STOOL TELLS. Bloody, mucoid stool with fecal leukocytes and fever is the inflammatory pattern (mucosal invasion). Voluminous watery non-bloody stool is secretory (ETEC, cholera). Greasy, malodorous stool is the malabsorptive/osmotic picture of Giardia — its trophozoites carpet the mucosa so fat isn't absorbed. And the timing tells too: rotavirus classically causes two to three days of vomiting before the watery diarrhea begins, a sequence Blavo flags as a distinguishing clue."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Greasy, foul-smelling, non-bloody stool points to Giardia (fat malabsorption)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Rotavirus: 2-3 days of vomiting before watery diarrhea."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE EXAM IS REALLY A DEHYDRATION EXAM. Blavo closed the first hour on this for a reason: in diarrhea, most of the physical exam is hunting for dehydration. Look for dry mucosa, decreased skin turgor, poor capillary refill, tachycardia, hypotension, sunken eyes, and reduced urine output. In an infant, the pathognomonic pair is the fontanelle: a sunken anterior fontanelle means dehydration; a bulging one means raised intracranial pressure (think meningitis). The exam loves to make you flip those two."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Infant sunken fontanelle = dehydration; bulging = raised ICP."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "The infant fontanelle is a two-way sign: sunken → dehydration, bulging → raised ICP. Same anatomy, opposite emergencies."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Secretory = voluminous watery that persists with fasting; osmotic = smaller volume that stops with fasting. Volume + fasting separate them."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "In any diarrhea workup, assess dehydration first — it is the finding that changes your disposition fastest."}, {"t": "q", "x": "What three stool characteristics let you sort a diarrhea into inflammatory, secretory, or osmotic right at the bedside?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Recognize the differential diagnosis of common infectious diarrhea", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. There is no rigid formal classification, but the working schema gastroenterologists carry — and the one that organizes your whole differential — is inflammatory vs non-inflammatory, with non-inflammatory splitting into secretory and osmotic. The classification is the differential diagnosis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SECRETORY / OSMOTIC FORK. The cleanest discriminator is what happens when the patient stops eating. Secretory diarrhea is enterotoxin-driven active secretion — the lumen stays wet whether or not food is present, so it is voluminous and persists with fasting (ETEC, cholera). Osmotic diarrhea depends on an unabsorbed solute pulling water in, so it is smaller-volume and resolves with fasting (rotavirus, EPEC, Giardia). Inflammatory diarrhea sits apart, marked by blood, mucus, and fecal leukocytes."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Secretory diarrhea persists with fasting; osmotic diarrhea resolves with it."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Inflammatory = blood + fecal leukocytes + fever; non-inflammatory lacks all three."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Type / Stool / Examples / Key tell): Inflammatory — Bloody, mucoid, fecal leukocytes, fever · EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter · Blood + leukocytes ; Secretory — Voluminous watery, non-bloody · ETEC, V. cholerae · Persists with fasting ; Osmotic — Small-volume watery, ± greasy · Rotavirus, Giardia, EPEC · Resolves with fasting"}, {"t": "p", "x": "MECHANISM UNDER THE FORK. Normal absorption runs on coupled transporters — SGLT1 (Na/glucose), NHE3 (Na/H), the DRA Cl⁻/HCO₃⁻ exchanger — and on tight junctions that gate the paracellular path. Toxins tip this balance: secretion up, absorption down. You don't need the molecular detail memorized, but knowing the machinery is why ORS (next LO) even works."}, {"t": "p", "x": "INTEGRATE THE EXPOSURE HISTORY. This is Blavo's \"Cyril Why Blavo\" lesson — the differential is only as good as the targeted questions you ask to collapse it. Travel and stream/well water raise ETEC and Giardia; day-care raises rotavirus and Shigella; recent antibiotics raise C. difficile; undercooked ground beef / fast food raises O157:H7. Generate the broad list, then let one or two intentional questions sort it."}, {"t": "key", "x": "The classification IS the differential: inflammatory vs secretory vs osmotic. Place the case in a bucket and the workup and treatment fall out."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Secretory and osmotic are both non-bloody — separate them by stool volume and the response to fasting, not by blood."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Calling every loose-stool patient \"gastroenteritis\" — it can be IBD/IBS, not infection. The term implies infectious but doesn't prove it."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A patient has voluminous watery non-bloody diarrhea that doesn't stop when they stop eating. Secretory or osmotic — and what is the reasoning?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Identify the workup of infectious diarrheas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Most diarrhea is mild, self-limited, and needs no workup at all — observation, fluids, and anticipatory guidance. You investigate only when a red flag raises the stakes: moderate/severe dehydration, an ill child or elderly patient, bloody or voluminous stool, duration >48 h, high fever, severe abdominal pain, recent antibiotics, or an immunocompromised host."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PICK THE TEST THAT CONFIRMS A HYPOTHESIS. Stool guaiac finds occult blood; calprotectin / lactoferrin are leukocyte proteins that detect inflammation more reliably than the fecal-leukocyte smear; stool culture & sensitivity targets bacterial causes in severe or high-risk cases; ova & parasites repeated ×3 catches Giardia a single sample misses; a stool osmotic gap >160 mOsm/kg marks osmotic diarrhea; and a urine specific gravity >1.020 with elevated BUN confirms dehydration. Blavo's frame: you order the test that validates a specific suspicion, never a shotgun panel."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Calprotectin / lactoferrin beat fecal leukocytes for detecting gut inflammation."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "A stool osmotic gap >160 mOsm/kg indicates osmotic diarrhea."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Suspected Giardia: repeat stool O&P ×3 before calling it negative."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Work up only the red flags (bloody/voluminous, severe dehydration, >48 h, fever, recent antibiotics, immunocompromised). Otherwise observe and rehydrate."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Calprotectin and lactoferrin are more reliable than the fecal-leukocyte smear for confirming intestinal inflammation."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Treating one negative O&P as ruling out Giardia — sensitivity is low, so repeat ×3 when the clinical picture fits."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Blavo says a test is run \"to validate what you think, not to find the answer.\" How should that change which stool study you order?"}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Recognize the management of common infectious diarrheas, including fluid and electrolyte management (ORS, IV)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Management is mostly rehydration, because most infectious diarrhea is self-limited — the body heals itself if you keep it in a workable fluid and electrolyte state. Blavo's childhood memory of a cholera outbreak in Ghana, and his later cholera intervention in Haiti, anchor the stakes: secretory losses can kill through dehydration even when the patient doesn't look classically \"septic.\" Oral rehydration is first-line."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHY ORS WORKS. Oral rehydration solution exploits glucose-coupled sodium cotransport (SGLT1): glucose pulls sodium across the mucosa, and water follows osmotically. That coupling is why ORS must contain both glucose and sodium in balance — the WHO formulation is ~245 mOsm/L, with Na 75 and glucose 75. It also explains why sodas and fruit juices are poor substitutes: their glucose far exceeds their sodium, so the unbalanced osmotic load can actually pull more water into the gut and worsen the diarrhea — Blavo's chart showing Coca-Cola's huge sugar load makes the point."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ORS works by glucose-sodium cotransport (SGLT1) pulling water across the gut."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Sodas/juices: glucose ≫ sodium → can worsen diarrheal losses."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHEN TO REACH FOR IV. Use ORT whenever possible; go intravenous only when ORT is not feasible or appropriate — persistent vomiting, severe dehydration, ileus, aspiration risk, or impaired mental status. Note that mild vomiting is NOT a contraindication to ORS. IV options (normal saline, half-normal saline, lactated Ringer's, D5/NS) are individualized to severity and labs; monitor closely and transition back to ORS once the patient is resuscitated."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE DRUG TRAPS. Antibiotics are reserved for severe febrile bacterial diarrhea or the immunocompromised — empiric use is not beneficial and can be harmful: they raise HUS risk in O157:H7 and prolong fecal shedding in Salmonella. Use antimotility (loperamide) and antiemetic agents cautiously. Bismuth subsalicylate risks Reye syndrome in patients <17 (it's a salicylate). The BRAT diet is obsolete (too restrictive), while zinc shortens duration and severity."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Bismuth subsalicylate risks Reye syndrome in children <17."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "In O157:H7, antibiotics increase HUS risk — withhold them."}, {"t": "key", "x": "ORS = glucose-sodium cotransport. Both ingredients are required; the glucose is what drives the sodium-and-water absorption that rehydrates."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "ORT first, IV only when oral fails (persistent vomiting, severe dehydration, ileus, aspiration risk). Mild vomiting alone is not a contraindication."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Empiric antibiotics / antimotility for every diarrhea — harmful in O157:H7 (HUS) and Salmonella (shedding). Treat with fluids, not reflexes."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Why is an ORS containing BOTH glucose and sodium more effective than plain water — and why is Coca-Cola a poor substitute?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Antibiotics for every bacterial diarrhea. The reflex to treat a \"bacterial\" bloody stool backfires in E. coli O157:H7, where antibiotics increase Shiga-toxin release and HUS risk. Treat with fluids. → LO 31.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Secretory = osmotic. Both are non-bloody, but secretory is voluminous and persists with fasting; osmotic is smaller-volume and resolves with fasting. → LO 31.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. \"Vomiting, so no oral fluids.\" Mild vomiting is not a contraindication to ORS; you can still rehydrate orally while the patient vomits a little. → LO 31.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Bismuth in a child. Bismuth subsalicylate is a salicylate → Reye syndrome risk in patients under 17. → LO 31.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Cytotoxin vs neurotoxin. C. difficile makes a cytotoxin; the neurotoxin producer is C. botulinum. → LO 31.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. One negative O&P rules out Giardia. A single ova-and-parasite exam is insensitive — repeat it ×3 when the picture fits. → LO 31.4"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"bloody diarrhea, stool grows O157:H7\" → withhold antibiotics. Fluids only; antibiotics worsen HUS."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"voluminous watery stools, no blood, rapid dehydration\" → secretory (ETEC/cholera), not osmotic."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"child is vomiting, so mom withheld fluids\" → still give ORS; mild vomiting isn't a contraindication."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"parent gave Pepto-Bismol to a 6-year-old\" → Reye-syndrome risk (salicylate)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"pseudomembranous colitis after antibiotics\" → C. difficile cytotoxin (not a neurotoxin)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"one O&P negative but greasy stools persist\" → repeat O&P ×3 for Giardia."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Oral rehydration & antimotility/antidiarrheal pharmacology — also Lec 41 (Laxative & Antidiarrheal Agents)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Secretory-vs-inflammatory reasoning reappears in the GI-bleed logic — also Lec 33-34 (GI Endoscopy), this doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Infectious vs inflammatory (IBD/IBS) overlap on the differential — revisited in later GI pathology"}]}]}, "33": {"prof": "Jeffrey Schneider, M.D.", "tldr": "Endoscopy is organized by what each scope can see and whether it is diagnostic, therapeutic, or both — and CRC screening (start at 45, colonoscopy offered first) is the single highest-yield piece.", "mustKnows": ["Diagnostic vs therapeutic vs both — tag every scope. EGD and EUS are both; ERCP is therapeutic (you already know the diagnosis); wireless capsule is diagnostic only (it can't biopsy or treat). This single frame answers most procedure questions.", "The #1 cause of a big lower-GI bleed is an upper source. A brisk upper bleed (e.g., duodenal ulcer) pumps maroon stool from below. It matters because endoscopic therapy stops upper bleeds (clip the vessel, band varices) but has limited power for lower bleeds — so exclude an upper source first.", "EUS = staging (and deep biopsy). Endoscopic ultrasound stages esophageal, gastric, and pancreatic cancer (absent widespread mets) and biopsies a pancreatic mass through the stomach wall. It is the answer to \"how do you biopsy the pancreatic mass\" — not percutaneous CT. MRCP is the noninvasive test for common-bile-duct stones.", "ERCP is the most dangerous scope — and it's therapeutic. Since MRCP, ERCP is reserved almost exclusively for therapy (relieve biliary obstruction: stones causing jaundice, gallstone pancreatitis, cholangitis; unblock a malignant duct). Complication rate ~10%; the dreaded one is post-ERCP pancreatitis.", "Barrett's → adenocarcinoma (lower esophagus). Barrett's (salmon mucosa, intestinal metaplasia) is a precursor of adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus; the upper esophagus gives squamous cell cancer. Surveil q3-5y; don't sit on a PPI for years without a look.", "Dysphagia logic: solids vs solids-and-liquids. Solids only = a structural narrowing (cancer, EoE rings, Schatzki ring). Solids AND liquids = a motility disorder (achalasia) — get a barium study first; endoscopy looks near-normal in motility disorders.", "CRC screening: start 45; colonoscopy first. Average-risk screening starts at 45; colonoscopy q10y is offered FIRST, with annual FIT only if colonoscopy is declined. High-risk (first-degree relative <60, or two first-degree relatives): colonoscopy q5y, starting age 40 or 10 yr before the youngest affected relative.", "Cologuard = detection, not prevention. Cologuard (FIT-DNA) is 92% sensitive for cancer but only 42% for advanced adenomas — so it finds cancer, it doesn't prevent it. Every positive needs a colonoscopy; it is contraindicated in high-risk patients and is not equivalent to colonoscopy."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Describe the role of endoscopic procedures for GI hemorrhage", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Endoscopy for a GI bleed turns on two questions: is the patient hemodynamically stable or unstable, and where is the source. Unstable patients (hypotensive, tachycardic, syncope) get volume and, if exsanguinating, unmatched blood — you resuscitate before you scope."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE PPI TRICK. Before endoscopy you start an IV proton pump inhibitor. It works not by reducing pain but by clot stability: acutely raising the gastric pH toward neutral lets the platelet clot hold (clot stability = pH + platelets). In places without a gastroenterologist, that is sometimes the only bridge for hours."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "An IV PPI raises gastric pH so the clot holds (clot stability = pH + platelets)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "UPPER IS TREATABLE; LOWER OFTEN IS NOT. The role of endoscopy in a bleed is both diagnostic and therapeutic — but the therapy is far more powerful for upper pathology. A bleeding ulcer with a visible vessel of the gastroduodenal artery gets clipped; esophageal varices (portal hypertension from cirrhosis) get banded. For lower-GI bleeding the endoscopic therapeutic potential is genuinely limited."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE EXAM'S FAVORITE LINE. Schneider repeats it: the most important cause of a big lower-GI bleed is an upper GI bleed moving fast. A brisk duodenal ulcer pumps maroon stool from below — and because you can stop an upper source but mostly cannot stop a lower one, you exclude the top first in a big, unstable bleed."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Endoscopic hemostasis works far better for UPPER than LOWER GI bleeds."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "A brisk upper source is the most important cause of a big lower-GI bleed."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Endoscopy can stop upper bleeds (clip ulcers, band varices) but has limited power for lower bleeds — which is why an upper source is excluded first."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Bleeding workup order: resuscitate (volume ± blood) → IV PPI → endoscopy to diagnose and treat."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Assuming maroon stool = a lower source. A fast duodenal-ulcer bleed presents from below; miss it and you miss the treatable lesion."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A patient pumps out large-volume maroon stool from below. Why is your first worry an UPPER source — and what does that change about management?"}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe the use of ERCP, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS), and wireless capsule endoscopy", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Beyond the standard EGD and colonoscopy, three scopes are each defined by what they can do. The trick is to tag each one diagnostic, therapeutic, or both."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Scope / Reaches / sees / Role / Core use): EGD — Mouth → 2nd duodenum · Both · GERD/Barrett's, ulcers, varices ; EUS — Behind stomach: pancreas, CBD, nodes · Both · Staging; biopsy pancreatic mass ; ERCP — Ampulla; bile & pancreatic ducts · Therapeutic · Relieve biliary obstruction ; Capsule — Small bowel · Dx only · Occult small-bowel bleed"}, {"t": "p", "x": "EUS = STAGING (and deep biopsy). Endoscopic ultrasound puts an ultrasound probe on the scope tip, so it sees behind the stomach — the pancreas, common bile duct, vessels, and nodes. Its indication is staging esophageal, gastric, and pancreatic cancer (in the absence of widespread metastases), and it biopsies a pancreatic mass through the stomach wall. Schneider's standing case: jaundice plus a pancreatic mass → the answer is EUS, not a percutaneous CT-guided biopsy (which risks tract seeding and undersampling). EUS also analyzes IPMN cyst fluid and diagnoses GISTs (submucosal — a surface biopsy reads normal)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "EUS stages esophageal/gastric/pancreatic cancer and biopsies a pancreatic mass through the stomach wall."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ERCP = THERAPEUTIC. ERCP is the most dangerous procedure gastroenterologists do: a side-viewing scope reaches the ampulla, cuts a sphincterotomy, and pulls out stones. Since MRCP can diagnose noninvasively, ERCP is now reserved almost exclusively for therapy — relieving biliary obstruction (stones causing jaundice, gallstone pancreatitis, or cholangitis; unblocking a malignant duct). It does not diagnose a pancreatic mass."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WCE = DIAGNOSTIC ONLY. Wireless capsule endoscopy is a swallowed camera (the makers named it M2A) for the small bowel beyond scope reach. Its #1 indication is occult GI bleeding with a negative upper and lower endoscopy — it usually finds angiodysplasia / AVMs. It cannot biopsy or treat, you don't know exactly where it is, and it is contraindicated in stricturing Crohn disease (it can lodge and require surgery)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ERCP is therapeutic (relieve obstruction), not diagnostic — MRCP/EUS diagnose."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Capsule endoscopy is diagnostic-only; #1 use is occult small-bowel bleed; avoid in stricturing Crohn."}, {"t": "key", "x": "EUS = staging. It stages and biopsies a pancreatic mass through the stomach wall in one step — the answer to \"how do you biopsy it?\""}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Sending a pancreatic mass to a radiologist for percutaneous biopsy, or doing ERCP to diagnose it — both wrong. EUS stages and biopsies; ERCP only treats."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Capsule = diagnostic only; ERCP = therapeutic; EGD and EUS = both. Tagging each scope answers most procedure questions."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A jaundiced patient has a pancreatic-head mass and no metastases. Which procedure stages AND biopsies it — and why not just send them to a radiologist?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "List the disease entities and endoscopic findings of the upper gastrointestinal tract", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Upper endoscopy (EGD) sees from the oropharynx to the second portion of the duodenum. The biggest indication is GERD — and the reason to scope reflux is to look for Barrett's esophagus, a silent change in the lining."}, {"t": "p", "x": "GERD → BARRETT'S → ADENOCARCINOMA. GERD's mechanism is a loose valve — transient lower esophageal sphincter relaxation, not excess acid. Chronic reflux can produce Barrett's: salmon-colored mucosa whose biopsy shows intestinal metaplasia, a precursor of adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus. Keep the esophagus's split straight: upper = squamous cell cancer, lower = adenocarcinoma. This is why it's irresponsible to sit on a PPI for years without a look; Barrett's gets surveyed every 3-5 years."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Barrett's (intestinal metaplasia) → adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus; upper = squamous."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DYSPHAGIA: ONE HISTORY QUESTION. The discriminator is what gets stuck. Solids only = a structural narrowing — cancer (not in a 30-year-old), eosinophilic esophagitis (concentric rings, atopic patient, frequent food impaction), or a Schatzki ring (a single distal ring, the 'steakhouse' bolus). Solids AND liquids = a motility disorder (achalasia) — and here endoscopy is near-normal, so get a barium study first. Achalasia's birds-beak is a radiographic, not endoscopic, finding."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Solids only = structural narrowing; solids + liquids = motility (barium first)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DYSPEPSIA, AND THE BEST-TEST TRAP. Dyspepsia (bloating, belching, no heartburn) is usually a functional motility issue; scope it when conservative measures fail or alarm features appear. While in there, you can biopsy for H. pylori and celiac disease — but Schneider's repeated burn: endoscopy is NOT the best test for either. Because both are patchy, the noninvasive tests win: urea breath / stool antigen for H. pylori and tissue transglutaminase IgA for celiac, especially to confirm eradication or diagnosis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "For H. pylori and celiac, noninvasive tests beat endoscopic biopsy (patchy disease)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Barrett's = adenocarcinoma precursor (lower esophagus, intestinal metaplasia). The esophagus splits: upper squamous, lower adeno."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "EoE = multiple concentric rings in an atopic patient with impactions; Schatzki = a single distal ring. Both cause solid dysphagia."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Calling endoscopic biopsy the best test for H. pylori or celiac — the disease is patchy, so noninvasive tests are better."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A patient has progressive dysphagia. What single feature of the history tells you to think 'structural' versus 'motility' before any test?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe the use of lower endoscopic procedures for the differential diagnosis of the colorectal area", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Colonoscopy diagnoses the colorectal differential and removes polyps, but for bleeding its therapeutic reach is limited. The high-yield separations are the diverticular pair and the IBD patterns."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DIVERTICULOSIS vs DIVERTICULITIS — never mix osis and itis. DiverticulOSIS is the #1 cause of acute, painless, hemodynamically significant hematochezia over age 50, and it stops on its own ~80% of the time. DiverticulITIS is the inflamed one — left-lower-quadrant pain and fever, usually without significant bleeding — and colonoscopy is contraindicated in the acute phase. (And the seeds-and-nuts taboo is debunked.)"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "DiverticulOSIS = painless significant lower bleed (stops ~80%); diverticulITIS = LLQ pain + fever, no bleed."}, {"t": "p", "x": "OTHER LOWER BLEEDS. Angiodysplasia / AVMs weep slowly (often found on capsule); internal hemorrhoids give small-volume bright-red blood; ischemic colitis is painful bloody diarrhea at watershed zones; and colorectal cancer bleeds occultly through the adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence — the reason we screen (LO 33.6)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "IBD IS A VISUAL DIAGNOSIS. Schneider's line: \"the diagnosis is more visual than histologic.\" Crohn disease is discontinuous — skip lesions, cobblestoning, aphthous and serpiginous ulcers, anywhere mouth-to-anus. Ulcerative colitis is continuous from the rectum proximally. If you see the word cobblestoning, say Crohn's."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Crohn's = discontinuous skip lesions + cobblestoning; UC = continuous from the rectum."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Mixing diverticulOSIS (painless bleed) and diverticulITIS (LLQ pain, fever, no bleed). Say the wrong one and you get the question wrong."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Cobblestoning or skip lesions → Crohn's; continuous from the rectum → ulcerative colitis. IBD is read more by eye than by biopsy."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Acute painless significant hematochezia in the elderly → diverticulosis (stops ~80%); first exclude a fast upper source."}, {"t": "q", "x": "An elderly patient has acute, painless, large-volume hematochezia and is stable. What is the most likely source, and why is endoscopic therapy limited?"}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Understand the indications and complications of endoscopy", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Indications run through the other LOs; the complications and contraindications are the testable headlines. ERCP is the most dangerous procedure gastroenterologists perform, with an overall complication rate around 10%. Its signature complication is post-ERCP pancreatitis — you are working at the tiny opening where the bile and pancreatic ducts meet, so even a flawless operator can inflame the pancreas."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ERCP is the most dangerous GI scope (~10% complications); the dreaded one is post-ERCP pancreatitis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CONTRAINDICATIONS WORTH KNOWING. Colonoscopy is contraindicated in acute diverticulitis (abdominal inflammation — you don't push a scope through it). Wireless capsule is contraindicated in stricturing Crohn disease (it can lodge). General complications across scopes include bleeding and perforation; ERCP adds bleeding from the sphincterotomy and duodenal perforation."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Colonoscopy is contraindicated in acute diverticulitis; capsule in stricturing Crohn's."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Forgetting that ERCP — not the bigger-looking colonoscopy — is the highest-risk scope, because of post-ERCP pancreatitis."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Don't scope through inflammation: acute diverticulitis contraindicates colonoscopy; stricturing Crohn's contraindicates the capsule."}, {"t": "key", "x": "The two procedure headlines: ERCP = most dangerous (pancreatitis ~10%); capsule = safest but powerless (diagnostic only, can lodge in a stricture)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Which endoscopic procedure carries the highest complication rate, and what is its signature complication?"}]}, {"id": 6, "statement": "State the colonoscopy and the screening recommendations of the American College of Gastroenterology", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Schneider calls screening his primary responsibility — and the single highest-yield block. The logic is the adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence: precancerous adenomatous polyps become cancer over roughly a decade, so we scope to find and remove them."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE NUMBERS (2022 update). Average-risk screening now starts at 45 (down from 50; African Americans also 45). Colonoscopy every 10 years is offered FIRST; annual FIT is for patients who decline colonoscopy — not an equal menu option. Individualize ages 76-85; stop routine screening by 85 (or earlier when life expectancy is under ~10 years)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Average-risk CRC screening: start 45; colonoscopy q10y offered first; annual FIT if declined."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HIGH-RISK TIMING. A first-degree relative with CRC/advanced adenoma under 60, or two first-degree relatives at any age, makes a patient high-risk: colonoscopy every 5 years, starting at age 40 OR 10 years before the youngest affected relative, whichever is earlier. (Relative diagnosed at 55 → start at 45 by the math, but 40 is earlier, so start 40.)"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "High-risk: colonoscopy q5y, start 40 or 10 yr before the youngest affected relative."}, {"t": "p", "x": "COLOGUARD — DETECTION, NOT PREVENTION. Cologuard is FIT-DNA (FIT plus a methylated-DNA assay), repeated every 3 years. It is ~92% sensitive for cancer but only ~42% for advanced adenomas — so it finds cancer but doesn't prevent it (you can't remove a polyp through a stool test). Every positive needs a colonoscopy; only ~4% of positives have cancer; and it is contraindicated in high-risk patients. Offer it only to someone refusing colonoscopy — never as an equivalent."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cologuard (FIT-DNA, q3y) = 92% cancer / 42% advanced adenoma → detection, not prevention."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Group / Start / Interval / Notes): Average-risk — 45 · Colonoscopy q10y (first) · Annual FIT only if colonoscopy declined ; High-risk — 40, or 10 yr before youngest case · Colonoscopy q5y · FDR <60, or two FDRs ; Cologuard (FIT-DNA) — — · q3y · 92% cancer / 42% adenoma; not high-risk"}, {"t": "key", "x": "Average-risk: start 45, colonoscopy q10y offered first, annual FIT only if declined. High-risk: q5y, start 40 or 10 yr before the youngest case."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Telling a patient a stool test equals colonoscopy — colonoscopy is offered first; FIT/Cologuard are for those who decline, and Cologuard is not equivalent."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Cologuard = detection, not prevention: great at finding cancer (92%), poor at advanced adenomas (42%), useless in high-risk, and every positive still needs a colonoscopy."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A patient's primary-care office told them a stool test is an equal alternative to colonoscopy. What is wrong with that, and what should have been said?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. ERCP for diagnosis. ERCP is therapeutic (relieve obstruction); diagnose with EUS / MRCP. With MRCP available, ERCP is reserved for treatment. → LO 33.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. \"Endoscopy is the best test for H. pylori / celiac.\" Both are patchy, so noninvasive tests (urea breath / stool antigen; tTG-IgA) are better. → LO 33.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. DiverticulOSIS = diverticulITIS. OSIS = painless significant bleed; ITIS = LLQ pain + fever, no bleed (and colonoscopy is contraindicated). → LO 33.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Stopping a lower-GI bleed endoscopically. Endoscopic therapy is limited below; upper bleeds you can clip or band. → LO 33.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Barrett's → squamous. Barrett's → adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus; squamous is the upper esophagus. → LO 33.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Biopsy a pancreatic mass percutaneously. Use EUS — it stages and biopsies through the stomach wall; percutaneous biopsy risks seeding. → LO 33.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. \"Stool test or colonoscopy — your choice.\" Colonoscopy is offered FIRST; FIT is for those who decline, and Cologuard is not equivalent. → LO 33.6"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "8. Cologuard for everyone (and high-risk). It is detection-not-prevention, only 42% for advanced adenomas, and contraindicated in high-risk. → LO 33.6"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"we did an ERCP to find out what was going on\" → wrong framing; ERCP treats, EUS/MRCP diagnose."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"scope biopsy was negative for H. pylori, so it's gone\" → confirm with urea breath / stool antigen."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"elderly, painless, large-volume maroon stool, stable\" → diverticulosis (after excluding a fast upper source)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"brisk maroon stool, hypotensive\" → think upper source moving fast (treatable), not just \"lower bleed.\""}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"salmon tongue above the GE junction, years on a PPI\" → Barrett's → adenocarcinoma; surveil q3-5y."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"jaundice + pancreatic-head mass, how do you biopsy?\" → EUS, not percutaneous."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. \"told the stool test is equivalent to colonoscopy\" → colonoscopy first; FIT only if colonoscopy refused."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "8. \"Cologuard was negative, so reassured\" → only 42% for advanced adenomas; detection, not prevention."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — H. pylori testing & acid-suppression pharmacology — also Lec 35 (Drugs for Peptic Ulcers & Gastric Acidity)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Esophageal varices, portal hypertension & cirrhosis — also Lec 39-40 (Chronic Liver Disease)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — ERCP, choledocholithiasis & biliary obstruction — also Lec 44-45 (Pathology / Surgery of the Biliary Tract)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — DiverticulOSIS (bleed) vs diverticulITIS (inflammation) — also Lec 38 (Abdominal Pain / Diverticulitis)"}]}]}, "35": {"prof": "Dr. Mayur Parmar", "tldr": "GI pharmacology by target: acid suppression climbs antacids → H2 blockers → PPIs to H. pylori quadruple therapy; antiemetics block the vomiting-reflex receptors — 5-HT3, dopamine, NK1, histamine.", "mustKnows": ["1. One pump, four switches. Acetylcholine (M3), histamine (H2), and gastrin (CCK-B) all activate protein kinases that drive the H⁺/K⁺-ATPase proton pump to secrete acid, while PGE2 is inhibitory and cytoprotective. Every acid drug works by blocking one of these switches or the pump itself.", "2. The acid-suppression ladder. Antacids neutralize acid already present (transient); H2RAs reversibly block H2 and cut acid ~60-70% (best nocturnally, prone to tachyphylaxis); PPIs irreversibly inhibit the pump for >90% suppression (resynthesis ~18-24 h); vonoprazan (PCAB) reversibly blocks the pump's K⁺ site without needing acid activation.", "3. Cimetidine is the interaction drug. Cimetidine is a potent CYP450 inhibitor (↑warfarin, diazepam, eletriptan), has antiandrogenic effects at high dose (gynecomastia / galactorrhea), and can ↑serum creatinine without true renal injury. Famotidine is ~20× more potent, longer-acting, and has far fewer interactions — the preferred H2RA.", "4. PPI + clopidogrel = the CYP2C19 trap. Omeprazole and esomeprazole inhibit CYP2C19, which is the enzyme that activates the prodrug clopidogrel — so they blunt its antiplatelet effect and the pair should be avoided. Pantoprazole is the safer PPI when clopidogrel is required.", "5. Four receptors, four classes; acute vs delayed. Vomiting is integrated at the chemoreceptor trigger zone (CTZ) / area postrema, driven by four receptor pairs: ACh (M1) → scopolamine; histamine (H1) → meclizine/dimenhydrinate; substance P (NK1) → the -pitants; serotonin (5-HT3) → the -setrons. In CINV, the acute phase is serotonin/5-HT3 (peripheral, <24 h) and the delayed phase is substance P/NK1 (central, days 1-5) — setrons cover acute, -pitants cover delayed.", "6. Meclizine is H1, NOT H2 — the planted trap. Meclizine and dimenhydrinate are H1 antihistamines for motion sickness/vestibular nausea; scopolamine is the M1 antagonist. A stem calling meclizine an \"H2 antagonist\" is a deliberate distractor — H2 blockers are the -tidines for acid suppression. H1/M1 agents are ineffective at the CTZ, so they don't cover CINV.", "7. D2 antagonists → EPS; two different boxed warnings. All D2 antagonists (prochlorperazine, promethazine, droperidol, metoclopramide, amisulpride) cause extrapyramidal symptoms. Metoclopramide carries a boxed warning for irreversible tardive dyskinesia — avoid use beyond 12 weeks. Droperidol carries a boxed warning for QT prolongation/torsades, requiring a 12-lead ECG before and 2-3 h after dosing.", "8. All D2 antagonists are contraindicated in Parkinson's. Blocking dopamine worsens a disease defined by dopamine loss, so every D2 antagonist antiemetic is contraindicated in Parkinson's disease — prochlorperazine, promethazine, droperidol, metoclopramide, and amisulpride alike. It is the same D2 blockade that produces their EPS."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Describe the physiology of gastric acid secretion and the cellular targets that regulate it", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Parmar anchors the entire lecture on one picture: the parietal cell and the H⁺/K⁺-ATPase proton pump that does the actual work of secreting hydrogen ions into the gastric lumen in exchange for K⁺. Everything you study after this — every drug class — is just a different way of getting at that pump, so it pays to fix the wiring now. Four signals converge on it: three stimulate, one restrains."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE THREE STIMULATORS. Acetylcholine binds M3 muscarinic receptors, histamine (released from nearby ECL cells) binds H2 receptors, and gastrin binds CCK-B (gastrin) receptors. Each receptor, once bound, activates protein kinases that switch on the proton pump — so the three pathways are parallel inputs to one output. That parallel wiring is exactly why a histamine blocker only gets you partway: shut off H2 and you still have ACh and gastrin driving the pump. The exam's favorite move here is to swap the receptor subtypes — histamine is H2, not H1; gastrin is CCK-B, not CCK-A."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Parietal-cell stimulators: ACh→M3, histamine→H2, gastrin→CCK-B, all → the proton pump."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE INHIBITORY ARM. Prostaglandin E2 is the counterweight: it binds parietal-cell EP receptors to inhibit acid secretion while it boosts mucus, bicarbonate, and mucosal blood flow — the cytoprotective package. Hold onto this, because it pays off twice downstream: it is why NSAIDs (which knock out protective prostaglandins) cause ulcers, and why the PGE1 analog misoprostol can prevent them. PGE2 is the only one of the four that turns acid down."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PGE2 is inhibitory + cytoprotective (mucus, HCO₃, blood flow) — the opposite of the other three."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Every acid drug maps onto this one diagram: antacids neutralize the product, H2RAs block H2, PPIs/PCAB hit the pump, misoprostol mimics PGE2. Learn the wiring once."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Histamine acts at H2 (not H1) and gastrin at CCK-B (not CCK-A) on the parietal cell — the subtype swap is the classic distractor."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Three parallel ON switches (ACh, histamine, gastrin) feed one pump — which is why blocking the pump itself (PPI) beats blocking any single upstream receptor."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Four molecules regulate the parietal cell. Three turn acid ON and one turns it DOWN — name each, its receptor, and which way it pushes."}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe the agents used to treat peptic ulcers and gastric acidity and their adverse effects", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. This is the workhorse LO — Parmar marches one class per slide on a fixed template (mechanism / uses / adverse effects), and he is explicit that you should learn the class logic rather than memorize every interchangeable agent. The organizing spine is a potency ladder: antacids neutralize, H2RAs block a receptor, PPIs and PCABs hit the pump itself. Climb the ladder and acid suppression deepens."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ANTACIDS — NEUTRALIZE, DON'T SUPPRESS. These are weak bases that react with gastric HCl to form salt and water; rapid onset (minutes), short duration (30-60 min), good only for occasional dyspepsia and heartburn, weak in erosive esophagitis or true ulcer disease. The adverse effects fall out of the cation: aluminum → constipation (plus hypophosphatemia), magnesium → diarrhea, so the two are combined to counterbalance the bowel. Calcium carbonate is the preferred antacid in pregnancy; sodium bicarbonate is a systemic alkalinizer used for metabolic acidosis and salicylate toxicity but risks sodium overload; bismuth subsalicylate joins H. pylori therapy and famously turns the tongue and stool grayish-black. Parmar repeats one OTC-safety line all lecture: don't use an antacid beyond 2 weeks without seeing a doctor."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Aluminum → constipation; magnesium → diarrhea — combined to counterbalance."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "CaCO₃ = preferred antacid in pregnancy; NaHCO₃ = systemic alkalinizer (acidosis, salicylate toxicity)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "H2RAs — REVERSIBLE, ~60-70%. Ranitidine, famotidine, cimetidine competitively and reversibly block H2 receptors, cutting acid ~60-70% and working best against nocturnal (rather than meal-stimulated) secretion — hence dosing at bedtime, and the mnemonic that the ‘-tidine’ drugs are taken before you dine. Two H2RA-specific facts earn flags: tachyphylaxis develops within days to weeks of continuous use, and reversible confusion can appear in the elderly or renally impaired. Ranitidine (Zantac) is the one Parmar brings back specifically to tell its story: it was pulled from the market because the manufacturing process generated the carcinogen NDMA — “that's why now it's part of my lecture,” reformulated and returned."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "H2RAs reversibly block H2 → ~60-70% acid reduction, best nocturnally; tachyphylaxis in days-weeks."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CIMETIDINE IS THE OUTLIER. Among the H2RAs, cimetidine is the first-generation drug that carries the baggage: antiandrogenic effects at high dose (gynecomastia, galactorrhea), a rise in serum creatinine without true renal injury, and a thick list of CYP-mediated interactions (LO 35.4). Famotidine is the one to default to — about 20× more potent than cimetidine, longer-acting (~12 h vs ~6 h), and largely free of those effects. Parmar called the famotidine-over-cimetidine point out as something you will actually use prescribing."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PPIs — IRREVERSIBLE, >90%. The ‘-prazole’ drugs (omeprazole, esomeprazole, pantoprazole, lansoprazole, dexlansoprazole, rabeprazole) are prodrugs that, once activated in the acidic parietal-cell canaliculi, irreversibly inhibit the H⁺/K⁺-ATPase and suppress >90% of basal and stimulated acid. Because the bond is covalent, the effect outlasts the drug: plasma half-life is short, but secretion only recovers as new pumps are made over ~18-24 hours. Dose before a meal for best effect. Two PK pearls Parmar repeated: esomeprazole and pantoprazole are the only IV PPIs, and long-term use carries real risks (next LO covers B12; also hypomagnesemia, fracture from impaired calcium absorption, and C. difficile from lost acid barrier). Use the lowest effective dose for the shortest duration."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PPIs = prodrugs that irreversibly inhibit the pump → >90% suppression; recovery needs ~18-24 h of new pump synthesis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Only IV-available PPIs: esomeprazole and pantoprazole."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PCAB, MISOPROSTOL, SUCRALFATE — THE REST OF THE LADDER. Vonoprazan, a potassium-competitive acid blocker (PCAB), reversibly competes with K⁺ at the pump, is acid-stable with rapid onset, and does not need acid activation — a newer agent Parmar notes “wasn't in last year's lecture.” Misoprostol is a synthetic PGE1 analog that inhibits acid and boosts the mucous barrier; its niche is NSAID-induced ulcer prophylaxis, and it is contraindicated in pregnancy (abortifacient). Sucralfate is a sucrose-sulfate / aluminum-hydroxide complex that forms a viscous protective gel over the ulcer base — but only in an acidic pH, which sets up its key interaction rule (LO 35.4)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Vonoprazan (PCAB) = reversible K-competitive pump blocker; no acid activation needed."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Misoprostol = PGE1 analog for NSAID-ulcer prophylaxis; pregnancy-contraindicated."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "PPI vs PCAB: both target the pump, but PPIs bind irreversibly and need acid activation, while vonoprazan blocks the K⁺ site reversibly and is acid-stable."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Read the suffix: -tidine = H2RA, -prazole = PPI, -prazan = PCAB. The endings sort the class faster than any list."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Don't pin gynecomastia on ‘the H2 blocker’ generically — it is cimetidine specifically; famotidine and ranitidine are free of the antiandrogenic effect."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Walk the acid-suppression ladder from weakest to strongest and name the one signature adverse effect that flags each rung."}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Compare the relationship of histamine-2 receptor antagonists to proton pump inhibitors and the effect of acid suppression on vitamin B12 and intrinsic factor", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The whole point of this LO is one comparison: H2RA versus PPI. Parmar drew the contrast explicitly in numbers, and the exam loves it because the two drugs sit on the same pathway but act at different points — a receptor versus the pump."}, {"t": "p", "x": "POTENCY AND DURABILITY. An H2RA reversibly blocks a single receptor (H2), so it removes only the histamine input and reaches about 60-70% acid reduction — strongest against nocturnal acid, and blunted further by tachyphylaxis over days to weeks. A PPI shuts the final common step, the pump itself, and does so irreversibly, reaching >90% suppression of both basal and stimulated acid with an effect that outlasts the drug. So the relationship is simple and directional: same axis, but the PPI is more potent, more durable, and not subject to tolerance. That is why the typical sequence is a PPI to heal, then an H2RA for maintenance once erosions are gone."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PPI >90% irreversible vs H2RA ~60-70% reversible (nocturnal, tachyphylaxis) — PPI is more potent and durable."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE B12 COST OF ACID SUPPRESSION. Strength has a price over time. Both classes — PPIs on slide 17, long-term H2RAs on slide 11 — decrease the bioavailability of vitamin B12. The mechanism is the whole reason this LO pairs acid with B12: gastric acid is required to cleave cobalamin (B12) off dietary protein before it can be picked up for absorption. Suppress acid for long enough (the H2RA warning specifies ≥2 years) and that release step fails, so serum B12 drifts down — a quiet, chronic-use adverse effect rather than an acute one."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Chronic acid suppression (PPI or long-term H2RA) ↓vitamin B12 — acid is needed to free B12 from food."}, {"t": "p", "x": "INTRINSIC FACTOR — ADDED SCAFFOLDING. Parmar didn't cover intrinsic factor, but the LO names it, so for completeness: intrinsic factor is made by the same parietal cells that secrete acid and is the carrier that B12 needs for absorption in the terminal ileum — which is why loss of parietal-cell function (as in atrophic gastritis or autoimmune pernicious anemia) causes B12 deficiency. Standard acid-suppressive drugs lower B12 by blocking acid-dependent release of B12 from food, not by destroying intrinsic factor."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "H2RA vs PPI: same pathway, different target — H2RA blocks the H2 receptor (~60-70%, reversible, tachyphylaxis); PPI blocks the pump (>90%, irreversible)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Picture the sequence: PPI to heal the erosive disease, then step down to an H2RA for maintenance once erosions have resolved."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Don't confuse the two B12 mechanisms: acid-suppressive drugs impair acid-dependent release of B12 from food; they do not knock out intrinsic factor (that is the pernicious-anemia route)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Two patients need GERD control — one started on an H2RA, one on a PPI. What two features make the PPI the stronger choice, and what is the long-term cost of that strength?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe the clinically significant drug interactions of acid-suppressive and mucosal-protective agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Parmar flagged the interaction material directly — “focus from exam point of view, this is important” — while warning that the full list reads as an unmemorizable laundry. The way through is to sort by mechanism: enzyme inhibition (CYP), a change in gastric pH, and physical binding/chelation. Get the three buckets and any specific pair is predictable."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CIMETIDINE = CYP450 INHIBITION. Cimetidine is the broad CYP450 inhibitor of the group: it raises levels of warfarin, diazepam, and eletriptan (and many others) by slowing their metabolism, which is why those co-prescriptions get dangerous. It also raises serum creatinine without causing real renal impairment (it blocks creatinine's tubular secretion, not filtration). Famotidine has far fewer interactions — the practical reason it has displaced cimetidine. Slide 14 lays the serious interactions out as warfarin / diazepam / eletriptan; pin those three as your representatives."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cimetidine = CYP450 inhibitor → ↑warfarin / diazepam / eletriptan; also ↑SCr without renal injury."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PPI + CLOPIDOGREL = THE CYP2C19 TRAP. This is the single highest-yield PPI interaction. Clopidogrel is a prodrug that must be activated by CYP2C19; omeprazole and esomeprazole inhibit CYP2C19, so they reduce clopidogrel's activation and blunt its antiplatelet effect — avoid the combination, and reach for pantoprazole (minimal CYP2C19 effect) when a stented patient needs a PPI. Separately, because PPIs raise gastric pH, they impair absorption of drugs that need an acidic environment (digoxin, ketoconazole, itraconazole) — the pH-change bucket."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Omeprazole/esomeprazole inhibit CYP2C19 → ↓activation of clopidogrel; use pantoprazole instead."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE pH AND BINDING RULES. Two more patterns close the LO. Sucralfate needs an acidic pH to form its gel, so it must not be co-administered with PPIs, H2RAs, or antacids, and it impairs absorption of quinolone antibiotics by binding them — the chelation/binding bucket. Antacids likewise bind or chelate many drugs (tetracyclines, bisphosphonates, iron, digoxin, quinolones), so the fix is mechanical: separate dosing by ~2-4 hours rather than co-administer."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Sucralfate needs acidic pH (no PPI/H2RA/antacid co-admin) and impairs quinolone absorption."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Antacids chelate tetracyclines/bisphosphonates/iron/quinolones → space dosing ~2-4 h."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Stent on clopidogrel and needs acid suppression? Choose pantoprazole — avoid omeprazole and esomeprazole (CYP2C19 inhibitors that blunt clopidogrel)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Cimetidine raising creatinine is a pseudo-rise — it blocks tubular secretion of creatinine, so the GFR is actually unchanged."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Co-dosing sucralfate with a PPI — the raised pH stops sucralfate from gelling, so the protectant simply doesn't work. Space them, or pick one."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Three different mechanisms drive the interactions in this lecture — CYP inhibition, a raised gastric pH, and physical binding. Give the headline drug pair for each."}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Describe the regimens used for Helicobacter pylori eradication", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Parmar time-boxed this to a few minutes but framed it as high-stakes — H. pylori is a common infection linked to peptic ulcer disease and an established risk factor for gastric adenocarcinoma and MALT lymphoma. The cancer link is the reason eradication is taken seriously, and the reason the rules tightened in the 2024 guidelines."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHY IT'S COMBINATION THERAPY. Eradication always pairs acid suppression with antibiotics, and each half has a job. The PPI (or PCAB) suppresses acid and promotes mucosal healing — and a higher gastric pH also makes the antibiotics work better. The antibiotics kill the organism and cut recurrence and complications. Bismuth subsalicylate adds antimicrobial punch and helps overcome antibiotic resistance. Antibiotic selection is driven by resistance patterns, prior use, allergy, and cost — which is exactly why clarithromycin fell out of favor."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "H. pylori = risk factor for peptic ulcer disease, gastric adenocarcinoma, and MALT lymphoma."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE GOLD-STANDARD REGIMEN. The preferred first-line is the 14-day Optimized Bismuth Quadruple Therapy (BQT): PPI + tetracycline + metronidazole + bismuth. (Parmar: don't sweat the dosing frequency — just know it as the gold standard.) The modern 14-day alternatives are PCAB Dual Therapy (vonoprazan + amoxicillin) and Rifabutin-Based Triple Therapy. The key change to know: clarithromycin was dropped from first-line use because of widespread resistance in North America, which made the old clarithromycin-triple unreliable. Commonly used antibiotics now are tetracycline, metronidazole, amoxicillin, and rifabutin."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "First-line: 14-day BQT = PPI + tetracycline + metronidazole + bismuth; alternatives = PCAB-dual, rifabutin-triple."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Clarithromycin dropped from first-line → resistance."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CONFIRMATION IS NOW MANDATORY. The 2024-guideline headline Parmar stressed: after the 14-day course, proof of eradication is now mandatory for every treated patient — documented with a fecal antigen test, urea breath test, or gastric biopsy. Eradicating the organism measurably reduces the risk of PUD complications (bleeding, perforation, gastric-outlet obstruction) and of gastric cancer, so confirming the cure is the point, not an afterthought."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Eradication confirmation is mandatory (fecal antigen, urea breath test, or biopsy) after therapy."}, {"t": "key", "x": "First-line H. pylori = 14-day BQT (PPI + tetracycline + metronidazole + bismuth); PCAB-dual and rifabutin-triple are the modern alternatives."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Reaching for clarithromycin triple — it was dropped from first-line for resistance. And acid suppression alone never eradicates the organism."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "After treating, confirm eradication with a fecal antigen test, urea breath test, or biopsy — it is now mandatory for every patient."}, {"t": "q", "x": "An H. pylori-positive ulcer patient in a high-clarithromycin-resistance region: what is the gold-standard regimen, what changed about it recently, and what must you do after 14 days?"}]}, {"id": 6, "statement": "List the categories of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Parmar builds this whole lecture as a receptor map, so the first move is to learn the categories, not the individual drugs. Nausea and vomiting are integrated at the chemoreceptor trigger zone (CTZ) / area postrema and the vomiting center, and four neurotransmitter-receptor pairs feed them: ACh (M1), histamine (H1), substance P (NK1), and serotonin (5-HT3). Each pair has a drug class that blocks it. Two adjunct families — cannabinoids (CB1 agonists) and benzodiazepines (GABA-A modulators) — plus dexamethasone and olanzapine round out the rescue/adjuvant tier."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE DRUG-ENDING SHORTCUTS. Two name endings do most of the binning for you: the -setrons (ondansetron, dolasetron, granisetron, palonosetron) are the 5-HT3 antagonists, and the -pitants (aprepitant, fosaprepitant, netupitant, rolapitant) are the NK1 antagonists. The D2 antagonists are a mixed-name group (prochlorperazine, promethazine, droperidol, metoclopramide, amisulpride), and the antihistamine/antimuscarinic motion-sickness agents are scopolamine (M1) and meclizine/dimenhydrinate (H1). Prokinetics are a separate list organized by mechanism, and metoclopramide deliberately appears in both buckets."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "-setron = 5-HT3 antagonist; -pitant = NK1 antagonist."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Four vomiting receptors: M1, H1, NK1, 5-HT3 — one drug class each."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Antiemetics sort by receptor target: M1 (scopolamine), H1 (meclizine/dimenhydrinate), D2 (the mixed group), 5-HT3 (-setrons), NK1 (-pitants), plus cannabinoid/benzo/steroid adjuncts."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "The -setron / -pitant endings bin two whole classes on sight — anchor the rest of the lecture on these two name tells."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Scopolamine = M1 (muscarinic); meclizine/dimenhydrinate = H1 (histamine). Same motion-sickness use, different receptors."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Parmar groups antiemetics by their receptor target. Name the four core receptors and the drug class that blocks each."}]}, {"id": 7, "statement": "Discuss the mechanism of action of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The mechanism story is the heart of the lecture, and Parmar tells it as one vomiting-reflex framework: stimuli converge on the CTZ/area postrema and the vomiting center in the floor of the fourth ventricle, and each antiemetic class simply blocks one input. Get the framework first and every drug's MOA is just \"which receptor does it sit on.\""}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE TWO CHEMO PATHWAYS — ACUTE vs DELAYED. Chemotherapy drives nausea two ways, and this is the most-repeated point in the lecture. Peripherally, it makes enterochromaffin cells release serotonin onto 5-HT3 receptors on vagal afferents — the acute phase (resolves within ~24 h). Centrally, it triggers release of substance P onto NK1 receptors in the area postrema — the delayed phase (days 1-5). So 5-HT3 antagonists (setrons) own the acute phase and NK1 antagonists (-pitants) own the delayed phase; a highly emetogenic regimen needs both, plus dexamethasone."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Acute CINV = serotonin → 5-HT3 (peripheral); delayed CINV = substance P → NK1 (central)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Setrons cover the acute phase; -pitants cover the delayed phase."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE OTHER BLOCKERS, BY SITE. Scopolamine (M1) and the H1 antihistamines act centrally at the area postrema and on the vestibular system — which is why they treat motion sickness but, as Parmar stresses, are ineffective at the CTZ (so they don't cover CINV). D2 antagonists block dopamine in the CTZ. Setrons work at two sites at once — centrally in the area postrema and peripherally on GI vagal terminals — and selectively, without meaningful D2, H1, or muscarinic activity. NK1 antagonists block substance P in the area postrema and on vagal afferents."}, {"t": "p", "x": "METOCLOPRAMIDE — THE DUAL DRUG. Metoclopramide is the one to understand mechanistically, because it works in two compartments. Centrally it is a D2 antagonist at the CTZ (the antiemetic effect, no antipsychotic activity). Peripherally it facilitates cholinergic transmission in the gut — relieving dopamine's brake on ACh release — which raises lower-esophageal-sphincter tone, accelerates gastric emptying, and promotes small-bowel transit (the prokinetic effect, revisited in LO 36.3). That second action is why it treats diabetic gastroparesis, and why the GLP-1 weight-loss agents — which slow gastric emptying — can produce the gastroparesis metoclopramide reverses."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PROKINETICS BY MECHANISM. The prokinetic class is a mechanism quiz waiting to happen: erythromycin is a motilin receptor agonist (short-term only — receptors downregulate); prucalopride is a selective 5-HT4 agonist; bethanechol is a direct muscarinic agonist; and neostigmine is an AChE inhibitor (raising gut ACh, used for colonic pseudo-obstruction). All converge on the same outcome — coordinated GI motility and faster gastric emptying — by different receptors."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Erythromycin = motilin agonist; prucalopride = 5-HT4 agonist; neostigmine = AChE inhibitor."}, {"t": "key", "x": "One framework: stimuli converge on the CTZ/area postrema → vomiting center, and each antiemetic class blocks one receptor input (M1/H1/D2/5-HT3/NK1)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Acute CINV = 5-HT3/serotonin (peripheral, <24 h); delayed CINV = NK1/substance P (central, days 1-5). Phase tells you the class."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Metoclopramide is two drugs in one: central D2 antagonist (antiemetic) + peripheral cholinergic facilitation (prokinetic — ↑LES tone, gastric emptying)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A chemotherapy patient is nauseated immediately, then again on day 3. Which mediator and receptor drive each episode, and which drug covers each?"}]}, {"id": 8, "statement": "Discuss the therapeutic and adverse effects of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Therapeutic uses cluster around a short vocabulary you'll see repeated on every slide — CINV (chemotherapy-induced), PONV (postoperative), RINV (radiation-induced), motion sickness, and gastroparesis. Because the indications overlap so heavily, the exam discriminates by adverse effect: each class has a signature toxicity, and that's where Parmar spends his emphasis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "D2 ANTAGONISTS → EPS, AND TWO DISTINCT BOXED WARNINGS. Because they block dopamine, all D2 antagonists cause extrapyramidal symptoms — dystonia, akathisia, parkinsonism, and tardive dyskinesia. The high-yield split is the boxed warnings. Metoclopramide carries a boxed warning for tardive dyskinesia that can be irreversible; risk climbs with duration and cumulative dose, so avoid use beyond 12 weeks — a point that matters because its prokinetic role tempts longer courses. Droperidol instead carries a boxed warning for QT prolongation and torsades: all patients need a 12-lead ECG before dosing and monitoring 2-3 hours after, and it's limited to PONV. Parmar walks through the droperidol ECG requirement specifically to show \"how careful you need to be\" with this agent."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Metoclopramide boxed warning = irreversible tardive dyskinesia; limit to ≤12 weeks."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Droperidol boxed warning = QT/torsades; 12-lead ECG before and after."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE QT CLUSTER AND THE APOMORPHINE TRAP. QT prolongation recurs across antiemetics — droperidol, amisulpride, the setrons, and the macrolide prokinetics — so combining them stacks the risk. Among setrons, palonosetron (2nd-generation: high affinity, long half-life, covers acute AND delayed CINV) has the least QT effect, while ondansetron is the one agent that requires dose adjustment in hepatic insufficiency. The setron toxicity worth memorizing is the hard contraindication: ondansetron + apomorphine → profound hypotension and loss of consciousness. Other classes have milder signatures — H1/M1 agents cause sedation, dry mouth, blurred vision; cannabinoids cause euphoria/dysphoria and, chronically, cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome; dexamethasone brings hyperglycemia, weight gain, and infection risk."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ADJUVANTS AND THE GUIDELINE COMBINATION. Three rescue/adjuvant agents earn their own niches: benzodiazepines (lorazepam, alprazolam) treat anticipatory nausea where anxiety is the trigger; olanzapine — a multi-receptor (D2/5-HT2,3/H1/M) blocker — is a key component of four-drug prophylaxis for highly emetogenic chemotherapy (HEC); and dexamethasone is the steroid backbone of multi-drug regimens. The guideline combination to hold onto: 5-HT3 antagonist + NK1 antagonist + dexamethasone, with olanzapine added as the fourth drug for HEC."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Ondansetron + apomorphine → profound hypotension; hard contraindication."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HEC four-drug regimen: 5-HT3 + NK1 + dexamethasone + olanzapine."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Two D2 antagonists, two different boxed warnings: metoclopramide → irreversible TD (≤12 wk), droperidol → QT/torsades (ECG). Don't swap them."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Palonosetron is the setron with the least QT effect and the only one covering both acute and delayed CINV — the long half-life does both jobs."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "For HEC, give the four-drug regimen: 5-HT3 + NK1 + dexamethasone + olanzapine. For anticipatory nausea, reach for a benzodiazepine."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Two D2 antagonists both cause EPS — but each carries a different boxed warning. Contrast metoclopramide's and droperidol's boxed warnings and the monitoring each demands."}]}, {"id": 9, "statement": "Discuss the potential contraindications and drug interactions of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Two interaction themes carry this LO, and Parmar flags both as testable: the Parkinson's contraindication that follows every dopamine blocker, and the CYP-P450 interactions of the NK1 antagonists — which he ties directly to COMLEX drug-interaction questions after talking to a student who took the exam."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PARKINSON'S — THE D2 CONTRAINDICATION. Parkinson's disease is dopamine-neuron loss, so a drug that blocks dopamine worsens it. That makes every D2 antagonist antiemetic contraindicated in Parkinson's — prochlorperazine, promethazine, droperidol, metoclopramide, and amisulpride alike. It's the same mechanism that gives the class its EPS, so the contraindication and the adverse-effect profile are one idea, not two."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "All D2 antagonists are contraindicated in Parkinson's disease (dopamine blockade)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE NK1 / CYP3A4 / DEXAMETHASONE INTERACTION. This is the cluster Parmar spends the most interaction-time on. Aprepitant, fosaprepitant, and netupitant are moderate CYP3A4 inhibitors. Dexamethasone — the steroid in the standard regimen — is a CYP3A4 substrate, so co-administering these NK1 agents raises dexamethasone levels and risks toxicity: the fix is to reduce the dexamethasone dose. The deliberate contrast is rolapitant, which inhibits CYP2D6, NOT CYP3A4 — so it does not touch dexamethasone metabolism and needs no dose adjustment (making it the choice for patients already on many CYP3A4 drugs). The exam version is a statement-evaluation: \"this NK1 drug is a moderate CYP3A4 inhibitor, so you do/don't adjust dexamethasone\" — and rolapitant is the trap."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Aprepitant/fosaprepitant/netupitant inhibit CYP3A4 → reduce dexamethasone."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Rolapitant = CYP2D6, not CYP3A4 → no dexamethasone adjustment."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SMALLER INTERACTION FLAGS. Round out the LO with the discrete contraindications: ondansetron + apomorphine (profound hypotension — never combine), the additive QT risk when QT-prolongers are stacked (droperidol/amisulpride/setrons/macrolides), and amisulpride/droperidol contraindicated with a prolonged baseline QT. Among prokinetics, the macrolides (erythromycin) also prolong QT, and the cannabinoids carry the chronic-use cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome caveat."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Rolapitant is CYP2D6, NOT CYP3A4 — so it needs no dexamethasone adjustment. Aprepitant/fosaprepitant/netupitant (CYP3A4) DO. This is the planted COMLEX distractor."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Any D2 antagonist + Parkinson's = stop. Pick a non-dopaminergic antiemetic (setron, NK1 antagonist, or an H1 agent) instead."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Inhibiting CYP3A4 raises the substrate (dexamethasone), so you reduce its dose — not increase it. Inhibitor → higher levels → lower the dose."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Two NK1 antagonists are given alongside dexamethasone. Why does aprepitant force a dexamethasone dose change while rolapitant does not?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. ‘The H2 blocker causes gynecomastia.’ Only cimetidine is antiandrogenic (gynecomastia/galactorrhea) and a broad CYP450 inhibitor; famotidine and ranitidine are largely free of both — don't generalize cimetidine's baggage to the class. → LO 35.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. PPI of choice with clopidogrel. Omeprazole and esomeprazole inhibit CYP2C19 and blunt clopidogrel activation; the safe pick is pantoprazole, not ‘any PPI is fine.’ → LO 35.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Co-dosing sucralfate with a PPI/antacid. Sucralfate needs an acidic pH to gel; raising pH with an acid suppressor makes it inert. Space them or choose one. → LO 35.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Clarithromycin-triple as first-line H. pylori therapy. Clarithromycin was dropped for resistance; first-line is 14-day BQT, and eradication confirmation is mandatory. → LO 35.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Meclizine is an H2 antagonist. Meclizine and dimenhydrinate are H1 antihistamines for motion sickness; the -tidine H2 blockers are for acid suppression. Parmar plants this exact distractor — \"be very careful. No.\" → LO 36.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Acute = NK1, delayed = 5-HT3. It's the reverse: the acute phase is serotonin/5-HT3 (setrons), the delayed phase is substance P/NK1 (-pitants). Phase tells you the class. → LO 36.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. Same boxed warning for both D2 antagonists. They differ — metoclopramide = irreversible tardive dyskinesia (≤12 wk), droperidol = QT/torsades (mandatory ECG). Don't merge them. → LO 36.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "8. Every NK1 antagonist needs a dexamethasone dose cut. Only the CYP3A4 inhibitors (aprepitant/fosaprepitant/netupitant) do. Rolapitant is CYP2D6 → no adjustment. → LO 36.4"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. “older man on an H2 blocker develops breast tenderness” → think cimetidine (antiandrogenic) — switch to famotidine."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. “post-stent patient on clopidogrel started on omeprazole” → flag the CYP2C19 interaction — change to pantoprazole."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. “sucralfate plus a PPI, ulcer not healing” → the raised pH inactivated the sucralfate — separate the doses."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. “H. pylori-positive ulcer, high local clarithromycin resistance” → 14-day bismuth quadruple therapy, then confirm eradication."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"motion-sickness drug is an H2 antagonist\" → false — it's H1 (meclizine/dimenhydrinate); H2 blockers are the -tidines for acid."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"nausea on day 3 after chemo\" → delayed phase = substance P/NK1 → add a -pitant, not another setron."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. \"12-lead ECG required before and after the antiemetic\" → droperidol (QT boxed warning), not the TD warning of metoclopramide."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "8. \"NK1 agent that needs NO dexamethasone change\" → rolapitant (CYP2D6, not CYP3A4)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Acid-secretion physiology & the parietal-cell pump feed the antiemetic/prokinetic receptor logic — also Lec 36 (Antiemetic & Prokinetic Agents), this doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — H. pylori, NSAID ulcers, and the ulcer/upper-GI-bleed thread — callback to Lec 33-34 (GI Endoscopy)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Misoprostol (PGE1) and the prostaglandin/NSAID-ulcer axis — revisited in later GI & pharmacology coverage"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Metoclopramide's dual antiemetic/prokinetic role + GLP-1-induced gastroparesis — also Lec 35 (Drugs for Peptic Ulcers & Gastric Acidity), this block"}]}]}, "37": {"prof": "Dr. Norman Rose", "tldr": "Hemodynamic stability decides the path — unstable or peritonitic goes straight to the OR; stable goes to FAST/CT and observation — and organ-injury grading drives the rest. The spleen dominates.", "mustKnows": ["1. Kehr's sign is your board question. Kehr's sign is left-shoulder pain from diaphragmatic irritation by blood pooling under the diaphragm — classically from a splenic injury. Rose called it out by name as your board question; it occurs in about half of cases, and the hiccups that accompany it are the same phrenic-nerve irritation.", "2. Stability decides the path. Run the ABCs first. An unstable or peritonitic patient (hypotension, tachycardia, distended/tight abdomen, positive FAST) goes straight to the OR for laparotomy. A patient you can stabilize with 1–2 L crystalloid earns time for a CT and a trial of observation.", "3. Grade the spleen I–V. Splenic injury is graded I–V: I–III (capsular tear → through-and-through laceration) are usually repairable or observable; IV–V (stellate/crush, bisection, hilar injury, shattered spleen) are not repairable and need splenectomy. Delayed rupture can present up to ~2 weeks later.", "4. Splenectomy risks OPSI — save the spleen in kids. After splenectomy the patient loses filtering of encapsulated bacteria and makes less IgM and opsonins → overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI), worst in children. That is why we repair or observe (Types I–III) rather than remove whenever it is safe.", "5. Renal hematuria localizes the injury. 70–80% of renal injuries are blunt (MVA, falls). Hematuria means the injury reached the collecting system / renal pelvis, and the depth of the laceration determines whether surgery is needed. The trap: a child's UPJ avulsion can give a NEGATIVE urinalysis (no urine reaches the bladder).", "6. Cullen vs Gray-Turner. Two bruising signs of intra-abdominal/retroperitoneal bleeding: Cullen sign = periumbilical ecchymosis; Gray-Turner sign = flank ecchymosis. Bruising not explained by the surface injury should make you suspicious of bleeding underneath."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Describe abdominal anatomy and mapping", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Rose opens the way an old-school trauma surgeon does: before he lays a hand on the patient he pictures what's going on inside — skin, fascia, muscle, and peritoneum stripped away, the organs laid bare. The whole lecture rests on this. For trauma the single most useful map is the four quadrants, because the quadrant plus the mechanism tells you which organs are at risk. (The finer nine-region map — epigastric, umbilical, hypogastric, and the paired hypochondriac, lumbar, and iliac regions — is for localizing abdominal pain, not trauma.)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "RETROPERITONEAL VS INTRAPERITONEAL — THE KEY SPLIT. The dividing question for every organ is whether it is fixed (retroperitoneal) or mobile (intraperitoneal). Fixed organs cannot dodge a force, so they take crush injuries against the spine: the pancreas (Rose's biggest worry — it can be crushed or even bifurcated against the vertebral column), the kidneys and adrenals, the duodenum, and the ascending/descending colon. Mobile organs slip out of the way — the small intestine usually escapes blunt force, and the stomach or colon get into trouble mainly when markedly distended. The sigmoid is fixed enough that a LLQ stab wound reliably catches it."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Retroperitoneal/fixed organs (pancreas, kidneys, duodenum) take crush-against-spine injury; mobile organs slip away."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "LUQ holds the spleen; RUQ the liver; a LLQ stab catches the fixed sigmoid colon."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE VASCULATURE YOU MUST KNOW. The abdominal aorta is the largest artery in the body; it starts below the diaphragm and bifurcates into the common iliacs at about L4–L5. That landmark is not trivia — it is why a REBOA balloon can occlude the aorta in one zone but not across the renal arteries (LO 37.5). A crushing or penetrating injury to the great vessels is the bleed that kills fastest."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Abdominal aorta bifurcates into common iliacs at ~L4–L5 (largest artery in the body)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "For trauma, think in four quadrants: quadrant + mechanism = the organs at risk. The nine-region map is for localizing abdominal pain, not trauma."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Retroperitoneal/fixed (pancreas, kidney, duodenum, ascending/descending colon) get crushed against the spine; intraperitoneal/mobile (small bowel) dodge the blow."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "The spleen (LUQ) and liver (RUQ) both have thin capsules that tear easily — which is exactly why they top the solid-organ injury list."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Rose says he mentally strips away the skin, fascia, muscle, and peritoneum before he touches a trauma patient. What is the diagnostic payoff of picturing the organs by quadrant?"}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe diagnostic imaging and lab studies requested for abdominal trauma patients", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. If Rose makes one point in this lecture, it is ultrasound: that's the thing that's going to make all the difference. The bedside FAST exam (Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma) is fast, cheap, repeatable, and increasingly done on a phone probe — he told the class to chase the ultrasound teams in the ED and learn it. FAST hunts for free fluid (blood), air, and gross organ injury in the liver, kidneys, and spleen, and the density of the fluid even distinguishes blood from serous fluid. The volume of blood in the abdomen can be estimated from it."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE STABILITY-DRIVEN PATHWAY — THE SPINE OF THE LECTURE. Do the ABCs first and ask one question: is the patient stable? The unstable patient — hypotensive, tachycardic, a tense and distended abdomen, dull to percussion, positive FAST — is bleeding too fast to image. You resuscitate and go straight to the OR for an open exploration; there is no time to laparoscope and no time to scan. The patient you can stabilize with a couple of liters of crystalloid (mild hypotension that responds) has bought time — now you can get a CT, a focused ultrasound, and decide between operation and observation. Stability, not the organ, drives the disposition."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Trauma disposition: unstable/peritonitic → OR (open); stabilizes → CT and observe."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHEN ULTRASOUND ISN'T ENOUGH — CT, CONTRAST, AND THE OLD PLAIN FILM. In a non-critical patient, CT is the best quick screen (MRI takes too long); the one place you reach for contrast is the urinary tract, to look for extravasation of urine and gauge the renal injury. Before ultrasound, all Rose had was an upright chest/abdomen film hunting for free air under the diaphragm and signs of peritoneal irritation — worth knowing as the fallback when imaging is thin. And through all of it: nothing beats a good history of how the trauma happened."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE LABS, READ FOR WHAT THEY MEAN. The H/H (hemoglobin/hematocrit) lags reality but tells you how much blood was lost and how many units you may need — it runs a step behind the bleed, so trend it. On the differential, watch the white count: a left shift with rising leukocytes means the body is mobilizing white cells against contamination (think a perforated viscus). The UA looks for blood; amylase/lipase flag the pancreas; liver and renal panels, electrolytes, and an EKG round out the metabolic picture. Read the H/H for blood loss and the WBC for contamination — they answer different questions."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "H/H tracks blood loss (and lags); a WBC left shift flags contamination/perforation."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Reach for contrast in trauma mainly for the urinary tract (urine extravasation = renal injury)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Workup order: ABCs → is the patient stable? Unstable + positive FAST → straight to the OR. Stabilizes → CT, then observe vs operate."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "FAST finds free fluid, air, and organ injury at the bedside — Rose's single biggest message was to learn ultrasound. Density tells blood from serous fluid."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "The H/H answers 'how much blood was lost' (and lags); the WBC left shift answers 'is there contamination' — two different labs for two different questions."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Two blunt-trauma patients both have a positive FAST. One is hypotensive with a tense abdomen; the other stabilizes after 1.5 L of crystalloid. Why do they go to two completely different places?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "List different types of abdominal trauma", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The mechanism tells you what to look for, so name it. Blunt / compression (the common one) drives organs against the spine and breaks ribs over the spleen and liver. Penetrating (stab, gunshot) injures along its trajectory — and the trajectory, not just the entry point, is what matters: a wound below the nipple line can cross the diaphragm into the abdomen because the diaphragm rides up to the nipples on expiration. Crush is severe compression (steering wheel, a wall). Iatrogenic injury is caused by us during an operation. Blast injury drives foreign bodies inward and combines penetrating with crush."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PENETRATING: TRACE THE PATH. With a penetrating wound you reason from the direction of penetration and the instrument used — was it from the flank, transthoracic, anterior, or posterior? Rose's nail-gun case drove this home: the nail tracked far enough lateral and retroperitoneal that it spared the kidney, ureter, and vasculature — a quick UA confirmed the kidney was fine, and he removed the nail with an OR ready in case the patient crashed. The lesson is that the path predicts the organs, and many penetrating injuries still warrant exploration."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "A wound below the nipple line can cross the diaphragm into the abdomen (diaphragm rises on expiration)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Iatrogenic splenic injury = capsule torn during a LUQ operation (traction on the gastrosplenic ligament)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "For penetrating trauma, the trajectory predicts the injured organs — a sub-nipple wound can breach the diaphragm because it rides up on expiration."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Always reconstruct the mechanism first (blunt vs penetrating vs crush vs iatrogenic vs blast) — it sets which organs you hunt for and whether to explore."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Treating the entry point as the injury. The path is the injury; a flank or transthoracic angle changes everything about what's hit."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Rose says that for a penetrating wound you have to 'figure out the direction.' Why does the trajectory matter more than the entry point?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe splenic, liver, and renal injuries", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. This is the heart of the lecture, and the spleen is its center. The spleen is the most frequently injured organ in blunt abdominal trauma and the most common reason for splenectomy in the U.S. Its capsule is paper-thin and its attachments (gastrosplenic ligament, attachments to the diaphragm) tear easily. Injury comes from penetrating, blunt, or iatrogenic mechanisms — and isolated splenic injury occurs in only about 30% of cases, so when you find a hurt spleen, look for the stomach, left kidney, pancreas, and ribs too."}, {"t": "p", "x": "GRADE THE SPLEEN I–V. Your radiologist reports a type, not a dissertation, so you must know what each means. Type I = minor capsular tear/laceration (easily repaired). Type II = capsular avulsion, most of the spleen intact. Type III = major parenchymal fracture or a through-and-through laceration (stab/gunshot) — still usually repairable with technique. Types IV–V are different animals: severe stellate fracture, crush or bisection, hilar injury, and the shattered spleen — not repairable, so they come out. The clean cutoff: I–III repair or observe; IV–V splenectomy."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Spleen grades I–III are often repairable/observable; IV–V (crush/bisection/shattered) need splenectomy."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SPLENIC SIGNS — AND THE BOARD QUESTION. Once blood is in the abdomen it irritates the diaphragm, and the prof flagged the consequence as your board question: Kehr's sign — left-shoulder pain referred from diaphragmatic irritation, occurring in about half of splenic injuries, often with hiccups (same phrenic-nerve irritation). Ballance's sign (fixed dullness to percussion ± a palpable mass) is described but Rose said he never saw it. And learn the two bruising signs: Cullen sign = periumbilical ecchymosis, Gray-Turner sign = flank ecchymosis — bruising not explained by the surface injury should make you suspicious of bleeding underneath."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Kehr's sign = left-shoulder pain from diaphragmatic irritation by splenic blood — the prof's explicit board flag."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cullen = periumbilical ecchymosis; Gray-Turner = flank ecchymosis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "SAVE THE SPLEEN — OPSI AND DELAYED RUPTURE. Why bend over backward to repair or observe? Because the asplenic patient loses the filter for encapsulated bacteria and makes less IgM and opsonins → overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI), worst in children — so in kids especially we save the spleen, and nonoperative management is done only in an ICU with an OR immediately available (Rose insisted a county hospital transfer its stable splenic-injury child to him for exactly that reason). Watch too for delayed splenic rupture: a subcapsular hematoma that looks to be resolving can rupture ~2 weeks later and bring the patient back in shock."}, {"t": "p", "x": "LIVER — SAME THIN CAPSULE, GRADED I–VI. The liver tells the same story: thin capsule, easy laceration, graded by hematoma size and laceration depth. I subcapsular hematoma <10% / laceration <1 cm; II hematoma 10–50% / laceration 1–3 cm deep; III >50% or expanding / laceration >3 cm deep; IV 25–75% of a lobe (1–3 Couinaud segments); V >75% or >3 segments, including juxtahepatic venous (retrohepatic IVC / major hepatic veins); VI hepatic avulsion. The surgeon must know the segmental blood supply because you can resect part of the liver and survive on the rest — even on just the right side."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Liver is graded by hematoma size + laceration depth (I–VI); juxtahepatic venous injury (grade V) is the dangerous one."}, {"t": "p", "x": "RENAL — BLUNT, BLEEDS, AND THE HEMATURIA RULE. 70–80% of renal injuries are blunt (MVA, falls, deceleration onto the flank/back), and the kidney sits in the retroperitoneum, so injury makes a retroperitoneal hematoma — suspect it in a shocked patient with rib / vertebral / transverse-process fractures. The key clinical logic: hematuria means the injury reached the collecting system / renal pelvis. Grade by depth — I contusion/subcapsular hematoma; II cortical laceration <1 cm; III deeper laceration not reaching the collecting system; IV through the corticomedullary junction INTO the collecting system (urine extravasation) or a segmental vessel; V main-vessel thrombosis/avulsion or a shattered kidney. It is the depth of the laceration that determines whether surgery is needed; an unstable patient goes to the OR regardless, where a one-shot IVP may be the only imaging you get."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Hematuria → injury reached the renal pelvis/collecting system; depth of laceration determines surgery."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Child + rapid deceleration + negative UA → suspect UPJ avulsion (no urine reaches the bladder)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Kehr's sign (left-shoulder pain from diaphragmatic irritation) is the prof's explicit board flag for splenic injury — paired with hiccups from the same phrenic irritation."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "A child with a deceleration injury and a negative urinalysis can still have a major renal injury (UPJ avulsion — no urine reaches the bladder). Don't be reassured by a clean UA."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Solid-organ grading: spleen I–V (I–III repair/observe, IV–V remove); liver I–VI; renal I–V with hematuria = collecting-system reached."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A radiologist's report on a trauma CT will say only 'Grade III splenic injury,' not a paragraph. Why is the grade enough to drive your decision — and where is the cutoff between 'fix or watch' and 'remove'?"}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Describe pancreatic, pelvic, and thoracoabdominal trauma", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Rose closes fast and by anecdote, so keep this tight. The pancreas is a crush injury: lying retroperitoneally across the spine, a focal midline blow can crush or even transect it against the vertebral column — his garbage-truck case bisected the pancreas right over the spine, repaired with a Roux-en-Y pancreaticojejunostomy. Work it up with amylase and lipase (also checked in lavage fluid), see it on CT/ultrasound, and use ERCP to define the ductal anatomy; expect severe back pain because there's no room in the retroperitoneum. Thoracoabdominal and pelvic trauma in a crashing multi-trauma patient is a team approach through a thoracoabdominal incision, working chest and abdomen at once."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DPL IS HISTORICAL; REBOA BUYS TIME. Diagnostic peritoneal lavage once answered 'is there blood, bile, fecal material, bacteria, or amylase in the belly?' — but CT answers those quickly, so lavage is now mostly of historical interest (still used where imaging is unavailable). REBOA is the newer temporizing tool: a balloon occludes the aorta to control hemorrhage, but only in certain zones — never across the renal-artery segment, which would cause renal ischemia. It buys minutes for resuscitation; it is a bridge, not a repair."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Pancreas = crush/transection over the spine; work up with amylase/lipase and ERCP (ductal anatomy)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "DPL is largely historical (CT replaced it); REBOA temporizes — only in safe aortic zones."}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Scanning the unstable patient. A hypotensive trauma patient with a positive FAST goes straight to the OR, not to CT — stability, not the organ, drives disposition. CT is only for the patient you can stabilize. → LO 37.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Reading maroon/entry point as the injury. For penetrating trauma the trajectory is the injury; a sub-nipple wound can cross the diaphragm into the abdomen because it rides up on expiration. → LO 37.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Calling Kehr's sign abdominal pain. Kehr's sign is LEFT-SHOULDER pain (referred diaphragmatic irritation from splenic blood), the prof's explicit board flag — not localized belly pain. → LO 37.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Removing every injured spleen. Grades I–III repair or observe (especially in children, to avoid OPSI from encapsulated bacteria); only IV–V (crush/bisection/shattered) come out. → LO 37.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Trusting a negative UA in a child. A pediatric UPJ avulsion after deceleration can give a NEGATIVE urinalysis because no urine reaches the bladder — image the child anyway. → LO 37.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Putting the REBOA balloon anywhere. REBOA occludes the aorta only in certain zones — never across the renal arteries, which would cause renal ischemia. It temporizes; it does not repair. → LO 37.5"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"hypotensive, tense abdomen, positive FAST\" → to the OR, not the scanner. Scan only if they stabilize."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"stab wound just below the left nipple\" → think diaphragm + spleen; trace the trajectory, not the entry point."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"splenic injury with left-shoulder pain and hiccups\" → Kehr's sign (the board answer)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"stable child with an isolated splenic laceration\" → save the spleen (observe in ICU); avoid OPSI."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"child, deceleration, flank pain, clean urinalysis\" → still suspect UPJ avulsion; a negative UA doesn't clear it."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"balloon inflated to control aortic hemorrhage\" → REBOA, and only in a safe zone (not across the renals)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Traumatic injury of the liver, biliary tree, and pancreas — the elective-surgical counterparts of these same organs are in Lec 45-46 (Surgical Aspects of the Gallbladder & Biliary Tract / Liver & Pancreas)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Hemodynamic stability deciding OR vs imaging echoes the GI-bleed logic — also Lec 33-34 (GI Endoscopy), prior doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — FAST/CT and amylase/lipase reasoning for the acute abdomen carries into Lec 38 (Abdominal Pain / Diverticulitis), this doc"}]}]}, "38": {"prof": "Dr. R. Jackeline Moljo", "tldr": "Don't confuse diverticulOSIS (the pouches) with diverticulITIS (inflamed pouches): CT with contrast confirms it, most uncomplicated cases need no antibiotics, and the Hinchey stage decides who goes to surgery.", "mustKnows": ["1. CT is the study of choice. CT of the abdomen and pelvis with oral and IV contrast is the imaging study of choice for acute diverticulitis — sensitivity 94%, specificity 99%. It looks for localized bowel-wall thickening (>4 mm), pericolonic fat stranding, and diverticula, and it stages the complications (abscess, obstruction, fistula, free air).", "2. Water-soluble contrast, never barium. If perforation is suspected, any contrast study uses a water-soluble medium — never barium. Leaked barium causes barium peritonitis; water-soluble contrast is harmlessly absorbed. Moljo flagged this twice: \"if there's a perforation and we use barium… very big trouble.\"", "3. Uncomplicated diverticulitis usually needs NO antibiotics. For uncomplicated diverticulitis in a reliable, immunocompetent outpatient, manage with a clear-then-low-fiber diet and analgesia — antibiotics are usually not required. When abx are used, a fluoroquinolone or TMP-SMX must be paired with metronidazole for anaerobes (amoxicillin-clavulanate covers both alone).", "4. Abscess size sets the move: 4 cm. A diverticular abscess <4 cm is treated with antibiotics alone; one ≥4 cm gets CT-guided percutaneous drainage. Separately, microperforation (contained — air bubbles, no extraluminal contrast) is managed nonoperatively in ~94%, while frank perforation with feculent peritonitis mandates emergency surgery.", "5. Hinchey stages it; obstruction is the #1 complication. The modified Hinchey classification (0–IV) is CT-based — zero is good, four is bad — and stages III/IV (purulent or fecal peritonitis) drive surgery. The most common complication is obstruction, then perforation, then abscess.", "6. A colonic diverticulum is a PSEUDOdiverticulum; recurrence climbs. A colonic diverticulum is a pseudodiverticulum — it herniates mucosa/submucosa through the wall but does not include all layers. After a first attack, recurrence is 33%; after a second, 66%. Colonoscopy is done 6–8 weeks AFTER resolution, never during the acute attack."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "List the appropriate history questions needed for a patient with diverticulitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "ANATOMY FIRST. Moljo built the whole lecture around a single ED vignette — a 68-year-old woman with three days of left-lower-quadrant pain, low-grade fever and chills — and her one repeated instruction is to start with anatomy: \"for the abdominal exam… always start with anatomy.\" Name what lives in the painful quadrant (sigmoid colon, ovary, bladder) and the history questions write themselves. The classic tell is constant LLQ pain with fever; ask too about timing, change in bowel habits, urinary symptoms, and — in a woman — gynecologic causes, which is why she argued the declined pelvic exam still leaves a real gap (an ovarian source can masquerade as colonic pain). Notice the exam targets recognition here, not deep recall — you are pattern-matching a presentation, not memorizing a checklist."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE TWO CLUES WORTH ASKING ABOUT. First, the fistula screen: pneumaturia (air in the urine) and fecaluria (stool in the urine) point to a colovesical fistula between the inflamed colon and the bladder — a complication you only catch if you ask. Second, the dietary myth Moljo defended twice under student questioning: patients with diverticular disease do not need to avoid nuts, seeds, corn, or popcorn — \"we don't have to tell them not to eat those things.\" The genuine dietary risk is red meat (six or more servings a week) on a low-fiber background; she noted the meat data was specific to red meat, with chicken and fish fine."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Pneumaturia + fecaluria = colovesical fistula."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Seeds/nuts/corn/popcorn do NOT raise risk; red meat (≥6/wk) does."}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe which tests are necessary to distinguish between the differential diagnoses in a patient with diverticulitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The workup runs on one idea Moljo built into a quiz slide: each test answers a specific question, and you order it to confirm a suspicion rather than to fish. The lab panel sorts the differential — CBC (infection? anemia from a GI bleed?), CMP (diabetes, electrolytes, and crucially renal function before contrast), CRP/ESR (inflammation), urinalysis and culture (UTI, the LLQ mimic), HCG (pregnancy in any woman of childbearing age), and blood cultures if she looks septic. Two of those — the CMP renal check and the HCG — exist specifically to make it safe to give contrast."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CT IS THE STUDY OF CHOICE. CT of the abdomen and pelvis with oral and IV contrast is the imaging study of choice for acute diverticulitis, and the numbers are worth knowing cold: sensitivity 94%, specificity 99%. The high specificity is what makes a positive scan confirmatory. Look for the triad of localized bowel-wall thickening (>4 mm), pericolonic fat stranding from inflammation, and the diverticula themselves — and the same scan stages the complications (abscess, obstruction, fistula, free air), which is exactly why it feeds straight into the Hinchey system and the management decisions in LO 38.4."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "CT abd/pelvis with oral + IV contrast = study of choice; Se 94 / Sp 99."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "CT triad: wall thickening >4 mm + pericolonic fat stranding + diverticula."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WATER-SOLUBLE CONTRAST, NEVER BARIUM. If a perforation is suspected and any contrast study is used, the contrast must be a water-soluble medium — never barium. The mechanism is the whole point: water-soluble contrast that leaks into the peritoneum is harmlessly absorbed, whereas leaked barium causes barium peritonitis, a severe chemical inflammatory reaction. Moljo hit this twice and with weight — if there is a perforation and you use barium, \"very big trouble.\" This is the single most quotable test-selection rule in the lecture."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Suspected perforation → water-soluble contrast, never barium (barium peritonitis)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE OTHER MODALITIES, AND WHY CT WINS. Ultrasound can show a hypoechoic peridiverticular reaction and segmental wall thickening, but it is operator-dependent and less reliable — Moljo called it easy to do but inferior. MRI matches CT's anatomy and spares radiation, but it is slower and costlier and lacks the validated diverticulitis criteria CT carries. Plain abdominal films (supine and upright) are a screen for air-fluid levels, obstruction, and free air, not a confirmatory test. When the question asks how you distinguish diverticulitis from its mimics, the answer is the contrast CT."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Water-soluble contrast, never barium, when perforation is on the table — leaked barium causes barium peritonitis. Water-soluble contrast is simply absorbed."}, {"t": "key", "x": "CT abd/pelvis with oral + IV contrast is the study of choice (Se 94 / Sp 99) — it both confirms the diagnosis and stages the complications for Hinchey."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "In a woman of childbearing age, gate the contrast: check renal function (CMP) and an HCG before the scan."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Your patient may have a perforation and needs a contrast study. Which contrast do you choose, and what is the specific disaster you are avoiding?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Describe the clinical presentation and management of diverticulosis versus diverticulitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "THE DEFINITIONS LADDER. The whole LO turns on keeping four terms straight, so climb the ladder deliberately. A diverticulum is a single sac-like outpouching of colonic mucosa through a weak point in the muscular wall; diverticula is just the plural. DiverticulOSIS is the presence of diverticula — often asymptomatic. DiverticulITIS is inflammation of a diverticulum, which is then subdivided into uncomplicated versus complicated (abscess, fistula, obstruction, or free perforation). Diverticular disease is the umbrella term for clinically significant, symptomatic disease — including diverticulitis, diverticular bleeding, and segmental colitis. The exam loves to swap osis and itis on you, so anchor it: -osis = the pouches, -itis = the pouches inflamed."}, {"t": "p", "x": "A COLONIC DIVERTICULUM IS A PSEUDODIVERTICULUM. This is the slide's one mechanistic nuance and a clean board point. A colonic diverticulum herniates only the mucosa and submucosa through gaps in the muscular wall (typically where vasa recta penetrate) — it does not include all the colonic layers, so \"in reality it is a pseudodiverticulum.\" A true diverticulum would contain the full wall thickness. That same vessel-adjacent weak point is why the pouches bleed, which is the bridge to the diverticulOSIS painless-bleed story from the endoscopy lecture."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "-osis = diverticula present; -itis = diverticula inflamed (uncomplicated vs complicated)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "A colonic diverticulum is a pseudodiverticulum — mucosa/submucosa only, not all layers."}, {"t": "p", "x": "EPIDEMIOLOGY BY AGE, SEX, AND SIDE. DiverticulOSIS is fundamentally a disease of aging: US prevalence rises from under 20% at age 40 to about 60% by age 60, with the number and size of diverticula climbing too. In Western countries the disease is left-sided (sigmoid); Asian people and Pacific Islanders skew toward proximal (right-sided) disease that is often congenital — a point a student confirmed from a rotation in Asia, where the diverticulosis ran right-sided. The sex pattern flips with age: under 50 it is more common in men, with a female preponderance after 50 that becomes marked over 70. As for how often osis turns into trouble — diverticulitis hits ~1–2% of the general population and ~4% of those with diverticulosis, and bleeding occurs in 3–5%."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Diverticulosis prevalence: <20% at 40 → ~60% at 60; Western = left, Asian = proximal/right."}, {"t": "p", "x": "MANAGEMENT SPLITS WITH THE NAME. Treat diverticulOSIS by modifying risk factors only — diet, exercise, weight, alcohol, smoking — there is no drug for the pouches themselves. DiverticulITIS management depends on severity and complications, and that full decision tree (outpatient versus admission, antibiotics or not, abscess thresholds, surgery) is the work of LO 38.4."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "DiverticulOSIS = the pouches (often asymptomatic, the painless-bleed source); diverticulITIS = the pouches inflamed (LLQ pain + fever). Same anatomy, different word and different disease."}, {"t": "key", "x": "A colonic diverticulum is a pseudodiverticulum: it herniates mucosa/submucosa but not all wall layers — and it forms at the vessel-weak point, which is why these pouches bleed."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Side and population are a clue: Western diverticulosis is left-sided; Asian/Pacific patients skew proximal/right-sided and often congenital."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A diverticulum, diverticulOSIS, diverticulITIS, and diverticular disease are four different words. Define each, and say which one is a pseudodiverticulum and why."}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe the management of diverticulitis, its prognosis, and resultant complications", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW — UNCOMPLICATED VS COMPLICATED. Every management decision forks on one split: uncomplicated diverticulitis (inflammation only) is managed medically, often outpatient; complicated disease (abscess, perforation, obstruction, fistula) needs a more aggressive, usually inpatient and sometimes surgical approach. The modern, high-yield shift lives on the uncomplicated side — and the entire complication ladder lives on the other."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ANTIBIOTIC SHIFT. Antibiotics were long the mainstay, but European trials consistently show that uncomplicated diverticulitis usually does NOT need them. For a selected patient — immunocompetent, reliable for follow-up, no systemic disturbance — manage with a clear diet for 2–3 days advancing to low fiber, acetaminophen and antispasmodics for pain, and close follow-up. Moljo was candid that this is a hard habit to break: \"it's very hard for us physicians to stop doing that,\" but \"we really don't need antibiotics for uncomplicated diverticulitis.\" Reserve antibiotics for patients with major comorbidities, immunocompromise, immunomodulating drugs, or signs of systemic disturbance."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHEN YOU DO TREAT — COVER ANAEROBES. When antibiotics are indicated, give 7–10 days of broad-spectrum oral coverage spanning aerobes and anaerobes. The trap is the anaerobe gap: a fluoroquinolone or TMP-SMX does NOT cover anaerobes, so each must be paired with metronidazole (or clindamycin if metronidazole isn't tolerated). Amoxicillin-clavulanate is the single-agent option because it already covers both. Moljo drove this as a rhetorical quiz — what does metronidazole cover? Anaerobes."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Uncomplicated + reliable + immunocompetent → no antibiotics; diet + analgesia + follow-up."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Fluoroquinolone or TMP-SMX + metronidazole (anaerobes); amox-clav covers both alone."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ADMIT WHEN. Hospitalize if CT shows complicated disease, or if CT shows uncomplicated disease but the patient carries a high-risk feature: sepsis/SIRS (temp >38°C or <36°C, HR >90, RR >20, WBC >12,000 or <4,000, CRP >15), severe pain that can't be controlled below 5/10 in the ED, age >70, significant comorbidities, immunosuppression, intolerance of oral intake (obstruction/ileus), or unreliability for follow-up (e.g., no support system). Inpatients get IV antibiotics against gram-negative rods and anaerobes, IV fluids, analgesia, and NPO for bowel rest, then advance the diet; they discharge on oral antibiotics to finish a 10–14 day course."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE COMPLICATIONS, AND THE TWO THRESHOLDS THAT MATTER. First, perforation comes in two flavors. Frank perforation — free air under the diaphragm with feculent diffuse peritonitis — is life-threatening and mandates emergency surgery. Microperforation (contained — small air bubbles but no extraluminal contrast) is treated with IV antibiotics, and ~94% are managed nonoperatively. Second, the abscess 4-cm rule: an abscess <4 cm → antibiotics alone; ≥4 cm → CT-guided percutaneous drainage added (surgery only if drainage fails or the collection is inaccessible). A fistula (colovesical, colovaginal, and others) is managed surgically."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Frank perforation → emergency surgery; microperforation → IV abx, ~94% nonoperative."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Abscess <4 cm → antibiotics alone; ≥4 cm → CT-guided percutaneous drainage."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HINCHEY STAGES IT; III/IV GO TO SURGERY. The modified Hinchey classification (0–IV) is CT-based and guides intervention. Moljo de-emphasized rote memorization — \"you don't need to memorize this… zero is good and four is bad\" — but know the shape: 0 = mild (wall thickening); I = pericolic phlegmon/abscess; II = distant/pelvic abscess; III = generalized purulent peritonitis; IV = generalized fecal peritonitis. The operational point is that stages III and IV drive surgery, along with uncontrolled sepsis, a ruptured abscess, an undrainable abscess, fistula, obstruction/stricture, and failed medical therapy."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Hinchey / What it is / Move): 0 — Mild diverticulitis (wall thickening on CT) · Medical, often outpatient ; I — Pericolic/mesocolic phlegmon or abscess · Antibiotics; drain if abscess ≥4 cm ; II — Distant (pelvic/retroperitoneal) abscess · Antibiotics + percutaneous drainage ; III — Generalized PURULENT peritonitis · Surgery ; IV — Generalized FECAL peritonitis · Surgery"}, {"t": "p", "x": "PROGNOSIS AND THE FOLLOW-UP SCOPE. Recurrence climbs with each attack: 33% after a first episode, 66% after a second (rebleeding up to ~6%). Among complications, obstruction is the most common, followed by perforation, then abscess. Younger patients can paradoxically have more severe disease, often from delayed diagnosis, and immunocompromised patients carry markedly higher morbidity and mortality. Finally, the timing rule the exam loves: perform colonoscopy 6–8 WEEKS after the attack resolves (the slide says weeks; the transcript's \"hours\" is a transcription slip) — never during the acute attack, when scoping the inflamed colon risks perforation. The point of the delayed scope is to exclude colorectal cancer or other pathology, especially in a younger first-time patient."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Recurrence 33% after 1st episode, 66% after 2nd; obstruction = most common complication."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Colonoscopy 6–8 weeks AFTER resolution, never during the acute attack."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Reflexively giving antibiotics for every diverticulitis — uncomplicated disease in a reliable, immunocompetent patient usually doesn't need them. And if you use a fluoroquinolone/TMP-SMX, you must add metronidazole for anaerobes."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Abscess <4 cm → antibiotics alone; ≥4 cm → CT-guided percutaneous drainage. Frank perforation → emergency surgery; contained microperforation → IV abx."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Hinchey: zero good, four bad. Stages III (purulent) and IV (fecal) peritonitis are the ones that go to the OR."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Moljo says \"we really don't need antibiotics for uncomplicated diverticulitis\" — so when ARE antibiotics indicated, and when you do use a fluoroquinolone, what must you add and why?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. DiverticulOSIS vs diverticulITIS. They are different words for different diseases: -osis is the presence of pouches (often asymptomatic; the painless lower-GI bleeder from the endoscopy lecture), while -itis is the pouches inflamed (LLQ pain + fever). Don't let the exam swap them on you. → LO 38.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Barium when perforation is possible. If a perforation is suspected, any contrast study uses a water-soluble medium — leaked barium causes barium peritonitis. Water-soluble contrast is harmlessly absorbed. → LO 38.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Antibiotics for every diverticulitis. Uncomplicated disease in a reliable, immunocompetent patient usually needs no antibiotics — diet and analgesia suffice. Reserve abx for complicated disease or high-risk hosts. → LO 38.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. A fluoroquinolone alone covers diverticulitis. Fluoroquinolones and TMP-SMX don't cover anaerobes, so each must be paired with metronidazole (amoxicillin-clavulanate covers both alone). → LO 38.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. All abscesses get drained. The 4-cm rule: an abscess <4 cm → antibiotics alone; only ≥4 cm → CT-guided percutaneous drainage. → LO 38.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Scope during the acute attack. Colonoscopy is done 6–8 weeks AFTER resolution, never during the acute attack — scoping the inflamed colon risks perforation. Counsel away from the seeds/nuts myth too; red meat is the real dietary risk. → LO 38.1"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"painless large-volume rectal bleeding in a 70-year-old\" → think diverticulOSIS (the pouches bleeding), not the inflamed diverticulITIS."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"suspect perforation, ordering a contrast enema\" → water-soluble contrast, never barium (barium peritonitis)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"reliable young patient, CT shows uncomplicated diverticulitis\" → no antibiotics; clear→low-fiber diet, analgesia, close follow-up."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"started on ciprofloxacin for diverticulitis\" → add metronidazole for anaerobes (or use amox-clavulanate alone)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"CT shows a 5 cm pericolic abscess\" → CT-guided percutaneous drainage plus antibiotics (≥4 cm)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"first diverticulitis, never scoped, now recovered\" → colonoscopy 6–8 weeks later to exclude cancer; not during the attack."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — diverticulOSIS (painless lower-GI bleed, #1 cause >50, self-limits ~80%) vs this lecture's diverticulITIS — the explicit osis-vs-itis hinge — also Lec 33-34 (GI Endoscopy), the 31-34 doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Colonoscopy timing & CRC screening (the 6-8-week post-resolution scope to exclude cancer) — also Lec 33-34 (GI Endoscopy), the 31-34 doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Surgical management of complicated lower-GI disease (abscess drainage, resection) — also Lec 45-46 (Surgical Aspects of the Liver, Biliary Tract & Pancreas)"}]}]}, "39": {"prof": "Dr. Jeffrey Schneider", "tldr": "Chronic liver disease by cause: read the pattern — AST>ALT means alcohol, ALT>AST means everything else; sort the genetic/cholestatic causes (PBC, hemochromatosis, Wilson) and MASLD, all converging on cirrhosis.", "mustKnows": ["1. AST > ALT is the alcohol pearl. In alcohol-related liver disease the labs read AST > ALT (roughly 2:1); in almost every other liver disease — including non-alcoholic/metabolic fatty liver — it is ALT > AST. Schneider called this one of the biggest pearls in medical school and repeated it six-plus times. If AST is higher than ALT, think alcohol.", "2. Low platelets + high PT/INR = cirrhosis. Two blood-work findings betray a cirrhotic before you ever examine them: low platelets (portal hypertension causes splenomegaly/hypersplenism that eats platelets) and an elevated PT/INR (the failing liver underproduces the vitamin-K-dependent clotting factors II, VII, IX, X). The prof called reading these off a CBC a superpower.", "3. Discriminant Function > 32 -> steroids. Alcoholic-hepatitis severity is scored by the Discriminant Function = 4.6 (PT − PT control) + total bilirubin. A DF > 32 means mortality > 50% and the patient should receive steroids. This gold-starred slide is the one number to carry out of the alcoholic-hepatitis discussion.", "4. MASH is the point of reversibility. The metabolic fatty-liver spectrum runs simple steatosis (MASL, ~80%) -> MASH ('inflammation from fat,' ~20%) -> cirrhosis -> HCC. Cirrhosis is the risk factor for liver cancer, but MASH is the point of reversibility — the window where drugs and lifestyle can still turn it around, which is why identifying MASH matters.", "5. PBC = 95% women + AMA. Primary biliary cholangitis is 95% women, a cholestatic disease with a striking alkaline-phosphatase elevation and antimitochondrial antibodies (AMA) in 95%. Schneider called AMA the easiest answer you ever give on a test. It is microhepatic, not macrohepatic — the key contrast with PSC — and is treated with ursodeoxycholic acid (UDCA).", "6. HHC: too much iron ABSORBED. Hereditary hemochromatosis is autosomal recessive, chromosome 6 (mutations C282Y and H63D), the most common single-gene inherited disorder in the white US population. The defect is increased iron ABSORPTION (2–4 mg/day vs 1 normal) over decades. Screen with transferrin saturation (serum iron/TIBC); treat with phlebotomy. Cirrhosis is irreversible and carries a 120× HCC risk.", "7. Wilson: copper EXCRETION fails. Wilson disease is autosomal recessive, chromosome 13. Copper absorption is normal but biliary EXCRETION is decreased — copper spills into blood, then urine (elevated 24-h urinary copper). Ceruloplasmin is LOW because it is consumed — not a deficiency (a common student mistake); a high level excludes WD. Think WD in a young patient with acute liver failure + hemolysis or unexplained parkinsonism. Liver biopsy is the gold standard.", "8. Absorption vs excretion: HHC vs WD. The high-frequency discriminator: HHC absorbs too much iron; Wilson fails to excrete copper. Same autosomal-recessive overload mechanism, opposite step — HHC is an intake problem (chr 6, iron), Wilson is an output problem (chr 13, copper). Get this contrast and most exam versions sort themselves."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Describe alcohol-related liver diseases: epidemiology, risk factors and ethanol metabolism", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Alcohol is the disease Schneider opens with because it is everywhere — implicated in over 50% of liver-related deaths, contributing to 250,000 deaths a year and $3 billion in health-care cost. But the paradox he wants you to hold is that most people who abuse alcohol never get severe liver disease — only about 20% develop alcoholic hepatitis, cirrhosis, or both. So the lecture is really about who tips over, how you spot them on labs, and how the body handles ethanol in the first place."}, {"t": "p", "x": "RISK FACTORS — IT'S THE DOSE, NOT THE DRINK. The threshold for advanced liver disease is roughly 60-80 g of ethanol (4-6 drinks) daily for years in men, and about HALF that in women — and it does not depend on the type of alcohol. As Schneider put it, it's quantity, not quality; a standard drink is 14 g (a 12-oz beer, 5 oz of wine, or a 1.5-oz shot). Women are hit harder for the same weight-adjusted dose — partly a relative gastric alcohol-dehydrogenase deficiency plus hormonal effects, giving them a higher blood-alcohol level. Layer on genetics (TNF-promoter and alcohol-enzyme polymorphisms) and the threshold varies widely person to person."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Advanced alcoholic liver disease needs ~60-80 g/day in men, half that in women; standard drink = 14 g."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "It's quantity, not quality — risk does not depend on the type of alcohol."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ETHANOL METABOLISM — A MAJOR AND A MINOR ROAD. The major pathway is oxidative: alcohol dehydrogenase (ADH) turns ethanol into acetaldehyde, then acetaldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH) turns that into harmless acetate — both steps burning NAD+ to NADH. The minor pathway is MEOS (microsomal ethanol oxidizing system, CYP2E1), which is induced by chronic or heavy drinking. That induction is a clinical trap: a chronic drinker's revved-up CYP2E1 accelerates the conversion of acetaminophen into its toxic metabolite, so alcohol history is crucial in a Tylenol overdose."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ENZYME THAT EXPLAINS FLUSHING — AND DISULFIRAM. Acetaldehyde dehydrogenase is the clearance step, and more than 1 in 3 people of East Asian heritage carry a relative deficiency of it. When they drink, acetaldehyde piles up and they flush. Pharmacology weaponizes exactly this: disulfiram (Antabuse) blocks acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, so a drink brings on flushing, nausea, and misery — Schneider likes to prescribe it in front of the spouse so the patient can't quietly skip it. For the craving itself rather than the aversion, naltrexone is the go-to."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Disulfiram blocks acetaldehyde dehydrogenase -> acetaldehyde accumulates -> flushing/nausea; same enzyme is relatively deficient in >1/3 of East Asians."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Chronic alcohol induces CYP2E1 (MEOS) -> faster toxic-metabolite formation -> alcohol history is crucial in Tylenol overdose."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SPECTRUM AND THE BIGGEST PEARL — AST > ALT. The disease climbs in three steps: fatty liver (usually asymptomatic, reversible with abstinence) -> alcoholic hepatitis (the patient is sick, and can occur with or without cirrhosis) -> Laennec cirrhosis. Across all of it the laboratory signature is the same and it is the single most-repeated fact of the hour: AST > ALT in alcohol, versus ALT > AST in non-alcoholic and most other liver disease. Schneider flagged this as one of the biggest pearls in medical school — if the AST is the higher of the two, your first thought is alcohol."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE TWO NUMBERS — DISCRIMINANT FUNCTION AND THE CIRRHOSIS BLOOD-WORK 'SUPERPOWER.' For alcoholic hepatitis, severity is the gold-starred Discriminant Function = 4.6 (PT − PT control) + total bilirubin; DF > 32 -> mortality > 50% -> give steroids. For cirrhosis, the prof's superpower is diagnosing it off blood work alone: low platelets (portal hypertension -> splenomegaly/hypersplenism sequesters them) and an elevated PT/INR (the liver underproduces the vitamin-K-dependent factors II, VII, IX, X). Add the exam findings of decompensation — jaundice, gynecomastia/testicular atrophy/spider angiomata, ascites, splenomegaly — and once decompensated the path is supportive care then transplant (MELD-driven). As Schneider says of end-stage organ function, there are no stages — the liver is either working or it isn't."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Discriminant Function = 4.6(PT − PT control) + Tbili; DF > 32 -> mortality > 50% -> steroids."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cirrhosis blood-work: low platelets (hypersplenism from portal HTN) + high PT/INR (low vit-K factors II,VII,IX,X)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "AST > ALT = alcohol; ALT > AST = non-alcoholic and most other liver disease. Schneider's single biggest pearl, repeated six-plus times — if AST is the higher one, think alcohol."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "A chronic drinker's induced CYP2E1 speeds acetaminophen toward its toxic metabolite, so the same Tylenol dose is more dangerous — always take an alcohol history in a suspected Tylenol overdose."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "In cirrhosis, low platelets come from portal-HTN hypersplenism, while the high PT/INR comes from failed synthesis of vitamin-K factors — two different mechanisms, two different labs."}, {"t": "q", "x": "You are handed a CBC and a basic LFT panel on a patient you have never met — no history. Which two blood-work findings let you call cirrhosis on the spot, and why does each happen?"}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Review primary biliary cirrhosis (PBC)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Schneider opens his 'Hit Parade' of chronic liver diseases by telling you exactly how to study them — sort each one by who gets it, how it presents, the one diagnostic serology if any, and the treatment. Primary biliary cholangitis is the easiest to pin down: a cholestatic disease of middle-aged women with a single near-perfect antibody. (A naming note: he learned it as primary biliary cirrhosis for a career and now teaches it as primary biliary cholangitis — the deck still shows both, but 'cholangitis' is the current name because most patients never reach cirrhosis.)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHO GETS IT. PBC is 95% women, with onset between 30 and 65 and rare before 30 — more common in Caucasian women but seen in others. Unlike HHC and Wilson, no chromosome has been identified and there is no genetic test; the best current model is a two-hit process (an undefined genetic predisposition plus an environmental trigger), and the female skew may reflect X-related immunologic tolerance. The engine of injury is a T-lymphocyte attack on the small intrahepatic bile ducts, gradually destroying them."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HOW IT PRESENTS. The majority are asymptomatic and caught on routine labs; when symptoms come they are fatigue and pruritus (itching), with variable hyperpigmentation, xanthelasma (the cholesterol eyelid deposits on the title slide), and hepatosplenomegaly. The high-yield wrinkle is the company PBC keeps: it is classically associated with other autoimmune diseases — Sjögren, CREST, rheumatoid arthritis. That is why Schneider says the rheumatologist often makes the diagnosis first: chasing one autoimmune complaint, they order a broad panel, the antibody lights up, and the patient lands in your office already labeled."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PBC is 95% women, mostly asymptomatic, with fatigue + pruritus and xanthelasma when symptomatic."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE DIAGNOSIS — AND THE BOARD ANSWER. Two laboratory facts carry PBC. First, a striking elevation of alkaline phosphatase — it is the classic cholestatic liver disease, and the liver is microhepatic, not macrohepatic (a contrast Schneider draws explicitly with PSC). Second, the serology you cannot miss: antimitochondrial antibodies (AMA), present in 95% — he called this 'the easiest answer you ever give' on a test. ANA is also present in many. Liver biopsy is for staging, not for making the diagnosis — you do not biopsy to diagnose PBC. On histology the classic look is the 'onion-skin' concentric fibrosis around a damaged duct."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PBC = striking alk phos (cholestatic) + AMA in 95%; biopsy is for staging, not diagnosis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "TREATMENT AND PROGNOSIS. First-line is ursodeoxycholic acid (UDCA) — given so liberally before hepatitis C was curable that Schneider calls it 'chicken soup for the liver' — with obeticholic acid (OCA) for refractory patients. Diagnosed early, patients have a normal life expectancy; treatment delays progression and the time to transplant, and transplant (when needed) is often driven by the extrahepatic burden — intractable pruritus and osteoporosis. Because PBC is cholestatic, expect fat-soluble vitamin (A, D, E, K) malabsorption and hyperlipidemia. And the reassuring contrast: HCC is rare in PBC (very much unlike HHC)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PBC treated with UDCA; normal life expectancy if early; HCC is rare (vs HHC)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Recognize PBC from a three-part fingerprint: a middle-aged woman + a striking cholestatic alk phos + AMA in 95%. Schneider's 'easiest answer you ever give.'"}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "PBC vs PSC: PBC = women, microhepatic, AMA; PSC = men, macrohepatic, no serology (ERCP). Both attack bile ducts — but opposite demographics and tests."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "PBC is cholestatic, so it malabsorbs the fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K) and runs hyperlipidemic — and the rheumatologist often diagnoses it via a broad autoimmune panel (Sjögren/CREST/RA company)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A rheumatologist works up a 50-year-old woman with fatigue and a sky-high alkaline phosphatase, orders a broad autoimmune panel, and sends her to you with a positive antibody. What is the antibody, and why did the rheumatologist — not the gastroenterologist — make this call first?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Describe hereditary hemochromatosis (HHC)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Schneider promised this one would be 'super fun' and that 'you'll get pimped on it by everybody' — translation: high-yield, learn it cold. Hereditary hemochromatosis is the disease of too much iron absorbed. It is autosomal recessive on chromosome 6, carries two classic mutations — C282Y and H63D — and is the most common single-gene inherited disorder in the white US population (about 1 in 10 are carriers, 1 in 200–300 homozygous). A 1980s genetic survey of an entire Kodak factory turned up iron overload everywhere among old-stock Caucasians — that is how common the gene is."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WALK THE IRON. Normal absorption is ~1 mg/day; in HHC it runs 2–4 mg/day. The math is the disease: ~3 mg extra daily is ~90 mg a month, roughly 1 gram a year, and symptoms need a 20–30 gram overload — so it takes decades and patients usually present in the 4th–5th decade. Women present even later because menstruation offloads iron for years. There is no excretory escape valve, so the excess iron is deposited everywhere — and the exam wants you to map each organ to its presentation."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CORRELATE ORGAN WITH PRESENTATION. Liver → abnormal LFTs and cirrhosis. Skin → bronzing. Pancreas → diabetes (together giving the classic 'bronze diabetes'). Joints → arthralgias and pseudogout, classically in the MCP joints. Pituitary → impotence. Heart → restrictive cardiomyopathy. The clinical pearl Schneider drove home: think hemochromatosis in new-onset type 2 diabetes when the patient is NOT overweight — iron in the pancreas, not adiposity, is the cause."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Map HHC organs: liver (cirrhosis), skin (bronzing), pancreas (diabetes), joints (MCP), pituitary, heart (restrictive CM)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Think HHC in new diabetes in a non-obese patient ('bronze diabetes')."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DIAGNOSIS — SCREEN, THEN CONFIRM. Screen with transferrin saturation = serum iron / TIBC × 100. A saturation >60% in men or >50% in women means ~90% are HHC homozygous (lowering the cutoff just buys false positives). Then confirm with commercial genetic testing for C282Y and H63D. Liver biopsy is for staging, and not needed in everyone. Note the parallel to PBC and Wilson — each disease gets you to the diagnosis with one screening lab and then a confirmatory step."}, {"t": "p", "x": "TREATMENT, AND WHY EARLY MATTERS. The treatment is delightfully low-tech: phlebotomy, once or twice a week — one unit of blood removes ~250 mg of iron, so de-ironing a 20–30 g load takes 2–3 years. The whole prognosis hinges on one fork: prognosis is excellent if there is no cirrhosis, but once cirrhosis has set in it is the point of irreversibility — phlebotomy will not reverse it, and these patients carry an enormous 120× risk of hepatocellular carcinoma (up to 1/3 of HHC cirrhotics develop it). That HCC risk is the headline contrast with PBC, where liver cancer is rare. Catch the iron before the scar and you change the entire trajectory."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HHC screen = transferrin saturation (>60% M / >50% W); treat with phlebotomy (1 unit = 250 mg iron)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cirrhotic HHC = irreversible + 120× HCC risk (up to 1/3); HCC rare in PBC."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "HHC vs Wilson: HHC = too much iron ABSORBED (chr 6); Wilson = copper not EXCRETED (chr 13). Same overload logic, opposite step — intake vs output."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "New diabetes in a non-obese patient = look for hemochromatosis ('bronze diabetes'). The same iron also hits skin, MCP joints, pituitary, and heart."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Cirrhosis is the point of irreversibility in HHC: phlebotomy won't undo it, and the HCC risk jumps 120× (up to 1/3 of cirrhotics) — the opposite of PBC, where HCC is rare."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Two organs are deposited with the same excess metal, yet one gives a fully reversible problem and the other an irreversible one with a 120-fold cancer risk. Walk the iron from gut to organ, and explain why catching HHC before cirrhosis changes everything."}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe Wilson disease (WD)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Wilson disease is the copper twin of hemochromatosis — and Schneider builds the whole LO on the contrast. It is autosomal recessive on chromosome 13, with over 100 mutations, which makes genetic testing less useful and the clinical presentation highly variable. Where HHC is a disease of the 4th–5th decade, Wilson is the young person's disease (median presentation 12–23, oldest diagnosed at 58). Michael J. Fox, diagnosed with young-onset Parkinson's, was famously worked up for Wilson's — the right reflex, even though he did not have it."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE CORE DEFECT — EXCRETION, NOT ABSORPTION. This is the single most testable line. Copper homeostasis normally runs through biliary excretion. In Wilson, copper absorption is NORMAL but biliary excretion is DECREASED — so copper has nowhere to go: more copper is absorbed into the blood, and urinary copper excretion is therefore elevated (the elevated 24-hour urinary copper is a key test). Lay it directly against HHC: hemochromatosis absorbs too much iron; Wilson fails to excrete copper. Schneider promised you would 'read this 17 times before the test' — believe him."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Wilson: copper absorption normal, biliary EXCRETION decreased → blood copper up, urinary copper elevated."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE CERULOPLASMIN TRAP. Ceruloplasmin is the copper-transport protein, and in Wilson it is LOW — but the slide states the rule outright: 'Deficiency is not the cause of WD.' The level falls as a consequence of the disordered copper handling (it is consumed), not as the primary lesion. Schneider flags the inverse as the genuinely useful test: a high ceruloplasmin level excludes Wilson disease. So read low ceruloplasmin as supporting evidence, not as the mechanism."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Ceruloplasmin is LOW in WD because it is consumed, not deficient; a high level excludes WD."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HOW IT PRESENTS — AND THE TWO 'THINK WILSON' SITUATIONS. Presentation is variable: hepatic in ~42% (asymptomatic LFTs → portal hypertension → acute liver failure), neuropsychiatric in ~35% (parkinsonism, depression, poor school performance), and hemolysis in ~12%. Kayser-Fleischer rings — bands of copper at the superior and inferior corneal poles, seen on slit-lamp — are more common in neuro Wilson. Schneider's pearl: think Wilson in two unusual situations — (1) a young person with acute/severe liver dysfunction plus hemolytic anemia, and (2) a young person with unexplained parkinsonism."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Kayser-Fleischer rings (corneal copper, slit-lamp) — more common in neuro Wilson."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DIAGNOSIS AND TREATMENT. Diagnosis leans on young age, the slit-lamp exam, a low ceruloplasmin, an elevated urinary copper, and — the gold standard — liver biopsy for copper quantification (genetic testing helps mainly when a proband is known). Treat by decoppering with penicillamine or trientine, and use zinc to inhibit copper absorption; transplant is for fulminant cases (WD is a leading etiology of pediatric liver transplant). Prognosis is excellent if the patient stays compliant — but stopping the meds can tip many into fulminant failure within 1–2 years. Unlike HHC, HCC is rare in Wilson."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Wilson: liver biopsy = gold standard; decopper with penicillamine/trientine, zinc blocks absorption."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Wilson vs HHC: Wilson = copper, chr 13, EXCRETION fails (young, neuropsych); HHC = iron, chr 6, ABSORPTION excess (4th–5th decade, organ deposition)."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Wilson is NOT a ceruloplasmin deficiency — the level is low because it is consumed, a consequence not a cause. A high ceruloplasmin excludes WD."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Think Wilson in a young patient with acute liver failure + hemolytic anemia or unexplained parkinsonism; look for Kayser-Fleischer rings on slit-lamp."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A student says Wilson disease is 'a ceruloplasmin deficiency.' Schneider calls that the common mistake. What is actually wrong with the copper, and why does ceruloplasmin end up low anyway?"}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Overview of autoimmune hepatitis, alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency, primary sclerosing cholangitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Schneider closes the Hit Parade with three diseases at breadth, not depth — learn each by its one signature. Autoimmune hepatitis (AIH) attacks hepatocytes; primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) attacks large bile ducts and lives next to IBD; alpha-1 antitrypsin (A1AT) hits liver AND lung. He warned that fourth-year students chronically blur the bile-duct diseases and forget the antibodies — so the antibodies and the PBC-vs-PSC split are the durable discriminators here."}, {"t": "p", "x": "AUTOIMMUNE HEPATITIS — URGENT, AND IT MIMICS VIRAL. AIH can present as an acute symptomatic hepatitis mimicking viral hepatitis, or quietly with only abnormal liver tests, and is frequently tied to other autoimmune disease. What makes it different from hepatitis A or B is urgency: acute AIH needs urgent treatment and can be fatal. The pathophysiology is an immune-mediated attack on the hepatocytes — contrast PBC, which is cholestatic injury against the bile ducts. Diagnosis is by antibody: in adults, anti-smooth-muscle antibody (ASMA) (many also have ANA); in children, anti-LKM (anti-liver-kidney microsomal). Treat acute disease with steroids (they 'work great'), then transition chronic disease to steroid-sparing immunomodulators like 6-mercaptopurine / azathioprine."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "AIH attacks hepatocytes (vs PBC's ducts); ASMA+ANA in adults, anti-LKM in kids; urgent steroids."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PSC — THE MEN'S CHOLANGITIS, DIAGNOSED BY PICTURE. PSC is predominantly men and lives with bowel disease: 90% of PSC patients have underlying IBD, though fewer than 10% of IBD patients have PSC. The pathophysiology is an aberrant immune/genetic attack on predominantly macrohepatic (large, visible) bile ducts — the mirror image of PBC's microhepatic, small-duct disease. Its diagnosis is genuinely special: there is no suggestive serology, so you make it by imaging — ERCP (MRCP also suggestive), looking for bile-duct beading and the 'chain of lakes' appearance. No medical therapy is curative; transplant is effective. (Walter Payton, 'Sweetness,' died of cholangiocarcinoma with PSC — a reminder of the bile-duct-cancer risk.)"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PSC: men, 90% have IBD, macrohepatic ducts, no serology → dx by ERCP ('chain of lakes')."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ALPHA-1 ANTITRYPSIN — LIVER AND LUNG. The one line to carry: think liver AND lung. The lung manifestation is early-onset emphysema — classically in a non-smoker (or a smoker far too young for it). The liver runs a spectrum from simple abnormal liver tests to cirrhosis, and it can develop in adults without any antecedent childhood liver disease. Diagnosis combines clinical suspicion, a measured AAT level, and targeted genotyping/phenotyping for the common variants (the M/Z alleles — ZZ being the classic disease genotype)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "A1AT = liver AND lung: early emphysema in a non-smoker + liver spectrum to cirrhosis; dx by AAT level + genotype."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Antibodies, sorted: AMA = PBC; ASMA (adult) / anti-LKM (peds) = AIH; PSC has none — diagnosed by ERCP. Schneider says students forget exactly these."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "A1AT = liver AND lung: early emphysema in a non-smoker plus a liver spectrum to cirrhosis. The lung clue is what flags the liver disease."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Acute AIH is an emergency — unlike hepatitis A/B it needs urgent steroids and can be fatal; chronic disease moves to steroid-sparing immunomodulators."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Three diseases, three signatures: which one needs urgent steroids, which one is diagnosed by an endoscopic procedure with no serology, and which one makes you think of the lungs as much as the liver?"}]}, {"id": 6, "statement": "Discuss the spectrum of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Schneider calls this the most common cause of liver disease you will see in your career — and he means it: an estimated 100 million Americans (~25% of the population) have fatty liver, and in the U.S. it is arguably the #1-2 cause of cirrhosis, hepatocellular carcinoma, and liver transplant. The nomenclature changed to reflect the real driver: NAFLD is now MASLD (metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease) and NASH is now MASH. The whole topic is the metabolic twin of the alcohol story — two roads to a fatty liver."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SPECTRUM — AND WHY MASH IS THE WORD THAT MATTERS. The disease runs from simple steatosis (MASL, ~80%) to MASH (~20%), the aggressive variant defined as steatohepatitis — 'inflammation from fat' — and on to cirrhosis, end-stage liver disease, and HCC. Hold one line above all: cirrhosis is the risk factor for liver cancer, but MASH is the point of reversibility. MASH is the window where the process can still be turned around, which is why finding the MASH-with-fibrosis subset is the whole game. (Schneider explicitly de-emphasized the proposed thyroid-hormone-signaling pathophysiology — 'please don't know this' — so we note it exists and move on.)"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Spectrum: MASL (simple steatosis, ~80%) -> MASH ('inflammation from fat,' ~20%) -> cirrhosis -> HCC."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cirrhosis is the risk factor for liver cancer; MASH is the point of reversibility."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHO HAS IT — THE METABOLIC-SYNDROME CLUSTER. The risk factors ARE the metabolic syndrome: obesity, type-2 diabetes, dyslipidemia, hypertension. The prevalence numbers track that company it keeps — 80-90% of obese adults, 50% of diabetics, 90% of hyperlipidemics, and 40-70% of obese children have fatty liver. So the exam vignette writes itself: an obese, diabetic, hypertensive, hyperlipidemic patient with abnormal LFTs who does not drink. And here the alcohol pearl comes back as the discriminator — this patient shows ALT > AST (Schneider's worked case had ALT 78 / AST 55), which is exactly the non-alcoholic pattern, while alcohol would have given AST > ALT."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DIAGNOSIS — IMAGING SEES FAT, NITs SEE FIBROSIS. Here is the highest-yield diagnostic distinction in the lecture: ultrasound, CT, and MRI all see only fat — they do NOT identify inflammation or fibrosis (the prof's image: 'helicopters over your lawn — they just see fat'). Since the dangerous patient is the one with fibrosis, you find them with non-invasive tests (NITs): blood biomarkers + elastography, and only rarely a liver biopsy. Fibrosis is staged F0 to F4. The diagnosis itself rests on clinical suspicion in a risk-factor patient plus variable LFT/lipid/glucose abnormalities — abnormal LFTs are not mandatory."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "US/CT/MRI see fat, NOT fibrosis; find MASH-with-fibrosis using NITs = biomarkers + elastography, rarely biopsy."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Fatty-liver vignette (obese/diabetic/HTN, no alcohol) shows ALT > AST — the non-alcoholic pattern."}, {"t": "p", "x": "TREATMENT — THE FIRST-EVER DRUGS, AND THE CAUSE OF DEATH. For the prof's whole career there was nothing but diet and exercise; now the first-ever treatments are here. Resmetirom is the first-in-class drug, FDA-approved March 2024 for MASH, indicated for F2-F3 fibrosis on non-invasive testing — it has been shown to reverse fibrosis and reduce liver fat. Semaglutide (the GLP-1 agonist) had its NEJM Phase 3 trial published May 2025 showing resolution of steatohepatitis and improved fibrosis, and per slide 38 is 'now indicated for MASH with obesity' (in lecture Schneider hedged that wording to 'going to be indicated'). But do not lose the clinical punchline: cardiovascular disease — not the liver — is the leading cause of mortality in MASH."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Resmetirom (first-in-class, FDA Mar 2024) treats MASH F2-F3 fibrosis and reverses fibrosis; semaglutide = NEJM Phase-3 May 2025, MASH + obesity."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Leading cause of death in MASH is cardiovascular disease, not liver-related death."}, {"t": "key", "x": "MASH is the point of reversibility. Cirrhosis is the cancer risk factor, but MASH is the still-fixable window — which is why pulling the MASH-with-fibrosis subset out of the fatty-liver crowd is the entire diagnostic point."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Imaging just sees fat. Ultrasound, CT, and MRI cannot see inflammation or fibrosis — the fibrotic (MASH) subset is found with NITs: blood biomarkers + elastography, rarely a biopsy."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Two fatty livers, one ratio: alcohol = AST > ALT, metabolic/MASLD = ALT > AST. The transaminase ratio is how the vignette wants you to tell them apart."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A 45-year-old obese diabetic with hypertension has abnormal LFTs, no alcohol use, and no hepatotoxic drugs. Her ALT is 78 and her AST is 55. What is the diagnosis, and which single lab ratio rules alcohol out?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Flipping the alcohol ratio. Students reflexively expect ALT to be highest in any liver injury. In alcohol it is AST > ALT; ALT > AST is the pattern of non-alcoholic/metabolic fatty liver and most everything else. If AST is higher, think alcohol. → LO 39.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Blaming the high PT/INR on platelets. In cirrhosis the low platelets come from hypersplenism (portal HTN), while the prolonged PT/INR comes from failed synthesis of vitamin-K factors II, VII, IX, X — two separate mechanisms, not one. → LO 39.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Thinking imaging can stage MASH. Ultrasound, CT, and MRI see only fat, not inflammation or fibrosis. The MASH-with-fibrosis subset is found with NITs (biomarkers + elastography), rarely a biopsy. → LO 39.6"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Expecting MASH patients to die of their liver. MASH does cause cirrhosis, cancer, and transplant — but cardiovascular disease is the leading cause of mortality in MASH. → LO 39.6"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Confusing PBC and PSC. PBC = women, microhepatic, AMA; PSC = men, macrohepatic, no serology (ERCP 'chain of lakes'). Schneider says students forget exactly this distinction and all the antibodies. → LO 39.2 / 39.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Mixing up absorption vs excretion. HHC absorbs too much iron (chromosome 6); Wilson fails to excrete copper (chromosome 13). Same overload logic, opposite step — intake vs output. → LO 39.3 / 39.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. Calling Wilson a 'ceruloplasmin deficiency.' Ceruloplasmin is low because it is consumed, not the primary cause — the slide says 'deficiency is not the cause of WD.' A high level excludes Wilson. → LO 39.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "8. Forgetting HHC's cirrhosis cliff. Pre-cirrhosis HHC has an excellent prognosis with phlebotomy; cirrhosis is irreversible and carries a 120× HCC risk (up to 1/3). HCC is rare in PBC and Wilson. → LO 39.3"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"alcoholic with AST roughly twice the ALT\" → the ratio itself is the diagnosis; AST > ALT = alcohol."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"low platelets and a prolonged INR, no history given\" → call cirrhosis off the labs (hypersplenism + lost clotting-factor synthesis)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"ultrasound shows fatty liver — what next to assess fibrosis?\" → non-invasive tests / elastography, because imaging only sees fat."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"patient with MASH — most likely cause of death?\" → cardiovascular disease, not the liver."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"man with ulcerative colitis, beaded ducts on ERCP\" → PSC, not PBC; no serology, macrohepatic ducts."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"young patient, copper, low ceruloplasmin\" → Wilson (excretion defect, chr 13); iron + transferrin sat → HHC (chr 6)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. \"ceruloplasmin is high\" → that excludes Wilson; don't anchor on 'low ceruloplasmin = deficiency.'"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "8. \"hemochromatosis patient with cirrhosis\" → think hepatocellular carcinoma (120× risk); screen, because it's irreversible."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Alcohol, MASH, and the metabolic causes of cirrhosis all funnel toward the same end organ whose circulatory consequences (passive congestion, Budd-Chiari, portal-vein thrombosis) are taught in Lec 42 (Circulatory Disorders of the Liver), this doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — The autoimmune/genetic chronic-liver diseases that complete this shared LO set — PBC, hemochromatosis, Wilson, AIH/A1AT/PSC — are taught in the Lec 40 half of this merged block, this doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Lactulose for the hepatic encephalopathy of decompensated cirrhosis is the same osmotic laxative whose ammonia-trapping MOA is taught in Lec 41 (Laxatives), this doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — These hereditary/autoimmune diseases are all causes of cirrhosis — their alcohol and MASH counterparts are the OTHER half of this block (Lec 39, this doc); the vascular consequences of cirrhosis (Budd-Chiari, portal-vein thrombosis, passive congestion) are Lec 42, this doc"}]}]}, "41": {"prof": "Dr. Mayur Parmar", "tldr": "Sort every drug by class and mechanism, not dose: laxatives by how they move water and stool, antidiarrheals by how they slow the gut — then match the agent to the condition (IBS-C vs IBS-D).", "mustKnows": ["1. Two halves, eight buckets. Laxatives split into bulk-forming, stool softeners/lubricants, osmotic, and stimulant/irritant (plus the severe-constipation secretagogues); antidiarrheals into opioid-antimotility, antisecretory, bile-salt-binding resins, and probiotics. Parmar tests class + mechanism + signature AE, not the dose — he said repeatedly he is not expecting you to remember the microgram numbers.", "2. Lactulose traps ammonia. Lactulose is a non-absorbed disaccharide degraded by colonic bacteria into organic acids that lower colonic pH and trap ammonia (NH₃ → NH₄⁺) so it can't be absorbed — which is why it has a dual use: chronic constipation and hepatic encephalopathy (lowers blood ammonia). The osmotic pull also softens stool.", "3. The '-tide' secretagogues raise cGMP. Linaclotide (14-aa) and plecanatide (16-aa) are guanylate cyclase-C agonists: they raise intracellular cGMP → secretion of Cl⁻ and HCO₃⁻ into the lumen, pulling in water for CIC and IBS-C. Lubiprostone is a PGE1 derivative that activates ClC-2 chloride channels (CIC, OIC, IBS-C in women).", "4. Linzess 20% vs Trulance 5% diarrhea. Both GC-C agonists, but linaclotide (Linzess) causes ~20% diarrhea versus plecanatide (Trulance) ~5% — so Trulance is often preferred. Both carry a boxed warning and are contraindicated in children <6 years (dehydration risk) and in suspected mechanical GI obstruction.", "5. Stimulant laxatives are the abuse class. Bisacodyl and the anthraquinones (senna) directly stimulate the colon and are the most commonly abused laxative class. Chronic abuse → cathartic colon (lost motility) and melanosis coli (benign brownish-black mucosal pigment from lipofuscin, classic with senna); bisacodyl overuse can cause metabolic alkalosis.", "6. Opioid antimotility — and where it's banned. Diphenoxylate/atropine, difenoxin, loperamide, and eluxadoline activate gut μ-opioid receptors to slow transit. The trap: do NOT use them in infectious/inflammatory diarrhea (C. difficile, IBD) — they risk toxic megacolon and sepsis. Loperamide is OTC (no BBB, low abuse), carries a boxed warning for torsades/QT, and is contraindicated <2 years.", "7. Eluxadoline = IBS-D; the others differ. Eluxadoline is a mixed μ-/κ-agonist + δ-antagonist for IBS-D — Parmar's flagged exam trap (IBS with diarrhea → eluxadoline). It is contraindicated in sphincter-of-Oddi dysfunction, pancreatitis, biliary obstruction, and >3 alcoholic drinks/day. Difenoxin is the active metabolite of diphenoxylate, ~5× more potent (Schedule I alone, Schedule IV with atropine).", "8. The 41.5 rationale trio: 5-ASA, steroids, octreotide. Sulfasalazine is cleaved by colonic bacteria into 5-ASA (anti-inflammatory in ulcerative colitis); glucocorticoids are anti-inflammatory for IBD flares; and octreotide, a somatostatin analog, inhibits secretion of serotonin/gastrin/VIP/motilin to control neuroendocrine-tumor (carcinoid, VIPoma) secretory diarrhea and refractory CID. Octreotide's signature AE is cholelithiasis."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "List the categories of laxatives and antidiarrheal agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Parmar runs this lecture as a two-part drug-class spine — laxatives first, antidiarrheals second — and the single most useful thing you can do is build the category map before you learn a single mechanism. He said it plainly and repeatedly: he is not expecting you to remember the doses; he wants you to know which class a drug belongs to, how it works, and its one signature adverse effect. Laxatives start with a definition — drugs that accelerate fecal passage or decrease fecal consistency, used primarily for constipation — and the recurring caution that they treat the symptom, not the underlying cause, so undiagnosed abdominal pain, IBD, or obstruction must be excluded first."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE LAXATIVE BUCKETS. Four core classes, plus a fifth for severe disease. Bulk-forming agents are the fibers — psyllium, methylcellulose, wheat dextrin, and the synthetic polycarbophil. Stool softeners / lubricants are docusate sodium and mineral oil. Osmotic laxatives subdivide into salt-containing (saline) agents (magnesium hydroxide/citrate, sodium phosphate, Suflave), salt-free PEG (GoLYTELY, MiraLAX), and non-digestible sugars/alcohols (lactulose, lactitol). Stimulant/irritant laxatives are bisacodyl and the anthraquinones (senna). For severe constipation, the secretagogues — linaclotide, plecanatide, lubiprostone — sit in their own group."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Laxative classes: bulk-forming, softener/lubricant, osmotic, stimulant (+ secretagogues for severe)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ANTIDIARRHEAL BUCKETS. The second half mirrors the first. Opioid-agonist / antimotility agents — diphenoxylate (with atropine), difenoxin, loperamide, eluxadoline — slow the gut. Antisecretory agents are bismuth subsalicylate and octreotide. Bile-salt-binding resins are cholestyramine, colestipol, colesevelam. And probiotics (Lactobacillus GG, Saccharomyces boulardii) round it out. Like the laxatives, antidiarrheals are supportive therapy — they control the symptom, and you stop them and seek evaluation if the diarrhea is bloody, febrile, or worsening."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Antidiarrheal classes: opioid-antimotility, antisecretory, bile-salt resins, probiotics."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Build the category map first: four laxative buckets (bulk / softener / osmotic / stimulant, + secretagogues) and four antidiarrheal buckets (antimotility / antisecretory / resins / probiotics). Class + mechanism + signature AE is what Parmar tests."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Both halves share one rule: these are supportive agents that do not treat the underlying cause — identify the diagnosis before any long-term use."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Don't blur osmotic subtypes: salt-containing (saline) vs salt-free PEG vs sugars/alcohols (lactulose, lactitol) are three distinct osmotic sub-buckets."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Parmar told the class he is not testing the microgram doses. If the doses don't matter, what is the spine he actually wants you to carry out of this lecture?"}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Discuss the mechanism of action of the laxative and antidiarrheal agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. This is the deepest LO of the lecture — every drug slide leads with Mechanism of action, and Parmar spends most of his minutes here. The trick is to see that all the laxatives are variations on getting water into the stool and all the antidiarrheals on keeping it in the body; the testable detail is by what molecular route. Work down the laxative buckets first, then cross to the antidiarrheals."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE PHYSICAL LAXATIVES — BULK, SOFTEN, LUBRICATE, OSMOSE. Bulk-forming colloids absorb water in the small and large intestine, forming an emollient gel that distends the colon and promotes peristalsis. Docusate (a stool softener) lowers surface tension so water and fat mix into the stool, with a mild bowel-stimulant effect; mineral oil coats the stool and mucosa and reduces water absorption to ease passage. Osmotic laxatives — saline (poorly absorbed Mg/Na/phosphate ions), PEG, and sugars/alcohols — raise luminal osmotic pressure and draw water into the bowel (Mg²⁺ = Must go 2 the bathroom). Same end (more luminal water), four different routes."}, {"t": "p", "x": "LACTULOSE — THE AMMONIA-TRAPPER. The osmotic sugar that earns its own paragraph. Lactulose is not absorbed in the small intestine, so it reaches the colon intact, where gut bacteria degrade it into organic acids that lower colonic pH. The acidic lumen converts ammonia to its charged form and traps ammonia (NH₃ → NH₄⁺), which can't be reabsorbed — so lactulose both relieves constipation and lowers blood ammonia in hepatic encephalopathy. The same osmotic pull draws water in to soften stool. That dual use is the high-yield reason lactulose bridges this lecture and the chronic-liver-disease block."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Lactulose: colonic bacteria → organic acids → trap NH₃ as NH₄⁺ → dual use in hepatic encephalopathy."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SECRETAGOGUES — cGMP AND ClC-2. The severe-constipation drugs secrete chloride to pull water in. Linaclotide (synthetic 14-amino-acid peptide) and plecanatide (16-amino-acid) are guanylate cyclase-C (GC-C) receptor agonists: they raise intracellular cGMP, which drives secretion of chloride and bicarbonate into the lumen, accelerating transit and softening stool (the -tide ending = GC-C, increases cyclic GMP rule). Lubiprostone takes a different door — a PGE1 derivative that selectively activates ClC-2 chloride channels on the apical membrane to secrete chloride-rich fluid. GC-C raises cGMP; lubiprostone hits the ClC-2 channel directly — keep the two doors separate."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Linaclotide (14-aa) / plecanatide (16-aa) = GC-C agonists → ↑cGMP → Cl⁻/HCO₃⁻ secretion; lubiprostone (PGE1) = ClC-2 activator."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ANTIDIARRHEAL MECHANISMS — SLOW IT, DRY IT, BIND IT. Crossing to the other half: opioid-antimotility agents activate gut μ-opioid receptors to reduce propulsive peristalsis, increase segmental contractions, and prolong transit so more water is reabsorbed — diphenoxylate, difenoxin, loperamide, and the mixed eluxadoline (μ-/κ-agonist, δ-antagonist) for IBS-D. Bile-salt-binding resins (cholestyramine, colestipol, colesevelam) bind bile acids that have spilled into the colon and would otherwise drive secretory diarrhea. Bismuth is antisecretory (salicylate moiety) plus antimicrobial (bismuth). And crofelemer inhibits CFTR and CaCC chloride channels to cut secretion without touching nutrient absorption."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Antimotility agents = gut μ-opioid receptor agonists → slow transit → more water reabsorbed."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Lactulose's dual use falls straight out of its mechanism — trapping ammonia as NH₄⁺ in an acidified colon makes it both a laxative and a hepatic-encephalopathy drug."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Both secrete chloride, different doors: GC-C agonists (-tide) raise cGMP; lubiprostone (PGE1) opens the ClC-2 channel directly."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Read the suffix on the secretagogues: a drug ending in '-tide' is a guanylate cyclase-C agonist that raises cGMP."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Three different drugs all 'pull water into the lumen,' but by three different molecular routes. Name the route for a saline laxative, lactulose, and linaclotide — and why the route, not the effect, is what gets tested."}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Discuss the therapeutic and adverse effects of the laxative and antidiarrheal agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Every drug slide carries therapeutic uses and adverse effects in parallel, and the exam pattern Parmar coaches is a drug-matching one: which agent for which condition, and which signature AE flags which agent. The organizing move is to learn one headline indication and one signature toxicity per drug, because that pairing is what a vignette keys off. Below, the high-emphasis ones."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE LAXATIVE USES — AND THE UNIVERSAL RISK. Bulk-forming fibers are the preferred long-term agents for chronic constipation and are safe in pregnancy (e.g., psyllium); their common AE is bloating/flatulence from bacterial digestion. Osmotic agents share one universal toxicity Parmar restates at nearly every slide — dehydration and electrolyte imbalance (with overuse: hypokalemic paralysis, renal failure, worst in the elderly, diabetics, and the renally impaired). PEG (GoLYTELY 4 L, MiraLAX) is the colonoscopy/constipation workhorse; magnesium citrate preps for colonoscopy; bisacodyl is for bowel prep and reduces repeated enemas in the elderly, but overuse → metabolic alkalosis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Bulk-forming = preferred long-term + pregnancy-safe; osmotics = universal dehydration/electrolyte risk."}, {"t": "p", "x": "STIMULANTS — THE ABUSE CLASS. Bisacodyl and the anthraquinones are the most commonly abused laxative class, and chronic abuse leaves two findings worth recognizing on sight: cathartic colon (loss of normal colonic motility) and melanosis coli — a benign brownish-black pigmentation of the colonic mucosa (lipofuscin), classically from senna. Neither is life-threatening, but both signal long-term stimulant abuse and argue for switching to a safer maintenance agent."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Stimulant laxatives = most-abused class → cathartic colon + melanosis coli (senna, lipofuscin pigment)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SECRETAGOGUE USES — AND LINZESS vs TRULANCE. The severe-constipation agents map to specific indications: linaclotide for CIC and IBS-C; plecanatide for CIC and IBS-C; lubiprostone for CIC, opioid-induced constipation (OIC), and IBS-C in women. Both GC-C agonists cause dose-related diarrhea as their main AE — and the discriminator Parmar repeats is that linaclotide (Linzess) ~20% diarrhea vs plecanatide (Trulance) ~5%, which is why Trulance is often preferred. Lubiprostone can cause hypokalemia with prolonged use and nausea best blunted by taking it with food."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Diarrhea risk: Linzess ~20% > Trulance ~5%; lubiprostone covers CIC, OIC, and IBS-C in women."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ANTIDIARRHEAL USES — AND THEIR FLAGS. Loperamide is the OTC workhorse for traveler's, acute/chronic, and chemotherapy-induced diarrhea — no BBB crossing, no analgesia, low abuse — but overdose causes severe constipation/ileus. Bismuth covers heartburn through diarrhea and joins H. pylori quadruple therapy; it famously turns the tongue and stool grayish-black (bismuth sulfide). Octreotide's headline use is secretory diarrhea from neuroendocrine tumors and refractory CID, and its signature AE is cholelithiasis (gallstones from biliary stasis). Crofelemer is for non-infectious diarrhea in HIV/AIDS patients on antiretrovirals, and its advantage is that it spares nutrient absorption and doesn't cause constipation."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Octreotide = neuroendocrine secretory diarrhea, signature AE cholelithiasis; crofelemer = HIV antiretroviral diarrhea, spares absorption."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "A colonoscopy photo of brownish-black mucosa = melanosis coli from chronic senna/anthraquinone abuse — benign, but a tell for stimulant-laxative overuse."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Same class, different diarrhea risk: Linzess (linaclotide) ~20% vs Trulance (plecanatide) ~5% — the reason Trulance is often preferred."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Secretory diarrhea from a carcinoid/VIPoma not responding to loperamide → octreotide — and watch for its gallstones."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A radiologist won't help you here — a single colonoscopy photo of brownish-black mucosa, or a one-line 'gallstones on chronic therapy,' is enough to name the drug. Which signature adverse effect flags each of the abuse-prone laxative and the somatostatin analog?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Discuss the potential contraindications and drug interactions of the laxative and antidiarrheal agents", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The contraindications here are flagged hard because they are the drug-matching traps a vignette is built to spring. The pattern to carry: for each agent, one setting where giving it is dangerous. A 'which drug do you withhold' question is far more likely than a dosing question. Below are the four that recur."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ANTIMOTILITY IN INFECTIOUS/INFLAMMATORY DIARRHEA. The biggest trap. Opioid-antimotility agents slow transit — exactly the wrong thing when a pathogen or toxin needs to clear. Do not use loperamide, diphenoxylate, or difenoxin in infectious diarrhea (especially C. difficile) or in IBD: trapping the contents risks ileus, toxic megacolon, and sepsis. The same agents are off-limits with bloody stools, high fever, or systemic toxicity — those signal an invasive process that demands evaluation, not a brake on the gut. Loperamide additionally carries a boxed warning for torsades/QT in overdose and is contraindicated in children <2 years."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "No antimotility agents in infectious (C. diff)/inflammatory or bloody/febrile diarrhea → toxic megacolon/sepsis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ELUXADOLINE AND THE BILIARY TRACT. Eluxadoline carries a focused contraindication set tied to its sphincter-of-Oddi risk: avoid it in sphincter-of-Oddi dysfunction, pancreatitis, biliary duct obstruction, and in those drinking more than 3 alcoholic drinks per day. Its main adverse effect is sphincter-of-Oddi spasm (about 1% of patients, usually in the first week) — the same anatomy that drives the contraindications. Difenoxin's distinct footnote is scheduling: Schedule I alone, Schedule IV when combined with atropine (the atropine discourages abuse)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Eluxadoline contraindicated in sphincter-of-Oddi dysfunction, pancreatitis, biliary obstruction, >3 drinks/day."}, {"t": "p", "x": "BISMUTH, MINERAL OIL, AND THE SPACING RULES. Bismuth subsalicylate carries a salicylate moiety, so it is avoided in children/adolescents with viral infections (influenza, chickenpox) for Reye syndrome risk, in salicylate allergy, and alongside other salicylates — a one-line callback to the bismuth/Reye material already in the prior pharmacology block. Mineral oil is contraindicated in patients at aspiration risk (bedridden, dysphagia, GERD) because of aspiration pneumonia, impairs fat-soluble vitamin (A, D, E, K) absorption with prolonged use, and should not be combined with docusate (which increases its absorption). And the interaction to remember for the bulk-forming fibers: take with ≥8 oz water and dose ~2 hours apart from other medications, since the gel can bind them and impair absorption."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Bismuth = Reye risk in viral-illness kids (salicylate); mineral oil = aspiration pneumonia + ↓ADEK; bulk fiber = 2 h apart from other drugs."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "The classic kill: giving an antimotility agent in C. difficile or invasive diarrhea. Trapping the toxin risks toxic megacolon and sepsis — withhold it if the stool is bloody or febrile."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Eluxadoline is the biliary-risk drug: avoid in sphincter-of-Oddi dysfunction, pancreatitis, biliary obstruction, or >3 drinks/day."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Two pediatric flags, two drugs: bismuth → Reye in viral illness (salicylate); loperamide → contraindicated <2 years (torsades boxed warning)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Four contraindication traps recur on these slides — antimotility in one setting, eluxadoline in another, bismuth in a third, mineral oil in a fourth. Name the forbidden setting for each."}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Discuss the rationale for the use of sulfasalazine, glucocorticoids, and octreotide in treating diarrhea", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. This LO is a discrete rationale trio, and the unifying idea is that these three agents control diarrhea by treating the underlying disease, not by braking the gut. Sulfasalazine and glucocorticoids quiet inflammatory bowel disease; octreotide shuts off tumor hormone secretion. Match each to the disease it actually treats and the question answers itself."}, {"t": "p", "x": "SULFASALAZINE → 5-ASA IN ULCERATIVE COLITIS. Sulfasalazine is a prodrug: colonic bacteria cleave it at the azo bond into sulfapyridine (the absorbed carrier) and 5-aminosalicylic acid (5-ASA / mesalamine), which is the active anti-inflammatory moiety. The 5-ASA reduces colonic inflammation, neutralizes oxygen free radicals, and decreases intestinal secretion — controlling symptoms (including diarrhea) in mild-to-moderate ulcerative colitis flares. The key caveats: it does not cure the disease, and it reduces folic acid absorption, so folate supplementation is recommended."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Sulfasalazine → colonic bacteria release 5-ASA (active anti-inflammatory) for ulcerative colitis; supplement folate."}, {"t": "p", "x": "GLUCOCORTICOIDS → THE IBD FLARE. Glucocorticoids have broad anti-inflammatory effects and reduce cytokines, making them highly effective at controlling symptoms and inducing remission in moderate-to-severe ulcerative colitis and Crohn's disease flares — they reduce the GI inflammation driving the diarrhea and bleeding. They are flare (induction) therapy, not maintenance, and their systemic AEs — hypomania, insomnia, acute psychosis among them — limit long-term use."}, {"t": "p", "x": "OCTREOTIDE → SECRETORY DIARRHEA FROM TUMORS. The third agent treats a different disease entirely. Octreotide is a synthetic somatostatin analog that inhibits secretion of GI hormones and peptides — serotonin, gastrin, VIP, motilin — giving an antisecretory and proabsorptive effect and slowing transit. That is exactly the rationale for secretory diarrhea from neuroendocrine tumors (carcinoid syndrome, VIPomas) and refractory chemotherapy-induced diarrhea not responding to loperamide: shut off the hormone drive and the diarrhea stops. Its signature adverse effect remains cholelithiasis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Octreotide (somatostatin analog) inhibits serotonin/gastrin/VIP/motilin → controls carcinoid/VIPoma secretory diarrhea."}, {"t": "key", "x": "The 41.5 trio treats the disease, not the stool: sulfasalazine (5-ASA) and glucocorticoids for IBD inflammation; octreotide for neuroendocrine-tumor secretory diarrhea."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Sulfasalazine is inert until colonic bacteria cleave it into 5-ASA — the bug does the activating, which is why it works in the colon."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Hormone-driven secretory diarrhea (carcinoid, VIPoma) or CID failing loperamide → reach for octreotide."}, {"t": "q", "x": "These three drugs are not 'antidiarrheals' in the loperamide sense — they treat the disease that is causing the diarrhea. For sulfasalazine, glucocorticoids, and octreotide, what is the disease each one is actually treating?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Giving an antimotility agent in C. difficile. Slowing transit in infectious or inflammatory diarrhea traps the toxin and risks ileus, toxic megacolon, and sepsis — withhold loperamide / diphenoxylate if the stool is bloody, febrile, or C. diff. → LO 41.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Reaching for eluxadoline in IBS-C. Eluxadoline is for IBS-D (mixed μ-/κ-agonist, δ-antagonist); the constipation drugs are the GC-C agonists and lubiprostone. Direction is the trap. → LO 41.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Memorizing the microgram doses. Parmar said he is not testing the doses (linaclotide 290 vs 72/145 µg, plecanatide 3 mg CIC / 6 mg IBS-C) — know class, mechanism, and signature AE, not the numbers. → LO 41.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Confusing the two secretagogue doors. GC-C agonists (-tide) raise cGMP; lubiprostone (PGE1) opens the ClC-2 channel. Both secrete chloride, but by different mechanisms. → LO 41.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Calling both GC-C agonists equal on diarrhea. Linaclotide (Linzess) ~20% vs plecanatide (Trulance) ~5% diarrhea — the difference is why Trulance is often preferred, and a likely discriminator. → LO 41.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Bismuth subsalicylate in a child with a viral illness. The salicylate moiety means Reye syndrome risk — avoid it in children/adolescents with influenza or chickenpox. → LO 41.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. Reading melanosis coli as something sinister. Brownish-black colonic mucosa is benign melanosis coli from chronic senna/anthraquinone abuse (lipofuscin) — a tell, not a malignancy. → LO 41.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "8. Treating carcinoid secretory diarrhea like ordinary diarrhea. Loperamide won't touch it — the driver is tumor hormone secretion, so the agent is octreotide (somatostatin analog). → LO 41.5"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"bloody, febrile diarrhea, stool positive for C. difficile toxin\" → do NOT give an antimotility agent; toxic-megacolon risk."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"which drug for IBS with diarrhea?\" → eluxadoline (IBS-D); the '-tides' and lubiprostone are the IBS-C drugs."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"name the standard dose of linaclotide\" → don't take the bait; the exam wants class + mechanism + AE, not the µg."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"drug ending in -tide for chronic constipation\" → guanylate cyclase-C agonist that raises cGMP (not the ClC-2 door)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"GC-C agonist with the higher diarrhea rate\" → linaclotide (Linzess) ~20% vs Trulance ~5%."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"child recovering from chickenpox given Pepto-Bismol\" → Reye syndrome risk from the salicylate — avoid it."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. \"colonoscopy shows brownish-black colonic mucosa\" → melanosis coli from chronic senna use (benign)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "8. \"flushing + watery diarrhea, no response to loperamide\" → carcinoid/VIPoma → octreotide."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Lactulose bridges the pharmacology here to chronic liver disease — its ammonia-trapping is the hepatic-encephalopathy use in Lec 39-40 (Chronic Liver Disease), this doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Bismuth / Reye & salicylate and the broader GI-pharmacology spine were introduced in the prior block — callback to Lec 35-36 (GI Pharmacology) in gi 35-38.pdf; don't re-teach"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Sulfasalazine, glucocorticoids, and the IBD-flare logic connect to the inflammatory-bowel-disease and diverticular material — also Lec 38 (Abdominal Pain / IBD), prior doc"}]}]}, "42": {"prof": "Dr. Matthew Machini", "tldr": "Sort the five hereditary hyperbilirubinemias by conjugation — CN-I/CN-II/Gilbert are unconjugated (UGT1A1), Dubin-Johnson/Rotor are conjugated — and read the liver's vascular disorders off its dual blood supply and zone-3 vulnerability.", "mustKnows": ["1. Three unconjugated, two conjugated. The double-starred board table splits five hereditary hyperbilirubinemias by conjugation: the first three — Crigler-Najjar I, Crigler-Najjar II, Gilbert — are unconjugated (a defect in the UGT1A1 conjugating enzyme, gene 2q37); the last two — Dubin-Johnson and Rotor — are conjugated (an excretion/transport problem). All five are autosomal recessive. Machini flagged this slide as the source of two prior board questions.", "2. Crigler-Najjar I vs II. CN type I has an absent UGT1A1 enzyme → bilirubin >20 mg/dL, kernicterus, fatal in the neonatal period, and phenobarbital is ineffective (no enzyme to induce). CN type II has a decreased (not absent) enzyme → bilirubin <20, kernicterus uncommon, and phenobarbital is effective — the phenobarbital response is what separates the two types.", "3. Gilbert is the common, benign one. Gilbert syndrome is the most common hereditary hyperbilirubinemia (5-10% of the population), a mild unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia from two extra bases inserted in the UGT1A1 promoter that lower enzyme expression. It is benign and needs no treatment; jaundice surfaces with stress/fasting/illness. The diagnostic biopsy finding is lipofuscin (brown-black) pigment in hepatocytes.", "4. Dubin-Johnson = black liver, inverted coproporphyrin. Dubin-Johnson syndrome is a conjugated hyperbilirubinemia from a defective ABCC2/MRP2 canalicular transporter. The liver is grossly black from pigmented granules (polymerized epinephrine metabolites, NOT bilirubin). The board test: the urinary coproporphyrin ratio inverts from the normal 3:1 to 1:3 (III:I).", "5. Rotor: conjugated, no black pigment. Rotor syndrome is also a conjugated hyperbilirubinemia, from defective SLCO1B1/SLCO1B3 uptake/storage transporters. Unlike Dubin-Johnson there is NO black pigment in the liver; total urinary coproporphyrin is ~5x elevated, conjugated bilirubin appears in the urine, and LFTs are normal. It is benign with a good prognosis.", "6. Nutmeg liver = chronic passive congestion. Chronic passive congestion is venous-outflow stasis, most often from right-sided heart failure. The cut surface shows the mottled nutmeg liver — dilated, congested centrilobular (zone 3) sinusoids and terminal venules against paler periportal tissue. Machini flagged the nutmeg liver as a favorite board image.", "7. Zone 3 is the ischemic zone. In ischemic hepatitis (shock liver) and liver infarction, the histologic hallmark is necrosis of centrilobular (zone 3) hepatocytes — zone 3 is farthest from the arterial supply and most vulnerable to ischemia. Triggers cluster as acetaminophen, arrhythmia, and sepsis. The dual blood supply (portal vein + hepatic artery) is why the liver rarely truly infarcts.", "8. Budd-Chiari out, portal vein in — and PVT has NO necrosis. Budd-Chiari is hepatic-vein OUTFLOW obstruction (>2 veins) → hepatomegaly, ascites, centrilobular necrosis and a dark congested liver. Portal vein thrombosis is INFLOW obstruction → pre-sinusoidal portal hypertension with NO necrosis, only inflammation and atrophy (the liver's dual supply protects it); Virchow's triad is the usual setting, schistosomiasis the classic small-branch cause."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Describe the major pathological features of the hereditary hyperbilirubinemias", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. This is the high-yield heart of the lecture, and Machini handed you the organizing trick on a single slide he put in red and double-starred — he told the class 'I want you to know this slide' and that your board exam pulled two questions from it. The trick is one sort: conjugation. The first three diseases — Crigler-Najjar I, Crigler-Najjar II, and Gilbert — are UNCONJUGATED (a problem making bilirubin water-soluble), and the last two — Dubin-Johnson and Rotor — are CONJUGATED (a problem getting already-conjugated bilirubin out of the cell). Get that boundary and the rest is detail. All five are autosomal recessive."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE BILIRUBIN PRIMER YOU NEED FIRST. Bilirubin comes in two forms, and their properties are mirror images. Unconjugated bilirubin is albumin-bound, insoluble in water, toxic, NOT excreted in the urine, and needs an accelerator (the enzyme) to be processed. Conjugated bilirubin is loosely albumin-bound, water-soluble, non-toxic, excreted in the urine, and needs no accelerator. Direct = conjugated, indirect = unconjugated. Know the numbers: normal total bilirubin is 0.3-1.2 mg/dL (above 1.2 is hyperbilirubinemia), and clinically visible color — jaundice in the skin, icterus in the sclera — appears above ~2.5 mg/dL."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE UNCONJUGATED TRIO — ALL UGT1A1. The first three share one broken enzyme: UGT1A1 (uridine diphosphate glucuronosyltransferase), the conjugating enzyme, whose gene sits at chromosome 2q37 — Machini flagged that locus as a possible board detail. The three differ only in how much enzyme survives. Crigler-Najjar type I has the enzyme completely ABSENT: bilirubin climbs above 20 mg/dL, kernicterus sets in, and the disease is fatal in the neonatal period; critically, phenobarbital is INEFFECTIVE because there is no enzyme to induce. Crigler-Najjar type II keeps partial activity: bilirubin stays below 20, kernicterus is uncommon, and phenobarbital WORKS — that phenobarbital response is exactly what separates type II from type I."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "First three (CN-I, CN-II, Gilbert) = unconjugated, defect in UGT1A1 (gene 2q37)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "CN-I: absent enzyme, bili >20, kernicterus, phenobarbital ineffective; CN-II: partial, bili <20, phenobarbital effective."}, {"t": "p", "x": "GILBERT — THE COMMON, BENIGN ONE. Gilbert syndrome is the third UGT1A1 disorder and the one you will actually meet: it is the most common hereditary hyperbilirubinemia, affecting 5-10% of the population. The molecular defect is subtle — two extra bases inserted in the UGT1A1 promoter — which simply lowers enzyme expression, giving mildly decreased conjugation and bilirubin in the 1.5-5.0 mg/dL range. It is asymptomatic; jaundice surfaces only with stress, fasting, or illness, and it needs no treatment. The board's favorite handle is histologic: a biopsy shows increased lipofuscin (brown-black) pigment in hepatocytes — Machini framed it as a 'a biopsy shows lipofuscin, which is the diagnosis?' stem."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE CONJUGATED PAIR — EXPORT VS UPTAKE. The last two diseases have normal conjugation but can't move conjugated bilirubin where it belongs. Dubin-Johnson syndrome is the memorable one: a defective ABCC2/MRP2 canalicular export pump means conjugated bilirubin can't be secreted into bile, so it backs up — and the liver turns grossly black from pigmented granules (polymerized epinephrine metabolites, NOT bilirubin) in centrilobular hepatocytes. Its board-flagged test is the coproporphyrin ratio: normally coproporphyrin III:I is 3:1, but in Dubin-Johnson it INVERTS to 1:3 — Machini said 'underline it, put it in yellow, it's a board question.' Rotor syndrome is its quieter cousin: defective SLCO1B1/SLCO1B3 uptake/storage transporters, also conjugated, but with NO black pigment in the liver, a total urinary coproporphyrin ~5x elevated (ratio not inverted), and normal LFTs. Both are benign."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Dubin-Johnson: conjugated, MRP2/ABCC2, black liver, coproporphyrin inverted 3:1 → 1:3."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Rotor: conjugated, SLCO1B1/1B3, NO black pigment, coproporphyrin ~5x total, normal LFTs."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Sort all five by conjugation first: CN-I, CN-II, Gilbert = unconjugated (UGT1A1, 2q37); Dubin-Johnson, Rotor = conjugated (export/uptake). Machini's double-starred, 'board-twice' slide."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Dubin-Johnson vs Rotor: both conjugated and benign, but Dubin-Johnson has a black liver + inverted 1:3 coproporphyrin, while Rotor has no black pigment and ~5x total coproporphyrin."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Phenobarbital separates the Crigler-Najjars: it induces residual UGT1A1, so it works in type II (and Gilbert) but is useless in enzyme-absent type I."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini double-starred the five-disease table and said the board pulled from it twice. What is the single first sort that organizes all five, and which two diagnostic findings separate the two conjugated ones?"}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe the pathology of circulatory disorders of the liver", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The whole vascular block hangs on one anatomical fact Machini drilled — the liver has a dual blood supply, the portal vein plus the hepatic artery — so losing one channel is usually buffered by the other and the liver rarely truly infarcts. When flow does fail, it is the hepatocytes farthest from the oxygenated inflow — the centrilobular (zone 3) cells — that die first. Frame the disorders by where flow is compromised: impaired inflow (portal vein), intrahepatic (cirrhosis/sinusoidal), and outflow (hepatic vein, i.e. Budd-Chiari) — that Robbins grid predicts the whole presentation."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CHRONIC PASSIVE CONGESTION — THE NUTMEG LIVER. When venous outflow stagnates — most often from right-sided heart failure — blood backs up into the liver. The cut surface shows the classic mottled 'nutmeg liver': dilated, congested centrilobular (zone 3) sinusoids and terminal venules (the dark speckles) against paler surviving periportal tissue. Machini said the board 'loves this' image. Clinically the liver is enlarged and tender below the costal margin, and chronically the central-vein zones develop fibrosis (so-called cardiac cirrhosis); expect splenomegaly and renal congestion to travel with it."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Nutmeg liver = chronic passive congestion, most often right-sided heart failure; dilated centrilobular (zone 3) sinusoids."}, {"t": "p", "x": "SHOCK LIVER AND THE THREE ZONES. Ischemic hepatitis (liver shock) follows inadequate perfusion or oxygen — Machini's trigger cluster is acetaminophen toxicity, arrhythmia, infections, and surgery. Its cardinal feature is ischemic necrosis of centrilobular hepatocytes: zone 3 is most vulnerable (farthest from the inflow), zone 2 shows coagulative necrosis with hemorrhage when injury is worse, and zone 1 rarely takes permanent damage. Labs show a sharp transaminase spike — the steepest ALT/AST elevations (into the thousands) track the worst ischemic injury. This is the same zone-3 logic from the dual-supply opener."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Shock liver: ischemic necrosis of centrilobular (zone 3) hepatocytes; zone 3 = most vulnerable; triggers acetaminophen/arrhythmia/sepsis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "INFARCTION AND THE THREE BRIDGES. Because of the dual supply, frank liver infarction is rare; when it happens the histologic hallmark is necrosis of hepatocytes in zone 3. Machini then delivered bridging necrosis as worked board stems ('I was born to question about it') — three patterns by which areas link up: portal-to-portal bridging is the signature of chronic hepatitis; central-to-central reflects venous outflow obstruction / hypoperfusion; and central-to-portal reflects acute viral hepatitis (and exacerbations of chronic). Match the bridge to the process and the stem answers itself."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ZAHN INFARCT — THE 'INFARCT' THAT ISN'T. Finally, the infarct of Zahn is a pseudo-infarction: occlusion of a portal vein branch causes collateral sinusoidal congestion and hepatocyte atrophy but NO necrosis — the hepatic artery keeps the region alive. It can be an anemic or a hemorrhagic infarct grossly, and it ties directly into portal vein thrombosis (LO 42.4). The recurring theme of the whole LO: the dual supply means inflow problems give atrophy without necrosis, while outflow/ischemic problems give zone-3 necrosis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Liver rarely infarcts (dual supply); when it does, hallmark = zone-3 necrosis; Zahn = portal-branch occlusion, atrophy NO necrosis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Bridging necrosis: portal-portal = chronic hepatitis; central-central = outflow obstruction; central-portal = acute viral hepatitis."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Frame every vascular disorder by site: inflow (portal vein → varices/splenomegaly), intrahepatic (cirrhosis/ascites), outflow (hepatic vein → Budd-Chiari). The dual supply is why the liver rarely infarcts."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Zone 3 (centrilobular) is the ischemic zone — farthest from inflow, first to die in shock liver and the hallmark of liver infarction; it is also the congested zone in nutmeg liver."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Bridging necrosis tells the story: portal-portal = chronic hepatitis, central-central = outflow obstruction, central-portal = acute viral hepatitis."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini kept repeating 'remember that word — dual blood supply.' How does the liver's dual supply explain both why it rarely infarcts AND which specific zone of hepatocytes dies when blood flow does fail?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Discuss the etiological factors and major pathological features of Budd-Chiari syndrome", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Machini compressed this into the last few minutes, but the anchor is simple: Budd-Chiari syndrome is hepatic-vein OUTFLOW obstruction — thrombosis of the major hepatic veins (AKA hepatic vein thrombosis, a congestive hepatopathy). Obstruct more than two hepatic veins and blood can't leave the liver, producing the triad of hepatomegaly, ascites, and liver dysfunction. It is the outflow end of the vascular spectrum — contrast it with portal vein thrombosis, the inflow end (LO 42.4)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE PATHOPHYSIOLOGIC CASCADE. Trace the arrow-chain, because the board likes the steps: hepatic vein thrombosis → outflow obstruction → blood backs up into the liver → portal hypertension → centrilobular (zone 3) necrosis and fatty change → ascites and ultimately cirrhosis. Because outflow is blocked, the liver becomes dark and congested — the gross specimen is a deep red-black, congested liver, and a thrombus is visible in the hepatic vein on histology. This is the same zone-3 vulnerability you met in LO 42.2, now driven by back-pressure rather than forward ischemia."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Budd-Chiari = hepatic-vein OUTFLOW obstruction; >2 veins → hepatomegaly, ascites, liver dysfunction; dark congested liver."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SMALL-BRANCH VARIANT AND THE HISTO TAIL. When the obstruction sits not at the large hepatic veins but at the small intrahepatic venous branches, the entity is renamed sinusoidal obstruction syndrome (historically veno-occlusive disease) — same outflow-blockage theme, smaller caliber. Over time the centrilobular congestion/necrosis matures into centrilobular fibrosis with sinusoidal dilation, and the regenerating liver throws up large regenerative nodules, focal nodular hyperplasia, and hepatocellular adenomas. The etiologies are the hypercoagulable states (the same Virchow logic that drives portal vein thrombosis next door)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Small intrahepatic-branch Budd-Chiari = sinusoidal obstruction syndrome (veno-occlusive disease)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Budd-Chiari vs portal vein thrombosis: Budd-Chiari is OUTFLOW (hepatic vein) → congested dark liver with centrilobular necrosis; PVT is INFLOW (portal vein) → no necrosis."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Obstructing >2 hepatic veins is the threshold that yields the Budd-Chiari triad of hepatomegaly, ascites, and liver dysfunction."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Small intrahepatic-branch obstruction is the same disease one caliber down — call it sinusoidal obstruction syndrome (veno-occlusive disease)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Budd-Chiari and portal vein thrombosis are both venous clots in the liver, yet they sit at opposite ends of the circulation. Where exactly does Budd-Chiari obstruct, and what does that one fact predict about the liver's gross appearance and histology?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Discuss the pathophysiology, etiology, morphology, and clinical aspects of portal vein obstruction and thrombosis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Portal vein thrombosis (PVT) is narrowing or blockage of the portal vein by clot — the INFLOW end of the vascular spectrum, the mirror image of Budd-Chiari's outflow block. Machini gave the class one anchor he called 'the only one point here you should know': there is NO necrosis — only inflammation, hepatocellular atrophy, and sinusoidal congestion. The reason is the recurring theme of this whole lecture — the liver's dual blood supply means the hepatic artery keeps the tissue perfused even when portal inflow is blocked, so cells atrophy but do not die."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ETIOLOGY — VIRCHOW'S TRIAD AND THE WORM. The most common setting is Virchow's triad: hypercoagulability, endothelial (blood-vessel) damage, and decreased flow. The named causes run from idiopathic to neonatal umbilical sepsis / umbilical-vein catheterization, to intra-abdominal infection and injury (appendicitis, diverticulitis, trauma, surgery — pylephlebitis), to cirrhosis (whose scarred, slow-flow liver favors clot). Worldwide, the most common cause of small portal-vein-branch obstruction is schistosomiasis — Machini's image of the worm lodging in the portal vein 'in certain parts of the world.'"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PVT = INFLOW obstruction; the one point — NO necrosis, only inflammation + atrophy (dual supply protects)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "MORPHOLOGY AND CLINICAL TAIL. The downstream consequences are pre-sinusoidal portal hypertension (and its sequelae — varices, splenomegaly) and, when chronic, a portal cavernoma (cavernous transformation: a tangle of collateral vessels recanalizing around the clot). Obstruction of intrahepatic radicles produces the infarct of Zahn (a red-blue discoloration — congestion and atrophy, again no true necrosis), tying PVT back to LO 42.2. PVT comes in three types — acute, chronic, and tumor-related. Clinically expect abdominal pain and swelling, fever, and chills; the workup is Doppler ultrasound plus CT, with LFTs and endoscopy to assess varices."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PVT etiology = Virchow's triad; schistosomiasis = #1 small-branch cause; chronic PVT → portal cavernoma."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Don't assign necrosis to portal vein thrombosis — the single highest-yield point is that PVT gives inflammation and atrophy only, NO necrosis, because the hepatic artery keeps the tissue alive."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Chronic PVT recanalizes into a portal cavernoma (cavernous transformation of the portal vein) — a tangle of collateral vessels around the old clot."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Suspect PVT with abdominal pain + portal-hypertension signs; confirm with Doppler ultrasound + CT, then LFTs and endoscopy for varices."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini said the 'only point you should know' about portal vein thrombosis is one negative finding. What is it, and why does the liver's anatomy make that finding true?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Flipping the conjugation split. The first three (Crigler-Najjar I, Crigler-Najjar II, Gilbert) are UNCONJUGATED (UGT1A1 defect); the last two (Dubin-Johnson, Rotor) are CONJUGATED. Memorize the boundary the way slide 5 draws it. → LO 42.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Giving phenobarbital in Crigler-Najjar type I. Phenobarbital induces residual UGT1A1, so it helps type II and Gilbert but is useless in enzyme-absent type I — the response itself separates the two types. → LO 42.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Confusing Dubin-Johnson with Rotor. Both are conjugated and benign, but Dubin-Johnson has the black liver and the inverted 1:3 coproporphyrin; Rotor has no black pigment and ~5x total coproporphyrin. → LO 42.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Reading the coproporphyrin ratio backwards. Normal coproporphyrin III:I is 3:1; in Dubin-Johnson it INVERTS to 1:3. The inversion — not just an elevation — is the diagnostic clue. → LO 42.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Calling the liver an organ that infarcts easily. The dual blood supply (portal vein + hepatic artery) means it rarely infarcts; inflow problems give atrophy, and only ischemia/outflow give zone-3 necrosis. → LO 42.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Mismatching the bridging-necrosis patterns. Portal-portal = chronic hepatitis, central-central = venous outflow obstruction, central-portal = acute viral hepatitis — match the bridge to the process. → LO 42.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. Putting Budd-Chiari on the inflow side. Budd-Chiari is hepatic-vein OUTFLOW obstruction (>2 veins) → congested dark liver, ascites, centrilobular necrosis; the inflow block is portal vein thrombosis. → LO 42.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "8. Assigning necrosis to portal vein thrombosis. The single point to know is that PVT gives inflammation and atrophy only, NO necrosis — the hepatic artery keeps the tissue perfused. → LO 42.4"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"sort these five inherited jaundices by conjugation\" → first three (CN-I/CN-II/Gilbert) unconjugated, last two (Dubin-Johnson/Rotor) conjugated."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"jaundiced infant whose bilirubin doesn't fall on phenobarbital\" → Crigler-Najjar type I (absent enzyme, nothing to induce)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"benign conjugated jaundice with a grossly black liver\" → Dubin-Johnson (MRP2); if no black pigment, think Rotor."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"coproporphyrin III:I ratio reported as 1:3\" → the inverted ratio = Dubin-Johnson."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"vascular insult to the liver, yet no true infarct\" → invoke the dual blood supply; when it does fail, look for zone-3 necrosis."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"portal-to-portal fibrous bridges on biopsy\" → chronic hepatitis (central-portal = acute viral; central-central = outflow)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. \"hepatomegaly, ascites, and a dark congested liver\" → Budd-Chiari (hepatic-vein outflow obstruction)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "8. \"portal vein clot with atrophy but no hepatocyte death\" → portal vein thrombosis (no necrosis is the tell)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Cirrhosis & portal hypertension — the causes (alcohol, MASH, PBC/HHC/WD) live in Lec 39-40 (Chronic Liver Disease I & II), this doc; the vascular consequences (Budd-Chiari, PVT, passive congestion) are their downstream home here"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Bilirubin metabolism — the hereditary UGT1A1 / MRP2 hyperbilirubinemias are the molecular counterpart of the cholestatic bile-duct injury in PBC (Lec 39-40), this doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Acetaminophen / alcohol hepatotoxicity (zone-3, CYP2E1) — the ischemic/toxic zone-3 necrosis here echoes the alcohol-metabolism injury in Lec 39 (Chronic Liver Disease I), this doc"}]}]}, "43": {"prof": "Dr. Matthew Machini", "tldr": "Liver injury reads as one arrow — steatosis → steatohepatitis → cirrhosis → hepatic failure (zone-3, acetaminophen) and portal hypertension; then the biliary tree by category: congenital, autoimmune (PBC vs PSC), stones, cholecystitis, and the tumors.", "mustKnows": ["1. The alcoholic-liver arrow: steatosis -> steatohepatitis -> cirrhosis. Alcohol drives three lesions: steatosis (reversible fatty change) -> alcoholic steatohepatitis -> fibrosis/cirrhosis. The middle lesion's biopsy triad: ballooning (hydropic degeneration), Mallory-Denk bodies (ropy cytokeratin 8/18), neutrophils. Alcohol = >60% of chronic liver disease; HCC in ~15% of cirrhotics.", "2. Two enzymes, one bad ratio — the NADH story. The board pulled a question from the pathway: ADH makes ethanol -> acetaldehyde (cytosol), then ALDH makes acetaldehyde -> acetate (-> CO2 + H2O, mito). Both steps generate NADH, raising the NADH/NAD ratio — which increases fat synthesis AND decreases fat oxidation, piling up triglyceride = steatosis.", "3. Micronodular vs macronodular — size and what separates them. Cirrhosis = nodules + fibrosis + loss of architecture. Micronodular (Laennec/alcoholic) = uniform 1-3 mm nodules, thin passive septa. Macronodular (post-necrotic, non-alcoholic — HBV/HCV, Wilson, A1AT) = >3 mm variable nodules, wider scars. Size AND the septa-vs-scars separator are the discriminator.", "4. Liver color reads out the etiology. On gross pathology the color names the cause: alcoholic fatty = yellow; hemochromatosis = rusty/dark brown (iron); chronic biliary obstruction = large and green (retained bile). Machini color-coded the slide deliberately — green = obstruction, rusty = iron, yellow = alcohol/fat, so the color is the recall handle before any stain.", "5. Biliary atresia = obliterative cholangiopathy, #1 pediatric transplant. Biliary atresia (progressive obliterative cholangiopathy) = obstruction and fibrosis of the extrahepatic ducts, linked to GPC1 (glypican-1) deletion. The #1 neonatal cholestasis driving cirrhosis and death, and the #1 cause of pediatric liver transplant in the US. Type III (no anastomosable ducts at the porta hepatis) is most common.", "6. PBC vs PSC — the board contrast. PBC: AMA 90-95%, women (6:1), nonsuppurative loss of small/medium intrahepatic ducts, granulomatous florid duct lesion, Sjögren (70%) — 'above the question.' PSC: p-ANCA ~65%, men, intra- AND extrahepatic ducts, ulcerative colitis, onion-skin fibrosis → tombstone scar, beaded ERCP. Both → cirrhosis + cholangiocarcinoma.", "7. Cholesterol vs pigment stones. Cholesterol stones (~90%): yellow, gallbladder only, radiolucent (Ca-carbonate makes some radiopaque); risk = 4 F's (female, fat, forty, fertile) + estrogen/OCP, rapid weight loss, Native American. Pigment stones = unconjugated bilirubin: black (hemolysis/cirrhosis/TPN, radiopaque) vs brown (infection/stasis, Asian, radiolucent).", "8. Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses = chronic cholecystitis. Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses — mucosal herniations through the muscularis (pseudodiverticula) — are the microscopic hallmark of chronic cholecystitis (deck prints ~90%). Chronic cholecystitis follows repeated acute attacks: a thickened, shrunken wall (2-3x normal) with mononuclear infiltrate, fibrosis, and metaplasia.", "Mallory-Denk bodies = twisted-rope, cytokeratin 8/18, alcoholic steatohepatitis", "Alzheimer type II astrocytes = hepatic encephalopathy, swollen, hypertrophy + hyperplasia", "Asterixis = flapping tremor, encephalopathy, raised ammonia", "Gamna-Gandy bodies = iron-laden splenic nodules, congestive splenomegaly, portal HTN", "Budd-Chiari = hepatic vein thrombosis, post-sinusoidal, portal HTN", "Zone 2 (mid-zonal) = yellow fever, intermediate oxygenation", "Zone 1 (periportal) = phosphorus poisoning, eclampsia, best oxygenated", "Caput medusae = periumbilical, portosystemic shunt, portal HTN", "Liver flukes (cholangiocarcinoma) = Opisthorchis viverrini, Clonorchis sinensis, bile-duct cancer", "CA 19-9 + CEA = cholangiocarcinoma markers, painless jaundice, bile-duct adeno", "Charcot triad = fever, jaundice, RUQ pain, ascending cholangitis", "Caroli disease = intrahepatic ductal cysts, AR, polycystic kidneys, ductal plate malformation", "Beads-on-a-string ERCP = PSC, alternating strictures/dilations, large ducts", "Florid duct lesion = PBC, granulomatous, small intrahepatic duct destruction", "Xanthelasma + pruritus = PBC, hypercholesterolemia, high alkaline phosphatase", "Gangrenous cholecystitis = green-black gallbladder, ischemia, perforation risk"], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Describe alcoholic liver disease and the steatosis -> steatohepatitis -> fibrosis/cirrhosis progression, and distinguish ALD from NAFLD", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Alcohol is the dominant liver disease Machini teaches — he said it causes more than 60% of chronic liver disease and that the US is one of the top three alcohol-consuming countries. The key is one arrow with three sequential lesions: steatosis (fatty change) -> alcoholic steatohepatitis -> fibrosis/cirrhosis. If the disease is from alcohol it is alcoholic liver disease (ALD); if the identical fatty morphology occurs without alcohol it is non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD), whose drivers are obesity, insulin resistance, type 2 diabetes, and metabolic syndrome. Alcohol also drives 40-50% of cirrhosis deaths, and the natural history thins out as it advances: ~95% of heavy drinkers develop fatty liver, ~20% alcoholic hepatitis, ~15% cirrhosis, and hepatocellular carcinoma eventually arises in about 15% of alcoholic cirrhotics."}, {"t": "p", "x": "STEATOSIS — THE REVERSIBLE FIRST HIT. The first lesion is fatty change (steatosis): fat accumulates in hepatocytes from excessive entry, defective metabolism, or defective export, producing large macrovesicular fat globules. It is the reversible stage — injury that has not yet killed the cell — and Machini stressed that it appears fast, within a few days to weeks of heavy drinking. The liver grossly enlarges and turns soft, greasy, and yellow. Stop drinking here and the liver recovers."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ALCOHOLIC STEATOHEPATITIS — THE BIOPSY TRIAD. The middle lesion, alcoholic steatohepatitis, is where injury turns inflammatory, and it has a board-flagged biopsy triad: (1) hepatocyte ballooning — hydropic/ballooning degeneration, the most common form of hepatic injury, in which cells swell to double or triple size; (2) Mallory-Denk (Mallory hyaline) bodies — eosinophilic intracytoplasmic aggregates of damaged cytokeratin 8/18 with a 'twisted-rope' appearance; and (3) neutrophil infiltration. Fibrosis then begins around the central vein (centrilobular / pericellular), spreads to bridge into portal septa, and matures into nodular cirrhosis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Arrow: steatosis (reversible) -> steatohepatitis -> fibrosis/cirrhosis; alcohol = >60% of chronic liver disease."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Steatohepatitis triad: ballooning + Mallory-Denk bodies (cytokeratin 8/18) + neutrophils."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ALD = AST > ALT (≥2:1); NAFLD/MASLD = ALT > AST — the ratio splits the two fatty livers. [board, not a Lec-43 slide]"}, {"t": "key", "x": "One arrow, three lesions: steatosis -> steatohepatitis -> fibrosis/cirrhosis. Steatosis is reversible; the steatohepatitis biopsy triad is ballooning + Mallory-Denk bodies + neutrophils."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "ALD vs NAFLD: identical fatty morphology, different cause. Alcohol gives AST > ALT (≥2:1); the non-alcoholic (metabolic) form gives ALT > AST and is driven by obesity/insulin resistance/type 2 diabetes."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Mallory-Denk bodies are damaged cytokeratin 8/18, not specific to alcohol (also Wilson disease, NASH, biliary disease) — but in a drinker they anchor the steatohepatitis diagnosis."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini built the whole alcoholic liver around a single arrow with three lesions. Name the three in order, and give the three biopsy findings that define the middle one."}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Explain alcohol metabolism (ADH and aldehyde dehydrogenase) and how the rise in NADH drives hepatic fat accumulation", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Machini flagged this slide explicitly — 'I saw a question in the board from it.' Two enzymes do the work and you must keep them straight. Alcohol dehydrogenase (ADH) handles step one in the cytosol: ethanol -> acetaldehyde. Then aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH) handles step two in the mitochondria: acetaldehyde -> acetate, finally oxidized to CO2 and water. The mnemonic order: alcohol dehydrogenase first, aldehyde dehydrogenase second — substrate names track the enzyme names."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE NADH PIVOT — WHY THE LIVER GETS FATTY. Both oxidation steps strip electrons and generate NADH, so the NADH/NAD ratio rises. That single biochemical shift is the whole reason for steatosis, and Machini noted it cuts both ways. Higher NADH induces fatty-acid synthesis (more fat made) AND decreases fatty-acid oxidation (less fat burned). The net effect is triglyceride accumulation in the hepatocyte — the fatty (steatotic) liver. The acetaldehyde intermediate is independently toxic (it binds proteins and damages membranes), adding the inflammatory push toward steatohepatitis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ADH: ethanol -> acetaldehyde (cytosol). ALDH: acetaldehyde -> acetate (mito). Both make NADH."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "High NADH/NAD = ↑ fat synthesis + ↓ fat oxidation -> triglyceride accumulation = steatosis."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Ethanol -(ADH)-> acetaldehyde -(ALDH)-> acetate; both steps raise NADH, which increases fat synthesis and decreases fat oxidation -> steatosis."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Acetaldehyde is the toxic intermediate — it forms protein adducts and damages membranes, linking metabolism to the inflammatory steatohepatitis lesion."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Board handle: the by-product that explains the fatty liver is NADH — high NADH = make more fat, burn less fat."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini said the board pulled a question from the alcohol-metabolism pathway. Walk the pathway from ethanol to acetate, name both enzymes, and explain in one step why the by-product (NADH) causes a fatty liver."}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Define cirrhosis (nodules + fibrosis + loss of architecture) and distinguish micronodular (Laennec) from macronodular cirrhosis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Machini put the definition in red: hear cirrhosis and think three things — (1) abnormal nodule formation, (2) fibrosis, and (3) loss of the normal liver architecture. He framed it as a sequela, not a disease itself — the common endpoint of hepatitis, steatohepatitis, biliary disease, and others (alcohol in the US; schistosomiasis and parasites in much of the world). Pathologically it advances through fibrosis (excess collagen types I and III made by hepatic stellate/ITO cells, driven by TNF-alpha, TGF-beta, and IL-1 from Kupffer cells, with inflammation and regenerative nodules) and is partly reversible (regression) if the insult stops."}, {"t": "p", "x": "MICRONODULAR (LAENNEC) — SMALL, UNIFORM, ALCOHOLIC. Micronodular cirrhosis is also called alcoholic or Laennec's cirrhosis. The nodules are small and uniform, about 1-3 mm (the transcript: 1-2, maximum 3 mm), and are separated by thin passive septa of connective tissue. The sequence Machini drew: injury -> degeneration -> fibrosis -> dissection into nodules -> rearrangement of blood circulation -> cirrhosis. Two nodule populations appear: dissection nodules (hypoplastic, between the septa) and regenerative nodules (round, pseudo-encapsulated, with two-cell-thick plates that can turn dysplastic). It is the gross color slide too: yellow in alcoholic fatty cirrhosis, rusty in hemochromatosis, large and green in biliary obstruction (covered in LO 43.4)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cirrhosis = nodules + fibrosis + loss of architecture (three red words); a sequela, not a disease."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Micronodular = Laennec/alcoholic, 1-3 mm uniform nodules, thin septa."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Macronodular = post-necrotic, >3 mm, wider scars, non-alcoholic (HBV/HCV, Wilson, A1AT)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Cirrhosis = nodules + fibrosis + loss of architecture. Split by size: micronodular (Laennec, alcoholic, ≤3 mm, thin septa) vs macronodular (post-necrotic, non-alcoholic, >3 mm, wider scars)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Septa vs scars: micronodules are separated by thin passive septa; macronodules by wider, unhealthy scars — the separator, not just the size, is testable."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Macronodular = 'post-necrotic' and usually non-alcoholic (chronic hepatitis B/C, Wilson disease, alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini said when you hear 'cirrhosis' think three things, and then he split it two ways by nodule size. What are the three defining features, and what are the two size-based subtypes with their typical causes and what separates the nodules?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Match cirrhosis etiology to gross liver color (alcohol = yellow, hemochromatosis = rusty/brown, biliary obstruction = green)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Machini said he color-coded the slide on purpose — 'I want you to remember in what disease, what color the liver will have.' The gross color of a cirrhotic liver is a direct recall handle for its cause. Yellow = alcoholic fatty cirrhosis (the fat itself tints the liver yellow and greasy). Rusty / dark brown = hemochromatosis (deposited iron). Enlarged and green = chronic biliary obstruction (retained bile pigment). One look at the specimen narrows the differential before any stain."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHY IT WORKS. Each color is its pathology made visible. The yellow liver of alcohol is steatosis — triglyceride loading the hepatocytes. The rusty-brown liver of hemochromatosis is hemosiderin/iron in the parenchyma (Prussian-blue positive on stain). The green, enlarged liver of biliary obstruction is cholestasis — bile that cannot drain backs up and stains the tissue. Use the color as the first sort, then confirm with history and stains."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Color = cause: yellow = alcohol/fat, rusty = hemochromatosis (iron), green = biliary obstruction (bile)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Yellow = alcohol/fat; rusty/brown = hemochromatosis (iron); green = biliary obstruction (bile). The gross color is the etiology cue."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "See a green, enlarged liver -> think obstruction; rusty -> iron/hemochromatosis; yellow, greasy -> alcohol/steatosis."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini deliberately color-coded the cirrhosis slide. A cut liver surface is (a) yellow, (b) rusty-brown, (c) enlarged and green. Name the etiology each color points to and the pigment responsible."}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Describe acute and chronic hepatic failure, the three hepatic zones, acetaminophen as the leading US cause, and the acute-liver-failure triad", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Acute liver failure (ALF, fulminant) produces hepatic encephalopathy within ~6 months of diagnosis ('altered mental status and coagulopathies'); hepatocellular necrosis begins in the central zone and spreads toward the portal tracts. Chronic liver failure (CRF) follows repeated bouts and is mostly tied to cirrhosis (necrosis, inflammation, fibrosis), with HCC the usual cause of death. The morphologic clue that distinguishes them: in acute failure the liver is initially enlarged and then shrinks dramatically, and serum transaminases decline as viable hepatocytes are lost."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE THREE ZONES — KNOW THE NAMES. Machini said the board emphasized the zone names, so anchor them: zone 1 = periportal (best oxygenated; hit by injuries that need oxygen — phosphorus poisoning, eclampsia); zone 2 = mid-zonal (intermediate; classic for yellow fever); zone 3 = centrilobular (least oxygenated, highest P450; the ischemic/toxic zone — acetaminophen, carbon tetrachloride, chloroform). Zone 3 is the preferential site of damage because of its low oxygen and high drug-metabolizing capacity."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ACUTE-FAILURE TRIAD AND HEPATORENAL TAIL. Machini flagged a board question on the triad of acute liver failure: jaundice, coagulopathy, and encephalopathy. The coagulopathy is objective — INR >1.5 from impaired synthesis of clotting factors and vitamin K dependence. If the failing liver drags the kidney down, that is hepatorenal syndrome: a functional renal failure with decreased renal perfusion and GFR (systemic vasodilation + renal vasoconstriction) but histologically normal kidneys — prerenal physiology, not intrinsic damage. Untreated progression goes to multi-organ failure and death."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Zones: 1 periportal (phosphorus/eclampsia), 2 mid-zonal (yellow fever), 3 centrilobular (acetaminophen/CCl4)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Acetaminophen = ~50% of US acute liver failure, a zone-3 toxin (highest P450, lowest O2)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ALF triad = jaundice + coagulopathy + encephalopathy; coag = INR >1.5."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Hepatorenal syndrome = functional renal failure; ↓ perfusion/GFR, kidneys normal."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Zones 1 periportal / 2 mid-zonal / 3 centrilobular; acetaminophen = #1 US cause of acute liver failure and a zone-3 toxin; the triad = jaundice + coagulopathy + encephalopathy (INR >1.5)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Zone 3 is least oxygenated AND has the highest P450 - the double reason it is the preferential site for ischemic and drug/toxin injury (acetaminophen, CCl4)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Hepatorenal syndrome is functional (prerenal): perfusion/GFR fall but the kidney is structurally normal - don't call it acute tubular necrosis."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini said the board emphasized the zone NAMES and that he had a board question on the acute-failure triad. Name the three zones and an injury to each, name the #1 US cause of acute liver failure and its zone, and give the triad."}]}, {"id": 6, "statement": "Order liver labs by category: integrity (ALT/AST/LDH), function (bilirubin/bile acids/ALP/GGT), and synthetic (PT/PTT/factors)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW (background — full LFT lecture is Lec 48). Machini gave a single orientation slide: order liver labs by what they ask. To check hepatocyte integrity (are the cells intact?) order the cytosolic enzymes that leak when cells die — AST, ALT, and LDH. To check biliary excretory function (is bile flowing?) order serum bilirubin (total = unconjugated + conjugated; direct = conjugated only), urine bilirubin, serum bile acids, and the canalicular enzymes alkaline phosphatase (ALP) and gamma-glutamyl transpeptidase (GGT). To check synthetic (hepatocyte) function order what the liver makes — serum albumin and the clotting times PT and PTT (the liver makes most coagulation factors — fibrinogen, prothrombin, factors V, VII, IX, X). Keep this as a filing system; the detail comes in Lec 48."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "LFTs: integrity = AST/ALT/LDH; excretory = bilirubin/bile acids/ALP/GGT; synthetic = albumin/PT/PTT."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Three buckets: integrity (AST/ALT/LDH), excretory function (bilirubin, bile acids, ALP, GGT), synthetic function (albumin, PT/PTT) - full detail lives in Lec 48."}]}, {"id": 7, "statement": "Distinguish prehepatic/hepatic/posthepatic jaundice and conjugated vs unconjugated, and explain hepatic encephalopathy and hepatorenal syndrome", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "JAUNDICE — THREE PHASES, TWO CONJUGATION CLASSES. Jaundice is yellow discoloration of sclera/skin from elevated bilirubin; clinically visible when bilirubin reaches ~2.5 mg/dL (normal 0.3-1.2). Sort it by location: prehepatic (before the liver — excess RBC breakdown/hemolysis, unconjugated), hepatic (in the liver — hepatocellular dysfunction/intrahepatic cholestasis), and posthepatic (after the liver — obstruction of bile egress, conjugated). Unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia comes from increased production, decreased uptake, or decreased conjugation; conjugated from hepatocellular dysfunction or obstruction of intra-/extrahepatic bile flow."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HEPATIC ENCEPHALOPATHY — THE AMMONIA CASCADE. When hepatocytes can no longer metabolize waste, ammonia accumulates, crosses the blood-brain barrier, and is absorbed by astrocytes. Inside the astrocyte, ammonia is fixed into glutamine, which raises intracellular osmotic pressure -> astrocyte swelling -> cerebral edema -> coma and death (cerebral edema is the cause of death). The histologic signature is Alzheimer type II astrocytes showing hypertrophy and hyperplasia. It is seen in 30-45% of cirrhotics, can be triggered by ammonia, infection, GI bleeding, sedatives, or diuretics, and is staged grades 0-4. Clinically it runs from an inverted sleep-wake pattern and asterixis (the flapping tremor) up through confusion to coma; treatment is ICU care, a protein-restricted diet, and gut antibiotics."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Jaundice: prehepatic (hemolysis, unconjug.), hepatic, posthepatic (obstruction, conjug.); visible >2.5."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cascade: ammonia -> BBB -> astrocyte -> glutamine -> swelling -> cerebral edema (= cause of death)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Histo = Alzheimer type II astrocytes (hypertrophy + hyperplasia); flapping tremor = asterixis."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Jaundice: prehepatic = unconjugated (hemolysis), posthepatic = conjugated (obstruction). Encephalopathy: ammonia -> astrocyte -> edema; cerebral edema kills."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "The encephalopathy biopsy buzzword is Alzheimer type II astrocytes (swollen, hypertrophy + hyperplasia) - NOT Alzheimer dementia."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Don't confuse hepatic encephalopathy (ammonia/astrocytes) with hepatorenal syndrome (functional kidney failure, normal kidney histology) - both are complications of advanced liver disease but different organs."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini split jaundice three ways by location and two ways by conjugation, then explained why a failing liver scrambles the brain. Give the three locations with their conjugation class, and trace the encephalopathy cascade from a failing hepatocyte to cerebral edema."}]}, {"id": 8, "statement": "Integrate portal hypertension (prehepatic/intrahepatic/post-sinusoidal) with its systemic complications: varices, splenomegaly, ascites", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Portal hypertension is increased pressure in the portal venous system. Sort it by where the resistance sits: prehepatic (before the liver — portal vein thrombosis, splenic vein thrombosis, portal vein atresia); intrahepatic (within the liver — cirrhosis, the most common cause overall; presinusoidal; also schistosomiasis, PBC, fatty liver, Wilson); and post-sinusoidal / posthepatic (after the sinusoids — Budd-Chiari (hepatic vein thrombosis), IVC thrombosis, restrictive pericarditis, severe right-sided heart failure). In cirrhosis, fibrosis and nodularity raise sinusoidal resistance, slightly lowering portal-vein flow pressure and forcing blood into portosystemic collaterals."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE COMPLICATIONS — ONE BACK-PRESSURE, MANY ESCAPE ROUTES. The raised portal pressure has three downstream stories. (1) Portosystemic shunting opens collateral channels: esophageal/gastric varices (engorged serpentine submucosal veins in the lower esophagus — rupture is one of the most common causes of death in cirrhotics; diagnose by esophagogastroduodenoscopy), caput medusae (periumbilical), and hemorrhoids; the same shunting routes gut-derived ammonia past the liver and worsens encephalopathy. (2) Splenomegaly (congestion) -> hypersplenism -> pancytopenia (anemia, leukopenia, thrombocytopenia), with iron-laden Gamna-Gandy bodies in the spleen. (3) Ascites — increased peritoneal-capillary pressure plus hypoalbuminemia (low oncotic pressure) and renin-angiotensin/sympathetic-driven sodium and water retention drive fluid into the peritoneal cavity (hepatic venous pressure gradient: normal 1-5 mmHg, >10 mmHg predicts ascites)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "By site: prehepatic (portal/splenic thrombosis), intrahepatic (cirrhosis = most common), post-sinusoidal (Budd-Chiari)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Complications: varices (top killer), caput medusae, hemorrhoids, splenomegaly (-> pancytopenia), ascites."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Bleeding varices = leading death in cirrhotics; HVPG >10 mmHg predicts ascites; spleen = Gamna-Gandy bodies."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Portal HTN by site: prehepatic (portal/splenic vein thrombosis), intrahepatic (cirrhosis = most common), post-sinusoidal (Budd-Chiari, IVC, right heart failure). Complications: varices, splenomegaly, ascites."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Bleeding esophageal varices (engorged serpentine submucosal veins, lower esophagus) are one of the most common causes of death in cirrhotics - diagnosed by EGD."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Splenomegaly here is congestive -> hypersplenism -> pancytopenia; the iron-laden splenic nodules are Gamna-Gandy bodies, not a separate disease."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini split portal hypertension three ways by site and then walked its complications. Name the three sites with an example cause each, and explain why the same back-pressure produces esophageal varices, splenomegaly, AND ascites."}]}, {"id": 9, "statement": "Describe the pathological features of congenital anomalies of the biliary tract including, biliary atresia and choledochal cyst.", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The congenital block is three diseases that all obstruct the biliary tree from birth: biliary atresia (the duct that isn't there), the choledochal cyst (the duct that balloons), and Caroli disease (the intrahepatic ducts that go cystic). Machini's exam handle is to know the Latin root — 'atresia' means the tube is closed and does not exist, and if you miss the word you miss the question. All three present as obstructive cholestasis, and all three carry a long-tail risk of cholangiocarcinoma."}, {"t": "p", "x": "BILIARY ATRESIA — THE DUCT THAT ISN'T. Biliary atresia (AKA progressive obliterative cholangiopathy) is luminal obstruction and fibrosis of the extrahepatic bile ducts, driven by genetic or environmental injury — it is associated with deletion of GPC1, the gene for glypican-1 heparan sulfate proteoglycan, which governs cell division and growth. It is the most common cause of neonatal cholestasis, marching to cirrhosis and death, and — the high-yield line — it accounts for most of the children who undergo liver transplant in the US. There are three extrahepatic types; Type III (obliteration of common bile, hepatic, and cystic ducts with no anastomosable ducts at the porta hepatis) is the most common. Bile backs up into the liver, so the infant shows jaundice and kernicterus, then portal hypertension and liver failure; the gross liver is rock-hard and dark green."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CHOLEDOCHAL CYST — THE DUCT THAT BALLOONS. A choledochal cyst is a congenital dilation of the common bile duct, usually presenting in children before age 10 (and found incidentally in ~20% of adults). The mechanism Machini stressed: most have an anomalous junction of the common bile duct with the pancreatic duct, which lets pancreatic enzymes reflux into the bile duct, inflame and weaken the wall, and balloon it into a cyst. There are four Todani types: Type I (fusiform/spherical dilation of the extrahepatic tree — most common), Type II (a diverticular sac off the duct), Type III (choledochocele within the duodenal/pancreatic wall), and Type IV (a Type-I cyst extending into the liver). Infants obstruct → jaundice → cirrhosis → portal hypertension; adults get pain, jaundice, and pancreatitis. The feared complication is biliary epithelial dysplasia progressing to cholangiocarcinoma (also adeno- and squamous carcinoma)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Biliary atresia = obliterative cholangiopathy, gene GPC1; #1 pediatric liver transplant in the US; Type III most common."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Choledochal cyst: Type I fusiform extrahepatic dilation (most common); anomalous pancreaticobiliary junction → enzyme reflux → cholangiocarcinoma."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CAROLI DISEASE — THE INTRAHEPATIC COUSIN. Round out the trio with Caroli disease (AKA communicating cavernous biliary ectasia), an autosomal recessive fibropolycystic disorder of segmental cystic dilation of the intrahepatic ducts, tied to ductal plate malformations and polycystic kidney disease. Pathology shows multiple cystic dilations lined by cuboidal/columnar epithelium with fibrotic walls; complications are intrahepatic stones, recurrent cholangitis, portal hypertension, cholangiocarcinoma, and liver failure. The discriminator to carry: Caroli is intrahepatic, the choledochal cyst is classically the extrahepatic common bile duct."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Caroli = AR intrahepatic ductal cystic dilation + polycystic kidneys; vs choledochal cyst = extrahepatic CBD."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Biliary atresia = obliterative cholangiopathy (GPC1), the #1 cause of pediatric liver transplant; choledochal cyst = extrahepatic CBD dilation from pancreaticobiliary reflux, Type I most common, → cholangiocarcinoma."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Machini's exam trick: know the Latin — atresia = the tube is closed and does not exist. Read the root and the stem answers itself."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Caroli vs choledochal cyst: Caroli dilates the intrahepatic ducts (AR, with polycystic kidneys); the choledochal cyst balloons the extrahepatic common bile duct."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini stressed that knowing the Latin root of 'atresia' is how you answer the question. What does it tell you, what gene is implicated, and why does this disease dominate the pediatric transplant list?"}]}, {"id": 10, "statement": "Describe the major features of primary sclerosing cholangitis.", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The LO names PSC, but the only way to be safe is to author it against PBC, because the board lives on the contrast (Machini went straight to the comparison slide). Both are autoimmune cholestatic diseases that destroy bile ducts and end in cirrhosis and cholangiocarcinoma, but everything else is a mirror image: PBC = the AMA-positive woman with small intrahepatic ducts and a granulomatous florid duct lesion; PSC = the p-ANCA man with ulcerative colitis, large and small ducts, and onion-skin fibrosis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PRIMARY SCLEROSING CHOLANGITIS (PSC) — THE LO. PSC is a progressive segmental fibrosis and inflammation of the intra- AND extrahepatic bile ducts, with dilation of the preserved segments in between. It strikes men aged ~32-40, and is strongly associated with ulcerative colitis (and Crohn's). T-cells in the periductal stroma (with HLA-B8 alleles) drive immune-mediated duct injury → scarring and obstruction; the serology is an atypical perinuclear ANCA (p-ANCA), positive in ~65% (the PBC-vs-PSC comparison table; the prose slide quotes ~80%). The microscopic signature is high-yield: smaller ducts show a striking circumferential 'onion-skin' periductal fibrosis around an atrophic lumen that is eventually obliterated, leaving a 'tombstone' scar; larger ducts inflame like UC (neutrophils, strictures, narrowing). On ERCP the ducts are 'beaded' — strictures alternating with dilations ('beads-on-a-string'). Complications: liver failure, portal hypertension, and bile-duct and colon cancer (cholangiocarcinoma)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PRIMARY BILIARY CHOLANGITIS (PBC) — THE CONTRAST. PBC (formerly primary biliary cirrhosis) is a nonsuppurative, inflammatory destruction of small- and medium-sized intrahepatic bile ducts that spares the large intrahepatic ducts and the extrahepatic tree. It affects middle-aged women (female-to-male 6:1), and its defining serology is the anti-mitochondrial antibody (AMA), present in 90-95% — note this is anti-mitochondrial, NOT 'anti-microbial.' The biopsy hallmark is the 'florid duct lesion': interlobular ducts destroyed by lymphoplasmacytic inflammation with a granulomatous reaction, in a patchy distribution (one duct attacked, its neighbor spared), progressing to portal-portal septal fibrosis. Clinically: severe itching, hypercholesterolemia / xanthelasma, skin hyperpigmentation, steatorrhea, and a high alkaline phosphatase. The board flag Machini double-underlined: PBC is associated with Sjögren syndrome (70%) — 'I would highlight that one, that's above the question.'"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PSC: p-ANCA ~65%, men, UC, intra+extrahepatic ducts, onion-skin → tombstone scar, beaded ERCP."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PSC small-duct lesion = concentric onion-skin periductal fibrosis around an atrophic lumen, obliterated into a tombstone scar."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PBC: AMA 90-95%, women (6:1), small/medium intrahepatic ducts, granulomatous florid duct lesion, Sjögren 'above the question.'"}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE MIMIC YOU CAN'T SKIP — IgG4 CHOLANGITIS. Machini deliberately included IgG4-related cholangitis because 'there was a question, and it's not even in the book.' It is a steroid-responsive hepatobiliary disease that mimics PSC, associated with autoimmune pancreatitis (type 1, ~90%) and a high serum IgG4. The cascade is immune activation → infiltration of IgG4-positive plasma cells → cytokines → obliterative phlebitis → storiform fibrosis → organ damage. The clinical separator is everything: IgG4 responds to immunotherapy/steroids and biliary drainage, whereas PSC is progressive and steroid-resistant. Its differentials are PSC and cholangiocarcinoma."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "IgG4 cholangitis = steroid-RESPONSIVE PSC mimic; high serum IgG4 + autoimmune pancreatitis; storiform fibrosis + phlebitis."}, {"t": "key", "x": "PSC = p-ANCA man with ulcerative colitis, intra+extrahepatic ducts, onion-skin → tombstone, beaded ERCP. PBC = AMA woman, small intrahepatic ducts, florid duct lesion, Sjögren."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Machini's flagged stem: 'which is associated with Sjögren?' → PBC (70%). He called it 'above the question' — i.e., the line they pull from."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "PBC's antibody is anti-MITOCHONDRIAL (AMA), not 'anti-microbial' — the transcript garbles it. AMA is 90-95% in PBC, while PSC is the p-ANCA disease."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "IgG4 cholangitis looks like PSC but is steroid-responsive and tied to autoimmune pancreatitis — Machini flagged it as a question that 'isn't even in the book.'"}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini said the board can ask 'which one is associated with Sjögren?' — calling it 'above the question.' Lay the two autoimmune cholangitides side by side: which antibody, which sex, which duct level, and which biopsy lesion separates PBC from PSC?"}]}, {"id": 11, "statement": "Describe the pathogenesis and complications of cholelithiasis.", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Cholelithiasis (gallstones) is the most common cause of biliary obstruction in the US, affecting ~10% of adult women and 6% of adult men. Stones are crystalline cholesterol, bile pigment, and calcium salts in a protein matrix, and the whole LO collapses into one sort: cholesterol (the yellow, ~90% majority) versus pigment (the black/brown minority). Get color, percentage, radiodensity, and location right and the stem answers itself."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CHOLESTEROL STONES — THE 90% MAJORITY. Cholesterol stones (~90% of cases) are yellow (or yellow/dark-green), 50-100% cholesterol, typically 2-3 cm, oval, and often solitary. They arise only in the gallbladder, and most are radiolucent — but calcium carbonate can render some radiopaque (visible on X-ray). Risk is the classic 4 F's: female, fat, forty, fertile, plus female sex hormones / oral contraceptives / pregnancy, obesity and insulin resistance, rapid weight loss, gallbladder stasis, and the demographic flag Native American (and Northern European). The pathogenesis is a three-step arrow: supersaturation of bile with cholesterol → gallbladder hypomotility promotes nucleation → mucus hypersecretion acts like glue, trapping crystals so they aggregate and grow — supersaturation is the initiating step."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cholesterol stones ~90%: yellow, radiolucent (Ca-carbonate → some radiopaque), gallbladder only; risk = 4 F's + OCP, weight loss, Native American."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cholesterol-stone pathogenesis: supersaturation → hypomotility/nucleation → mucus traps crystals (aggregation/growth)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PIGMENT STONES — BLACK VS BROWN. Pigment stones contain unconjugated bilirubin plus calcium, mucin, and glycoproteins, and they can arise anywhere in the biliary system. Split them: BLACK stones form in sterile bile from chronic hemolysis (sickle cell anemia, hereditary spherocytosis), cirrhosis, and TPN, and are radiopaque; BROWN (mixed) stones form in infected, stagnant ducts — biliary infection/stasis (bacterial or parasitic) — are common in Asian, rural populations, and are radiolucent. Machini's mnemonic logic: the more calcium and glycoprotein, the darker and more opaque the stone."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Pigment stones = unconjugated bilirubin: BLACK = hemolysis/cirrhosis/TPN, radiopaque; BROWN = infection/stasis (Asian), radiolucent."}, {"t": "p", "x": "COMPLICATIONS — WHEN A STONE MOVES. Untreated cholelithiasis drives the rest of the lecture: biliary colic (a stone intermittently lodging in the cystic or common bile duct), acute and chronic cholecystitis, obstruction and jaundice, perforation/tears and peritonitis, infection (ascending cholangitis), pancreatitis (gallstone pancreatitis when the stone blocks pancreatic outflow), and — long-term — cancer. Choledocholithiasis (stone in the common bile duct) is the bridge: it causes obstructive jaundice (total bilirubin often > 3.5 mg/dL), bactibilia, and ascending cholangitis. Two named complications to carry: Mirizzi syndrome — a stone impacted in the cystic duct / Hartmann pouch externally compressing the common hepatic duct — and gallstone pancreatitis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Complications: colic, cholecystitis, jaundice, perforation, cholangitis, pancreatitis, cancer; Mirizzi = cystic-duct stone compressing the common hepatic duct."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Sort stones first: cholesterol (~90%, yellow, radiolucent, gallbladder-only, 4 F's) vs pigment (unconjugated bilirubin) — black (hemolysis, radiopaque) vs brown (infection, radiolucent)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "The 4 F's = female, fat, forty, fertile (plus estrogen/OCP, rapid weight loss, Native American). Pathogenesis starts at cholesterol supersaturation of bile."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Radiodensity flips by stone: most cholesterol = radiolucent, black pigment = radiopaque, brown pigment = radiolucent. Don't blanket-call gallstones radiolucent."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Mirizzi syndrome: a stone in the cystic duct / Hartmann pouch compresses the common hepatic duct from outside — obstruction without a stone in the CHD lumen."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Two stones, two stories. Sort gallstones into the cholesterol and pigment camps by color, percentage, radiodensity, where they form, and who gets them — and name the one pathogenic step that starts a cholesterol stone."}]}, {"id": 12, "statement": "Describe the causes, morphology, and complications of acute and chronic cholecystitis, cholesterolosis, polyps and mucocele of the gallbladder.", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. This is the gallbladder grab-bag: the two cholecystitides (acute and chronic, each with a calculous and acalculous flavor), plus three benign-to-watch lesions — cholesterolosis (strawberry gallbladder), polyps, and mucocele/hydrops — and the pre-malignant porcelain gallbladder. The unifying histologic thread is the Rokitansky-Aschoff sinus; the unifying gross lesson is telling the red strawberry gallbladder from the white porcelain one."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ACUTE CHOLECYSTITIS — CALCULOUS VS ACALCULOUS. Acute calculous cholecystitis is the common form: a gallstone obstructs the neck of the gallbladder or the cystic duct, then phospholipase and released prostaglandins inflame the wall and bile salts strip the protective mucus, exposing mucosa to chemical injury (bacterial infection follows). Grossly the gallbladder is distended, edematous, hemorrhagic, with stones and pus; gangrenous cholecystitis turns it green-black. Acute acalculous cholecystitis is inflammation without stones, seen in the critically ill (severe illness → ischemia of the wall, bacterial contamination with lysolecithin); it accounts for ~10% of cholecystectomies and tends to perforate. Complications of either: ulceration, perforation, peritonitis, fistula, sepsis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CHRONIC CHOLECYSTITIS AND THE ROKITANSKY-ASCHOFF SINUS. Chronic cholecystitis follows repeated bouts of acute cholecystitis (more common in women after 40); obstruction is not a prerequisite, and E. coli / enterococci are in the bile in ~33%. Repeated attacks thicken the wall (2-3x normal) and shrink the gallbladder; the lumen holds green-yellow mucoid bile and stones. Microscopically: a mononuclear infiltrate (T-cells, plasma cells, eosinophils) in the lamina propria, lymphoid follicles, muscular hypertrophy, fibrosis, and metaplasia — but the board signature is the accentuation of Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses (mucosal pseudodiverticula herniating through the muscularis), present ~90% of the time. These same sinuses appear in acute cholecystitis and adenomyomatosis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Acute calculous = stone in the cystic duct/neck; acute acalculous = inflammation WITHOUT stones in the critically ill (ischemia)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses (mucosal pseudodiverticula through the muscularis) = hallmark of chronic cholecystitis, ~90%."}, {"t": "p", "x": "STRAWBERRY VS PORCELAIN — THE RED AND THE WHITE. Cholesterolosis ('strawberry gallbladder') is present in ~20% of cholecystectomies (multiparous adult women): bile supersaturated with cholesterol is taken up into foamy macrophages in the lamina propria, giving focal yellow flecks — and when diffuse, a bright red 'strawberry' coating. It is asymptomatic and benign. Contrast the porcelain gallbladder ('hyalinizing cholecystitis'): a calcified, brittle, bluish-white wall from chronic inflammation/gallstone stasis, in elderly women — and the high-yield point is its increased risk of gallbladder carcinoma (surface epithelium often shows carcinoma in situ), so it warrants cholecystectomy. Red strawberry = benign; white porcelain = pre-malignant."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Strawberry = cholesterolosis (foamy macrophages, benign); porcelain = calcified wall, increased cancer risk."}, {"t": "p", "x": "POLYPS AND THE MUCOCELE. Gallbladder polyps — Machini: 'they always ask about polyps' — are mucosal projections, usually asymptomatic and < 1 cm, formed from cholesterol/bile-salt precipitation (cholesterol polyps with foamy macrophages on a fibrovascular stalk, found in 15-20% of cholesterolosis). The rule: pseudopolyps and inflammatory polyps do NOT become cancer, but adenomatous polyps are neoplastic, and any polyp > 1 cm needs cholecystectomy (potentially malignant). Finally, hydrops / mucocele is marked gallbladder dilation from chronic obstruction of the cystic duct (an impacted stone in the neck), with accumulation of mucus; rising intraluminal pressure → ischemia → gangrene and perforation → sepsis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Polyps: >1 cm → cholecystectomy; adenomatous = neoplastic, pseudo/inflammatory = not. Mucocele/hydrops = cystic-duct obstruction + mucus."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Acute calculous (cystic-duct stone) vs acalculous (critically ill); chronic cholecystitis = repeated attacks + Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses (~90%); strawberry (benign) vs porcelain (pre-malignant)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses = mucosal pseudodiverticula herniating through the muscularis; the histologic signature of chronic cholecystitis."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Strawberry gallbladder (cholesterolosis, foamy macrophages, red, benign) vs porcelain gallbladder (calcified, bluish-white, cancer risk). Red = safe, white = watch."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Machini: 'they always ask about polyps' — the rule is > 1 cm → cholecystectomy (potentially malignant); adenomatous polyps are the neoplastic ones."}, {"t": "q", "x": "This LO is a grab-bag of gallbladder lesions. Which single histologic structure ties acute and chronic cholecystitis together, and which two gross gallbladders — one red, one white — must you tell apart, given one is benign and one is pre-malignant?"}]}, {"id": 13, "statement": "Discuss the major pathological feature of tumors of the gallbladder and bile ducts.", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Biliary tumors are nearly all adenocarcinoma of bile-duct (or gallbladder) epithelium, share a poor prognosis, and are tied to the lesions earlier in the lecture — gallstones, porcelain gallbladder, ulcerative colitis (PSC), and liver flukes. Sort them by site: the gallbladder, the bile ducts (cholangiocarcinoma, by location), and the ampulla of Vater."}, {"t": "p", "x": "GALLBLADDER ADENOCARCINOMA AND CHOLANGIOCARCINOMA. Gallbladder adenocarcinoma is the most common biliary malignancy, more common in women, with a poor prognosis; its big risk factors are the porcelain gallbladder and gallstones. Cholangiocarcinoma is adenocarcinoma of the bile-duct lining, risk-flagged for gallstones, ulcerative colitis, and parasitic liver flukes (Opisthorchis viverrini, Clonorchis sinensis). Sort it by location into three types: intrahepatic (within the liver, classed as a liver cancer), perihilar/hilar (just outside the liver), and distal/extrahepatic (near the small intestine). The board handle Machini flagged: when the tumor sits at the junction where the left and right hepatic ducts meet to form the common hepatic duct, it is a Klatskin tumor (a perihilar cholangiocarcinoma) — 'I think there was a board question from it.' Serum CEA and CA 19-9 are often elevated."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CARCINOMA OF THE AMPULLA OF VATER. Ampullary carcinoma is a glandular/mucinous adenocarcinoma at the ampulla, often from extension of advanced duodenal, distal common bile duct, or pancreatic carcinoma. It affects women more (ages 60-80), is more common with familial adenomatous polyposis and ulcerative colitis, and carries KRAS mutations. The key board line: it follows the adenoma-carcinoma sequence, and 90% of these carcinomas are surrounded by adenoma. Histologic subtypes are intestinal (columnar, pseudostratified nuclei, goblet/Paneth cells), pancreatobiliary (cuboidal, desmoplastic), and mixed. It presents with anemia, jaundice, weight loss, back pain, and acute pancreatitis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Gallbladder adenocarcinoma = #1 biliary cancer (porcelain GB/gallstone risk, poor prognosis); cholangiocarcinoma risk = gallstones, UC, liver flukes."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Klatskin tumor = perihilar cholangiocarcinoma at the junction of the L+R hepatic ducts (forming the common hepatic duct)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Ampulla of Vater carcinoma: adenocarcinoma via adenoma-carcinoma sequence — 90% surrounded by adenoma; KRAS, FAP/UC association."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Gallbladder adenocarcinoma = #1 biliary cancer (porcelain/gallstone risk); cholangiocarcinoma by site, the Klatskin tumor at the L+R hepatic-duct junction; ampulla of Vater = 90% surrounded by adenoma."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Klatskin tumor = perihilar cholangiocarcinoma at the confluence of the left and right hepatic ducts — Machini explicitly flagged a board question here."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Liver flukes (Opisthorchis viverrini, Clonorchis sinensis), ulcerative colitis (via PSC), gallstones, and the porcelain gallbladder are the recurring biliary-cancer risk factors."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Machini said there was a board question on the tumor that sits at one specific anatomical junction. Where is that junction, what is the tumor called, and what is the 90% rule for the ampulla of Vater?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Calling steatosis irreversible. Simple steatosis (fatty change) is reversible - stop drinking and the liver recovers. Irreversibility begins once steatohepatitis/fibrosis sets in. The steatohepatitis triad is ballooning + Mallory-Denk bodies + neutrophils. → LO 43.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Swapping the two alcohol enzymes. Alcohol dehydrogenase (ADH) makes ethanol -> acetaldehyde; aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH) makes acetaldehyde -> acetate. Both raise NADH, which makes more fat and burns less. → LO 43.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Mixing up micronodular and macronodular. Micronodular = Laennec/alcoholic, ≤3 mm, thin septa; macronodular = post-necrotic/non-alcoholic, >3 mm, wider scars. Size AND the separator are testable. → LO 43.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Putting acetaminophen in the wrong zone. Acetaminophen is a zone-3 (centrilobular) toxin (highest P450, lowest O2) and the #1 US cause of acute liver failure - not a periportal zone-1 injury. → LO 43.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Confusing PBC and PSC antibodies/sex. PBC = anti-MITOCHONDRIAL antibody (AMA) in women (small intrahepatic ducts, florid duct lesion, Sjögren); PSC = p-ANCA in men (intra+extrahepatic ducts, onion-skin, ulcerative colitis). Don't swap them — and PBC's antibody is anti-mitochondrial, NOT 'anti-microbial.' → LO 44.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Calling all gallstones radiolucent. Most cholesterol stones are radiolucent, but black pigment stones are radiopaque and brown pigment stones are radiolucent — radiodensity flips by stone type. → LO 44.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. Using the wrong cholesterol-stone percentage. Per the pathogenesis slide, cholesterol stones are ~90% of cases (not 80%); they arise only in the gallbladder and are yellow. → LO 44.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "8. Mixing up strawberry and porcelain gallbladders. Strawberry gallbladder = cholesterolosis (foamy macrophages, red, benign); porcelain gallbladder = calcified wall (bluish-white, increased cancer risk). → LO 44.4"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"ballooned hepatocytes with ropy eosinophilic inclusions and neutrophils in a drinker\" → alcoholic steatohepatitis (Mallory-Denk bodies = damaged cytokeratin 8/18)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"why does the alcoholic liver get fatty?\" → the high NADH/NAD ratio increases fatty-acid synthesis and decreases fatty-acid oxidation → triglyceride accumulation."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"uniform 1-2 mm nodules, thin septa\" → micronodular (Laennec/alcoholic) cirrhosis; >3 mm with wider scars → macronodular/post-necrotic."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"overdose patient, jaundice + INR 2.4 + confusion\" → acetaminophen acute liver failure, zone-3 necrosis, the jaundice-coagulopathy-encephalopathy triad."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"jaundiced neonate, rock-hard dark-green liver, heading for transplant\" → biliary atresia (obliterative cholangiopathy, GPC1)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"young man, ulcerative colitis, beaded ducts on ERCP, onion-skin fibrosis\" → primary sclerosing cholangitis (p-ANCA)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. \"middle-aged woman, AMA-positive, granulomatous florid duct lesion, Sjögren\" → primary biliary cholangitis (anti-mitochondrial)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "8. \"thickened shrunken gallbladder with mucosal pseudodiverticula\" → chronic cholecystitis (Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Bilirubin metabolism & jaundice - the conjugated/unconjugated split and the hereditary hyperbilirubinemias behind prehepatic vs hepatic vs posthepatic jaundice are detailed with the gallbladder/bile-duct and bilirubin lectures (Lec 47-48); the LFT panel here is the orientation slide for the full liver-function lecture (Lec 48)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Liver function tests - the three-bucket LFT framework (integrity / excretory / synthetic) introduced in LO 43.6 is taught in full in the dedicated LFT lecture (Lec 48); this is background only here"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Cirrhosis & HCC roads - the steatosis-to-cirrhosis arrow and the macronodular post-necrotic pathway feed the hepatocellular-carcinoma and chronic-liver-disease material (Lec 46/49); portal hypertension and its varices/splenomegaly/ascites are the vascular downstream of that same cirrhosis"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Cholangiocarcinoma & gallstone disease — the pathology framed here (Klatskin tumor, choledocholithiasis, Mirizzi, ampullary carcinoma) is the substrate for the surgical management of biliary tract disease in Lec 45, this exam"}]}]}, "45": {"prof": "Dr. Khavir Sharieff", "tldr": "Pathology becomes decisions: not all stones come out, read the HIDA, give antibiotics first in cholangitis, and stage gallbladder cancer; for liver/pancreas masses, solid = malignant, cystic = rule out cancer, and apply Milan for HCC.", "mustKnows": ["1. NOT all gallstones need to be removed — asymptomatic = observe. Asymptomatic cholelithiasis is observed (expectant management) — lifetime risk of complicated disease ~8%, so prophylactic cholecystectomy is for individualized special cases only. Higher-risk: female, immobile/numerous stones, large (>10 mm) or small (<5 mm). Stones are the #1 risk factor for gallbladder cancer, but not all cause cancer.", "2. HIDA timing: 60-min non-visualization = ACUTE, 120-min visualization = CHRONIC. After ultrasound first, the HIDA scan (technetium iminodiacetic-acid tracer excreted into bile) reads cystic-duct patency: non-visualization at 60 min = acute (duct obstructed); not seen at 60 but fills by ~120 min = chronic. For biliary dyskinesia, give CCK and measure ejection fraction: GbEF <35-40% confirms it, most need cholecystectomy.", "3. Cholangitis: antibiotics + resuscitation FIRST, THEN drainage (ERCP). Charcot triad = fever, RUQ pain, jaundice -> cholangitis (biliary obstruction by stone, stricture, tumor). Add AMS + hypotension = Reynolds pentad, a surgical emergency. Fixed: broad-spectrum antibiotics (gram-neg aerobes/anaerobes — E. coli, Klebsiella) + resuscitation FIRST, THEN drainage (ERCP + sphincterotomy, clears distal CBD >90%); surgery if it fails.", "4. Gallbladder cancer staging: T1a = cholecystectomy; T1b/T2 = extended cholecystectomy + lymphadenectomy. Gallbladder cancer is rare but aggressive (no submucosa -> early lymphatic/hepatic spread), mostly fundal adenocarcinoma, staged by TNM. T1a (lamina propria, does NOT cross muscularis) -> simple cholecystectomy cures; T1b/T2 (invades muscularis) -> extended cholecystectomy + lymphadenectomy (hepatic segments IVb/V). Suspected pre-op -> operate OPEN to avoid seeding.", "5. Hepatic adenoma: resect ANY size in a man, watch <4 cm in a woman. Flagged twice. Hepatic adenoma (women on OCPs, men on steroids) carries rupture + malignant-transformation risk: in a man, any size -> resect; in a woman <4 cm, stop estrogen/steroids and watch (resect if >4 cm or symptomatic). Contrast FNH (central scar, no malignant potential, watch) and hemangioma (most common, asymptomatic, no biopsy).", "6. HCC + the Milan criteria -> transplant. HCC arises on cirrhosis (HCV, alcohol, NASH): a hypervascular mass + ↑AFP, no biopsy. The board point is the Milan criteria — a single nodule ≤5 cm OR ≤3 nodules each ≤3 cm, with no macrovascular invasion and no distant disease -> liver transplant, now the best option (beats resection alone, higher UNOS priority). A ≤5 cm HCC in a cirrhotic -> transplant.", "7. Pancreas: solid = malignant; cystic = rule out cancer by its mucin. Every solid lesion = malignant (resect); a cystic lesion -> rule out cancer. Serous cysts and pseudocysts hold thin benign fluid; find mucin and risk climbs — MCN 15-25%, IPMN 35-65% (main-duct > side-branch). Workup = triple-phase CT/MRI + CA 19-9; avoid biopsy (EUS-FNA only, with a reason — risks pancreatitis and delay). Metastasis to the pancreas is rare (opposite of liver).", "8. PDAC and the PNET / Whipple's-triad insulinoma. PDAC = most common pancreatic cancer, worst prognosis (5-yr <10%), usually head with painless jaundice, projected 2nd-leading cancer death by 2030; resectable head -> Whipple. PNETs are mostly nonfunctional but carry high malignant potential -> resect, esp. ≥2 cm; a functional PNET with Whipple's triad (hypoglycemia <~50-60, symptoms, relief with glucose) = insulinoma.", "Murphy sign = RUQ palpation, inspiratory arrest, acute cholecystitis", "Porcelain gallbladder = calcified GB wall, premalignant, GBC risk", "Mirizzi syndrome = cystic-duct stone, extrinsic CBD compression, jaundice", "Pneumobilia = air in biliary tree, gallstone ileus, fistula", "Rigler triad = pneumobilia, SBO, ectopic gallstone", "BOAS sign = right infrascapular pain, hyperesthesia, biliary colic", "Triangle of Calot = cystic duct, common hepatic duct, liver edge", "Emphysematous cholecystitis = gas in GB wall, Clostridium perfringens, diabetic, open surgery", "Kasabach-Merritt syndrome = giant hemangioma, consumptive coagulopathy, thrombocytopenia, children", "Central stellate scar = FNH, radiating septa, no malignant potential, ~15%", "Whipple procedure = pancreaticoduodenectomy, resectable head PDAC, fistula, delayed gastric emptying", "Puestow procedure = lateral pancreaticojejunostomy, refractory chronic pancreatitis, dilated duct", "Painless jaundice = head of pancreas, PDAC, biliary obstruction", "Chronic pancreatitis CT triad = calcifications, dilated irregular duct, parenchymal atrophy", "Echinococcal (hydatid) cyst = sheep-raising, no aspiration, anaphylaxis, albendazole + PAIR", "Amebic abscess = Entamoeba histolytica, anchovy-paste, metronidazole, no aspiration"], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Describe bile/gallbladder physiology (CCK contraction, bile acids, cystic artery)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW (baseline anatomy/physiology). The gallbladder is a saccular organ on the inferior surface of the liver (fundus, body, infundibulum, neck) that stores bile (capacity ~50 mL). The liver makes ~600-700 mL of bile per day, which is ~90% water plus electrolytes and solutes (bile salts/acids, phospholipids, cholesterol, protein). After a meal, cholecystokinin (CCK) triggers gallbladder contraction. Bile matters for absorption of fat-soluble vitamins, elimination of bilirubin, and excretion of cholesterol and bile acids. The primary bile acids are cholic and chenodeoxycholic; the secondary bile acids are deoxycholic and lithocholic. Blood supply is the cystic artery, which runs in the triangle of Calot (hepatocystic triangle) and is a branch of the right hepatic artery."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "CCK contracts GB; primary acids cholic/chenodeoxycholic, secondary deoxycholic/lithocholic; cystic artery (Calot) off right hepatic."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Three baseline recalls: CCK contracts the gallbladder, cystic artery lives in the triangle of Calot (off the right hepatic), and the bile acids split primary (cholic/chenodeoxycholic) vs secondary (deoxycholic/lithocholic)."}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe gallstone types and the spectrum of gallstone complications", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "STONE TYPES. Gallstones are pigment or non-pigment. Cholesterol stones are the non-pigment majority (most stones you see), forming from biliary stasis, calcium nucleation, and increased water absorption (risk: obesity, estrogen/OCPs, diabetes). Pigment stones are black or brown: black pigment stones are seen with hemolysis, cirrhosis, or chronic TPN; brown pigment stones are seen with biliary stasis, infection, and Asian descent. Calcium bilirubinate is the other pigment category."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cholesterol = non-pigment majority; black = hemolysis/cirrhosis/TPN; brown = stasis/infection/Asian."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE COMPLICATION TREE — WHERE THE STONE LODGES. A stone by itself is harmless; trouble is a matter of location. (1) Lodged in the cystic duct -> acute cholecystitis (and, if it stays, mucocele/empyema, chronic cholecystitis, even porcelain gallbladder). (2) Lodged in the common bile duct -> obstruction -> cholangitis and obstructive jaundice. (3) Lodged at the ampulla of Vater -> pancreatic-duct backflow -> acute (gallstone) pancreatitis. (4) Eroded through a cholecystoduodenal fistula into the gut and impacted in the terminal ileum -> gallstone ileus. And looming over all of it: stones are the #1 risk factor for gallbladder cancer."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "By location: cystic duct -> cholecystitis; CBD -> cholangitis/jaundice; ampulla -> pancreatitis; fistula/ileum -> ileus."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Stone type by association: cholesterol (most, metabolic), black pigment (hemolysis/cirrhosis/TPN), brown pigment (stasis/infection/Asian). Complications follow location: cystic duct (cholecystitis), CBD (cholangitis), ampulla (pancreatitis), fistula (gallstone ileus)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Black pigment = sterile metabolic causes (hemolysis, cirrhosis, TPN); brown pigment = infected/stagnant bile - the color tracks the mechanism."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "One stone, many diseases - the exam tests which duct it's stuck in, not the stone itself."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff said a single stone can write a whole disease tree depending on where it lodges. Name the three gallstone types with their associations, and walk the four destinations of an escaped stone with the disease each one causes."}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Explain the management of asymptomatic gallstones", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW — THE OPENING AND CLOSING RULE. Sharieff bookended the whole lecture with one message: NOT all gallstones need to be removed. Asymptomatic cholelithiasis is common and is managed conservatively — observation / expectant management. The reasoning is risk-versus-benefit: the lifetime risk of complicated disease from initially silent stones is low (estimated ~8%), so a routine or incidentally found stone in a patient with no biliary colic and no symptoms is simply watched. Do not be in a hurry to take the gallbladder."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Asymptomatic gallstones = observe; lifetime complicated-disease risk ~8%; do NOT rush to cholecystectomy."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHEN TO RECONSIDER — AND THE CANCER CAVEAT. Surgery for asymptomatic stones is individualized: prophylactic cholecystectomy is reserved for special cases (e.g., high progression risk). Features independently associated with a higher chance of becoming symptomatic/complicated include female sex, immobility of stones, numerous stones, and large (>10 mm) or small (<5 mm) stones. The one fact that keeps gallstones on the radar is that they are the #1 risk factor for gallbladder cancer — but Sharieff was emphatic in his closing recap that not all gallstones cause cancer, so the default for a silent stone remains observation, not resection."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "#1 risk factor for GB cancer, yet not all cause cancer - still observe; higher-risk >10 mm or <5 mm, numerous/immobile, female."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Asymptomatic gallstones -> observe. Lifetime complication risk is low (~8%); prophylactic cholecystectomy is only for individualized special cases."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Gallstones are the #1 risk factor for gallbladder cancer, yet not all stones cause cancer - that risk does NOT convert silent stones into a surgical indication."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Higher-symptom-risk features: female, immobile stones, numerous stones, >10 mm or <5 mm - flags to individualize, not an automatic operation."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff opened and closed the lecture with the same line. A patient has gallstones found incidentally with no symptoms - what do you do, why, and what features (and what single downstream cancer fact) make you think twice?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe biliary colic and biliary dyskinesia (HIDA, CCK ejection fraction)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "BILIARY COLIC. Biliary colic is RUQ or epigastric pain that develops after eating (postprandial), with or without nausea/vomiting, lasting ~30 minutes to ~5 hours (can radiate to the back or right scapula; classically after a fatty meal). The mechanism is a stone transiently impacting the gallbladder neck/cystic duct and then passing — so the pain comes, peaks, and resolves. Pain >5 hours suggests something more than colic (e.g., evolving cholecystitis). BOAS sign = referred pain/hyperesthesia at the right infrascapular region. Rome criteria describe the recurrent, steady, daily-living-disturbing pattern used clinically."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Biliary colic = postprandial RUQ/epigastric pain, 30 min-5 h, transient neck/cystic-duct stone; >5 h = think worse."}, {"t": "p", "x": "BILIARY DYSKINESIA. Biliary dyskinesia is a functional gallbladder disorder (the gallbladder does not contract/empty fully) and a diagnosis of exclusion — you need biliary-type pain with NO stones or structural pathology. Work-up: an ultrasound first to exclude stones, then a CCK-augmented HIDA scan to measure the gallbladder ejection fraction (GbEF). A GbEF <35-40% confirms biliary dyskinesia, and most patients are treated with cholecystectomy (about half improve without surgery, so the decision is individualized)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Biliary dyskinesia = functional GB disorder, diagnosis of exclusion; CCK-HIDA GbEF <35-40% confirms; Tx = cholecystectomy."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Biliary colic = postprandial RUQ pain, 30 min-5 h (impacted neck/cystic-duct stone). Biliary dyskinesia = functional, no stones; CCK-HIDA ejection fraction <35-40% confirms it -> cholecystectomy."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Colic has a stone (transient cystic-duct obstruction); dyskinesia has NO stone (a contractility problem) - same pain, opposite ultrasound."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "The dyskinesia number is the CCK ejection fraction <35-40%; BOAS sign and Rome criteria are the descriptive supports."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff said biliary colic is the one term he really wanted understood, then contrasted it with biliary dyskinesia. Define biliary colic (with timing), and explain how you diagnose biliary dyskinesia and what number clinches it."}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Describe acute (calculous/acalculous) and chronic cholecystitis and management", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "ACUTE CHOLECYSTITIS — CALCULOUS vs ACALCULOUS. Acute calculous cholecystitis is inflammation of the gallbladder from a stone impacted in the cystic duct (the common form). Acalculous cholecystitis is inflammation without stones, seen in the critically ill / low-perfusion / biliary-stasis setting — severe burns, prolonged TPN, trauma, major surgery. Clinically: RUQ pain (4-6 h), nausea/vomiting, fever, and a positive Murphy sign (inspiratory arrest on RUQ palpation). Infection is usually gram-negative aerobes (E. coli, Klebsiella, Enterococcus); always check LFTs to catch a CBD stone."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Acute calculous = cystic-duct stone; acalculous = no stone, critically ill/stasis (burns, TPN, trauma). Ultrasound is FIRST."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE HIDA CLOCK — ACUTE vs CHRONIC. Ultrasound is always first (wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, stones/sludge); if equivocal, get a HIDA scan. The timing rule the board wants: non-visualization of the gallbladder at 60 minutes = acute cholecystitis (the cystic duct is obstructed). Chronic cholecystitis is the sequela of repeated bouts (gallstones present in >90%); on HIDA the gallbladder is not seen at 60 minutes but fills by ~120 minutes. So: 60-minute non-visualization = acute, 120-minute (delayed) visualization = chronic."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HIDA: non-visualization at 60 min = acute; delayed visualization by 120 min = chronic (>90% have stones)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "MANAGEMENT. The plan is the same backbone: NPO, IV fluids, IV antibiotics, and cholecystectomy (remove the gallbladder). Prefer laparoscopic cholecystectomy, but go open when needed — e.g., emphysematous cholecystitis or suspected cancer (open avoids tumor seeding and lets you extend the operation if needed). Acalculous cholecystitis in a patient too unstable for surgery can be temporized with a cholecystostomy drain, but the gallbladder still ultimately comes out."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Ultrasound first, HIDA if equivocal. 60-min non-visualization = acute; 120-min visualization = chronic. Management = NPO + IV fluids + antibiotics + cholecystectomy (open if emphysematous or cancer-suspected)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Acalculous cholecystitis lives in the ICU - critically ill, low perfusion, TPN, burns, trauma, major surgery; ultrasound shows wall thickening + fluid + sludge WITHOUT stones."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Don't flip the HIDA clock: not seen at 60 = acute; finally seen at 120 = chronic. A gallbladder seen within the first hour is a NORMAL scan."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff anchored cholecystitis on an imaging algorithm and a clock. Distinguish calculous from acalculous cholecystitis, give the first and second imaging tests, state the HIDA timing rule for acute vs chronic, and outline management."}]}, {"id": 6, "statement": "Describe cholangitis (Charcot triad, Reynolds pentad) and its management sequence", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "RECOGNITION — CHARCOT TO REYNOLDS. Acute cholangitis is infection of an obstructed biliary tree (stone — most often from choledocholithiasis — stricture, or tumor). Charcot triad = fever, RUQ pain, and jaundice -> think cholangitis. Add altered mental status and hypotension and you have Reynolds pentad (the 5: fever, RUQ pain, jaundice, AMS, hypotension), which signals suppurative cholangitis / septic shock — a surgical emergency needing immediate treatment. Infection is typically polymicrobial gram-negative gut flora (E. coli, Klebsiella)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Charcot triad = fever + RUQ pain + jaundice; Reynolds pentad = + AMS + hypotension (surgical emergency)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE MANAGEMENT SEQUENCE — DON'T DRAIN FIRST. The order is fixed and board-flagged: (1) broad-spectrum IV antibiotics (cover gram-negative aerobes AND anaerobes) plus fluids and resuscitation FIRST, then (2) biliary drainage. Drainage is usually ERCP with sphincterotomy, which clears distal CBD stones in >90% of cases; the combination of antibiotics + ERCP fixes most patients. If endoscopic drainage fails (stones can't be removed/obstruction can't be relieved), escalate to the operating room for surgical drainage/CBD exploration and enteric bypass, removing the stone source (the gallbladder). The takeaway: resuscitate and treat the sepsis before you relieve the obstruction."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cholangitis: antibiotics + resuscitation FIRST, THEN drainage (ERCP + sphincterotomy); surgery if drainage fails."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Charcot triad (fever/RUQ/jaundice) -> cholangitis; Reynolds pentad (+AMS+hypotension) -> emergency. Sequence: antibiotics + resuscitation FIRST, then ERCP drainage, surgery only if drainage fails."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "The trap is doing ERCP first in a septic, hypotensive patient - stabilize (abx + fluids) BEFORE you drain."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "ERCP with sphincterotomy clears distal CBD stones in >90%; the OR is the backup when endoscopic drainage fails."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff called this one of the most important things to know. Give Charcot triad and Reynolds pentad, and state the exact management sequence for acute cholangitis (and what changes when drainage fails)."}]}, {"id": 7, "statement": "Describe gallstone pancreatitis and gallstone ileus", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "GALLSTONE PANCREATITIS. When a stone impacts at the ampulla of Vater, it causes backflow into the pancreatic duct and acute pancreatitis (most stones in the common duct are cholesterol stones that came from the gallbladder; in ~20% of people the pancreatic duct inserts separately, but usually it joins the common duct before the duodenum — which is why gallstones so commonly cause pancreatitis). The good news: gallstone pancreatitis usually improves on its own once the stone passes. If obstruction persists, do an ERCP with stone removal; and to prevent recurrence, perform a cholecystectomy (interval cholecystectomy removes the stone source)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Gallstone pancreatitis = stone at ampulla of Vater -> pancreatic-duct backflow; resolves on passage; cholecystectomy prevents recurrence."}, {"t": "p", "x": "GALLSTONE ILEUS. A large stone erodes through a cholecystoduodenal (cholecystoenteric) fistula into the bowel and travels distally until it impacts at the narrowest point — the terminal ileum, causing a mechanical small-bowel obstruction with proximal dilation. Classic clues: elderly patient, pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree) on imaging, and dilated small-bowel loops with a 'stacked-coin' appearance. Treatment is an operation: enterotomy proximal to the obstruction to extract the stone, then close. You generally do NOT take down the fistula or remove the gallbladder at the same operation — the single-stage repair carries high complication rates and the recurrence risk is low."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Gallstone ileus = cholecystoduodenal fistula -> stone at terminal ileum (pneumobilia); Tx enterotomy, leave fistula/gallbladder."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Gallstone pancreatitis = ampullary stone -> usually self-resolves -> cholecystectomy to prevent recurrence. Gallstone ileus = cholecystoduodenal fistula -> terminal-ileum impaction (pneumobilia) -> enterotomy."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Gallstone ileus = elderly + pneumobilia + SBO; the stone lodges at the terminal ileum (the narrowest small-bowel segment)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "In gallstone ileus you usually do NOT fix the fistula or remove the gallbladder at the same operation - just enterolithotomy; one-stage repair is higher-risk and recurrence is low."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff gave two distinct gallstone complications downstream of the gallbladder. Explain gallstone pancreatitis (why it happens and how it usually resolves) and gallstone ileus (the fistula, the impaction site, and the operation)."}]}, {"id": 8, "statement": "Describe biliary strictures and biliary cysts", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "BILIARY STRICTURES. Strictures of the biliary tree arise from stones, cancer, trauma, inflammation, or surgery — but the #1 cause of benign biliary strictures is IATROGENIC injury, classically a bile-duct injury during laparoscopic cholecystectomy in an inflamed field (often not apparent until edema subsides). A stricture causes obstruction and can lead to cholangitis, jaundice, sepsis. The board one-liner: a biliary stricture in the absence of prior pancreatitis or biliary surgery is CANCER until you prove otherwise — evaluate thoroughly (endoscopic evaluation), and most of these go to an operation (often a choledochojejunostomy / hepaticojejunostomy reconstruction)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Benign stricture #1 = iatrogenic (lap chole); a stricture without prior pancreatitis/surgery = CANCER until proven otherwise."}, {"t": "p", "x": "BILIARY (CHOLEDOCHAL) CYSTS. Biliary cysts are dilatations of the biliary tree, either extrahepatic or intrahepatic, classified into four (Todani) types. Definitive management is the province of expert biliary surgeons, so the one number to carry is the malignancy risk: biliary cysts have a ~15% risk of developing cholangiocarcinoma. Therefore, when you find a bile-duct cyst, the key action is to evaluate the patient to rule out an underlying cancer (and, in practice, resect to remove that risk)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Biliary cysts = biliary-tree dilatations (extra-/intrahepatic), 4 types, ~15% cholangiocarcinoma risk -> rule out cancer."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Benign biliary stricture #1 = iatrogenic (lap chole). Stricture without prior pancreatitis/surgery = cancer until proven otherwise. Biliary cysts (4 types) carry ~15% cholangiocarcinoma risk."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "The exam one-liner is verbatim: an unexplained biliary stricture is 'cancer until you prove it otherwise.'"}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff gave a one-liner about strictures he wanted remembered, plus a single fact about biliary cysts. What is the #1 cause of benign biliary strictures, what is the cancer rule for an unexplained stricture, and what is the key cancer number for biliary cysts?"}]}, {"id": 9, "statement": "Describe gallbladder cancer and polyps, including staging and surgical management", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "WHAT GALLBLADDER CANCER IS. Gallbladder cancer (GBC) is rare but aggressive. Because the gallbladder lacks a submucosa, tumors spread early via lymphatics and into the liver, and survival is poor. Adenocarcinoma is the most common histology, most cancers arise in the fundus, and the #1 risk factor is gallstones/cholelithiasis (others: porcelain gallbladder, large/long-standing stones, gallbladder polyps, PSC, anomalous pancreaticobiliary junction). Nearly half are found incidentally at routine cholecystectomy. A fundal mass is a red flag — gallstone disease usually involves the infundibulum/cystic duct, so fundal involvement suggests a neoplastic process."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "GBC = aggressive adenocarcinoma, fundus, #1 risk = gallstones; no submucosa -> early spread; ~half incidental."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE STAGING-DRIVEN OPERATION. GBC is staged by TNM, and the operation follows the T stage — this was repeated all lecture: T1a (tumor confined to the lamina propria, does NOT invade the muscularis) -> simple cholecystectomy is curative. T1b/T2 (tumor invades the muscularis, raising lymphatic-spread risk) -> extended cholecystectomy + regional lymphadenectomy, with a segmental/wedge hepatic resection of segments IVb and V. Once lymph nodes or metastases are involved, survival is very poor (stage IV rarely survives beyond ~6 months; 5-year survival 0-10% even for early cancers)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "OPEN-TO-AVOID-SEEDING + POLYPS. When cancer is suspected before surgery (e.g., a fundal mass or a large polyp), operate OPEN, not laparoscopically — laparoscopy/robot raises the risk of seeding/spreading the tumor, and going open lets you proceed straight to an extended cholecystectomy if needed. Stage GBC with triple-phase CT or MRI (intraoperative frozen section helps). For gallbladder polyps: most are benign cholesterol polyps, but size predicts cancer — adenomatous polyps ~10-18 mm warrant cholecystectomy (preferably open), and polyps >20 mm should undergo open cholecystectomy. The bottom line: gallbladder lesions = think surgery."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "T1a -> simple cholecystectomy (curative); T1b/T2 -> extended cholecystectomy + lymphadenectomy (segments IVb/V)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cancer suspected -> operate OPEN (avoid seeding); polyps ~10-18 mm = chole, >20 mm = open. [transcript-sourced]"}, {"t": "key", "x": "GBC = aggressive fundal adenocarcinoma, #1 risk = gallstones. T1a -> simple cholecystectomy; T1b/T2 -> extended cholecystectomy + lymphadenectomy (segments IVb/V). Suspected cancer -> operate OPEN to avoid seeding."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "A fundal gallbladder mass is suspicious - benign stone disease favors the infundibulum/cystic duct, so fundal involvement points to a neoplasm."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "The whole T-stage hinges on the muscularis: T1a does NOT cross it (cholecystectomy cures); T1b invades it (extended cholecystectomy + lymphadenectomy)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff said when it comes to gallbladder lesions, think surgery - and the staging line was repeated all lecture. Give the key features of gallbladder cancer (origin, histology, #1 risk), the T1a vs T1b/T2 operation rule, why you operate open, and the polyp size thresholds."}]}, {"id": 10, "statement": "Describe cholangiocarcinoma", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Cholangiocarcinoma is cancer of the biliary tree other than the gallbladder, and the most common histology is adenocarcinoma. It can occur anywhere along the biliary tree; classification includes intrahepatic, extrahepatic, and perihilar (plus right/left distinctions). The classic and most-recognized variant is the perihilar tumor at the confluence of the hepatic ducts — the Klatskin tumor. About two-thirds of cholangiocarcinomas are extrahepatic. Presentations include a mass, stricture, jaundice, and weight loss; survival is poor."}, {"t": "p", "x": "TREATMENT. The best chance for survival is a curative surgical excision (resection), but unfortunately many tumors are unresectable at diagnosis, leaving palliative drainage (bypass) procedures to relieve the obstruction, plus chemotherapy. Liver transplantation was tried for highly selected, very limited disease but in most centers no longer offers a long-term survival advantage and is largely abandoned for cholangiocarcinoma. Note the natural pathology↔surgery pairing: the cholangiocarcinoma/Klatskin pathology is detailed in Lec 44, and this is its surgical-management counterpart."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cholangiocarcinoma = biliary-tree adenocarcinoma; perihilar = Klatskin; ~2/3 extrahepatic; best = curative resection."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Cholangiocarcinoma = adenocarcinoma of the biliary tree; the perihilar (hilar confluence) variant is the Klatskin tumor; best chance for survival = curative surgical excision, but most are unresectable."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Klatskin = perihilar cholangiocarcinoma at the hepatic-duct confluence; ~two-thirds of cholangiocarcinomas are extrahepatic."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff closed on cholangiocarcinoma. What is it (histology and location), what is the classic perihilar variant called, and what is the best chance for survival?"}]}, {"id": 11, "statement": "Evaluate a liver mass (imaging, tumor markers, role of biopsy)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Liver masses usually surface incidentally — found on imaging done for something else, noticed intraoperatively, picked up on screening of abnormal liver function tests, or during a metastatic workup (e.g., a colon-cancer patient with elevated LFTs). When you see one, you must hold both benign and malignant causes in mind. Sharieff's framework: benign = hemangioma (most common, usually asymptomatic), hepatic adenoma (the symptomatic one), focal nodular hyperplasia, simple cyst; malignant = metastasis (the most common, covered in LO 46.4), then the primaries hepatocellular carcinoma and cholangiocarcinoma."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE WORKUP — IMAGING + MARKERS, ALMOST NEVER A BIOPSY. Workup is twofold: laboratory assessment and imaging. The best study to characterize a liver mass is a triple-phase (arterial/venous/delayed) contrast CT with a liver protocol or an MRI; nuclear scans (e.g., sulfur-colloid, used to read FNH/adenoma) help in selected functional or indeterminate cases. If a tumor is suspected, assess tumor markers — the combination of imaging and markers 'almost always gives away' the lesion. Crucially, Sharieff hammered that you do not need a biopsy: history/physical + good imaging + blood work tells you what is going on. The classic example: cirrhosis + elevated alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) + a hypervascular mass = hepatocellular carcinoma, diagnosed without tissue. Always also evaluate for cirrhosis, because it raises the chance the mass is a primary malignancy and dictates the hepatic reserve you have to work with if you resect. LI-RADS (analogous to BI-RADS in mammography) stratifies the malignant potential of a liver lesion in the cirrhotic patient."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Liver-mass workup = triple-phase CT/MRI + markers, avoid biopsy; cirrhosis + ↑AFP + hypervascular mass = HCC."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Assess cirrhosis (raises primary-malignancy odds, sets hepatic reserve); LI-RADS grades malignancy like BI-RADS for breast."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Characterize a liver mass with triple-phase CT or MRI + tumor markers and avoid biopsy. Cirrhosis + elevated AFP + a hypervascular mass = HCC without tissue."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "LI-RADS is the liver analog of BI-RADS — it grades a lesion's malignant potential in the cirrhotic patient. Read a little about it (Sharieff's explicit ask)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Biopsy is avoided because imaging + markers usually settle it and tissue sampling adds bleeding/seeding risk for little gain."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff said the whole take-home from the liver-mass workup slide is that you rarely need one particular test. What is the imaging-plus-labs workup, what is that test you avoid, and what single combination of findings tells you a mass is hepatocellular carcinoma without any tissue?"}]}, {"id": 12, "statement": "Distinguish and manage benign liver lesions (hemangioma, adenoma, FNH, cyst)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Four benign liver lesions, each with its own behavior. Hemangioma is the most common benign tumor and is usually asymptomatic — follow it, don't biopsy, and resect only when large/symptomatic or at high rupture risk (e.g., giant hemangiomas, or Kasabach-Merritt syndrome, where hemangiomas reach ~10 cm with consumptive coagulopathy in children). Simple cysts (often with polycystic kidney/liver disease) are typically <3 cm and need nothing unless they bleed, infect, rupture, or look complex/suspicious for a mucinous cystadenoma/carcinoma."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HEPATIC ADENOMA — THE EXAM RULE. The benign tumor that makes trouble is the hepatic adenoma: encapsulated plates of glycogen-rich hepatocytes, classically in young women on oral contraceptives (and men on anabolic steroids), presenting with pain. It matters because it carries two threats — rupture/intraabdominal hemorrhage and malignant transformation. The board rule Sharieff stated twice: in men, resect ANY size (higher malignant-transformation risk); in women, a lesion <4 cm can be watched after stopping estrogen/anabolic steroids, while >4 cm (or symptomatic/growing) is resected regardless. On nuclear imaging adenomas lack Kupffer cells, so they appear cold on sulfur-colloid scan."}, {"t": "p", "x": "FOCAL NODULAR HYPERPLASIA — THE 'NO MALIGNANT POTENTIAL' LESION. FNH is the second most common benign lesion after hemangioma — a hyperplastic (not neoplastic) response around a congenital arteriovenous malformation. Its imaging signature is a central fibrous stellate scar with radiating septa (seen in ~15% of cases). The board point: FNH has NO malignant potential and an extremely low risk of bleeding, so it is managed conservatively (observation), resected only for significant symptoms or when it cannot be distinguished from adenoma/fibrolamellar carcinoma. Sharieff's exam framing: given a menu of liver lesions, the one with no malignant potential is FNH, and you watch it."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Adenoma: resect any size in men; women <4 cm watch (stop estrogen/steroids), >4 cm resect. Risk = rupture + malignancy."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "FNH = central stellate scar, NO malignant potential, very low bleed risk -> watch. The 'no malignant potential' answer is FNH."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Adenoma: resect any-size in men, >4 cm in women (rupture + malignant risk). FNH: central scar, no malignant potential -> watch. Hemangioma: most common, asymptomatic, no biopsy. Simple cyst: watch unless complicated/complex."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Adenoma vs FNH: adenoma has malignant + rupture risk and needs resection by the size/sex rule; FNH (central scar) has no malignant potential and is watched. Don't swap them."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Kasabach-Merritt syndrome = giant hemangioma (up to ~10 cm in children) with consumptive thrombocytopenia/coagulopathy — a reason to resect an otherwise-benign hemangioma."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff gave an explicit exam call-out on hepatic adenoma and on the one benign liver lesion with no malignant potential. Walk the four benign lesions, give the adenoma resection rule for men versus women, and name the lesion that is always managed conservatively and why."}]}, {"id": 13, "statement": "Diagnose and manage hepatocellular carcinoma, including Milan criteria", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) is the more common primary liver malignancy (cholangiocarcinoma is the other) and almost always arises in the background of cirrhosis. In the US the classic drivers are hepatitis C cirrhosis and, increasingly, alcoholic cirrhosis (also NASH/fatty liver). Diagnosis is by imaging + markers, not biopsy: a hypervascular mass on multiphase CT/MRI plus an elevated alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) in a cirrhotic is HCC. Sharieff's refrain — 'imaging, imaging, imaging', with MRI added when you need to define biliary-tree extension before any treatment."}, {"t": "p", "x": "TREATMENT — RESECTION VS TRANSPLANT, AND WHY TRANSPLANT WON. Surgery is the curative option. A small, resectable HCC (<5 cm) in a liver with decent reserve could historically be resected; but accumulated data over the last decade show that for HCC on a cirrhotic background, liver transplantation gives better outcomes than resection alone — it removes both the tumor and the diseased, at-risk liver. So in the cirrhotic patient with a qualifying HCC, transplant is now the best option, and qualifying patients gain higher priority on the UNOS (United Network for Organ Sharing) wait list."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE MILAN CRITERIA — MEMORIZE THE NUMBERS. Eligibility for transplant is defined by the Milan criteria: a single nodule ≤5 cm, OR up to three nodules each ≤3 cm, with NO macrovascular invasion and NO distant/extrahepatic disease. Meeting Milan -> best indication for liver transplant. (The UCSF criteria are slightly more permissive — single ≤6.5 cm or up to 3 each ≤4.5 cm, total ≤8 cm — but are center-specific; most transplant centers use Milan.) Sharieff's exam framing: a ~5 cm HCC on a cirrhotic background -> the best option is transplantation, not resection. (Liver transplant — first done by Thomas Starzl in 1963 — is itself a separate lecture; here it is simply the surgical answer for HCC.)"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HCC = cirrhosis background (HCV/alcohol/NASH) + hypervascular mass + ↑AFP, no biopsy."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Milan = single ≤5 cm OR ≤3 nodules each ≤3 cm, no vascular invasion, no distant disease -> liver transplant."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Within Milan, transplant > resection in cirrhotics (removes tumor + at-risk liver), higher UNOS priority. ~5 cm HCC on cirrhosis -> transplant."}, {"t": "key", "x": "HCC = cirrhotic background + hypervascular mass + ↑AFP (no biopsy). Milan criteria: single ≤5 cm OR ≤3 nodules each ≤3 cm, no vascular invasion, no distant disease -> liver transplant, the best option."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Transplant now beats resection alone for HCC in cirrhosis because it removes the tumor AND the diseased liver; Milan-eligible patients get higher UNOS priority. UCSF criteria are more permissive but center-specific."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Exam pattern: ~5 cm mass + cirrhosis -> liver transplant is the best answer (everything else underperforms it)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff said that for hepatocellular carcinoma the best answer on the exam is one specific treatment, governed by a named set of criteria. How do you diagnose HCC, what are the Milan criteria exactly, and why is transplant now preferred over resection?"}]}, {"id": 14, "statement": "Manage liver abscesses and metastatic liver disease", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "PYOGENIC ABSCESS — DRAIN IF >5 cm. Liver abscesses split into pyogenic (bacterial), amebic, and fungal. Pyogenic liver abscess is the most common in the US, involves the right hemiliver in ~75%, and classically presents with fever, jaundice, and right-upper-quadrant pain. Cover broadly (aerobes + anaerobes, gram-negatives). Size drives drainage: <3 cm -> IV antibiotics alone; >5 cm -> drain (percutaneous first; excise if percutaneous fails and the patient decompensates)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "AMEBIC AND ECHINOCOCCAL — THE ASPIRATION TRAPS. An amebic abscess (Entamoeba histolytica; think travel/South America) is treated medically with metronidazole (Flagyl) — no aspiration needed; on the board, a right-upper-quadrant mass you suspect is amebic should get drugs, not a needle (aspiration yields 'anchovy-paste' fluid but is generally unnecessary). An echinococcal (hydatid) cyst (Echinococcus; Egyptian/Middle-Eastern, sheep-raising populations) is the dangerous one: do NOT simply aspirate/puncture, because spillage causes allergic/anaphylactic shock. Treat with a scolicidal agent (albendazole) to shrink the cyst, then resect; for large/refractory cysts use the PAIR approach (Puncture, Aspiration, Injection of scolicidal, Re-aspiration) under cover — image first to check for biliary-tree communication."}, {"t": "p", "x": "METASTATIC DISEASE — THE #1 MALIGNANT LIVER LESION. The single most common malignant liver lesion is metastasis, far outnumbering primary tumors — colon (colorectal) first, then pancreas and stomach. Colorectal liver metastases are the most frequent indication for liver resection, and in a patient with a healthy (non-cirrhotic) liver they are often resectable for cure, either synchronously (taken with the primary colon resection) or metachronously (when a met appears later) — resection gives a real survival benefit."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Pyogenic = most common (US), right liver ~75%, fever/jaundice/RUQ pain; <3 cm abx, >5 cm drain; broad aerobe + anaerobe."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Amebic -> metronidazole, no aspiration. Echinococcal -> no aspiration (anaphylaxis); albendazole + PAIR then resect."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Metastasis = #1 malignant liver lesion (>> primary); top primary = colon, then pancreas/stomach; mets in a healthy liver -> resect."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Pyogenic (most common US, fever/jaundice/RUQ): <3 cm abx, >5 cm drain. Amebic: metronidazole, no aspiration. Echinococcal: no aspiration (anaphylaxis), albendazole + PAIR. Metastasis = #1 malignant lesion (colon first)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Liver vs pancreas: in the liver the most common malignant lesion is metastasis; in the pancreas, metastasis is rare (PDAC dominates). Don't carry the liver rule into the pancreas."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Echinococcal cyst: puncturing it spills antigenic fluid -> anaphylaxis. Shrink first with albendazole, then PAIR/resect — never a naive aspiration."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff walked three liver abscesses and flagged an aspiration trap on two of them, then reminded us what the most common malignant liver lesion really is. Name the three abscesses with organism and management, say which two you must NOT simply aspirate and why, and give the #1 malignant liver lesion and its top primary."}]}, {"id": 15, "statement": "Evaluate a pancreatic mass (solid vs cystic; rule out malignancy)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Unlike liver masses, most pancreatic masses are found incidentally; they are rarely identified intraoperatively because the pancreas is retroperitoneal and hard to see. The differential holds both benign and malignant lesions, but Sharieff's organizing rule is binary by consistency: every SOLID pancreatic lesion is considered malignant and treated as such (resect early — surgery is the only cure), while a CYSTIC lesion obligates you to rule out cancer. A key contrast with the liver: metastasis to the pancreas is rare (in the liver, metastasis is the #1 lesion), so a solid pancreatic mass is your own primary cancer until proven otherwise."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE CYST KEY — MUCIN. For a cyst, the determinant of malignancy is what fluid is inside. Serous/simple cysts and pseudocysts hold thin serous fluid and are usually benign (little follow-up needed). The moment you find mucin, malignant risk appears: mucinous cystic neoplasm (MCN) carries ~15-25% malignancy, and a higher mucin concentration with elevated CEA points to an intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm (IPMN), ~35-65% malignant (graded main-duct > mixed > side-branch). That is the whole reason a pancreatic cyst makes you 'rule out cancer.'"}, {"t": "p", "x": "WORKUP — CT/MRI + CA 19-9, AND AVOID BIOPSY. As in the liver, the best study is a triple-phase CT with a pancreas protocol or MRI/MRCP (define ductal anatomy and vascular invasion -> resectability), and pancreatic lesions need staging. The key tumor marker is CA 19-9 (often elevated; check it on aspirated cyst fluid too — elevated -> mucinous neoplasm/adenocarcinoma); chromogranin A flags neuroendocrine tumors. Avoid biopsy. The only real indication is an indeterminate cyst (can't tell serous from mucinous), and then by EUS-FNA with a clear reason — because percutaneous biopsy risks acute pancreatitis and delays definitive management."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Solid lesion = treat as malignant (resect); cystic = rule out cancer. Metastasis to pancreas is rare (opposite of liver)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cyst malignancy = mucin: serous/pseudocyst benign; MCN 15-25%, IPMN 35-65% (main-duct worst, ↑CEA); cyst-fluid ↑CA 19-9 = mucinous."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Pancreatic workup = triple-phase CT/MRI(MRCP) + CA 19-9; avoid biopsy (EUS-FNA only, with a reason - risks pancreatitis + delay)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Solid pancreatic mass = treat as malignant (resect); cystic = rule out cancer by its mucin (serous/pseudocyst benign; MCN 15-25%; IPMN 35-65%). Workup = CT/MRI + CA 19-9; avoid biopsy (EUS-FNA only)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Liver vs pancreas: liver mass -> metastasis is #1; pancreas -> metastasis is rare, so a solid pancreatic mass is a primary cancer until proven otherwise."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Biopsy is avoided in BOTH liver and pancreas; in the pancreas the harm is concrete — iatrogenic acute pancreatitis plus a delay in care. EUS-FNA is the selective exception for an indeterminate cyst."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff said the pancreatic-mass slide caps with two rules - one for solid lesions, one for cystic - and that, just like the liver, there is one test you avoid. Give the solid-vs-cystic rule, the workup (imaging + marker), the role of biopsy, and how the pancreas differs from the liver on metastasis."}]}, {"id": 16, "statement": "Manage pancreatic cystic lesions (pseudocyst, MCN, IPMN)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "PSEUDOCYST — NO EPITHELIUM, EXPECTANT MANAGEMENT. A pancreatic pseudocyst is a well-defined peripancreatic fluid collection with a fibrotic wall but NO epithelial lining (that absent lining is what makes it a pseudocyst), filled with amylase-rich fluid from disruption of the main pancreatic duct after an acute inflammatory process; the common cause is chronic pancreatitis/alcohol. Most are discovered after pancreatitis with vague pain, nausea, and vomiting, and diagnosed by contrast CT/MRI. The board point Sharieff highlighted: pseudocysts are usually sterile (no antibiotics) and most resolve spontaneously, so initial management is expectant — pain control, nutritional support, and treating the pancreatitis — sometimes waiting >3-6 months."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHEN TO DRAIN, AND THE 'RULE OUT CANCER' BANNER. Drainage (percutaneous, endoscopic, or open) is reserved for persistence or complications — necrosis, hemorrhage, rupture, or infection; the approach depends on the actual problem. The banner rule for everything else: if a cyst is NOT associated with pancreatitis or trauma, you MUST rule out cancer — is it a mucinous cystic neoplasm (MCN, ~15-25% malignant) or an intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm (IPMN, ~35-65% malignant)? So a cyst in the setting of acute pancreatitis + alcohol is a pseudocyst you watch; an unprovoked cyst is a cancer you must exclude."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Pseudocyst = fibrous wall, NO epithelium, amylase-rich; sterile (no abx), expectant (most resolve); drain only if persistent/complicated."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cyst with no pancreatitis/trauma -> MUST rule out cancer (MCN 15-25% vs IPMN 35-65%); pancreatitis + alcohol cyst -> pseudocyst -> watch."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Pseudocyst (fibrous wall, no epithelium, amylase-rich, post-pancreatitis): usually sterile, expectant management; drain only for persistence or complications. Cyst not tied to pancreatitis/trauma -> MUST rule out cancer (MCN vs IPMN)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "A pseudocyst is a pseudocyst because it has no true epithelial lining — just a fibrous/inflammatory wall around amylase-rich fluid. A mucinous neoplasm DOES have epithelium and mucin -> that is the malignant worry."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Pseudocyst on the exam = watch (expectant management); antibiotics are NOT routine because pseudocysts are usually sterile."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff gave an explicit exam call-out on the pseudocyst and a banner rule for any cyst not tied to pancreatitis or trauma. Define a pseudocyst, give its initial management and the indications to drain, and state the rule that splits 'watch' from 'rule out cancer.'"}]}, {"id": 17, "statement": "Manage pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma and pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "PDAC — THE BIG BURDEN. Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC) is the most common pancreatic cancer and the one Sharieff most wants learned, because it carries a very poor prognosis (5-year survival <10%) — by the time it is found, many patients are unresectable. It is projected to become the 2nd-leading cause of cancer death by 2030 (stated three times), arises usually in the head of the pancreas (classic painless jaundice from biliary obstruction), and has a genetic contribution. Workup is the same triple-phase CT/MRI (define ductal/vascular invasion -> resectability) plus CA 19-9."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PDAC TREATMENT — RESECT EARLY, WHIPPLE THE HEAD. Surgery is the only cure, so finding and removing the lesion early is everything. For a resectable lesion in the head of the pancreas, the operation is a pancreaticoduodenectomy (Whipple procedure); done well for localized head lesions the outcomes are reasonable, though many patients develop post-surgical fistula or delayed gastric emptying. Do NOT biopsy a solid pancreatic lesion (risk of pancreatitis + delay) — treat it as malignant and resect."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PNETs — MOSTLY NONFUNCTIONAL, STILL RESECT; WHIPPLE'S TRIAD = INSULINOMA. Pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors (PNETs) are 80-90% sporadic and 60-90% nonfunctional, but they carry a high malignant potential, so a solid PNET is treated as malignant: check functional markers, and resect — lesions ≥2 cm definitely need an open resection (small neuroendocrine lesions may be enucleated, but most surgeons resect). Metastasis is common, usually to the liver; high tumor burden may need adjuvant chemo/radiation. The exam call-out: a functional PNET presenting with Whipple's triad — (1) symptomatic hypoglycemia, (2) low measured glucose (~<50-60), and (3) relief of symptoms with glucose — is an insulinoma until proven otherwise. (Other functional PNETs: gastrinoma, glucagonoma, somatostatinoma, VIPoma.)"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PDAC = most common pancreatic cancer, worst prognosis (5-yr <10%), head (painless jaundice), 2nd cancer death by 2030; resectable head -> Whipple."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PNET: mostly nonfunctional but high malignant potential -> resect (esp. ≥2 cm); mets to liver. Whipple's triad -> insulinoma."}, {"t": "key", "x": "PDAC: most common, worst prognosis (5-yr <10%), head/painless jaundice, 2nd-leading cancer death by 2030, Whipple for resectable head lesions. PNET: mostly nonfunctional but high malignant potential -> resect ≥2 cm; Whipple's triad = insulinoma."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Two different 'Whipples': the Whipple PROCEDURE (pancreaticoduodenectomy, the operation) vs Whipple's TRIAD (the hypoglycemia triad that names an insulinoma). Same surname, different concept."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Solid pancreatic mass (PDAC or PNET) = treat as malignant, resect, don't biopsy; PNETs metastasize to the liver and may need adjuvant therapy for high burden."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff said one pancreatic malignancy is the big burden to learn and that a functional neuroendocrine tumor has a classic triad on the exam. Describe PDAC (frequency, prognosis, location, operation, the 2030 stat) and then explain the PNET rule, including what Whipple's triad means and which tumor it names."}]}, {"id": 18, "statement": "Manage chronic pancreatitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW + THE CT TRIAD. Chronic pancreatitis is irreversible injury to the pancreas, most often from alcohol (with tobacco), increasingly idiopathic/genetic. The classic patient is a long-time heavy drinker with epigastric pain radiating to the back, weight loss, and steatorrhea (bulky, foul-smelling, fatty stools) from malabsorption. The CT triad Sharieff wants read off the scan: pancreatic calcifications + an irregular, dilated pancreatic duct + parenchymal atrophy. Get a good CT (MRCP supplements ductal anatomy) to gauge how dilated the duct is and whether the patient needs an operation."}, {"t": "p", "x": "MANAGEMENT — REPLACE WHAT'S LOST, THEN OPERATE FOR PAIN. Because the injury is irreversible, treatment is supportive and aimed at the lost exocrine and endocrine functions: pain management, correcting nutritional/fat-soluble-vitamin (A, D, E, K) deficiencies, pancreatic enzyme replacement therapy for the steatorrhea, and glucose monitoring/control for the diabetes that develops as islets are lost. When pain persists despite medical therapy and the duct is dilated, the operation is a Puestow procedure (lateral pancreaticojejunostomy) — the pancreas is opened along its length and the entire duct is anastomosed side-to-side to a loop of jejunum to drain it. (Chronic pancreatitis can also spawn pseudocysts — see LO 46.6.)"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Chronic pancreatitis = alcohol/tobacco, irreversible; CT triad = calcification + dilated irregular duct + atrophy; back pain + steatorrhea + weight loss."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Manage = pain control + enzyme replacement + fat-soluble vitamins + glucose control; refractory ductal pain -> Puestow (lateral pancreaticojejunostomy)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Chronic pancreatitis (alcohol/tobacco, irreversible): CT triad = calcification + dilated irregular duct + atrophy. Manage with pain control + pancreatic enzyme replacement + fat-soluble vitamins + glucose control; refractory ductal pain -> Puestow."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Puestow = lateral pancreaticojejunostomy — open the duct along the gland and drain it side-to-side into jejunum; reserved for a dilated duct with pain that medical therapy can't control."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Long alcohol history + epigastric-to-back pain + steatorrhea + a CT with calcifications, a dilated irregular duct, and atrophy = chronic pancreatitis."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Sharieff showed a long-time-drinker's CT and asked you to read it, then build a plan. What is the classic CT triad of chronic pancreatitis, what does its irreversibility mean for management, and what surgery do you reach for when pain persists despite medical therapy?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Removing every gallbladder with stones. NOT all gallstones need removal - asymptomatic cholelithiasis is observed (lifetime complicated-disease risk ~8%). Prophylactic cholecystectomy is only for individualized special cases. → LO 45.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Flipping the HIDA clock. Non-visualization at 60 min = ACUTE cholecystitis; delayed visualization by 120 min = CHRONIC. A gallbladder seen within the first hour is a NORMAL scan. → LO 45.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Draining the cholangitic before resuscitating. In acute cholangitis, antibiotics + resuscitation come FIRST, THEN biliary drainage (ERCP). Don't ERCP a septic, hypotensive patient before stabilizing. → LO 45.6"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Over- or under-operating gallbladder cancer. T1a (not beyond muscularis) = simple cholecystectomy cures; T1b/T2 (invades muscularis) = extended cholecystectomy + lymphadenectomy (segments IVb/V). Suspected cancer -> operate OPEN to avoid seeding. → LO 45.9"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Mis-stating the hepatic-adenoma resection rule. Resect a hepatic adenoma in ANY-size man and in a woman >4 cm (watch <4 cm after stopping estrogen/steroids) - not 'watch everything because it's benign.' Adenoma carries rupture + malignant-transformation risk; FNH (central scar) is the one with no malignant potential. → LO 46.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Garbling the Milan criteria. Milan = single nodule ≤5 cm OR ≤3 nodules each ≤3 cm, no vascular invasion, no distant disease -> transplant (the best option, beating resection alone in cirrhotics). Don't permit vascular invasion or scramble the size/number. → LO 46.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. Carrying the liver 'mets is #1' rule into the pancreas. In the liver, metastasis is the most common malignant lesion (colon first); in the pancreas, metastasis is rare and PDAC dominates - a solid pancreatic mass is a primary cancer until proven otherwise. → LO 46.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "8. Aspirating the wrong abscess. Echinococcal (hydatid) cysts must NOT be simply aspirated - spillage causes anaphylaxis; use albendazole + PAIR. Amebic abscess -> metronidazole, no aspiration. Only pyogenic >5 cm is routinely drained. → LO 46.4"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"incidental gallstones, no symptoms, no biliary pain\" → observe (expectant management); not all gallstones need removal."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"HIDA: gallbladder not seen at 60 min but fills by 120 min\" → chronic cholecystitis (60-min non-visualization alone = acute)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"fever + RUQ pain + jaundice + confusion + hypotension\" → Reynolds pentad; antibiotics + resuscitation FIRST, then ERCP drainage."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"elderly, pneumobilia, SBO, stone in the terminal ileum\" → gallstone ileus (cholecystoduodenal fistula) → enterotomy to extract the stone."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"young woman on OCPs with a 5 cm painful liver adenoma / any-size adenoma in a man\" → resect (rupture + malignant-transformation risk); an adenoma <4 cm in a woman -> stop estrogen/steroids and watch."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"~5 cm hepatocellular carcinoma on a cirrhotic background, no vascular invasion\" → liver transplant (meets Milan criteria; beats resection alone)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. \"alcoholic with acute pancreatitis and a 7 cm simple cyst, no fever\" → pseudocyst -> expectant management (no antibiotics; most resolve)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "8. \"hypoglycemia + neuroglycopenic symptoms + relief with glucose (Whipple's triad)\" → insulinoma, a functional pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Cholangiocarcinoma & Klatskin tumor - the surgical management here (adenocarcinoma of the biliary tree, perihilar Klatskin variant, curative resection) is the operative counterpart to the cholangiocarcinoma/Klatskin pathology in Lec 44 (tumors of the gallbladder and bile ducts); a natural pathology↔surgery pairing"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Gallstones - the cholesterol-vs-pigment stone types and the complication tree (cholecystitis, cholangitis, pancreatitis, ileus) developed here are the surgical sequel to the cholelithiasis pathology in Lec 44 (cholesterol ~90% vs black/brown pigment); the arc is stone → inflammation → infection → cancer across Lec 44 → 45"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Cholecystitis labs - the LFT check Sharieff orders in acute cholecystitis/cholangitis (bilirubin, ALP, transaminases to catch a CBD stone) is the clinical use of the integrity/excretory/synthetic LFT framework taught in full in the hepatic function-test lecture (Lec 48)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Roads to HCC - the cirrhosis that hepatocellular carcinoma grows on is the steatosis-to-cirrhosis endpoint built in Lec 43 (alcoholic/NASH cirrhosis, the macronodular post-necrotic pathway), while Lec 49 adds the viral driver (HBV can cause HCC even without cirrhosis via direct integration; HCV cirrhosis is the common US route); this lecture supplies the surgical endpoint - Milan criteria -> transplant"}]}]}, "47": {"prof": "Dr. R. Daniel Bonfil", "tldr": "Walk bilirubin heme-to-bile (UGT1A1, MRP2) and read each jaundice off the broken step — five syndromes sorted unconjugated (UGT1A1) vs conjugated (MRP2/OATP), cholestasis the ALP/GGT picture beside them.", "mustKnows": ["1. The bilirubin assembly line, enzyme by enzyme. Heme (~80% from senescent RBCs in splenic macrophages) → heme oxygenase → biliverdin → biliverdin reductase → unconjugated bilirubin (UCB), water-insoluble so it rides albumin. In the hepatocyte UGT1A1 adds 1-2 glucuronic acids → conjugated bilirubin (CB), water-soluble, which MRP2 pumps into bile. Bonfil: UGT1A1 is the enzyme 'you have to remember.'", "2. UCB vs CB — the property table that predicts the labs. UCB = water-insoluble, albumin-bound, toxic, NOT in urine. CB = water-soluble, non-toxic, in urine. Direct = CB; indirect = UCB. Numbers: normal total 0.2-1.2 mg/dL (>1.2 = hyperbilirubinemia), direct ≤0.3; scleral icterus > 2-3, skin yellowing > 4-5 mg/dL (sclera before skin).", "3. The four-cause framework splits the hyperbilirubinemias. Four general causes. First three raise UNCONJUGATED bilirubin: (1) increased production (hemolysis, ineffective erythropoiesis), (2) decreased hepatic uptake (viral hepatitis; rifampin, probenecid), (3) impaired conjugation (neonatal, Gilbert, Crigler-Najjar). The fourth, (4) impaired canalicular transport of CONJUGATED bilirubin, raises CONJUGATED bilirubin (Dubin-Johnson, Rotor).", "4. Five hereditary syndromes: three unconjugated, two conjugated. Sort by conjugation. UNCONJUGATED (UGT1A1): Gilbert (promoter A[TA]7, ~10-35% enzyme, benign), Crigler-Najjar II (partial), Crigler-Najjar I (near-absent → kernicterus, fatal at birth). CONJUGATED (transport): Dubin-Johnson (ABCC2/MRP2 efflux, black liver), Rotor (SLCO1B1/1B3 → OATP-1B1/1B3 reuptake, no pigment). UGT1A1 disorders are autosomal recessive.", "5. Crigler-Najjar I vs II, and why phenobarbital matters. Both CN types are autosomal recessive coding-region UGT1A1 mutations. Type I = near-complete absence → severe jaundice, kernicterus, fatal around birth. Type II = partial activity → milder, kernicterus uncommon. Induction logic: agents that induce residual UGT1A1 help the partial states (type II, Gilbert) but cannot rescue enzyme-absent type I.", "6. Dubin-Johnson is the black liver; Rotor is its pigment-free twin. Dubin-Johnson = ABCC2 → non-functional MRP2 canalicular efflux; CB backs up, shunted to blood via MRP3 (basolateral). Liver grossly black (dark-brown melanin-like granules in centrilobular hepatocytes/Kupffer cells), ~50% very dark urine, common in Iranian/Iraqi/Moroccan Jews (~1 in 1,300). Rotor = same conjugated picture but NO pigment (OATP-1B1/1B3 reuptake defect).", "7. Kernicterus = unconjugated bilirubin in the basal ganglia. Because UCB is lipid-soluble, a high unconjugated load (untreated neonatal jaundice, Crigler-Najjar I) crosses into the brain and collects in the basal ganglia → kernicterus, irreversible brain damage, death. Newborn UGT1A1 is only ~1% of adult, reaching adult levels ~2 weeks after birth; phototherapy converts UCB to a more water-soluble form to head this off.", "8. Cholestasis = the ALP/GGT obstruction picture, with feathery degeneration. Cholestasis = reduced/stopped bile flow, intrahepatic (impaired secretion) or extrahepatic (large-duct; adult #1 = CBD gallstones). Labs: ↑ALP (detergent action of retained bile salts) + ↑GGT. Morphology (both): feathery degeneration, bile plugs in dilated canaliculi, apoptotic hepatocytes; extrahepatic adds ductular reaction + bile lakes. ICP = ABCB4/MDR3, 3rd-trimester palm/sole pruritus, ↑bile acids.", "Heme oxygenase byproducts = CO, Fe2+, biliverdin (green)", "UGT1A1*28 allele = Gilbert, A[TA]7 promoter, reduced transcription", "Pigment (bilirubin) gallstones = chronic hemolysis, ineffective erythropoiesis, increased UCB", "Dubin-Johnson demographics = Iranian/Iraqi/Moroccan Jews, 1 in 1,300, unmasked by OCPs/pregnancy", "MRP3 (basolateral) = Dubin-Johnson, shunts CB to blood, sinusoidal", "Mallory-Denk bodies = alcoholic steatohepatitis, ropy cytokeratin, NOT cholestasis", "Councilman bodies = viral hepatitis, apoptotic hepatocyte, distractor", "Ground-glass hepatocytes = HBsAg, chronic hep B, not bile droplets", "Infant/child biliary obstruction = biliary atresia, cystic fibrosis, NOT CBD stone", "Decreased hepatic uptake drugs = rifampin, probenecid, unconjugated", "Beta-glucuronidase = gut deconjugation, ~20% CB recycled, enterohepatic", "Phototherapy = neonatal jaundice, converts UCB water-soluble, prevents kernicterus", "Skin xanthomas = dermal cholesterol, chronic cholestasis, extrahepatic", "Cholestasis constrictor drugs = chlorpromazine, metformin, cyclosporin A, RhoA/Rho-kinase", "Splenic macrophages = senescent RBCs ~120 days, ~80% bilirubin source", "Crigler-Najjar type II rescue = phenobarbital induces residual UGT1A1, type I cannot"], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Discuss the pathophysiology of jaundice", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Jaundice (icterus) is the accumulation of unconjugated or conjugated bilirubin (UCB or CB) in tissues — chiefly skin, sclera, and mucous membranes — giving them a golden-yellow color. Bonfil built the whole lecture on one idea: 'whenever we talk about jaundice, bilirubin is going to take an important role.' Master the bilirubin pathway and every jaundice becomes the step that broke. Know the numbers first: normal total bilirubin is 0.2-1.2 mg/dL (above 1.2 = hyperbilirubinemia), normal direct (conjugated) is ≤0.3 mg/dL; clinically, scleral icterus appears > 2-3 mg/dL and skin yellowing > 4-5 mg/dL."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE PATHWAY — ENZYME BY ENZYME. About 80% of bilirubin comes from senescent RBCs (~120-day lifespan) cleared by splenic macrophages. Hemoglobin splits into globin and heme; heme oxygenase opens heme to biliverdin (releasing Fe2+ and CO), and biliverdin reductase makes unconjugated bilirubin. UCB is water-insoluble, so it travels bound to albumin. At the liver it dissociates, enters the hepatocyte, binds glutathione-S-transferases (GSTs), and is conjugated by UGT1A1 (UDP-glucuronosyltransferase 1A1) with 1-2 glucuronic acids into water-soluble conjugated bilirubin. MRP2 then pumps CB across the canalicular membrane into bile. In the gut, most CB is excreted in feces; ~20% is deconjugated by β-glucuronidase and reabsorbed."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Pathway: heme →(heme oxygenase) biliverdin →(biliverdin reductase) UCB → albumin → UGT1A1 → CB → MRP2 into bile."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "UCB = insoluble, albumin-bound, toxic, not in urine; CB = soluble, non-toxic, in urine. Direct=CB, indirect=UCB."}, {"t": "p", "x": "FOUR GENERAL CAUSES, THEN THE UNCONJUGATED (UGT1A1) GROUP. Bonfil's framework reads straight off the pathway. Three causes raise UNCONJUGATED bilirubin: (1) increased production of free bilirubin (extravascular hemolytic anemia, ineffective erythropoiesis — UGT normal but overwhelmed, with increased risk of pigment gallstones); (2) decreased hepatic uptake (generalized liver-cell injury — viral hepatitis; drugs like rifampin, probenecid that interfere with membrane carriers); and (3) impaired conjugation. The fourth — (4) impaired transport of CONJUGATED bilirubin into the canaliculi — raises CONJUGATED bilirubin. Causes 3 and 4 house the hereditary syndromes."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cause 3 is the UGT1A1 group. Physiologic neonatal jaundice hits ~70% of newborns: UGT is only ~1% of adult, reaching adult levels ~2 weeks after birth; phototherapy converts UCB to a more soluble form. If UGT stays inactive, lipid-soluble UCB collects in the basal ganglia → kernicterus (irreversible brain damage) → death. Gilbert syndrome (prevalence 3-7%) is the common, benign one: most cases are homozygous for an extra TA in the UGT1A1 promoter TATA-box (A[TA]7TAA vs A[TA]6TAA, the UGT1A1*28 allele) → ~10-35% enzyme, autosomal recessive; a rare Asian heterozygous coding missense is autosomal dominant. Crigler-Najjar = coding-region UGT1A1 mutations, both autosomal recessive: type I = near-absent enzyme, severe jaundice, kernicterus, fatal around birth; type II = partial activity, milder."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "First three (Gilbert, CN-II, CN-I) = unconjugated, UGT1A1 defect, autosomal recessive."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Kernicterus = lipid-soluble UCB in basal ganglia, irreversible; newborn UGT ~1% of adult, normal ~2 wks."}, {"t": "p", "x": "IMPAIRED CB TRANSPORT (CONJUGATED). Here UGT1A1 works fine, so bilirubin is conjugated but can't move correctly. Dubin-Johnson syndrome = an ABCC2 mutation giving a non-functional MRP2 canalicular efflux pump; CB backs up and is shunted to blood via MRP3 (basolateral), giving plasma bilirubin ~2-5 mg/dL. The liver is grossly black from dark-brown melanin-like granules in centrilobular hepatocytes/Kupffer cells; ~50% pass very dark urine; it is common in Iranian/Iraqi/Moroccan Jews (~1 in 1,300) and often surfaces with oral contraceptives or pregnancy. Rotor syndrome shares the conjugated picture but has NO liver pigmentation: inactivating SLCO1B1/SLCO1B3 mutations disable OATP-1B1/1B3, the transporters that re-take up CB from blood → conjugated hyperbilirubinemia. Both are benign and autosomal recessive."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Dubin-Johnson: conjugated, ABCC2/MRP2 efflux defect, black liver, dark urine, CB via MRP3."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Rotor: conjugated, SLCO1B1/1B3 → OATP-1B1/1B3 re-uptake defect, NO pigment, benign."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Walk the pathway: heme oxygenase → biliverdin reductase → UCB-albumin → UGT1A1 → CB → MRP2. The four causes and five syndromes are just named breaks in that chain — first three syndromes unconjugated (UGT1A1), last two conjugated (MRP2 / OATP)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Dubin-Johnson vs Rotor: both conjugated and benign, but Dubin-Johnson has a black liver (MRP2/ABCC2 efflux defect) while Rotor has no pigment (OATP-1B1/1B3 re-uptake defect). The black pigment is the discriminator."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "UCB never appears in urine (albumin-bound, insoluble); CB does (water-soluble). So conjugated hyperbilirubinemias darken the urine; unconjugated ones do not."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Bonfil's flagged enzyme: UGT1A1 — 'you have to remember' it. Every unconjugated hereditary syndrome (Gilbert, CN-I, CN-II) is a UGT1A1 defect; the conjugated pair is not."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Bonfil said UGT1A1 is the one enzyme 'you have to remember.' Walk bilirubin from heme to bile naming each enzyme/transporter, then use that pathway to organize the four general causes of jaundice and sort the five hereditary syndromes by conjugation."}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Discuss the pathophysiology of cholestasis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Cholestasis is a condition in which bile flow is markedly reduced or stopped, from either impaired hepatocyte secretion of bile or obstruction anywhere from the liver to the Ampulla of Vater. It splits two ways anatomically: intrahepatic cholestasis (within the parenchyma — impaired secretion of bile into canaliculi, or blockage of intrahepatic ducts) and extrahepatic cholestasis (the biliary tree — blockage of large ducts outside the liver). Intrahepatic causes are a wide spectrum — drugs (contraceptive pills, anabolic steroids), primary sclerosing cholangitis, infections, sepsis — while extrahepatic causes are primarily anatomic (the most common adult cause is a gallstone in the common bile duct; in infants/children, cystic fibrosis and biliary atresia)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cholestasis = bile flow reduced/stopped (impaired secretion OR obstruction); intrahepatic vs extrahepatic."}, {"t": "p", "x": "INTRAHEPATIC CHOLESTASIS OF PREGNANCY (ICP). Bonfil singled this one out — 'it is very important to diagnose.' It is a rare cholestasis with intense pruritus, worse on the palms and soles, in the last trimester, that disappears after delivery. The molecular lesion is a mutation in ABCB4, encoding MDR3, a canalicular phospholipid translocator; without available phospholipids to bind bile acids, toxic bile acids build up. High gonadal and placental hormones are causal cofactors. Morphology = centrilobular cholestasis; diagnosis is confirmed by very high total bile acid. It matters because it raises fetal morbidity and mortality, fetal distress, and premature labor."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ICP = ABCB4/MDR3, 3rd-trimester pruritus of palms/soles, resolves post-delivery; Dx by ↑ total bile acid."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THREE PROPOSED CANALICULAR MECHANISMS. Bile is normally propelled along canaliculi by a peristaltic-like activity, and Bonfil gave three ways drugs break that. (1) Altered contractility: constrictors (chlorpromazine, metformin, cyclosporin A) activate the RhoA/Rho-kinase pathway → increased myosin light-chain phosphorylation → constriction of the canaliculi. (2) Canalicular plasma-membrane damage: the membrane is the site of Na+ (thus fluid) secretion into bile; drugs that disturb it decrease Na+/K+-ATPase activity and bile flow. (3) Altered canalicular transporters: agents like estrogens inhibit the canalicular export pump, causing back-diffusion of cholic acid, cholesterol, and conjugated bilirubin into blood."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Three mechanisms: RhoA/Rho-kinase contractility · ↓Na+/K+-ATPase membrane damage · estrogen transporter inhibition."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Cholestasis = reduced/stopped bile flow, intrahepatic (secretion) vs extrahepatic (obstruction; adult #1 = CBD gallstone). Three drug mechanisms hit the canaliculus: contractility (RhoA/Rho-kinase), membrane (Na+/K+-ATPase), transporter (estrogens)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "ICP = ABCB4/MDR3 phospholipid translocator. Third-trimester pruritus on palms and soles, gone after delivery, confirmed by very high total bile acids — diagnose it for the fetus, not the mother."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Estrogens are the cholestasis through-line: oral contraceptives/pregnancy can inhibit the canalicular export pump, and Dubin-Johnson is often first unmasked in the same settings."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Cholestasis is bile that won't flow. Define it, split it into its two anatomic classes, give the gene/protein and the clinical picture of intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy, and name the three proposed canalicular mechanisms."}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Discuss the etiological factors, morphologic changes and effects of jaundice", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. This objective is the synthesis LO — the etiology, morphology, and effects of the jaundice/cholestasis picture. A note on sourcing: the deck's morphology slides are cholestasis morphology, so that is where the 'morphologic changes' come from; jaundice's own morphology is simpler — tissue bilirubin staining (the yellow sclera/skin) and, at the extreme, kernicterus (UCB in the basal ganglia). The etiologic factors are the four general causes from 47.1 plus the cholestatic obstructions of 47.2; the effects are the clinical and laboratory consequences below."}, {"t": "p", "x": "MORPHOLOGY — SHARED FEATURES. In both obstructive and non-obstructive cholestasis the histology shows: (1) feathery degeneration — enlarged hepatocytes with intracytoplasmic bile-pigment droplets giving a foamy appearance; (2) characteristic bile plugs in dilated bile canaliculi; (3) apoptotic hepatocytes (bile is toxic to hepatocytes); and (4) rupture of canaliculi with extravasated bile phagocytosed by Kupffer cells. These four are the recognizable core of the cholestasis biopsy."}, {"t": "p", "x": "MORPHOLOGY — EXTRAHEPATIC EXTRAS. When the block is extrahepatic (obstructive), bile pigment accumulates in the parenchyma with dilated canaliculi and feathery degeneration, and the ducts react: distended ductules with a ductular proliferative reaction at the portal-parenchymal interface, with edema and periductular neutrophils. Cholestasis reaches the lobule periphery, dilated ducts/ductules may rupture to form bile lakes (extravasated pools of bile) ringed by necrotic hepatocytes, and prolonged obstruction causes periportal fibrosis and eventually cirrhosis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Morphology (both): feathery degeneration + bile plugs in dilated canaliculi + apoptotic hepatocytes + Kupffer phagocytosis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Extrahepatic adds ductular reaction (periductular neutrophils) + bile lakes → periportal fibrosis → cirrhosis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "EFFECTS — CLINICAL AND LAB. Integrate the bedside picture: jaundice from hyperbilirubinemia; pruritus from retained bile salts deposited in skin; skin xanthomas (focal dermal cholesterol — more characteristic of extrahepatic disease); and intestinal malabsorption because bile salts never reach the gut → pale stools (no fecal bile pigment) and steatorrhea (fat in stool). The laboratory signature of cholestasis is elevated alkaline phosphatase (ALP) — released by the detergent action of retained bile salts on hepatocyte membranes — together with elevated GGT, which confirms the hepatobiliary source."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Effects: jaundice, pruritus (bile salts in skin), xanthomas, pale stools + steatorrhea; labs ↑ALP + ↑GGT."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Cholestasis morphology = feathery degeneration + bile plugs + apoptotic hepatocytes (both types); extrahepatic adds ductular reaction + bile lakes → fibrosis/cirrhosis. Labs = ↑ALP + ↑GGT."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Intrahepatic vs extrahepatic morphology: feathery degeneration and bile plugs are in both; the ductular proliferative reaction, periductular neutrophils, and bile lakes point to extrahepatic obstruction."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Pale stools + steatorrhea + xanthomas all trace to one fact — bile (salts) never reaching the gut and instead depositing in skin; ALP rises by the detergent action of retained bile salts, not by bile-duct cells alone."}, {"t": "q", "x": "The 'morphologic changes' for this objective come from the cholestasis-morphology slides. Name the histologic features shared by all cholestasis, the extra features of extrahepatic obstruction, the lab pattern, and the clinical effects you would integrate at the bedside."}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Calling UCB the form that shows up in urine. Unconjugated bilirubin is NEVER in urine — it is water-insoluble and albumin-bound. Only conjugated (water-soluble) bilirubin spills into urine, so dark urine points to a conjugated process (e.g., Dubin-Johnson), not an unconjugated one."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Swapping the Dubin-Johnson and Rotor defects. Dubin-Johnson = ABCC2 / non-functional MRP2 canalicular efflux (→ black liver). Rotor = SLCO1B1/1B3 / OATP-1B1/1B3 re-uptake of CB from blood (→ NO pigment). Black pigment vs no pigment is the clean split — don't flip the transporters."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Assuming kernicterus is a conjugated-bilirubin injury. Kernicterus is caused by UNCONJUGATED bilirubin — it is lipid-soluble, so it crosses into the basal ganglia. It is the danger of neonatal jaundice and Crigler-Najjar type I, not of the conjugated (Dubin-Johnson/Rotor) syndromes."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Sourcing 47.3 'morphology of jaundice' from a jaundice-specific slide. The deck's morphology section is cholestasis morphology (feathery degeneration, bile plugs, bile lakes, ductular reaction). That is the intended source for 'morphologic changes.' Jaundice's own morphology is just tissue bilirubin staining + kernicterus — don't invent a separate slide."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Putting the wrong drug in the wrong cholestasis mechanism. Three mechanisms, three handles: constrictors (chlorpromazine, cyclosporin A) → RhoA/Rho-kinase canalicular constriction; membrane-disturbing drugs → ↓ Na+/K+-ATPase; estrogens → canalicular export-pump inhibition. Don't blur them together."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. The pathway names every jaundice. Heme oxygenase → biliverdin reductase → UCB-albumin → UGT1A1 → CB → MRP2. Find the broken step and you have the diagnosis: production/uptake/conjugation = unconjugated; canalicular transport = conjugated."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. The thresholds. Normal total bilirubin 0.2-1.2 mg/dL (direct ≤0.3). Scleral icterus > 2-3 mg/dL; skin yellowing > 4-5 mg/dL. Sclera before skin."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. The five syndromes in one line. Unconjugated (UGT1A1): Gilbert (promoter A[TA]7, benign), CN-II (partial), CN-I (absent → kernicterus, fatal). Conjugated (transport): Dubin-Johnson (MRP2, black) and Rotor (OATP, no pigment)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. Cholestasis is the ALP/GGT picture. Bile flow stopped → ↑ALP + ↑GGT, feathery degeneration + bile plugs on biopsy, and pruritus/xanthomas/pale stools/steatorrhea at the bedside. ICP = ABCB4/MDR3, palms/soles, 3rd trimester."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. Black liver = Dubin-Johnson; basal ganglia = kernicterus. Two image hooks to anchor: a grossly black liver with melanin-like granules is Dubin-Johnson (conjugated, MRP2); UCB in the basal ganglia is kernicterus (unconjugated, irreversible)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Bilirubin metabolism is the spine of the jaundice run. The full UGT1A1 cascade lives here in 47.1 — it was introduced as background in Lec 43 (jaundice within hepatic failure) and is picked up again in Lec 48 (direct vs indirect bilirubin as a function test). 47 is the mechanistic home; 48 is the interpretive home."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — The hereditary-hyperbilirubinemia matrix overlaps Lec 42. Lec 42 (Machini) taught the same five syndromes from the circulatory-disorders angle; Bonfil reframes them here by conjugation and transporter. Reconcile the two: both call the UGT1A1 trio unconjugated and Dubin-Johnson/Rotor conjugated — 47's slide adds the MRP3 basolateral shunt and OATP re-uptake transporter detail."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Cholestasis labs hand off to Lec 48. The ↑ALP + ↑GGT mechanism is established here in 47.2/47.3 (retained bile salts' detergent action); Lec 48 is the quantitative/interpretive home (GGT and 5'-nucleotidase to confirm a hepatobiliary source, cholestatic vs hepatocellular patterns)."}]}]}, "48": {"prof": "Dr. Jeanette Rodriguez", "tldr": "Enzymes (AST/ALT, alk phos, GGT) report INJURY; albumin, PT/INR, bilirubin report FUNCTION - so a normal AST/ALT never proves a healthy liver. Read the pattern and magnitude (AST:ALT >= 2:1 = alcohol); a rising INR calls acute failure.", "mustKnows": ["1. 'True' liver function tests are the SYNTHETIC markers, not the enzymes. 'Liver function tests' is a misnomer — banner: 'Health ≠ Function.' The enzymes (aminotransferases, alkaline phosphatase) mark INJURY: damaged hepatocytes/bile-duct cells leak them into serum, yet an injured liver can still function. The genuine FUNCTION tests are the liver's synthetic/metabolic products — albumin, PT/INR, bilirubin: it makes albumin and clotting factors and conjugates bilirubin.", "2. Normal AST/ALT does NOT mean a healthy or functioning liver. A board-AND-rotation paradox: normal aminotransferases do not guarantee a healthy liver. In end-stage cirrhosis or non-recovering acute liver failure, too few hepatocytes remain to leak, so AST/ALT normalize. Rodriguez's case: a jaundiced, edematous woman told she had no cirrhosis on normal transaminases; biopsy showed end-stage cirrhosis, she died months later. Read the whole patient, not one normal lab.", "3. ALT is more liver-specific; AST lives in muscle too and in the mitochondria. ALT is in HIGHEST concentration in the liver, so it is more specific for liver pathology (mnemonic: L for liver). AST is also abundant in cardiac and skeletal muscle, kidney, brain, pancreas, lung, leukocytes, and erythrocytes — it was even used to detect MIs before troponin. Subcellular twist: both are cytosolic, but AST is the ONLY one also in the MITOCHONDRIAL MATRIX.", "4. GGT & 5'-nucleotidase confirm a HEPATOBILIARY source for a high alkaline phosphatase. Alk phos (ALP) rises in cholestasis but ALSO from bone, pregnancy, and growing infants. To prove a high ALP is liver/bile-duct, add GGT or 5'-nucleotidase — neither is affected by bone disease, so a co-elevation confirms hepatobiliary origin. In pregnancy use GGT (5'-NT's pregnancy effect is unknown); for bone disease either works. A very high GGT is 'particularly board relevant' for alcoholic liver disease.", "5. AST:ALT ≥ 2:1 (and/or high GGT) = ALCOHOLIC liver disease. The most board-tested ratio of the lecture: an AST:ALT ≥ 2:1, often with a markedly elevated GGT, points to alcoholic liver disease — Rodriguez: 'they love to ask this on boards in some tricky way.' Contrast the metabolic/viral fatty livers, where ALT tends to run higher than AST. The ratio is the recall handle that separates alcohol from the other hepatocellular causes.", "6. The magnitude ladder: x5 / x25 / x50 of the upper limit. Within the hepatocellular pattern, the AST/ALT magnitude names the cause. MASH/MASLD (metabolic, mildest) = < 5x ULN. Acute viral or toxin (e.g. acetaminophen) = > 25x (into the thousands). Ischemic hepatitis (worst, 'the liver is dying') = > 50x ULN plus an elevated LDH. Acetaminophen is hepatotoxic; NSAIDs are nephrotoxic.", "7. Elevated INR/PT is the KEY feature of ACUTE LIVER FAILURE. Acute liver failure = rapid deterioration causing coagulopathy in a patient without cirrhosis/pre-existing liver disease, illness < 26 weeks (chronic = > 26 weeks). The best indicator is an elevated INR/PT — fewer clotting factors are made, so clotting takes longer. Acute hepatic injury (not failure) keeps a NORMAL INR/PT. Whatever AST/ALT/ALP do, the INR declares failure.", "8. The patterns: hepatocellular vs cholestatic (plus isolated-bili and infiltrative). Four patterns. Hepatocellular = aminotransferases >> alk phos (hepatocytes). Cholestatic = alk phos >> aminotransferases (bile ducts). Isolated hyperbilirubinemia = isolated bilirubin, normal enzymes (the congenital hyperbilirubinemias). Infiltrative = a subtype of cholestatic (tumor): very high ALP, near-normal aminotransferases. Rodriguez wants hepatocellular-vs-cholestatic cold.", "Ischemic hepatitis (shock liver) = AST/ALT >50x ULN, elevated LDH, hypoperfusion/shock", "AST = SGOT, ALT = SGPT = aspartate vs alanine aminotransferase, transaminase aliases", "EBV / CMV hepatitis = mononucleosis, beyond A-E viruses, bumped transaminases", "GGT = gamma-glutamyl transfer, very high = alcohol, not bone/pregnancy", "Indirect (unconjugated) hyperbilirubinemia = overproduction, impaired uptake, impaired conjugation", "Direct (conjugated) hyperbilirubinemia = decreased excretion into bile ductules", "Acetaminophen (Tylenol) = hepatotoxic, AST/ALT >25x, into the thousands", "NSAIDs = nephrotoxic not hepatotoxic, board contrast vs Tylenol", "Isolated hyperbilirubinemia = bilirubin only, normal AST/ALT, normal ALP, congenital", "Infiltrative pattern = cholestatic subtype, very high ALP, near-normal transaminases, tumor", "MASH / MASLD = formerly NASH/NAFLD, ALT>=AST, <5x ULN", "5'-nucleotidase = confirms hepatobiliary ALP, not bone, pregnancy effect unknown", "Acute liver failure definition = coagulopathy, no cirrhosis, illness <26 weeks", "AST mitochondrial release = alcohol, mitochondrial matrix injury, drives AST:ALT >=2:1", "Alkaline phosphatase in cholestasis = ~4x ULN, bile-duct obstruction, biliary epithelium", "Low albumin = slow turnover, chronic liver disease, decreased synthesis"], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Define 'true' liver function tests.", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Rodriguez frames the whole lecture around a naming problem. The panel everyone calls liver function tests (LFTs) has five 'true LFT' components: serum aminotransferases (AST/ALT), alkaline phosphatase, serum bilirubin, serum albumin, and PT/INR. But the name is a misnomer — most of these do not actually test function. The slide banner spells it out: 'Health ≠ Function.'"}, {"t": "p", "x": "INJURY MARKERS VS FUNCTION MARKERS. The slide deliberately sorts the five into two boxes. The enzymes — aminotransferases and alkaline phosphatase — are markers of LIVER INJURY: they sit inside hepatocytes and bile-duct cells, and when those tissues are damaged the enzymes leak into the serum. An injured liver, though, can still function. The genuine function tests are the ones that report the liver's synthetic and metabolic work — serum albumin, PT/INR, and serum bilirubin. Albumin and the clotting factors behind PT/INR are made by the liver; bilirubin is processed/conjugated by it. Bilirubin straddles both boxes — it reflects injury AND function — but albumin and PT/INR are pure function."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Enzymes (AST/ALT, alk phos) = injury; albumin, PT/INR, bilirubin = function. Health ≠ Function."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHY PT AND INR ARE LISTED TOGETHER. Rodriguez's in-slide review question: PT (prothrombin time) measures clotting through the extrinsic and common pathways in seconds, but the normal range in seconds differs lab to lab by reagent. INR standardizes it — the patient's PT over a normal-range PT, raised to a sensitivity index — giving a single number (1.0, 1.1, 1.2...) that is comparable across labs. They travel together because INR is just the standardized form of PT."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PT = clotting time (extrinsic + common pathway, seconds, lab-variable); INR = standardized PT, comparable across labs."}, {"t": "key", "x": "'Liver function tests' is a misnomer: AST/ALT and alkaline phosphatase mark INJURY; the true FUNCTION tests are albumin, PT/INR, and bilirubin. Health ≠ Function."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "An injured liver (leaking enzymes) can still be functioning; and a failing liver can have normal enzymes. Injury and function are different axes — that is the whole point of the slide."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Bilirubin is the one component that reports both injury and function; albumin and PT/INR are the purest function markers."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Rodriguez opened by calling 'liver function tests' a misnomer and put up the banner 'Health does not equal Function.' Which of the five LFT components actually test FUNCTION, which test INJURY, and what does the banner mean?"}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe the functions of selected liver enzymes, such as aminotransferase and alkaline phosphatase.", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "AMINOTRANSFERASES (AST & ALT) — THE BREAD AND BUTTER. The aminotransferases (older term: transaminases) transfer the alpha-amino group of alanine or aspartate. ALT (alanine aminotransferase, a.k.a. SGPT) and AST (aspartate aminotransferase, a.k.a. SGOT) both report hepatocellular injury/inflammation — they leak when hepatocytes die. Both are useful, but ALT is more specific for liver pathology. Why? Location. ALT is present in the highest concentration in the liver (mnemonic: L for liver). AST, by contrast, is also abundant in cardiac muscle, skeletal muscle, kidney, brain, pancreas, lung, leukocytes, and erythrocytes — so much so that AST was used to detect MIs before troponin. A subcellular pearl Rodriguez flags: both enzymes are cytosolic, but AST is the ONLY one also found in the MITOCHONDRIAL MATRIX."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ALKALINE PHOSPHATASE (ALP) — THE CHOLESTASIS ENZYME. ALP catalyzes the hydrolysis of organic phosphate esters and physiologically helps downregulate the secretory activity of the intrahepatic biliary epithelium (controlling bile flow). It lives in liver, bone, and intestine. Because its hepatic home is the bile-duct system, ALP is the enzyme for cholestatic disease — any condition where bile is not flowing (choledocholithiasis, tumor obstruction, post-procedure scarring, inflammatory hepatitis affecting the ducts, infiltrative disease). In cholestasis ALP is often elevated about 4x the upper limit. The catch: ALP also rises from bone (Paget, rickets/osteomalacia, bony tumors, parathyroid disease, vitamin-D deficiency), from pregnancy (3rd trimester), and in growing infants/toddlers (bone remodeling) — so an isolated ALP is ambiguous about its source."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ALT = highest in liver -> most liver-specific; AST also in cardiac/skeletal muscle and the only one in the mitochondrial matrix."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Alk phos = cholestasis enzyme, ~4x ULN in cholestasis; but also from bone, pregnancy, growing infants."}, {"t": "p", "x": "GGT & 5'-NUCLEOTIDASE — CONFIRM THE HEPATOBILIARY SOURCE. This is the high-yield use Rodriguez calls 'a very important concept.' When alkaline phosphatase is high and you don't know whether it is from liver, bone, or pregnancy, order GGT (gamma-glutamyl transpeptidase) or 5'-nucleotidase. Neither is affected by bone disease, so a co-elevation confirms the ALP is of hepatobiliary origin. GGT (which transfers the gamma-glutamyl group of glutathione) is mainly in the liver; 5'-nucleotidase (hydrolyzes nucleotides; sits on the bile-canalicular and sinusoidal membranes) is also not affected by bone. Decision rule: in a pregnant patient use GGT (5'-NT's pregnancy behavior is unknown); for bone disease, either works. And a very high GGT is 'particularly board relevant' for alcoholic liver disease."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "High alk phos, unclear source -> add GGT or 5'-NT (neither affected by bone) to confirm hepatobiliary origin; pregnancy = GGT."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Very high GGT = 'particularly board relevant' for alcoholic liver disease."}, {"t": "key", "x": "ALT = liver-specific hepatocellular injury; AST also in muscle (+ mitochondrial matrix). Alkaline phosphatase = cholestasis (~4x ULN); GGT / 5'-nucleotidase confirm a hepatobiliary source because neither rises with bone disease."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Don't read a high alkaline phosphatase as automatically 'liver' — it also comes from bone, pregnancy, and growing infants. The GGT/5'-NT co-test is what proves the liver."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "AST in the mitochondrial matrix 'has to do with something later' — it underlies why heavy mitochondrial injury (e.g., alcohol) pushes AST up relative to ALT (the AST:ALT ≥ 2:1 of alcoholic disease)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Pregnant patient with right-upper-quadrant pain + high ALP? Use GGT — 5'-NT's behavior in pregnancy is unknown."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Rodriguez calls these enzymes 'your bread and butter' and says they are all board-relevant. For the aminotransferases, alkaline phosphatase, GGT, and 5'-nucleotidase: what does each detect, where does each live, why is ALT more liver-specific than AST, and how do GGT/5'-NT rescue an ambiguous alkaline phosphatase?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Describe diseases associated with the elevation of liver enzymes.", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "CAUSES OF AMINOTRANSFERASE ELEVATION. Essentially anything that harms the liver raises AST/ALT: acetaminophen toxicity (acetaminophen is hepatotoxic; NSAIDs are nephrotoxic), alcoholic hepatitis, MASH (metabolic dysfunction-associated steatohepatitis, formerly NASH), ischemic hepatitis, acute viral hepatitis (A-E, plus HSV, VZV, EBV, CMV — EBV causes mono and can bump LFTs), autoimmune hepatitis, malignancy (breast, small-cell lung, lymphoma, melanoma, myeloma), pre-eclampsia/eclampsia, and muscular disorders (recall AST lives in skeletal muscle, so muscular dystrophy can raise AST). Hemolysis can raise AST too (erythrocytes)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Aminotransferase elevators: acetaminophen, alcohol, MASH, ischemic, viral (incl. EBV/CMV), autoimmune, malignancy, (pre)eclampsia, muscle."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ALCOHOL RATIO — AST:ALT ≥ 2:1. Within the hepatocellular pattern, the way to flag alcoholic liver disease is the AST:ALT ratio ≥ 2:1, usually with a markedly elevated GGT. Rodriguez stresses this is heavily tested: 'they love to ask this on boards in some tricky way.' Contrast the metabolic/viral fatty livers, where ALT tends to exceed AST."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE MAGNITUDE LADDER — x5 / x25 / x50. Rodriguez calls the hepatocellular chart 'very, very important' and turns the magnitude of the AST/ALT rise into the diagnosis. Using a worked upper limit of ~50 U/L: MASH/MASLD (the mildest) = < 5x (so < ~250, often 100-150). Acute viral or toxin-related hepatitis (e.g., acetaminophen) = > 25x (so > ~1,250 — into the thousands). Ischemic hepatitis (the worst — 'no flow, the liver is dying') = > 50x (so > ~2,500) plus an elevated LDH (the differentiating clue). Alcoholic disease 'varies,' but is anchored by the 2:1 ratio + high GGT rather than by raw magnitude."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Hepatocellular cause / AST & ALT vs upper limit / Defining clue): MASH / MASLD (metabolic, mildest) — < 5x ULN · mild rise; ex-NASH/NAFLD naming ; Acute viral OR toxin (acetaminophen) — > 25x ULN · into the thousands ; Ischemic hepatitis (worst) — > 50x ULN · elevated LDH ; Alcoholic liver disease — varies · AST:ALT ≥ 2:1 and/or high GGT"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Ladder: MASH < 5x, viral/toxin (acetaminophen) > 25x, ischemic > 50x + ↑LDH; alcohol = AST:ALT ≥ 2:1."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Acetaminophen = hepatotoxic; NSAIDs = nephrotoxic — a one-line board contrast."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Read the hepatocellular cause off the magnitude: MASH < 5x, acute viral/toxin > 25x, ischemic > 50x with high LDH; and AST:ALT ≥ 2:1 (+ high GGT) = alcohol ('they love to ask this on boards')."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Ischemic hepatitis is the giveaway pair: aminotransferases > 50x the upper limit AND an elevated LDH — because the ischemic, anaerobic tissue dumps LDH."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Naming: MASH = formerly NASH; the disease spectrum MASLD = formerly NAFLD. Don't swap the abbreviations or conflate them with alcoholic disease."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "A young patient with mono (EBV) and bumped LFTs is acute viral hepatitis — viruses beyond A-E (EBV, CMV, HSV, VZV) raise aminotransferases."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Rodriguez says the magnitude of the aminotransferase rise (and the AST:ALT ratio) 'tells you the diagnosis,' and that boards love it. List the causes of aminotransferase elevation, give the alcohol ratio, and walk the x5/x25/x50 ladder with the disease at each rung and the extra clue for the top rung."}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe bilirubin, prothrombin time and albumin.", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "BILIRUBIN — DIRECT VS INDIRECT. Bilirubin is the yellow product of heme catabolism, excreted in bile and urine. Three tests: total, direct, and indirect. Direct = CONJUGATED (direct hyperbilirubinemia); indirect = UNCONJUGATED (indirect hyperbilirubinemia). Rodriguez's memory hook: bilirubin comes in unconjugated, and once conjugated it goes 'directly' out into the biliary/gut system. Indirect (unconjugated) hyperbilirubinemia arises from overproduction, impaired uptake, or impaired conjugation; direct (conjugated) hyperbilirubinemia from decreased excretion into the bile ductules. Bilirubin is the component that straddles both axes — it reflects liver function AND liver injury, in acute or chronic disease. (Full metabolism is detailed in the bilirubin/jaundice lecture.)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "ALBUMIN & PT/INR — THE SYNTHETIC PRODUCTS. The liver makes albumin and the coagulation factors behind PT/INR, so both are true function tests. In liver disease albumin DECREASES (the liver makes less) — and because albumin turns over slowly, a low albumin usually means more long-standing (chronic) liver disease. PT/INR INCREASES (fewer clotting factors are synthesized, so it takes longer to clot, and PT measures the time to clot). Neither is usually an isolated abnormality — they travel with other LFT changes. PT/INR can move in acute or chronic disease, which sets up the key acute-failure point in LO 48.5."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Direct = conjugated, indirect = unconjugated. Indirect: overproduction/uptake/conjugation; direct: ↓excretion into ductules."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Liver disease: albumin ↓ (slow turnover -> chronic), PT/INR ↑ (fewer factors -> longer to clot)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Direct = conjugated; indirect = unconjugated. In liver disease albumin falls (chronic) and PT/INR rises (fewer clotting factors). These three are the liver's true function products."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "A low albumin implies a chronic process (slow turnover); a rising INR/PT can be acute and is the marker that flags acute liver failure (LO 48.5)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "PT/INR goes UP (longer to clot), not down — it measures the time to clot, and fewer factors means more time."}, {"t": "q", "x": "These three are the liver's PRODUCTS, the genuine function markers. For bilirubin, give the direct/indirect = conjugated/unconjugated split and the mechanisms of each; for albumin and PT/INR, say which way each moves in liver disease, why, and which tempo of disease each implies."}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Evaluate cases of patients who present with abnormal hepatic tests.", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "THE FOUR PATTERNS. Step one in any abnormal panel is to see which value is disproportionately elevated. HEPATOCELLULAR = aminotransferases >> alkaline phosphatase (hepatocytes more affected; e.g., a transaminase of 2,000 with only a slightly high ALP). CHOLESTATIC = alkaline phosphatase >> aminotransferases (bile ducts more affected; e.g., cholecystitis). ISOLATED HYPERBILIRUBINEMIA = an isolated bilirubin rise with normal aminotransferases AND normal alkaline phosphatase (the congenital hyperbilirubinemias). INFILTRATIVE = a subtype of cholestatic (tumor/infiltrate): very high ALP with near-normal aminotransferases (the hepatocytes are replaced). Each pattern raises BOTH enzymes somewhat — the dominant one names the pattern. Rodriguez wants the hepatocellular-vs-cholestatic split cold."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Pattern / Aminotransferases / Alkaline phosphatase / Bilirubin): Hepatocellular — ↑↑↑ · ↑ (mild) · ± ; Cholestatic — ↑ (mild) · ↑↑↑ · ± ; Isolated hyperbilirubinemia — normal · normal · ↑ ; Infiltrative (subtype of cholestatic) — normal/mild · ↑↑↑ · ±"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Hepatocellular (AST/ALT >> ALP), cholestatic (ALP >> AST/ALT), isolated hyperbilirubinemia (bili only), infiltrative (cholestatic subtype)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ACUTE FAILURE VS ACUTE INJURY — LET THE INR DECIDE. Acute liver failure = rapid deterioration causing coagulopathy in a patient without cirrhosis or pre-existing liver disease, illness < 26 weeks (chronic failure = > 26 weeks). The best indicator is an elevated INR/PT. Acute hepatic injury (not failure) keeps a NORMAL INR/PT. So no matter what the AST/ALT, alkaline phosphatase, or bilirubin are doing, the question 'is this FAILURE?' is answered by the INR — the synthetic, true-function marker."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE CLOSING CASE. A 45-year-old in acute hepatic failure shows falling AST and ALT but rising total bilirubin and lengthening PT/INR. The tempting wrong read (Reasoning 1) is 'transaminases are improving, so the liver is recovering.' The correct read (Reasoning 3) is that falling aminotransferases mean either acute damage has ceased OR the liver is so destroyed that few hepatocytes remain to leak enzyme — and since bilirubin and PT/INR are rising, function is worsening. Therefore this combination predicts a POOR PROGNOSIS, not recovery. It is the bookend to her opening paradox: normal/normalizing enzymes can mark a dying liver, not a healing one."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Elevated INR/PT = best indicator of ACUTE LIVER FAILURE (no cirrhosis, < 26 wk); acute injury keeps a normal INR/PT."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Falling AST/ALT + rising bilirubin + prolonged PT/INR = liver too destroyed to leak enzymes -> poor prognosis (NOT recovery)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Read the pattern (hepatocellular vs cholestatic by which enzyme dominates), then let the INR declare acute failure vs injury. Falling enzymes + rising bilirubin/INR = a dying liver, not a healing one."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Isolated hyperbilirubinemia = bilirubin up with normal aminotransferases AND normal alkaline phosphatase (the congenital hyperbilirubinemias); infiltrative is a subtype of cholestatic (very high ALP, near-normal aminotransferases)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Don't call falling transaminases 'improvement' in a failing liver — paired with a rising bilirubin and INR it signals hepatocyte loss and a poor prognosis."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Rotation question 'is this acute liver failure?' -> answer 'check the INR/PT'; coagulopathy is the defining feature."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Rodriguez says the pattern differentiation is something she 'really, really, really' wants known cold, and she ends on a case. Name the four patterns of abnormal LFTs and what defines each, give the single best discriminator of acute liver FAILURE, and solve the closing case (falling AST/ALT + rising bilirubin + prolonged PT/INR)."}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Treating a normal AST/ALT as proof of a healthy liver. Normal aminotransferases do NOT guarantee a healthy or functioning liver — in end-stage cirrhosis or non-recovering acute liver failure there are too few hepatocytes left to leak enzyme, so AST/ALT normalize. Health ≠ Function. → LO 48.1/48.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Calling AST the liver-specific enzyme. ALT (L for liver) is the more liver-specific aminotransferase; AST is also in cardiac/skeletal muscle (and is the only one in the mitochondrial matrix). → LO 48.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Assuming a high alkaline phosphatase is always hepatobiliary. ALP also comes from bone, pregnancy, and growing infants. Confirm a liver source with GGT or 5'-nucleotidase (neither affected by bone); in pregnancy use GGT. → LO 48.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Swapping the magnitude ladder or the alcohol ratio. MASH < 5x, acute viral/toxin > 25x, ischemic > 50x + ↑LDH; alcohol = AST:ALT ≥ 2:1 (+ high GGT). Don't put alcohol at a huge magnitude or forget the ischemic LDH. → LO 48.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Reversing direct and indirect bilirubin. Direct = conjugated; indirect = unconjugated (comes in unconjugated, goes 'directly' out once conjugated). → LO 48.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Using AST/ALT (or ALP) to declare acute liver FAILURE. Failure is defined by coagulopathy — the best indicator is an elevated INR/PT; acute injury keeps a normal INR/PT. And falling transaminases with a rising bilirubin/INR = a dying liver, not a healing one. → LO 48.5"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"which of the 'LFTs' actually test function?\" → albumin, PT/INR, and bilirubin (the enzymes AST/ALT and alkaline phosphatase mark injury) — Health ≠ Function."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"high alkaline phosphatase — liver or bone?\" → add GGT or 5'-nucleotidase (unaffected by bone); a co-elevation confirms hepatobiliary origin (use GGT if pregnant)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"AST:ALT about 2:1 with a high GGT\" → alcoholic liver disease (\"they love to ask this on boards\")."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"shock patient, AST/ALT > 50x with a high LDH\" → ischemic hepatitis; > 25x → acute viral or toxin (e.g., acetaminophen); < 5x → MASH/MASLD."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"is this acute liver FAILURE or just injury?\" → check the INR/PT — coagulopathy (elevated INR) defines failure; a normal INR means injury only (no cirrhosis, < 26 weeks)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"falling AST/ALT but rising bilirubin and PT/INR in acute failure\" → poor prognosis — the liver is too destroyed to leak enzymes while function worsens, NOT recovery."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — LFT interpretation & the three-bucket panel — this whole lecture is the dedicated home of the LFT framework introduced as background in Lec 43 (LO 43.6: integrity AST/ALT/LDH vs excretory bilirubin/ALP/GGT vs synthetic albumin/PT) and reinforced in Lec 49 (hepatitis vs cholestasis; ALT > AST viral vs AST > ALT alcohol). Read 43.6 → 48 → 49.1 as one LFT thread"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Bilirubin (direct/indirect = conjugated/unconjugated) — the conjugation split touched here in LO 48.4 is the orientation for the full UGT1A1 metabolic cascade and the hereditary hyperbilirubinemias (Gilbert / Crigler-Najjar / Dubin-Johnson / Rotor) detailed in the jaundice/bilirubin lecture (Lec 47); the isolated-hyperbilirubinemia pattern here points straight at those congenital diseases"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — AST:ALT ≥ 2:1 + high GGT for alcohol — this lecture's alcohol fingerprint is the lab readout of the alcoholic-liver pathology in Lec 43 (steatosis → steatohepatitis → cirrhosis; AST > ALT from mitochondrial AST release), and acetaminophen as a hepatotoxin connects to Lec 43's zone-3 acetaminophen #1 acute-failure point"}]}]}, "49": {"prof": "Dr. Matthew Soff", "tldr": "Read HBV serology — HBsAg = infection, anti-HBc fills the window and tells infected from vaccinated, anti-HBs = immunity — then sort the five viruses by route/chronicity; HBV reaches HCC without cirrhosis, HCV ~95% curable.", "mustKnows": ["1. HBsAg = current infection; anti-HBs = immunity; anti-HBc fills the window. Three HBV markers carry the diagnosis. HBsAg (surface antigen), first to rise = current infection; anti-HBs (surface antibody), last to appear = immunity (recovered or vaccinated). Between them lies the serologic window — HBsAg fallen, anti-HBs not yet up — and the banner rescue: anti-HBc (core antibody) STAYS ELEVATED and fills it, so a window patient is caught only by anti-HBc.", "2. Acute vs chronic vs resolved vs VACCINATED — the four-state serology matrix. Four states. ACUTE = HBsAg+ + anti-HBc IgM. CHRONIC = HBsAg+ >6 months + anti-HBc IgG, with the key negative — anti-HBs NEVER appears. RESOLVED = anti-HBs+ AND anti-HBc+. VACCINATED = anti-HBs+ but anti-HBc NEGATIVE. The discriminator is anti-HBc: positive = met the real virus; negative = vaccine only.", "3. HBV reaches HCC even WITHOUT cirrhosis. Most hepatocellular carcinoma rides on cirrhosis — but Soff flagged the banner exception: HEPATITIS B CAN LEAD TO HCC WITHOUT CIRRHOSIS. The mechanism: HBV DNA integrates into the hepatocyte genome, making the virus directly oncogenic so risk is not gated by scarring. Consequence: lifelong HCC surveillance in chronic HBV, regardless of fibrosis stage.", "4. HCV: anti-HCV screens, HCV RNA confirms chronic, ~85% become chronic, no vaccine. Anti-HCV is the screen (CDC: all adults once); a positive screen is confirmed by HCV RNA viral load, which establishes CHRONIC hepatitis C. Natural history is the opposite of HBV in adults: ~85% of acute HCV becomes chronic (vs ~5% adult HBV). Transaminases fluctuate normal-to-mild. NO HCV vaccine — but pan-genotypic regimens CURE ~95%.", "5. HAV: fecal-oral, IgM = acute, IgG = immune, NO chronic state. Hepatitis A spreads fecal-oral (person-to-person, food/water), incubates ~28 days (15-50), an RNA virus with NO chronic carrier state — ~99% self-limited, ~1% fulminant (usually on chronic HBV/HCV or HIV). Serology: anti-HAV IgM = acute (lasts 3-6 mo); anti-HAV IgG = lifelong immunity. Labs: AST/ALT >1,000, ALT>AST, Alk Phos <400, bili <10.", "6. Chronic HBV: treat by criteria with entecavir or tenofovir, then watch for life. Treat chronic HBV for ANY of: cirrhosis/advanced fibrosis, HBV DNA >2000, or AST >2x ULN. First-line oral nucleos(t)ide analogs = entecavir (Baraclude) and tenofovir (Viread/Vemlidy). Goals: eliminate HBsAg/HBeAg, suppress HBV DNA, cut cirrhosis/HCC risk. Treatment and HCC monitoring are lifelong — HBV is suppressed, not cured.", "7. Perinatal HBV is preventable: HBIG + vaccine within 12 hours. Untreated, an HBsAg+ mother transmits to the newborn at ~90%. Giving HBIG (Hepatitis B Immune Globulin) PLUS hepatitis B vaccine within 12 hours of delivery drops transmission by ~95%. High maternal viral load → treat her in pregnancy. Breastfeeding is NOT a risk factor. Neonatal infection matters because ~90% of neonates progress to chronic (vs ~5% of adults).", "8. MASLD = #1 cause of abnormal LFTs in the US; ALT>AST viral, AST>ALT alcohol. Sorting the hepatitis differential, MASLD (metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease) is the #1 cause of abnormal LFTs in the US. Two patterns split it: ALT > AST = viral (and most non-alcoholic injury); AST > ALT = alcohol. Round out the DDx: metabolic (hemochromatosis, Wilson, A1AT), autoimmune (ANA = lupoid hepatitis), celiac (anti-tTG), vascular (portal vein thrombosis, Budd-Chiari, shock liver).", "HBV serum-sickness-like prodrome = fever, rash, painful joints, pre-icteric HBV", "Twinrix = dual HAV+HBV vaccine, 3 doses", "Havrix / Vaqta = HAV single-antigen, 2 doses each, inactivated", "Heplisav = 2-dose HBV vaccine", "Wilson disease = low ceruloplasmin, high copper, young hepatitis", "Hereditary hemochromatosis = high ferritin, high iron, high transferrin sat", "Budd-Chiari syndrome = hepatic vein outflow obstruction, vascular hepatitis", "Shock liver = ischemic hepatitis, massive transient transaminases, hypotension", "Lupoid hepatitis = autoimmune hepatitis, elevated ANA", "Celiac hepatitis = anti-tTG, abnormal LFTs", "HBeAg = high infectivity, contagious HBV", "Baby Boomer cohort = HCV screening, 1945-1965, parenteral", "HAV labs = AST/ALT >1000 ALT>AST, alk phos <400, bili <10", "Fulminant hepatitis = encephalopathy, coagulopathy, transplant center transfer", "HBV the only DNA hepatitis virus = DNA, integrates genome, serum hepatitis", "HEV = fecal-oral, self-limited, fulminant in pregnancy"], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Discuss the differential diagnosis of viral hepatitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW — HEPATITIS VS CHOLESTASIS FIRST. Before naming a virus, Soff sorts the injury two ways. Hepatitis is destruction/death of hepatocytes with inflammatory infiltrate of the parenchyma — the markers that leak are the transaminases AST and ALT (with bilirubin and PT-INR rising only if damage is extensive). Cholestasis is a problem of the biliary tree (canaliculi -> intrahepatic ducts -> extrahepatic ducts), and its marker is alkaline phosphatase. Because alk phos lives in both liver and bone, you confirm a liver source with GGT or 5'-nucleotidase — both liver/biliary-specific and not found in bone. One more practical split: imaging is minimal help in hepatitis but a major help in cholestasis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE NON-VIRAL DIFFERENTIAL. When viral serologies are negative, Soff runs the buckets. Metabolic — inherited: hemochromatosis (check Fe/iron-binding capacity, ferritin), Wilson disease (copper, ceruloplasmin), alpha-1-antitrypsin levels. Metabolic — acquired: fatty liver = MASLD/MASH (history, ultrasound, FibroScan). Autoimmune hepatitis (elevated ANA — 'lupoid hepatitis'). Celiac disease (anti-tTG). Toxins: alcohol (AST>ALT), medications, herbs, organic solvents. Vascular: portal vein thrombosis, Budd-Chiari syndrome, shock liver. Towering over all of it: MASLD is the #1 cause of abnormal/elevated LFTs in the US."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Hepatitis = hepatocyte death (AST/ALT up); cholestasis = biliary (alk phos up); GGT/5'-NT confirm liver, not bone."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "MASLD = #1 cause of abnormal LFTs in the US. Buckets: metabolic / autoimmune (ANA) / celiac / toxic / vascular."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ALT > AST = viral pattern; AST > ALT = alcohol pattern."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Sort the injury first: hepatitis (AST/ALT) vs cholestasis (alk phos, confirmed liver by GGT/5'-NT). Non-viral DDx: MASLD is #1, then metabolic/autoimmune/toxic/vascular. ALT>AST = viral, AST>ALT = alcohol."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "GGT and 5'-nucleotidase are liver/biliary-specific and not in bone — they tell you an elevated alkaline phosphatase is coming from the liver, not the skeleton."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Autoimmune hepatitis = elevated ANA ('lupoid hepatitis'); celiac = anti-tTG; hemochromatosis = ferritin/iron studies; Wilson = copper/ceruloplasmin."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Soff opened by sorting 'hepatitis' from 'cholestasis' and then listed everything that mimics viral hepatitis. Give the lab pattern that separates hepatitis from cholestasis, name the #1 US cause of abnormal LFTs, and say which enzyme ratio points to alcohol versus viral injury."}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe the etiology and epidemiology of viral hepatitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW — FIVE VIRUSES, TWO ROUTES. The classic viral causes are hepatitis A, B, C, D, and E (plus other viruses — CMV, EBV/mono, COVID-19). The organizing split is transmission: HAV and HEV are fecal-oral and self-limited/acute; HBV, HCV, and HDV are blood/body-fluid (parenteral) and can become chronic. HAV is an RNA 'infectious hepatitis' (1.4 million cases/yr) spread person-to-person and by contaminated food/water — households, daycare, prisons, military — with no prenatal spread. US incidence has fallen since vaccination began (1996 high-risk, all infants 2006): from ~6 to ~0.4 cases per 100,000."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HBV AND HCV EPIDEMIOLOGY. HBV is a DNA virus ('serum hepatitis'); in the US ~82% of cases are foreign-born (immigration-driven), and incidence fell from 8.5 to ~1 per 100,000 (1990 -> 2016). Routes: vertical (mother-to-child), parenteral (IV drug use, transfusion, tattoo), and sexual. HCV is a small RNA virus spread parenterally; incidence persists high (rose ~3x from 2010-2015) and the classic at-risk cohort is the 'Baby Boomers.' 1.3% of the US has/had hepatitis C (~3.6 million). The critical chronicity contrast: ~85% of acute HCV becomes chronic, versus only ~5% for adult HBV — HCV's danger is its years-to-decades silent chronicity."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HAV/HEV = fecal-oral, self-limited; HBV/HCV/HDV = parenteral (blood/body fluids), can become chronic."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HBV = DNA, ~82% foreign-born in US, vertical/parenteral/sexual. HCV = RNA, parenteral, 1.3% of US (~3.6M), 'Boomers'."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Chronicity: HCV ~85% acute -> chronic vs HBV ~5% in adults (but ~90% in neonates)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Route splits the field: HAV/HEV fecal-oral, acute, self-limited; HBV/HCV/HDV parenteral, can be chronic. HBV = DNA; HAV/HCV/HDV/HEV = RNA. ~85% of HCV becomes chronic vs ~5% of adult HBV."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "HBV is the only DNA hepatitis virus — and the one whose DNA integrates into the host genome (the basis for its HCC risk in LO 49.6)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "US handles: HBV is mostly foreign-born (~82%); HCV is the 'Boomer' cohort, 1.3% of the US (~3.6 million)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Soff framed the five hepatitis viruses by how they spread and who gets them. Give the transmission route and genome for HAV, HBV, and HCV, and state the headline epidemiologic fact Soff attached to each."}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Describe the clinical features and lab findings of viral hepatitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW — THE THREE WORKING HBV MARKERS. The acute presentation is nonspecific (fever, N/V, RUQ pain, anorexia, jaundice, malaise; HBV adds a serum-sickness-like prodrome — fever, rash, painful joints), and AST/ALT run 1,000-2,000 with ALT>AST — so the serology, not the symptoms, makes the diagnosis. Three markers do the work. HBsAg (surface antigen) is the first to rise and means current infection. Anti-HBs (surface antibody) is the last to appear and means immunity. Anti-HBc (core antibody) sits between them and is the key to the window. Two more report infectivity: HBeAg (highly contagious) and anti-HBe (lower infectivity)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE WINDOW AND THE CORE-ANTIBODY RESCUE. There is a gap in acute HBV when HBsAg has already fallen but anti-HBs has not yet risen — the serologic window. Test only HBsAg and anti-HBs there and both are negative, so the infection would be missed. Soff's banner is the save: CORE ANTIBODY STAYS ELEVATED (anti-HBc) — anti-HBc fills the window and is the marker that catches a window-period patient. In acute disease the core antibody is the IgM class; later it converts to IgG, which persists for life as the durable footprint that the patient once met the actual virus."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE FOUR-STATE MATRIX — READ ANY HBV PANEL. This is the spine of the lecture. ACUTE = HBsAg+ with anti-HBc IgM. CHRONIC = HBsAg+ for >6 months with anti-HBc IgG, HBeAg telling you if they are contagious, and the defining negative — anti-HBs NEVER appears. RESOLVED (past, recovered) = anti-HBs+ AND anti-HBc+ (immunity plus the footprint of real infection). VACCINATED = anti-HBs+ but anti-HBc NEGATIVE. The single discriminator between the two immune states is anti-HBc: a vaccine presents only the surface antigen, so a vaccinated person makes anti-HBs but never anti-HBc (developed fully in LO 49.4). See the master comparison table below for how the five viruses line up on genome, route, and course."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HBsAg = infection (rises first); anti-HBs = immunity (last); HBeAg/anti-HBe = infectivity."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Window: HBsAg fallen, anti-HBs not yet up - anti-HBc FILLS IT and catches it. Acute = IgM; later = IgG."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (HBV state / HBsAg / anti-HBc / anti-HBs): Acute — Positive · Positive (IgM) · Negative ; Chronic (>6 mo) — Positive · Positive (IgG) · NEGATIVE (never) ; Resolved / past — Negative · Positive · Positive ; Vaccinated — Negative · NEGATIVE · Positive"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Acute HBsAg+/IgM; Chronic HBsAg+ >6 mo/IgG, anti-HBs never; Resolved anti-HBs+ & anti-HBc+; Vaccinated anti-HBs+, anti-HBc neg."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HAV AND HCV LABS. HAV: anti-HAV IgM appears with symptoms (lasts 3-6 months) = acute; anti-HAV IgG persists for years = lifelong immunity ('M = modern/now, G = gone/past'). HAV transaminases run >1,000 with ALT>AST, peak ~1 month then fall, Alk Phos <400, bili <10. HCV: anti-HCV is the screen; an elevated HCV RNA viral load CONFIRMS chronic hepatitis C. Crucially, HCV AST/ALT fluctuate between normal and slightly elevated and do not correlate with histology — so enzymes can't stage it; genotypes 1-5 guide treatment, and FibroScan/ultrasound/AFP monitor fibrosis and HCC."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HAV: IgM = acute, IgG = immunity. HCV: anti-HCV screens, HCV RNA confirms chronic; enzymes fluctuate."}, {"t": "key", "x": "The four HBV states: Acute (HBsAg+, anti-HBc IgM) · Chronic (HBsAg+ >6 mo, anti-HBc IgG, anti-HBs never) · Resolved (anti-HBs+ AND anti-HBc+) · Vaccinated (anti-HBs+, anti-HBc negative). Anti-HBc fills the window."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Resolved vs vaccinated — both are anti-HBs positive (immune). The discriminator is anti-HBc: positive = recovered from real infection, negative = vaccine only. In chronic HBV, anti-HBs never appears."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "HCV RNA confirms chronic hepatitis C; the AST/ALT fluctuate between normal and mildly elevated and don't track histology — never stage HCV by enzymes."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Soff said Mother Nature 'gave us the core antibody' to fill the window. Walk the four HBV serologic states (acute, chronic, resolved, vaccinated) with the markers that define each, explain what anti-HBc does in the window period, and add how HAV and HCV are diagnosed serologically."}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe vaccination and post-exposure prophylaxis for HBV and HCV", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "VACCINATED VS INFECTED — ONE MARKER DECIDES. A vaccine presents only the surface antigen, so the immune response is anti-HBs alone — the body never sees the core, so it never makes anti-HBc. That gives the decisive rule: vaccinated = anti-HBs POSITIVE + anti-HBc NEGATIVE; previously infected (recovered) = anti-HBs POSITIVE + anti-HBc POSITIVE. Two patients can both be immune (anti-HBs+); the one who is anti-HBc positive met the real virus, the one who is anti-HBc negative got there by vaccine. (This is the same anti-HBc that fills the window in LO 49.3 — it is the universal footprint of true exposure.)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "PERINATAL HBV — HBIG + VACCINE WITHIN 12 HOURS. Mother-to-child is the highest-stakes prevention because ~90% of neonates who acquire HBV become chronic (vs ~5% of adults). Without intervention an HBsAg-positive mother transmits at ~90%. The intervention: within 12 hours of delivery give the newborn HBIG (Hepatitis B Immune Globulin) PLUS the hepatitis B vaccine, which cuts transmission by ~95%. If the mother has a high viral load, treat her during pregnancy to lower it. Breastfeeding is NOT a risk factor. Beyond perinatal care, US blood banks screen with HBsAg, anti-HBc, and HBV DNA, dropping transfusion risk to <1 in a million."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHICH VIRUSES HAVE VACCINES. HAV: single-antigen inactivated vaccines Havrix and Vaqta (each 2 doses), and the dual HAV+HBV vaccine Twinrix (3 doses) — vaccination is the key to prevention, especially for chronic-liver-disease patients and travelers to endemic areas; post-exposure = immune globulin + vaccine. HBV: routine vaccine (the newer 2-dose Heplisav among them). HCV: there is NO vaccine — so HCV prevention rests on universal screening (CDC: screen all adults once), harm reduction, and curative treatment rather than immunization."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Vaccinated = anti-HBs+ / anti-HBc NEGATIVE; previously infected = anti-HBs+ / anti-HBc positive. Anti-HBc discriminates."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Perinatal HBV: HBIG + vaccine within 12 h cuts ~90% transmission by ~95%; breastfeeding not a risk factor."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Vaccines exist for HAV (Havrix/Vaqta 2-dose, Twinrix 3-dose dual) and HBV (incl. Heplisav 2-dose). HCV has NO vaccine."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Anti-HBc separates vaccinated (negative) from previously infected (positive). Perinatal HBV: HBIG + vaccine within 12 h (~95% reduction). Vaccines for HAV and HBV; none for HCV."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Why no anti-HBc after vaccination? The vaccine contains only surface antigen, so the body makes anti-HBs and never sees the core — anti-HBc only follows real infection."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "HAV vaccines: Havrix / Vaqta (2 doses each); Twinrix = dual HAV+HBV (3 doses). HBV: Heplisav (2-dose). HCV: no vaccine — screen and treat."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Soff said a vaccinated patient and a recovered patient both look immune until you check one marker. Name that discriminating marker, give the serologic pattern for vaccinated vs previously infected, state the perinatal HBV prophylaxis and timing, and say which hepatitis viruses have vaccines."}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Describe the treatment of acute viral hepatitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW — SUPPORTIVE CARE IS THE TREATMENT. Acute viral hepatitis is largely self-limited, so the mainstay is supportive care: fluids (assuring hydration), rest, reassurance, and time. There is no routine antiviral for uncomplicated acute disease — symptoms are nonspecific and resolve. The judgment call is recognizing when supportive outpatient care is not enough: hospitalize if the patient cannot tolerate fluids, or shows hepatic dysfunction — coagulopathy (elevated PT-INR), encephalopathy, or severe jaundice. If the course is fulminant (acute, severe liver destruction with organ failure), transfer to a transplant center. (Chronic-disease antiviral management is LO 49.6.)"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Acute viral hepatitis = supportive (fluids, rest, time). Hospitalize for coagulopathy/encephalopathy; fulminant -> transplant."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Uncomplicated acute viral hepatitis = fluids, rest, reassurance, time. Escalate for coagulopathy (high PT-INR), encephalopathy, severe jaundice, or inability to tolerate fluids; fulminant failure goes to a transplant center."}]}, {"id": 6, "statement": "Describe the management of chronic viral hepatitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "CHRONIC HBV — WHO TO TREAT, WITH WHAT. Not every chronic HBV patient is treated; treat if ANY of: cirrhosis/advanced fibrosis, HBV DNA >2000, or AST >2x ULN. First-line oral nucleos(t)ide analogs are entecavir (Baraclude) and tenofovir (Viread/Vemlidy) (others: lamivudine, adefovir, telbivudine). The goals: eliminate HBsAg and HBeAg, suppress HBV DNA, and decrease long-term cirrhosis and HCC risk. Both treatment and HCC monitoring are LIFELONG — these drugs suppress, they do not cure HBV."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE BANNER — HBV REACHES HCC WITHOUT CIRRHOSIS. Soff flagged the exception in red: HEPATITIS B CAN LEAD TO HCC WITHOUT CIRRHOSIS. The mechanism is on the chronic-HBV slide: Hep B DNA gets incorporated into the hepatocyte DNA (integrates into the host genome), making HBV directly oncogenic rather than needing cirrhosis to drive cancer. That single fact justifies lifelong HCC surveillance (ultrasound +/- AFP) in chronic HBV regardless of fibrosis stage — the integrated viral DNA, not the scarring, carries the risk."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CHRONIC HCV — DIFFERENT GAME, CURABLE. Management is a sequence: consider HCV (CDC recommends universal screening of all adults), test anti-HCV, confirm with HCV RNA viral titer, establish fibrosis/cirrhosis (FibroScan), then treat based on genotype, renal status, and cirrhosis. Unlike HBV, HCV is curable: pan-genotypic regimens cure ~95% of hepatitis C. The catch is there is still NO HCV vaccine and the drugs are costly (~$23,000), so screening and cure are the public-health levers. This is the HCC convergence: cirrhosis from alcohol/MASH, the macronodular post-necrotic road, and direct HBV integration all funnel into hepatocellular carcinoma."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Treat chronic HBV if cirrhosis / HBV DNA >2000 / AST >2x ULN; first-line entecavir or tenofovir; lifelong (suppress, not cure)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HBV -> HCC WITHOUT cirrhosis because HBV DNA integrates into the hepatocyte genome -> lifelong HCC surveillance."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Chronic HCV: anti-HCV -> HCV RNA -> FibroScan -> treat by genotype; pan-genotypic cures ~95%; no vaccine."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Treat chronic HBV (cirrhosis / DNA >2000 / AST >2x ULN) with entecavir or tenofovir, lifelong (suppress, not cure) + lifelong HCC surveillance because HBV DNA integrates -> HCC without cirrhosis. Chronic HCV is ~95% curable (pan-genotypic), no vaccine."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "HBV is suppressed, HCV is cured. Entecavir/tenofovir control HBV for life; pan-genotypic direct-acting antivirals eradicate HCV in ~95% — don't promise an HBV 'cure.'"}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "The board hook: HBV is the HCC exception — its DNA integrates into the hepatocyte genome, so it causes liver cancer without cirrhosis, mandating lifelong surveillance."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Soff put a banner on the screen: hepatitis B can cause liver cancer without cirrhosis. Explain the mechanism behind that banner, give the criteria and first-line drugs for treating chronic HBV (and why it is lifelong), and contrast that with how chronic HCV is managed."}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Confusing resolved infection with vaccination. Both are anti-HBs positive (immune). The discriminator is anti-HBc: positive = recovered from real infection; negative = vaccine only. A vaccine carries only surface antigen, so it never raises anti-HBc. → LO 49.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Expecting anti-HBs to appear in chronic hepatitis B. In chronic HBV, anti-HBs NEVER appears — HBsAg stays positive >6 months with anti-HBc IgG. Anti-HBs showing up means recovery or vaccination, not chronic disease. → LO 49.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Missing the window period. When HBsAg has fallen but anti-HBs is not yet up, both are negative — only anti-HBc fills the window and catches the infection. Don't call a window-period patient HBV-negative. → LO 49.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Thinking HBV needs cirrhosis to cause liver cancer. HBV can cause HCC WITHOUT cirrhosis because HBV DNA integrates into the hepatocyte genome — so HCC surveillance is lifelong regardless of fibrosis. → LO 49.6"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Promising a hepatitis B 'cure' or a hepatitis C vaccine. HBV is suppressed, not cured (entecavir/tenofovir, lifelong). HCV is curable (~95% pan-genotypic) but has NO vaccine. Don't swap them. → LO 49.6"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Staging or confirming hepatitis C by the transaminases. HCV AST/ALT fluctuate between normal and mildly elevated and don't track histology — the HCV RNA viral load confirms chronic disease, not the enzymes. → LO 49.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. Flipping the AST/ALT ratio. ALT > AST = viral hepatitis; AST > ALT = alcohol. And remember MASLD is the #1 cause of abnormal LFTs in the US when serologies are negative. → LO 49.1"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"anti-HBs positive, anti-HBc NEGATIVE\" → vaccinated; anti-HBs+ AND anti-HBc+ → previously infected / resolved."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"HBsAg positive >6 months, anti-HBc IgG, anti-HBs never appears\" → chronic hepatitis B."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"HBsAg fallen, anti-HBs not yet up\" → the window period, caught only by anti-HBc (the core antibody that stays elevated)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"chronic HBV, no cirrhosis, still needs lifelong HCC surveillance\" → because HBV DNA integrates into the hepatocyte genome (HCC without cirrhosis)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"chronic HBV meeting criteria (cirrhosis / DNA >2000 / AST >2x ULN)\" → entecavir or tenofovir, lifelong."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"chronic hepatitis C, treat by genotype\" → pan-genotypic regimen, ~95% cure — but no HCV vaccine."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. \"HBsAg-positive mother, newborn within 12 hours\" → HBIG + hepatitis B vaccine (~95% reduction in transmission)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Roads to HCC - chronic HBV reaches hepatocellular carcinoma without cirrhosis (viral DNA integrates into the hepatocyte genome), a road that runs alongside the cirrhosis-driven HCC of alcohol/MASH and the macronodular post-necrotic pathway of the cirrhosis lecture (Lec 43) and the surgical/transplant HCC + Milan-criteria material (Lec 46)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — LFT patterns - the hepatitis-vs-cholestasis split (AST/ALT vs alk phos), the GGT/5'-nucleotidase confirmation of a hepatobiliary source, and the ALT>AST viral / AST>ALT alcohol ratio are developed in full in the dedicated hepatic-function-test lecture (Lec 48); this lecture applies them to the viral differential"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — MASLD as #1 - the metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease named here as the leading US cause of abnormal LFTs is the same fatty-liver spectrum (MASLD/MASH, formerly NAFLD/NASH) detailed under abnormal liver chemistries in the function-test lecture (Lec 48) and the steatosis-to-cirrhosis arc of the pathology lecture (Lec 43)"}]}]}, "50": {"prof": "Dr. Cyril Blavo", "tldr": "Walk bilirubin through the enterohepatic circulation, then read every jaundice off the broken step — sort it UNCONJUGATED vs CONJUGATED and pre- / hepatocellular / post-hepatic, and the named syndromes fall into place.", "mustKnows": ["1. The bilirubin pathway, enzyme by enzyme. Heme → heme oxygenase → biliverdin → biliverdin reductase → unconjugated bilirubin (UCB), which is fat-soluble so it rides albumin to the liver. UDP glucuronyl transferase (UGT) conjugates it → water-soluble conjugated bilirubin (CB); colonic bacteria make urobilinogen → stercobilin (colors stool), and reabsorbed urobilinogen is excreted in urine as urobilin. Blavo: 'you need to know these.'", "2. Two sorts organize the whole differential. Read every jaundice two ways. By bilirubin form: UNCONJUGATED (increased production, impaired conjugation, impaired uptake) vs CONJUGATED (cholestasis / transport defects). By site: pre-hepatic (hemolysis, Gilbert, Crigler-Najjar), hepatocellular (alcohol, viral hepatitis, PBC/PSC, HCC), post-hepatic (gallstones, cholangiocarcinoma, pancreatic cancer). Most board callouts live in these two grids.", "3. UCB vs CB — the table that drives the labs. UCB = fat-soluble, albumin-bound, toxic (crosses lipid membranes → tissues, brain), not in urine; measured as indirect bilirubin. CB = water-soluble, non-toxic, in urine; measured as direct. The fractionation rule: unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia → indirect up; conjugated → BOTH direct AND indirect up (some unconjugated precedes conjugation).", "4. Gilbert vs Crigler-Najjar — deficiency vs absence. Both are autosomal-recessive UDP-glucuronyl-transferase defects giving unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia. Gilbert = a DEFICIENCY (reduced enzyme): mild, benign, rises with stress/fasting, more common in boys. Crigler-Najjar = an ABSENCE of the enzyme: severe, with dark urine and acholic (clay-colored) stool. Blavo drilled the deficiency vs absence split as the board point.", "5. Wilson disease = copper, ATP7B, Kayser-Fleischer. Wilson disease is an autosomal-recessive defect of the ATP7B copper transporter that leaves the body unable to eliminate copper, so toxic copper deposits in liver, eyes, and brain (hepatolenticular degeneration). Blavo's anchor: 'think copper.' The ocular sign — a copper ring in the iris, the Kayser-Fleischer ring — is the classic tell (he noted it should have been on the slide).", "6. Dubin-Johnson is the black liver; Rotor is its pigment-free twin. Both are benign autosomal-recessive CONJUGATED hyperbilirubinemias. Dubin-Johnson = a canalicular organic-anion-transport defect (ABCC2 gene / MRP2 protein) blocking bilirubin export → the liver looks grossly BLACK. Rotor = a sinusoidal re-uptake defect, digenic (SLCO1B1 + SLCO1B3 on chromosome 12p), with NO black pigment. Black-liver vs no-pigment is the clean split.", "7. PSC and biliary atresia are the post-hepatic must-knows. Primary sclerosing cholangitis = inflammatory scarring/narrowing of bile ducts, diagnosed by MRCP, associated with p-ANCA and a history of IBD — Blavo: 'we like to ask questions on that.' Biliary atresia is the infant cause: a congenital bile-duct/gallbladder absence (absent gallbladder on ultrasound) fixed by the Kasai portoenterostomy; stool is acholic, urine is dark.", "8. Kernicterus is the neonatal emergency; phototherapy heads it off. Because UCB is fat-soluble, a high unconjugated load in a newborn crosses the blood-brain barrier and causes kernicterus — life-threatening bilirubin encephalopathy. Physiologic neonatal jaundice (immature liver, high RBC turnover) is self-limited; phototherapy photo-isomerizes UCB into a water-soluble form. Separate breast-feeding jaundice (poor intake) from breast-milk jaundice (milk substances).", "Heme oxygenase / biliverdin reductase = heme -> biliverdin -> unconjugated bilirubin", "Urobilin vs stercobilin = urobilin = urine, stercobilin = stool", "Beta-glucuronidase = gut, deconjugates CB back to UCB, reabsorbed", "Gilbert syndrome = UGT deficiency, unconjugated, stress/fasting, boys", "Crigler-Najjar = UGT absence, severe, dark urine, acholic stool", "Wilson disease = ATP7B, copper, Kayser-Fleischer rings, AR", "Dubin-Johnson = black liver, ABCC2/MRP2, canalicular, conjugated", "Rotor syndrome = digenic SLCO1B1/1B3, 12p, no pigment, sinusoidal", "Primary sclerosing cholangitis = MRCP, p-ANCA, IBD, post-hepatic", "Biliary atresia = infant, absent gallbladder on US, Kasai", "Kasai portoenterostomy = biliary atresia surgery, neonate", "Kernicterus = fat-soluble UCB, brain, bilirubin encephalopathy", "Phototherapy = photo-isomerizes UCB water-soluble, neonate", "Acholic stool = clay/pale, no gut bile pigment, dark urine", "Indirect vs direct bilirubin = indirect = unconjugated, direct = conjugated", "GGT vs haptoglobin = GGT = biliary obstruction, haptoglobin = hemolysis"], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Differential diagnosis of hyperbilirubinemia", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Hyperbilirubinemia is an excess of bilirubin in the blood; when it stains tissue it shows as jaundice (icterus) — yellow pigment in skin, sclera, nail beds, and oral mucosa. Blavo framed the whole hour as a biochem review aimed at one skill: 'this lecture is really about differential diagnosis.' Master the bilirubin pathway and every cause becomes the step that broke. Two definitions anchor everything: unconjugated bilirubin (UCB) is fat-soluble (crosses lipid membranes into tissues, is toxic, rides albumin, is not in urine), and conjugated bilirubin (CB) is water-soluble (non-toxic, excreted in urine)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE PATHWAY — THE ENTEROHEPATIC CIRCULATION. Senescent RBCs (~120-day lifespan) are cleared by the reticuloendothelial system (chiefly the spleen); hemoglobin is broken down by two enzymes Blavo flagged as mandatory — heme oxygenase (heme → biliverdin) and biliverdin reductase (biliverdin → unconjugated bilirubin). UCB rides albumin to the liver, dissociates, and enters the hepatocyte, where UDP glucuronyl transferase (UGT) adds glucuronic acid → conjugated bilirubin. In the gut, colonic bacteria convert CB to urobilinogen, then to stercobilin (which colors the stool); some urobilinogen is reabsorbed and excreted in urine as urobilin (the prof stressed: urobilin, not urobilinogen). A counter-enzyme, intestinal β-glucuronidase, does the opposite — it deconjugates CB back to UCB for reabsorption."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Pathway: heme →(heme oxygenase) biliverdin →(biliverdin reductase) UCB → albumin → UGT → CB → gut urobilinogen → stercobilin (stool) / urobilin (urine)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "UCB = fat-soluble, albumin-bound, toxic, not in urine, indirect; CB = water-soluble, non-toxic, in urine, direct."}, {"t": "p", "x": "TWO SORTS ORGANIZE EVERYTHING. The first sort is by bilirubin form. UNCONJUGATED hyperbilirubinemia has three mechanisms: (1) increased production (hemolytic anemias — sickle cell, G6PD deficiency, malaria; intravascular hemolysis; dyserythropoiesis; Wilson disease), (2) impaired conjugation (Gilbert, Crigler-Najjar, neonatal physiologic, breast-feeding/breast-milk, hyperthyroidism), and (3) impaired hepatic uptake (heart failure, portosystemic shunts, rifampin, probenecid). CONJUGATED hyperbilirubinemia is the obstruction/transport side: posthepatic cholestasis, intrahepatic cholestasis, and the canalicular/sinusoidal transport defects (Dubin-Johnson, Rotor). The second sort is by site — pre-hepatic / hepatocellular / post-hepatic — the framework on the three-column slide. The hepatocellular column is the liver-injury list: alcoholic liver disease, viral hepatitis, iatrogenic/medication, hereditary haemochromatosis, autoimmune hepatitis, PBC/PSC, and hepatocellular carcinoma."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Sort 1 (form): UNCONJUGATED = production / conjugation / uptake; CONJUGATED = cholestasis / transport defect. Sort 2 (site): pre- / hepatocellular / post-hepatic."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE UNCONJUGATED NAMED SYNDROMES. Gilbert and Crigler-Najjar are the high-yield UGT pair, both autosomal recessive, and Blavo drilled the discriminator: Gilbert = a DEFICIENCY (reduced enzyme) → mild, benign, surfaces with stress/fasting, more common in boys; Crigler-Najjar = an ABSENCE of the enzyme → severe, with dark urine and acholic (clay-colored) stool (note: acholic = pale; the urine is the dark one). Wilson disease rounds out the increased-production list: an autosomal-recessive ATP7B defect that blocks copper elimination, so copper deposits in liver, eyes, and brain (hepatolenticular degeneration) — Blavo's anchor was 'think copper,' and the ocular sign is the Kayser-Fleischer ring (he flagged that it belongs on the slide)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Gilbert = UGT deficiency, mild, stress-triggered; Crigler-Najjar = UGT absence, severe, dark urine + acholic (pale) stool. Both AR, unconjugated."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE CONJUGATED SIDE — OBSTRUCTION AND TRANSPORT. Posthepatic cholestasis is mechanical, and the slide sorts it by where the block sits: intra-luminal (gallstones), mural (in the duct wall — cholangiocarcinoma, strictures e.g. PSC), and extra-mural (compressing from outside — pancreatic cancer, abdominal masses e.g. lymphomas). Add the parasites (Ascaris, Fasciola hepatica), the lesser members (pancreatitis, AIDS cholangiopathy, post-procedure strictures), and two infant/board favorites. Primary sclerosing cholangitis is inflammatory scarring/narrowing of bile ducts — Blavo: 'we like to ask questions on that' — diagnosed by MRCP, associated with p-ANCA and a history of IBD. Biliary atresia is the neonatal post-hepatic cause: a congenital bile-duct/gallbladder absence (absent gallbladder on ultrasound) fixed by the Kasai portoenterostomy. Finally, the two transport defects: Dubin-Johnson (ABCC2/MRP2 canalicular-export defect → grossly BLACK liver) and Rotor (a digenic SLCO1B1 + SLCO1B3 sinusoidal re-uptake defect on chromosome 12p, with NO pigment). Both are benign; black-vs-no-pigment is the split."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "PSC = MRCP + p-ANCA + IBD. Biliary atresia = absent gallbladder on US → Kasai. Dubin-Johnson = MRP2/black liver; Rotor = digenic, no pigment."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Walk the pathway (heme oxygenase → biliverdin reductase → UCB-albumin → UGT → CB → gut), then sort every cause twice: by form (unconjugated = production/conjugation/uptake vs conjugated = cholestasis/transport) and by site (pre- / hepatocellular / post-hepatic). Every named syndrome is a labeled break in that chain."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Gilbert vs Crigler-Najjar: both AR UGT defects, both unconjugated — but Gilbert is a deficiency (mild, benign) and Crigler-Najjar is an absence (severe). Dubin-Johnson vs Rotor: both AR conjugated — Dubin-Johnson is the black liver (MRP2), Rotor has no pigment (digenic SLCO1B1/1B3)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "UCB never appears in urine (fat-soluble, albumin-bound); only CB does (water-soluble). So conjugated hyperbilirubinemias darken the urine, and the fractionation reads unconjugated → indirect, conjugated → both direct and indirect."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Blavo said this lecture 'is really about differential diagnosis.' Walk bilirubin through the enterohepatic circulation, then use that pathway to organize the two sorts (unconjugated vs conjugated; pre-/hepatocellular/post-hepatic) and place Gilbert, Crigler-Najjar, Wilson, Dubin-Johnson, and Rotor."}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Clinical implications of jaundice", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Jaundice is the visible end of hyperbilirubinemia, and the first tell is the sclera: scleral icterus appears because fat-soluble UCB crosses lipid membranes and stains tissue, and the sclera is a sensitive, easily inspected site (skin, nail beds, and oral mucosa pick up the yellow too). Beyond the bilirubin itself, the exam is a hunt for signs of liver disease: hepatomegaly, splenomegaly (think hemolysis), caput medusae (dilated abdominal-wall veins from portal hypertension), ascites, palmar erythema, spider angiomas, xanthomas (dermal fat/cholesterol deposits), and Courvoisier's sign (a painless palpable enlarged gallbladder suggesting biliary obstruction)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE WORKUP — FRACTIONATE FIRST. The initial labs are serum total bilirubin fractionated into direct (conjugated) and indirect (unconjugated), plus the liver panel: ALP, AST, ALT, PT/INR, albumin. The fractionation rule Blavo drilled: unconjugated → indirect bilirubin is the predominant elevation; conjugated → BOTH direct AND indirect rise (because some unconjugated always precedes conjugation). He deliberately deferred the detailed enzyme-pattern reading (ALP vs the aminotransferases) to the dedicated LFT lecture — 'that was her lecture' — so here, just know which fraction points where."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ADD-ON TESTS. Imaging follows the suspicion: abdominal ultrasound for the gallbladder, CT/MRI, and the one Blavo singled out to remember — MRCP (magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography) for the sclerosing disease (PSC) and biliary-duct dilatation; MRE for fibrosis; EUS/ERCP and liver biopsy when needed. Two targeted labs sort the mechanism: GGT (gamma-glutamyl transferase) is more specific for biliary obstruction, and haptoglobin helps diagnose hemolytic anemias. The closing refrain: anchor the workup to the enterohepatic circulation — a suspected intrahepatic problem points you to a liver MRI, a suspected post-hepatic one to a gallbladder ultrasound."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Scleral icterus first (fat-soluble UCB stains tissue); scan for caput medusae / ascites / palmar erythema / spider angiomas / xanthomas / Courvoisier."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Fractionate: unconjugated → indirect up; conjugated → direct + indirect up. Add-ons: GGT = biliary obstruction, haptoglobin = hemolysis, MRCP = PSC."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A jaundiced patient walks in. What physical signs would you look for, what is the fractionation rule that splits unconjugated from conjugated, and which two add-on labs tell hemolysis apart from biliary obstruction?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Discuss the causes and treatments for neonatal hyperbilirubinemia", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Neonatal hyperbilirubinemia is the one place this lecture talks treatments, and almost all of it is unconjugated — the newborn liver is immature, so its conjugating enzymes lag while red-cell turnover is high. The stakes are set by one fact: because UCB is fat-soluble, a high neonatal load crosses the blood-brain barrier and causes kernicterus — life-threatening bilirubin encephalopathy. Everything else here is about telling the benign causes apart and treating before bilirubin climbs that high."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE CAUSES — THREE NEONATAL JAUNDICES. Physiologic neonatal jaundice is the common, benign one: an immature liver plus high RBC turnover gives a transient unconjugated rise that surfaces at day 2-3 and is self-limited. Breast-FEEDING jaundice occurs in the first week of life from poor intake/mild dehydration (the baby is not feeding well) — treat by increasing feeding frequency. Breast-MILK jaundice is later and transient, attributed to substances in the milk that affect how the liver processes bilirubin — monitor. (Hyperthyroidism, which alters bilirubin uptake/excretion, and chronic hepatitis round out the slide's list.) The two hereditary extremes are Crigler-Najjar I and II (an absence of UGT, severe) and the post-hepatic biliary atresia (absent gallbladder on ultrasound → Kasai portoenterostomy)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Physiologic = immature liver, self-limited; breast-FEEDING = first week, poor intake → feed more; breast-MILK = milk substances, transient → monitor."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE TREATMENTS. Phototherapy is the workhorse: light photo-isomerizes unconjugated bilirubin into a more water-soluble isomer the newborn can excrete without conjugation — exactly what heads off kernicterus in physiologic jaundice. Feeding (more frequent) treats breast-feeding jaundice; breast-milk jaundice is monitored. For Crigler-Najjar, the response splits by type: type II keeps partial UGT1A1 activity, so phenobarbital works — it induces the residual enzyme and lowers bilirubin (the milder, survivable form). Type I has a complete absence of the enzyme, so phenobarbital does NOT help (no enzyme to induce); it needs phototherapy + liver transplant, and untreated it causes fatal kernicterus. Biliary atresia is surgical — the Kasai portoenterostomy."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Kernicterus = fat-soluble UCB → brain (bilirubin encephalopathy). Phototherapy photo-isomerizes UCB water-soluble; feeding for breast-feeding jaundice; Kasai for atresia."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Newborns get jaundiced for several distinct reasons. Separate physiologic from breast-feeding and breast-milk jaundice, name the dreaded complication and why UCB causes it, and match each cause to its treatment."}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Calling UCB the form that shows up in urine. Unconjugated bilirubin is NEVER in urine — it is fat-soluble and albumin-bound. Only conjugated (water-soluble) bilirubin spills into urine. So dark urine and an elevated direct fraction point to a conjugated process, not an unconjugated one. → LO 50.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Mixing up Gilbert (deficiency) and Crigler-Najjar (absence). Both are autosomal-recessive UGT defects giving unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia, but the amount of enzyme differs: Gilbert = a deficiency (mild, benign, stress-triggered) vs Crigler-Najjar = an absence (severe, dark urine, acholic stool). Deficiency vs absence is the exam point. → LO 50.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Reading 'acholic stool' as dark stool. Acholic = clay-colored / PALE, because bile pigment never reaches the gut. In Crigler-Najjar and biliary atresia the stool is pale and it is the urine that is dark (conjugated spillover). Don't let 'acholic' read as dark. → LO 50.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Swapping the Dubin-Johnson and Rotor defects. Dubin-Johnson = a canalicular organic-anion-transport defect (ABCC2 / MRP2) → black liver. Rotor = a sinusoidal re-uptake defect, digenic (SLCO1B1 + SLCO1B3, chromosome 12p), NO pigment. Black vs no-pigment is the clean split. → LO 50.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Treating kernicterus as a conjugated-bilirubin injury. Kernicterus is caused by UNCONJUGATED bilirubin — it is fat-soluble, so it crosses the blood-brain barrier into the neonatal brain (bilirubin encephalopathy). It is the danger of neonatal jaundice and Crigler-Najjar, never of the conjugated Dubin-Johnson/Rotor syndromes. → LO 50.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Forgetting that conjugated hyperbilirubinemia raises BOTH fractions. The fractionation rule isn't symmetric: unconjugated raises indirect alone, but conjugated raises BOTH direct AND indirect (some unconjugated always precedes conjugation). Don't expect a 'pure direct' rise in a conjugated picture. → LO 50.2"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"dark urine\" / elevated direct bilirubin → think CONJUGATED process (obstruction or a transport defect). Only water-soluble CB enters urine; UCB never does."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"mild jaundice with stress or fasting, more common in boys\" → Gilbert syndrome — a UGT deficiency, benign, unconjugated. The severe enzyme-absence version is Crigler-Najjar."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"copper... Kayser-Fleischer rings... hepatolenticular degeneration\" → Wilson disease, the ATP7B autosomal-recessive copper disorder. 'Think copper.'"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"black liver on biopsy\" → Dubin-Johnson (conjugated, ABCC2/MRP2 canalicular defect). Its pigment-free twin is Rotor (digenic SLCO1B1/1B3)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"infant, jaundice, absent gallbladder on ultrasound, acholic stool\" → biliary atresia → the Kasai portoenterostomy. The bile-duct scarring read by MRCP with p-ANCA + IBD is PSC instead."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"newborn, lethargic, very high unconjugated bilirubin\" → risk of kernicterus (fat-soluble UCB in the brain). Treat with phototherapy (photo-isomerizes UCB water-soluble)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Bilirubin pathway & the hereditary syndromes — also Lec 47. Lec 47 (Bonfil) taught the same bilirubin cascade and the five hereditary syndromes from the pathology angle (UGT1A1, MRP2/ABCC2, OATP/SLCO, the black-liver image); Blavo reframes them here inside a clinical differential diagnosis (unconjugated vs conjugated; pre-/hepatocellular/post-hepatic). Both call Gilbert/Crigler-Najjar unconjugated and Dubin-Johnson/Rotor conjugated — taught in full here, tested from the DDx angle."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — LFT patterns & enzyme reading — handed off to Lec 48. Blavo deliberately deferred the detailed ALP vs aminotransferase pattern reading — 'that was her lecture' — to the dedicated LFT lecture (Lec 48). Here you only need the fractionation rule (unconjugated → indirect, conjugated → both) and the targeted markers (GGT for obstruction, haptoglobin for hemolysis)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Post-hepatic obstruction & biliary tumors — picked up in Lec 51-52. The post-hepatic causes named here (cholangiocarcinoma, pancreatic cancer, biliary obstruction) are the mechanistic setup for Lec 51 (liver tumors) and Lec 52 (pancreatic/biliary tumors), where the same lesions are taught as their own pathology. The jaundice presentation is the clinical thread that ties them together."}]}]}, "51": {"prof": "Dr. R. Daniel Bonfil", "tldr": "Sort liver tumors benign-to-malignant and let the molecular fingerprint pick the diagnosis: the 3 adenoma subtypes (HNF1a/beta-catenin/inflammatory), HCC's aflatoxin-p53 / CTNNB1 / IL-6-JAK-STAT drivers, the Klatskin cholangiocarcinoma, and metastasis as the #1 malignancy.", "mustKnows": ["1. Cavernous hemangioma is the most common primary liver tumor. Cavernous hemangioma is the most common primary tumor of the liver — a ≤2 cm red-blue soft nodule usually under the capsule, found incidentally on CT/MRI and often mistaken for a metastasis. Histology = endothelium-lined channels filled with blood ('caverns') in a fibrous-tissue bed.", "2. FNH has a central stellate scar; nodular regenerative hyperplasia causes portal hypertension. Focal nodular hyperplasia (FNH) = a poorly encapsulated nodule with a central gray-white stellate scar (fibrous septa radiate), normal hepatocytes, in females 30-50. Nodular regenerative hyperplasia = 1-3 mm nodules over the whole liver, NOT separated by fibrosis, that may cause portal hypertension.", "3. Hepatocellular adenoma: pill-using women, steroid-using men, can rupture. Hepatocellular adenoma is a rare benign tumor in women 30-40 on long-term oral contraceptives (30-40-fold risk) or men on anabolic steroids. Usually an incidental finding, but the feared complication is rupture with intra-abdominal bleeding — a surgical emergency. Three molecular subtypes follow.", "4. The three adenoma subtypes by molecule, IHC, and risk. HNF1a-inactivated: HNF1a mutation → L-FABP loss on IHC + steatosis (steatosis only here); 10% germline = MODY3. Beta-catenin-activated: CTNNB1 → nuclear beta-catenin on IHC, very high malignant risk → resect even if asymptomatic. Inflammatory: gp130 → IL-6/JAK-STAT → CRP overexpression, NAFLD-linked.", "5. HCC epidemiology splits by geography, virus, age, and cirrhosis. HCC is the most common primary liver cancer (worldwide ~5.4% of all cancers). >85% in sub-Saharan Africa / SE Asia with chronic HBV — young (20-40), and ~50% WITHOUT cirrhosis. In the US it tripled with HCV — older (>60), and ~90% WITH cirrhosis. Cirrhosis is common background but not required.", "6. The HCC driver-mutation triad. Aflatoxin B1 (from Aspergillus on stored grain) → CYP450 epoxide → guanine DNA adduct → G:T transversion → inactivates p53 (~60% of aflatoxin-linked HCC). CTNNB1/beta-catenin activation in ~40% of non-HBV HCC. IL-6/JAK-STAT → downregulates HNF4-alpha → less differentiation, more proliferation.", "7. Fibrolamellar carcinoma is the favorable young-patient HCC variant. Fibrolamellar carcinoma = an HCC variant, 5% of HCCs, 85% at 20-40 y/o, no gender predilection, usually favorable prognosis, typically a single well-circumscribed mass. Histology Bonfil said to 'please remember': oncocytic (mitochondria-rich) cells in parallel lamellae of dense collagen.", "8. Cholangiocarcinoma is the Klatskin/Clonorchis adenocarcinoma; metastasis is #1 overall. Cholangiocarcinoma: perihilar (Klatskin) tumors at the confluence of the R & L hepatic ducts = 60%; risks = Clonorchis sinensis fluke, PSC, hepatolithiasis; desmoplastic adenocarcinoma with perineural invasion. But metastatic disease is by far the most common malignant liver tumor — colon, breast, lung.", "Cavernous hemangioma = most common primary liver tumor, blood-filled caverns, mistaken for metastasis", "Central stellate scar = focal nodular hyperplasia, normal hepatocytes, F 30-50", "1-3 mm nodules, no fibrosis = nodular regenerative hyperplasia, portal hypertension", "L-FABP loss + steatosis = HNF1a-inactivated adenoma, MODY3 if germline", "Nuclear beta-catenin (IHC) = CTNNB1 adenoma, very high malignant risk, resect", "CRP overexpression = inflammatory adenoma, gp130/IL-6/JAK-STAT, NAFLD", "Aflatoxin B1 = Aspergillus on stored grain, G:T transversion, p53", "CTNNB1 / beta-catenin = ~40% of non-HBV HCC, nuclear translocation", "IL-6/JAK-STAT = HCC, downregulates HNF4-alpha", "Oncocytic cells + lamellar collagen = fibrolamellar carcinoma, young, favorable", "Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) = elevated in 50-75% of HCC", "Klatskin tumor = perihilar, R/L hepatic-duct confluence, 60%", "Clonorchis sinensis = SE-Asia liver fluke, cholangiocarcinoma 30-40x", "Desmoplastic glandular adenocarcinoma = cholangiocarcinoma, perineural invasion", "Liver metastasis = most common malignant liver tumor, 1/3 of carcinomas", "Colon, breast, lung = top primaries metastatic to the liver"], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Discuss the etiological factors, morphology, and diagnosis of benign tumors of the liver and of hepatocellular carcinoma", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. This LO is the heart of the lecture — a ladder from benign liver tumors up to hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC), and the trick is that each lesion has a signature you can name. The benign side sorts by morphology (a scar, a cavern, diffuse nodules); the hepatocellular adenoma sorts by molecular subtype; and HCC sorts by its driver-mutation triad. Bonfil built the block so that the adenoma's beta-catenin subtype literally feeds into HCC, so learn the benign molecules and the malignant ones answer themselves."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE THREE BENIGN NON-ADENOMAS. Cavernous hemangioma is the most common primary tumor of the liver — a ≤2 cm red-blue soft nodule usually under the capsule, found incidentally on CT/MRI and often mistaken for a metastasis; histology is endothelium-lined channels filled with blood ('caverns') in a fibrous bed. Focal nodular hyperplasia (FNH) is a well-demarcated but poorly encapsulated nodule (1-10 cm) with a central gray-white stellate scar from which fibrous septa radiate; crucially it is made of normal hepatocytes, most often in women 30-50. Nodular regenerative hyperplasia is different again: 1-3 mm regenerative nodules covering the whole liver, NOT separated by fibrosis, which alter intrahepatic blood flow and can cause portal hypertension."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cavernous hemangioma = most common primary liver tumor; blood-filled endothelial caverns, mistaken for metastasis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "FNH = central stellate scar + normal hepatocytes (F 30-50); nodular regenerative hyperplasia = 1-3 mm nodules → portal HTN."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HEPATOCELLULAR ADENOMA — THE THREE SUBTYPES BONFIL SAID TO 'REMEMBER.' The adenoma itself is rare, classically in women 30-40 on long-term oral contraceptives (30-40-fold risk) or men on anabolic steroids; it is usually incidental, but the feared complication is rupture with intra-abdominal bleeding — a surgical emergency. Bonfil explicitly flagged the three molecular subtypes as must-memorize, and each maps molecule → IHC → risk. (1) HNF1a-inactivated: somatic HNF1a mutation (90%; the 10% germline cases link to MODY3 diabetes) → L-FABP loss on IHC + steatosis — and steatosis appears ONLY in this subtype. (2) Beta-catenin-activated: a CTNNB1 mutation drives beta-catenin into the nucleus (nuclear staining on IHC); this subtype carries a very high risk of malignant transformation, so nuclear beta-catenin is diagnostic and prompts surgery even without symptoms. (3) Inflammatory: a gp130 mutation (the IL-6 co-receptor) activates JAK-STAT → overexpression of acute-phase reactants like C-reactive protein (CRP); it is NAFLD-related with only a small malignant risk (higher if beta-catenin is co-mutated)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HNF1a adenoma = L-FABP loss + steatosis (only subtype); beta-catenin = nuclear IHC, high malignant risk → surgery; inflammatory = CRP/IL-6-JAK-STAT."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HCC — EPIDEMIOLOGY READS AS TWO GEOGRAPHIES. Hepatocellular carcinoma is the most common primary liver cancer and worldwide accounts for ~5.4% of all cancers. Bonfil framed it as two populations. (A) High-prevalence regions — sub-Saharan Africa and SE Asia (China, Korea, Taiwan), >85% of cases — driven by chronic HBV: patients are young (20-40), and a self-corrected key point is that ~50% have NO cirrhosis. (B) Western (US) — driven by HCV (incidence nearly tripled since the 1980s): patients are >60 and ~90% have cirrhosis. The reconciling rule: HCC usually sits on a cirrhotic background, but cirrhosis is not required for hepatocarcinogenesis. Other risks: alcohol (synergizes with HBV/HCV), aflatoxin B1, NAFLD, hemochromatosis, alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency, and Wilson disease."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HCC — THE DRIVER-MUTATION TRIAD. The mechanism is repeated cycles of death and regeneration (chronic hepatitis) letting driver mutations accumulate. Three drivers are the high-yield set. (1) p53 via aflatoxin B1: aflatoxin is converted by hepatic CYP450 to an exo-8,9-epoxide that forms a guanine DNA adduct → a G:T transversion → inactivates p53 (~60% of aflatoxin-linked HCC). (2) CTNNB1/beta-catenin activating mutations → nuclear translocation, found in ~40% of non-HBV HCC — the same molecule as the high-risk adenoma subtype. (3) IL-6/JAK-STAT activation → downregulates HNF4-alpha → less hepatocyte differentiation, more proliferation. Precursors to know: large-cell change, small-cell change, and dysplastic nodules (high-grade = the most important precursor in viral hepatitis and alcoholic liver disease)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HCC triad: aflatoxin B1 → G:T transversion → p53 (~60%); CTNNB1/beta-catenin (~40% non-HBV); IL-6/JAK-STAT → HNF4-alpha down."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "HCC = ~5.4% of cancers; HBV/young/SE Asia = ~50% no cirrhosis; HCV/>60/US = ~90% cirrhosis; cirrhosis common but not required."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HCC MORPHOLOGY AND THE FIBROLAMELLAR VARIANT. Grossly, HCC is unifocal (one large mass), multifocal (varied sizes), or diffusely infiltrative. Microscopically it ranges from well-differentiated cells that resemble hepatocytes (thickened trabeculae, pseudoglandular spaces, dilated canaliculi — and the tell that the portal tract is missing) to highly anaplastic. Then the variant Bonfil told you to 'please remember': fibrolamellar carcinoma, 5% of HCCs, 85% at 20-40 y/o, no gender predilection, usually favorable prognosis — typically a single well-circumscribed 'scirrhous' mass traversed by fibrous bands. Its histology is the image hook: oncocytic (mitochondria-rich) hepatocytes growing in nests/cords interspersed with parallel lamellae of dense collagen. Clinically HCC gives upper-abdominal pain, weight loss, a nodular enlarged liver, and elevated serum AFP in 50-75%; prognosis is poor (most die within 2 years)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Fibrolamellar HCC = young (20-40), no cirrhosis, favorable; oncocytic cells + parallel lamellar collagen; AFP up in 50-75% of HCC."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Three adenoma subtypes by molecule → IHC → risk: HNF1a (L-FABP loss + steatosis), beta-catenin (nuclear IHC, very high malignant risk → surgery), inflammatory (gp130/IL-6/JAK-STAT → CRP). Beta-catenin is the bridge to HCC."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Fibrolamellar carcinoma is the HCC that is good news: young (20-40), no cirrhosis, favorable prognosis. Recognize it by oncocytic cells + parallel lamellae of dense collagen — Bonfil's 'please remember this' image."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Most common primary liver TUMOR = cavernous hemangioma (benign); most common primary liver CANCER = HCC; most common malignant liver tumor overall = metastasis. Three different superlatives — don't merge them."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Bonfil flagged the 3 hepatocellular-adenoma subtypes as the ones to 'remember.' Name each subtype's driver molecule, its diagnostic IHC stain, and its malignant risk — then give the HCC driver-mutation triad that the highest-risk subtype feeds into."}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Discuss the etiological factors, morphology, and diagnosis of cholangiocarcinoma", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Cholangiocarcinoma is an adenocarcinoma of the bile-duct epithelium — about one-sixth of all primary hepatic cancers. The three things to carry are the anatomic map (which tells you the Klatskin number), the etiologic risks (a fluke, a duct disease, and stones), and the desmoplastic morphology. Unlike HCC, intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma usually arises in a non-cirrhotic liver."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ANATOMY AND THE KLATSKIN NUMBER. Sort cholangiocarcinoma by site: intrahepatic (~10%), extrahepatic / distal common bile duct (20-30%), and perihilar — the Klatskin tumors — at the confluence (junction) of the right and left hepatic ducts, which make up 60% of all cases. The risk factors are the high-yield etiology cluster: Clonorchis sinensis liver fluke (cholangiocarcinoma is 30-40x more common in endemic SE Asia, e.g. Thailand), chronic large-duct inflammation (primary sclerosing cholangitis), hepatolithiasis, biliary cysts, fatty liver, and chronic HBV/HCV (HCC and cholangiocarcinoma can coexist in one patient)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cholangiocarcinoma sites: intrahepatic ~10%, extrahepatic 20-30%, perihilar (Klatskin) = 60% at the R/L hepatic-duct confluence."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Risks = Clonorchis sinensis (SE Asia 30-40x), PSC, hepatolithiasis, biliary cysts; histology = desmoplastic glandular adenocarcinoma, perineural invasion."}, {"t": "p", "x": "MORPHOLOGY AND DIAGNOSIS. Histologically cholangiocarcinoma resembles adenocarcinoma: well-to-moderately differentiated glands/tubules lined by cuboidal-to-low-columnar epithelium set in a dense desmoplastic (collagenous) stroma that separates the glands, with frequent lymphovascular and perineural invasion seeding intra- and extra-hepatic metastases. Clinically, perihilar/extrahepatic tumors present with biliary obstruction, cholangitis, and RUQ pain; intrahepatic tumors are found late (mean survival ~6 months after diagnosis). Curative radical resection is possible only in the minority without dissemination — otherwise treatment is palliative. (Clinical/surgical management is also covered in Lec 44/46; the pathology depth lives here.)"}, {"t": "q", "x": "Cholangiocarcinoma is a bile-duct adenocarcinoma. Where do most of them sit anatomically (and what is that location called), which infection is the classic SE-Asian risk factor, and what does the biopsy show?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Discuss the etiological factors, morphology, and diagnosis of metastatic tumors of the liver", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Bonfil bookended the lecture — intro and close — with the single high-yield fact of this LO: involvement of the liver by metastatic cancer is by far more common than primary hepatic tumors. About one-third of all carcinomas metastasize to the liver, so metastasis is the most common malignant liver tumor overall. Keep this distinct from the LO 51.1 superlatives: hemangioma is the most common primary tumor, HCC the most common primary cancer, but metastasis beats them all as a malignancy."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PRIMARIES, MORPHOLOGY, AND DIAGNOSIS. The most common primaries that metastasize to the liver are colon, breast, and lung. Grossly, metastases present as a few large lesions with central necrosis or as multiple small round lesions scattered throughout the organ — a multifocal pattern that contrasts with the solitary scar of FNH or the diffuse fine nodules of nodular regenerative hyperplasia. The first clue is often an unexplained rise in serum AFP or hepatomegaly, though ~1/3 of patients show no clinical or lab evidence of hepatic insufficiency. Complications track the anatomy: portal/hepatic-vein metastases → portal hypertension (splenomegaly, ascites), and bile-duct obstruction or parenchymal replacement → jaundice and elevated liver enzymes. A solitary metastasis (~20%) may be surgically curable; otherwise survival is usually ~1 year. On biopsy, cells morphologically distinct from hepatocytes with atypical nuclei plus a known prior primary make the call."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Metastasis = the most common malignant liver tumor (1/3 of all carcinomas); top primaries = colon, breast, lung."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Gross metastases = few large lesions w/ central necrosis or multiple small round nodules; solitary (~20%) may be resectable."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Bonfil opened AND closed the lecture with one fact about liver metastases. What is it, which primaries are responsible, and how do metastases look grossly compared with the primary tumors you just learned?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Merging the three 'most common liver tumor' superlatives. Most common primary liver TUMOR = cavernous hemangioma (benign). Most common primary liver CANCER = HCC. Most common malignant liver tumor overall = metastasis. Three different claims — a stem that drops 'benign,' 'primary,' or 'malignant' is steering you to the wrong one."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Mixing up the three adenoma IHC stains. HNF1a = L-FABP loss (+ steatosis, only here). Beta-catenin = nuclear beta-catenin (high malignant risk → surgery). Inflammatory = CRP overexpression (IL-6/JAK-STAT). One molecule, one stain, one risk each — don't cross-wire them."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Forgetting which adenoma subtype is dangerous. Only the beta-catenin-activated adenoma carries a very high malignant-transformation risk and warrants resection even if asymptomatic. HNF1a is low-risk; inflammatory is small-risk (higher only if beta-catenin is co-mutated). Nuclear beta-catenin is the surgical trigger."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Assigning the wrong driver mutation to HCC. Aflatoxin B1 → G:T transversion → p53 (~60% of aflatoxin-linked HCC); CTNNB1/beta-catenin in ~40% of non-HBV HCC; IL-6/JAK-STAT → HNF4-alpha downregulation. The aflatoxin→p53 transversion is the most-tested single fact."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Saying HCC always requires cirrhosis. Cirrhosis is the common background (~90% in Western/HCV disease), but it is NOT required. In high-prevalence HBV regions HCC strikes at 20-40 and ~50% have NO cirrhosis — and fibrolamellar carcinoma classically arises in a non-cirrhotic young liver."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Placing the Klatskin tumor in the wrong duct. Perihilar (Klatskin) = the confluence of the right and left hepatic ducts = 60% of cholangiocarcinomas. Intrahepatic is ~10% and extrahepatic/distal is 20-30%. The 60%/confluence pairing is the testable handle."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"most common primary tumor of the liver\" → cavernous hemangioma (benign). If the stem says 'cancer,' switch to HCC; if 'malignant tumor,' switch to metastasis."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"adenoma with absence of L-FABP and fatty change\" → HNF1a-inactivated adenoma — the only steatotic subtype; think MODY3 if germline."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"nuclear beta-catenin on IHC in a liver adenoma\" → beta-catenin-activated adenoma → very high malignant risk → resect even if asymptomatic."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"stored grain, Aspergillus, p53 mutation\" → aflatoxin B1 → G:T transversion → p53 inactivation in HCC."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"young SE-Asian HBV patient, no cirrhosis, liver cancer\" → HCC without cirrhosis (cirrhosis common but not required); if non-cirrhotic and 20-40 with lamellar collagen, think fibrolamellar."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"tumor at the junction of the right and left hepatic ducts\" → perihilar (Klatskin) cholangiocarcinoma — 60% of cases; recall the Clonorchis/PSC risks."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — HCC & cholangiocarcinoma — pathology here, clinic next door. Bonfil teaches the pathology (adenoma subtypes, HCC driver mutations, IHC, fibrolamellar, Klatskin) in full here. The clinical/surgical side of HCC and cholangiocarcinoma is covered in Lec 44/46 (gi 43-49.pdf) — resection, transplant/Milan criteria, Whipple. Same diseases, complementary angles."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — HBV → HCC is one thread across the GI block. The HBV → HCC link (here as the dominant worldwide driver, >85% of cases) is also developed in Lec 49 (viral-hepatitis sequelae). This lecture is the tumor-pathology home; the carcinogenesis mechanism (chronic injury → driver mutations) lives in the driver-triad here."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Beta-catenin / aflatoxin-p53 oncogenesis ties to the pancreas. The driver-mutation logic — beta-catenin (CTNNB1) and the aflatoxin→p53 transversion — rhymes with the KRAS / p53 / PanIN oncogenesis sequence of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma in Lec 52 (this doc): chronic injury and stepwise driver accumulation as the shared cancer theme."}]}]}, "52": {"prof": "Dr. Broderick Jones", "tldr": "Read the exocrine pancreas off enzyme autodigestion: acute pancreatitis converges on activated enzymes (lipase>amylase, CT, Turner/Cullen), chronic is irreversible fibrosis with pathognomonic calcifications, and ductal adenocarcinoma is the PanIN/KRAS-to-SMAD4 desmoplastic killer.", "mustKnows": ["1. Three initiating mechanisms, one convergence point. Acute pancreatitis starts three ways: (1) pancreatic duct obstruction (gallstones, neoplasms, parasites), (2) primary acinar cell injury (alcohol, drugs, ischemia — a Ca2+ influx inappropriately activates digestive enzymes), and (3) defective intracellular transport (role unclear). On the Robbins flowchart all three converge on acinar cell injury → ACTIVATED ENZYMES → autodigestion, the unifying lesion.", "2. Diagnose with lipase, image with CT. Jones hammered this: testing both amylase and lipase is discouraged; lipase should be PREFERRED over total/pancreatic amylase for the initial diagnosis (more specific). The radiographic test of choice is contrast-enhanced CT, with ductal calcifications pathognomonic. Treatment is supportive (IV fluids, analgesics, nutrition). The bedside urine trypsinogen-2 dipstick is >90% sensitive and specific.", "3. Turner vs Cullen — where the bruise is. Two hemorrhagic signs of severe acute pancreatitis sort by location. Turner's sign = flank ecchymosis (bruising in the flank areas). Cullen sign = periumbilical bruising/hemorrhage/edema around the umbilicus. Both indicate intraperitoneal or retroperitoneal hemorrhage. Full-blown acute pancreatitis is a medical emergency with a SIRS picture → DIC, ARDS, shock, and acute renal tubular necrosis.", "4. Chronic pancreatitis is irreversible alcohol fibrosis with pathognomonic calcifications. Chronic pancreatitis = prolonged inflammation with IRREVERSIBLE destruction of exocrine AND endocrine parenchyma; the #1 cause by far is long-term alcohol abuse. Morphology: fibrosis, acinar atrophy/dropout, duct dilation, and calcified concretions (islets are lost late). Calcifications are virtually pathognomonic (up to 90% of alcoholic cases); exocrine insufficiency → steatorrhea, weight loss, and secondary diabetes.", "5. Serous vs mucinous cystic neoplasm — benign vs premalignant. Serous cystadenoma = BENIGN, multicystic, small cysts (1-3 mm), glycogen-rich cuboidal cells, clear straw-colored fluid, ~25% of cystic neoplasms, 2x in women. Mucinous cystic neoplasm = women, thick tenacious mucin, columnar mucin-producing epithelium with ovarian-type stroma; ~1/3 progress to invasive carcinoma; mutations in KRAS, TP53, RNF43. Both favor the tail.", "6. PDAC: smoking #1, head 60%, the PanIN/KRAS sequence. Infiltrating ductal adenocarcinoma is the 4th leading cause of cancer deaths in the US. Smoking is the strongest environmental influence — it doubles the risk; BRCA2 ~10% (Ashkenazi Jews), LOF CDKN2A. It arises in the head ~60% (body 15%, tail 5%) as a firm, stellate, gray-white desmoplastic mass. The precursor is PanIN: KRAS early → p16/CDKN2A → TP53/SMAD4/BRCA2 late.", "7. Three paraneoplastic eponyms + the head-vs-tail rule. Trousseau sign = migratory thrombophlebitis (paraneoplastic thromboses that spontaneously appear and disappear). Courvoisier sign = a painless enlarged gallbladder from CBD obstruction (head tumors give obstructive jaundice). Leser-Trelat = eruptive seborrheic keratoses. Head tumors are found earlier (jaundice); body/tail stay silent until large and widely disseminated.", "8. CA 19-9 monitors; Whipple resects. CA 19-9 and CEA are serum tumor antigens — useful for following a patient's response to treatment, but nonspecific and lacking sensitivity (NOT screening tests). Biopsy is definitive for diagnosis. The surgical resection is the Whipple procedure (pancreaticoduodenectomy) — potentially curative or palliative; the specimen removes the duodenum, pancreatic head, and tumor en bloc.", "Acinar cells = 80-85% of pancreas, zymogen granules, autodigestion source", "Increased Ca2+ influx = trigger for inappropriate enzyme activation, acinar injury", "Lipase > amylase = preferred initial dx, more specific, testing both discouraged", "Contrast-enhanced CT = radiographic test of choice, ductal calcifications pathognomonic", "Urine trypsinogen-2 dipstick = >90% sens/spec, noninvasive bedside, acute pancreatitis", "Turner's sign = flank ecchymosis, retroperitoneal hemorrhage, severe acute", "Cullen sign = periumbilical bruising, intraperitoneal hemorrhage, severe acute", "Pancreatic calcifications = virtually pathognomonic of chronic, 90% alcoholic", "Chronic pancreatitis = irreversible, alcohol #1, exocrine insufficiency, secondary diabetes", "Serous cystadenoma = benign, glycogen-rich cuboidal, clear straw fluid, 2x women", "Mucinous cystic neoplasm = women, mucin, ~1/3 invasive carcinoma, KRAS/TP53/RNF43", "Pancreatic pseudocyst = non-neoplastic, no epithelial lining, post-pancreatitis", "Cigarette smoking = strongest PDAC risk, doubles the risk", "PanIN = noninvasive precursor in small ducts, KRAS early, SMAD4 late", "Trousseau sign = migratory thrombophlebitis, paraneoplastic, clots come and go", "Courvoisier sign = painless enlarged gallbladder, CBD obstruction, head tumor"], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Discuss the etiological factors, pathogenesis, morphology, diagnosis, and complications of acute and chronic pancreatitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The exocrine pancreas is 80-85% acinar cells packed with membrane-bound zymogen (proenzyme) granules — trypsinogen, chymotrypsinogen, procarboxypeptidase, proelastase, prophospholipase. Pancreatitis is what happens when those enzymes activate inside the gland and digest it. Acute pancreatitis is the acute onset of abdominal pain from enzymatic necrosis and inflammation; common triggers are gallstones, alcohol, and hyperlipidemia. Chronic pancreatitis is the irreversible end-state — fibrosis that follows repeated injury. Frame everything off the one idea: inappropriately activated digestive enzymes."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THREE INITIATING MECHANISMS. Jones organized pathogenesis into three routes. (1) Pancreatic duct obstruction — periampullary gallstones/biliary sludge, neoplasms (e.g., pancreatic cancer), choledochoceles, parasites (Ascaris, Clonorchis sinensis), cystic fibrosis — raises intrapancreatic ductal pressure, accumulates enzyme-rich fluid in the interstitium, releases proinflammatory cytokines, and compromises blood flow. (2) Primary acinar cell injury — alcohol, drugs, ischemia, viruses — causes release of digestive enzymes, inflammation, and autodigestion; an increased Ca2+ influx is the trigger for inappropriate enzyme activation. (3) Defective intracellular transport — delivery of proenzymes to the lysosomal compartment, with a role the slide calls 'not clear.'"}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ROBBINS CONVERGENCE FLOWCHART. The single highest-value figure: the three CAUSES (duct obstruction, acinar cell injury, defective transport) each run through their MECHANISMS and all converge on a central box — acinar cell injury → ACTIVATED ENZYMES. From there the LESIONS fan out: interstitial inflammation/edema, proteolysis (proteases), fat necrosis (lipase, phospholipase), and hemorrhage (elastase digesting vessel walls) — together = ACUTE PANCREATITIS. Alcohol works through several of these: it increases sphincter of Oddi contraction, has direct toxic effects on acinar cells, and generates oxidative stress / free radicals."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Three mechanisms — duct obstruction, acinar injury (Ca2+ trigger), defective transport — all converge on activated enzymes."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DIAGNOSIS — LIPASE, THEN CT. Jones drilled the labs: testing both amylase and lipase is discouraged (added cost, marginal benefit), and lipase should be PREFERRED over total and pancreatic amylase for the initial diagnosis (more specific). The radiographic test of choice is contrast-enhanced CT, with ductal calcifications pathognomonic; treatment is supportive (IV fluids, analgesics, nutritional support). A noninvasive bedside urine trypsinogen-2 dipstick is >90% sensitive and specific. Morphology of acute disease: microvascular leak + edema, fat necrosis, acute inflammation, destruction of parenchyma and blood vessels with interstitial hemorrhage."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Dx: lipase preferred over amylase; contrast CT = test of choice; urine trypsinogen-2 dipstick >90% sens/spec; treat supportive."}, {"t": "p", "x": "COMPLICATIONS — A MEDICAL EMERGENCY. Full-blown acute pancreatitis is a medical emergency with a systemic inflammatory response (SIRS): leukocytosis, DIC, edema with ARDS, shock, and acute renal tubular necrosis. Local complications: pseudocyst (peripancreatic fluid collection), splenic-vein thrombosis, pseudoaneurysm (splenic & gastroduodenal artery — the prof said 'take some notes'), and gastric outlet dysfunction. The two hemorrhagic skin signs sort by location: Turner's sign = flank ecchymosis; Cullen sign = periumbilical bruising. Both indicate intraperitoneal or retroperitoneal hemorrhage."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Turner's = flank; Cullen = periumbilical; both = intra-/retroperitoneal hemorrhage. SIRS → DIC, ARDS, shock, ARF."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CHRONIC PANCREATITIS — IRREVERSIBLE. Now the contrast. Chronic pancreatitis = prolonged inflammation with IRREVERSIBLE destruction of exocrine AND endocrine parenchyma; it follows repeated acute episodes (perilobular fibrosis, duct distortion, altered secretions). The #1 cause by far is long-term alcohol abuse (red-box slide). Morphology: fibrosis, acinar atrophy and dropout, variable duct dilation, a fibrotic/calcified gland with calcified concretions, ductal squamous metaplasia, and islets lost in advanced disease. Diagnosis: mild-to-moderate serum amylase elevation and visualization of calcifications — virtually pathognomonic, up to 90% of alcoholic cases (abdominal X-ray or CT). The consequence is pancreatic exocrine insufficiency → steatorrhea, weight loss/edema, and secondary diabetes."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Chronic = irreversible fibrosis, alcohol #1; calcifications pathognomonic (90% alcoholic); exocrine insufficiency → secondary diabetes."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Three mechanisms converge on activated enzymes (duct obstruction · acinar injury w/ Ca2+ trigger · defective transport). Dx = lipase>amylase + CT; Turner=flank, Cullen=periumbilical. Chronic = irreversible, alcohol #1, calcifications pathognomonic."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Acute vs chronic: acute can resolve (edema, fat necrosis, hemorrhage, SIRS) and is diagnosed by lipase + CT; chronic is irreversible fibrosis diagnosed by calcifications and ends in exocrine insufficiency + secondary diabetes."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Lipase over amylase — the prof's refrain. Testing both is discouraged; lipase is more specific and is the preferred initial lab, with contrast-enhanced CT as the imaging test of choice."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Acute pancreatitis is enzyme autodigestion of the gland. Name its three initiating mechanisms and the single event they converge on, give the preferred lab and imaging tests plus the two hemorrhagic signs, then say what makes CHRONIC pancreatitis fundamentally different."}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe the major pathological features of non-neoplastic and neoplastic masses of the pancreas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Pancreatic masses split into non-neoplastic (the post-inflammatory pseudocyst) and neoplastic cystic lesions. The Mayo schematic lays them out: serous cystadenoma, mucinous cystic neoplasm, main-duct and side-branch intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm (IPMN), cystic neuroendocrine tumor, and pseudocyst. The single most useful split is benign vs premalignant: serous is benign, the mucinous family is the one that turns into carcinoma. Diagnosis uses US/CT/MRI/PET, but biopsy is definitive."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Masses = non-neoplastic pseudocyst (no epithelium) vs neoplastic cysts; biopsy is definitive for diagnosis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "SEROUS CYSTADENOMA — BENIGN. The reassuring one. Serous cystadenomas are multicystic neoplasms that usually arise in the tail, made of small cysts (1-3 mm) lined by glycogen-rich cuboidal cells and filled with clear, thin, straw-colored fluid. They account for about 25% of cystic neoplasms, occur twice as often in women, cause nonspecific abdominal pain, and many are now found incidentally. The key word is BENIGN — the glycogen-rich cuboidal lining and clear fluid are the tells that separate it from its mucinous neighbor."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Serous cystadenoma = BENIGN, tail, small cysts, glycogen-rich cuboidal cells, clear straw fluid, 2x women."}, {"t": "p", "x": "MUCINOUS CYSTIC NEOPLASM — PREMALIGNANT. The one to worry about. Mucinous cystic neoplasms arise almost entirely in women, favor the tail, are filled with thick, tenacious mucin, and are lined by a columnar mucin-producing epithelium over a dense ovarian-type stroma. Crucially, ~1/3 of these precursors can progress to invasive carcinoma, and they carry mutations in KRAS, TP53, and RNF43. The IPMN variant is the same mucinous biology but intraductal — arising in the main pancreatic duct or its side branches. The pseudocyst, by contrast, is the non-neoplastic mass: a post-pancreatitis fluid collection walled by fibrous/granulation tissue with no true epithelial lining."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Mucinous cystic neoplasm = women, tail, mucin, ~1/3 → invasive carcinoma, KRAS/TP53/RNF43; IPMN = intraductal variant."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A pancreatic cyst lands on your desk. Walk the Mayo cystic-lesions map: which mass is non-neoplastic, which serous cyst is benign and why, and what makes the mucinous neoplasm the one to worry about?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Discuss the etiology, pathogenesis, morphology, and carcinoma of the pancreas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Infiltrating ductal adenocarcinoma is the 4th leading cause of cancer deaths in the US and has one of the highest mortality rates of any cancer. It is a disease of older adults — 80% of cases at 60-80 years, slightly more common in Black and in Ashkenazi-Jewish patients. Etiology: cigarette smoking is the strongest environmental influence and doubles the risk; a high-fat diet is implicated less consistently; chronic pancreatitis and diabetes are both risk factors AND complications. Inherited: germline BRCA2 ~10% (Ashkenazi Jews, even without a family history of breast/ovarian cancer/melanoma) and loss-of-function CDKN2A."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PATHOGENESIS — THE PanIN SEQUENCE. Pancreatic carcinoma evolves stepwise from precursor lesions: PanIN (pancreatic intraepithelial neoplasia), a noninvasive precursor in small ducts. The PanIN-to-invasive sequence is supported by shared genetic/epigenetic alterations and by PanIN being found adjacent to infiltrating carcinoma. The molecular order on the progression diagram: telomere shortening and KRAS mutation occur EARLY, CDKN2A/p16 inactivation in intermediate-grade lesions, and TP53, SMAD4, and BRCA2 inactivation LATE (high-grade PanIN-3). The slide cautions the accumulation of mutations matters more than their exact order."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Smoking #1 (doubles risk), BRCA2 ~10%, CDKN2A LOF. PanIN sequence: KRAS early → p16 → TP53/SMAD4/BRCA2 late."}, {"t": "p", "x": "MORPHOLOGY AND LOCATION. Carcinomas are firm, stellate, gray-white, poorly defined masses set in an intense desmoplastic (fibrous) stroma — so hard the prof joked the specimen 'breaks scalpel blades.' Location drives behavior: ~60% arise in the head, 15% in the body, 5% in the tail, and 20% diffusely involve the gland. Head tumors obstruct the common bile duct → obstructive jaundice, so they declare themselves earlier; body/tail tumors remain silent until large and widely disseminated. Pain is usually the first symptom; weight loss, anorexia, and malaise mark advanced disease."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE PARANEOPLASTIC EPONYMS + TUMOR MARKERS. Integrate the bedside signs. Trousseau sign = migratory thrombophlebitis — platelet-activating factors and procoagulants from the tumor drive thromboses that spontaneously appear and disappear. Courvoisier sign = a painless enlarged gallbladder from CBD/cystic-duct obstruction (a head-tumor sign). Leser-Trelat = eruptive seborrheic keratoses. Tumor markers: CA 19-9 and CEA are serum antigens useful for following response to treatment but nonspecific and lacking sensitivity — NOT screening or diagnostic tests (biopsy is definitive). The resection is the Whipple procedure (pancreaticoduodenectomy), potentially curative or palliative, removing the duodenum, pancreatic head, and tumor en bloc."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Eponyms: Trousseau (migratory thrombophlebitis), Courvoisier (painless gallbladder), Leser-Trelat (seborrheic keratoses); CA 19-9 monitors, Whipple resects."}, {"t": "key", "x": "PDAC: smoking #1 (doubles risk), BRCA2/CDKN2A; PanIN sequence KRAS-early → p16 → TP53/SMAD4/BRCA2-late; head 60%, firm desmoplastic mass; eponyms Trousseau / Courvoisier / Leser-Trelat; CA 19-9 monitors, Whipple resects."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Three eponyms: Trousseau = migratory thrombophlebitis (clots come and go), Courvoisier = painless enlarged gallbladder (head/CBD obstruction), Leser-Trelat = eruptive seborrheic keratoses. Don't blur them."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Head 60% declares early (obstructive jaundice + Courvoisier); body/tail stay silent until disseminated. CA 19-9 is for monitoring, not screening — biopsy is the definitive diagnosis."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma is the desmoplastic killer. Give its #1 risk factor and key mutations, build the PanIN molecular sequence, and integrate the head-vs-tail behavior with the three paraneoplastic eponyms, CA 19-9, and the Whipple."}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Ordering both amylase and lipase, or preferring amylase. The slide discourages testing both and says lipase should be PREFERRED over total/pancreatic amylase for the initial diagnosis (more specific). Don't reach for amylase first, and don't reflexively order both — lipase is the answer."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Swapping Turner's and Cullen signs. Turner's sign = FLANK ecchymosis; Cullen sign = PERIUMBILICAL bruising. Both indicate intra-/retroperitoneal hemorrhage in severe acute pancreatitis. Flank vs umbilicus is the whole distinction — don't flip them."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Calling chronic pancreatitis reversible. Chronic pancreatitis is IRREVERSIBLE — prolonged inflammation destroys exocrine AND endocrine parenchyma and replaces it with fibrosis. Acute disease can resolve; once chronic disease sets in, 'there's nothing you can do.'"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Mixing up serous and mucinous cystic neoplasms. Serous cystadenoma = BENIGN, glycogen-rich cuboidal cells, clear straw-colored fluid. Mucinous cystic neoplasm = women, thick mucin, columnar epithelium, ~1/3 → invasive carcinoma (KRAS/TP53/RNF43). Benign vs premalignant is the split."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Putting the wrong eponym on the wrong sign. Trousseau = migratory thrombophlebitis (clots come and go); Courvoisier = painless enlarged gallbladder (head/CBD obstruction); Leser-Trelat = eruptive seborrheic keratoses. Three different paraneoplastic handles — keep them straight."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Using CA 19-9 to screen for or diagnose pancreatic cancer. CA 19-9 (and CEA) are for following response to treatment — they are nonspecific and lack sensitivity, so they are NOT screening or diagnostic tests. Biopsy is definitive for the diagnosis."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. Assuming TP53/SMAD4 mutate early in PanIN. On the progression model, KRAS and telomere shortening are EARLY; CDKN2A/p16 is intermediate; TP53, SMAD4, and BRCA2 are LATE (high-grade PanIN-3). Don't front-load the late tumor-suppressor hits."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. Everything converges on activated enzymes. Three mechanisms (duct obstruction · acinar injury · defective transport) all funnel into acinar cell injury → ACTIVATED ENZYMES → edema, proteolysis, fat necrosis, hemorrhage = acute pancreatitis."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. Lipase, CT, dipstick. Diagnose acute pancreatitis with lipase (preferred over amylase) and contrast-enhanced CT (test of choice); the bedside urine trypsinogen-2 dipstick is >90% sensitive and specific. Treat supportively."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. Acute hemorrhages; chronic calcifies. Turner's = flank, Cullen = periumbilical hemorrhage in acute disease. Chronic = irreversible fibrosis, alcohol #1, with calcifications virtually pathognomonic (90% of alcoholic cases)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. Benign serous, premalignant mucinous. Serous cystadenoma = benign (glycogen-rich cuboidal, clear fluid). Mucinous cystic neoplasm = women, mucin, ~1/3 → invasive carcinoma (KRAS/TP53/RNF43). The pseudocyst is the non-neoplastic mass."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. Smoking is the #1 PDAC risk. Cigarette smoking doubles the risk of pancreatic adenocarcinoma — the strongest environmental factor. Inherited: BRCA2 ~10% (Ashkenazi Jews) and LOF CDKN2A."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. The PanIN molecular ladder. KRAS + telomere shortening early → CDKN2A/p16 intermediate → TP53/SMAD4/BRCA2 late. PanIN is the noninvasive precursor in small ducts; accumulation matters more than order."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. Head declares, body/tail hide. Head (~60%) tumors give obstructive jaundice + Courvoisier and are caught earlier; body/tail stay silent until disseminated. CA 19-9 monitors; the Whipple resects."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — This is the pathology/morphology home of pancreatitis. Pancreatitis recurs across the GI block — Lec 46 (surgical, in gi 43-49.pdf) and the merged Lec 53/54 (clinical: Ranson criteria, 2-of-3 dx, treatment) — but 52 is where the morphology and pathogenesis live (the three mechanisms, the Robbins convergence, the calcification/fibrosis picture). Teach it fully here; cross-reference the clinical workups."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — PDAC is taught fully here on its molecular/morphologic side. Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma also appears in Lec 53/54 (clinical staging, NET eponyms) and Lec 46 (Whipple, surgical); 52 owns the PanIN/KRAS-to-SMAD4 sequence, the desmoplastic morphology, and the paraneoplastic eponyms. The Whipple's triad (insulinoma, Lec 54) is a DIFFERENT eponym from the Whipple procedure taught here — keep them distinct."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — The pseudocyst is the shared pancreatitis complication. The pancreatic pseudocyst (post-acute fluid collection, no epithelial lining) is introduced here as a non-neoplastic mass and a complication of acute pancreatitis; Lec 46 (gi 43-49.pdf) and Lec 53/54 carry its clinical/surgical management. Courvoisier sign also threads to the obstructive-jaundice teaching in Lec 50."}]}]}, "53": {"prof": "Dr. Ari Lamet", "tldr": "Pancreatitis by the numbers: gallstones + alcohol ≈ 90%, diagnose on lipase >3× ULN + 2-of-3, stage with Ranson, treat fluids first / no prophylactic antibiotics; then chronic (alcohol, fecal elastase) and the pancreatic NET eponyms.", "mustKnows": ["1. Gallstones + alcohol = ~90% of acute pancreatitis. Two causes dominate: gallstones (incl. biliary sludge/microlithiasis, 30-45%) and alcohol (30-45%) → together ~90% of cases. A gallstone elevates transaminases >3x ULN with high PPV. The rest are zebras: hypertriglyceridemia (TG >1000), hypercalcemia, post-ERCP, drugs, scorpion venom, and ampullary obstruction (Ascaris, Lemmel, pancreas divisum, tumors).", "2. Diagnosis is 2-of-3 — so imaging is NOT required. Acute pancreatitis needs 2 of 3 criteria: (1) clinical presentation (acute severe epigastric pain radiating to the back ± n/v); (2) lipase OR amylase >3x ULN; (3) characteristic findings on imaging (CT/MR/US). Because the first two alone suffice, imaging is NOT required to make the diagnosis (the yellow-highlighted, STAR-slide point). Imaging still helps stage severity and exclude mimics.", "3. Lipase beats amylase, and the threshold is 3x ULN. Amylase is nonspecific (pancreas AND salivary glands) and must be >3x ULN. Lipase rises earlier and lasts longer, is more specific, and must also be >3x ULN. A mildly elevated enzyme (the ER lipase of 450-550) does not count — Lamet drilled the 3x-ULN rule. WBC and CRP are the supporting inflammatory markers.", "4. Cullen's vs Grey-Turner's — periumbilical vs flank. Cullen's sign = periumbilical ecchymosis (C for the Circle around the umbilicus). Grey-Turner's sign = flank ecchymosis. Both are nonspecific but suggest retroperitoneal bleeding in the setting of pancreatic necrosis, and occur in only ~3% of patients. Lamet flagged this pair 'for the exam coming up.'", "5. Chronic pancreatitis: alcohol #1, and the 90% rule. Chronic pancreatitis (CP) is progressive inflammation causing permanent structural damage. Etiology: alcohol ~70% (#1), idiopathic/tropical ~20%, other ~10%; gallstones are NOT a cause of CP. The load-bearing rule: deficiencies do not appear until >90% of pancreatic function is lost, and <10% of alcoholics ever develop CP.", "6. The CP clinical picture. Abdominal pain is dominant — typically epigastric, radiating to the back (may be absent). The late-loss findings follow: exocrine insufficiency → fat malabsorption → steatorrhea and weight loss, plus pancreatic (secondary) diabetes from islet destruction, usually insulin-requiring — all gated by the same >90%-loss threshold.", "7. Diagnosing CP: enzymes fail, fecal elastase wins. Serum amylase/lipase may be elevated, NORMAL, or low in CP — so they are NOT diagnostic (opposite of acute, >3x ULN). Test exocrine output instead: steatorrhea >7 g fat/day = malabsorption; 72-hr fecal fat is the gold standard; fecal elastase is the test of choice, <200 mcg/g = insufficiency. Imaging: calcifications and ductal dilation; MRCP now the test of choice, ERCP when no calcifications.", "8. The double duct sign = pancreatic-head cancer. The double duct sign (GOLD-STAR slide) is dilation of BOTH the pancreatic duct and the common bile duct on CT or MRCP — a mass at the pancreatic head obstructing both. Lamet: patients with that finding 'you can assume are dealing with pancreatic cancer.' It ties to the classic painless jaundice + weight loss presentation and the serum tumor marker CA 19-9 of ductal adenocarcinoma.", "Gallstones + alcohol = ~90% of acute pancreatitis, ~30-45% each", "Hypertriglyceridemia (AP) = serum TG >1000 mg/dL, must order it", "Cullen's sign = periumbilical ecchymosis, retroperitoneal bleed, ~3%", "Grey-Turner's sign = flank ecchymosis, pancreatic necrosis, nonspecific", "Lipase vs amylase = lipase more specific, earlier + longer, both >3x ULN", "2-of-3 diagnosis = pain + enzymes >3x ULN + imaging; imaging NOT required", "Ranson admission five = age>55, WBC>16k, glucose>200, AST>250, LDH>350", "Ranson 7-8 criteria = 100% mortality; 0-2 = 2%", "Chronic pancreatitis #1 cause = alcohol ~70%, <10% of alcoholics", "Gallstones = cause ACUTE, not chronic; not a CP cause", "90% function-loss rule = steatorrhea only after >90% lost", "Fecal elastase <200 mcg/g = exocrine insufficiency, test of choice", "Pancreatic calcifications = chronic pancreatitis, plain film/CT", "Double duct sign = pancreatic + bile duct dilated, head cancer", "CA 19-9 = serum marker, ductal adenocarcinoma", "Cyst-fluid CEA >192-200 = mucinous cyst, premalignant (serous = low)"], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "List the causes of acute pancreatitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Acute pancreatitis is an acute inflammatory process of the pancreas, driven by intracellular activation of digestive enzymes (trypsinogen → trypsin, which then autocatalyzes the other proenzymes) so the gland digests itself. Lamet built the etiology block around one pair you cannot miss: gallstones and alcohol together account for ~90% of cases. Everything else is a zebra worth recognizing but rarely the answer. Anatomically the set-up is the shared ampulla of Vater (main pancreatic duct + common bile duct, ringed by the sphincter of Oddi) — anything that obstructs it can back up pancreatic juice and ignite pancreatitis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE TOP TWO. Gallstones (including biliary sludge and microlithiasis) cause 30-45% of cases — a stone passing the cystic duct into the common bile duct can lodge at the ampulla; a gallstone etiology raises transaminases >3x ULN with high positive predictive value. Alcohol causes another 30-45%. Those two together are Lamet's 'almost 90% of cases.' Then come the metabolic causes: hypertriglyceridemia (serum TG >1000 mg/dL — you only catch it if you order the level) and hypercalcemia."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Gallstones (30-45%) + alcohol (30-45%) = ~90% of acute pancreatitis; a gallstone cause bumps transaminases >3x ULN."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE IATROGENIC, TOXIC, AND INFLAMMATORY ZEBRAS. Post-ERCP pancreatitis happens even with a flawless procedure (asymptomatic hyperamylasemia in 35-70%). Drugs are idiosyncratic, usually within the first 2 months — azathioprine/6-MP, sulfasalazine, ACE-inhibitors, didanosine, valproate, estrogens. Scorpion venom is the classic toxin (Tityus trinitatis / T. serrulatus, Trinidad and Brazil). Infections (HIV/AIDS, bacterial/parasitic) and lymphoplasmacytic sclerosing (autoimmune) pancreatitis round out the list, alongside hereditary, trauma, and idiopathic."}, {"t": "p", "x": "AMPULLARY OBSTRUCTION — THE THREE FIGURES. Anything that blocks the ampulla can do it. Biliary ascariasis — the roundworm projects right out of the ampulla of Vater on duodenoscopy. A periampullary diverticulum compressing the papilla is Lemmel syndrome (Lamet's 'good to be pimped on rounds' zebra). Pancreas divisum — the dorsal and ventral pancreatic buds fail to fuse, so the bulk of the gland drains through the small minor papilla via the duct of Santorini (the duct of Wirsung drains only the ventral portion through the major papilla) — a congenital cause of obstructive pancreatitis. Periampullary tumors complete the obstructive set."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Ampullary obstruction figures: Ascaris at the ampulla · Lemmel (periampullary diverticulum) · pancreas divisum (bud non-fusion)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Gallstones + alcohol = ~90% of acute pancreatitis (each 30-45%). The zebras: TG >1000, hypercalcemia, post-ERCP, drugs, scorpion venom, and ampullary obstruction (Ascaris, Lemmel, pancreas divisum, tumors)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Hypertriglyceridemia only counts as a cause at TG >1000 mg/dL, and you have to order the level — it is invisible unless you look for it."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Pancreas divisum = failure of the dorsal + ventral buds to fuse; the gland then drains through the small minor papilla (duct of Santorini) — a congenital obstructive cause."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Lamet spent the largest block of the hour on causes and kept returning to one pair. Name the two causes that together reach ~90%, then run the zebra list by category (metabolic, iatrogenic, toxic, obstructive) and match the three obstructive figures to their causes."}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe the history, clinical manifestations, and diagnosis of acute pancreatitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW — THE HISTORY. The classic presentation is acute onset of persistent, severe epigastric pain that radiates to the back, often with nausea and vomiting; the pain may ease when the patient sits or leans forward. Severe acute pancreatitis can add dyspnea (diaphragmatic inflammation, pleural effusions, or ARDS); rarely a severe case presents with respiratory failure or altered mental status and no abdominal pain. Physical findings track severity — epigastric-to-generalized tenderness, a possible ileus with hypoactive bowel sounds, and in severe cases fever, tachycardia, hypoxemia, and hypotension."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CULLEN'S VS GREY-TURNER'S. Two ecchymosis signs are the bedside flags of severe, necrotizing disease. Cullen's sign = periumbilical ecchymosis (anchor it as the Circle around the umbilicus). Grey-Turner's sign = flank ecchymosis. Both are nonspecific but suggest retroperitoneal bleeding in the setting of pancreatic necrosis, and they occur in only ~3% of patients — Lamet flagged the pair 'for the exam coming up.'"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cullen's = periumbilical ecchymosis; Grey-Turner's = flank; both nonspecific, retroperitoneal bleed in necrosis, ~3%."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE LABS. Serum amylase is nonspecific (released by pancreas AND salivary glands) and must be >3x ULN. Serum lipase elevates earlier and lasts longer, is more specific, and must also be >3x ULN. Lamet hammered this: a lipase of 450-550 that everyone calls 'pancreatitis' is not diagnostic unless it clears three times the upper limit. WBC and CRP are the supporting inflammatory markers."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE DIAGNOSIS — 2 OF 3 (THE STAR SLIDE). Acute pancreatitis requires 2 of the following 3 criteria: (1) the clinical presentation (acute severe epigastric pain radiating to the back, ± n/v); (2) lipase or amylase >3x ULN; (3) characteristic findings of AP on imaging (CT, MR, or US). The yellow-highlighted punchline: because any two suffice, imaging is NOT required to make the diagnosis — if you already have the pain and the enzymes, you have it. Imaging still earns its keep for staging severity and excluding mimics."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Dx = 2 of 3: clinical presentation · lipase/amylase >3x ULN · imaging. Any two suffice → imaging NOT required."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Acute pancreatitis = 2 of 3: (1) classic pain (epigastric → back, n/v), (2) lipase/amylase >3x ULN, (3) imaging. Because two suffice, imaging is NOT required to diagnose AP — the starred, yellow-highlighted point."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Cullen's vs Grey-Turner's: Cullen's is periumbilical (Circle around the umbilicus), Grey-Turner's is flank. Both are nonspecific signs of retroperitoneal bleeding in necrosis, seen in only ~3%."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Lipase beats amylase (more specific, rises earlier, lasts longer) — but the threshold for either is the same: >3x ULN. A merely 'high' lipase doesn't count."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Lamet starred the Diagnosis slide and highlighted one sentence in yellow. State the 2-of-3 diagnostic criteria, give the exact enzyme threshold, explain what that rule means about imaging, and pair the two ecchymosis signs to their locations."}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Discuss Ranson criteria for acute pancreatitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Ranson criteria were established to differentiate mild from severe (originally alcohol-induced) acute pancreatitis; higher scores mean higher morbidity and mortality. The score answers the clinical question on admission: is this patient going to improve on the floor, or head toward organ failure and the ICU? The catch is timing — 11 criteria scored across 48 hours (5 on admission, 6 at 48h). Lamet's exam rule: 'not that you have to calculate it, but you have to know what does and doesn't fall into Ranson criteria.'"}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE FIVE ON ADMISSION. Age >55, WBC >16,000, glucose >200, AST >250, and LDH >350. These are mostly readily available on a standard admission panel — except the LDH, which a classic patient won't have unless it is specifically ordered. That 'is the LDH already drawn?' detail is exactly the kind of recognition the exam tests."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Ranson on admission (5): age >55 · WBC >16k · glucose >200 · AST >250 · LDH >350."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SIX AT 48 HOURS. Hematocrit drop >10%, BUN rise >5, serum calcium <8, PaO2 <60, base deficit >4, and estimated fluid sequestration >6 L. These are not all routinely available unless you go out of your way to obtain them. Mortality climbs with the count: 0-2 = 2%, 3-4 ~15%, 5-6 ~40%, and 7-8 = 100%. There is also a simplified Glasgow score — Lamet stamped it 'you don't need to know this.'"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Ranson at 48h: Hct ↓>10% · BUN ↑>5 · Ca <8 · PaO2 <60 · base deficit >4 · fluid >6L. Mortality 0-2=2% → 7-8=100%."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Ranson admission (5): age >55, WBC >16k, glucose >200, AST >250, LDH >350. At 48h (6): Hct ↓>10%, BUN ↑>5, Ca <8, PaO2 <60, base deficit >4, fluid >6L. Mortality 0-2 = 2% → 7-8 = 100%."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Know what falls into Ranson, not how to calculate it — Lamet's exact framing. The discriminator stems are 'is this an admission or a 48-hour value?'"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Don't put a 48-hour value (Hct drop, calcium, PaO2, fluid sequestration) on the admission list. Admission is the age/WBC/glucose/AST/LDH five."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Lamet starred both Ranson slides and said 'not that you have to calculate it, but you have to know what does and doesn't fall into Ranson criteria.' List the five admission values, name a couple of the 48-hour values, and give the mortality for the lowest and highest score bands."}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "List the differential diagnosis and complications of acute pancreatitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "DIFFERENTIAL DIAGNOSIS. Sudden severe epigastric pain with n/v is shared by a row of acute-abdomen emergencies, so the differential is wide: peptic ulcer disease, choledocholithiasis / cholangitis, cholecystitis, perforated viscus (e.g., a large ulcer that perforated), intestinal obstruction, mesenteric ischemia, and hepatitis — with myocardial infarction the classic must-not-miss add. A CT on presentation is valuable precisely because it rules out several of these (free air, an inflamed gallbladder) at once."}, {"t": "p", "x": "LOCAL COMPLICATIONS — THE 4-WEEK RULE. Acute pancreatitis can recur and can progress to chronic pancreatitis. Locally: an acute peripancreatic fluid collection appears early, has no defining wall, and usually resolves on its own (observe). A pancreatic pseudocyst is fluid contained by a wall of fibrosis/granulation tissue with NO epithelial lining; it requires ~4 weeks to form, occurs in ~10%, and is observed if asymptomatic. Acute necrotic collections (start sterile, may infect) mature into walled-off necrosis after 4 weeks. The yellow-highlighted rule: hold invasive intervention ≥4 weeks to let the body wall it off — outcomes improve."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Complications: local = fluid collection → pseudocyst (no lining, 4 wks) → walled-off necrosis (≥4 wks before intervention); systemic = ARDS/shock/renal failure."}, {"t": "p", "x": "SYSTEMIC COMPLICATIONS. Beyond the gland, acute pancreatitis can exacerbate underlying comorbidities and precipitate organ failure: respiratory failure / ARDS, shock, and renal failure. Early mortality (first ~2 weeks) is driven by SIRS and organ failure; later deaths are driven by infection/sepsis — which is exactly why the 4-week wall-off rule and selective (not prophylactic) antibiotics matter."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Acute pancreatitis looks like several other acute-abdomen emergencies. List the differentials, then sort the complications into local and systemic and state the one timing rule (4 weeks) that governs when to intervene."}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Describe the treatment for acute pancreatitis", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW — FLUIDS FIRST. The management of acute pancreatitis is largely supportive, and the first step is always aggressive isotonic crystalloid — normal saline or lactated Ringer's. Given in the first 12-24 hours, fluid resuscitation reduces morbidity and mortality. You then monitor: vital signs, urine output, and reduction in BUN/hematocrit. Lamet's bedside point — a pancreatitis patient lying tachycardic in bed is decompensating until proven otherwise; vitals are vital."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Step 1 = aggressive isotonic fluids (NS or LR), first 12-24h → ↓morbidity/mortality; monitor vitals + urine output."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PAIN CONTROL — THE MEPERIDINE BOARD MYTH. Here is the classic exam-vs-reality split. Meperidine was 'favored' over morphine on board questions, on the theory that morphine raises sphincter-of-Oddi pressure. But no clinical studies support this, and in actuality morphine is and can be given. Lamet called it 'a board-style question that would always come up' — know the traditional answer, but know it is a myth."}, {"t": "p", "x": "NUTRITION, ANTIBIOTICS, AND THE CAUSE. Feed the gut: nasojejunal (NJ) enteral nutrition is preferred over TPN, even in sick ICU patients who have no appetite and find feeding painful — maintaining enteral nutrition beats total parenteral nutrition. Prophylactic antibiotics are NOT recommended; antibiotics are reserved for a suspected or proven active infection, not given routinely. Finally, treat the underlying cause — e.g., remove an obstructing CBD stone (ERCP) and arrange cholecystectomy for gallstone pancreatitis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "NJ feeds > TPN; NO prophylactic antibiotics (only for proven infection); treat the cause; meperidine = board myth, morphine OK."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Treatment order: (1) aggressive isotonic fluids FIRST (NS/LR, first 12-24h), (2) NJ enteral feeds > TPN, (3) NO prophylactic antibiotics (proven infection only), (4) treat the cause. Pain: meperidine = board answer, morphine = reality."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Prophylactic antibiotics are NOT part of the plan for acute pancreatitis — a discrete, exam-flagged 'do-not-do.' Reserve antibiotics for a suspected/proven infection."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "The meperidine-over-morphine teaching is a board myth (the sphincter-of-Oddi story has no clinical support). Pick meperidine for the exam if forced, but morphine is fine in practice."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Lamet gave a short, ordered treatment list with two explicit exam flags. What is the first step, what nutrition route wins, what is NOT recommended, and what is the famous board-vs-reality split on pain control?"}]}, {"id": 6, "statement": "Discuss chronic pancreatitis with regard to the etiology and clinical findings", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Chronic pancreatitis (CP) is a syndrome of progressive inflammatory change that produces permanent structural damage and impaired exocrine and endocrine function. It contrasts with acute pancreatitis (AP), an acute, usually non-progressive inflammatory response; recurrent episodes of AP may eventually lead to CP. Lamet built this hour on two anchors: the etiology (alcohol dominates) and the >90%-function-loss rule that gates every clinical finding."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ETIOLOGY — ALCOHOL FIRST. The breakdown on the slide: alcohol abuse ~70% (the #1 cause), idiopathic (including tropical/nutritional) ~20%, and other ~10% (hereditary, hyperparathyroidism, hypertriglyceridemia, autoimmune pancreatitis, obstruction, trauma, pancreas divisum). Two cautions Lamet drilled: gallstone (biliary) pancreatitis is NOT listed as a cause of CP (it causes acute pancreatitis — you can reassure those patients), and cigarette smoking increases the risk of both acute and chronic pancreatitis. On the mechanism: ethanol and its metabolites activate pancreatic stellate cells to drive the fibrosis, but it is dose-related and idiosyncratic — fewer than 10% of alcoholics develop CP, usually after 6-12 years of heavy intake."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "CP etiology: alcohol ~70% (#1), idiopathic ~20%, other ~10%; gallstones do NOT cause CP; smoking raises risk."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CLINICAL FINDINGS AND THE 90% RULE. The dominant symptom is abdominal pain — typically epigastric, radiating to the back, often with nausea/vomiting (it can also be absent). The rest of the picture is loss-of-function, and here is the rule Lamet repeated four times: protein and fat deficiencies do not occur until more than 90% of pancreatic function is lost (the gland has enormous reserve, so disease is far advanced before deficits show). Once past that threshold: exocrine insufficiency → fat malabsorption → steatorrhea (loose, greasy, foul-smelling, hard-to-flush stools) and weight loss; and endocrine loss → pancreatic (secondary) diabetes, usually insulin-requiring. One advancing fibrosis explains both the steatorrhea and the diabetes."}, {"t": "cq", "x": ">90% of pancreatic function must be lost before steatorrhea/malabsorption appear; then exocrine + endocrine fail together."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "CP clinical: back-radiating pain, steatorrhea + weight loss (exocrine), insulin-requiring secondary diabetes (endocrine)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Chronic pancreatitis = alcohol ~70% (#1), idiopathic ~20%, other ~10%; gallstones are NOT a CP cause. Clinical deficits (steatorrhea, weight loss, secondary diabetes) only surface after >90% of function is lost."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Gallstones cause ACUTE pancreatitis, not chronic. Lamet re-taught this in Q&A: pancreatic-duct stones are diagnostic of CP, but gallstones do not cause CP — reassure the biliary-pancreatitis patient."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Steatorrhea and secondary diabetes are two faces of one advanced fibrosis: exocrine acini and endocrine islets are both destroyed once the gland is >90% gone, so they tend to appear together late in the disease."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Lamet hammered the 90%-function-loss rule and insisted gallstones do NOT cause chronic pancreatitis. Name the #1 etiology, explain why an alcoholic with CP develops BOTH steatorrhea AND insulin-requiring diabetes, and state the threshold that gates those findings."}]}, {"id": 7, "statement": "Describe the uses of the various tests necessary to diagnose acute and chronic pancreatitis and tumors of the pancreas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. This objective is the diagnostic toolkit across acute pancreatitis, chronic pancreatitis, and pancreatic tumors — Lamet operationalized it through two case workups. The spine: serum enzymes are an acute test (not chronic), fecal elastase is the exocrine test of choice, and a handful of imaging/marker findings (double-duct sign, CA 19-9, cyst-fluid CEA) point at tumors."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ENZYMES — ACUTE YES, CHRONIC NO. In acute pancreatitis, amylase/lipase >3x the upper limit of normal support the diagnosis (the Lec 53 half of this block). In chronic pancreatitis the gland is largely burned out, so serum pancreatic enzymes may be elevated, NORMAL, or low — and are therefore NOT diagnostic; during an acute-on-chronic flare they may rise mildly but seldom reach AP levels. For chronic exocrine function, test the output instead: steatorrhea >7 g fat/day = malabsorption, the 72-hr fecal fat collection is the gold standard, and fecal elastase is the test of choice — a single random stool, with <200 mcg/g suggestive of pancreatic insufficiency."}, {"t": "p", "x": "IMAGING — CALCIFICATIONS AND THE DUCTS. For CP, imaging climbs in yield: a plain film may show speckled calcification (sens 30-40%), US and CT show ductal dilation, calcifications, and atrophy (CT sens ~80%), ERCP is the test of choice when calcifications are absent, MRCP has become the test of choice, and on EUS the presence of stones is the most predictive feature of CP. For tumors, the headline finding is the double duct sign (GOLD-STAR slide): simultaneous dilation of both the pancreatic duct and the common bile duct on CT/MRCP, from a mass at the pancreatic head obstructing both — assume pancreatic cancer. It pairs with painless jaundice + weight loss and a rising serum CA 19-9."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Acute: amylase/lipase >3x ULN. Chronic: enzymes may be high/normal/low — NOT diagnostic; use fecal elastase <200."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Double duct sign (CT/MRCP) = both pancreatic duct + CBD dilated = pancreatic-head cancer; serum marker CA 19-9."}, {"t": "p", "x": "TUMOR-MARKER NUANCE. Keep two markers straight: CA 19-9 is the serum marker for ductal adenocarcinoma (used to monitor, not screen), while CEA is read from cyst-fluid to triage a cystic lesion — an elevated cyst-fluid CEA above the ~192-200 ng/mL threshold points to a mucinous (premalignant) cyst rather than a benign serous one. Tissue is obtained by EUS-guided biopsy when a diagnosis or resectability decision is needed."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Lamet ran two Socratic cases to teach the tests. State why serum enzymes work for ACUTE but fail for CHRONIC pancreatitis, name the test of choice for exocrine insufficiency, and explain what the double-duct sign tells you in a 68-year-old with painless jaundice."}]}, {"id": 8, "statement": "List the various benign and malignant tumors of the pancreas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Sort pancreatic tumors into the exocrine (non-endocrine) majority and the endocrine (neuroendocrine, NET / islet-cell) minority. The exocrine group holds the common malignancies; the endocrine group is a dense eponym catalog Lamet flagged with gold stars — each functioning NET is named by the hormone it oversecretes and the syndrome that follows."}, {"t": "p", "x": "EXOCRINE TUMORS. Solid: pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma — the most common exocrine neoplasm and what people mean by 'pancreatic cancer' (painless jaundice, weight loss, marker CA 19-9, poor 5-year survival) — plus acinar cell carcinoma. Cystic: serous cystadenoma (benign, older women, central scar/'sunburst', low cyst-fluid CEA <5); mucinous cystadenoma/cystadenocarcinoma (women, body/tail, elevated cyst-fluid CEA ≥192-200, premalignant); intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm (IPMN) (main- vs side-branch duct, malignant potential); and solid pseudopapillary neoplasm (SPN) (young women, low-grade malignancy, treated by surgical resection)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Exocrine: ductal adenocarcinoma (#1), acinar; cystic = serous (benign, low CEA) / mucinous (CEA ≥192-200, premalignant) / IPMN / SPN."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ENDOCRINE NETs — THE EPONYM SET. Insulinoma is the most common pancreatic NET: diagnosed by Whipple's triad (hypoglycemia symptoms with fasting + glucose <50 + relief with glucose), confirmed by a supervised 72-hr fast. Gastrinoma is the 2nd most common = Zollinger-Ellison syndrome: excess gastrin → refractory peptic ulcers (+ diarrhea); ~25% are part of MEN-1; and ~90% arise in the gastrinoma triangle (superior = confluence of the cystic and common bile ducts; inferior = junction of the 2nd and 3rd parts of the duodenum; medial = junction of the neck and body of the pancreas). Glucagonoma → necrolytic migratory erythema (a cyclic rash that migrates with central healing) + mild diabetes, stomatitis, anemia, weight loss. VIPoma = WDHA / Verner-Morrison: watery diarrhea ~5 L/day, hypokalemia, achlorhydria. Somatostatinoma is extremely rare (<1 in 40 million): steatorrhea, diabetes, cholelithiasis; associated with neurofibromatosis and pheochromocytoma. Non-functional islet-cell tumors make no syndrome and present as space-occupying head/neck/uncinate masses."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Insulinoma Whipple's triad · Gastrinoma Zollinger-Ellison + triangle (90%) · Glucagonoma necrolytic migratory erythema."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "VIPoma = WDHA / Verner-Morrison, watery diarrhea ~5 L/day · Somatostatinoma rare (steatorrhea/diabetes/gallstones)."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Two buckets: exocrine (ductal adenocarcinoma #1, plus acinar, serous/mucinous cystadenoma, IPMN, SPN) and endocrine NETs read by eponym — insulinoma (Whipple's triad), gastrinoma (Zollinger-Ellison + triangle), glucagonoma (necrolytic migratory erythema), VIPoma (WDHA)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Gastrinoma triangle = cystic/CBD confluence (superior), 2nd-3rd duodenal junction (inferior), pancreatic neck-body junction (medial); ~90% of gastrinomas live there."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Whipple's TRIAD diagnoses an insulinoma (hypoglycemia/glucose<50/relief). The Whipple PROCEDURE is a pancreaticoduodenectomy for ductal adenocarcinoma (Lec 52/46). Same name, opposite ends of the tumor map."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Lamet gold-starred the NET eponyms. List the exocrine tumors (naming the #1 malignancy) and then match each functioning NET to its hallmark — insulinoma, gastrinoma, glucagonoma, VIPoma, somatostatinoma — including the gastrinoma triangle's three corners."}]}, {"id": 9, "statement": "Differentiate between exocrine and endocrine types of tumors", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. The whole of LO 53.9 is one clean definitional contrast. Exocrine glands secrete a substance out through a duct; endocrine glands secrete a hormone into the bloodstream ('glands of external' vs 'internal' secretion). That single distinction sorts every pancreatic tumor."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SPLIT. Exocrine (non-endocrine) tumors arise from the pancreatic ductal and acinar cells and account for ~95% of malignant pancreatic neoplasms — the most common being pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma, which is aggressive with poor survival. Endocrine tumors are the neuroendocrine / islet-cell (NET) tumors: rare (~5%), they secrete peptide hormones (insulin, gastrin, glucagon, VIP) producing the clinical syndromes of LO 53.8, and they tend to be more indolent with longer survival. So: exocrine = ductal, common, aggressive; endocrine = islet, rare, indolent."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Exocrine = duct secretion, ductal/acinar, ~95% of malignancies (ductal adeno, aggressive). Endocrine = hormone into blood, NET, ~5%, indolent."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Lamet opened the tumor block with one definitional slide. In one line each, define exocrine vs endocrine secretion, give the percentage of pancreatic malignancies each accounts for, and state which group is the more aggressive."}]}, {"id": 10, "statement": "Describe cystic fibrosis of the pancreas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Cystic fibrosis (CF) is the most common life-shortening autosomal recessive disease among Caucasian populations, with a frequency of 1 in 2000-3000 live births. The underlying lesion is abnormal chloride and bicarbonate transport from mutations in the CFTR gene (CF transmembrane conductance regulator) on chromosome 7. The defect produces abnormally tenacious mucus in the lungs, GI tract, pancreas, and hepatobiliary system, so the lumens of these organs become obstructed."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE PANCREAS IN CF. Pancreatic insufficiency is the most common GI complication: decreased enzyme production → fat malabsorption. Pancreatitis develops in about 10% of CF patients (typically late adolescence/early adulthood). And CF-related diabetes (CFRD) is a distinct form of diabetes from a relative insulin deficiency as the islets are destroyed — annual screening with an OGTT is recommended from age 10. The pancreatic story is the same obstruction-and-destruction theme as the rest of CF."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "CF = most common life-shortening AR disease in Caucasians; CFTR on chr 7; pancreatic exocrine insufficiency + CFRD."}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Diagnosing acute pancreatitis only after imaging. The diagnosis is 2 of 3 — clinical presentation, lipase/amylase >3x ULN, or imaging. Because the first two alone make the diagnosis, imaging is NOT required. Don't withhold a diagnosis (or the fluids) waiting on a CT."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Counting a merely 'high' lipase/amylase. The threshold is >3x the upper limit of normal, not just above normal. An ER lipase of 450-550 is not automatically pancreatitis — it has to clear three times the ULN to count toward the 2-of-3 criteria."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. Swapping Cullen's and Grey-Turner's. Cullen's = periumbilical (the Circle around the umbilicus); Grey-Turner's = flank. Both are nonspecific markers of retroperitoneal bleeding in pancreatic necrosis, seen in only ~3% — don't flip the locations."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Putting a 48-hour Ranson value on the admission list. Admission (5) = age >55, WBC >16k, glucose >200, AST >250, LDH >350. The Hct drop, BUN rise, Ca <8, PaO2 <60, base deficit, and fluid sequestration are all 48-hour values."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Saying gallstones cause chronic pancreatitis. Gallstones cause ACUTE pancreatitis — they are NOT a cause of chronic pancreatitis (alcohol ~70% leads CP). Lamet re-taught this in Q&A: a pancreatic-duct stone is diagnostic of CP, but a gallstone does not cause CP. Reassure the biliary-pancreatitis patient."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Trusting serum amylase/lipase to diagnose chronic pancreatitis. The >3x-ULN enzyme rule is for ACUTE disease. In chronic pancreatitis enzymes may be elevated, normal, or low — NOT diagnostic. Use fecal elastase <200 mcg/g (the exocrine test of choice) and imaging calcifications instead."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. Colliding Whipple's TRIAD with the Whipple PROCEDURE. Whipple's TRIAD diagnoses an insulinoma (hypoglycemia symptoms + glucose <50 + relief with glucose). The Whipple PROCEDURE is a pancreaticoduodenectomy for resectable ductal adenocarcinoma. Same surname, opposite ends of the tumor map — keep distinct."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "8. Mixing up the NET hormone syndromes. Anchor each: insulinoma → hypoglycemia (Whipple's triad); gastrinoma → ulcers (Zollinger-Ellison + triangle); glucagonoma → necrolytic migratory erythema; VIPoma → watery diarrhea (WDHA). Don't swap the rash and the diarrhea."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. Two causes own the disease. Gallstones (30-45%) + alcohol (30-45%) = ~90% of acute pancreatitis. The rest are zebras: TG >1000, hypercalcemia, post-ERCP, drugs, scorpion venom, and ampullary obstruction (Ascaris, Lemmel, pancreas divisum)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. Two of three, so imaging is optional. Dx = 2 of 3: classic pain, lipase/amylase >3x ULN, imaging. Any two suffice, so imaging is NOT required. Lipase beats amylase, but the threshold for either is 3x ULN."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. Ranson, by timing. Admission: age >55, WBC >16k, glucose >200, AST >250, LDH >350. 48h: Hct ↓, BUN ↑, Ca <8, PaO2 <60, base deficit, fluid >6L. Mortality 0-2 = 2% → 7-8 = 100%."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. The 4-week rule. A pseudocyst (fibrous wall, no epithelial lining, ~10%) and walled-off necrosis both need ~4 weeks. Hold invasive intervention ≥4 weeks so the body walls it off — outcomes are better."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. Chronic pancreatitis in one line. Alcohol ~70% (#1; gallstones NOT a cause); back-radiating pain; >90% function lost before steatorrhea + weight loss + insulin-requiring secondary diabetes appear."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. The diagnostic tests. Acute: amylase/lipase >3x ULN. Chronic: enzymes not diagnostic; fecal elastase <200 = test of choice + calcifications. Tumor: double duct sign (CT/MRCP) + CA 19-9."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. Exocrine vs endocrine. Exocrine = duct, ductal/acinar, ~95% of malignancies (ductal adenocarcinoma, aggressive). Endocrine = hormone into blood, NET ~5%, indolent."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "8. The NET eponym chain. Insulinoma Whipple's triad · Gastrinoma Zollinger-Ellison + triangle (90%) · Glucagonoma necrolytic migratory erythema · VIPoma WDHA/Verner-Morrison (5 L/day)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Gallstone pancreatitis and ERCP overlap the biliary block. The gallstone → ampullary-obstruction → pancreatitis chain, and ERCP as both a treatment and an iatrogenic cause, are also taught in the biliary material of gi 43-49.pdf. Here is the medical-pancreatitis home for the same stone; that doc is the biliary-tree home."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Pancreatic tumors continue in Lecture 54. Lec 53 is the acute-pancreatitis half (LOs 53.1-53.5). The chronic pancreatitis, diagnostic tests, and pancreatic tumors (ductal adenocarcinoma, cystic neoplasms, neuroendocrine tumors, cystic fibrosis) are Lec 54 (LOs 53.6-53.10) in this same merged block."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — The pathology view of pancreatitis sits in Lec 52. Lec 52 (Jones, exocrine-pancreas pathology, this doc) teaches the same acute pancreatitis from the pathology angle (Robbins pathogenesis flowchart, fat necrosis, lipase>amylase). Lamet's Lec 53 is the clinical/medical companion — reconcile the shared dx facts across both."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Acute pancreatitis is the OTHER half of this merged block. This Lec 54 section (53.6-53.10) is the chronic pancreatitis + tumors + CF hour; the acute pancreatitis material — etiology (gallstones/alcohol ~90%), the 2-of-3 dx criteria, Ranson criteria, and treatment — is the Lec 53 half (LOs 53.1-53.5) of this same merged block. Read the two hours together: gallstones drive acute, alcohol drives chronic."}]}]}};
const LECTURE_REFERENCES = {};

// QUIZ_START
const QUIZ = [[31, "Infectious Diarrhea (Lec 31–32)", [[1, "Recognize the etiology of common infectious diarrheas", [["A traveler returns with profuse, voluminous, watery, non-bloody diarrhea and rapid dehydration. The most likely organism is:", ["Enterotoxigenic E. coli", "Enterohemorrhagic E. coli", "Shigella sonnei", "Campylobacter jejuni", "Salmonella typhi"], 0, "Voluminous watery non-bloody stools with rapid dehydration is the secretory pattern. ETEC is the classic traveler's-diarrhea enterotoxin producer; cholera is the other archetype.\n\nWhy not — Enterohemorrhagic E. coli: EHEC is inflammatory — bloody stools and HUS, not voluminous watery.  Shigella sonnei: Shigella is inflammatory dysentery — bloody, mucoid, febrile.  Campylobacter jejuni: Campylobacter is inflammatory and often poultry-linked, not secretory.  Salmonella typhi: Salmonella typhi is inflammatory/systemic, not a watery secretory bug.", "advanced"], ["Clostridioides difficile damages colonic cells through which type of toxin?", ["Cytotoxin", "Neurotoxin", "Endotoxin", "Enterotoxin", "Superantigen"], 0, "C. difficile produces cytotoxins (toxins A/B) that damage colonic mucosa. Blavo self-corrected in lecture: the neurotoxin producer is C. botulinum, not C. difficile.\n\nWhy not — Neurotoxin: Neurotoxin is C. botulinum (botulism), which damages nerves.  Endotoxin: Endotoxin is LPS released on gram-negative cell death, not a C. diff product.  Enterotoxin: Enterotoxins (cholera, Staph) act on the gut surface to drive secretion.  Superantigen: Superantigens drive massive T-cell activation, not C. diff colitis.", "basic"], ["Bloody diarrhea from E. coli O157:H7 progresses to renal failure, hemolysis, and thrombocytopenia. The complication is:", ["Hemolytic uremic syndrome", "Disseminated intravascular coagulation", "Reye syndrome", "Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura", "Guillain-Barré syndrome"], 0, "The classic triad — azotemia, microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, and thrombocytopenia — is hemolytic uremic syndrome, driven by the Shiga-like toxin of EHEC O157:H7.\n\nWhy not — Disseminated intravascular coagulation: DIC has consumptive coagulopathy with bleeding and abnormal coags, not the HUS triad.  Reye syndrome: Reye syndrome is salicylate-associated hepatic/cerebral injury, not an O157:H7 sequela.  Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura: TTP shares MAHA but is ADAMTS13-related with neuro signs and fever, not O157:H7.  Guillain-Barré syndrome: Guillain-Barré (ascending paralysis) follows Campylobacter, not O157:H7.", "basic"], ["An endotoxin that triggers inflammation only when the bacterium dies is best described as the:", ["Lipopolysaccharide of gram-negative bacteria", "Exotoxin of gram-positive bacteria", "Secreted protein of gram-positive bacteria", "Capsular polysaccharide of gram-negative bacteria", "Teichoic acid of gram-positive bacteria"], 0, "Endotoxin is the lipopolysaccharide (LPS) of the gram-negative outer membrane, released on cell lysis to trigger inflammation — distinct from secreted exotoxins.\n\nWhy not — Exotoxin of gram-positive bacteria: Exotoxins are actively secreted, not released only on death.  Secreted protein of gram-positive bacteria: Secreted proteins are exotoxins, released by living bacteria.  Capsular polysaccharide of gram-negative bacteria: Capsular polysaccharide is an anti-phagocytic coat, not endotoxin.  Teichoic acid of gram-positive bacteria: Teichoic acid is a gram-positive wall component, not LPS.", "basic"]]], [2, "Identify the clinical presentations of common infectious diarrheas", [["Greasy, malodorous, non-bloody stools with fat malabsorption most suggest:", ["Giardia duodenalis", "Shigella sonnei", "Enterohemorrhagic E. coli", "Vibrio cholerae", "Salmonella typhi"], 0, "Giardia trophozoites line the mucosa and blunt fat absorption, producing oily, foul-smelling, non-bloody stools — the classic osmotic/malabsorptive picture.\n\nWhy not — Shigella sonnei: Shigella is bloody inflammatory dysentery, not greasy malabsorption.  Enterohemorrhagic E. coli: EHEC is bloody and inflammatory, not fatty.  Vibrio cholerae: Cholera is voluminous watery secretory, not greasy.  Salmonella typhi: Salmonella is inflammatory/systemic, not a malabsorptive picture.", "basic"], ["Frequent moderate-volume bloody mucoid stools with fecal leukocytes and fever indicate which diarrhea type?", ["Inflammatory diarrhea", "Secretory diarrhea", "Osmotic diarrhea", "Factitious diarrhea", "Functional diarrhea"], 0, "Blood, mucus, fecal leukocytes, and fever signal mucosal invasion/damage — the inflammatory pattern (EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter).\n\nWhy not — Secretory diarrhea: Secretory diarrhea is voluminous watery and non-bloody, without leukocytes.  Osmotic diarrhea: Osmotic diarrhea is non-bloody and resolves with fasting.  Factitious diarrhea: Factitious (laxative) diarrhea lacks blood and fecal leukocytes.  Functional diarrhea: Functional diarrhea has no inflammatory markers or fever.", "basic"], ["Which finding most specifically signals dehydration in an infant?", ["Sunken anterior fontanelle", "Bulging anterior fontanelle", "Brisk capillary refill", "Increased skin turgor", "Excessive tearing"], 0, "A sunken anterior fontanelle reflects reduced body fluid (dehydration); a bulging fontanelle reflects raised intracranial pressure (e.g., meningitis) — the opposite concern.\n\nWhy not — Bulging anterior fontanelle: A bulging fontanelle suggests raised ICP, not dehydration.  Brisk capillary refill: Brisk capillary refill is normal perfusion, not dehydration.  Increased skin turgor: Dehydration decreases skin turgor; it does not increase it.  Excessive tearing: Reduced (not excessive) tearing accompanies dehydration.", "basic"], ["A child vomits for two to three days before watery diarrhea begins. The most likely agent is:", ["Rotavirus", "Vibrio cholerae", "Giardia duodenalis", "Enterotoxigenic E. coli", "Entamoeba histolytica"], 0, "Rotavirus characteristically causes several days of vomiting before watery diarrhea — Blavo's point that the vomiting-to-diarrhea sequence distinguishes one case from another.\n\nWhy not — Vibrio cholerae: Cholera presents with abrupt voluminous watery diarrhea, not a vomiting prodrome.  Giardia duodenalis: Giardia is subacute greasy diarrhea, not a vomiting prodrome.  Enterotoxigenic E. coli: ETEC is acute traveler's watery diarrhea without the prodrome.  Entamoeba histolytica: E. histolytica causes dysentery/abscesses, not a vomiting prodrome.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Recognize the differential diagnosis of common infectious diarrhea", [["Compared with osmotic diarrhea, secretory diarrhea is characterized by:", ["Voluminous watery stools that persist with fasting", "Small-volume stools that resolve with fasting", "Bloody mucoid stools with fecal leukocytes", "Greasy stools with prominent fat malabsorption", "Stools driven by a high stool osmotic gap"], 0, "Secretory diarrhea is enterotoxin-driven active secretion: voluminous, watery, and it continues even when the patient stops eating. Osmotic diarrhea depends on ingested solute and stops with fasting.\n\nWhy not — Small-volume stools that resolve with fasting: Resolving with fasting is the osmotic pattern.  Bloody mucoid stools with fecal leukocytes: Blood and leukocytes define inflammatory, not secretory, diarrhea.  Greasy stools with prominent fat malabsorption: Greasy malabsorptive stool is the osmotic/Giardia pattern.  Stools driven by a high stool osmotic gap: A high osmotic gap defines osmotic, not secretory, diarrhea.", "basic"], ["A traveler has one week of greasy, foul-smelling, non-bloody diarrhea with bloating; one stool O&P is negative. The best read is:", ["Giardia, and repeat stool ova-and-parasite testing", "ETEC, and give oral rehydration salts", "Vibrio cholerae, and start IV crystalloid", "Norovirus, and simply reassure the patient", "EHEC, and strictly avoid all antibiotics"], 0, "Greasy, malodorous, bloating, subacute non-bloody diarrhea after travel is Giardia. A single O&P is insensitive — repeat it up to three times before excluding the parasite.\n\nWhy not — ETEC, and give oral rehydration salts: ETEC is acute voluminous watery diarrhea, not greasy and bloating.  Vibrio cholerae, and start IV crystalloid: Cholera is voluminous watery secretory, not greasy malabsorption.  Norovirus, and simply reassure the patient: Norovirus is acute self-limited vomiting/diarrhea, not weeks of greasy stool.  EHEC, and strictly avoid all antibiotics: EHEC is bloody inflammatory diarrhea, not greasy non-bloody.", "advanced"], ["A patient has profuse watery non-bloody diarrhea with severe dehydration and no fever. The priority intervention is:", ["Aggressive fluid and electrolyte replacement", "Empiric oral ciprofloxacin therapy", "Loperamide to slow gut motility", "Bismuth subsalicylate for symptoms", "Stool culture before any treatment"], 0, "This is the secretory/cholera-like pattern; the immediate threat is fluid and electrolyte loss, so rehydration comes first — diagnostics and drugs do not precede resuscitation.\n\nWhy not — Empiric oral ciprofloxacin therapy: Empiric antibiotics are not first-line and can harm (e.g., O157:H7).  Loperamide to slow gut motility: Antimotility agents are used with caution and don't treat dehydration.  Bismuth subsalicylate for symptoms: Bismuth treats symptoms, not the life-threatening fluid loss.  Stool culture before any treatment: Culture doesn't change the immediate need to rehydrate.", "advanced"]]], [4, "Identify the workup of infectious diarrheas", [["Which feature most justifies a diagnostic work-up rather than observation alone?", ["Bloody stools with high fever", "Two days of mild watery stools", "A single loose stool after travel", "Self-limited nausea without diarrhea", "Normal vital signs and good hydration"], 0, "Bloody stools plus high fever flags an inflammatory/invasive process and the need for testing. Mild, brief, well-hydrated cases are observed, not worked up.\n\nWhy not — Two days of mild watery stools: Mild brief watery stools are observed, not investigated.  A single loose stool after travel: A single loose stool needs no work-up.  Self-limited nausea without diarrhea: Nausea without diarrhea is not an indication to test stool.  Normal vital signs and good hydration: Normal vitals and hydration argue against work-up.", "basic"], ["Which stool test most reliably confirms intestinal inflammation?", ["Fecal calprotectin", "Fecal leukocytes", "Stool guaiac", "Stool osmotic gap", "Urine specific gravity"], 0, "Stool calprotectin (and lactoferrin) are leukocyte proteins that detect intestinal inflammation more reliably than the older fecal-leukocyte smear.\n\nWhy not — Fecal leukocytes: Fecal leukocytes are less sensitive/reliable than calprotectin.  Stool guaiac: Guaiac detects occult blood, not inflammation per se.  Stool osmotic gap: The osmotic gap separates osmotic from secretory, not inflammation.  Urine specific gravity: Urine specific gravity gauges hydration, not gut inflammation.", "basic"], ["A stool osmotic gap above 160 mOsm/kg most supports which diarrhea type?", ["Osmotic diarrhea", "Secretory diarrhea", "Inflammatory diarrhea", "Bacillary dysentery", "Antibiotic-associated colitis"], 0, "A high stool osmotic gap means an unabsorbed osmotically active solute is driving water into the lumen — the definition of osmotic diarrhea. Secretory diarrhea has a low gap.\n\nWhy not — Secretory diarrhea: Secretory diarrhea has a LOW osmotic gap (electrolyte-driven).  Inflammatory diarrhea: Inflammatory diarrhea is defined by blood/leukocytes, not the gap.  Bacillary dysentery: Dysentery is inflammatory, characterized by blood, not the gap.  Antibiotic-associated colitis: C. diff colitis is inflammatory, not gap-defined.", "advanced"], ["A urine specific gravity above 1.020 with an elevated BUN most suggests:", ["Dehydration", "Overhydration", "Active GI bleeding", "Bacterial coinfection", "Lactose intolerance"], 0, "Concentrated urine (SG >1.020) and a rising BUN are markers of volume depletion — Blavo's point that the test confirms the dehydration you already suspect.\n\nWhy not — Overhydration: Overhydration produces dilute urine and a low-normal BUN.  Active GI bleeding: GI bleeding is suggested by guaiac/hematochezia, not urine SG.  Bacterial coinfection: Coinfection is suggested by leukocytosis, not urine concentration.  Lactose intolerance: Lactose intolerance relates to the osmotic gap, not urine SG.", "advanced"]]], [5, "Recognize the management of common infectious diarrheas, including fluid and electrolyte management (ORS, IV)", [["Oral rehydration solution works primarily because glucose drives absorption of:", ["Sodium and water across the gut", "Potassium and water across the gut", "Chloride against its electrochemical gradient", "Bicarbonate into the intestinal lumen", "Protein across the mucosal barrier"], 0, "ORS exploits glucose-coupled sodium cotransport (SGLT1): glucose pulls sodium in, and water follows osmotically — which is why ORS needs both glucose and sodium.\n\nWhy not — Potassium and water across the gut: Cotransport is glucose-SODIUM, not glucose-potassium.  Chloride against its electrochemical gradient: Chloride is not the cotransported species in SGLT1.  Bicarbonate into the intestinal lumen: Bicarbonate secretion is not the ORS mechanism.  Protein across the mucosal barrier: Protein is not cotransported with glucose for rehydration.", "basic"], ["Why are sodas and fruit juices poor rehydration fluids in diarrhea?", ["Glucose far exceeds sodium content", "Sodium far exceeds glucose content", "They are essentially isotonic fluids", "They contain excessive potassium content", "They contain no usable carbohydrate"], 0, "Sodas/juices have glucose vastly exceeding sodium; the unbalanced osmotic load lacks the sodium needed for cotransport and can pull more water into the lumen, worsening losses.\n\nWhy not — Sodium far exceeds glucose content: It's the reverse — glucose exceeds sodium in these drinks.  They are essentially isotonic fluids: They are hyperosmolar, not isotonic.  They contain excessive potassium content: Excess potassium is not the issue; the glucose:sodium ratio is.  They contain no usable carbohydrate: They contain plenty of carbohydrate — that's the problem.", "basic"], ["When is intravenous rehydration preferred over oral rehydration?", ["Persistent vomiting with severe dehydration", "Mild dehydration tolerating oral fluids", "Mild vomiting without bowel obstruction", "A stable child drinking fluids well", "Self-limited mild watery diarrhea"], 0, "IV is reserved for when ORT is not feasible or safe — persistent vomiting, severe dehydration, ileus, or aspiration risk. Mild vomiting alone is not a contraindication to ORS.\n\nWhy not — Mild dehydration tolerating oral fluids: Mild dehydration tolerating fluids is treated orally.  Mild vomiting without bowel obstruction: Mild vomiting without obstruction still allows ORS.  A stable child drinking fluids well: A child drinking well does not need IV.  Self-limited mild watery diarrhea: Self-limited mild diarrhea needs oral fluids at most.", "basic"], ["Bismuth subsalicylate is avoided in children under 17 because of the risk for:", ["Reye syndrome", "Hemolytic uremic syndrome", "Serotonin syndrome", "Clostridioides difficile colitis", "Lactic acidosis"], 0, "Bismuth subsalicylate contains a salicylate; in children/teens this carries Reye-syndrome risk — Blavo notes it is a frequent exam point.\n\nWhy not — Hemolytic uremic syndrome: HUS is the O157:H7 sequela, not a bismuth effect.  Serotonin syndrome: Serotonin syndrome is a serotonergic-drug effect, unrelated.  Clostridioides difficile colitis: C. diff colitis follows broad antibiotics, not bismuth.  Lactic acidosis: Lactic acidosis is not the bismuth concern in children.", "advanced"], ["A child with bloody diarrhea and confirmed E. coli O157:H7 should NOT receive antibiotics because they:", ["Increase hemolytic uremic syndrome risk", "Meaningfully shorten the diarrheal illness", "Reliably eradicate the Shiga toxin", "Completely prevent further fecal shedding", "Have no effect on the clinical course"], 0, "Antibiotics can increase Shiga-toxin release and the risk of HUS in O157:H7, so they are withheld; fluids and supportive care are the mainstay.\n\nWhy not — Meaningfully shorten the diarrheal illness: Antibiotics do not reliably shorten the illness here.  Reliably eradicate the Shiga toxin: They do not eradicate the toxin — they can increase its release.  Completely prevent further fecal shedding: They do not reliably stop shedding (and can prolong Salmonella carriage).  Have no effect on the clinical course: They are not neutral — they are potentially harmful.", "advanced"]]]]], [33, "GI Endoscopy (Lec 33–34)", [[1, "Describe the role of endoscopic procedures for GI hemorrhage", [["A patient pumps out large-volume maroon stool and is hemodynamically unstable. The most important source to exclude FIRST is:", ["A brisk upper GI source moving fast", "Internal hemorrhoids of the rectum", "Diverticulosis of the sigmoid colon", "Angiodysplasia of the cecum", "Ischemic colitis of the splenic flexure"], 0, "A fast upper bleed (e.g., duodenal ulcer) is the most important cause of a big lower-GI bleed — and, unlike most lower sources, you can stop it endoscopically. Exclude it first.\n\nWhy not — Internal hemorrhoids of the rectum: Hemorrhoids cause small-volume bright-red bleeding, not unstable maroon stool.  Diverticulosis of the sigmoid colon: Diverticulosis bleeds but is the answer for painless STABLE elderly hematochezia.  Angiodysplasia of the cecum: Angiodysplasia usually weeps slowly, rarely causing instability first.  Ischemic colitis of the splenic flexure: Ischemic colitis causes pain and bloody diarrhea, not brisk maroon exsanguination.", "advanced"], ["Endoscopic therapy to STOP active bleeding is far more effective for:", ["Upper GI bleeding lesions", "Lower GI bleeding lesions", "Cecal vascular ectasias", "Diverticular bleeding sites", "Small-bowel angiodysplasias"], 0, "The therapeutic potential of endoscopy is much greater for UPPER pathology (clip an ulcer vessel, band varices); lower-GI bleeding has limited endoscopic therapy.\n\nWhy not — Lower GI bleeding lesions: Lower-GI bleeding has limited endoscopic therapeutic options.  Cecal vascular ectasias: Cecal ectasias are lower-tract lesions with limited durable therapy.  Diverticular bleeding sites: Diverticular bleeding usually stops on its own; endoscopic control is limited.  Small-bowel angiodysplasias: Small-bowel AVMs are hard to reach and treat durably.", "basic"], ["Why is an IV proton pump inhibitor given for an acute bleeding ulcer?", ["Raising gastric pH stabilizes the clot", "It directly cauterizes the bleeding vessel", "It replaces the lost circulating volume", "It rapidly reverses anticoagulation", "It immediately eradicates Helicobacter pylori"], 0, "Clot stability depends on pH and platelets; acutely raising gastric pH toward neutral lets the clot hold while you arrange endoscopy.\n\nWhy not — It directly cauterizes the bleeding vessel: The PPI doesn't cauterize — endoscopic clips/thermal therapy do.  It replaces the lost circulating volume: Volume is replaced with fluids/blood, not a PPI.  It rapidly reverses anticoagulation: A PPI does not reverse anticoagulation.  It immediately eradicates Helicobacter pylori: H. pylori eradication takes a multi-drug course, not an acute PPI.", "basic"], ["Sudden massive bright-red hematemesis in a patient with cirrhosis is most likely from:", ["Esophageal varices", "A Mallory-Weiss tear", "Erosive gastritis", "A Schatzki ring", "Reflux esophagitis"], 0, "Portal hypertension from cirrhosis produces esophageal varices, which can bleed massively and painlessly — sometimes the presenting sign of unrecognized cirrhosis.\n\nWhy not — A Mallory-Weiss tear: A Mallory-Weiss tear is a benign, usually self-limited bleed after retching.  Erosive gastritis: Erosive gastritis oozes; it rarely causes massive variceal-type hemorrhage.  A Schatzki ring: A Schatzki ring causes dysphagia, not hemorrhage.  Reflux esophagitis: Reflux esophagitis bleeds little and isn't the cirrhosis association.", "advanced"]]], [2, "Describe the use of ERCP, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS), and wireless capsule endoscopy", [["A jaundiced patient has a pancreatic-head mass and no distant metastases. The best way to stage AND biopsy it is:", ["Endoscopic ultrasound", "ERCP with duct brushings", "Percutaneous CT-guided biopsy", "Wireless capsule endoscopy", "Upper endoscopy with biopsy"], 0, "EUS biopsies the mass through the stomach wall, assesses vascular involvement, and samples nodes — all in one staging procedure; percutaneous biopsy risks tract seeding and undersampling.\n\nWhy not — ERCP with duct brushings: ERCP relieves obstruction; it rarely gets a tissue diagnosis of the mass.  Percutaneous CT-guided biopsy: Percutaneous biopsy risks tract seeding and may undersample.  Wireless capsule endoscopy: Capsule endoscopy cannot reach or biopsy the pancreas.  Upper endoscopy with biopsy: A forward-viewing EGD can't see or sample a mass behind the stomach.", "advanced"], ["Since the advent of MRCP, ERCP is reserved almost exclusively for:", ["Therapeutic relief of biliary obstruction", "Diagnosis of pancreatic masses", "Routine evaluation of abnormal liver tests", "Staging of esophageal cancer", "Screening for common-bile-duct stones"], 0, "ERCP is the most dangerous GI procedure; with MRCP available for diagnosis, ERCP is done to TREAT — sphincterotomy and stone extraction to relieve obstruction.\n\nWhy not — Diagnosis of pancreatic masses: Pancreatic masses are diagnosed by EUS, not ERCP.  Routine evaluation of abnormal liver tests: Abnormal liver tests are worked up noninvasively first.  Staging of esophageal cancer: Esophageal cancer is staged by EUS.  Screening for common-bile-duct stones: CBD stones are screened noninvasively with MRCP.", "basic"], ["Wireless capsule endoscopy is best suited for evaluating:", ["Occult bleeding of the small intestine", "Therapy of a bleeding duodenal ulcer", "Biopsy of a submucosal gastric mass", "Removal of a pedunculated colon polyp", "Staging of an early gastric cancer"], 0, "Capsule endoscopy is diagnostic-only and shines in the small bowel beyond scope reach; its #1 indication is occult GI bleeding (negative upper and lower), typically finding AVMs.\n\nWhy not — Therapy of a bleeding duodenal ulcer: The capsule cannot treat anything — it only takes pictures.  Biopsy of a submucosal gastric mass: It cannot biopsy a mass.  Removal of a pedunculated colon polyp: It cannot perform polypectomy.  Staging of an early gastric cancer: It cannot stage tumors or reliably image the stomach.", "basic"], ["Wireless capsule endoscopy is contraindicated in a patient with known:", ["Stricturing Crohn disease", "Iron-deficiency anemia", "Occult GI bleeding", "A prior negative colonoscopy", "Small-bowel angiodysplasia"], 0, "A stricture can trap the capsule, requiring surgical retrieval; known stricturing Crohn disease is a contraindication.\n\nWhy not — Iron-deficiency anemia: Iron-deficiency anemia is an indication, not a contraindication.  Occult GI bleeding: Occult GI bleeding is the #1 indication.  A prior negative colonoscopy: A prior negative colonoscopy is part of the occult-bleed workup, not a contraindication.  Small-bowel angiodysplasia: Angiodysplasia is exactly what capsule endoscopy looks for.", "advanced"]]], [3, "List the disease entities and endoscopic findings of the upper gastrointestinal tract", [["Barrett esophagus is a precursor to which malignancy?", ["Esophageal adenocarcinoma", "Esophageal squamous cell carcinoma", "Gastric adenocarcinoma", "Pancreatic adenocarcinoma", "Duodenal carcinoid tumor"], 0, "Barrett's (intestinal metaplasia from chronic reflux) is the precursor of adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus — not squamous cell carcinoma.\n\nWhy not — Esophageal squamous cell carcinoma: Squamous cell carcinoma arises in the UPPER esophagus, unrelated to Barrett's.  Gastric adenocarcinoma: Gastric adenocarcinoma is not the Barrett's sequela.  Pancreatic adenocarcinoma: Pancreatic cancer is unrelated to Barrett's.  Duodenal carcinoid tumor: Duodenal carcinoid is unrelated to Barrett's.", "basic"], ["Squamous cell carcinoma of the esophagus classically arises in the:", ["Upper esophagus", "Lower esophagus", "Gastroesophageal junction", "Gastric antrum", "Duodenal bulb"], 0, "The upper esophagus gives squamous cell carcinoma; the lower esophagus (Barrett-associated) gives adenocarcinoma. The esophagus is 'tricky' precisely because the two split by location.\n\nWhy not — Lower esophagus: The lower esophagus gives adenocarcinoma (Barrett-related).  Gastroesophageal junction: The GE junction is the adenocarcinoma/Barrett zone.  Gastric antrum: The gastric antrum is stomach, not esophagus.  Duodenal bulb: The duodenal bulb is small bowel, not esophagus.", "basic"], ["Progressive dysphagia to SOLIDS ONLY most suggests a:", ["Fixed structural narrowing", "Primary esophageal motility disorder", "Functional swallowing complaint", "Diffuse esophageal spasm", "Globus sensation from anxiety"], 0, "Solids-only dysphagia points to a structural narrowing (cancer, EoE, Schatzki ring); dysphagia to BOTH solids and liquids points to a motility disorder — get a barium study first there.\n\nWhy not — Primary esophageal motility disorder: Motility disorders cause solid AND liquid dysphagia.  Functional swallowing complaint: Functional complaints don't progress with a fixed pattern.  Diffuse esophageal spasm: Spasm causes intermittent solid-and-liquid dysphagia.  Globus sensation from anxiety: Globus is a constant lump sensation, not progressive solid dysphagia.", "basic"], ["Concentric esophageal rings (a 'corrugated' esophagus) with recurrent food impaction in an atopic patient indicate:", ["Eosinophilic esophagitis", "A Schatzki ring", "Esophageal adenocarcinoma", "Achalasia of the sphincter", "A peptic reflux stricture"], 0, "Eosinophilic esophagitis is an allergic esophagus producing multiple concentric rings and frequent food impaction in atopic patients; a Schatzki ring is a single distal ring.\n\nWhy not — A Schatzki ring: A Schatzki ring is a SINGLE distal ring, not multiple rings.  Esophageal adenocarcinoma: Adenocarcinoma is a mass/stricture, not concentric rings in a young atopic.  Achalasia of the sphincter: Achalasia has near-normal endoscopy, not rings.  A peptic reflux stricture: A peptic stricture is a single tight narrowing, not corrugated rings.", "advanced"]]], [4, "Describe the use of lower endoscopic procedures for the differential diagnosis of the colorectal area", [["The most common cause of acute, painless, hemodynamically significant hematochezia in an elderly patient is:", ["Diverticulosis", "Diverticulitis", "Internal hemorrhoids", "Ischemic colitis", "Colorectal carcinoma"], 0, "Diverticulosis is the classic cause of acute, painless, large-volume lower-GI bleeding over age 50; it stops on its own in roughly 80%.\n\nWhy not — Diverticulitis: DiverticulITIS causes pain and fever, typically WITHOUT significant bleeding.  Internal hemorrhoids: Hemorrhoids cause small-volume bright-red bleeding.  Ischemic colitis: Ischemic colitis is painful with bloody diarrhea, not painless.  Colorectal carcinoma: Colorectal cancer usually bleeds slowly/occultly, not acutely and massively.", "advanced"], ["A patient with left-lower-quadrant pain and fever but no bleeding most likely has:", ["Diverticulitis", "Diverticulosis", "Angiodysplasia", "Internal hemorrhoids", "A colonic adenoma"], 0, "DiverticulITIS = inflammation: LLQ pain and fever, usually WITHOUT significant bleeding (and colonoscopy is contraindicated acutely). DiverticulOSIS is the painless bleeder. Never mix osis and itis.\n\nWhy not — Diverticulosis: DiverticulOSIS is the painless bleeder, not the painful febrile picture.  Angiodysplasia: Angiodysplasia bleeds painlessly; it doesn't cause fever.  Internal hemorrhoids: Hemorrhoids cause painless bright-red bleeding, not fever.  A colonic adenoma: An adenoma is usually asymptomatic.", "advanced"], ["Discontinuous skip lesions with cobblestoning on colonoscopy indicate:", ["Crohn disease", "Ulcerative colitis", "Ischemic colitis", "Pseudomembranous colitis", "Diverticular colitis"], 0, "Crohn disease is discontinuous (skip lesions) with cobblestoning and aphthous ulcers; the diagnosis is more visual than histologic. UC is continuous from the rectum.\n\nWhy not — Ulcerative colitis: Ulcerative colitis is CONTINUOUS from the rectum, without skip lesions.  Ischemic colitis: Ischemic colitis is segmental at watershed zones, not cobblestoned.  Pseudomembranous colitis: Pseudomembranous colitis shows yellow plaques (C. difficile).  Diverticular colitis: 'Diverticular colitis' is not the cobblestoning/skip pattern.", "basic"]]], [5, "Understand the indications and complications of endoscopy", [["The most dreaded complication of ERCP is:", ["Post-ERCP pancreatitis", "Esophageal perforation", "Aspiration pneumonia", "Splenic laceration", "Colonic perforation"], 0, "Manipulating the ampulla where the bile and pancreatic ducts meet can inflame the pancreas; post-ERCP pancreatitis is the dreaded complication, with an overall ~10% complication rate.\n\nWhy not — Esophageal perforation: Perforation is possible but not THE dreaded complication.  Aspiration pneumonia: Aspiration is a general anesthesia risk, not the signature ERCP complication.  Splenic laceration: Splenic injury is a colonoscopy-related rarity, not ERCP.  Colonic perforation: Colonic perforation is a colonoscopy complication, not ERCP.", "basic"]]], [6, "State the colonoscopy and the screening recommendations of the American College of Gastroenterology", [["Average-risk colorectal cancer screening should now begin at age:", ["45", "40", "50", "55", "60"], 0, "The 2022 update lowered the average-risk start age to 45 (from 50); African Americans now start at 45 as well.\n\nWhy not — 40: 40 is the high-risk/family-history start, not average-risk.  50: 50 was the OLD average-risk start, before 2022.  55: 55 is not a guideline start age.  60: 60 is far too late to begin average-risk screening.", "basic"], ["For average-risk colorectal cancer screening, the FIRST test that should be offered is:", ["Colonoscopy every 10 years", "Annual fecal immunochemical testing", "Cologuard every three years", "CT colonography every five years", "Flexible sigmoidoscopy every five years"], 0, "Colonoscopy q10y should be offered FIRST; a stool test (annual FIT) is offered only to patients who decline colonoscopy — not as an equivalent menu choice.\n\nWhy not — Annual fecal immunochemical testing: Annual FIT is first-tier but offered when colonoscopy is declined, not first.  Cologuard every three years: Cologuard is second-tier and not a first offer.  CT colonography every five years: CT colonography is a second-tier option.  Flexible sigmoidoscopy every five years: Flexible sigmoidoscopy is a limited second-tier option.", "basic"], ["Cologuard (FIT-DNA) is best described as a:", ["Cancer-detection test, not a prevention test", "Cancer-prevention test equal to colonoscopy", "First-tier test for high-risk patients", "Reliable test for advanced adenomas", "Replacement that needs no follow-up colonoscopy"], 0, "Cologuard is ~92% sensitive for cancer but only ~42% for advanced adenomas — so it detects cancer but doesn't prevent it (you can't remove a polyp through it). Every positive needs a colonoscopy.\n\nWhy not — Cancer-prevention test equal to colonoscopy: It is not equivalent to colonoscopy and does not prevent cancer.  First-tier test for high-risk patients: It is contraindicated in high-risk patients.  Reliable test for advanced adenomas: It misses ~58% of advanced adenomas — detection of polyps is only fair.  Replacement that needs no follow-up colonoscopy: Every positive Cologuard requires a follow-up colonoscopy.", "basic"], ["A 30-year-old's father had colon cancer at age 55. When and how often should screening colonoscopy be done?", ["Start at 40, every 5 years", "Start at 45, every 10 years", "Start at 50, every 10 years", "Start at 55, every 5 years", "Start at 45, every 5 years"], 0, "A first-degree relative with CRC under 60 makes this high-risk: colonoscopy every 5 years, starting at age 40 OR 10 years before the youngest affected relative (55 - 10 = 45), whichever is earlier — so 40.\n\nWhy not — Start at 45, every 10 years: q10y average-risk timing ignores the high-risk family history.  Start at 50, every 10 years: Start 50/q10y is the old average-risk rule, not high-risk.  Start at 55, every 5 years: 55 is too late; high-risk starts at 40 here.  Start at 45, every 5 years: Correct interval (q5y) but the start age should be 40, not 45.", "advanced"]]]]], [35, "GI Pharmacology (Lec 35–36)", [[1, "Describe the physiology of gastric acid secretion and the cellular targets that regulate it", [["On the parietal cell, acetylcholine, gastrin, and histamine each stimulate acid secretion by binding which receptors, respectively?", ["M3 muscarinic, CCK-B gastrin, and H2 receptors", "M1 muscarinic, CCK-A gastrin, and H1 receptors", "Nicotinic, secretin, and H2 receptors", "M3 muscarinic, CCK-B gastrin, and H1 receptors", "Alpha-2 adrenergic, CCK-A, and H2 receptors"], 0, "Acetylcholine acts at M3 muscarinic receptors, gastrin at CCK-B (gastrin) receptors, and histamine at H2 receptors. All three converge on protein kinases that drive the H+/K+-ATPase, which is why each is a separate drug target.\n\nWhy not — M1 muscarinic, CCK-A gastrin, and H1 receptors: M1/CCK-A/H1 are the wrong subtypes; the parietal cell uses M3, CCK-B, and H2.  Nicotinic, secretin, and H2 receptors: ACh works through muscarinic (not nicotinic) receptors, and secretin is inhibitory, not the gastrin receptor.  M3 muscarinic, CCK-B gastrin, and H1 receptors: Histamine acts at H2, not H1 — the H1 swap is the classic distractor.  Alpha-2 adrenergic, CCK-A, and H2 receptors: Alpha-2 and CCK-A are not the parietal-cell acid-secretory receptors.", "basic"], ["Prostaglandin E2 differs from acetylcholine, histamine, and gastrin at the parietal cell in that PGE2:", ["Inhibits acid secretion and is cytoprotective", "Stimulates acid secretion through CCK-B receptors", "Activates the H+/K+-ATPase directly", "Is the final common pathway all secretagogues use", "Triggers histamine release from ECL cells"], 0, "Unlike the three secretagogues, PGE2 binds parietal-cell EP receptors to INHIBIT acid secretion while enhancing mucus, bicarbonate, and mucosal blood flow — the cytoprotective arm. This is exactly why the PGE1 analog misoprostol protects against NSAID ulcers.\n\nWhy not — Stimulates acid secretion through CCK-B receptors: Gastrin (not PGE2) uses CCK-B receptors, and PGE2 inhibits rather than stimulates.  Activates the H+/K+-ATPase directly: The H+/K+-ATPase is the pump itself; PGE2 down-regulates, it does not activate it.  Is the final common pathway all secretagogues use: The H+/K+-ATPase (the pump), not PGE2, is the final common pathway.  Triggers histamine release from ECL cells: ECL-cell histamine release is driven by gastrin/ACh, not by inhibitory PGE2.", "basic"]]], [2, "Describe the agents used to treat peptic ulcers and gastric acidity and their adverse effects", [["An aluminum-hydroxide / magnesium-hydroxide antacid is formulated as a combination chiefly to:", ["Counterbalance bowel effects: aluminum constipates, magnesium loosens", "Prolong the duration of acid neutralization beyond several hours", "Prevent the rebound acid hypersecretion that aluminum alone causes", "Add antimicrobial coverage against H. pylori", "Avoid the CO2 production seen with single-agent antacids"], 0, "Aluminum salts slow motility and cause constipation; magnesium salts cause an osmotic diarrhea. Combining them lets the two opposite bowel effects counterbalance — Parmar drilled this Al-constipation / Mg-diarrhea pairing repeatedly.\n\nWhy not — Prolong the duration of acid neutralization beyond several hours: Antacids have a uniformly short duration (30-60 min); combining them does not prolong it.  Prevent the rebound acid hypersecretion that aluminum alone causes: Rebound hypersecretion is associated with calcium carbonate, and is not the reason for combining Al and Mg.  Add antimicrobial coverage against H. pylori: Bismuth (not Al/Mg) contributes antimicrobial activity in H. pylori therapy.  Avoid the CO2 production seen with single-agent antacids: CaCO3 and NaHCO3 generate CO2; the Al/Mg combination is not designed around that.", "basic"], ["Which acid-suppressive agent irreversibly inhibits the gastric H+/K+-ATPase, so that recovery of acid secretion requires new pump synthesis over roughly 18-24 hours?", ["Omeprazole", "Famotidine", "Vonoprazan", "Aluminum hydroxide", "Misoprostol"], 0, "Proton pump inhibitors such as omeprazole are prodrugs that covalently and irreversibly bind the activated H+/K+-ATPase; acid secretion only returns as new pumps are synthesized over ~18-24 hours, giving a long duration despite a short plasma half-life.\n\nWhy not — Famotidine: Famotidine is a reversible H2-receptor antagonist, not a pump inhibitor.  Vonoprazan: Vonoprazan (PCAB) blocks the pump's K+ site reversibly — it does not bind covalently.  Aluminum hydroxide: Aluminum hydroxide neutralizes acid already secreted; it does not touch the pump.  Misoprostol: Misoprostol is a PGE1 analog acting at EP receptors, not the pump.", "basic"], ["A patient on chronic high-dose cimetidine develops gynecomastia. The mechanism is:", ["Antiandrogenic activity of cimetidine", "Hyperprolactinemia from dopamine-receptor blockade", "Estrogen-receptor agonism by the imidazole ring", "Inhibition of aromatase in adipose tissue", "Suppression of luteinizing hormone secretion"], 0, "Cimetidine has antiandrogenic effects at high dose, producing gynecomastia and galactorrhea — an effect essentially unique to cimetidine among H2RAs (famotidine and others are free of it).\n\nWhy not — Hyperprolactinemia from dopamine-receptor blockade: Dopamine-blockade hyperprolactinemia is the metoclopramide mechanism (Lec 36), not cimetidine's.  Estrogen-receptor agonism by the imidazole ring: Cimetidine antagonizes androgen action; it is not an estrogen-receptor agonist.  Inhibition of aromatase in adipose tissue: Aromatase inhibition would lower estrogen and is not how cimetidine acts.  Suppression of luteinizing hormone secretion: Cimetidine does not work by suppressing LH.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Compare the relationship of histamine-2 receptor antagonists to proton pump inhibitors and the effect of acid suppression on vitamin B12 and intrinsic factor", [["Compared with an H2-receptor antagonist, a proton pump inhibitor provides acid suppression that is best described as:", ["Greater and longer-lasting because pump inhibition is irreversible", "Roughly equal in magnitude but with a faster onset of action", "Weaker but free of any tachyphylaxis", "Greater only against nocturnal, not meal-stimulated, acid", "Greater but reversible, so acid returns within one drug half-life"], 0, "PPIs suppress >90% of basal and stimulated acid versus the ~60-70% achieved by H2RAs, and because PPIs bind the pump irreversibly the effect outlasts the drug. H2RAs are reversible, weaker, and develop tachyphylaxis over days to weeks.\n\nWhy not — Roughly equal in magnitude but with a faster onset of action: PPIs are substantially MORE potent than H2RAs, and H2RAs actually have the faster onset.  Weaker but free of any tachyphylaxis: PPIs are stronger, and it is the H2RAs (not PPIs) that show tachyphylaxis.  Greater only against nocturnal, not meal-stimulated, acid: The nocturnal-selectivity description fits H2RAs; PPIs suppress both basal and stimulated acid.  Greater but reversible, so acid returns within one drug half-life: PPI suppression is irreversible and outlasts the plasma half-life — acid does not return that quickly.", "basic"], ["Long-term acid suppression with a PPI predisposes to deficiency of which vitamin, because gastric acid is needed to release it from dietary protein?", ["Vitamin B12, cobalamin", "Vitamin C, ascorbate", "Folate", "Vitamin K", "Thiamine, vitamin B1"], 0, "Chronic acid suppression decreases the bioavailability of vitamin B12, because acid is required to cleave cobalamin from dietary protein before intrinsic factor can bind it. Both PPIs (slide 17) and long-term H2RA use are implicated.\n\nWhy not — Vitamin C, ascorbate: Vitamin C absorption is not acid-dependent in this way.  Folate: Folate is absorbed in the jejunum and is not the acid-suppression deficiency.  Vitamin K: Vitamin K depends on bile and gut flora, not gastric acid.  Thiamine, vitamin B1: Thiamine is not the vitamin affected by chronic acid suppression.", "basic"]]], [4, "Describe the clinically significant drug interactions of acid-suppressive and mucosal-protective agents", [["A patient who had a coronary stent placed and takes clopidogrel needs a PPI. Which agent is the safest choice, and why?", ["Pantoprazole, because omeprazole/esomeprazole inhibit CYP2C19 and reduce clopidogrel activation", "Omeprazole, because it has the least effect on CYP2C19", "Esomeprazole, because the S-isomer bypasses CYP2C19", "Any PPI, because clopidogrel is not metabolized by CYP enzymes", "Famotidine is mandatory, because all PPIs are absolutely contraindicated"], 0, "Clopidogrel is a prodrug activated by CYP2C19. Omeprazole and esomeprazole inhibit CYP2C19, blunting clopidogrel's antiplatelet effect, so they are avoided; pantoprazole has minimal CYP2C19 inhibition and is the preferred PPI in this setting.\n\nWhy not — Omeprazole, because it has the least effect on CYP2C19: Omeprazole is one of the worst offenders — it strongly inhibits CYP2C19.  Esomeprazole, because the S-isomer bypasses CYP2C19: Esomeprazole is the S-isomer of omeprazole and shares the CYP2C19 inhibition.  Any PPI, because clopidogrel is not metabolized by CYP enzymes: Clopidogrel is a prodrug that absolutely requires CYP2C19 for activation.  Famotidine is mandatory, because all PPIs are absolutely contraindicated: PPIs are not absolutely contraindicated; a low-interaction PPI (pantoprazole) is acceptable.", "advanced"], ["Sucralfate should NOT be co-administered with a PPI or antacid primarily because:", ["Sucralfate needs an acidic pH to form its gel", "The combination causes dangerous aluminum toxicity in normal kidneys", "PPIs accelerate sucralfate's hepatic first-pass metabolism", "Sucralfate inactivates PPIs in the small intestine", "Both bind the H+/K+-ATPase and compete for the pump"], 0, "Sucralfate is a sucrose-sulfate / aluminum-hydroxide complex that needs an acidic environment to polymerize into the viscous gel that binds the ulcer base. Raising gastric pH with a PPI, H2RA, or antacid removes the activation step, so the agents are spaced apart or not combined. (Sucralfate also impairs quinolone absorption.)\n\nWhy not — The combination causes dangerous aluminum toxicity in normal kidneys: Aluminum accumulation is a concern mainly in renal impairment, and is not the reason for the timing rule.  PPIs accelerate sucralfate's hepatic first-pass metabolism: Sucralfate is barely absorbed; this is not a hepatic-metabolism interaction.  Sucralfate inactivates PPIs in the small intestine: The problem is loss of sucralfate's own acid activation, not inactivation of the PPI.  Both bind the H+/K+-ATPase and compete for the pump: Sucralfate does not act at the proton pump at all.", "basic"]]], [5, "Describe the regimens used for Helicobacter pylori eradication", [["A 55-year-old with a duodenal ulcer tests positive for H. pylori on stool antigen. He has no penicillin allergy and lives in a region of high clarithromycin resistance. The preferred first-line regimen and the required follow-up are:", ["14-day bismuth quadruple therapy, then mandatory confirmation of eradication", "Clarithromycin-based triple therapy for 7 days, with no eradication testing needed", "A PPI alone for 8 weeks, then repeat endoscopy", "Single-dose azithromycin plus an antacid, then symptom monitoring only", "Sucralfate plus misoprostol for 14 days, then a urea breath test"], 0, "The gold-standard first-line regimen is 14-day Optimized bismuth quadruple therapy — PPI + tetracycline + metronidazole + bismuth — which avoids clarithromycin where resistance is high. Under the 2024 guidelines, confirmation of eradication (fecal antigen, urea breath test, or biopsy) is now mandatory for every treated patient.\n\nWhy not — Clarithromycin-based triple therapy for 7 days, with no eradication testing needed: Clarithromycin was dropped from first-line use for resistance, and eradication testing is now mandatory — both halves are wrong.  A PPI alone for 8 weeks, then repeat endoscopy: Acid suppression alone does not eradicate the organism; antibiotics are required.  Single-dose azithromycin plus an antacid, then symptom monitoring only: A single antibiotic with an antacid is not an evidence-based eradication regimen.  Sucralfate plus misoprostol for 14 days, then a urea breath test: Sucralfate and misoprostol are mucosal agents with no antimicrobial role against H. pylori.", "advanced"]]], [6, "List the categories of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", [["A patient prone to motion sickness needs a prophylactic patch placed behind the ear. The drug acts as a:", ["Muscarinic M1 receptor antagonist", "Histamine H1 receptor antagonist", "Dopamine D2 receptor antagonist", "Serotonin 5-HT3 receptor antagonist", "Neurokinin-1 receptor antagonist"], 0, "The behind-the-ear motion-sickness patch is scopolamine, an M1 muscarinic antagonist that crosses the blood-brain barrier to act centrally at the area postrema and on the vestibular system. H1 antihistamines (meclizine, dimenhydrinate) also treat motion sickness but are oral, not the patch.\n\nWhy not — Histamine H1 receptor antagonist: H1 antihistamines (meclizine, dimenhydrinate) treat motion sickness too, but are not the scopolamine patch.  Dopamine D2 receptor antagonist: D2 antagonists treat CINV/PONV and are ineffective for motion sickness.  Serotonin 5-HT3 receptor antagonist: 5-HT3 antagonists are for CINV/PONV/RINV and are explicitly ineffective for motion sickness.  Neurokinin-1 receptor antagonist: NK1 antagonists target the delayed phase of CINV, not motion sickness.", "advanced"], ["Which agent belongs to the serotonin 5-HT3 receptor antagonist class of antiemetics?", ["Palonosetron", "Prochlorperazine", "Aprepitant", "Scopolamine", "Dronabinol"], 0, "The 5-HT3 antagonists are the '-setrons': ondansetron, dolasetron, granisetron, and palonosetron. The drug-ending shortcut (-setron = serotonin) is the fastest way to bin these agents by class.\n\nWhy not — Prochlorperazine: Prochlorperazine is a phenothiazine D2 antagonist.  Aprepitant: Aprepitant is an NK1 antagonist (a '-pitant').  Scopolamine: Scopolamine is an M1 muscarinic antagonist.  Dronabinol: Dronabinol is a cannabinoid CB1 agonist.", "basic"]]], [7, "Discuss the mechanism of action of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", [["A chemotherapy patient develops nausea on days 2-4 after the infusion. The mediator and target driving this delayed phase are:", ["Substance P acting at NK1 receptors", "Serotonin acting at 5-HT3 receptors", "Dopamine acting at D2 receptors", "Histamine acting at H1 receptors", "Acetylcholine acting at M1 receptors"], 0, "The delayed phase of CINV (roughly days 1-5) is mediated centrally by substance P binding NK1 receptors — which is why NK1 antagonists (-pitants) are added for delayed coverage. The acute phase (<24 h) is the serotonin/5-HT3 peripheral pathway, the classic distractor here.\n\nWhy not — Serotonin acting at 5-HT3 receptors: Serotonin/5-HT3 drives the ACUTE phase (<24 h), not the delayed phase.  Dopamine acting at D2 receptors: D2 is the CTZ target for several antiemetics but is not the delayed-phase mediator.  Histamine acting at H1 receptors: H1 mediates vestibular/motion nausea, not delayed-phase CINV.  Acetylcholine acting at M1 receptors: M1 mediates motion sickness via the vestibular system, not delayed-phase CINV.", "advanced"], ["Ondansetron exerts its antiemetic effect by blocking 5-HT3 receptors at which two sites?", ["Central area postrema and peripheral vagal afferents", "Vestibular nuclei and the cerebral cortex", "Lower esophageal sphincter and gastric antrum", "Nigrostriatal pathway and the basal ganglia", "Carotid body and the respiratory center"], 0, "5-HT3 antagonists work at two sites: centrally in the CNS at the area postrema/CTZ and peripherally on GI vagal afferent nerve terminals — giving both central and peripheral antiemetic effect. This dual location is why they cover CINV, PONV, and RINV.\n\nWhy not — Vestibular nuclei and the cerebral cortex: Vestibular/cortical sites are H1/M1 territory (motion sickness), not 5-HT3.  Lower esophageal sphincter and gastric antrum: LES and antrum are prokinetic (metoclopramide) targets, not 5-HT3 antiemetic sites.  Nigrostriatal pathway and the basal ganglia: Nigrostriatal D2 blockade explains EPS from dopamine antagonists, not setron action.  Carotid body and the respiratory center: The carotid body and respiratory center are not 5-HT3 antiemetic sites.", "basic"], ["Metoclopramide relieves diabetic gastroparesis because, beyond blocking central D2 receptors, it also:", ["Facilitates gut cholinergic transmission, raising LES tone and emptying", "Directly stimulates motilin receptors on GI smooth muscle", "Agonizes 5-HT4 receptors to trigger the peristaltic reflex", "Inhibits acetylcholinesterase to raise gut acetylcholine levels", "Blocks peripheral 5-HT3 receptors on vagal afferent fibers"], 0, "Metoclopramide is the dual-action drug: central D2 antagonism at the CTZ gives the antiemetic effect, while peripherally it facilitates cholinergic (ACh) transmission in the gut — increasing LES tone, speeding gastric emptying, and promoting small-bowel transit. Each distractor is the mechanism of a DIFFERENT prokinetic.\n\nWhy not — Directly stimulates motilin receptors on GI smooth muscle: Direct motilin-receptor agonism is erythromycin's mechanism.  Agonizes 5-HT4 receptors to trigger the peristaltic reflex: 5-HT4 agonism is prucalopride's mechanism.  Inhibits acetylcholinesterase to raise gut acetylcholine levels: AChE inhibition is neostigmine's mechanism (colonic pseudo-obstruction).  Blocks peripheral 5-HT3 receptors on vagal afferent fibers: Blocking peripheral 5-HT3 is the setron antiemetic mechanism, not metoclopramide's prokinetic action.", "basic"]]], [8, "Discuss the therapeutic and adverse effects of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", [["Before continuing metoclopramide in a patient on a multi-month course, the key adverse effect to monitor for and time-limit therapy against is:", ["Tardive dyskinesia, potentially irreversible", "Profound apomorphine-induced hypotension", "Cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome", "Serotonin syndrome from 5-HT3 blockade", "Hyperglycemia and weight gain"], 0, "Metoclopramide carries a boxed warning for tardive dyskinesia, which can be irreversible; risk rises with treatment duration and cumulative dose, so use is limited to no more than 12 weeks whenever possible. Parmar flags this as the exam-relevant adverse effect for this widely used drug.\n\nWhy not — Profound apomorphine-induced hypotension: Apomorphine hypotension is the ondansetron contraindication, not a metoclopramide effect.  Cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome: CHS is a chronic cannabinoid (dronabinol/nabilone) effect.  Serotonin syndrome from 5-HT3 blockade: Serotonin syndrome is a rare setron effect, not the metoclopramide boxed warning.  Hyperglycemia and weight gain: Hyperglycemia/weight gain are dexamethasone effects, not metoclopramide's.", "advanced"], ["Droperidol carries a boxed warning that mandates a 12-lead ECG before dosing and continued monitoring afterward because it causes:", ["QT prolongation and torsades", "Irreversible tardive dyskinesia", "Profound serotonin syndrome", "Cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome", "Acute dystonic respiratory depression"], 0, "Droperidol (a butyrophenone D2 antagonist used for PONV) has a boxed warning for QT prolongation and torsades de pointes; it is contraindicated with a prolonged baseline QT, and all patients need a 12-lead ECG before and for 2-3 hours after the dose.\n\nWhy not — Irreversible tardive dyskinesia: Irreversible TD is metoclopramide's boxed warning, not droperidol's ECG concern.  Profound serotonin syndrome: Serotonin syndrome is a setron risk, not droperidol's.  Cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome: CHS is a cannabinoid effect.  Acute dystonic respiratory depression: Respiratory depression is the promethazine/dimenhydrinate pediatric warning, not droperidol's QT issue.", "basic"], ["Compared with first-generation setrons, palonosetron is preferred for both acute and delayed CINV chiefly because it has:", ["Higher receptor affinity and a longer half-life", "Selective antagonism at NK1 substance-P receptors", "Added muscarinic and histaminic blockade", "Direct dopamine D2 antagonism in the CTZ", "A faster onset with a shorter duration of action"], 0, "Palonosetron is the second-generation 5-HT3 antagonist: higher receptor affinity and a markedly longer half-life give it efficacy against both acute and delayed CINV and the least QT effect of the class. It does not gain its advantage by acting on other receptors.\n\nWhy not — Selective antagonism at NK1 substance-P receptors: NK1 antagonism is the -pitants; setrons are selective for 5-HT3.  Added muscarinic and histaminic blockade: Multi-receptor (M/H) blockade describes olanzapine, not palonosetron.  Direct dopamine D2 antagonism in the CTZ: Setrons lack significant D2 activity by design.  A faster onset with a shorter duration of action: Palonosetron has a LONGER, not shorter, duration.", "basic"]]], [9, "Discuss the potential contraindications and drug interactions of the antiemetics and prokinetic agents", [["A patient with Parkinson's disease needs an antiemetic. Which class must be avoided because it worsens the underlying disease?", ["Dopamine D2 receptor antagonists", "Serotonin 5-HT3 receptor antagonists", "Neurokinin-1 receptor antagonists targeting substance P", "Histamine H1 receptor antagonists", "Cannabinoid CB1 receptor agonists"], 0, "Parkinson's reflects dopamine-neuron loss, so blocking dopamine worsens it — every D2 antagonist antiemetic (prochlorperazine, promethazine, droperidol, metoclopramide, amisulpride) is contraindicated. This is the same D2-blockade mechanism behind their EPS.\n\nWhy not — Serotonin 5-HT3 receptor antagonists: 5-HT3 antagonists don't block dopamine and are not Parkinson's-contraindicated.  Neurokinin-1 receptor antagonists targeting substance P: NK1 antagonists target substance P, not dopamine.  Histamine H1 receptor antagonists: H1 antihistamines are not contraindicated by dopamine blockade.  Cannabinoid CB1 receptor agonists: Cannabinoids act at CB1 and don't worsen Parkinson's by this mechanism.", "advanced"], ["A highly emetogenic regimen is covered with a 5-HT3 antagonist, dexamethasone, and an NK1 antagonist. If aprepitant is the NK1 agent, the prescriber must adjust therapy by:", ["Reducing the dexamethasone dose, because aprepitant inhibits CYP3A4", "Leaving dexamethasone unchanged, because aprepitant induces CYP3A4", "Reducing the dexamethasone dose, because aprepitant inhibits CYP2D6", "Doubling the dexamethasone dose to overcome CYP3A4 induction", "Switching dexamethasone to the 5-HT3 antagonist to avoid the interaction"], 0, "Aprepitant (and fosaprepitant/netupitant) are moderate CYP3A4 inhibitors. Dexamethasone is a CYP3A4 substrate, so inhibiting that enzyme raises dexamethasone levels and risks toxicity — the dexamethasone dose must be reduced. Rolapitant would be the contrast: it inhibits CYP2D6, not CYP3A4, so it needs no adjustment. Parmar flags this as a frequent COMLEX P450 question.\n\nWhy not — Leaving dexamethasone unchanged, because aprepitant induces CYP3A4: Aprepitant inhibits (does not induce) CYP3A4, so dexamethasone is NOT left unchanged.  Reducing the dexamethasone dose, because aprepitant inhibits CYP2D6: Aprepitant inhibits CYP3A4, not CYP2D6 — that's rolapitant (which needs no adjustment).  Doubling the dexamethasone dose to overcome CYP3A4 induction: Inhibition raises levels, so the dose is reduced, not doubled.  Switching dexamethasone to the 5-HT3 antagonist to avoid the interaction: You reduce the dexamethasone dose; you don't substitute the setron for it.", "advanced"]]]]], [37, "Abdominal Trauma (Lec 37)", [[1, "Describe abdominal anatomy and mapping", [["A stab wound to the left upper quadrant is most likely to injure which organ?", ["Spleen", "Appendix", "Sigmoid colon", "Gallbladder", "Cecum"], 0, "The left upper quadrant houses the spleen (plus the left lobe of liver, stomach, body of pancreas, and left kidney). The spleen's thin capsule and ligamentous attachments make it the classic LUQ injury.\n\nWhy not — Appendix: The appendix is a right-lower-quadrant structure, not LUQ.  Sigmoid colon: The sigmoid colon is a left-lower-quadrant structure.  Gallbladder: The gallbladder is in the right upper quadrant and rarely injured.  Cecum: The cecum is in the right lower quadrant.", "advanced"], ["Which structure is retroperitoneal and therefore vulnerable to a crush injury against the spine?", ["Pancreas", "Transverse colon", "Stomach", "Small intestine", "Gallbladder"], 0, "The pancreas lies retroperitoneally across the spine, so a midline compressive force can crush or even transect it against the vertebral column. Mobile organs like the small intestine slide out of the way.\n\nWhy not — Transverse colon: The transverse colon is intraperitoneal and relatively mobile.  Stomach: The stomach is intraperitoneal and gets injured mainly when markedly distended.  Small intestine: The small intestine is mobile and usually slips away from blunt force.  Gallbladder: The gallbladder is intraperitoneal and very rarely ruptures.", "basic"], ["The abdominal aorta bifurcates into the common iliac arteries at approximately which level?", ["Fourth-to-fifth lumbar vertebra", "First lumbar vertebra", "Twelfth thoracic vertebra", "First sacral vertebra", "Tenth thoracic vertebra"], 0, "The abdominal aorta begins below the diaphragm and bifurcates into the right and left common iliac arteries at about the L4–L5 level — anatomy that matters for where a REBOA balloon can be safely seated.\n\nWhy not — First lumbar vertebra: L1 is roughly where the aorta gives off the renal/SMA region, not where it bifurcates.  Twelfth thoracic vertebra: T12 is near the aortic hiatus where the aorta enters the abdomen.  First sacral vertebra: S1 is below the bifurcation, in the iliac territory.  Tenth thoracic vertebra: T10 is the esophageal-hiatus level, well above the abdominal aorta.", "basic"]]], [2, "Describe diagnostic imaging and lab studies requested for abdominal trauma patients", [["During a FAST examination in a trauma patient, the sonographer is primarily looking for:", ["Free intraperitoneal blood", "Gallstones in the gallbladder", "Bowel-wall thickening", "Renal artery stenosis", "An abdominal aortic aneurysm"], 0, "FAST (Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma) screens the dependent spaces for free fluid — blood — and can also reveal air and gross organ injury. Density even lets you tell blood from serous fluid. Rose's single biggest point was to learn ultrasound.\n\nWhy not — Gallstones in the gallbladder: Gallstones are a non-trauma indication; FAST is hunting for free fluid.  Bowel-wall thickening: Bowel-wall thickening is an inflammatory finding, not the FAST target.  Renal artery stenosis: Renal artery stenosis is a chronic vascular question, not a trauma FAST.  An abdominal aortic aneurysm: An AAA can be seen on ultrasound but is not what the trauma FAST is for.", "advanced"], ["A trauma patient is hypotensive and tachycardic with a tense, distended abdomen and a positive FAST. The next step is:", ["Immediate exploratory laparotomy", "CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis with contrast", "Admit for serial abdominal exams", "Diagnostic peritoneal lavage", "MRI of the abdomen"], 0, "An unstable patient with a positive FAST is exsanguinating into the abdomen and goes straight to the OR — there is no time to scan. CT is reserved for the patient you can stabilize. Stability, not the organ, drives the disposition.\n\nWhy not — CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis with contrast: CT is only for the patient who stabilizes; an unstable patient cannot wait for it.  Admit for serial abdominal exams: Serial exams are for a stable, reassuring patient, not a crashing one.  Diagnostic peritoneal lavage: DPL is largely historical and would only confirm what the positive FAST already shows.  MRI of the abdomen: MRI takes far too long for an unstable trauma patient.", "advanced"], ["A hemodynamically stable blunt-trauma patient has a white-count differential showing a left shift with rising leukocytes. This finding most directly suggests:", ["An evolving infectious/inflammatory process from visceral contamination", "Acute blood loss with hemodilution", "A normal stress response requiring no action", "An electrolyte disturbance on the metabolic panel", "Renal injury reaching the collecting system"], 0, "A left shift with increasing leukocytes signals the body mobilizing white cells against contamination — for example a perforated viscus spilling bowel content. The H/H tracks blood loss; the WBC differential tracks contamination/infection.\n\nWhy not — Acute blood loss with hemodilution: Blood loss is read from the hemoglobin/hematocrit, not the WBC left shift.  A normal stress response requiring no action: A frank left shift with rising leukocytes is not a finding to ignore.  An electrolyte disturbance on the metabolic panel: Electrolyte disturbances show on the BMP, not as a WBC left shift.  Renal injury reaching the collecting system: Collecting-system injury is signaled by hematuria, not the WBC differential.", "advanced"]]], [3, "List different types of abdominal trauma", [["A surgeon tears the splenic capsule while retracting on the gastrosplenic ligament during a hiatal hernia repair. This is an example of which type of trauma?", ["Iatrogenic", "Blast", "Crush", "Penetrating", "Deceleration"], 0, "Injury caused by the medical procedure itself is iatrogenic. Rose noted the spleen is injured in roughly 2% of left-upper-quadrant operations via traction on the gastrosplenic ligament — a traction-type capsular avulsion.\n\nWhy not — Blast: Blast injury is from an explosive pressure wave, not an operation.  Crush: Crush is external compression, e.g., against the spine.  Penetrating: Penetrating implies an object breaching the wall, not surgical traction.  Deceleration: Deceleration is the rapid-stop mechanism of MVAs, not operative traction.", "advanced"]]], [4, "Describe splenic, liver, and renal injuries", [["The most frequently injured solid organ in blunt abdominal trauma is the:", ["Spleen", "Liver", "Kidney", "Pancreas", "Stomach"], 0, "The spleen is the most frequently injured organ following blunt trauma to the abdomen or lower thorax, and splenic injury is the most common reason for splenectomy in the U.S. Its thin capsule tears easily.\n\nWhy not — Liver: The liver is also commonly injured but is not the single most frequent in blunt trauma.  Kidney: The kidney is injured less often and usually with flank/back force.  Pancreas: The pancreas is injured mainly by focal crush against the spine, not commonly.  Stomach: The stomach is rarely injured unless markedly distended.", "advanced"], ["A patient with a splenic injury complains of left-shoulder pain and hiccups. This finding is:", ["Kehr's sign", "Ballance's sign", "Cullen sign", "Gray-Turner sign", "Cullen-Murphy sign"], 0, "Kehr's sign is left-shoulder pain referred from diaphragmatic irritation by subdiaphragmatic blood — the same phrenic-nerve irritation that causes the hiccups. Rose flagged it explicitly as a board question.\n\nWhy not — Ballance's sign: Ballance's sign is fixed dullness to percussion (a mass effect), and is seldom seen.  Cullen sign: Cullen sign is periumbilical ecchymosis, not referred shoulder pain.  Gray-Turner sign: Gray-Turner sign is flank ecchymosis, not referred shoulder pain.  Cullen-Murphy sign: There is no such entity; this distractor mixes two unrelated eponyms.", "advanced"], ["A shattered spleen with multiple fractures and hilar injury is best classified as:", ["Grade IV–V (not repairable)", "Grade I (minor capsular tear)", "Grade II (capsular avulsion, minor)", "Grade III (through-and-through laceration)", "Grade 0 (contusion only)"], 0, "Grades IV–V are severe stellate fractures, crush/bisection, hilar injury, and the shattered spleen — injuries that are not repairable and require splenectomy. Grades I–III can usually be repaired or observed.\n\nWhy not — Grade I (minor capsular tear): Grade I is a minor capsular tear or laceration, easily repaired.  Grade II (capsular avulsion, minor): Grade II adds a capsular avulsion but most of the spleen is intact.  Grade III (through-and-through laceration): Grade III is a major fracture/through-and-through laceration — still often repairable.  Grade 0 (contusion only): AAST splenic grading runs I–V; there is no 'grade 0 contusion' category here.", "advanced"], ["Why are children with splenic injury preferentially managed with repair or observation rather than splenectomy?", ["To prevent overwhelming infection after splenectomy", "Because their spleens cannot be removed surgically", "Because pediatric spleens never rupture", "To preserve red-cell production by the spleen", "Because antibiotics fully replace splenic function"], 0, "Splenectomy removes the filter for encapsulated bacteria and lowers IgM and opsonin production, leaving the patient — especially a child — at risk for overwhelming post-splenectomy infection. So we save the spleen when it is safe.\n\nWhy not — Because their spleens cannot be removed surgically: Pediatric spleens can be removed; we avoid it to preserve immune function.  Because pediatric spleens never rupture: Children's spleens absolutely can rupture — that is the whole problem.  To preserve red-cell production by the spleen: The spleen's key lost function here is immune filtering/opsonization, not adult RBC production.  Because antibiotics fully replace splenic function: Vaccination and prophylaxis help but do not fully replace splenic function.", "advanced"], ["A patient had a resolving splenic hematoma observed in hospital, then returns two weeks later in shock with a growing hematoma. This is best described as:", ["Delayed splenic rupture", "Spontaneous splenic rupture", "A grade I capsular tear", "Subphrenic abscess", "Iatrogenic splenic injury"], 0, "Delayed splenic rupture presents with instability days to weeks (usually within 2 weeks) after trauma, from a slowly enlarging subcapsular hematoma that finally bursts — Rose's own observed case. It is distinct from spontaneous rupture of a diseased spleen.\n\nWhy not — Spontaneous splenic rupture: Spontaneous rupture occurs in a diseased spleen (malaria, mono) without antecedent trauma.  A grade I capsular tear: A grade I capsular tear is a minor injury, not a delayed catastrophic rupture.  Subphrenic abscess: A subphrenic abscess is a post-splenectomy infection, not a hematoma rupture.  Iatrogenic splenic injury: Iatrogenic injury happens during an operation, not two weeks later at home.", "advanced"], ["Worldwide, the most common cause of spontaneous rupture of a diseased spleen is:", ["Malaria", "Infectious mononucleosis", "Polycythemia vera", "Chronic leukemia", "Sarcoidosis"], 0, "Worldwide the leading cause of spontaneous splenic rupture is malaria, followed by infectious mononucleosis. Both engorge and enlarge the spleen, stretching its thin capsule until it tears.\n\nWhy not — Infectious mononucleosis: Infectious mononucleosis is the second-most-common cause (and the classic U.S. one).  Polycythemia vera: Polycythemia vera enlarges the spleen but is not the leading worldwide cause.  Chronic leukemia: Chronic leukemia causes splenomegaly but is not the top cause worldwide.  Sarcoidosis: Sarcoidosis is on the list but is uncommon as a rupture cause.", "basic"], ["In a stable patient with blunt renal trauma, gross hematuria indicates that the injury has reached the:", ["Renal collecting system", "Renal capsule only", "Perirenal fat without parenchyma", "Adrenal gland", "Ureterovesical junction"], 0, "Hematuria means the laceration has communicated with the collecting system (renal pelvis). A contusion or contained subcapsular hematoma that spares the collecting system may show little or no blood. The depth of laceration drives the need for surgery.\n\nWhy not — Renal capsule only: A capsule-only injury (grade I) gives at most microscopic hematuria.  Perirenal fat without parenchyma: Injury limited to perirenal fat does not produce gross hematuria.  Adrenal gland: Adrenal injury does not produce hematuria.  Ureterovesical junction: The UVJ is distal; renal-pelvis communication is what gross hematuria signals here.", "advanced"], ["A child with a rapid-deceleration injury has flank pain but a NEGATIVE urinalysis. The injury you must not miss is:", ["Avulsion of the ureteropelvic junction", "A grade I renal contusion", "A bladder rupture", "A renal-vein thrombosis with hematuria", "A simple renal capsular tear"], 0, "In children, rapid deceleration can avulse the ureteropelvic junction; because no urine then reaches the bladder, the urinalysis can be falsely negative. A negative UA does not exclude a major renal injury in this setting — image the child.\n\nWhy not — A grade I renal contusion: A grade I contusion would typically still show some hematuria, not justify the concern.  A bladder rupture: Bladder rupture usually shows hematuria and a different mechanism.  A renal-vein thrombosis with hematuria: Vein thrombosis would not be the classic 'negative UA' pediatric trap — UPJ avulsion is.  A simple renal capsular tear: A simple capsular tear is minor and is not the dangerous miss here.", "advanced"], ["A stable patient with blunt flank trauma has CT showing a renal laceration. The single factor that most determines whether operative exploration is needed is:", ["The depth of the laceration", "The patient's age", "The presence of microscopic hematuria", "Whether a rib is fractured", "The serum creatinine on admission"], 0, "Rose's rule: it is the depth of the laceration that determines the need for surgery. A stable patient with a deep injury into the collecting system or vasculature may need exploration, while shallow injuries trend toward observation; an unstable patient goes to the OR regardless.\n\nWhy not — The patient's age: Age affects overall risk tolerance but does not define the renal-surgery decision.  The presence of microscopic hematuria: Microscopic hematuria alone often does not even mandate imaging in stable adults.  Whether a rib is fractured: A rib fracture is an associated finding, not the determinant of renal surgery.  The serum creatinine on admission: Creatinine reflects baseline function, not the acute need to explore.", "advanced"]]], [5, "Describe pancreatic, pelvic, and thoracoabdominal trauma", [["Pancreatic injury from blunt trauma most characteristically results from:", ["A crush against the spine", "A penetrating flank stab wound", "Rapid deceleration tearing a ligament", "An iatrogenic traction injury", "A blast pressure wave"], 0, "The pancreas lies across the spine retroperitoneally, so a focal midline blow (steering wheel, handlebar) crushes — or even transects — it against the vertebral column. Rose's garbage-truck case bisected the pancreas right over the spine.\n\nWhy not — A penetrating flank stab wound: Penetrating injury can hit the pancreas but is not the characteristic blunt mechanism.  Rapid deceleration tearing a ligament: Deceleration ligament tears are the spleen/liver story, not the pancreas.  An iatrogenic traction injury: Iatrogenic traction is the splenic-capsule mechanism, not pancreatic.  A blast pressure wave: Blast injury is a different mechanism than the classic spine-crush.", "advanced"], ["Which laboratory studies are most useful for suspected pancreatic injury?", ["Amylase and lipase", "Troponin and BNP", "PT/PTT/INR", "Lactate dehydrogenase and haptoglobin", "Ammonia and bilirubin"], 0, "Pancreatic enzymes — amylase and lipase — rise with pancreatic injury, and ERCP can define the ductal anatomy. They are also part of what is checked for in peritoneal fluid when lavage is used.\n\nWhy not — Troponin and BNP: Troponin/BNP are cardiac markers, irrelevant to pancreatic injury.  PT/PTT/INR: Coagulation studies matter before surgery but do not diagnose pancreatic injury.  Lactate dehydrogenase and haptoglobin: LDH/haptoglobin assess hemolysis, not the pancreas.  Ammonia and bilirubin: Ammonia/bilirubin reflect hepatic function, not pancreatic injury.", "basic"], ["Diagnostic peritoneal lavage (DPL) is now largely of historical interest mainly because:", ["CT answers the same questions quickly", "DPL cannot detect intraperitoneal blood", "DPL requires general anesthesia to perform", "Ultrasound cannot be used in trauma", "Amylase in lavage fluid is never informative"], 0, "DPL once answered 'is there blood, bile, fecal material, or amylase in the abdomen?' but CT answers those quickly and noninvasively, so lavage is rarely performed now (still used where imaging is unavailable).\n\nWhy not — DPL cannot detect intraperitoneal blood: DPL is in fact very sensitive for blood — that was its purpose.  DPL requires general anesthesia to perform: DPL is a bedside procedure, not one requiring general anesthesia.  Ultrasound cannot be used in trauma: Ultrasound (FAST) is heavily used in trauma — it complements CT.  Amylase in lavage fluid is never informative: Amylase in lavage fluid is informative; that was part of DPL's value.", "basic"], ["REBOA (resuscitative endovascular balloon occlusion of the aorta) is used to temporarily control hemorrhage and:", ["May be deployed only in certain zones", "Is placed across the renal arteries to maximize control", "Replaces the need for any operative repair", "Is a permanent indwelling device", "Is contraindicated in all hemorrhagic shock"], 0, "REBOA buys time by occluding the aorta in defined zones; the balloon is deliberately NOT placed across the renal-artery segment (Zone II) because that would cause renal ischemia. It is a temporizing bridge, not a definitive repair.\n\nWhy not — Is placed across the renal arteries to maximize control: Occluding across the renal arteries causes renal ischemia — that zone is avoided.  Replaces the need for any operative repair: REBOA is temporizing; definitive control still requires surgery or angioembolization.  Is a permanent indwelling device: It is a temporary balloon, not a permanent device.  Is contraindicated in all hemorrhagic shock: REBOA is used precisely in selected hemorrhagic-shock patients.", "basic"]]]]], [38, "Abdominal Pain — Diverticulitis (Lec 38)", [[1, "List the appropriate history questions needed for a patient with diverticulitis", [["A 68-year-old woman has 3 days of left-lower-quadrant abdominal pain with subjective fever. Following Moljo's approach, the FIRST framing that should drive your history is:", ["What anatomic structures sit in that quadrant", "Which antibiotic regimen she will ultimately need", "Her modified Hinchey stage", "Whether she requires emergency surgery", "Which CT contrast medium is safest"], 0, "Moljo's repeated lesson is anatomy-first: \"for the abdominal exam… always start with anatomy.\" Naming what sits in the painful quadrant (colon, ovary, bladder) generates the differential, and the targeted history questions follow from it. Staging, antibiotics, and contrast come later.\n\nWhy not — Which antibiotic regimen she will ultimately need: The regimen is a management decision made after diagnosis, not the opening history framing.  Her modified Hinchey stage: Hinchey is a CT-based stage assigned after imaging, not a history starting point.  Whether she requires emergency surgery: Surgical need is decided by stability and stage, not at the history-taking step.  Which CT contrast medium is safest: Contrast choice is a testing decision, not the frame that drives the history.", "advanced"], ["A man with known diverticular disease reports passing air in his urine (pneumaturia) and seeing stool in the urine. These history clues point to:", ["A colovesical fistula", "An uncomplicated diverticular abscess", "A simple urinary tract infection", "A free perforation with peritonitis", "Diverticular bleeding"], 0, "Pneumaturia (air in urine) and fecaluria (stool in urine) are the classic tells of a colovesical fistula — an abnormal connection between the inflamed colon and the bladder. They are specific history questions worth asking when a fistulizing complication is on the table.\n\nWhy not — An uncomplicated diverticular abscess: An abscess causes a tender mass and fever, not air and stool in the urine.  A simple urinary tract infection: A plain UTI causes dysuria and frequency, not stool or air passing in the urine.  A free perforation with peritonitis: Free perforation produces diffuse peritonitis, not selectively urinary symptoms.  Diverticular bleeding: Diverticular bleeding produces hematochezia/melena, not pneumaturia and fecaluria.", "advanced"], ["Which feature in the diverticulitis history is MOST consistent with the typical presentation?", ["Constant left-lower-quadrant pain with fever and chills", "Sudden painless large-volume rectal bleeding", "Right-upper-quadrant pain radiating to the scapula", "Burning epigastric pain relieved by food", "Crampy periumbilical pain migrating to the right-lower quadrant"], 0, "Diverticulitis classically presents as constant LLQ pain with low-grade fever (the sigmoid colon is the usual site in Western patients). Painless bleeding is diverticulOSIS, not diverticulITIS — the osis/itis split the course flags repeatedly.\n\nWhy not — Sudden painless large-volume rectal bleeding: Painless large-volume bleeding describes diverticulOSIS, not the inflammatory diverticulITIS.  Right-upper-quadrant pain radiating to the scapula: RUQ pain to the scapula suggests biliary disease, not sigmoid diverticulitis.  Burning epigastric pain relieved by food: Epigastric burning relieved by food is the peptic-ulcer pattern.  Crampy periumbilical pain migrating to the right-lower quadrant: Periumbilical-to-RLQ migration is the classic appendicitis history.", "basic"], ["Moljo defends the modern view that, in a patient with diverticular disease, you do NOT need to advise avoiding:", ["Nuts, seeds, corn, and popcorn", "Red meat eaten six or more times weekly", "A chronically low-fiber diet", "Heavy alcohol use", "A sedentary lifestyle"], 0, "The seeds/nuts/corn/popcorn restriction is a debunked myth — these foods are not associated with increased diverticulitis risk, and Moljo defended this point repeatedly. The real dietary risk is red meat (≥6 servings/week) plus a low-fiber diet.\n\nWhy not — Red meat eaten six or more times weekly: High red-meat intake (≥6 servings/week) IS a genuine risk factor to counsel against.  A chronically low-fiber diet: A low-fiber diet is a real risk factor and should be corrected.  Heavy alcohol use: Heavy alcohol use is associated with diverticulitis and is worth limiting.  A sedentary lifestyle: A sedentary lifestyle raises risk; physical activity is protective.", "advanced"], ["When a woman presents with LLQ pain, why does Moljo argue the declined pelvic exam still matters?", ["Ovarian and uterine pathology can mimic the colonic source", "It is required before ordering any CT scan", "It establishes the modified Hinchey stage", "It is the only way to detect a colovesical fistula", "It rules out an upper-GI bleeding source"], 0, "Anatomy-first reasoning means the LLQ pain could arise from the ovary or uterus, not the colon. A bimanual exam can localize the pain to a pelvic structure and detect cervical motion tenderness (PID) — which is exactly why declining it leaves a gap.\n\nWhy not — It is required before ordering any CT scan: A pelvic exam is not a prerequisite for ordering CT imaging.  It establishes the modified Hinchey stage: Hinchey staging comes from CT findings, not a pelvic exam.  It is the only way to detect a colovesical fistula: Pneumaturia and fecaluria, not the pelvic exam, are the colovesical-fistula clues.  It rules out an upper-GI bleeding source: A pelvic exam says nothing about an upper-GI source.", "advanced"]]], [2, "Describe which tests are necessary to distinguish between the differential diagnoses in a patient with diverticulitis", [["The imaging study of choice for confirming acute diverticulitis is:", ["CT abdomen/pelvis with oral and IV contrast", "Abdominal and pelvic ultrasound", "MRI of the abdomen and pelvis", "Supine and upright abdominal radiographs", "Colonoscopy during the acute attack"], 0, "CT of the abdomen and pelvis with oral and IV contrast is the study of choice — sensitivity 94%, specificity 99% — and it both confirms the diagnosis and stages complications. Ultrasound is operator-dependent and inferior; MRI avoids radiation but is slower and costlier.\n\nWhy not — Abdominal and pelvic ultrasound: Ultrasound is easy but operator-dependent and less reliable for diverticulitis.  MRI of the abdomen and pelvis: MRI works and spares radiation but is slower, costlier, and lacks the validated CT criteria.  Supine and upright abdominal radiographs: Plain films screen for free air and obstruction but cannot confirm diverticulitis.  Colonoscopy during the acute attack: Colonoscopy is contraindicated during the acute attack (risk of perforation).", "basic"], ["The sensitivity and specificity of abdominal/pelvic CT for acute diverticulitis are approximately:", ["94% sensitivity and 99% specificity", "99% sensitivity and 94% specificity", "75% sensitivity and 80% specificity", "60% sensitivity and 70% specificity", "50% sensitivity and 50% specificity"], 0, "Moljo recited these explicitly: CT sensitivity is 94% and specificity is 99% for acute diverticulitis. The high specificity is what makes a positive CT confirmatory.\n\nWhy not — 99% sensitivity and 94% specificity: The figures are reversed — sensitivity 94, specificity 99, not the other way around.  75% sensitivity and 80% specificity: These understate CT's accuracy for diverticulitis.  60% sensitivity and 70% specificity: 60/70 are far below CT's actual performance here.  50% sensitivity and 50% specificity: Coin-flip accuracy would not make CT the study of choice.", "basic"], ["Perforation is suspected, so a contrast study is being considered. The correct contrast choice is:", ["A water-soluble medium, because leaked barium causes peritonitis", "Barium, because it gives superior mucosal detail", "Barium, because it is absorbed if it leaks", "No contrast at all, because contrast is always unsafe here", "A water-soluble medium, because barium is too costly"], 0, "When perforation is possible, use a water-soluble medium: if it leaks into the peritoneum it is harmlessly absorbed, whereas leaked barium causes severe barium peritonitis. Moljo emphasized this — barium leak is \"very big trouble.\"\n\nWhy not — Barium, because it gives superior mucosal detail: Barium's detail advantage is irrelevant when a leak would cause peritonitis.  Barium, because it is absorbed if it leaks: It is backwards: water-soluble contrast is absorbed; barium is not and causes peritonitis.  No contrast at all, because contrast is always unsafe here: Contrast is not categorically unsafe — the water-soluble medium is safe.  A water-soluble medium, because barium is too costly: Cost is not the reason; the reason is barium peritonitis risk on perforation.", "basic"], ["On CT, which combination of findings is most suggestive of acute diverticulitis?", ["Bowel-wall thickening >4 mm, pericolonic fat stranding, and diverticula", "Diffuse small-bowel dilation with multiple air-fluid levels", "A thickened gallbladder wall with pericholecystic fluid", "Free air under the diaphragm as the only finding", "Target-sign appendiceal wall thickening in the right lower quadrant"], 0, "The CT triad for diverticulitis is localized bowel-wall thickening (>4 mm), pericolonic fat stranding from inflammation, and the presence of colonic diverticula. Isolated free air points to perforation; the others describe different organs.\n\nWhy not — Diffuse small-bowel dilation with multiple air-fluid levels: Diffuse small-bowel dilation with air-fluid levels is an obstruction/ileus pattern.  A thickened gallbladder wall with pericholecystic fluid: Gallbladder-wall thickening with pericholecystic fluid is cholecystitis.  Free air under the diaphragm as the only finding: Isolated free air signals perforation, not uncomplicated diverticulitis.  Target-sign appendiceal wall thickening in the right lower quadrant: Appendiceal wall thickening with a target sign is appendicitis.", "basic"], ["A woman of reproductive age is being worked up for possible diverticulitis before contrast CT. Which two tests does Moljo specifically tie to giving contrast safely?", ["Renal function on the CMP and HCG", "C-reactive protein and erythrocyte sedimentation rate", "Blood cultures and a complete blood count", "Liver function tests and a lipase", "Urinalysis and a stool guaiac"], 0, "Before IV contrast you confirm adequate renal function (CMP) — \"if we need to use contrast we need to make sure the renal function is good\" — and in a woman of childbearing age you check an HCG. CRP/ESR gauge inflammation but do not gate contrast.\n\nWhy not — C-reactive protein and erythrocyte sedimentation rate: CRP/ESR mark inflammation but neither gates the safety of giving contrast.  Blood cultures and a complete blood count: Blood cultures and CBC assess bacteremia and infection, not contrast safety.  Liver function tests and a lipase: LFTs and lipase help other differentials, not contrast clearance or pregnancy.  Urinalysis and a stool guaiac: Urinalysis and guaiac address UTI and bleeding, not contrast safety.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Describe the clinical presentation and management of diverticulosis versus diverticulitis", [["A colonic diverticulum is correctly described as a PSEUDOdiverticulum because it:", ["Herniates mucosa and submucosa, not all wall layers", "Contains all layers of the colonic wall, including muscularis", "Is a congenital outpouching present from birth", "Forms only after an episode of acute inflammation", "Is a true diverticulum lined by gastric-type mucosa"], 0, "A colonic diverticulum is a pseudodiverticulum: mucosa and submucosa herniate through weak points in the muscular wall (often where vessels penetrate), so it does NOT contain all the colonic layers. A true diverticulum would include the full wall.\n\nWhy not — Contains all layers of the colonic wall, including muscularis: If it contained all wall layers it would be a true diverticulum, not a pseudodiverticulum.  Is a congenital outpouching present from birth: Most Western colonic diverticula are acquired, not congenital.  Forms only after an episode of acute inflammation: Diverticula precede and predispose to inflammation; they are not caused by it.  Is a true diverticulum lined by gastric-type mucosa: Gastric-type lining describes a Meckel diverticulum, not a colonic pseudodiverticulum.", "advanced"], ["Which statement correctly separates diverticulOSIS from diverticulITIS?", ["Diverticulosis is diverticula present; diverticulitis is them inflamed", "Diverticulosis is inflamed diverticula; diverticulitis is uninflamed pouches", "Diverticulosis always causes pain; diverticulitis is always painless", "Diverticulosis requires surgery; diverticulitis is observed", "Diverticulosis is congenital; diverticulitis is always acquired"], 0, "DiverticulOSIS is simply the presence of diverticula (often asymptomatic); diverticulITIS is inflammation of a diverticulum, which can be uncomplicated or complicated. This osis/itis hinge is the course-flagged distinction — and the painless-bleed counterpart lives in the endoscopy lecture.\n\nWhy not — Diverticulosis is inflamed diverticula; diverticulitis is uninflamed pouches: This reverses the two terms.  Diverticulosis always causes pain; diverticulitis is always painless: Diverticulosis is frequently asymptomatic; diverticulitis is the painful one.  Diverticulosis requires surgery; diverticulitis is observed: Most diverticulitis is managed medically; diverticulosis needs only risk-factor modification.  Diverticulosis is congenital; diverticulitis is always acquired: Western diverticula are usually acquired; the congenital note applies to proximal Asian disease.", "basic"], ["In Western countries, diverticulosis is most prevalent in the LEFT colon. Which population is noted for predominantly PROXIMAL (right-sided) disease that is often congenital?", ["Asian people and Pacific Islanders", "Northern Europeans", "Patients with chronic NSAID use", "Patients with inflammatory bowel disease", "Vegans on high-fiber diets"], 0, "Asian people and Pacific Islanders have increased odds of proximal (right-sided) diverticulosis that is often congenital — Moljo confirmed this with a student's report of right-sided disease on a rotation in Asia. Western disease is predominantly left-sided/sigmoid.\n\nWhy not — Northern Europeans: Northern Europeans follow the Western left-sided pattern.  Patients with chronic NSAID use: NSAIDs raise bleeding/perforation risk but do not shift diverticula to the right colon.  Patients with inflammatory bowel disease: IBD is a separate entity and does not define proximal diverticulosis.  Vegans on high-fiber diets: A high-fiber vegan diet is protective; it does not relocate diverticula proximally.", "basic"], ["How does the prevalence of diverticulOSIS change across the adult lifespan in the United States?", ["Under 20% at 40, ~60% by age 60", "About 60% at 40, falling to under 20%", "Stays near 50% across all adult ages", "Essentially absent until after age 70", "Peaks in the twenties, then declines thereafter"], 0, "US diverticulosis prevalence climbs steeply with age — from fewer than 20% at age 40 to roughly 60% by age 60 — and the number and size of diverticula increase as well. It is fundamentally a disease of aging.\n\nWhy not — About 60% at 40, falling to under 20%: The trend rises with age; it does not fall.  Stays near 50% across all adult ages: Prevalence is strongly age-dependent, not flat at 50%.  Essentially absent until after age 70: Diverticula are common well before 70 and increase steadily from mid-adulthood.  Peaks in the twenties, then declines thereafter: It increases with age rather than peaking in the twenties.", "basic"]]], [4, "Describe the management of diverticulitis, its prognosis, and resultant complications", [["A reliable, immunocompetent outpatient has CT-confirmed UNCOMPLICATED diverticulitis. The most appropriate management is:", ["Low-fiber diet and analgesia, no antibiotics", "Immediate broad-spectrum IV antibiotics and admission", "Urgent sigmoid colectomy now", "CT-guided percutaneous abscess drainage", "Colonoscopy this admission to confirm diagnosis"], 0, "Selected uncomplicated outpatients are managed with a clear diet advancing to low fiber, acetaminophen and antispasmodics, and close follow-up — antibiotics are usually not required. Moljo stressed the data: \"we really don't need antibiotics for uncomplicated diverticulitis.\"\n\nWhy not — Immediate broad-spectrum IV antibiotics and admission: IV antibiotics and admission are for complicated disease or high-risk hosts, not this patient.  Urgent sigmoid colectomy now: Urgent colectomy is reserved for Hinchey III/IV or failure of medical therapy.  CT-guided percutaneous abscess drainage: Percutaneous drainage treats an abscess ≥4 cm, which uncomplicated disease lacks.  Colonoscopy this admission to confirm diagnosis: Colonoscopy is deferred to 6–8 weeks after resolution, never during the acute attack.", "advanced"], ["Antibiotics are chosen for a patient with diverticulitis and a fluoroquinolone is selected. To cover anaerobes adequately, you must add:", ["Metronidazole", "Azithromycin", "A second fluoroquinolone", "Vancomycin", "Ceftriaxone"], 0, "Fluoroquinolones and TMP-SMX do not cover anaerobes, so each must be paired with metronidazole (clindamycin if metronidazole is not tolerated). Amoxicillin-clavulanate is the single-agent alternative because it covers both aerobes and anaerobes.\n\nWhy not — Azithromycin: Azithromycin does not provide the anaerobic coverage diverticulitis requires.  A second fluoroquinolone: Adding a second fluoroquinolone still leaves the anaerobic gap unfilled.  Vancomycin: Vancomycin targets gram-positives (e.g., C. diff), not gut anaerobes here.  Ceftriaxone: Ceftriaxone covers gram-negatives but not the anaerobes; it too would need metronidazole.", "advanced"], ["CT shows a 5 cm pericolic abscess complicating diverticulitis. The most appropriate next step is:", ["CT-guided percutaneous drainage plus antibiotics", "Antibiotics alone with no drainage", "Immediate sigmoid colectomy", "Oral diet advancement and discharge", "Barium enema to define the abscess"], 0, "The 4 cm threshold decides the move: an abscess <4 cm is managed with antibiotics alone, while one ≥4 cm gets CT-guided percutaneous drainage added. At 5 cm, drain it. Surgery is reserved for drainage failure or inaccessible collections.\n\nWhy not — Antibiotics alone with no drainage: Antibiotics alone suffice only for abscesses <4 cm; this one is ≥4 cm.  Immediate sigmoid colectomy: Colectomy is for ruptured abscess, Hinchey III/IV, or failed drainage — not a first move here.  Oral diet advancement and discharge: Discharging an untreated 5 cm abscess risks rupture and peritonitis.  Barium enema to define the abscess: Barium is contraindicated when perforation is possible; CT already defines the abscess.", "basic"], ["On CT, a patient has small extraluminal air bubbles but NO oral contrast leaking outside the colon (microperforation). The expected management is:", ["IV antibiotics, with about 94% managed nonoperatively", "Emergency laparotomy for all such patients", "Discharge home on no treatment", "Percutaneous drainage of the free air", "Barium enema to confirm the leak"], 0, "Microperforation (contained — air bubbles but no extraluminal contrast) is treated initially with IV antibiotics, and roughly 94% are managed nonoperatively. That contrasts sharply with frank perforation (free air, feculent peritonitis), which mandates emergency surgery.\n\nWhy not — Emergency laparotomy for all such patients: Emergency surgery is for frank perforation with peritonitis, not contained microperforation.  Discharge home on no treatment: Microperforation still requires IV antibiotics and inpatient observation.  Percutaneous drainage of the free air: You drain a fluid abscess, not scattered air bubbles.  Barium enema to confirm the leak: Barium is contraindicated with a perforation and adds nothing over CT.", "advanced"], ["A patient recovers from a SECOND episode of acute diverticulitis. The approximate risk of a further recurrence, and the most common complication of diverticulitis overall, are:", ["About 66% recurrence; obstruction is the most common complication", "About 33% recurrence; perforation is the most common complication", "About 10% recurrence; abscess is the most common complication", "About 90% recurrence; fistula is the most common complication", "About 50% recurrence; bleeding is the most common complication"], 0, "Recurrence is 33% after a first episode and 66% after a second. Across all complications, obstruction is the most common, followed by perforation and then abscess. These two numbers and the complication ranking are high-yield exam anchors.\n\nWhy not — About 33% recurrence; perforation is the most common complication: 33% is the recurrence after the FIRST episode; after the second it is 66%.  About 10% recurrence; abscess is the most common complication: 10% understates recurrence, and abscess is not the most common complication.  About 90% recurrence; fistula is the most common complication: 90% overstates recurrence; fistula is not the leading complication.  About 50% recurrence; bleeding is the most common complication: 50% is not the quoted figure, and bleeding is not the leading complication.", "advanced"], ["A 45-year-old recovers from his first episode of diverticulitis and has never had a colonoscopy. The correct plan is to perform colonoscopy:", ["6–8 weeks after resolution, to exclude other pathology", "During the acute attack, to confirm the diagnosis", "Within 24 hours of presentation, before starting antibiotics", "Only if he ever develops painless rectal bleeding", "Never, because CT already made the diagnosis"], 0, "Colonoscopy is done 6–8 weeks AFTER the attack resolves (the slide says weeks; the transcript's \"hours\" is an ASR slip), never during the acute attack when scoping risks perforation. In a younger first-time patient it is indicated to exclude colorectal cancer or other pathology.\n\nWhy not — During the acute attack, to confirm the diagnosis: Scoping during the acute attack risks perforating the inflamed colon — it is avoided.  Within 24 hours of presentation, before starting antibiotics: There is no role for emergent colonoscopy before antibiotics in diverticulitis.  Only if he ever develops painless rectal bleeding: The post-resolution scope is to exclude cancer/other pathology, not contingent on later bleeding.  Never, because CT already made the diagnosis: CT diagnoses the attack, but colonoscopy still excludes a coexisting lesion after healing.", "advanced"]]]]], [39, "Chronic Liver Disease (Lec 39–40)", [[1, "Describe alcohol-related liver diseases: epidemiology, risk factors and ethanol metabolism", [["A man with chronic alcohol use has LFTs drawn. Which transaminase pattern is most characteristic?", ["AST higher than ALT", "ALT higher than AST", "AST and ALT both normal", "Alkaline phosphatase alone elevated", "GGT lower than normal"], 0, "Alcohol-related liver disease classically shows AST > ALT (about 2:1), whereas nearly every other liver disease, including metabolic fatty liver, shows ALT > AST. Schneider called this the biggest pearl of the lecture.\n\nWhy not — ALT higher than AST: ALT > AST is the pattern of non-alcoholic and most other liver disease, not alcohol.  AST and ALT both normal: Chronic alcohol injury raises the transaminases; normal values would not fit.  Alkaline phosphatase alone elevated: An isolated alkaline-phosphatase rise points to cholestatic disease, not alcohol.  GGT lower than normal: GGT actually rises with alcohol use; a low GGT would be the opposite finding.", "advanced"], ["Why does a cirrhotic patient characteristically have a low platelet count?", ["Portal hypertension causes splenic sequestration", "The liver stops making thrombopoietin entirely", "Alcohol directly lyses circulating platelets", "Iron overload destroys the bone marrow", "Vitamin K deficiency consumes platelets"], 0, "Cirrhosis raises portal pressure, which enlarges the spleen; the hypersplenic spleen sequesters and consumes platelets. Reading low platelets off a CBC as a clue to cirrhosis is what Schneider called a superpower.\n\nWhy not — The liver stops making thrombopoietin entirely: Thrombopoietin falls somewhat but is not abolished; sequestration is the headline mechanism.  Alcohol directly lyses circulating platelets: Alcohol does not directly lyse platelets in the circulation.  Iron overload destroys the bone marrow: Iron overload (hemochromatosis) is a different disease, not the cirrhosis mechanism here.  Vitamin K deficiency consumes platelets: Vitamin K deficiency raises the PT/INR; it does not consume platelets.", "advanced"], ["A cirrhotic has an elevated PT/INR. The best explanation is that the liver is failing to:", ["Synthesize the vitamin-K-dependent clotting factors normally", "Clear activated clotting factors from the blood", "Store adequate vitamin K within its hepatocytes", "Produce enough circulating platelets for hemostasis", "Absorb dietary vitamin K from the gut"], 0, "The liver synthesizes the vitamin-K-dependent clotting factors II, VII, IX, and X; a failing liver underproduces them, so the PT/INR climbs. This is paired with low platelets as the two-finding blood-work signature of cirrhosis.\n\nWhy not — Clear activated clotting factors from the blood: Impaired clearance of activated factors is not the mechanism of a prolonged PT in cirrhosis.  Store adequate vitamin K within its hepatocytes: The deficit is in making the factors, not in hepatic vitamin-K storage.  Produce enough circulating platelets for hemostasis: Low platelets explain bleeding risk but not the PT/INR specifically.  Absorb dietary vitamin K from the gut: Gut absorption of vitamin K is a separate problem (cholestasis), not the cirrhosis mechanism.", "advanced"], ["Disulfiram (Antabuse) discourages drinking by blocking which enzyme?", ["Acetaldehyde dehydrogenase", "Alcohol dehydrogenase", "Cytochrome P450 2E1", "Catalase in peroxisomes", "Aldehyde reductase in cytosol"], 0, "Disulfiram blocks acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, so toxic acetaldehyde accumulates and causes flushing, nausea, and headache when the patient drinks. This is the same deficiency that gives more than 1 in 3 people of East Asian heritage a flushing reaction.\n\nWhy not — Alcohol dehydrogenase: Alcohol dehydrogenase converts ethanol to acetaldehyde and is not the disulfiram target.  Cytochrome P450 2E1: CYP2E1 is the minor MEOS pathway, not where disulfiram acts.  Catalase in peroxisomes: Catalase plays a trivial role in ethanol metabolism and is not the disulfiram target.  Aldehyde reductase in cytosol: Aldehyde reductase is not the enzyme blocked by disulfiram.", "basic"], ["A patient with alcoholic hepatitis has a Discriminant Function of 38. The appropriate management step is to:", ["Start corticosteroids", "Begin lifelong naltrexone", "Schedule an urgent liver biopsy", "Withhold all pharmacologic therapy", "Give prophylactic broad-spectrum antibiotics"], 0, "A Discriminant Function above 32 marks mortality over 50% and is the threshold to give corticosteroids for alcoholic hepatitis. DF = 4.6(PT - PT control) + total bilirubin, the gold-starred number of the alcohol discussion.\n\nWhy not — Begin lifelong naltrexone: Naltrexone curbs cravings for alcohol use disorder; it does not treat the acute hepatitis.  Schedule an urgent liver biopsy: Biopsy is not the management step that the DF > 32 threshold triggers.  Withhold all pharmacologic therapy: Withholding therapy ignores the DF > 32 indication for steroids.  Give prophylactic broad-spectrum antibiotics: Antibiotic prophylaxis is not what the Discriminant Function score directs.", "advanced"]]], [2, "Review primary biliary cirrhosis (PBC)", [["Primary biliary cholangitis (PBC) occurs overwhelmingly in which patient group?", ["Middle-aged women", "Young men", "Adolescent girls", "Elderly men", "Newborn infants"], 0, "PBC is 95% women, with onset between 30 and 65 and rare before age 30. The professor stressed the female predominance as one of the easiest disease-recognition cues in the lecture.\n\nWhy not — Young men: PSC, not PBC, is the cholangitis that runs predominantly in men.  Adolescent girls: PBC is rare before age 30, so adolescents are not the target group.  Elderly men: Men of any age are the exception, not the rule, in PBC.  Newborn infants: PBC is an acquired adult autoimmune disease, not a neonatal one.", "advanced"], ["Which laboratory finding is most characteristic of primary biliary cholangitis?", ["Antimitochondrial antibodies in 95%", "Antinuclear antibodies in 95%", "Anti-smooth-muscle antibodies in 95%", "Anti-liver-kidney microsomal antibodies", "Elevated 24-hour urinary copper"], 0, "AMA is present in 95% of PBC patients and is the classic diagnostic serology — Schneider called it the easiest answer you will ever give on a test. ANA is also present in many but is not specific.\n\nWhy not — Antinuclear antibodies in 95%: ANA is present in many PBC patients but is not the 95% defining antibody.  Anti-smooth-muscle antibodies in 95%: ASMA marks autoimmune hepatitis in adults, not PBC.  Anti-liver-kidney microsomal antibodies: Anti-LKM marks pediatric autoimmune hepatitis, not PBC.  Elevated 24-hour urinary copper: Urinary copper is the Wilson-disease test, not a PBC finding.", "basic"], ["Which feature best distinguishes PBC from primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC)?", ["PBC is microhepatic; PSC is macrohepatic", "PBC affects men; PSC affects women", "PBC is diagnosed by ERCP; PSC by AMA", "PBC attacks hepatocytes; PSC attacks ducts", "PBC is pediatric; PSC is geriatric"], 0, "PBC injures small (microhepatic) intrahepatic bile ducts and carries AMA; PSC injures larger (macrohepatic) ducts, runs in men, and has no serology (diagnosed by ERCP). Schneider warned students chronically blur these two.\n\nWhy not — PBC affects men; PSC affects women: It is reversed: PBC is the women's disease and PSC the men's.  PBC is diagnosed by ERCP; PSC by AMA: It is reversed: PSC is diagnosed by ERCP and PBC carries AMA.  PBC attacks hepatocytes; PSC attacks ducts: Both PBC and PSC attack bile ducts; AIH attacks hepatocytes.  PBC is pediatric; PSC is geriatric: Neither is defined by pediatric versus geriatric age in this contrast.", "basic"]]], [3, "Describe hereditary hemochromatosis (HHC)", [["Hereditary hemochromatosis is inherited in which pattern and on which chromosome?", ["Autosomal recessive, chromosome 6", "Autosomal recessive, chromosome 13", "Autosomal dominant, chromosome 6", "X-linked recessive, chromosome 13", "Mitochondrial, chromosome 6"], 0, "HHC is autosomal recessive on chromosome 6, with the two classic mutations C282Y and H63D. The chromosome-6 versus chromosome-13 split is the easy way to keep HHC and Wilson apart.\n\nWhy not — Autosomal recessive, chromosome 13: Chromosome 13 is Wilson disease, not hemochromatosis.  Autosomal dominant, chromosome 6: HHC is recessive, not dominant — carriers are common but unaffected.  X-linked recessive, chromosome 13: HHC is autosomal, not X-linked.  Mitochondrial, chromosome 6: HHC is a nuclear single-gene disorder, not mitochondrial.", "basic"], ["A non-obese 45-year-old man develops new diabetes, bronze skin, and arthralgias of the MCP joints. The single mechanism underlying all of these is:", ["Increased iron absorption depositing in multiple organs", "Decreased biliary excretion of copper into bile", "Antimitochondrial destruction of small bile ducts", "Immune-mediated attack on the hepatocytes", "Thrombosis of the hepatic venous outflow"], 0, "In HHC excess iron is absorbed over decades and deposited everywhere — pancreas (diabetes), skin (bronzing), MCP joints (arthralgia/pseudogout). Schneider's pearl: think hemochromatosis in new diabetes when the patient is not overweight.\n\nWhy not — Decreased biliary excretion of copper into bile: Decreased copper excretion is the Wilson mechanism, not iron deposition.  Antimitochondrial destruction of small bile ducts: AMA bile-duct destruction is PBC and does not bronze the skin.  Immune-mediated attack on the hepatocytes: Hepatocyte autoimmune attack is AIH, not multi-organ iron overload.  Thrombosis of the hepatic venous outflow: Hepatic-vein thrombosis is Budd-Chiari, an outflow problem, not iron.", "advanced"], ["Which test is used to screen for hereditary hemochromatosis?", ["Transferrin saturation", "Ceruloplasmin level", "Antimitochondrial antibody", "24-hour urinary copper", "Anti-smooth-muscle antibody"], 0, "HHC is screened with transferrin saturation (serum iron/TIBC x 100); >60% in men or >50% in women makes homozygous HHC ~90% likely, then commercial genetic testing confirms C282Y/H63D.\n\nWhy not — Ceruloplasmin level: Ceruloplasmin is the Wilson-disease test, not the iron screen.  Antimitochondrial antibody: AMA screens for PBC, not iron overload.  24-hour urinary copper: Urinary copper is for Wilson disease, not hemochromatosis.  Anti-smooth-muscle antibody: ASMA marks autoimmune hepatitis, not HHC.", "basic"]]], [4, "Describe Wilson disease (WD)", [["The fundamental defect in Wilson disease is:", ["Decreased biliary excretion of copper", "Increased intestinal absorption of copper", "Decreased intestinal absorption of iron", "Increased biliary excretion of iron", "Decreased renal excretion of copper"], 0, "In Wilson disease copper absorption is normal but biliary excretion is decreased, so copper backs up into the blood and spills into the urine. Schneider hammered the absorption-versus-excretion contrast with HHC.\n\nWhy not — Increased intestinal absorption of copper: Copper absorption is normal in WD — the problem is excretion, not intake.  Decreased intestinal absorption of iron: Iron absorption is the hemochromatosis story, not Wilson.  Increased biliary excretion of iron: Wilson is a copper disease, not an iron-excretion disorder.  Decreased renal excretion of copper: Urinary copper is actually elevated in WD; the failed route is biliary.", "basic"], ["Why is the serum ceruloplasmin level characteristically LOW in Wilson disease?", ["It is consumed, not deficient", "The gene for it is deleted", "It is lost in the urine", "The liver overproduces it", "It binds iron instead of copper"], 0, "Ceruloplasmin falls because of the disordered copper handling — it is consumed, not primarily deficient. Schneider flagged 'it is NOT a ceruloplasmin deficiency' as a common student mistake; a high level excludes WD.\n\nWhy not — The gene for it is deleted: The defect is in copper transport, not deletion of the ceruloplasmin gene.  It is lost in the urine: Copper, not ceruloplasmin, is what spills into the urine in WD.  The liver overproduces it: The liver does not overproduce it; the level falls, it does not rise.  It binds iron instead of copper: Ceruloplasmin is a copper-carrying protein, not an iron carrier.", "basic"], ["An 18-year-old presents with acute liver failure and a hemolytic anemia. Which test is the gold standard for confirming the suspected diagnosis?", ["Liver biopsy for copper quantification", "Transferrin saturation panel", "Antimitochondrial antibody titer", "Serum genetic mutation panel", "Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography"], 0, "Young age plus acute liver failure with hemolysis is a classic Wilson presentation, and liver biopsy for copper quantification is the gold standard; genetic testing is less useful given >100 mutations.\n\nWhy not — Transferrin saturation panel: Transferrin saturation screens for hemochromatosis, not Wilson.  Antimitochondrial antibody titer: AMA diagnoses PBC, not Wilson disease.  Serum genetic mutation panel: With over 100 mutations, genetic testing is usually not helpful in WD.  Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography: ERCP diagnoses PSC, not Wilson disease.", "advanced"]]], [5, "Overview of autoimmune hepatitis, alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency, primary sclerosing cholangitis", [["Primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) is most strongly associated with which condition?", ["Inflammatory bowel disease", "Sjögren syndrome", "Early-onset emphysema", "Restrictive cardiomyopathy", "Parkinsonism in the young"], 0, "About 90% of PSC patients have underlying IBD (though fewer than 10% of IBD patients have PSC). PSC is predominantly in men, attacks macrohepatic ducts, and is diagnosed by ERCP with no serology.\n\nWhy not — Sjögren syndrome: Sjögren is a PBC association, not the hallmark PSC link.  Early-onset emphysema: Early emphysema points to alpha-1 antitrypsin disease, not PSC.  Restrictive cardiomyopathy: Restrictive cardiomyopathy is a hemochromatosis manifestation.  Parkinsonism in the young: Young parkinsonism points to Wilson disease, not PSC.", "basic"]]], [6, "Discuss the spectrum of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease", [["Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease has been renamed to which current term?", ["Metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease", "Metabolic alcoholic steatohepatitis of the liver", "Non-metabolic associated fatty liver disorder", "Macrovesicular dysfunction steatotic liver disease", "Mixed autoimmune steatotic liver derangement"], 0, "NAFLD is now MASLD (metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease), and the aggressive form NASH is now MASH. The new name pays tribute to the disease being one of altered metabolism.\n\nWhy not — Metabolic alcoholic steatohepatitis of the liver: This invents an 'alcoholic' label, which contradicts the non-alcoholic nature of the disease.  Non-metabolic associated fatty liver disorder: The term is metabolic-associated, not 'non-metabolic'; this reverses the meaning.  Macrovesicular dysfunction steatotic liver disease: 'Macrovesicular dysfunction' is not the new nomenclature for NAFLD.  Mixed autoimmune steatotic liver derangement: Autoimmunity is not part of the MASLD definition; this is a fabricated label.", "basic"], ["Within the metabolic fatty-liver spectrum, MASH is best defined as:", ["Steatohepatitis — inflammation from fat", "Simple steatosis without inflammation", "Established cirrhosis with portal hypertension", "Hepatocellular carcinoma arising in fat", "Alcohol-driven fatty change of the liver"], 0, "MASH is the aggressive variant of MASLD — steatohepatitis, literally inflammation from fat, with fibrosis. Simple steatosis (MASL) is the milder ~80% end of the spectrum.\n\nWhy not — Simple steatosis without inflammation: Simple steatosis without inflammation is MASL, the milder form, not MASH.  Established cirrhosis with portal hypertension: Cirrhosis is downstream of MASH, not the definition of it.  Hepatocellular carcinoma arising in fat: HCC is a late complication, not what MASH means.  Alcohol-driven fatty change of the liver: MASH is non-alcoholic by definition; alcohol-driven fatty change is a separate entity.", "basic"], ["Routine ultrasound, CT, and MRI in a fatty-liver patient are limited because they:", ["Detect fat but not inflammation or fibrosis", "Detect fibrosis but not steatosis", "Require sedation in most adults", "Cannot image the liver parenchyma at all", "Are only valid once cirrhosis is present"], 0, "Routine ultrasound, CT, and MRI see only fat; they do not identify the inflammation or fibrosis that defines MASH. The dangerous fibrotic subset is found with non-invasive tests — biomarkers plus elastography.\n\nWhy not — Detect fibrosis but not steatosis: It is the reverse — they see steatosis (fat), not fibrosis.  Require sedation in most adults: These imaging modalities do not require sedation in most adults.  Cannot image the liver parenchyma at all: They image the parenchyma fine; the limitation is what they cannot characterize.  Are only valid once cirrhosis is present: They suggest fatty liver well before cirrhosis; validity is not cirrhosis-dependent.", "advanced"], ["Resmetirom, FDA-approved in March 2024, is indicated for MASH patients who have:", ["F2-F3 fibrosis on non-invasive testing", "F4 cirrhosis with decompensation", "Simple steatosis without any fibrosis", "Acute alcoholic hepatitis with jaundice", "Normal liver enzymes and no risk factors"], 0, "Resmetirom is the first-in-class drug indicated for MASH with F2-F3 fibrosis identified on non-invasive testing (fibrosis is graded 0-4); it has been shown to reverse fibrosis and reduce liver fat content.\n\nWhy not — F4 cirrhosis with decompensation: The indication is F2-F3, not decompensated F4 cirrhosis.  Simple steatosis without any fibrosis: Simple steatosis without fibrosis is not the resmetirom target population.  Acute alcoholic hepatitis with jaundice: Resmetirom treats MASH, not acute alcoholic hepatitis.  Normal liver enzymes and no risk factors: A patient with normal enzymes and no risk factors would not need MASH therapy.", "advanced"], ["In a patient with established MASH, the leading cause of death is:", ["Cardiovascular disease", "Hepatocellular carcinoma", "Variceal hemorrhage", "Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis", "Hepatic encephalopathy"], 0, "Although MASH drives liver-related death through cirrhosis and HCC, cardiovascular disease remains the single leading cause of mortality in MASH patients — the gold-starred point on the treatment slide.\n\nWhy not — Hepatocellular carcinoma: HCC is a real liver-related cause of death but not the leading one in MASH.  Variceal hemorrhage: Variceal hemorrhage is a complication of cirrhosis, not the top mortality cause here.  Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis: SBP is a decompensation event, not the leading cause of death in MASH.  Hepatic encephalopathy: Encephalopathy is a cirrhosis complication, not the leading mortality cause.", "advanced"]]]]], [41, "Laxative & Antidiarrheal Agents (Lec 41)", [[1, "List the categories of laxatives and antidiarrheal agents", [["Psyllium, methylcellulose, wheat dextrin, and polycarbophil all belong to which laxative category?", ["Bulk-forming laxatives", "Stimulant laxatives", "Osmotic laxatives", "Stool softeners", "Antisecretory agents"], 0, "Bulk-forming laxatives are the indigestible hydrophilic colloids (psyllium, methylcellulose, wheat dextrin, synthetic polycarbophil) that absorb water and distend the colon. Parmar anchored each agent to its class on the two category-map slides.\n\nWhy not — Stimulant laxatives: Stimulant laxatives are bisacodyl and the anthraquinones, not the fiber agents.  Osmotic laxatives: Osmotic laxatives are the saline, PEG, and sugar-alcohol agents.  Stool softeners: Stool softeners are docusate and mineral oil, not bulk fibers.  Antisecretory agents: Antisecretory agents are bismuth and octreotide, an antidiarrheal class.", "basic"], ["Which set of agents are all classified as opioid-agonist antimotility antidiarrheals?", ["Diphenoxylate, difenoxin, loperamide, and eluxadoline", "Cholestyramine, colestipol, colesevelam, and bismuth", "Bisacodyl, senna, lactulose, and docusate", "Octreotide, sulfasalazine, glucocorticoids, and probiotics", "Linaclotide, plecanatide, lubiprostone, and crofelemer"], 0, "The opioid-agonist/antimotility class is diphenoxylate (with atropine), difenoxin, loperamide, and eluxadoline — all act on gut opioid receptors. Parmar grouped them under one category box on the antidiarrheal map.\n\nWhy not — Cholestyramine, colestipol, colesevelam, and bismuth: These are bile-salt resins plus an antisecretory agent, not opioid antimotility drugs.  Bisacodyl, senna, lactulose, and docusate: These are stimulant, osmotic, and stool-softener laxatives, not antidiarrheals.  Octreotide, sulfasalazine, glucocorticoids, and probiotics: These are the 41.5 rationale trio plus probiotics, not opioid agonists.  Linaclotide, plecanatide, lubiprostone, and crofelemer: These are secretagogues and a chloride-channel blocker, not opioid antimotility drugs.", "basic"], ["Which laxative category directly stimulates intestinal smooth muscle to accelerate stool movement?", ["Stimulant/irritant laxatives", "Bulk-forming laxatives", "Stool softeners", "Saline osmotic laxatives", "Bile-salt-binding resins"], 0, "Stimulant/irritant laxatives (bisacodyl, anthraquinones) act on the colon to directly stimulate smooth muscle and enteric nerves, increasing peristalsis. The other classes work by adding bulk, softening, or drawing in water.\n\nWhy not — Bulk-forming laxatives: Bulk-forming agents distend the colon by absorbing water, not by direct stimulation.  Stool softeners: Stool softeners lower surface tension; they do not stimulate muscle.  Saline osmotic laxatives: Saline osmotics draw water into the lumen osmotically, not by stimulation.  Bile-salt-binding resins: Bile-salt resins are antidiarrheals that sequester bile acids, not laxatives.", "basic"]]], [2, "Discuss the mechanism of action of the laxative and antidiarrheal agents", [["Linaclotide and plecanatide relieve constipation by acting on which intestinal target?", ["Guanylate cyclase-C, raising cGMP and Cl-/HCO3- secretion", "ClC-2 chloride channels on the apical epithelial membrane", "Mu-opioid receptors in the enteric nervous system", "Osmotic gradients from poorly absorbed magnesium ions", "Direct irritation of the colonic mucosa and enteric nerves"], 0, "Linaclotide (14-aa) and plecanatide (16-aa) are guanylate cyclase-C receptor agonists that raise intracellular cGMP, driving chloride and bicarbonate secretion into the lumen with water following. Parmar called this the '-tide ending = GC-C, increases cyclic GMP' rule.\n\nWhy not — ClC-2 chloride channels on the apical epithelial membrane: The ClC-2 chloride channel is the target of lubiprostone, not the '-tide' agents.  Mu-opioid receptors in the enteric nervous system: Mu-opioid receptors are the antimotility antidiarrheal target, not a laxative one.  Osmotic gradients from poorly absorbed magnesium ions: Magnesium osmotic pull is the saline-laxative mechanism, not GC-C agonism.  Direct irritation of the colonic mucosa and enteric nerves: Direct mucosal irritation is the stimulant-laxative mechanism.", "basic"], ["A cirrhotic patient with confusion and elevated blood ammonia is started on lactulose. Beyond its osmotic laxative effect, lactulose helps because it:", ["Lowers colonic pH and traps ammonia as non-absorbable NH4+", "Binds ammonia covalently in the small intestine for excretion", "Inhibits hepatic urea-cycle production of ammonia directly", "Stimulates renal excretion of ammonia through the kidneys", "Blocks bacterial production of ammonia in the stomach"], 0, "Colonic bacteria degrade lactulose into organic acids that lower colonic pH; the acidic lumen converts NH3 to NH4+, which is trapped and not reabsorbed, lowering blood ammonia. This dual use — chronic constipation plus hepatic encephalopathy — is the high-yield point.\n\nWhy not — Binds ammonia covalently in the small intestine for excretion: Lactulose does not covalently bind ammonia; it traps NH4+ by lowering colonic pH.  Inhibits hepatic urea-cycle production of ammonia directly: It does not act on the hepatic urea cycle.  Stimulates renal excretion of ammonia through the kidneys: Its action is luminal/colonic, not renal.  Blocks bacterial production of ammonia in the stomach: Ammonia trapping happens in the colon, not the stomach.", "advanced"], ["Bulk-forming laxatives such as psyllium produce their effect because the indigestible hydrophilic colloids:", ["Absorb water, distend the colon, and promote peristalsis", "Lower stool surface tension so water mixes into the stool", "Activate enteric nerves to trigger colonic contractions", "Draw water in by creating a high luminal osmotic pressure", "Coat the stool and intestinal mucosa to ease passage"], 0, "Indigestible hydrophilic colloids absorb water in the small and large intestine, forming a bulky emollient gel that distends the colon and promotes peristalsis. This distension-driven mechanism distinguishes them from softeners, osmotics, and stimulants.\n\nWhy not — Lower stool surface tension so water mixes into the stool: Lowering surface tension is the docusate (stool-softener) mechanism.  Activate enteric nerves to trigger colonic contractions: Activating enteric nerves is the stimulant-laxative mechanism.  Draw water in by creating a high luminal osmotic pressure: Creating osmotic pressure is the osmotic-laxative mechanism.  Coat the stool and intestinal mucosa to ease passage: Coating the mucosa is the mineral-oil (lubricant) mechanism.", "basic"], ["Lubiprostone facilitates stool passage through which mechanism of action?", ["Activating apical ClC-2 chloride channels to secrete fluid", "Agonizing guanylate cyclase-C to raise intracellular cGMP", "Sequestering bile acids in the small-intestinal lumen", "Antagonizing delta-opioid receptors in the gut wall", "Inhibiting CFTR and calcium-activated chloride channels"], 0, "Lubiprostone is a PGE1 derivative that selectively activates ClC-2 chloride channels on the apical membrane of intestinal epithelial cells, increasing chloride-rich fluid secretion. It is used in CIC, opioid-induced constipation, and IBS-C in women.\n\nWhy not — Agonizing guanylate cyclase-C to raise intracellular cGMP: Raising cGMP via GC-C is the linaclotide/plecanatide mechanism, not lubiprostone's.  Sequestering bile acids in the small-intestinal lumen: Sequestering bile acids is the resin mechanism, an antidiarrheal action.  Antagonizing delta-opioid receptors in the gut wall: Delta-opioid antagonism is part of eluxadoline's mechanism.  Inhibiting CFTR and calcium-activated chloride channels: Inhibiting CFTR/CaCC is crofelemer's antidiarrheal mechanism.", "basic"]]], [3, "Discuss the therapeutic and adverse effects of the laxative and antidiarrheal agents", [["A patient with years of senna abuse is found on colonoscopy to have benign brownish-black pigmentation of the colonic mucosa. This finding is:", ["Melanosis coli", "Cathartic colon", "Ischemic colitis", "Pseudomembranous colitis", "Bismuth-induced discoloration"], 0, "Melanosis coli is the benign brownish-black pigmentation of the colonic mucosa (lipofuscin pigment) classically seen with chronic anthraquinone/senna use. It is not life-threatening but flags stimulant-laxative abuse.\n\nWhy not — Cathartic colon: Cathartic colon is the loss of normal motility from abuse, not a mucosal pigment.  Ischemic colitis: Ischemic colitis is a vascular injury, not a pigment from laxative use.  Pseudomembranous colitis: Pseudomembranous colitis is C. difficile injury with pseudomembranes, not pigment.  Bismuth-induced discoloration: Bismuth darkens the tongue and stool, not the colonic mucosa on colonoscopy.", "advanced"], ["Octreotide, used for secretory diarrhea, characteristically causes which adverse effect with chronic use?", ["Gallstone formation from biliary stasis", "Melanosis coli of the colonic mucosa", "Torsades de pointes and QT prolongation", "Aspiration pneumonia in bedridden patients", "Metabolic alkalosis from chronic dosing"], 0, "Octreotide slows gallbladder emptying and impairs fat absorption, causing biliary stasis and cholelithiasis (gallstones). This is its signature adverse effect, distinct from the AEs of other antidiarrheals.\n\nWhy not — Melanosis coli of the colonic mucosa: Melanosis coli is from anthraquinone/senna abuse, not octreotide.  Torsades de pointes and QT prolongation: Torsades is the loperamide boxed-warning effect, not octreotide's.  Aspiration pneumonia in bedridden patients: Aspiration pneumonia is the mineral-oil risk in debilitated patients.  Metabolic alkalosis from chronic dosing: Metabolic alkalosis is associated with bisacodyl overuse, not octreotide.", "basic"], ["Two guanylate cyclase-C agonists are compared. Which statement about their diarrhea risk is correct?", ["Linaclotide causes about 20% diarrhea versus plecanatide's 5%", "Plecanatide causes about 20% diarrhea versus linaclotide's 5%", "Both agents cause an identical 20% rate of diarrhea", "Neither agent causes any diarrhea at therapeutic doses", "Diarrhea arises only when the two are combined together"], 0, "Linaclotide (Linzess) is associated with ~20% diarrhea versus ~5% for plecanatide (Trulance), so plecanatide is often preferred. Parmar repeated this Linzess-20 / Trulance-5 contrast as a likely discriminator.\n\nWhy not — Plecanatide causes about 20% diarrhea versus linaclotide's 5%: The direction is reversed — linaclotide, not plecanatide, has the higher rate.  Both agents cause an identical 20% rate of diarrhea: The rates differ markedly (~20% vs ~5%), they are not identical.  Neither agent causes any diarrhea at therapeutic doses: Diarrhea is in fact the most common, dose-related adverse effect of both.  Diarrhea arises only when the two are combined together: Each causes diarrhea on its own; they are not used in combination.", "basic"], ["Loperamide is available over the counter largely because, unlike prescription opioid antidiarrheals, it:", ["Does not cross the blood-brain barrier, low abuse", "Has strong central analgesic effects at therapeutic doses", "Carries no risk of constipation even in overdose", "Is safe in infectious diarrhea and C. difficile colitis", "Lacks any effect on the intestinal opioid receptors"], 0, "Loperamide acts on intestinal mu receptors but does not cross the blood-brain barrier at therapeutic doses, so it has no analgesic effect and low addictive potential — the basis for its OTC status. It still carries a boxed warning for torsades/QT in overdose.\n\nWhy not — Has strong central analgesic effects at therapeutic doses: Loperamide has no significant central analgesic effect — that is precisely why it is OTC.  Carries no risk of constipation even in overdose: Overdose can cause severe constipation and paralytic ileus.  Is safe in infectious diarrhea and C. difficile colitis: It is NOT safe in infectious/dysenteric diarrhea — that is a contraindication.  Lacks any effect on the intestinal opioid receptors: It does act on intestinal mu-opioid receptors to slow peristalsis.", "basic"], ["An HIV/AIDS patient on antiretroviral therapy has chronic non-infectious diarrhea. Crofelemer is chosen because it controls diarrhea while:", ["Inhibiting CFTR and CaCC channels, sparing nutrient absorption", "Binding the offending antiretroviral drugs in the gut lumen", "Slowing intestinal transit through mu-opioid receptor agonism", "Sequestering the excess bile acids spilling into the colon", "Replacing the gut flora killed by the antiretroviral regimen"], 0, "Crofelemer inhibits the apical CFTR and calcium-activated chloride channels, reducing chloride and fluid secretion. It is FDA-approved for non-infectious diarrhea in HIV/AIDS patients on ART, and its advantage is that it does not interfere with nutrient absorption or cause constipation.\n\nWhy not — Binding the offending antiretroviral drugs in the gut lumen: Crofelemer does not bind the antiretroviral drugs; it blocks chloride channels.  Slowing intestinal transit through mu-opioid receptor agonism: Mu-opioid agonism is the antimotility-class mechanism, not crofelemer's.  Sequestering the excess bile acids spilling into the colon: Bile-acid sequestration is the resin mechanism, not crofelemer's.  Replacing the gut flora killed by the antiretroviral regimen: Restoring flora is the probiotic role, not crofelemer's.", "advanced"]]], [4, "Discuss the potential contraindications and drug interactions of the laxative and antidiarrheal agents", [["Opioid-antimotility antidiarrheals such as loperamide are contraindicated in infectious diarrhea (e.g., C. difficile) chiefly because slowing transit risks:", ["Toxic megacolon and sepsis", "Sphincter-of-Oddi spasm", "Aspiration pneumonia", "Reye syndrome", "Metabolic alkalosis"], 0, "In infectious or inflammatory diarrhea, slowing motility lets pathogens and toxins dwell in the gut, risking ileus, toxic megacolon, and sepsis. That is why antimotility agents are withheld until invasive infection is excluded.\n\nWhy not — Sphincter-of-Oddi spasm: Sphincter-of-Oddi spasm is the eluxadoline-specific risk, not the general antimotility risk.  Aspiration pneumonia: Aspiration pneumonia is the mineral-oil risk, not the antimotility-in-infection risk.  Reye syndrome: Reye syndrome is the bismuth/salicylate pediatric risk.  Metabolic alkalosis: Metabolic alkalosis is the bisacodyl-overuse effect.", "basic"], ["Eluxadoline should be avoided in a patient who has which of the following?", ["Sphincter-of-Oddi dysfunction or prior pancreatitis", "Mild seasonal allergic rhinitis", "Well-controlled essential hypertension", "A remote history of appendectomy", "Occasional caffeine consumption"], 0, "Eluxadoline is contraindicated in sphincter-of-Oddi dysfunction, pancreatitis, biliary obstruction, and in patients drinking more than 3 alcoholic drinks per day, because of its risk of sphincter-of-Oddi spasm and pancreatitis.\n\nWhy not — Mild seasonal allergic rhinitis: Allergic rhinitis is unrelated to eluxadoline's biliary/pancreatic risks.  Well-controlled essential hypertension: Controlled hypertension is not a listed contraindication.  A remote history of appendectomy: A prior appendectomy does not contraindicate eluxadoline.  Occasional caffeine consumption: Occasional caffeine is irrelevant; the concern is >3 alcoholic drinks/day.", "advanced"], ["Bismuth subsalicylate should be avoided in children and adolescents recovering from a viral illness because of the risk of:", ["Reye syndrome", "Cathartic colon", "Cholelithiasis", "Torsades de pointes", "Sphincter-of-Oddi spasm"], 0, "Bismuth subsalicylate contains a salicylate moiety, so like aspirin it is avoided in children/adolescents with viral infections (influenza, chickenpox) because of Reye syndrome risk. Parmar flagged this slide as carried over and still exam-relevant.\n\nWhy not — Cathartic colon: Cathartic colon is from stimulant-laxative abuse, not bismuth.  Cholelithiasis: Cholelithiasis is the octreotide adverse effect.  Torsades de pointes: Torsades is the loperamide overdose risk.  Sphincter-of-Oddi spasm: Sphincter-of-Oddi spasm is the eluxadoline risk.", "advanced"], ["Bulk-forming laxatives should be taken with at least 8 oz of water and dosed about 2 hours apart from other medications. The 2-hour spacing rule exists to:", ["Prevent the fiber from impairing absorption of the other drugs", "Avoid neutralizing the gastric acid needed for the fiber", "Reduce the risk of torsades from drug interactions", "Stop the fiber from being degraded by colonic bacteria", "Keep the other drugs from inactivating the fiber gel"], 0, "The fiber gel can bind and impair the absorption of co-administered medications, so bulk-forming laxatives are spaced about 2 hours apart from other drugs. The ≥8 oz water requirement separately prevents esophageal obstruction and dehydration.\n\nWhy not — Avoid neutralizing the gastric acid needed for the fiber: Fiber action does not depend on gastric acid; the issue is binding other drugs.  Reduce the risk of torsades from drug interactions: The spacing is about absorption, not cardiac/torsades interactions.  Stop the fiber from being degraded by colonic bacteria: Colonic bacterial degradation is not the reason for the spacing rule.  Keep the other drugs from inactivating the fiber gel: The concern is the fiber binding the drugs, not the drugs inactivating the fiber.", "basic"]]], [5, "Discuss the rationale for the use of sulfasalazine, glucocorticoids, and octreotide in treating diarrhea", [["Sulfasalazine relieves diarrhea in ulcerative colitis because, after bacterial cleavage in the colon, it releases the active moiety:", ["The 5-aminosalicylic acid anti-inflammatory moiety", "The absorbed sulfapyridine carrier fragment", "An inhibitory somatostatin analog peptide", "A locally active glucocorticoid metabolite", "An antisecretory bismuth subsalicylate complex"], 0, "Colonic bacteria cleave sulfasalazine into sulfapyridine and 5-ASA (mesalamine); the 5-ASA is the active anti-inflammatory moiety that reduces colonic inflammation in ulcerative colitis. It controls symptoms (including diarrhea) but does not cure the disease.\n\nWhy not — The absorbed sulfapyridine carrier fragment: Sulfapyridine is the absorbed carrier fragment, not the active anti-inflammatory moiety.  An inhibitory somatostatin analog peptide: Somatostatin/octreotide is a separate agent in the rationale trio.  A locally active glucocorticoid metabolite: Glucocorticoids are a distinct agent; sulfasalazine does not release a steroid.  An antisecretory bismuth subsalicylate complex: Bismuth subsalicylate is an unrelated antisecretory antidiarrheal.", "basic"], ["Octreotide is the rationale agent for severe secretory diarrhea from a VIPoma or carcinoid because, as a somatostatin analog, it:", ["Inhibits secretion of serotonin, gastrin, VIP, and motilin", "Binds bile acids spilling into the colon", "Releases 5-ASA after colonic bacterial cleavage", "Directly blocks mu-opioid receptors in the gut", "Activates ClC-2 chloride channels in the epithelium"], 0, "Octreotide, a synthetic somatostatin analog, inhibits the secretion of GI hormones and peptides (serotonin, gastrin, VIP, motilin), giving antisecretory and proabsorptive effects. That is why it controls neuroendocrine-tumor secretory diarrhea (carcinoid, VIPoma) and refractory chemotherapy-induced diarrhea.\n\nWhy not — Binds bile acids spilling into the colon: Binding bile acids is the resin mechanism, not octreotide's.  Releases 5-ASA after colonic bacterial cleavage: Releasing 5-ASA is the sulfasalazine mechanism.  Directly blocks mu-opioid receptors in the gut: Octreotide does not block mu-opioid receptors; it inhibits hormone secretion.  Activates ClC-2 chloride channels in the epithelium: Activating ClC-2 is lubiprostone's mechanism, a laxative.", "basic"], ["Glucocorticoids are used to reduce diarrhea in moderate-to-severe inflammatory bowel disease flares because they:", ["Exert broad anti-inflammatory effects and reduce gut cytokines", "Trap colonic ammonia as the non-absorbable charged NH4+ form", "Sequester the luminal bile acids spilling past the ileum", "Slow intestinal transit by agonizing the gut mu receptors", "Draw water into the bowel by raising osmotic pressure"], 0, "Glucocorticoids reduce cytokines and GI inflammation, controlling symptoms (including diarrhea and bleeding) and inducing remission in moderate-to-severe ulcerative colitis and Crohn's flares. They treat the inflammatory driver rather than the stool directly.\n\nWhy not — Trap colonic ammonia as the non-absorbable charged NH4+ form: Ammonia trapping is the lactulose mechanism, unrelated to steroids.  Sequester the luminal bile acids spilling past the ileum: Bile-acid sequestration is the resin mechanism.  Slow intestinal transit by agonizing the gut mu receptors: Mu-receptor agonism is the opioid-antimotility mechanism.  Draw water into the bowel by raising osmotic pressure: Osmotic water shift is the osmotic-laxative mechanism.", "basic"], ["A patient with metastatic carcinoid has flushing and severe secretory diarrhea unresponsive to loperamide. The most appropriate agent and its rationale are:", ["Octreotide, because it inhibits the tumor's secretagogue hormones", "Sulfasalazine, because its 5-ASA moiety calms colonic inflammation", "Cholestyramine, because the diarrhea reflects bile-acid malabsorption", "A glucocorticoid, because the diarrhea is an inflammatory flare", "Bisacodyl, because the colon needs direct stimulation to clear"], 0, "Carcinoid secretory diarrhea is driven by tumor-secreted hormones (serotonin and others); octreotide, a somatostatin analog, inhibits that hormone secretion and is the agent for neuroendocrine-tumor secretory diarrhea and refractory CID not responding to loperamide.\n\nWhy not — Sulfasalazine, because its 5-ASA moiety calms colonic inflammation: Sulfasalazine treats ulcerative colitis inflammation, not hormone-driven carcinoid diarrhea.  Cholestyramine, because the diarrhea reflects bile-acid malabsorption: This is hormone-secretory, not bile-acid-malabsorption, diarrhea.  A glucocorticoid, because the diarrhea is an inflammatory flare: Carcinoid is a neuroendocrine tumor, not an inflammatory bowel flare.  Bisacodyl, because the colon needs direct stimulation to clear: Bisacodyl is a laxative and would worsen, not treat, the diarrhea.", "advanced"]]]]], [42, "Congenital/Hereditary & Circulatory Liver (Lec 42)", [[1, "Describe the major pathological features of the hereditary hyperbilirubinemias", [["Among the five hereditary hyperbilirubinemias, which two produce a conjugated (rather than unconjugated) hyperbilirubinemia?", ["Dubin-Johnson and Rotor syndromes", "Crigler-Najjar type I and Gilbert", "Crigler-Najjar type I and type II", "Gilbert and Crigler-Najjar type II", "Crigler-Najjar type II and Rotor"], 0, "On the board-flagged table, the first three (Crigler-Najjar I, Crigler-Najjar II, Gilbert) are UNCONJUGATED — UGT1A1 conjugating defects — while the last two, Dubin-Johnson and Rotor, are CONJUGATED, reflecting an excretion/transport problem rather than a conjugation problem.\n\nWhy not — Crigler-Najjar type I and Gilbert: Both of these are unconjugated UGT1A1 defects, not conjugated disorders.  Crigler-Najjar type I and type II: Both Crigler-Najjar types are unconjugated conjugation defects, not conjugated.  Gilbert and Crigler-Najjar type II: Gilbert and Crigler-Najjar II are both unconjugated, not conjugated, disorders.  Crigler-Najjar type II and Rotor: Crigler-Najjar II is unconjugated; only the Rotor half of this pair is conjugated.", "basic"], ["The enzyme defective in Crigler-Najjar and Gilbert syndromes, and its gene locus, are respectively:", ["UGT1A1 glucuronosyltransferase, on chromosome 2q37", "ABCC2 canalicular transporter, on chromosome 10q24", "SLCO1B1 uptake transporter, on chromosome 12p12", "ALDH mitochondrial dehydrogenase, on chromosome 12q24", "ATP7B copper transporter, on chromosome 13q14"], 0, "Crigler-Najjar (both types) and Gilbert all stem from reduced or absent UGT1A1 (uridine diphosphate glucuronosyltransferase) activity, the enzyme that conjugates bilirubin; the gene maps to chromosome 2q37, which Machini flagged as a possible board detail.\n\nWhy not — ABCC2 canalicular transporter, on chromosome 10q24: ABCC2/MRP2 is the Dubin-Johnson canalicular-export defect, not the UGT1A1 conjugation defect.  SLCO1B1 uptake transporter, on chromosome 12p12: SLCO1B1 is the Rotor uptake defect, not the Crigler-Najjar/Gilbert enzyme.  ALDH mitochondrial dehydrogenase, on chromosome 12q24: ALDH is the alcohol-metabolism enzyme, unrelated to bilirubin conjugation.  ATP7B copper transporter, on chromosome 13q14: ATP7B is the Wilson-disease copper transporter, not the bilirubin enzyme.", "basic"], ["Crigler-Najjar type I differs from type II in that type I shows:", ["Absent UGT1A1 enzyme and kernicterus risk", "Partial UGT1A1 activity and benign course", "Conjugated rather than unconjugated bilirubin", "A defective canalicular export transporter", "A reliable response to phenobarbital therapy"], 0, "Crigler-Najjar type I has a complete absence of UGT1A1, so unconjugated bilirubin climbs above 20 mg/dL with kernicterus and a fatal neonatal course; type II retains partial enzyme activity, keeps bilirubin under 20, and rarely causes kernicterus.\n\nWhy not — Partial UGT1A1 activity and benign course: Partial activity and a benign course describe type II, not type I.  Conjugated rather than unconjugated bilirubin: Both Crigler-Najjar types are unconjugated; the bilirubin is not conjugated.  A defective canalicular export transporter: An export-transporter defect describes Dubin-Johnson, not Crigler-Najjar I.  A reliable response to phenobarbital therapy: Phenobarbital works in type II, not in the enzyme-absent type I.", "basic"], ["Phenobarbital lowers serum bilirubin in Crigler-Najjar type II and Gilbert but NOT in type I because phenobarbital:", ["Induces residual UGT1A1 enzyme type I lacks", "Blocks intestinal reabsorption of conjugated bilirubin", "Competes with bilirubin for albumin binding sites", "Accelerates biliary excretion through the MRP2 pump", "Replaces the missing canalicular transport protein"], 0, "Phenobarbital works by inducing UGT1A1 expression, so it can boost the partial enzyme present in type II and Gilbert; type I has no enzyme to induce, which is exactly why the phenobarbital response distinguishes the two Crigler-Najjar types.\n\nWhy not — Blocks intestinal reabsorption of conjugated bilirubin: Phenobarbital induces the conjugating enzyme; it does not block intestinal reabsorption.  Competes with bilirubin for albumin binding sites: Albumin-binding competition is not the mechanism of phenobarbital's effect here.  Accelerates biliary excretion through the MRP2 pump: MRP2-driven excretion is the Dubin-Johnson defect, not phenobarbital's action.  Replaces the missing canalicular transport protein: Phenobarbital induces an existing enzyme; it does not supply a missing transporter.", "basic"], ["Gilbert syndrome, the most common hereditary hyperbilirubinemia, arises from a UGT1A1 abnormality best described as:", ["Two extra bases inserted in the promoter region", "Complete deletion of both UGT1A1 alleles", "A point mutation creating an early stop codon", "A defect in the ABCC2 export transporter gene", "Loss of the SLCO1B1 hepatic uptake transporter"], 0, "Gilbert syndrome comes from two extra bases inserted in the UGT1A1 promoter, which lowers transcription and gives mildly reduced enzyme activity and intermittent unconjugated jaundice — a benign disorder distinct from the coding-region damage seen in Crigler-Najjar.\n\nWhy not — Complete deletion of both UGT1A1 alleles: Complete loss of enzyme would produce Crigler-Najjar type I, not benign Gilbert.  A point mutation creating an early stop codon: A stop-codon change describes the more severe Crigler-Najjar end, not Gilbert.  A defect in the ABCC2 export transporter gene: ABCC2 is the Dubin-Johnson export defect, not the Gilbert promoter change.  Loss of the SLCO1B1 hepatic uptake transporter: SLCO1B1 loss is the Rotor uptake defect, not the Gilbert mechanism.", "basic"], ["A liver biopsy showing brown-black lipofuscin pigment in hepatocytes, with otherwise normal architecture, points to which diagnosis?", ["Gilbert syndrome", "Dubin-Johnson syndrome", "Rotor syndrome", "Crigler-Najjar type I", "Chronic passive congestion"], 0, "Increased lipofuscin (brown-black) pigment in hepatocytes is the characteristic, board-flagged histologic finding of Gilbert syndrome; the surrounding liver looks normal, fitting its benign nature. This is the slide Machini framed as a likely 'which is the diagnosis?' stem.\n\nWhy not — Dubin-Johnson syndrome: Dubin-Johnson shows coarse black granules (epinephrine-metabolite pigment), not lipofuscin.  Rotor syndrome: Rotor has NO abnormal pigment in the liver at all.  Crigler-Najjar type I: Crigler-Najjar I has no diagnostic hepatocyte pigment; it is an enzyme-absence disorder.  Chronic passive congestion: Passive congestion shows centrilobular congestion, not hepatocyte lipofuscin.", "advanced"], ["A patient with chronic conjugated hyperbilirubinemia has a grossly black liver and a urinary coproporphyrin III-to-I ratio of roughly 1:3. The diagnosis and defective protein are:", ["Dubin-Johnson syndrome from a defective MRP2 transporter", "Rotor syndrome from a defective SLCO1B1 transporter", "Gilbert syndrome from a defective UGT1A1 enzyme", "Crigler-Najjar from an absent UGT1A1 enzyme", "Budd-Chiari syndrome from a hepatic-vein thrombus"], 0, "A black liver plus an INVERTED coproporphyrin ratio (normal 3:1 flips to 1:3) is diagnostic of Dubin-Johnson syndrome, which stems from a defective ABCC2/MRP2 canalicular export pump that blocks excretion of conjugated bilirubin. Machini told the class to underline this as a board point.\n\nWhy not — Rotor syndrome from a defective SLCO1B1 transporter: Rotor has NO black liver and a ~5x total coproporphyrin rise, not an inverted ratio.  Gilbert syndrome from a defective UGT1A1 enzyme: Gilbert is unconjugated with lipofuscin, not a black liver with inverted coproporphyrin.  Crigler-Najjar from an absent UGT1A1 enzyme: Crigler-Najjar is unconjugated with no black pigment or coproporphyrin inversion.  Budd-Chiari syndrome from a hepatic-vein thrombus: Budd-Chiari is a vascular outflow disorder, not a conjugated-pigment syndrome.", "advanced"], ["Rotor syndrome is best distinguished from Dubin-Johnson syndrome by the fact that Rotor:", ["Lacks black pigment in the liver", "Produces unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia", "Carries a defective UGT1A1 enzyme", "Causes fatal neonatal kernicterus", "Inverts the coproporphyrin ratio to 1:3"], 0, "Both Rotor and Dubin-Johnson are benign conjugated hyperbilirubinemias, but Rotor has NO black hepatic pigment (its defect is in SLCO1B1/1B3 uptake/storage), whereas Dubin-Johnson's MRP2 defect gives the classic black liver — the cleanest discriminator between the two.\n\nWhy not — Produces unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia: Both Rotor and Dubin-Johnson are conjugated, not unconjugated, disorders.  Carries a defective UGT1A1 enzyme: UGT1A1 is the Crigler-Najjar/Gilbert enzyme, not the Rotor transporter.  Causes fatal neonatal kernicterus: Fatal kernicterus is Crigler-Najjar type I, not benign Rotor syndrome.  Inverts the coproporphyrin ratio to 1:3: The inverted 1:3 coproporphyrin ratio belongs to Dubin-Johnson, not Rotor.", "basic"], ["A patient's labs show a total bilirubin of 1.0 mg/dL with no scleral yellowing. Using the lecture's thresholds, this value is:", ["Within normal range, below the icterus threshold", "Elevated, defining a mild hyperbilirubinemia state", "Diagnostic of clinically visible scleral icterus", "Below the lower limit, indicating a deficiency", "At the exact level where jaundice first appears"], 0, "Normal total bilirubin runs 0.3-1.2 mg/dL, so 1.0 is normal; hyperbilirubinemia begins above 1.2, and clinically visible jaundice/icterus appears only above about 2.5 mg/dL, which is why this patient has no scleral yellowing.\n\nWhy not — Elevated, defining a mild hyperbilirubinemia state: Elevation requires a value above 1.2 mg/dL; 1.0 is still normal.  Diagnostic of clinically visible scleral icterus: Visible icterus needs roughly 2.5 mg/dL, far above this value.  Below the lower limit, indicating a deficiency: 1.0 sits comfortably within the 0.3-1.2 normal band, not below it.  At the exact level where jaundice first appears: Jaundice first appears near 2.5 mg/dL, not at 1.0.", "advanced"]]], [2, "Describe the pathology of circulatory disorders of the liver", [["The mottled 'nutmeg liver' of chronic passive congestion is most commonly produced by:", ["Right-sided heart failure", "Acute hepatic artery occlusion", "Portal vein branch thrombosis", "Acetaminophen-induced necrosis", "Schistosomal portal obstruction"], 0, "Chronic passive congestion is venous-outflow stasis; right-sided heart failure is its most common cause, backing blood into the centrilobular sinusoids to create the dilated-congested zone-3 'nutmeg' pattern against paler periportal tissue.\n\nWhy not — Acute hepatic artery occlusion: Hepatic artery occlusion causes ischemic injury, not the venous nutmeg pattern.  Portal vein branch thrombosis: Portal vein thrombosis blocks inflow and gives no necrosis, not nutmeg congestion.  Acetaminophen-induced necrosis: Acetaminophen causes zone-3 ischemic-type necrosis, not passive congestion.  Schistosomal portal obstruction: Schistosomiasis blocks small portal branches, not the venous outflow.", "basic"], ["In ischemic hepatitis ('shock liver'), the hepatocytes that undergo necrosis first are those located in:", ["The centrilobular zone, farthest from arterial supply", "The periportal zone, nearest the incoming vessels", "The midzonal region, between the two extremes", "The portal tracts, around the bile ductules", "The subcapsular rim, beneath Glisson capsule"], 0, "Zone 3 (centrilobular) hepatocytes sit farthest from the oxygenated periportal inflow, so they are most vulnerable to ischemia; shock liver therefore produces centrilobular (zone-3) ischemic necrosis as its cardinal feature.\n\nWhy not — The periportal zone, nearest the incoming vessels: Periportal zone 1 is best oxygenated and most resistant to ischemia.  The midzonal region, between the two extremes: The midzonal region is intermediate; zone 3 fails first.  The portal tracts, around the bile ductules: Portal tracts are not the parenchymal zone that necroses in shock liver.  The subcapsular rim, beneath Glisson capsule: The subcapsular rim is not the zone defined by ischemic vulnerability.", "basic"], ["The liver infarcts only rarely, even after vascular insults, primarily because it:", ["Receives a dual blood supply from two sources", "Regenerates lost hepatocytes within several hours", "Stores enough oxygen to tolerate long ischemia", "Has the highest collateral arterial flow of any organ", "Drains its venous blood directly into the vena cava"], 0, "The liver's dual blood supply — the portal vein plus the hepatic artery — means loss of one channel is usually buffered by the other, so true infarction is uncommon; Machini stressed 'remember that' as the reason zone-3 necrosis, not frank infarction, is the rule.\n\nWhy not — Regenerates lost hepatocytes within several hours: Regeneration restores tissue afterward but does not prevent the acute infarct.  Stores enough oxygen to tolerate long ischemia: The liver does not store enough oxygen to ride out prolonged ischemia.  Has the highest collateral arterial flow of any organ: It is the two-source supply, not unusually rich arterial collaterals, that protects it.  Drains its venous blood directly into the vena cava: Venous drainage to the cava does not explain resistance to infarction.", "basic"], ["Portal-to-portal bridging necrosis, in which fibrous bridges link adjacent portal tracts, is most characteristically a feature of:", ["Chronic hepatitis", "Acute viral hepatitis", "Venous outflow obstruction", "Acute alcoholic steatosis", "Physiologic neonatal jaundice"], 0, "Of the three bridging-necrosis patterns Machini delivered as board stems, portal-to-portal bridging (widened, linked portal areas) is the hallmark of chronic hepatitis; central-central reflects outflow obstruction/hypoperfusion, and central-portal reflects acute viral hepatitis.\n\nWhy not — Acute viral hepatitis: Acute viral hepatitis classically gives central-to-portal bridging, not portal-portal.  Venous outflow obstruction: Outflow obstruction gives central-to-central bridging, not portal-portal.  Acute alcoholic steatosis: Alcoholic steatosis is fat accumulation, not a bridging-necrosis pattern.  Physiologic neonatal jaundice: Neonatal jaundice is a bilirubin issue, not a bridging-necrosis pattern.", "basic"], ["A Zahn infarct (infarct of Zahn) of the liver is best characterized as:", ["Sinusoidal congestion with atrophy but no necrosis", "Centrilobular coagulative necrosis with hemorrhage", "Bridging fibrosis between adjacent central veins", "Diffuse fatty change of periportal hepatocytes", "Black canalicular pigment within hepatocytes"], 0, "A Zahn infarct is a pseudo-infarction from occlusion of a portal vein branch: it produces collateral sinusoidal congestion and hepatocyte atrophy, but — the key point — NO actual necrosis, because the hepatic artery keeps the area perfused.\n\nWhy not — Centrilobular coagulative necrosis with hemorrhage: True coagulative necrosis is exactly what a Zahn pseudo-infarct lacks.  Bridging fibrosis between adjacent central veins: Bridging fibrosis is a chronic-injury pattern, not the Zahn lesion.  Diffuse fatty change of periportal hepatocytes: Periportal fatty change is not what defines a Zahn infarct.  Black canalicular pigment within hepatocytes: Black canalicular pigment describes Dubin-Johnson, not a Zahn infarct.", "advanced"], ["Robbins groups compromised hepatic blood flow into inflow, intrahepatic, and outflow patterns. Impaired hepatic blood INFLOW classically presents with:", ["Esophageal varices and splenomegaly", "Ascites with bridging hepatic fibrosis", "Hepatomegaly, jaundice, and dark liver", "Centrilobular zone-3 ischemic necrosis", "Black pigment within canalicular hepatocytes"], 0, "On the Robbins forms table, impaired inflow (e.g., portal vein obstruction) produces pre-sinusoidal portal hypertension with esophageal varices and splenomegaly; intrahepatic disease gives cirrhosis/ascites, and outflow obstruction (Budd-Chiari) gives hepatomegaly, ascites, and jaundice.\n\nWhy not — Ascites with bridging hepatic fibrosis: Ascites with hepatic fibrosis fits the intrahepatic pattern, not inflow.  Hepatomegaly, jaundice, and dark liver: Hepatomegaly with a dark liver and jaundice describes outflow (Budd-Chiari).  Centrilobular zone-3 ischemic necrosis: Zone-3 ischemic necrosis is a shock/ischemia finding, not inflow obstruction.  Black pigment within canalicular hepatocytes: Black canalicular pigment is Dubin-Johnson, not an inflow finding.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Discuss the etiological factors and major pathological features of Budd-Chiari syndrome", [["Budd-Chiari syndrome is defined by obstruction at which point in the hepatic circulation?", ["The hepatic vein outflow tract", "The portal vein inflow tract", "The hepatic artery branches", "The intrahepatic bile ductules", "The common bile duct lumen"], 0, "Budd-Chiari syndrome is hepatic-vein OUTFLOW obstruction (thrombosis of the major hepatic veins); blocking more than two hepatic veins backs blood up into the liver, producing hepatomegaly, ascites, and liver dysfunction.\n\nWhy not — The portal vein inflow tract: Portal vein inflow obstruction is portal vein thrombosis, not Budd-Chiari.  The hepatic artery branches: Hepatic artery disease is the shock-liver/ischemia axis, not Budd-Chiari.  The intrahepatic bile ductules: Intrahepatic bile-duct injury is a cholestatic, not vascular, process.  The common bile duct lumen: Common bile duct obstruction is biliary, not the Budd-Chiari venous lesion.", "basic"], ["When Budd-Chiari involves only the small intrahepatic venous branches rather than the large hepatic veins, the resulting entity is called:", ["Sinusoidal obstruction syndrome", "Cavernous portal transformation", "Primary sclerosing cholangitis", "Nodular regenerative hyperplasia", "Chronic passive hepatic congestion"], 0, "When the obstruction sits at the small intrahepatic venules rather than the major hepatic veins, the process is termed sinusoidal obstruction syndrome (historically veno-occlusive disease), a variant on the same outflow-blockage theme.\n\nWhy not — Cavernous portal transformation: Cavernous transformation (portal cavernoma) is a portal-vein-thrombosis sequel, not this.  Primary sclerosing cholangitis: Sclerosing cholangitis is a bile-duct disease, not a venous-outflow variant.  Nodular regenerative hyperplasia: Nodular regenerative hyperplasia can follow but is not the named small-branch entity.  Chronic passive hepatic congestion: Passive congestion is the heart-failure pattern, not small-branch outflow obstruction.", "basic"], ["Trace the Budd-Chiari pathophysiologic cascade. After hepatic-vein thrombosis obstructs outflow and blood backs up into the liver, the next consequence is:", ["Portal hypertension with centrilobular necrosis", "Pre-sinusoidal varices without any necrosis", "Black canalicular pigment accumulation", "Periportal zone-1 coagulative infarction", "Inverted urinary coproporphyrin excretion"], 0, "The Budd-Chiari arrow-chain runs thrombosis → outflow obstruction → blood back-up → portal hypertension → centrilobular (zone-3) necrosis and fatty change → ascites and ultimately cirrhosis, so portal hypertension with centrilobular necrosis is the next link after the back-up.\n\nWhy not — Pre-sinusoidal varices without any necrosis: Pre-sinusoidal portal hypertension WITHOUT necrosis describes portal vein thrombosis, not Budd-Chiari.  Black canalicular pigment accumulation: Black canalicular pigment is Dubin-Johnson, not a Budd-Chiari step.  Periportal zone-1 coagulative infarction: Budd-Chiari damages zone 3 centrilobular tissue, not periportal zone 1.  Inverted urinary coproporphyrin excretion: Coproporphyrin inversion is a Dubin-Johnson finding, unrelated to this cascade.", "basic"]]], [4, "Discuss the pathophysiology, etiology, morphology, and clinical aspects of portal vein obstruction and thrombosis", [["The single most important pathological point distinguishing portal vein thrombosis from the other circulatory liver disorders is that PVT produces:", ["Inflammation and atrophy but no necrosis", "Centrilobular zone-3 coagulative necrosis", "Diffuse macrovesicular hepatic steatosis", "A grossly black, congested liver surface", "Bridging fibrosis across the central veins"], 0, "Machini's flagged 'only point here you should know': portal vein thrombosis causes NO necrosis — only inflammation, hepatocellular atrophy, and sinusoidal congestion — because the hepatic artery keeps the tissue perfused. That absence of necrosis is what sets PVT apart from the outflow/ischemic disorders.\n\nWhy not — Centrilobular zone-3 coagulative necrosis: Zone-3 necrosis is the ischemia/shock-liver and outflow finding, not PVT.  Diffuse macrovesicular hepatic steatosis: Macrovesicular steatosis is a fatty-liver pattern, not the PVT lesion.  A grossly black, congested liver surface: A black congested liver is the Budd-Chiari gross picture, not PVT.  Bridging fibrosis across the central veins: Central-vein bridging fibrosis is an outflow pattern, not PVT.", "basic"], ["Worldwide, the most common cause of obstruction of the small intrahepatic branches of the portal vein is:", ["Schistosomiasis", "Hepatic cirrhosis", "Umbilical vein sepsis", "Acute appendicitis", "Pancreatic carcinoma"], 0, "Schistosomiasis — the worm lodging in and obstructing small portal-vein branches — is the most common cause of small intrahepatic portal-branch obstruction worldwide; the broader PVT etiology list also includes cirrhosis, neonatal umbilical sepsis, and intra-abdominal infections.\n\nWhy not — Hepatic cirrhosis: Cirrhosis is a common cause of main portal vein thrombosis, not small-branch obstruction.  Umbilical vein sepsis: Umbilical vein sepsis is a neonatal PVT cause, not the small-branch leader worldwide.  Acute appendicitis: Appendicitis can seed pylephlebitis but is not the leading small-branch cause.  Pancreatic carcinoma: Pancreatic carcinoma compresses the main vein; it is not the small-branch leader.", "basic"]]]]], [43, "Pathology: Cirrhosis/Hepatic Failure & Biliary Tract (Lec 43–44)", [[1, "Describe alcoholic liver disease and the steatosis -> steatohepatitis -> fibrosis/cirrhosis progression, and distinguish ALD from NAFLD", [["A liver biopsy from a heavy drinker shows ballooned hepatocytes containing eosinophilic intracytoplasmic ropy inclusions, surrounded by neutrophils. These inclusions are:", ["Mallory-Denk bodies (damaged cytokeratin)", "Councilman bodies (apoptotic hepatocytes)", "Lipofuscin granules (wear-and-tear pigment)", "Ground-glass inclusions (hepatitis B surface antigen)", "Gamna-Gandy bodies (iron-laden fibrosis)"], 0, "Alcoholic steatohepatitis shows a triad of ballooning degeneration, Mallory-Denk (Mallory hyaline) bodies, and neutrophils; the Mallory-Denk bodies are eosinophilic intracytoplasmic aggregates of damaged cytokeratin 8/18 with a characteristic twisted-rope appearance.\n\nWhy not — Councilman bodies (apoptotic hepatocytes): Councilman bodies are apoptotic hepatocytes typical of viral hepatitis, not the ropy cytokeratin aggregates of alcohol.  Lipofuscin granules (wear-and-tear pigment): Lipofuscin is brown wear-and-tear pigment (e.g., Gilbert syndrome), not an eosinophilic ropy inclusion.  Ground-glass inclusions (hepatitis B surface antigen): Ground-glass cytoplasm reflects hepatitis B surface antigen accumulation, not alcoholic injury.  Gamna-Gandy bodies (iron-laden fibrosis): Gamna-Gandy bodies are iron-and-calcium nodules in a congested spleen, not hepatocyte inclusions.", "advanced"]]], [2, "Explain alcohol metabolism (ADH and aldehyde dehydrogenase) and how the rise in NADH drives hepatic fat accumulation", [["In hepatic alcohol metabolism, alcohol dehydrogenase (ADH) and aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH) act, respectively, to convert:", ["Ethanol to acetaldehyde, then acetaldehyde to acetate", "Acetaldehyde to ethanol, then ethanol to acetate", "Ethanol to acetate, then acetate to acetaldehyde", "Acetate to acetaldehyde, then acetaldehyde to ethanol", "Ethanol to glucuronide, then glucuronide to bilirubin"], 0, "ADH first oxidizes ethanol to acetaldehyde in the cytosol; aldehyde dehydrogenase then oxidizes the acetaldehyde to acetate (ultimately CO2 and water) in the mitochondria. Both steps generate NADH.\n\nWhy not — Acetaldehyde to ethanol, then ethanol to acetate: This reverses the pathway; ethanol is the substrate, not the product.  Ethanol to acetate, then acetate to acetaldehyde: ADH does not jump straight to acetate, and acetate is not converted back to acetaldehyde.  Acetate to acetaldehyde, then acetaldehyde to ethanol: This runs the entire sequence backwards.  Ethanol to glucuronide, then glucuronide to bilirubin: Glucuronidation/bilirubin conjugation is a separate pathway unrelated to ADH/ALDH.", "basic"], ["The accumulation of triglyceride (steatosis) in the alcoholic liver is best explained by the elevated NADH/NAD ratio because the high NADH:", ["Increases fatty-acid synthesis while decreasing fatty-acid oxidation", "Decreases fatty-acid synthesis while increasing fatty-acid oxidation", "Blocks hepatic uptake of dietary triglyceride from the gut", "Accelerates export of VLDL particles into the bloodstream", "Inhibits glucuronidation of bilirubin in the hepatocyte"], 0, "The two oxidation steps of alcohol metabolism raise NADH; the high NADH/NAD ratio both induces fatty-acid synthesis and suppresses fatty-acid oxidation, so triglyceride accumulates in the hepatocyte and produces the fatty (steatotic) liver.\n\nWhy not — Decreases fatty-acid synthesis while increasing fatty-acid oxidation: This is the opposite of the metabolic shift NADH produces.  Blocks hepatic uptake of dietary triglyceride from the gut: Steatosis here is driven by altered intrahepatic fat handling, not blocked gut uptake.  Accelerates export of VLDL particles into the bloodstream: Alcohol impairs, rather than accelerates, fat export, contributing to accumulation.  Inhibits glucuronidation of bilirubin in the hepatocyte: Bilirubin glucuronidation is a separate process and not the cause of fatty change.", "basic"]]], [3, "Define cirrhosis (nodules + fibrosis + loss of architecture) and distinguish micronodular (Laennec) from macronodular cirrhosis", [["At autopsy a cirrhotic liver shows uniform nodules measuring 1-2 mm separated by thin connective-tissue septa. This pattern is:", ["Micronodular (Laennec) cirrhosis, typically alcoholic", "Macronodular (post-necrotic) cirrhosis, typically viral", "Biliary cirrhosis from chronic large-duct obstruction", "Focal nodular hyperplasia, a benign regenerative mass", "Nodular regenerative hyperplasia without true fibrosis"], 0, "Micronodular (Laennec, alcoholic) cirrhosis is defined by small, uniform nodules up to about 3 mm separated by thin passive septa; macronodular cirrhosis has larger (>3 mm), variable nodules separated by wider scars and is usually non-alcoholic (e.g., viral hepatitis).\n\nWhy not — Macronodular (post-necrotic) cirrhosis, typically viral: Macronodular cirrhosis has nodules larger than 3 mm separated by wider scars, not uniform 1-2 mm nodules.  Biliary cirrhosis from chronic large-duct obstruction: Biliary cirrhosis produces a green liver from obstruction; it is not defined by this uniform micronodular pattern.  Focal nodular hyperplasia, a benign regenerative mass: Focal nodular hyperplasia is a solitary benign mass with a central scar, not diffuse micronodularity.  Nodular regenerative hyperplasia without true fibrosis: Nodular regenerative hyperplasia lacks the diffuse fibrosis that defines true cirrhosis.", "basic"]]], [4, "Match cirrhosis etiology to gross liver color (alcohol = yellow, hemochromatosis = rusty/brown, biliary obstruction = green)", [["A pathologist examines three cirrhotic livers: one is yellow, one is rusty-brown, and one is enlarged and green. The respective underlying etiologies are:", ["Alcoholic fatty change, hemochromatosis, biliary obstruction", "Hemochromatosis, biliary obstruction, alcoholic fatty change", "Biliary obstruction, alcoholic fatty change, hemochromatosis", "Alcoholic fatty change, biliary obstruction, hemochromatosis", "Hemochromatosis, alcoholic fatty change, biliary obstruction"], 0, "Liver color encodes etiology: alcoholic fatty cirrhosis is yellow, hemochromatosis is rusty/dark brown from iron, and chronic biliary obstruction produces a large green liver from retained bile.\n\nWhy not — Hemochromatosis, biliary obstruction, alcoholic fatty change: Yellow is alcohol/fat, not hemochromatosis; the pairings are scrambled.  Biliary obstruction, alcoholic fatty change, hemochromatosis: Green is biliary obstruction, not the yellow liver; the order is wrong.  Alcoholic fatty change, biliary obstruction, hemochromatosis: Rusty-brown is hemochromatosis (iron), not biliary obstruction.  Hemochromatosis, alcoholic fatty change, biliary obstruction: Yellow is alcohol/fat, not hemochromatosis; the first pairing is wrong.", "advanced"]]], [5, "Describe acute and chronic hepatic failure, the three hepatic zones, acetaminophen as the leading US cause, and the acute-liver-failure triad", [["In the United States, the single most common cause of acute (fulminant) liver failure is:", ["Acetaminophen toxicity", "Hepatitis B infection", "Hepatitis E infection", "Wilson disease", "Autoimmune hepatitis"], 0, "Acetaminophen accounts for roughly 50% of acute liver failure cases in the US; hepatitis B and E predominate in Asia, while autoimmune and other causes make up the remainder.\n\nWhy not — Hepatitis B infection: Hepatitis B is a leading cause in Asia, not the top US cause.  Hepatitis E infection: Hepatitis E predominates in Asia, not the US.  Wilson disease: Wilson disease is a rare cause, not the leading one.  Autoimmune hepatitis: Autoimmune hepatitis accounts for only a minority of US cases.", "basic"], ["A previously healthy adult presents 3 days after a large acetaminophen overdose with scleral icterus, an INR of 2.4, and confusion progressing to lethargy. Biopsy would be expected to show necrosis concentrated in which zone, and this clinical picture defines which syndrome?", ["Zone 3 (centrilobular) necrosis; acute liver failure with its jaundice-coagulopathy-encephalopathy triad", "Zone 1 (periportal) necrosis; chronic liver failure with portal hypertension", "Zone 2 (mid-zonal) necrosis; hepatorenal syndrome with a normal kidney", "Zone 3 (centrilobular) congestion; Budd-Chiari outflow obstruction", "Zone 1 (periportal) steatosis; benign Gilbert-type hyperbilirubinemia"], 0, "Acetaminophen is a zone-3 (centrilobular) toxin because that zone has the highest P450 and lowest oxygen; the combination of jaundice, coagulopathy (INR >1.5), and encephalopathy within months of onset defines acute liver failure and its classic triad.\n\nWhy not — Zone 1 (periportal) necrosis; chronic liver failure with portal hypertension: Acetaminophen damages zone 3, not zone 1, and this acute picture is not chronic portal-hypertensive failure.  Zone 2 (mid-zonal) necrosis; hepatorenal syndrome with a normal kidney: Acetaminophen targets zone 3, not zone 2, and hepatorenal syndrome is a renal complication, not this hepatic triad.  Zone 3 (centrilobular) congestion; Budd-Chiari outflow obstruction: The injury is true centrilobular necrosis from a toxin, not the venous congestion of Budd-Chiari.  Zone 1 (periportal) steatosis; benign Gilbert-type hyperbilirubinemia: Zone 1 steatosis and benign Gilbert hyperbilirubinemia do not produce coagulopathy and encephalopathy.", "advanced"]]], [6, "Order liver labs by category: integrity (ALT/AST/LDH), function (bilirubin/bile acids/ALP/GGT), and synthetic (PT/PTT/factors)", []], [7, "Distinguish prehepatic/hepatic/posthepatic jaundice and conjugated vs unconjugated, and explain hepatic encephalopathy and hepatorenal syndrome", [["Hepatic encephalopathy in liver failure is driven by accumulation of which substance, acting on which cell?", ["Ammonia acting on astrocytes", "Bilirubin acting on basal ganglia neurons", "Copper acting on the lenticular nucleus", "Glutamate acting on microglia", "Iron acting on cerebellar Purkinje cells"], 0, "When failing hepatocytes cannot clear waste, ammonia accumulates, crosses the blood-brain barrier, and is taken up by astrocytes, where it raises glutamine and osmotic pressure, causing astrocyte swelling and cerebral edema (Alzheimer type II astrocytes).\n\nWhy not — Bilirubin acting on basal ganglia neurons: Bilirubin-on-neurons describes kernicterus in neonates, not the ammonia-driven adult encephalopathy.  Copper acting on the lenticular nucleus: Copper in the lenticular nucleus is Wilson disease, a different entity.  Glutamate acting on microglia: The mediator is ammonia and the target is the astrocyte, not glutamate on microglia.  Iron acting on cerebellar Purkinje cells: Iron and Purkinje cells are not the mechanism of hepatic encephalopathy.", "basic"], ["Hepatorenal syndrome occurring in advanced liver disease is best characterized as:", ["Functional renal failure from decreased perfusion, with histologically normal kidneys", "Acute tubular necrosis from a nephrotoxin filtered by the liver", "Immune-complex glomerulonephritis driven by viral antigens", "Obstructive uropathy from stones precipitated by hyperbilirubinemia", "Polycystic kidney destruction associated with congenital hepatic fibrosis"], 0, "Hepatorenal syndrome is a functional renal failure of advanced liver disease: systemic vasodilation and renal vasoconstriction reduce renal perfusion and GFR, yet the kidneys are structurally/histologically normal, so the physiology is prerenal rather than intrinsic damage.\n\nWhy not — Acute tubular necrosis from a nephrotoxin filtered by the liver: Hepatorenal syndrome is functional, not direct tubular toxin injury; the kidneys look normal.  Immune-complex glomerulonephritis driven by viral antigens: It is a perfusion problem, not immune-complex glomerulonephritis.  Obstructive uropathy from stones precipitated by hyperbilirubinemia: It is not an obstructive stone disease.  Polycystic kidney destruction associated with congenital hepatic fibrosis: It is not the polycystic/fibrotic kidney of congenital hepatic fibrosis.", "basic"]]], [8, "Integrate portal hypertension (prehepatic/intrahepatic/post-sinusoidal) with its systemic complications: varices, splenomegaly, ascites", [["Robbins groups portal hypertension as prehepatic, intrahepatic, or post-sinusoidal. The single most common cause of portal hypertension is:", ["Cirrhosis (intrahepatic)", "Portal vein thrombosis (prehepatic)", "Splenic vein thrombosis (prehepatic)", "Budd-Chiari syndrome (post-sinusoidal)", "Right-sided heart failure (post-sinusoidal)"], 0, "Intrahepatic disease, dominated by cirrhosis, is by far the most common cause of portal hypertension; the increased fibrosis and nodularity raise sinusoidal resistance. Prehepatic (portal/splenic vein thrombosis) and post-sinusoidal (Budd-Chiari, right heart failure) causes are less common.\n\nWhy not — Portal vein thrombosis (prehepatic): Portal vein thrombosis is a prehepatic cause but is far less common than cirrhosis.  Splenic vein thrombosis (prehepatic): Splenic vein thrombosis is an uncommon prehepatic cause.  Budd-Chiari syndrome (post-sinusoidal): Budd-Chiari is a post-sinusoidal outflow cause, not the most common overall.  Right-sided heart failure (post-sinusoidal): Right heart failure is a post-sinusoidal cause but not the leading one.", "basic"], ["Among the complications of portal hypertension, the one most often cited as a major cause of death in cirrhotic patients is:", ["Bleeding esophageal varices", "Caput medusae", "Internal hemorrhoids", "Splenomegaly", "Mild ascites"], 0, "Dilated submucosal veins in the lower esophagus (varices) form to decompress the portal system; their rupture causes massive upper-GI bleeding and is one of the most common causes of death in cirrhotic patients with portal hypertension.\n\nWhy not — Caput medusae: Caput medusae is a visible collateral pattern but not a leading cause of death.  Internal hemorrhoids: Hemorrhoids are a portosystemic collateral but rarely lethal.  Splenomegaly: Splenomegaly causes cytopenias but is not the usual cause of death.  Mild ascites: Ascites contributes to morbidity but is not the catastrophic bleed that kills.", "advanced"]]], [9, "Describe the pathological features of congenital anomalies of the biliary tract including, biliary atresia and choledochal cyst.", [["Biliary atresia, the most common cause of pediatric liver transplantation in the United States, is best described as:", ["Progressive obliterative cholangiopathy of the extrahepatic ducts", "Cystic dilation of the common bile duct from pancreatic reflux", "Segmental cystic dilation of the large intrahepatic ducts", "Autoimmune destruction of small intrahepatic bile ducts", "Calcific transformation of the entire gallbladder wall"], 0, "Biliary atresia (AKA progressive obliterative cholangiopathy) is luminal obstruction and fibrosis of the extrahepatic biliary tree, linked to GPC1/glypican-1; it causes neonatal cholestasis and is the leading reason children undergo liver transplant in the US.\n\nWhy not — Cystic dilation of the common bile duct from pancreatic reflux: Cystic dilation of the common bile duct from anomalous pancreaticobiliary junction is a choledochal cyst, not atresia.  Segmental cystic dilation of the large intrahepatic ducts: Segmental cystic dilation of large intrahepatic ducts is Caroli disease, not biliary atresia.  Autoimmune destruction of small intrahepatic bile ducts: Autoimmune small-duct destruction is primary biliary cholangitis, not a congenital atresia.  Calcific transformation of the entire gallbladder wall: Calcific gallbladder transformation is the porcelain gallbladder, unrelated to biliary atresia.", "basic"], ["A choledochal cyst is most often a fusiform or spherical dilation of the extrahepatic biliary tree. Which Todani type does this describe, and what is its feared long-term complication?", ["Type I, with an increased risk of cholangiocarcinoma", "Type II, with an increased risk of hepatic adenoma", "Type III, with an increased risk of pancreatic insulinoma", "Type IV, with an increased risk of hepatocellular carcinoma", "Type V (Caroli), with an increased risk of renal carcinoma"], 0, "Type I — fusiform/spherical dilation of the extrahepatic biliary tree — is the most common choledochal cyst; an anomalous junction of the common bile duct with the pancreatic duct refluxes enzymes that weaken the wall, and the dreaded sequel is biliary epithelial dysplasia progressing to cholangiocarcinoma.\n\nWhy not — Type II, with an increased risk of hepatic adenoma: Type II is a true diverticular sac off the duct, and the cancer risk is cholangiocarcinoma, not hepatic adenoma.  Type III, with an increased risk of pancreatic insulinoma: Type III (choledochocele) sits in the duodenal/pancreatic wall; the risk is biliary cancer, not insulinoma.  Type IV, with an increased risk of hepatocellular carcinoma: Type IV extends into the liver but the feared cancer is cholangiocarcinoma, not hepatocellular carcinoma.  Type V (Caroli), with an increased risk of renal carcinoma: Caroli disease (type V) raises cholangiocarcinoma risk, not renal carcinoma; and it is not the fusiform extrahepatic type.", "advanced"]]], [10, "Describe the major features of primary sclerosing cholangitis.", [["A 35-year-old man with ulcerative colitis has cholestatic LFTs and an ERCP showing a 'beaded' pattern of strictures and dilations in the large bile ducts. The diagnosis and its associated antibody are:", ["Primary sclerosing cholangitis with p-ANCA positivity", "Primary biliary cholangitis with anti-mitochondrial antibody", "IgG4 cholangitis with elevated serum IgG4", "Cholangiocarcinoma with elevated serum CA 19-9", "Autoimmune hepatitis with anti-smooth-muscle antibody"], 0, "A young man with ulcerative colitis, cholestatic LFTs, and beaded large-duct strictures/dilations on ERCP is the textbook primary sclerosing cholangitis picture; PSC is p-ANCA positive in roughly 65% of patients (the PBC-vs-PSC comparison table; the prose slide quotes ~80%), the discriminator from PBC's anti-mitochondrial antibody.\n\nWhy not — Primary biliary cholangitis with anti-mitochondrial antibody: PBC affects middle-aged women, spares large ducts, and is anti-mitochondrial — not the male/UC/beaded large-duct picture.  IgG4 cholangitis with elevated serum IgG4: IgG4 cholangitis mimics PSC but is steroid-responsive and tied to autoimmune pancreatitis, not ulcerative colitis with p-ANCA.  Cholangiocarcinoma with elevated serum CA 19-9: Cholangiocarcinoma is a complication of PSC, not the primary diagnosis given these benign-stricture findings.  Autoimmune hepatitis with anti-smooth-muscle antibody: Autoimmune hepatitis is a hepatocellular, not cholestatic ductal, disease and lacks the beaded ERCP pattern.", "advanced"], ["On biopsy, primary sclerosing cholangitis is distinguished from primary biliary cholangitis by which characteristic small-duct lesion?", ["Concentric 'onion-skin' periductal fibrosis leaving a 'tombstone' scar", "Granulomatous 'florid duct lesion' destroying the duct epithelium", "Lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate with storiform fibrosis and phlebitis", "Ground-glass hepatocytes with intracytoplasmic viral inclusions", "Centrilobular cholestasis with feathery degeneration of hepatocytes"], 0, "PSC's small ducts show a striking circumferential 'onion-skin' periductal fibrosis around an atrophic lumen that is eventually obliterated, leaving a 'tombstone' scar — the histologic signature that separates it from PBC's granulomatous florid duct lesion.\n\nWhy not — Granulomatous 'florid duct lesion' destroying the duct epithelium: The granulomatous florid duct lesion is the hallmark of PBC, not PSC.  Lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate with storiform fibrosis and phlebitis: Storiform fibrosis with obliterative phlebitis and a lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate describes IgG4 cholangitis.  Ground-glass hepatocytes with intracytoplasmic viral inclusions: Ground-glass hepatocytes are a hepatitis B finding, unrelated to PSC duct lesions.  Centrilobular cholestasis with feathery degeneration of hepatocytes: Feathery degeneration is a nonspecific cholestasis change, not the diagnostic onion-skin lesion.", "basic"]]], [11, "Describe the pathogenesis and complications of cholelithiasis.", [["Cholesterol gallstones, which account for roughly 90% of stones in the US, are classically described as:", ["Yellow, radiolucent, and arising only within the gallbladder", "Black, radiopaque, and arising throughout the biliary tree", "Brown, radiopaque, and forming only in the common bile duct", "Composed mainly of unconjugated bilirubin and calcium salts", "Associated chiefly with chronic hemolysis and sickle cell disease"], 0, "Cholesterol stones (~90%, 50-100% cholesterol) are yellow, arise only in the gallbladder, and are mostly radiolucent (some become radiopaque from calcium carbonate); the pigment-stone features — bilirubin content, radiopacity, hemolysis links — belong to the other class.\n\nWhy not — Black, radiopaque, and arising throughout the biliary tree: Black, radiopaque, biliary-tree-wide stones are pigment stones, not cholesterol stones.  Brown, radiopaque, and forming only in the common bile duct: Brown stones are radiolucent and tied to infection; this option mislabels them as radiopaque.  Composed mainly of unconjugated bilirubin and calcium salts: Unconjugated bilirubin plus calcium salts is the composition of pigment stones, not cholesterol stones.  Associated chiefly with chronic hemolysis and sickle cell disease: Chronic hemolysis (e.g., sickle cell) drives black pigment stones, not cholesterol stones.", "basic"], ["A 45-year-old obese, multiparous woman on oral contraceptives develops gallstones. Beyond these classic '4 F' risks, which pathogenic step is the primary driver of cholesterol-stone formation?", ["Supersaturation of bile with cholesterol", "Chronic intravascular hemolysis of red cells", "Ascending bacterial infection of the bile", "Reflux of pancreatic enzymes into the duct", "Immune destruction of intrahepatic ductules"], 0, "The 4 F's (female, fat, forty, fertile) plus estrogen/OCP describe who, but the mechanism is bile supersaturated with cholesterol, then gallbladder hypomotility promoting nucleation and mucus hypersecretion trapping crystals — supersaturation is the initiating step.\n\nWhy not — Chronic intravascular hemolysis of red cells: Hemolysis drives black pigment stones, not cholesterol stones.  Ascending bacterial infection of the bile: Bacterial/parasitic infection drives brown pigment stones, not the cholesterol mechanism.  Reflux of pancreatic enzymes into the duct: Pancreatic-enzyme reflux underlies choledochal cysts, not cholesterol-stone pathogenesis.  Immune destruction of intrahepatic ductules: Immune ductule destruction is the cholangitis mechanism, not gallstone formation.", "advanced"]]], [12, "Describe the causes, morphology, and complications of acute and chronic cholecystitis, cholesterolosis, polyps and mucocele of the gallbladder.", [["A gallbladder removed for repeated attacks of biliary colic shows a thickened, shrunken wall and herniations of mucosa through the muscularis. These herniations are called:", ["Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses", "Crypts of Lieberkühn", "Brunner gland ducts", "Crypt abscesses", "Pseudomembranes"], 0, "Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses are outpouchings of mucosa herniating through the muscularis (pseudodiverticula); their accentuation, present ~90% of the time, is the histologic hallmark of chronic cholecystitis in a thickened, shrunken gallbladder.\n\nWhy not — Crypts of Lieberkühn: Crypts of Lieberkühn are normal intestinal glands, not gallbladder wall herniations.  Brunner gland ducts: Brunner glands belong to the duodenum, not the gallbladder.  Crypt abscesses: Crypt abscesses are a colonic inflammatory-bowel-disease finding, not a gallbladder structure.  Pseudomembranes: Pseudomembranes are a C. difficile colitis finding, unrelated to the gallbladder wall.", "advanced"], ["A gallbladder specimen shows a bright red mucosa studded with yellow flecks, and biopsy reveals cholesterol-laden foamy macrophages in the lamina propria. This benign 'strawberry gallbladder' is:", ["Cholesterolosis", "Porcelain gallbladder", "Acute calculous cholecystitis", "Adenomyomatosis", "Gallbladder adenocarcinoma"], 0, "Cholesterolosis ('strawberry gallbladder') is cholesterol accumulation in foamy macrophages of the lamina propria, seen as yellow flecks on a red mucosa; it is asymptomatic and benign, distinct from the calcified porcelain gallbladder or true cholecystitis.\n\nWhy not — Porcelain gallbladder: Porcelain gallbladder is a calcified, brittle, bluish wall — not yellow flecks on a red mucosa.  Acute calculous cholecystitis: Acute calculous cholecystitis shows an edematous, hemorrhagic, distended gallbladder, not strawberry flecking.  Adenomyomatosis: Adenomyomatosis is mucosal/muscular hyperplasia with Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses, not foamy-macrophage flecking.  Gallbladder adenocarcinoma: Adenocarcinoma is an infiltrative malignant mass, not the benign strawberry pattern.", "advanced"]]], [13, "Discuss the major pathological feature of tumors of the gallbladder and bile ducts.", [["A 70-year-old presents with painless jaundice. Imaging shows an infiltrative mass at the junction where the right and left hepatic ducts unite to form the common hepatic duct, and serum CA 19-9 is elevated. The most precise diagnosis is:", ["Perihilar cholangiocarcinoma (Klatskin tumor)", "Intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma within the liver parenchyma", "Distal cholangiocarcinoma near the ampulla of Vater", "Gallbladder adenocarcinoma arising in a porcelain gallbladder", "Carcinoma of the ampulla of Vater surrounded by adenoma"], 0, "A cholangiocarcinoma located precisely at the junction where the left and right hepatic ducts meet to form the common hepatic duct is, by definition, a perihilar (hilar) cholangiocarcinoma — the Klatskin tumor — which Machini flagged as a board point; the other sites are anatomically wrong for that junction.\n\nWhy not — Intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma within the liver parenchyma: Intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma sits within the liver parenchyma, not at the extrahepatic ductal confluence.  Distal cholangiocarcinoma near the ampulla of Vater: Distal cholangiocarcinoma is near the small intestine/ampulla, not at the hepatic-duct junction.  Gallbladder adenocarcinoma arising in a porcelain gallbladder: Gallbladder adenocarcinoma arises in the gallbladder wall, not at the confluence of hepatic ducts.  Carcinoma of the ampulla of Vater surrounded by adenoma: Ampullary carcinoma sits at the ampulla of Vater, far distal to the hepatic-duct junction.", "advanced"]]]]], [45, "Surgical Aspects: Gallbladder/Biliary & Liver/Pancreas (Lec 45–46)", [[1, "Describe bile/gallbladder physiology (CCK contraction, bile acids, cystic artery)", [["The gallbladder's arterial supply runs through the triangle of Calot. The cystic artery is most commonly a branch of the:", ["Right hepatic artery", "Left hepatic artery", "Gastroduodenal artery", "Superior mesenteric artery", "Splenic artery"], 0, "The cystic artery typically arises from the right hepatic artery and is found within the triangle of Calot (the hepatocystic triangle), the key landmark identified during cholecystectomy.\n\nWhy not — Left hepatic artery: The cystic artery comes off the right, not the left, hepatic artery in the standard anatomy.  Gastroduodenal artery: The gastroduodenal artery supplies the duodenum/pancreas, not the gallbladder.  Superior mesenteric artery: The SMA supplies the midgut, not the gallbladder.  Splenic artery: The splenic artery supplies the spleen and part of the pancreas, not the gallbladder.", "basic"]]], [2, "Describe gallstone types and the spectrum of gallstone complications", [["A patient with a mechanical heart valve and chronic hemolysis develops gallstones. These pigment stones are most specifically associated with:", ["Black pigment stones (hemolysis, cirrhosis, or chronic TPN)", "Brown pigment stones (biliary stasis and infection)", "Cholesterol stones (obesity and estrogen)", "Mixed stones from anomalous pancreaticobiliary junction", "Calcium oxalate stones from enteric hyperoxaluria"], 0, "Black pigment stones form in chronic hemolysis, cirrhosis, and long-term total parenteral nutrition; brown pigment stones instead arise from biliary stasis and infection (classically in Asian populations), and cholesterol stones are the non-pigment majority driven by metabolic risk factors.\n\nWhy not — Brown pigment stones (biliary stasis and infection): Brown stones come from stasis and infection, not hemolysis.  Cholesterol stones (obesity and estrogen): Cholesterol stones are non-pigment and tied to obesity/estrogen, not hemolysis.  Mixed stones from anomalous pancreaticobiliary junction: Anomalous pancreaticobiliary junction is a cancer risk factor, not a hemolytic-stone mechanism.  Calcium oxalate stones from enteric hyperoxaluria: Calcium oxalate stones are a renal-stone entity, not a biliary pigment stone.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Explain the management of asymptomatic gallstones", [["Gallstones are found incidentally on an abdominal CT ordered for an unrelated reason in an asymptomatic patient with no biliary pain. The most appropriate management is:", ["Observation (expectant management); no cholecystectomy", "Prophylactic laparoscopic cholecystectomy for all such patients", "ERCP with sphincterotomy to clear the gallbladder", "A course of ursodeoxycholic acid to dissolve the stones", "Empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics and admission"], 0, "Not all gallstones need to be removed: asymptomatic cholelithiasis is managed conservatively with observation because the lifetime risk of complicated disease is low (~8%); prophylactic cholecystectomy is reserved for individualized special cases.\n\nWhy not — Prophylactic laparoscopic cholecystectomy for all such patients: Prophylactic cholecystectomy is reserved for individualized special cases, not all asymptomatic patients.  ERCP with sphincterotomy to clear the gallbladder: ERCP treats bile-duct stones/obstruction, not silent gallbladder stones.  A course of ursodeoxycholic acid to dissolve the stones: Dissolution therapy is not the standard for asymptomatic stones; observation is.  Empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics and admission: Antibiotics are for infection (cholecystitis/cholangitis), not asymptomatic stones.", "advanced"]]], [4, "Describe biliary colic and biliary dyskinesia (HIDA, CCK ejection fraction)", []], [5, "Describe acute (calculous/acalculous) and chronic cholecystitis and management", [["A patient with RUQ pain and a positive Murphy sign is suspected of acute cholecystitis. The single most appropriate FIRST imaging test is:", ["Abdominal ultrasound of the right upper quadrant", "HIDA (cholescintigraphy) scan", "Triple-phase CT of the abdomen", "MRCP", "Diagnostic laparoscopy"], 0, "Ultrasound is the preferred initial test for suspected cholecystitis, looking for gallbladder wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, and stones/sludge; HIDA is used when ultrasound is equivocal, with non-visualization at 60 minutes supporting acute cholecystitis.\n\nWhy not — HIDA (cholescintigraphy) scan: HIDA is the second-line test when ultrasound is equivocal, not the first.  Triple-phase CT of the abdomen: CT is helpful in selected cases but is not the first-line gallbladder test.  MRCP: MRCP evaluates the ducts; it is not the initial cholecystitis test.  Diagnostic laparoscopy: Laparoscopy is therapeutic, not the initial diagnostic imaging step.", "advanced"], ["A HIDA scan shows no gallbladder filling at 60 minutes, but the gallbladder does become visualized by 120 minutes. This pattern is most consistent with:", ["Chronic cholecystitis", "Acute calculous cholecystitis", "Acute acalculous cholecystitis", "A normal HIDA scan", "Biliary dyskinesia with a normal ejection fraction"], 0, "Non-visualization at 60 minutes with delayed visualization by ~120 minutes indicates chronic cholecystitis; persistent non-visualization at 60 minutes (without later filling) indicates acute cholecystitis, and a normal scan shows the gallbladder within the first hour.\n\nWhy not — Acute calculous cholecystitis: Acute cholecystitis shows non-visualization at 60 minutes that does NOT fill later.  Acute acalculous cholecystitis: Acalculous cholecystitis also gives a positive (non-visualizing) 60-minute scan, not delayed filling.  A normal HIDA scan: A normal scan visualizes the gallbladder within the first 60 minutes.  Biliary dyskinesia with a normal ejection fraction: Dyskinesia is diagnosed by a low CCK ejection fraction, not by delayed filling.", "advanced"]]], [6, "Describe cholangitis (Charcot triad, Reynolds pentad) and its management sequence", [["A patient arrives with fever, RUQ pain, jaundice, confusion, and a blood pressure of 84/50. After recognizing Reynolds pentad, what is the correct FIRST priority before definitive biliary drainage?", ["IV broad-spectrum antibiotics plus fluid resuscitation", "Immediate ERCP with sphincterotomy", "Emergent open common bile duct exploration", "Percutaneous transhepatic cholecystostomy tube", "Laparoscopic cholecystectomy on the same admission"], 0, "Acute cholangitis (Charcot triad; Reynolds pentad adds altered mental status and hypotension) is managed with broad-spectrum antibiotics and resuscitation FIRST to stabilize the septic patient, and only THEN biliary drainage (most often ERCP with sphincterotomy); drainage precedes any decision about surgery.\n\nWhy not — Immediate ERCP with sphincterotomy: ERCP/drainage is the definitive step, but it comes AFTER antibiotics and resuscitation.  Emergent open common bile duct exploration: Open exploration is reserved for failed drainage, not the first move.  Percutaneous transhepatic cholecystostomy tube: A cholecystostomy tube does not address the obstructed bile duct and is not the first priority.  Laparoscopic cholecystectomy on the same admission: Cholecystectomy is not the emergency step in a septic, hypotensive cholangitis patient.", "advanced"]]], [7, "Describe gallstone pancreatitis and gallstone ileus", [["An elderly patient has a small-bowel obstruction with pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree) and a stone impacted in the distal ileum. This is gallstone ileus; the stone reached the bowel through a:", ["Cholecystoduodenal fistula", "Patent cystic duct that simply dilated", "Ruptured common bile duct into the peritoneum", "Pancreaticobiliary maljunction", "Surgical biliary-enteric anastomosis (choledochojejunostomy)"], 0, "Gallstone ileus follows formation of a cholecystoduodenal (cholecystoenteric) fistula through which a large stone passes into the gut and impacts at the narrow terminal ileum, producing pneumobilia and small-bowel obstruction; treatment is enterotomy proximal to the obstruction to extract the stone.\n\nWhy not — Patent cystic duct that simply dilated: Stones large enough to obstruct the ileum do not pass through a normal cystic duct.  Ruptured common bile duct into the peritoneum: A ruptured CBD causes bile peritonitis, not luminal stone impaction.  Pancreaticobiliary maljunction: Pancreaticobiliary maljunction is a cancer risk factor, not the fistula route here.  Surgical biliary-enteric anastomosis (choledochojejunostomy): The fistula is spontaneous (cholecystoduodenal), not a prior surgical anastomosis.", "advanced"]]], [8, "Describe biliary strictures and biliary cysts", []], [9, "Describe gallbladder cancer and polyps, including staging and surgical management", [["An incidental gallbladder adenocarcinoma found after routine cholecystectomy is staged T1a (tumor confined to the lamina propria, not invading the muscularis). The appropriate management is:", ["Simple cholecystectomy alone is curative; no further resection", "Extended cholecystectomy with segment IVb/V resection and lymphadenectomy", "Neoadjuvant chemoradiation followed by Whipple resection", "Total hepatectomy and liver transplantation", "Palliative biliary stenting only"], 0, "For T1a gallbladder cancer (confined to the lamina propria, not beyond the muscularis), simple cholecystectomy is curative; the extended cholecystectomy with hepatic segment IVb/V resection and regional lymphadenectomy is reserved for T1b/T2 lesions that invade the muscularis and carry lymphatic-spread risk.\n\nWhy not — Extended cholecystectomy with segment IVb/V resection and lymphadenectomy: Extended cholecystectomy + lymphadenectomy is for T1b/T2 (muscularis invasion), not T1a.  Neoadjuvant chemoradiation followed by Whipple resection: Whipple is for periampullary/pancreatic head tumors, not a T1a gallbladder cancer.  Total hepatectomy and liver transplantation: Transplantation is not the management for resectable gallbladder cancer.  Palliative biliary stenting only: Palliative stenting is for unresectable disease, not a curable T1a lesion.", "basic"], ["A gallbladder mass is found in the fundus, and a separate patient has a 22 mm gallbladder polyp. Two features that BEST raise concern for malignancy here are:", ["Fundal location of the lesion and polyp size greater than ~10-20 mm", "Infundibular location and any polyp regardless of size", "Multiple small cholesterol polyps and a thin gallbladder wall", "Presence of biliary sludge and a normal-caliber cystic duct", "A contracted gallbladder and a low CCK ejection fraction"], 0, "Gallstone disease usually affects the infundibulum/cystic duct, so a FUNDAL lesion is suspicious for a neoplastic process; polyp malignant risk rises with size, so polyps >10 mm (and especially >20 mm) warrant cholecystectomy (preferably open to avoid seeding).\n\nWhy not — Infundibular location and any polyp regardless of size: Most small polyps are benign cholesterol polyps; size, not 'any polyp,' drives concern.  Multiple small cholesterol polyps and a thin gallbladder wall: Multiple small cholesterol polyps with a thin wall are the benign pattern.  Presence of biliary sludge and a normal-caliber cystic duct: Sludge and a normal cystic duct are not specific cancer features.  A contracted gallbladder and a low CCK ejection fraction: A low ejection fraction indicates dyskinesia, not malignancy.", "advanced"]]], [10, "Describe cholangiocarcinoma", [["Cholangiocarcinoma arising at the confluence of the right and left hepatic ducts (the hilum) is classically called a:", ["Klatskin (perihilar) tumor", "Krukenberg tumor", "Pancoast tumor", "Whipple tumor", "Warthin tumor"], 0, "A perihilar cholangiocarcinoma at the hepatic-duct confluence is the classic Klatskin tumor; cholangiocarcinoma is most often adenocarcinoma, two-thirds occur outside the liver, and the best chance for survival is a curative surgical excision.\n\nWhy not — Krukenberg tumor: Krukenberg is a metastatic ovarian tumor from gastric/GI signet-ring cancer.  Pancoast tumor: Pancoast is a superior-sulcus lung tumor.  Whipple tumor: Whipple is the name of the pancreaticoduodenectomy operation/triad, not this tumor.  Warthin tumor: Warthin tumor is a benign salivary-gland (parotid) tumor.", "basic"]]], [11, "Evaluate a liver mass (imaging, tumor markers, role of biopsy)", [["A cirrhotic patient is found to have a 4 cm hypervascular liver mass and an elevated alpha-fetoprotein (AFP). What is the most appropriate next step to confirm the diagnosis?", ["No biopsy needed; triple-phase CT/MRI plus AFP is diagnostic", "Percutaneous core-needle biopsy of the mass", "Laparoscopic wedge biopsy for tissue diagnosis", "Sulfur-colloid scan to confirm malignancy", "Repeat ultrasound in six months before any further workup"], 0, "Sharieff stressed that a liver mass rarely needs a biopsy: history/physical, a triple-phase CT or MRI showing the enhancement pattern, plus tumor markers usually give the diagnosis. A hypervascular mass with elevated AFP in a cirrhotic is hepatocellular carcinoma and is diagnosed without tissue.\n\nWhy not — Percutaneous core-needle biopsy of the mass: Biopsy is generally avoided; the imaging-plus-marker combination is already diagnostic and biopsy risks seeding/bleeding.  Laparoscopic wedge biopsy for tissue diagnosis: Surgical biopsy is unnecessary when imaging and AFP already establish HCC.  Sulfur-colloid scan to confirm malignancy: Sulfur-colloid scans help characterize some lesions (e.g., FNH/adenoma) but do not confirm HCC here.  Repeat ultrasound in six months before any further workup: Delaying workup of a hypervascular AFP-positive mass in a cirrhotic is inappropriate.", "advanced"]]], [12, "Distinguish and manage benign liver lesions (hemangioma, adenoma, FNH, cyst)", [["A 28-year-old woman on oral contraceptives has a 5 cm hepatic adenoma; a 35-year-old man has a 2 cm hepatic adenoma. Which management plan is correct for these two patients?", ["Resect both — the woman because it is >4 cm, the man because any-size adenoma in a male is resected", "Watch both with serial imaging since adenomas are benign", "Resect the woman's but watch the man's because his is small", "Watch the woman's after stopping OCPs; resect the man's only if symptomatic", "Biopsy both first, then resect only if dysplasia is found"], 0, "Hepatic adenomas carry rupture and malignant-transformation risk. The exam rule: resect ANY-size adenoma in a man; in a woman, resect if >4 cm (or symptomatic/growing) but a lesion <4 cm may be watched after stopping estrogen/anabolic steroids. The woman's 5 cm lesion (>4 cm) and the man's adenoma (any size) both get resected.\n\nWhy not — Watch both with serial imaging since adenomas are benign: Adenomas are not simply watched; both of these meet resection criteria.  Resect the woman's but watch the man's because his is small: The man's small adenoma still warrants resection — any size in a male is resected.  Watch the woman's after stopping OCPs; resect the man's only if symptomatic: The woman's 5 cm lesion is >4 cm and should be resected, not watched.  Biopsy both first, then resect only if dysplasia is found: Biopsy is avoided for liver lesions; management is by size/sex/risk, not tissue.", "advanced"]]], [13, "Diagnose and manage hepatocellular carcinoma, including Milan criteria", [["A patient with hepatitis C cirrhosis has a single 4.5 cm hepatocellular carcinoma with no vascular invasion and no extrahepatic spread. Applying the Milan criteria, what is the best management and why?", ["Liver transplantation, because the lesion is a single nodule <=5 cm without vascular invasion or distant disease", "Wedge resection alone, because transplantation is never offered for malignancy", "Systemic chemotherapy first, because a 4.5 cm HCC exceeds all transplant criteria", "Observation with serial AFP, because a 4.5 cm lesion is too small to treat", "Radiofrequency ablation only, because cirrhosis precludes any surgery"], 0, "The Milan criteria define transplant eligibility: a single nodule <=5 cm OR up to three nodules each <=3 cm, with no macrovascular invasion and no distant disease. A single 4.5 cm HCC without invasion or spread meets Milan, and in a cirrhotic, transplant gives the best outcome (and removes the diseased liver) rather than resection alone.\n\nWhy not — Wedge resection alone, because transplantation is never offered for malignancy: Transplantation IS offered for HCC within Milan and outperforms resection alone in cirrhotics.  Systemic chemotherapy first, because a 4.5 cm HCC exceeds all transplant criteria: A single 4.5 cm lesion is well within Milan, not beyond all criteria.  Observation with serial AFP, because a 4.5 cm lesion is too small to treat: A 4.5 cm HCC is not 'too small to treat'; it qualifies for definitive transplant.  Radiofrequency ablation only, because cirrhosis precludes any surgery: Cirrhosis is a reason to transplant, not a contraindication to treatment.", "advanced"], ["Which set of findings correctly states the Milan criteria for liver transplantation in hepatocellular carcinoma?", ["Single nodule <=5 cm OR up to 3 nodules each <=3 cm, no vascular invasion, no distant disease", "Single nodule <=3 cm OR up to 5 nodules each <=5 cm, vascular invasion permitted", "Any number of nodules <=8 cm total, regardless of vascular invasion", "Single nodule of any size as long as AFP is normal", "Up to 3 nodules each <=5 cm with limited lymph-node spread allowed"], 0, "Milan criteria: one nodule up to 5 cm, or up to three nodules each up to 3 cm, with no macrovascular invasion and no extrahepatic/distant disease. The UCSF criteria are slightly more permissive (single <=6.5 cm or up to 3 each <=4.5 cm, total <=8 cm) but most centers use Milan.\n\nWhy not — Single nodule <=3 cm OR up to 5 nodules each <=5 cm, vascular invasion permitted: The size/number thresholds are scrambled and vascular invasion is NOT permitted.  Any number of nodules <=8 cm total, regardless of vascular invasion: Milan caps nodule size/number and excludes vascular invasion.  Single nodule of any size as long as AFP is normal: Milan is defined by size and number, not by AFP alone.  Up to 3 nodules each <=5 cm with limited lymph-node spread allowed: Lymph-node/distant spread disqualifies a patient under Milan.", "basic"]]], [14, "Manage liver abscesses and metastatic liver disease", [["Three liver lesions are described: (1) a 6 cm pyogenic abscess, (2) an amebic abscess, and (3) an echinococcal cyst. Which management triad is correct?", ["Drain the pyogenic abscess (>5 cm) with antibiotics; treat amebic with metronidazole and no aspiration; treat echinococcal with albendazole/PAIR and avoid simple aspiration (anaphylaxis risk)", "Aspirate all three for diagnosis before any drug therapy", "Treat all three with metronidazole alone and no drainage", "Resect all three primarily without medical therapy", "Give antibiotics only to the amebic abscess; observe the other two"], 0, "Pyogenic abscess (most common in the US) is treated with broad-spectrum antibiotics, draining lesions >5 cm. Amebic abscess responds to metronidazole and does not require aspiration. Echinococcal (hydatid) cysts must NOT be simply aspirated/punctured (spillage causes anaphylaxis); treat with a scolicidal agent (albendazole) plus the PAIR technique, then resection.\n\nWhy not — Aspirate all three for diagnosis before any drug therapy: Aspirating an echinococcal cyst risks anaphylaxis; routine aspiration of all three is wrong.  Treat all three with metronidazole alone and no drainage: Pyogenic and echinococcal disease are not cured by metronidazole alone.  Resect all three primarily without medical therapy: Medical therapy is central to amebic and echinococcal disease; primary resection of all is wrong.  Give antibiotics only to the amebic abscess; observe the other two: Pyogenic and echinococcal lesions also need directed therapy, not observation.", "basic"]]], [15, "Evaluate a pancreatic mass (solid vs cystic; rule out malignancy)", [["Sharieff contrasts solid and cystic pancreatic lesions. Which statement reflects the correct general rule?", ["Every solid pancreatic lesion is treated as malignant; a cystic lesion requires ruling out cancer", "Every cystic pancreatic lesion is treated as malignant; solid lesions are usually benign", "Both solid and cystic pancreatic lesions are presumed benign until biopsy proves otherwise", "Solid lesions are managed expectantly; cystic lesions are always resected", "Metastasis is the most common solid pancreatic lesion, as it is in the liver"], 0, "The core pancreatic-mass rule: all SOLID lesions are considered malignant and treated as such, whereas a CYSTIC lesion obligates you to rule out cancer (pseudocyst/serous vs mucinous). Unlike the liver, metastasis to the pancreas is rare; PDAC is the dominant solid lesion.\n\nWhy not — Every cystic pancreatic lesion is treated as malignant; solid lesions are usually benign: Solid (not cystic) lesions are the ones treated as malignant by default.  Both solid and cystic pancreatic lesions are presumed benign until biopsy proves otherwise: Solid lesions are presumed malignant, not benign-until-biopsy.  Solid lesions are managed expectantly; cystic lesions are always resected: Solid lesions are resected, not watched; cysts are individualized by fluid.  Metastasis is the most common solid pancreatic lesion, as it is in the liver: Metastasis to the pancreas is rare — that 'mets is #1' rule applies to the liver, not the pancreas.", "basic"], ["Regarding biopsy in the workup of a pancreatic mass, which approach does Sharieff endorse?", ["Avoid biopsy in general; reserve EUS-guided sampling for select cases, since percutaneous biopsy risks acute pancreatitis and delays care", "Routine percutaneous core biopsy of every pancreatic mass before treatment", "Open surgical biopsy of all solid lesions to obtain a tissue diagnosis", "Biopsy every cyst to exclude pseudocyst", "Always biopsy because imaging and tumor markers cannot guide management"], 0, "As in the liver, biopsy is generally avoided for pancreatic lesions. The main indication for sampling is an indeterminate cystic lesion, and then via endoscopic ultrasound (EUS-FNA) with a clear reason; percutaneous biopsy can trigger acute pancreatitis and delays definitive management.\n\nWhy not — Routine percutaneous core biopsy of every pancreatic mass before treatment: Routine percutaneous biopsy is exactly what is avoided.  Open surgical biopsy of all solid lesions to obtain a tissue diagnosis: Open biopsy of all solids is unnecessary and morbid.  Biopsy every cyst to exclude pseudocyst: Cysts are not all biopsied; EUS-FNA is selective.  Always biopsy because imaging and tumor markers cannot guide management: Imaging plus CA 19-9 usually does guide management without tissue.", "basic"]]], [16, "Manage pancreatic cystic lesions (pseudocyst, MCN, IPMN)", [["A heavy drinker with recent acute pancreatitis has a 7 cm unilocular cystic mass and no fever. What is the best initial management?", ["Expectant management — pain control, nutritional support, and treat the pancreatitis; most pseudocysts resolve", "Immediate broad-spectrum antibiotics for the infected pseudocyst", "Urgent surgical resection of the cyst", "Endoscopic cystgastrostomy drainage within 24 hours", "Whipple procedure given the malignant potential"], 0, "In the setting of acute pancreatitis and alcohol use, a simple cystic collection is a pseudocyst. Pseudocysts are usually sterile (no antibiotics) and most resolve spontaneously, so initial care is expectant: pain control, nutrition, and treating the pancreatitis, sometimes waiting beyond 3-6 months. Drainage is reserved for persistence or complications (necrosis, hemorrhage, infection, rupture).\n\nWhy not — Immediate broad-spectrum antibiotics for the infected pseudocyst: Pseudocysts are usually sterile; antibiotics are not given empirically.  Urgent surgical resection of the cyst: Resection is not first-line for an uncomplicated pseudocyst.  Endoscopic cystgastrostomy drainage within 24 hours: Drainage is reserved for failure of conservative care or complications.  Whipple procedure given the malignant potential: A Whipple is for resectable head cancers, not a pseudocyst.", "advanced"]]], [17, "Manage pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma and pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors", [["Which malignancy is the most common pancreatic cancer, carries the worst prognosis, and is projected to become the second-leading cause of cancer death by 2030?", ["Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC)", "Insulinoma", "Mucinous cystic neoplasm (MCN)", "Pancreatic serous cystadenoma", "Metastatic colorectal carcinoma to the pancreas"], 0, "Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma is the most common pancreatic cancer, usually in the head, with a 5-year survival under 10% and a projection to become the second-leading cause of cancer death by 2030 because most are unresectable at diagnosis.\n\nWhy not — Insulinoma: Insulinoma is a rare functional neuroendocrine tumor, not the dominant pancreatic cancer.  Mucinous cystic neoplasm (MCN): MCN is a cystic neoplasm with intermediate malignant risk, not the most common cancer.  Pancreatic serous cystadenoma: Serous cystadenoma is benign.  Metastatic colorectal carcinoma to the pancreas: Metastasis to the pancreas is rare, the opposite of the liver.", "basic"], ["A patient presents with documented hypoglycemia, neuroglycopenic symptoms, and prompt relief of symptoms after glucose administration (Whipple's triad). This is most consistent with which pancreatic tumor?", ["Insulinoma", "Gastrinoma", "Glucagonoma", "Somatostatinoma", "Nonfunctional pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor"], 0, "Whipple's triad - symptomatic hypoglycemia, low measured glucose, and relief with glucose - is the classic presentation of an insulinoma, an insulin-secreting functional pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor. On the exam, Whipple's triad points to insulinoma.\n\nWhy not — Gastrinoma: Gastrinoma causes refractory peptic ulcers (Zollinger-Ellison), not hypoglycemia.  Glucagonoma: Glucagonoma causes hyperglycemia and necrolytic migratory erythema.  Somatostatinoma: Somatostatinoma causes diabetes, gallstones, and steatorrhea.  Nonfunctional pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor: A nonfunctional PNET would not produce the hypoglycemia of Whipple's triad.", "advanced"]]], [18, "Manage chronic pancreatitis", []]]], [47, "Pathology of Jaundice (Lec 47)", [[1, "Discuss the pathophysiology of jaundice", [["In bilirubin metabolism, which enzyme converts biliverdin into unconjugated bilirubin?", ["Biliverdin reductase", "Heme oxygenase", "UGT1A1 (UDP-glucuronosyltransferase 1A1)", "Beta-glucuronidase", "Glutathione-S-transferase"], 0, "Heme oxygenase first opens the heme ring to biliverdin; biliverdin reductase then reduces biliverdin to unconjugated (water-insoluble) bilirubin, which travels bound to albumin. UGT1A1 acts later, inside the hepatocyte, to conjugate it.\n\nWhy not — Heme oxygenase: Heme oxygenase acts one step earlier, converting heme to biliverdin, not biliverdin to bilirubin.  UGT1A1 (UDP-glucuronosyltransferase 1A1): UGT1A1 conjugates bilirubin inside the hepatocyte; it does not make UCB from biliverdin.  Beta-glucuronidase: Beta-glucuronidase deconjugates bilirubin in the gut lumen; it is not in this synthesis step.  Glutathione-S-transferase: Glutathione-S-transferase binds UCB within the hepatocyte; it does not reduce biliverdin.", "basic"], ["Within the hepatocyte, which transporter normally pumps conjugated bilirubin across the canalicular membrane into bile?", ["MRP2", "MRP3", "OATP-1B1", "Albumin", "UGT1A1"], 0, "After UGT1A1 conjugates bilirubin, MRP2 (the ABCC2 product) exports conjugated bilirubin across the apical/canalicular membrane into the bile. MRP3 and OATP-1B1/1B3 sit on the basolateral (sinusoidal) membrane and move conjugated bilirubin to and from blood.\n\nWhy not — MRP3: MRP3 is basolateral and exports CB into blood, not across the canalicular membrane into bile.  OATP-1B1: OATP-1B1 is a basolateral re-uptake transporter, not the canalicular efflux pump.  Albumin: Albumin ferries unconjugated bilirubin in blood; it is not a canalicular transporter.  UGT1A1: UGT1A1 conjugates bilirubin; it does not transport it into the canaliculus.", "basic"], ["Which property correctly describes unconjugated bilirubin (UCB)?", ["Water-insoluble, albumin-bound, and not excreted in urine", "Water-soluble, loosely bound, and readily excreted in urine", "Non-toxic and unable to cross the blood-brain barrier", "Produced only after UGT1A1 adds glucuronic acid", "Pumped directly into bile by the MRP2 transporter"], 0, "Unconjugated bilirubin is water-insoluble, so it circulates bound to albumin and is NOT excreted in urine; it is lipid-soluble and toxic (can reach the basal ganglia). Conjugated bilirubin is the water-soluble, urine-excreted, MRP2-pumped form.\n\nWhy not — Water-soluble, loosely bound, and readily excreted in urine: Water-soluble and urine-excreted describes conjugated, not unconjugated, bilirubin.  Non-toxic and unable to cross the blood-brain barrier: UCB is lipid-soluble and toxic and can cross into the brain (kernicterus).  Produced only after UGT1A1 adds glucuronic acid: Glucuronidation by UGT1A1 produces conjugated bilirubin, not the unconjugated form.  Pumped directly into bile by the MRP2 transporter: MRP2 pumps conjugated bilirubin into bile; UCB is not its substrate.", "basic"], ["A patient's serum total bilirubin is 3.5 mg/dL. Based on the lecture's thresholds, this value is most likely to produce visible:", ["Scleral icterus, but not yet yellowing of the skin", "Yellowing of the skin, but not scleral icterus", "Neither scleral icterus nor skin yellowing", "Kernicterus from basal-ganglia bilirubin deposition", "Dark urine from conjugated bilirubin spilling over"], 0, "Scleral icterus appears once serum bilirubin exceeds about 2-3 mg/dL, while yellowing of the skin requires higher levels above about 4-5 mg/dL; at 3.5 mg/dL the sclerae are yellow but the skin is typically not yet discolored.\n\nWhy not — Yellowing of the skin, but not scleral icterus: Skin yellowing needs a higher level (> 4-5 mg/dL); the sclera yellows first.  Neither scleral icterus nor skin yellowing: 3.5 mg/dL is above the > 2-3 mg/dL scleral-icterus threshold, so the sclerae are yellow.  Kernicterus from basal-ganglia bilirubin deposition: Kernicterus is a basal-ganglia injury of high UNCONJUGATED loads in neonates, not a visible threshold here.  Dark urine from conjugated bilirubin spilling over: Whether urine darkens depends on conjugated bilirubin, not on this total-bilirubin threshold.", "advanced"], ["A neonate develops jaundice on day 3 of life that resolves over the next two weeks. The mechanism is that newborn UGT1A1 activity is:", ["About 1% of adult activity, rising to adult levels by ~2 weeks", "Completely and permanently absent from birth", "Normal, but overwhelmed by a defective MRP2 pump", "Elevated, causing excess conjugation of bilirubin", "Blocked by maternal antibodies against the enzyme"], 0, "Physiologic neonatal jaundice reflects an immature conjugating system: newborn UGT activity is only about 1% of adult levels and rises to adult levels roughly 2 weeks after birth, so the transient unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia resolves spontaneously (or with phototherapy).\n\nWhy not — Completely and permanently absent from birth: A permanent near-absence of UGT1A1 is Crigler-Najjar type I, not transient physiologic jaundice.  Normal, but overwhelmed by a defective MRP2 pump: Physiologic neonatal jaundice is a conjugation problem (UGT), not an MRP2 transport defect.  Elevated, causing excess conjugation of bilirubin: UGT activity is low, not elevated, in the newborn.  Blocked by maternal antibodies against the enzyme: The cause is enzyme immaturity, not maternal anti-enzyme antibodies.", "advanced"], ["Kernicterus, the dreaded outcome of severe neonatal unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia, results from bilirubin deposition in the:", ["Basal ganglia", "Sclera and skin", "Renal tubules", "Bile canaliculi", "Splenic red pulp"], 0, "Because unconjugated bilirubin is lipid-soluble, very high levels cross the blood-brain barrier and collect in the basal ganglia, producing kernicterus, an irreversible brain injury that can be fatal in the newborn.\n\nWhy not — Sclera and skin: Sclera and skin yellowing is jaundice/icterus, not the brain injury of kernicterus.  Renal tubules: Renal tubular deposition is not the mechanism of kernicterus.  Bile canaliculi: Canalicular pathology relates to cholestasis, not basal-ganglia kernicterus.  Splenic red pulp: The spleen is where bilirubin is produced, not where kernicterus occurs.", "basic"], ["Gilbert syndrome, the most common hereditary hyperbilirubinemia (prevalence 3-7%), most often arises from:", ["An extra TA in the UGT1A1 promoter TATA-box (A[TA]7TAA), reducing enzyme expression", "A complete coding deletion abolishing all UGT1A1 activity", "An inactivating mutation in the ABCC2/MRP2 transporter", "Loss of the SLCO1B1/SLCO1B3 (OATP) re-uptake transporters", "A defect in the ABCB4/MDR3 phospholipid translocator"], 0, "Most Gilbert cases are homozygous for an extra TA dinucleotide inserted in the TATA-box of the UGT1A1 promoter (A[TA]7TAA instead of A[TA]6TAA, the UGT1A1*28 allele), which lowers transcription to roughly 10-35% of normal and produces mild, benign unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia.\n\nWhy not — A complete coding deletion abolishing all UGT1A1 activity: A complete loss of UGT1A1 activity describes Crigler-Najjar type I, not benign Gilbert.  An inactivating mutation in the ABCC2/MRP2 transporter: ABCC2/MRP2 is the Dubin-Johnson efflux defect, not the Gilbert promoter change.  Loss of the SLCO1B1/SLCO1B3 (OATP) re-uptake transporters: SLCO1B1/1B3 (OATP) loss is the Rotor re-uptake defect, not Gilbert.  A defect in the ABCB4/MDR3 phospholipid translocator: ABCB4/MDR3 is the intrahepatic-cholestasis-of-pregnancy defect, not Gilbert.", "basic"], ["Crigler-Najjar type I is distinguished from type II by the fact that type I shows:", ["Near-complete absence of UGT1A1 with kernicterus and fatal early course", "Partial UGT1A1 activity with a mild, benign clinical course", "A conjugated rather than unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia", "A defective canalicular MRP2 export transporter", "A black liver with melanin-like centrilobular granules"], 0, "Both Crigler-Najjar types are autosomal-recessive coding-region UGT1A1 mutations, but type I has near-complete absence of the enzyme, giving severe unconjugated jaundice, kernicterus, and a course fatal around birth; type II retains partial activity and is milder, with kernicterus uncommon.\n\nWhy not — Partial UGT1A1 activity with a mild, benign clinical course: Partial activity and a benign course describe type II, not type I.  A conjugated rather than unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia: Both Crigler-Najjar types are unconjugated, not conjugated, disorders.  A defective canalicular MRP2 export transporter: An MRP2 export defect describes Dubin-Johnson, not Crigler-Najjar I.  A black liver with melanin-like centrilobular granules: The black liver with granules is Dubin-Johnson, not Crigler-Najjar.", "basic"], ["A patient has a chronic CONJUGATED hyperbilirubinemia with a grossly black liver and dark-brown granular pigment in centrilobular hepatocytes. The defective protein is:", ["MRP2 (the ABCC2 canalicular efflux transporter)", "OATP-1B1/1B3 (the SLCO1B1/1B3 re-uptake transporters)", "UGT1A1 (the bilirubin-conjugating enzyme)", "MDR3 (the ABCB4 phospholipid translocator)", "Heme oxygenase (the heme-ring-opening enzyme)"], 0, "A black liver with dark-brown melanin-like granules and conjugated hyperbilirubinemia is Dubin-Johnson syndrome, caused by an ABCC2 mutation that makes a non-functional MRP2 canalicular efflux transporter; conjugated bilirubin then backs up and is shunted to blood via MRP3.\n\nWhy not — OATP-1B1/1B3 (the SLCO1B1/1B3 re-uptake transporters): OATP-1B1/1B3 loss is Rotor syndrome, which has NO liver pigmentation.  UGT1A1 (the bilirubin-conjugating enzyme): UGT1A1 defects give unconjugated disorders (Gilbert, Crigler-Najjar), not a black liver.  MDR3 (the ABCB4 phospholipid translocator): MDR3/ABCB4 is the cholestasis-of-pregnancy defect, not the Dubin-Johnson pump.  Heme oxygenase (the heme-ring-opening enzyme): Heme oxygenase is a synthesis enzyme, unrelated to this conjugated transport defect.", "advanced"], ["Two siblings each have a benign chronic CONJUGATED hyperbilirubinemia. Sibling A has a black liver; sibling B has a normally pigmented liver. The transporter defects in A and B, respectively, are:", ["MRP2 canalicular efflux (Dubin-Johnson) and OATP-1B1/1B3 re-uptake (Rotor)", "OATP-1B1/1B3 re-uptake (Rotor) and MRP2 canalicular efflux (Dubin-Johnson)", "UGT1A1 conjugation (Gilbert) and MRP2 canalicular efflux (Dubin-Johnson)", "MDR3 phospholipid translocation (ICP) and UGT1A1 conjugation (Gilbert)", "Heme oxygenase (production) and biliverdin reductase (production)"], 0, "Both Dubin-Johnson and Rotor are benign conjugated hyperbilirubinemias, but Dubin-Johnson (defective ABCC2/MRP2 canalicular efflux) produces the black liver, whereas Rotor (defective SLCO1B1/1B3 -> OATP-1B1/1B3 re-uptake) has NO pigmentation; the presence or absence of black pigment is the clean discriminator.\n\nWhy not — OATP-1B1/1B3 re-uptake (Rotor) and MRP2 canalicular efflux (Dubin-Johnson): This reverses the pairing; the black liver is Dubin-Johnson (MRP2), not Rotor.  UGT1A1 conjugation (Gilbert) and MRP2 canalicular efflux (Dubin-Johnson): Gilbert is an unconjugated UGT1A1 disorder, not one of these conjugated transport defects.  MDR3 phospholipid translocation (ICP) and UGT1A1 conjugation (Gilbert): MDR3/ICP and Gilbert are not the benign conjugated transport pair in question.  Heme oxygenase (production) and biliverdin reductase (production): Heme oxygenase and biliverdin reductase are production enzymes, not transport defects.", "basic"]]], [2, "Discuss the pathophysiology of cholestasis", [["Cholestasis is best defined as a condition in which:", ["Bile flow is markedly reduced or stopped, from impaired secretion or obstruction", "Red blood cells are destroyed faster than bilirubin can be conjugated", "Unconjugated bilirubin collects in the basal ganglia of the brain", "Hepatocytes fail to take up bilirubin from the sinusoidal blood", "The UGT1A1 enzyme cannot conjugate bilirubin with glucuronic acid"], 0, "Cholestasis is reduced or stopped bile flow, caused either by impaired hepatocyte secretion of bile or by obstruction anywhere from the liver to the Ampulla of Vater; it is classified into intrahepatic and extrahepatic forms.\n\nWhy not — Red blood cells are destroyed faster than bilirubin can be conjugated: Accelerated hemolysis is a cause of increased-production jaundice, not the definition of cholestasis.  Unconjugated bilirubin collects in the basal ganglia of the brain: Basal-ganglia bilirubin is kernicterus, not cholestasis.  Hepatocytes fail to take up bilirubin from the sinusoidal blood: Failed hepatic uptake is one cause of unconjugated jaundice, not the cholestasis definition.  The UGT1A1 enzyme cannot conjugate bilirubin with glucuronic acid: A UGT1A1 conjugation defect is impaired-conjugation jaundice, not cholestasis.", "basic"], ["Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy (ICP) is caused by mutation in which gene/protein?", ["ABCB4, encoding the MDR3 canalicular phospholipid translocator", "ABCC2, encoding the MRP2 canalicular efflux transporter", "UGT1A1, encoding the bilirubin-conjugating enzyme", "SLCO1B1, encoding the OATP-1B1 re-uptake transporter", "ATP7B, encoding the hepatic copper transporter"], 0, "Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy is linked to ABCB4 mutations encoding MDR3, a canalicular phospholipid translocator; without available phospholipids to bind bile acids, toxic bile acids build up, producing the third-trimester pruritus and centrilobular cholestasis.\n\nWhy not — ABCC2, encoding the MRP2 canalicular efflux transporter: ABCC2/MRP2 is the Dubin-Johnson defect, not the ICP gene.  UGT1A1, encoding the bilirubin-conjugating enzyme: UGT1A1 underlies the unconjugated syndromes (Gilbert, Crigler-Najjar), not ICP.  SLCO1B1, encoding the OATP-1B1 re-uptake transporter: SLCO1B1/OATP-1B1 is the Rotor re-uptake defect, not ICP.  ATP7B, encoding the hepatic copper transporter: ATP7B is the Wilson-disease copper transporter, unrelated to ICP.", "basic"], ["A pregnant woman in her third trimester reports intense itching that is worst on the palms and soles, with very high serum total bile acids; it resolves after delivery. The diagnosis is:", ["Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy", "Dubin-Johnson syndrome", "Primary sclerosing cholangitis", "Extrahepatic gallstone obstruction", "Physiologic hyperbilirubinemia of pregnancy"], 0, "Third-trimester intense pruritus worst on the palms and soles, confirmed by very high total bile acids and resolving after delivery, is the classic presentation of intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy; it matters because it raises fetal morbidity and mortality.\n\nWhy not — Dubin-Johnson syndrome: Dubin-Johnson is a chronic conjugated hyperbilirubinemia with a black liver, not pregnancy pruritus.  Primary sclerosing cholangitis: PSC is a chronic bile-duct disease, not a trimester-limited, delivery-reversible pruritus.  Extrahepatic gallstone obstruction: Gallstone obstruction is anatomic and does not resolve simply with delivery.  Physiologic hyperbilirubinemia of pregnancy: There is no benign 'physiologic' pregnancy hyperbilirubinemia that fits this bile-acid picture.", "advanced"], ["Among the proposed mechanisms of cholestasis, which agents inhibit the canalicular export transporters, causing back-diffusion of bile components into blood?", ["Estrogens", "Heme oxygenase", "Biliverdin reductase", "Beta-glucuronidase", "Albumin"], 0, "In the canalicular-transporter mechanism, agents such as estrogens inhibit the canalicular export pump, so cholic acid, cholesterol, and conjugated bilirubin back-diffuse into blood; this is distinct from the contractility (RhoA/Rho-kinase) and membrane (Na+/K+-ATPase) mechanisms.\n\nWhy not — Heme oxygenase: Heme oxygenase is a bilirubin-production enzyme, not a transporter inhibitor.  Biliverdin reductase: Biliverdin reductase is a synthesis enzyme, unrelated to canalicular export.  Beta-glucuronidase: Beta-glucuronidase deconjugates bilirubin in the gut, not a cholestasis transporter mechanism.  Albumin: Albumin ferries UCB in blood; it does not inhibit canalicular transporters.", "basic"], ["Trace one proposed cholestasis mechanism. Constrictor drugs (e.g., chlorpromazine, cyclosporin A) activate RhoA/Rho-kinase, which next leads to:", ["Increased myosin light-chain phosphorylation and constriction of bile canaliculi", "Decreased Na+/K+-ATPase activity at the canalicular plasma membrane", "Direct inhibition of the canalicular bile-acid export pump", "Failure of UGT1A1 to conjugate bilirubin with glucuronic acid", "Loss of OATP-mediated re-uptake of conjugated bilirubin"], 0, "In the altered-contractility mechanism, constrictors activate the RhoA/Rho-kinase pathway, which increases myosin light-chain phosphorylation and constricts the bile canaliculi, impairing the peristaltic propulsion of bile; the Na+/K+-ATPase and export-pump effects are separate mechanisms.\n\nWhy not — Decreased Na+/K+-ATPase activity at the canalicular plasma membrane: Decreased Na+/K+-ATPase is the separate canalicular-membrane-damage mechanism.  Direct inhibition of the canalicular bile-acid export pump: Export-pump inhibition is the separate transporter mechanism (e.g., estrogens).  Failure of UGT1A1 to conjugate bilirubin with glucuronic acid: Failed conjugation is a jaundice mechanism, not the RhoA/Rho-kinase contractility step.  Loss of OATP-mediated re-uptake of conjugated bilirubin: Loss of OATP re-uptake is the Rotor defect, not the RhoA/Rho-kinase pathway.", "basic"]]], [3, "Discuss the etiological factors, morphologic changes and effects of jaundice", [["The characteristic histologic finding of cholestasis seen in BOTH obstructive and non-obstructive disease is enlarged, foamy hepatocytes laden with bile-pigment droplets, called:", ["Feathery degeneration", "Mallory-Denk bodies", "Councilman bodies", "Ground-glass change", "Ballooning degeneration"], 0, "Feathery degeneration - enlarged hepatocytes with intracytoplasmic bile-pigment droplets giving a foamy appearance - is the hallmark cholestasis finding in both obstructive and non-obstructive disease, accompanied by bile plugs in dilated canaliculi and apoptotic hepatocytes.\n\nWhy not — Mallory-Denk bodies: Mallory-Denk bodies are ropy cytokeratin aggregates of alcoholic steatohepatitis, not cholestasis.  Councilman bodies: Councilman bodies are apoptotic hepatocytes of viral hepatitis, not the foamy cholestatic change.  Ground-glass change: Ground-glass cytoplasm reflects hepatitis B surface antigen, not bile-pigment droplets.  Ballooning degeneration: Ballooning degeneration is hydropic swelling without the bile-pigment, foamy character.", "basic"], ["Which morphologic feature is more characteristic of EXTRAHEPATIC (obstructive) cholestasis than of intrahepatic cholestasis?", ["Ductular proliferative reaction with bile lakes and periportal fibrosis", "Isolated feathery degeneration with no ductular change", "Basal-ganglia bilirubin deposition", "A grossly black, melanin-pigmented liver", "Two-cell-thick regenerative nodules"], 0, "Extrahepatic (obstructive) cholestasis adds a ductular proliferative reaction at the portal-parenchymal interface, with edema and periductular neutrophils; prolonged obstruction produces bile lakes (ruptured ductules) surrounded by necrotic hepatocytes and eventually periportal fibrosis and cirrhosis.\n\nWhy not — Isolated feathery degeneration with no ductular change: Feathery degeneration occurs in both forms; it does not distinguish extrahepatic disease.  Basal-ganglia bilirubin deposition: Basal-ganglia bilirubin is kernicterus, not a cholestasis morphology feature.  A grossly black, melanin-pigmented liver: A black liver is Dubin-Johnson, not extrahepatic obstructive cholestasis.  Two-cell-thick regenerative nodules: Regenerative nodules are a cirrhosis feature, not the obstructive ductular reaction asked about.", "basic"], ["In the most common cause of biliary obstruction in adults, the obstructing lesion is:", ["A gallstone lodged in the common bile duct", "Congenital extrahepatic biliary atresia", "Cystic fibrosis inspissated secretions", "An enlarged porta hepatis lymph node", "A benign postoperative stricture"], 0, "In adults, the most common cause of biliary obstruction is a gallstone lodged in the common bile duct (extrahepatic choledocholithiasis); biliary atresia and cystic fibrosis are the leading causes in infants and children, and nodes/strictures are less common adult causes.\n\nWhy not — Congenital extrahepatic biliary atresia: Biliary atresia is a leading cause in infants and children, not the adult #1.  Cystic fibrosis inspissated secretions: Cystic fibrosis is an infant/child cause, not the most common adult obstruction.  An enlarged porta hepatis lymph node: Enlarged porta hepatis nodes are a less common adult cause, not the leader.  A benign postoperative stricture: Benign postoperative strictures occur but are not the single most common adult cause.", "basic"], ["Which laboratory pattern is characteristic of cholestasis?", ["Elevated alkaline phosphatase (ALP) and elevated GGT", "Elevated unconjugated bilirubin with a normal ALP", "A low alkaline phosphatase with a high albumin", "An isolated rise in lactate dehydrogenase", "A markedly inverted urinary coproporphyrin ratio"], 0, "Cholestasis characteristically elevates alkaline phosphatase (released by the detergent action of retained bile salts on hepatocyte membranes) together with elevated GGT; the GGT rise helps confirm a hepatobiliary, rather than bony, source of the ALP.\n\nWhy not — Elevated unconjugated bilirubin with a normal ALP: Isolated unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia with normal ALP is a pre-hepatic/hemolytic pattern, not cholestasis.  A low alkaline phosphatase with a high albumin: Cholestasis raises ALP; a low ALP is not its signature.  An isolated rise in lactate dehydrogenase: An isolated LDH rise is nonspecific and not the cholestatic pattern.  A markedly inverted urinary coproporphyrin ratio: An inverted coproporphyrin ratio is Dubin-Johnson, not the general cholestasis lab pattern.", "basic"], ["A patient with chronic cholestasis has jaundice, pruritus, skin xanthomas, pale stools, and steatorrhea. Integrate these findings: the pale stools and steatorrhea are explained by:", ["Bile salts failing to reach the small intestine, impairing fat absorption and stool pigmentation", "Overproduction of conjugated bilirubin spilling into the colon", "Excess bile salt deposition within the skin's dermis", "Unconjugated bilirubin collecting in the basal ganglia", "Increased beta-glucuronidase activity in the gut lumen"], 0, "In cholestasis, bile (and its salts) cannot reach the small intestine, so dietary fat is malabsorbed (steatorrhea) and the stool loses bile-derived pigment (pale stools); the same retained bile salts in skin drive the pruritus, and dermal cholesterol gives the xanthomas.\n\nWhy not — Overproduction of conjugated bilirubin spilling into the colon: Pale stools reflect a LACK of intestinal bile pigment, not overproduction reaching the colon.  Excess bile salt deposition within the skin's dermis: Bile-salt deposition in skin explains pruritus, not the stool/fat findings.  Unconjugated bilirubin collecting in the basal ganglia: Basal-ganglia bilirubin is kernicterus, unrelated to stool color and steatorrhea.  Increased beta-glucuronidase activity in the gut lumen: Increased gut beta-glucuronidase recycles bilirubin; it does not cause pale, fatty stools.", "advanced"]]]]], [48, "Hepatic Function Tests (Lec 48)", [[1, "Define 'true' liver function tests.", [["The term 'liver function tests' is partly a misnomer because several of its components actually report liver INJURY, not function. Which group represents the TRUE function (synthetic/metabolic) markers?", ["Serum albumin, PT/INR, and serum bilirubin", "AST, ALT, and alkaline phosphatase", "AST, ALT, and GGT", "Alkaline phosphatase, GGT, and 5'-nucleotidase", "LDH, AST, and isocitrate dehydrogenase"], 0, "The slide boxes the enzymes (aminotransferases, alkaline phosphatase) as 'Liver Injury' and albumin/PT-INR/bilirubin as 'Liver Function' under the banner 'Health != Function.' The genuine function tests report what the liver makes (albumin, clotting factors) or processes (bilirubin).\n\nWhy not — AST, ALT, and alkaline phosphatase: AST, ALT, and alkaline phosphatase are enzymes that leak from injured cells - injury markers, not function.  AST, ALT, and GGT: AST, ALT, and GGT are all injury/enzyme markers, not synthetic function tests.  Alkaline phosphatase, GGT, and 5'-nucleotidase: These are all enzymes (and ALP/GGT/5'-NT are cholestasis markers), not function tests.  LDH, AST, and isocitrate dehydrogenase: LDH, AST, and isocitrate dehydrogenase are all injury enzymes, not synthetic markers.", "advanced"], ["On the 'true LFTs' slide, the banner 'Health does not equal Function' is meant to convey that:", ["A liver can be injured (leaking enzymes) yet still functioning, and a normal enzyme panel does not prove the liver is healthy", "Only patients with symptoms can have abnormal liver enzymes", "Liver enzymes and synthetic markers always rise and fall together", "Alkaline phosphatase is the single best test of liver function", "Bilirubin is purely an injury marker with no functional meaning"], 0, "The point of the dichotomy is that injury and function are different axes: an injured liver may still function, and (per the paradox) a badly diseased liver may show NORMAL enzymes - so health and function are not the same thing.\n\nWhy not — Only patients with symptoms can have abnormal liver enzymes: Abnormal enzymes are frequently found incidentally on a CMP in asymptomatic patients.  Liver enzymes and synthetic markers always rise and fall together: They often dissociate - the whole point of the slide - e.g., normal enzymes with failing function.  Alkaline phosphatase is the single best test of liver function: Alkaline phosphatase is a cholestasis/injury marker, not the best test of function.  Bilirubin is purely an injury marker with no functional meaning: Bilirubin reports BOTH injury and function; it is not purely an injury marker.", "basic"]]], [2, "Describe the functions of selected liver enzymes, such as aminotransferase and alkaline phosphatase.", [["Which statement about the cellular distribution of the aminotransferases is correct?", ["ALT is highest in the liver (more liver-specific), while AST is also abundant in cardiac and skeletal muscle and is the only one found in the mitochondrial matrix", "AST is most liver-specific, while ALT is found in many extrahepatic tissues", "Both ALT and AST are found only in hepatocytes", "ALT is the only aminotransferase found in the mitochondrial matrix", "Neither enzyme is present in the cytosol"], 0, "ALT is present in highest concentration in the liver, making it more liver-specific; AST is also in cardiac muscle, skeletal muscle, and other tissues. Both are cytosolic, but AST is uniquely also in the mitochondrial matrix.\n\nWhy not — AST is most liver-specific, while ALT is found in many extrahepatic tissues: ALT, not AST, is the more liver-specific enzyme.  Both ALT and AST are found only in hepatocytes: AST in particular is widely distributed (heart, muscle, kidney, RBCs, etc.).  ALT is the only aminotransferase found in the mitochondrial matrix: It is AST, not ALT, that is in the mitochondrial matrix.  Neither enzyme is present in the cytosol: Both are present in the cytosol.", "basic"], ["A clinician needs a test that is more SPECIFIC for hepatocellular injury (rather than muscle injury). Which enzyme best serves that purpose, and why?", ["ALT, because it is present in the highest concentration in the liver", "AST, because it is present in cardiac and skeletal muscle", "Alkaline phosphatase, because it is in the bile ducts", "LDH, because it reflects anaerobic metabolism", "GGT, because it is higher in infants"], 0, "ALT is concentrated in the liver and has little extrahepatic distribution, so it is more specific for liver pathology than AST, which is shared with muscle and other tissues.\n\nWhy not — AST, because it is present in cardiac and skeletal muscle: AST's muscle distribution makes it LESS specific for the liver.  Alkaline phosphatase, because it is in the bile ducts: Alkaline phosphatase marks cholestasis, not hepatocellular injury.  LDH, because it reflects anaerobic metabolism: LDH is nonspecific and reflects ischemia/anaerobic metabolism.  GGT, because it is higher in infants: GGT confirms hepatobiliary origin but is not the aminotransferase asked for here.", "advanced"], ["Alkaline phosphatase is most useful clinically for detecting which category of liver disease, and roughly how high does it run in that setting?", ["Cholestatic disease, often elevated about 4 times the upper limit", "Hepatocellular injury, often elevated about 25 times the upper limit", "Ischemic hepatitis, often elevated about 50 times the upper limit", "Isolated hyperbilirubinemia, with a normal alkaline phosphatase", "Acute liver failure, detected by a prolonged INR"], 0, "Alkaline phosphatase is a canalicular/biliary enzyme that detects cholestatic disease (impaired bile flow) and is often elevated about 4x the upper limit in cholestasis.\n\nWhy not — Hepatocellular injury, often elevated about 25 times the upper limit: Hepatocellular injury is signaled by aminotransferases, not by alkaline phosphatase.  Ischemic hepatitis, often elevated about 50 times the upper limit: Ischemic hepatitis is an aminotransferase (>50x) plus LDH picture, not an ALP one.  Isolated hyperbilirubinemia, with a normal alkaline phosphatase: Isolated hyperbilirubinemia has a NORMAL alkaline phosphatase by definition.  Acute liver failure, detected by a prolonged INR: Acute liver failure is declared by INR/PT, not by alkaline phosphatase.", "basic"], ["The chief value of GGT and 5'-nucleotidase in interpreting an elevated alkaline phosphatase is to:", ["Confirm a hepatobiliary (liver) source, because neither is affected by bone disease", "Confirm a bony source, because both rise with osteomalacia and Paget disease", "Measure the liver's synthetic (clotting) capacity", "Replace the aminotransferases for hepatocellular injury", "Detect ischemia through anaerobic metabolism"], 0, "Alkaline phosphatase comes from liver, bone, and other sources; GGT and 5'-nucleotidase are not affected by bone disease, so a co-elevation confirms the alkaline phosphatase is of hepatobiliary origin.\n\nWhy not — Confirm a bony source, because both rise with osteomalacia and Paget disease: Both are NOT affected by bone disease - that is exactly why they isolate a liver source.  Measure the liver's synthetic (clotting) capacity: Synthetic capacity is measured by albumin and PT/INR, not GGT/5'-NT.  Replace the aminotransferases for hepatocellular injury: They do not replace aminotransferases; they clarify the source of a high ALP.  Detect ischemia through anaerobic metabolism: LDH, not GGT/5'-NT, is the ischemia marker.", "basic"], ["A pregnant patient has right-upper-quadrant pain and an elevated alkaline phosphatase, and you must decide whether it is hepatobiliary or simply from pregnancy. Which confirmatory enzyme is preferred, and why?", ["GGT, because 5'-nucleotidase's behavior in pregnancy is uncertain", "5'-nucleotidase, because it is reliably unaffected by pregnancy", "Either GGT or 5'-nucleotidase, because both are unaffected by pregnancy", "Aminotransferases, because they rise specifically with cholestasis", "LDH, because it confirms biliary obstruction"], 0, "Both GGT and 5'-nucleotidase are unaffected by bone disease, but whether 5'-nucleotidase is altered by pregnancy is unknown; GGT is the better confirmatory test in a pregnant patient. (For bone disease, either works.)\n\nWhy not — 5'-nucleotidase, because it is reliably unaffected by pregnancy: 5'-nucleotidase's effect in pregnancy is uncertain, so it is not preferred here.  Either GGT or 5'-nucleotidase, because both are unaffected by pregnancy: Pregnancy is exactly the setting where they differ - 5'-NT is uncertain, GGT is preferred.  Aminotransferases, because they rise specifically with cholestasis: Aminotransferases mark hepatocellular injury, not cholestasis source.  LDH, because it confirms biliary obstruction: LDH marks ischemia, not biliary origin of an elevated ALP.", "advanced"], ["A patient with bone disease (a known osteosarcoma) has an elevated alkaline phosphatase, and you want to know whether the liver is also involved. Which test(s) can confirm a hepatobiliary contribution?", ["Either GGT or 5'-nucleotidase, since neither is affected by bone disease", "Only GGT, since 5'-nucleotidase rises with bony tumors", "Only 5'-nucleotidase, since GGT rises with bony tumors", "Alkaline phosphatase repeated after a fatty meal", "Aminotransferases, since they distinguish bone from liver"], 0, "Because neither GGT nor 5'-nucleotidase is affected by bone disease, in a patient with a bony tumor either one can be used to confirm that an elevated alkaline phosphatase has a hepatobiliary source.\n\nWhy not — Only GGT, since 5'-nucleotidase rises with bony tumors: 5'-nucleotidase is also unaffected by bone disease, so GGT is not the only option.  Only 5'-nucleotidase, since GGT rises with bony tumors: GGT is also unaffected by bone disease, so 5'-nucleotidase is not the only option.  Alkaline phosphatase repeated after a fatty meal: Repeating ALP after a fatty meal does not localize the source to the liver.  Aminotransferases, since they distinguish bone from liver: Aminotransferases mark hepatocellular injury; they do not localize an ALP source.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Describe diseases associated with the elevation of liver enzymes.", [["Which of the following is a recognized cause of aminotransferase (AST/ALT) elevation listed in this lecture?", ["Acetaminophen toxicity", "Iron-deficiency anemia", "Hypothyroidism alone", "Simple dehydration", "Allergic rhinitis"], 0, "The slide lists acetaminophen toxicity, alcoholic hepatitis, MASH, ischemic hepatitis, acute viral hepatitis (including EBV/CMV), autoimmune hepatitis, malignancy, pre-eclampsia/eclampsia, and muscular disorders as causes of aminotransferase elevation.\n\nWhy not — Iron-deficiency anemia: Iron-deficiency anemia is not a listed cause of aminotransferase elevation.  Hypothyroidism alone: Hypothyroidism alone is not on the lecture's list of aminotransferase elevators.  Simple dehydration: Simple dehydration does not elevate aminotransferases.  Allergic rhinitis: Allergic rhinitis has no effect on liver enzymes.", "basic"], ["A 19-year-old with infectious mononucleosis has mildly elevated AST and ALT. The most likely explanation, consistent with this lecture, is:", ["Acute viral hepatitis from Epstein-Barr virus involving the liver", "Alcoholic liver disease with an AST:ALT ratio over 2:1", "Ischemic hepatitis with an LDH over 50 times normal", "Isolated hyperbilirubinemia from a congenital enzyme defect", "Cholestasis from a common-bile-duct stone"], 0, "The lecture explicitly notes that viruses beyond A-E - including Epstein-Barr virus (the cause of mononucleosis) and CMV - can cause acute viral hepatitis and elevate aminotransferases.\n\nWhy not — Alcoholic liver disease with an AST:ALT ratio over 2:1: Nothing in the vignette points to alcohol or a 2:1 ratio.  Ischemic hepatitis with an LDH over 50 times normal: There is no ischemia or massive LDH elevation described.  Isolated hyperbilirubinemia from a congenital enzyme defect: Isolated hyperbilirubinemia spares the aminotransferases, which are elevated here.  Cholestasis from a common-bile-duct stone: A duct stone would give a cholestatic (alkaline-phosphatase) picture, not this.", "advanced"], ["An alcohol-use-disorder patient has AST roughly twice the ALT and a markedly elevated GGT. This enzyme pattern is most consistent with:", ["Alcoholic liver disease (AST:ALT >= 2:1, often with high GGT)", "Metabolic dysfunction-associated steatohepatitis (MASH)", "Acute viral hepatitis", "Ischemic hepatitis", "Isolated hyperbilirubinemia"], 0, "An AST:ALT ratio of at least 2:1, frequently accompanied by a markedly elevated GGT, is the lecture's flagged board pattern for alcoholic liver disease.\n\nWhy not — Metabolic dysfunction-associated steatohepatitis (MASH): MASH typically shows ALT >= AST and only a mild (<5x) elevation.  Acute viral hepatitis: Acute viral hepatitis drives very high transaminases (>25x), not a 2:1 ratio.  Ischemic hepatitis: Ischemic hepatitis gives >50x transaminases plus high LDH, not a 2:1 ratio.  Isolated hyperbilirubinemia: Isolated hyperbilirubinemia leaves the aminotransferases normal.", "advanced"], ["Using a representative aminotransferase upper limit of 50 U/L, a patient with metabolic dysfunction-associated steatohepatitis (MASH/MASLD) would MOST likely show AST and ALT in which range?", ["Less than about 250 U/L (under 5 times the upper limit)", "About 1,250 U/L (over 25 times the upper limit)", "About 2,500 U/L (over 50 times the upper limit)", "Normal aminotransferases with an isolated bilirubin rise", "A markedly elevated alkaline phosphatase with normal aminotransferases"], 0, "MASH/MASLD is the mildest hepatocellular pattern, with AST and ALT less than 5x the upper limit (about <250 U/L if the upper limit is 50); >25x suggests acute viral/toxin and >50x with high LDH suggests ischemic hepatitis.\n\nWhy not — About 1,250 U/L (over 25 times the upper limit): About 1,250 (>25x) points to acute viral or toxin-related hepatitis, not MASH.  About 2,500 U/L (over 50 times the upper limit): About 2,500 (>50x) with LDH points to ischemic hepatitis, not MASH.  Normal aminotransferases with an isolated bilirubin rise: An isolated bilirubin rise is the isolated-hyperbilirubinemia pattern, not MASH.  A markedly elevated alkaline phosphatase with normal aminotransferases: A high ALP with normal aminotransferases is a cholestatic pattern, not MASH.", "advanced"], ["A patient is admitted in shock; AST and ALT exceed 50 times the upper limit and LDH is strikingly elevated. Which hepatocellular cause does this magnitude-plus-LDH pattern best identify, and what is the underlying mechanism?", ["Ischemic hepatitis - centrilobular hepatocyte death from inadequate perfusion, with LDH released from anaerobic/ischemic tissue", "MASH - fat-driven low-grade injury under 5 times the upper limit", "Alcoholic liver disease - an AST:ALT ratio just over 2:1 with mild elevations", "Cholestasis - bile-duct obstruction raising alkaline phosphatase", "Isolated hyperbilirubinemia - a congenital conjugation defect"], 0, "Aminotransferases >50x the upper limit together with an elevated LDH, in the setting of hypoperfusion/shock, define ischemic hepatitis ('the liver is dying'); LDH rises because the ischemic tissue shifts to anaerobic metabolism.\n\nWhy not — MASH - fat-driven low-grade injury under 5 times the upper limit: MASH is mild (<5x), not a >50x picture with high LDH.  Alcoholic liver disease - an AST:ALT ratio just over 2:1 with mild elevations: Alcoholic disease gives a 2:1 ratio with comparatively modest elevations, not >50x.  Cholestasis - bile-duct obstruction raising alkaline phosphatase: Cholestasis raises alkaline phosphatase, not aminotransferases to >50x.  Isolated hyperbilirubinemia - a congenital conjugation defect: Isolated hyperbilirubinemia leaves aminotransferases and LDH normal.", "advanced"], ["A toddler is found to have a transiently elevated alkaline phosphatase but normal GGT and normal aminotransferases. The best explanation is:", ["Active bone growth/remodeling, a benign source of alkaline phosphatase", "Early alcoholic liver disease", "Acute viral hepatitis", "Common-bile-duct obstruction", "Acute liver failure with coagulopathy"], 0, "Alkaline phosphatase comes from bone as well as liver; infants and toddlers undergoing rapid bone remodeling have benign transient ALP elevations, and the normal GGT (unaffected by bone) confirms it is not hepatobiliary.\n\nWhy not — Early alcoholic liver disease: Alcoholic disease would not occur in a toddler and would elevate GGT.  Acute viral hepatitis: Acute viral hepatitis would elevate aminotransferases, which are normal here.  Common-bile-duct obstruction: Duct obstruction would raise GGT along with ALP; GGT is normal here.  Acute liver failure with coagulopathy: Acute liver failure is defined by coagulopathy/high INR, not an isolated ALP.", "advanced"]]], [4, "Describe bilirubin, prothrombin time and albumin.", [["Regarding bilirubin nomenclature, which pairing is correct?", ["Direct = conjugated; indirect = unconjugated", "Direct = unconjugated; indirect = conjugated", "Direct and indirect both refer to conjugated bilirubin", "Total bilirubin equals direct minus indirect", "Indirect bilirubin is the form excreted directly into bile"], 0, "Direct bilirubin is the conjugated fraction (direct hyperbilirubinemia); indirect is the unconjugated fraction. Bilirubin arrives unconjugated and, once conjugated, goes 'directly' out into the biliary system.\n\nWhy not — Direct = unconjugated; indirect = conjugated: This reverses the definitions; direct is conjugated, not unconjugated.  Direct and indirect both refer to conjugated bilirubin: Direct and indirect are different fractions (conjugated vs unconjugated).  Total bilirubin equals direct minus indirect: Total equals direct PLUS indirect, not the difference.  Indirect bilirubin is the form excreted directly into bile: It is the conjugated (direct) form that is excreted into bile.", "basic"], ["In significant liver disease, what happens to serum albumin and to PT/INR, and why does PT/INR move in that direction?", ["Albumin falls and PT/INR rises, because fewer clotting factors are made so clotting takes longer", "Albumin rises and PT/INR falls, because the liver overproduces proteins", "Both albumin and PT/INR fall together", "Both albumin and PT/INR rise together", "Albumin falls and PT/INR falls, because clotting speeds up"], 0, "The liver makes albumin and clotting factors. In liver disease albumin falls (often chronic disease); PT/INR rises because fewer coagulation factors are synthesized, so it takes longer to clot - and PT measures the time to clot.\n\nWhy not — Albumin rises and PT/INR falls, because the liver overproduces proteins: A failing liver makes LESS protein, so albumin falls and PT/INR rises.  Both albumin and PT/INR fall together: PT/INR rises (longer to clot), it does not fall with albumin.  Both albumin and PT/INR rise together: Albumin falls, not rises, in liver disease.  Albumin falls and PT/INR falls, because clotting speeds up: Clotting slows (PT/INR rises) when factors are deficient.", "basic"], ["A low serum albumin attributable to the liver most strongly suggests which tempo of liver disease?", ["More long-standing (chronic) liver disease", "Hyperacute injury within the first few hours", "A purely biliary obstruction with normal hepatocytes", "An isolated congenital hyperbilirubinemia", "A normal physiologic finding requiring no liver disease"], 0, "Because albumin turns over slowly, a low albumin from the liver usually indicates more long-standing (chronic) liver disease rather than an acute insult.\n\nWhy not — Hyperacute injury within the first few hours: Albumin's slow turnover means it does not drop within hours of an acute hit.  A purely biliary obstruction with normal hepatocytes: Pure biliary obstruction need not lower albumin if synthesis is intact.  An isolated congenital hyperbilirubinemia: Isolated hyperbilirubinemia does not lower albumin.  A normal physiologic finding requiring no liver disease: A liver-attributable low albumin is abnormal, signaling chronic disease.", "advanced"]]], [5, "Evaluate cases of patients who present with abnormal hepatic tests.", [["Two patients each have aminotransferases and alkaline phosphatase elevated. Patient X: AST/ALT ~2,000 with only a mildly elevated ALP. Patient Y: ALP markedly elevated with only mildly elevated aminotransferases. The patterns are, respectively:", ["X hepatocellular, Y cholestatic", "X cholestatic, Y hepatocellular", "Both hepatocellular", "Both cholestatic", "X infiltrative, Y isolated hyperbilirubinemia"], 0, "The pattern is named by which enzyme is disproportionately high: aminotransferases >> ALP is hepatocellular (hepatocytes more affected); ALP >> aminotransferases is cholestatic (bile ducts more affected). Both enzymes rise in each, but the dominant one defines the pattern.\n\nWhy not — X cholestatic, Y hepatocellular: This reverses the assignment; the aminotransferase-dominant case is hepatocellular.  Both hepatocellular: Patient Y is alkaline-phosphatase-dominant, i.e., cholestatic, not hepatocellular.  Both cholestatic: Patient X is aminotransferase-dominant, i.e., hepatocellular, not cholestatic.  X infiltrative, Y isolated hyperbilirubinemia: Neither vignette matches infiltrative or isolated hyperbilirubinemia.", "advanced"], ["On a rotation, you are asked how to tell whether a patient has acute liver FAILURE rather than just acute liver injury. The single best discriminator is:", ["An elevated INR/PT (failure causes coagulopathy; injury keeps a normal INR/PT)", "A markedly elevated AST", "A markedly elevated alkaline phosphatase", "A low GGT", "A normal bilirubin"], 0, "Acute liver failure is defined by coagulopathy (no pre-existing cirrhosis, illness <26 weeks); the best indicator is an elevated INR/PT. Acute hepatic injury keeps a normal INR/PT regardless of how high the AST/ALT or ALP run.\n\nWhy not — A markedly elevated AST: A high AST signals injury magnitude but does not declare failure.  A markedly elevated alkaline phosphatase: Alkaline phosphatase reflects cholestasis, not synthetic failure.  A low GGT: A low GGT is irrelevant to declaring failure.  A normal bilirubin: Bilirubin may be normal or elevated; it is not the discriminator.", "advanced"], ["A 45-year-old in acute hepatic failure shows FALLING AST and ALT but RISING total bilirubin and lengthening PT/INR. The correct interpretation is:", ["Poor prognosis - the liver may be too destroyed to release enzymes while its function (bilirubin handling, clotting) keeps worsening", "The patient is clearly recovering because the aminotransferases are improving", "A purely cholestatic process from a new bile-duct stone", "A laboratory error, since AST/ALT and bilirubin should always move together", "Isolated hyperbilirubinemia from a congenital defect"], 0, "Falling aminotransferases can mean either that acute damage has ceased OR that the liver is so destroyed that few hepatocytes remain to leak enzyme; the rising bilirubin and prolonging PT/INR show function is worsening, so this combination predicts a poor prognosis - not recovery.\n\nWhy not — The patient is clearly recovering because the aminotransferases are improving: Falling transaminases with worsening function signal destruction, not recovery.  A purely cholestatic process from a new bile-duct stone: A cholestatic stone would raise alkaline phosphatase, not produce this synthetic decline.  A laboratory error, since AST/ALT and bilirubin should always move together: The dissociation is real and clinically meaningful, not a lab error.  Isolated hyperbilirubinemia from a congenital defect: Isolated hyperbilirubinemia spares PT/INR, which are prolonged here.", "advanced"]]]]], [49, "Viral Hepatitis (Lec 49)", [[1, "Discuss the differential diagnosis of viral hepatitis", [["A 52-year-old has persistently abnormal liver enzymes and all viral hepatitis serologies are negative. Statistically, the single most common cause of abnormal liver function tests in the United States is:", ["MASLD (metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease)", "Chronic hepatitis C", "Hereditary hemochromatosis", "Autoimmune (lupoid) hepatitis", "Alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency"], 0, "MASLD (formerly NAFLD) is the #1 cause of elevated/abnormal LFTs in the US, driven by obesity, insulin resistance, and metabolic syndrome; it leads the non-viral differential of hepatitis.\n\nWhy not — Chronic hepatitis C: Chronic hepatitis C is common but is not the leading overall cause of abnormal LFTs in the US.  Hereditary hemochromatosis: Hemochromatosis is a metabolic cause but far less common than MASLD.  Autoimmune (lupoid) hepatitis: Autoimmune hepatitis (elevated ANA) is uncommon relative to MASLD.  Alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency: Alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency is a rare inherited cause, not the leading one.", "advanced"], ["On liver chemistries, a ratio of AST greater than ALT (AST > ALT) points most specifically toward which cause of hepatitis?", ["Alcoholic liver injury", "Acute hepatitis A", "Acute hepatitis B", "Chronic hepatitis C", "Autoimmune hepatitis"], 0, "AST > ALT is the alcohol pattern; viral hepatitis (and most non-alcoholic injury) instead shows ALT > AST. The slide pairs 'Alcohol (AST>ALT)' explicitly.\n\nWhy not — Acute hepatitis A: Hepatitis A shows ALT > AST, the viral pattern, not AST > ALT.  Acute hepatitis B: Acute hepatitis B shows ALT > AST.  Chronic hepatitis C: Chronic hepatitis C shows fluctuating, mildly elevated enzymes, not an AST-dominant ratio.  Autoimmune hepatitis: Autoimmune hepatitis is not defined by an AST > ALT ratio.", "basic"], ["A patient with hepatitis has an elevated alkaline phosphatase, and you need to confirm the alk phos is coming from the liver rather than bone. Which test confirms a hepatobiliary (liver) source?", ["GGT (gamma-glutamyl transpeptidase) or 5'-nucleotidase", "Serum calcium and phosphate", "Lactate dehydrogenase (LDH)", "Serum ferritin and iron-binding capacity", "Anti-tissue transglutaminase (anti-tTG)"], 0, "GGT and 5'-nucleotidase are liver/biliary-specific and are NOT found in bone, so an elevated alk phos accompanied by a high GGT or 5'-nucleotidase confirms a hepatobiliary (not bony) source.\n\nWhy not — Serum calcium and phosphate: Calcium and phosphate address bone/metabolic processes, not the source of alk phos.  Lactate dehydrogenase (LDH): LDH is nonspecific and does not localize alk phos to liver vs bone.  Serum ferritin and iron-binding capacity: Ferritin/IBC screen for hemochromatosis, not the source of alk phos.  Anti-tissue transglutaminase (anti-tTG): Anti-tTG screens for celiac disease, not the alk phos source.", "advanced"]]], [2, "Describe the etiology and epidemiology of viral hepatitis", [["A college student develops acute hepatitis after an outbreak traced to a contaminated food source at a restaurant. The virus is an RNA virus with no chronic carrier state. The most likely transmission route and virus are:", ["Fecal-oral route; hepatitis A virus (HAV)", "Parenteral/blood-borne route; hepatitis B virus (HBV)", "Parenteral/blood-borne route; hepatitis C virus (HCV)", "Sexual transmission; hepatitis B virus (HBV)", "Vertical mother-to-child route; hepatitis C virus (HCV)"], 0, "A food/water-borne outbreak with an RNA virus and no chronic state is hepatitis A, transmitted fecal-orally (person-to-person, contaminated food/water); HBV and HCV are blood-borne/parenteral and can become chronic.\n\nWhy not — Parenteral/blood-borne route; hepatitis B virus (HBV): HBV is parenteral/sexual/vertical, not a fecal-oral food-borne outbreak, and it can become chronic.  Parenteral/blood-borne route; hepatitis C virus (HCV): HCV is parenteral and usually becomes chronic, not a food-borne self-limited outbreak.  Sexual transmission; hepatitis B virus (HBV): Sexual HBV transmission does not fit a point-source food outbreak.  Vertical mother-to-child route; hepatitis C virus (HCV): Vertical HCV transmission does not explain a restaurant outbreak.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Describe the clinical features and lab findings of viral hepatitis", [["A patient's hepatitis B panel shows HBsAg positive, anti-HBc IgM positive, anti-HBs negative, and the illness began 6 weeks ago. This serologic pattern indicates:", ["Acute hepatitis B infection", "Chronic hepatitis B infection", "Resolved past hepatitis B infection", "Successful hepatitis B vaccination", "No evidence of hepatitis B exposure"], 0, "Acute hepatitis B = HBsAg positive plus anti-HBc IgM positive, with anti-HBs not yet present. The IgM core antibody marks recent (acute) infection within the first ~6 months.\n\nWhy not — Chronic hepatitis B infection: Chronic disease requires HBsAg positive for >6 months with anti-HBc IgG, not IgM.  Resolved past hepatitis B infection: Resolved infection would show anti-HBs positive, not HBsAg positive.  Successful hepatitis B vaccination: Vaccination gives anti-HBs positive with anti-HBc negative.  No evidence of hepatitis B exposure: Positive HBsAg and anti-HBc rule out no exposure.", "advanced"], ["During the 'serologic window' of acute hepatitis B, HBsAg has already fallen and anti-HBs has not yet risen. The single marker that 'fills the window' and remains detectable is:", ["Anti-HBc (hepatitis B core antibody)", "HBsAg (hepatitis B surface antigen)", "Anti-HBs (hepatitis B surface antibody)", "HBeAg (hepatitis B e antigen)", "HBV DNA quantitative PCR"], 0, "In the window period HBsAg has cleared but anti-HBs is not yet detectable; anti-HBc (core antibody) stays elevated and bridges the gap, so it is the marker that catches a window-period patient.\n\nWhy not — HBsAg (hepatitis B surface antigen): By definition HBsAg has already fallen in the window period.  Anti-HBs (hepatitis B surface antibody): Anti-HBs has not yet appeared during the window.  HBeAg (hepatitis B e antigen): HBeAg parallels HBsAg and is gone by the window, and it marks infectivity, not the window.  HBV DNA quantitative PCR: HBV DNA may be low/undetectable in the window and is not the slide's window marker (anti-HBc).", "basic"], ["A patient is found to have HBsAg positive for the past 8 months, anti-HBc IgG positive, and anti-HBs negative. This indicates:", ["Chronic hepatitis B infection", "Acute hepatitis B infection", "Resolved past hepatitis B infection", "Hepatitis B vaccination only", "A false-positive surface antigen test"], 0, "Chronic hepatitis B = HBsAg persisting beyond 6 months with anti-HBc IgG; critically, in chronic infection anti-HBs NEVER appears, which is exactly the negative anti-HBs seen here.\n\nWhy not — Acute hepatitis B infection: Acute infection would show anti-HBc IgM and would not persist beyond 6 months.  Resolved past hepatitis B infection: Resolved infection would be anti-HBs positive and HBsAg negative.  Hepatitis B vaccination only: Vaccination is anti-HBs positive with anti-HBc negative.  A false-positive surface antigen test: Persistent HBsAg with IgG core antibody is a true chronic pattern, not a false positive.", "advanced"], ["In acute hepatitis A, which immune marker is detected when symptoms start and indicates ACUTE infection?", ["Anti-HAV IgM", "Anti-HAV IgG", "HBsAg", "Anti-HBc", "HCV RNA"], 0, "Anti-HAV IgM is detected when symptoms begin and lasts 3-6 months, marking acute hepatitis A; anti-HAV IgG persists for years and provides lifelong immunity.\n\nWhy not — Anti-HAV IgG: Anti-HAV IgG indicates past infection/immunity, not acute disease.  HBsAg: HBsAg is a hepatitis B marker, not hepatitis A.  Anti-HBc: Anti-HBc is a hepatitis B core marker, not hepatitis A.  HCV RNA: HCV RNA is a hepatitis C marker.", "basic"], ["A patient with known hepatitis C has aminotransferases that are normal on one visit and mildly elevated (2x ULN) on another, with no clear pattern. The test that actually confirms chronic hepatitis C in this fluctuating picture is:", ["HCV RNA viral load", "Repeat AST and ALT until they normalize", "Anti-HCV antibody titer trend", "Alkaline phosphatase and GGT", "Serum bilirubin and PT/INR"], 0, "HCV transaminases characteristically fluctuate between normal and slightly elevated and do not correlate with histology, so they cannot establish chronicity; an elevated HCV RNA viral load is what confirms chronic hepatitis C.\n\nWhy not — Repeat AST and ALT until they normalize: AST/ALT fluctuate and may be normal, so they cannot confirm or exclude chronic HCV.  Anti-HCV antibody titer trend: Anti-HCV indicates exposure but does not distinguish active/chronic infection; RNA does.  Alkaline phosphatase and GGT: Alk phos and GGT are usually normal in chronic HCV and do not confirm it.  Serum bilirubin and PT/INR: Bilirubin and PT are usually normal until advanced disease and do not confirm chronicity.", "advanced"]]], [4, "Describe vaccination and post-exposure prophylaxis for HBV and HCV", [["A healthy adult who completed the hepatitis B vaccine series has serologies checked. The pattern expected in a vaccinated (not previously infected) person is:", ["Anti-HBs positive, anti-HBc NEGATIVE", "Anti-HBs positive, anti-HBc positive", "HBsAg positive, anti-HBc positive", "HBsAg positive, anti-HBs negative", "All hepatitis B markers negative"], 0, "Vaccination presents the surface antigen only, so a vaccinated person makes anti-HBs but NEVER makes anti-HBc; the negative core antibody is what distinguishes vaccinated from previously infected.\n\nWhy not — Anti-HBs positive, anti-HBc positive: Anti-HBs positive WITH anti-HBc positive is previously infected (resolved), not vaccinated.  HBsAg positive, anti-HBc positive: HBsAg positive indicates active infection, not vaccination.  HBsAg positive, anti-HBs negative: HBsAg positive is active infection, the opposite of vaccine-derived immunity.  All hepatitis B markers negative: All-negative means no immunity; a vaccinated person is anti-HBs positive.", "advanced"], ["Two patients are both immune to hepatitis B (anti-HBs positive). Patient X is anti-HBc positive; Patient Y is anti-HBc negative. The correct interpretation is:", ["X was previously infected (recovered); Y was vaccinated", "X was vaccinated; Y was previously infected", "Both were vaccinated", "Both have chronic active infection", "X is acutely infected; Y is in the window period"], 0, "Anti-HBc only appears after exposure to the actual virus. So among two immune patients, the anti-HBc-positive one (X) recovered from real infection, while the anti-HBc-negative one (Y) is immune from vaccine alone.\n\nWhy not — X was vaccinated; Y was previously infected: This reverses the rule; anti-HBc positivity means natural infection, not vaccination.  Both were vaccinated: Vaccinated patients are anti-HBc negative, so X (anti-HBc positive) was not vaccine-only.  Both have chronic active infection: Both are anti-HBs positive (immune), not chronically infected.  X is acutely infected; Y is in the window period: Both are immune (anti-HBs positive), neither is acute or in the window.", "advanced"], ["A pregnant woman is HBsAg positive. To prevent mother-to-child transmission, the newborn should receive, within 12 hours of delivery:", ["Hepatitis B immune globulin (HBIG) PLUS hepatitis B vaccine", "Hepatitis B vaccine alone, delayed to 1 month of age", "A course of entecavir for the newborn", "Avoidance of breastfeeding as the primary measure", "Hepatitis B immune globulin (HBIG) alone, no vaccine"], 0, "Within 12 hours of delivery the infant of an HBsAg-positive mother should get BOTH HBIG and the hepatitis B vaccine, which lowers the ~90% transmission risk by about 95%; breastfeeding is not a risk factor.\n\nWhy not — Hepatitis B vaccine alone, delayed to 1 month of age: Delaying the vaccine and omitting HBIG misses the critical <12-hour window.  A course of entecavir for the newborn: Newborn entecavir is not the prophylaxis; HBIG + vaccine is.  Avoidance of breastfeeding as the primary measure: Breastfeeding is NOT a risk factor, so avoiding it is not the answer.  Hepatitis B immune globulin (HBIG) alone, no vaccine: HBIG alone is insufficient; the vaccine must be given with it.", "advanced"], ["A patient asks why there is a vaccine for hepatitis B but not for hepatitis C, and what protects against hepatitis A. The best integrated answer is:", ["HBV and HAV have effective vaccines; HCV has NO vaccine, so HCV prevention relies on screening and treatment", "All three (HAV, HBV, HCV) have routine vaccines available", "Only HCV has a vaccine; HAV and HBV rely on immune globulin", "HAV has no vaccine; HBV and HCV are both vaccine-preventable", "None of the hepatitis viruses has a vaccine; all rely on prophylaxis"], 0, "HAV (Havrix/Vaqta; Twinrix dual) and HBV (including Heplisav) have effective vaccines, but there is NO hepatitis C vaccine, so HCV prevention depends on universal screening, harm reduction, and curative treatment.\n\nWhy not — All three (HAV, HBV, HCV) have routine vaccines available: There is no hepatitis C vaccine, so not all three are vaccine-preventable.  Only HCV has a vaccine; HAV and HBV rely on immune globulin: This is backwards; HCV is the one WITHOUT a vaccine.  HAV has no vaccine; HBV and HCV are both vaccine-preventable: HAV has effective vaccines, and HCV does not have one.  None of the hepatitis viruses has a vaccine; all rely on prophylaxis: HAV and HBV both have vaccines, so this is false.", "advanced"]]], [5, "Describe the treatment of acute viral hepatitis", [["An otherwise healthy young adult has uncomplicated acute viral hepatitis with mild symptoms and is tolerating oral intake. The mainstay of treatment is:", ["Supportive care - fluids, rest, and reassurance", "Immediate combination antiviral therapy", "High-dose corticosteroids", "Empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics", "Urgent liver transplantation"], 0, "Acute viral hepatitis is treated supportively - fluids, rest, reassurance, and time - because most cases are self-limited; antivirals/transplant are reserved for chronic disease or fulminant failure.\n\nWhy not — Immediate combination antiviral therapy: Routine antivirals are not indicated for uncomplicated acute viral hepatitis.  High-dose corticosteroids: Corticosteroids are not standard for acute viral hepatitis.  Empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics: Antibiotics do not treat a viral hepatitis.  Urgent liver transplantation: Transplant is reserved for fulminant failure, not mild uncomplicated disease.", "basic"], ["A patient with acute hepatitis B is being managed supportively as an outpatient. Which finding would mandate hospitalization (or transfer to a transplant center if fulminant)?", ["Coagulopathy (elevated PT-INR) or encephalopathy", "A transient rise in ALT to 1,500 U/L", "Mild fatigue and decreased appetite", "Anti-HBc IgM positivity on serology", "Low-grade fever during the prodrome"], 0, "Outpatient supportive care suffices for most acute viral hepatitis, but signs of hepatic dysfunction - inability to tolerate fluids, coagulopathy (elevated PT-INR), encephalopathy, or severe jaundice - mandate hospitalization, with transfer to a transplant center if fulminant.\n\nWhy not — A transient rise in ALT to 1,500 U/L: Transaminases of 1,000-2,000 are expected in acute hepatitis and alone do not require admission.  Mild fatigue and decreased appetite: Mild fatigue and anorexia are typical and managed supportively.  Anti-HBc IgM positivity on serology: Anti-HBc IgM simply confirms acute HBV; it is not an admission criterion.  Low-grade fever during the prodrome: A low-grade prodromal fever is expected and not an admission trigger.", "advanced"]]], [6, "Describe the management of chronic viral hepatitis", [["First-line oral therapy for chronic hepatitis B that meets treatment criteria consists of nucleos(t)ide analogs. The preferred agents are:", ["Entecavir and tenofovir", "Acyclovir and valacyclovir", "Sofosbuvir and ledipasvir", "Interferon-alpha and ribavirin only", "Amoxicillin and metronidazole"], 0, "Entecavir (Baraclude) and tenofovir (Viread/Vemlidy) are the preferred first-line nucleos(t)ide analogs for chronic hepatitis B; sofosbuvir/ledipasvir are HCV drugs and acyclovir is for herpesviruses.\n\nWhy not — Acyclovir and valacyclovir: Acyclovir/valacyclovir treat herpesviruses, not hepatitis B.  Sofosbuvir and ledipasvir: Sofosbuvir/ledipasvir are direct-acting antivirals for hepatitis C.  Interferon-alpha and ribavirin only: Interferon/ribavirin are older/HCV-era agents, not the preferred first-line oral HBV regimen.  Amoxicillin and metronidazole: Antibiotics do not treat chronic hepatitis B.", "basic"], ["Which of the following is an accepted criterion to START treatment for chronic hepatitis B?", ["HBV DNA level greater than 2000", "Any positive HBsAg regardless of other findings", "Anti-HBs positivity", "A single ALT value within the normal range", "Presence of anti-HAV IgG"], 0, "Treat chronic HBV when there is cirrhosis/advanced fibrosis, HBV DNA >2000, or AST >2x ULN; a HBV DNA >2000 meets that threshold. Mere HBsAg positivity without these criteria does not mandate treatment.\n\nWhy not — Any positive HBsAg regardless of other findings: HBsAg positivity alone, without cirrhosis/high DNA/elevated AST, does not by itself mandate treatment.  Anti-HBs positivity: Anti-HBs indicates immunity, not active disease needing treatment.  A single ALT value within the normal range: A normal ALT argues against meeting the AST >2x ULN criterion.  Presence of anti-HAV IgG: Anti-HAV IgG reflects hepatitis A immunity, irrelevant to HBV treatment criteria.", "basic"], ["Pan-genotypic direct-acting antiviral regimens for chronic hepatitis C achieve a cure in approximately what percentage of patients?", ["About 95%", "About 50%", "About 25%", "About 10%", "Cure is not achievable in hepatitis C"], 0, "Pan-genotypic regimens cure roughly 95% of hepatitis C; unlike HBV (suppressed, not cured), HCV is genuinely curable, though there is still no HCV vaccine.\n\nWhy not — About 50%: Modern regimens far exceed 50% cure.  About 25%: 25% reflects older interferon-era results, not current pan-genotypic cure rates.  About 10%: 10% drastically understates current cure rates.  Cure is not achievable in hepatitis C: Hepatitis C IS curable with direct-acting antivirals.", "advanced"], ["A patient with chronic hepatitis B has no cirrhosis on imaging and elastography. Why does this patient still need lifelong hepatocellular carcinoma surveillance?", ["HBV DNA integrates into the hepatocyte genome, so HBV can cause HCC even WITHOUT cirrhosis", "HCC only occurs in hepatitis B after cirrhosis develops", "Surveillance is needed only if the patient also has hepatitis C", "Antiviral therapy eliminates all future HCC risk", "HCC in hepatitis B requires concurrent alcohol use"], 0, "Unlike most causes of HCC, hepatitis B can cause hepatocellular carcinoma without cirrhosis because HBV DNA integrates into the hepatocyte genome and is directly oncogenic, so lifelong HCC surveillance is required regardless of fibrosis stage.\n\nWhy not — HCC only occurs in hepatitis B after cirrhosis develops: HBV is the exception - it reaches HCC even without cirrhosis.  Surveillance is needed only if the patient also has hepatitis C: HBV alone, via DNA integration, confers HCC risk; co-infection is not required.  Antiviral therapy eliminates all future HCC risk: Antivirals reduce but do not eliminate HCC risk, so surveillance continues.  HCC in hepatitis B requires concurrent alcohol use: Concurrent alcohol is not required for HBV-driven HCC.", "advanced"], ["The stated goals of treating chronic hepatitis B include all of the following EXCEPT:", ["Achieving sustained eradication that makes lifelong monitoring unnecessary", "Eliminating HBsAg and HBeAg", "Suppressing HBV DNA viral load", "Decreasing the long-term risk of cirrhosis", "Decreasing the long-term risk of hepatocellular carcinoma"], 0, "The goals are to eliminate HBsAg/HBeAg, suppress HBV DNA, and reduce cirrhosis/HCC risk - but treatment and HCC monitoring are LIFELONG because HBV is suppressed rather than cured, so 'eradication ending the need for monitoring' is NOT a goal.\n\nWhy not — Eliminating HBsAg and HBeAg: Eliminating HBsAg/HBeAg is an explicit treatment goal.  Suppressing HBV DNA viral load: Suppressing HBV DNA is an explicit goal.  Decreasing the long-term risk of cirrhosis: Decreasing cirrhosis risk is an explicit goal.  Decreasing the long-term risk of hepatocellular carcinoma: Decreasing HCC risk is an explicit goal.", "basic"]]]]], [50, "Hyperbilirubinemia (Lec 50)", [[1, "Differential diagnosis of hyperbilirubinemia", [["In bilirubin metabolism, which two enzymes (in order) break heme down to unconjugated bilirubin?", ["Heme oxygenase, then biliverdin reductase", "Biliverdin reductase, then heme oxygenase", "UDP glucuronyl transferase, then heme oxygenase", "Beta-glucuronidase, then biliverdin reductase", "Heme oxygenase, then UDP glucuronyl transferase"], 0, "Heme oxygenase opens heme to biliverdin (green); biliverdin reductase then reduces biliverdin to unconjugated bilirubin (fat-soluble). Blavo flagged these as the two enzymes 'you need to know.' UGT acts later, in the hepatocyte, to conjugate.\n\nWhy not — Biliverdin reductase, then heme oxygenase: The order is reversed: heme oxygenase acts first, biliverdin reductase second.  UDP glucuronyl transferase, then heme oxygenase: UGT conjugates bilirubin in the hepatocyte; it does not break heme down to biliverdin.  Beta-glucuronidase, then biliverdin reductase: Beta-glucuronidase deconjugates CB in the gut; it is not in this synthesis step.  Heme oxygenase, then UDP glucuronyl transferase: UGT is the conjugating enzyme, not the second heme-breakdown enzyme; that is biliverdin reductase.", "basic"], ["Which property correctly describes unconjugated bilirubin (UCB)?", ["Fat-soluble, albumin-bound, and not excreted in the urine", "Water-soluble, loosely bound, and readily excreted in the urine", "Non-toxic and unable to cross lipid membranes into tissues", "Produced only after UGT adds glucuronic acid", "Measured directly as the 'direct' bilirubin fraction"], 0, "Unconjugated bilirubin is fat-soluble, so it rides albumin in blood, crosses lipid membranes into tissues (and the brain), is toxic, and is NOT excreted in urine; it is the indirect fraction. Conjugated bilirubin is the water-soluble, urine-excreted, direct form.\n\nWhy not — Water-soluble, loosely bound, and readily excreted in the urine: Water-soluble and urine-excreted describes conjugated, not unconjugated, bilirubin.  Non-toxic and unable to cross lipid membranes into tissues: UCB is fat-soluble and toxic precisely because it crosses lipid membranes into tissues.  Produced only after UGT adds glucuronic acid: Glucuronidation by UGT produces conjugated bilirubin; UCB exists before that step.  Measured directly as the 'direct' bilirubin fraction: UCB is the indirect fraction; conjugated bilirubin is the direct fraction.", "basic"], ["On the three-tier (pre-/hepatocellular/post-hepatic) framework, a hemolytic anemia is classified as which type of jaundice?", ["Pre-hepatic", "Hepatocellular", "Post-hepatic", "Canalicular-transport defect", "Sinusoidal re-uptake defect"], 0, "Hemolytic anemia overproduces bilirubin before it reaches the liver, so the pathology sits upstream of the hepatocyte: it is pre-hepatic jaundice (an unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia). Hepatocellular sits at the liver; post-hepatic sits in the biliary tree.\n\nWhy not — Hepatocellular: Hepatocellular jaundice is liver-cell injury (alcohol, viral hepatitis), not upstream hemolysis.  Post-hepatic: Post-hepatic jaundice is biliary obstruction, downstream of the liver.  Canalicular-transport defect: A canalicular-transport defect is Dubin-Johnson, a conjugated disorder, not hemolysis.  Sinusoidal re-uptake defect: A sinusoidal re-uptake defect is Rotor, a conjugated disorder, not pre-hepatic hemolysis.", "basic"], ["Gilbert syndrome differs from Crigler-Najjar syndrome in the amount of UDP glucuronyl transferase present. Gilbert shows:", ["A reduced amount of the enzyme", "A complete absence of the enzyme", "A defective MRP2 canalicular transporter", "A conjugated rather than unconjugated rise", "A digenic SLCO1B1/SLCO1B3 transport defect"], 0, "Blavo drilled the discriminator: Gilbert is a DEFICIENCY (a reduced amount) of UDP glucuronyl transferase, giving a mild benign unconjugated rise that surfaces with stress; Crigler-Najjar is a total ABSENCE of the enzyme, giving severe disease. Both are unconjugated, autosomal-recessive UGT defects.\n\nWhy not — A complete absence of the enzyme: A complete absence of the enzyme is Crigler-Najjar, not Gilbert.  A defective MRP2 canalicular transporter: An MRP2 defect is Dubin-Johnson (conjugated), not the Gilbert enzyme deficiency.  A conjugated rather than unconjugated rise: Both Gilbert and Crigler-Najjar are unconjugated; the bilirubin is not conjugated.  A digenic SLCO1B1/SLCO1B3 transport defect: The digenic SLCO1B1/SLCO1B3 defect is Rotor, not Gilbert.", "basic"], ["A patient with an autosomal-recessive disorder cannot eliminate copper, which deposits in the liver, brain, and the iris (Kayser-Fleischer rings). The defective gene is:", ["ATP7B", "ABCC2", "UGT1A1", "SLCO1B1", "HFE"], 0, "Wilson disease is the autosomal-recessive copper-handling disorder caused by an ATP7B mutation; copper accumulates in liver, brain, and the corneal limbus (Kayser-Fleischer rings) — hepatolenticular degeneration. Blavo's anchor: 'when you think Wilson's, think copper.'\n\nWhy not — ABCC2: ABCC2/MRP2 is the Dubin-Johnson canalicular-transport defect, not a copper disorder.  UGT1A1: UGT1A1 underlies Gilbert/Crigler-Najjar (conjugation), not copper handling.  SLCO1B1: SLCO1B1 is a Rotor uptake transporter, not the Wilson copper gene.  HFE: HFE is hereditary hemochromatosis (iron), not Wilson disease (copper).", "advanced"], ["Which laboratory trio is characteristic of primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC)?", ["Diagnostic MRCP, positive p-ANCA, and inflammatory bowel disease", "Diagnostic MRCP, positive anti-mitochondrial antibody, and pruritus", "Elevated indirect bilirubin, low haptoglobin, and splenomegaly", "Black liver on biopsy and an inverted coproporphyrin ratio", "Absent gallbladder on ultrasound and an acholic stool"], 0, "Blavo flagged PSC as a favorite board topic: progressive inflammatory scarring/narrowing of bile ducts, diagnosed by MRCP, associated with p-ANCA autoantibodies and a history of IBD. Anti-mitochondrial antibody belongs to primary biliary cholangitis, not PSC.\n\nWhy not — Diagnostic MRCP, positive anti-mitochondrial antibody, and pruritus: Anti-mitochondrial antibody is the primary biliary cholangitis marker, not PSC's p-ANCA.  Elevated indirect bilirubin, low haptoglobin, and splenomegaly: Indirect bilirubin with low haptoglobin and splenomegaly points to hemolysis, not PSC.  Black liver on biopsy and an inverted coproporphyrin ratio: Black liver with inverted coproporphyrin is Dubin-Johnson, not PSC.  Absent gallbladder on ultrasound and an acholic stool: Absent gallbladder on ultrasound with acholic stool is biliary atresia, not PSC.", "basic"], ["A chronic CONJUGATED hyperbilirubinemia with a grossly BLACK liver on biopsy is caused by a defect in:", ["The ABCC2 gene / MRP2 canalicular transporter", "The SLCO1B1 / SLCO1B3 sinusoidal uptake transporters", "The UDP glucuronyl transferase conjugating enzyme", "The ATP7B copper transport protein", "Intestinal beta-glucuronidase deconjugating enzyme"], 0, "A black liver with conjugated hyperbilirubinemia is Dubin-Johnson syndrome — an autosomal-recessive defect of canalicular organic-anion transport from an ABCC2 mutation / MRP2 deficiency that blocks export of conjugated bilirubin from the hepatocyte. Blavo: 'black liver, you think Dubin-Johnson.'\n\nWhy not — The SLCO1B1 / SLCO1B3 sinusoidal uptake transporters: SLCO1B1/1B3 loss is Rotor syndrome, which has NO black pigment.  The UDP glucuronyl transferase conjugating enzyme: UGT defects give unconjugated disorders (Gilbert, Crigler-Najjar), not a black liver.  The ATP7B copper transport protein: ATP7B is Wilson disease (copper), not the Dubin-Johnson transporter.  Intestinal beta-glucuronidase deconjugating enzyme: Beta-glucuronidase deconjugates CB in the gut; it does not pigment the liver.", "advanced"], ["Rotor syndrome is best distinguished from Dubin-Johnson syndrome by the fact that Rotor:", ["Lacks the black liver pigment and is digenic", "Produces an unconjugated rather than conjugated hyperbilirubinemia", "Is caused by an absence of UDP glucuronyl transferase", "Carries a defective ABCC2 / MRP2 canalicular transporter", "Causes fatal neonatal kernicterus from high UCB"], 0, "Both are benign autosomal-recessive conjugated hyperbilirubinemias, but Rotor has NO black pigment and is digenic — needing defects in both SLCO1B1 and SLCO1B3 (chromosome 12p), a sinusoidal re-uptake problem — whereas Dubin-Johnson (ABCC2/MRP2 canalicular defect) gives the black liver.\n\nWhy not — Produces an unconjugated rather than conjugated hyperbilirubinemia: Both Rotor and Dubin-Johnson are conjugated, not unconjugated, disorders.  Is caused by an absence of UDP glucuronyl transferase: Absent UGT is Crigler-Najjar (unconjugated), not the Rotor transporter defect.  Carries a defective ABCC2 / MRP2 canalicular transporter: The ABCC2/MRP2 canalicular defect is Dubin-Johnson, not Rotor.  Causes fatal neonatal kernicterus from high UCB: Fatal neonatal kernicterus is a high-UCB problem (Crigler-Najjar I), not benign Rotor.", "basic"], ["A patient on probenecid for gout develops jaundice. The mechanism by which probenecid raises bilirubin is that it:", ["Competes with conjugation and reduces hepatic uptake", "Accelerates red-cell hemolysis within the spleen", "Obstructs the common bile duct with stones", "Destroys the canalicular MRP2 export transporters", "Inactivates colonic beta-glucuronidase in the gut"], 0, "Probenecid is on the impaired-hepatic-uptake list: while it inhibits uric-acid secretion (helping gout), it also competes with bilirubin conjugation and reduces hepatic uptake of bilirubin, producing an unconjugated rise — Blavo's image was 'the pain in your toe goes away, then you look yellow.'\n\nWhy not — Accelerates red-cell hemolysis within the spleen: Probenecid does not accelerate hemolysis; that is the increased-production mechanism.  Obstructs the common bile duct with stones: Probenecid is a transport/uptake issue, not a mechanical bile-duct obstruction.  Destroys the canalicular MRP2 export transporters: MRP2 destruction is the Dubin-Johnson lesion, not probenecid's action.  Inactivates colonic beta-glucuronidase in the gut: Probenecid does not act on intestinal beta-glucuronidase.", "advanced"], ["A child is born jaundiced; ultrasound shows an absent gallbladder, the stool is acholic (clay-colored), and the urine is dark. Integrate these findings to the diagnosis and its definitive surgery:", ["Biliary atresia, treated with the Kasai portoenterostomy", "Crigler-Najjar syndrome, treated with the Kasai portoenterostomy", "Dubin-Johnson syndrome, treated with liver transplant", "Physiologic neonatal jaundice, treated with phototherapy", "Choledocholithiasis, treated with cholecystectomy"], 0, "Biliary atresia is the congenital post-hepatic obstruction of infancy: an absent gallbladder on ultrasound, acholic (pale) stool because bile pigment never reaches the gut, and dark urine from conjugated spillover. Blavo flagged the Kasai portoenterostomy as the procedure 'you need to know.'\n\nWhy not — Crigler-Najjar syndrome, treated with the Kasai portoenterostomy: Crigler-Najjar is an unconjugated enzyme-absence disorder, not a surgical biliary atresia.  Dubin-Johnson syndrome, treated with liver transplant: Dubin-Johnson is a benign conjugated disorder, not an absent-gallbladder surgical lesion.  Physiologic neonatal jaundice, treated with phototherapy: Physiologic neonatal jaundice is self-limited with a normal gallbladder, not acholic-stool atresia.  Choledocholithiasis, treated with cholecystectomy: Choledocholithiasis is an adult stone in the duct, not a congenital absent gallbladder.", "advanced"]]], [2, "Clinical implications of jaundice", [["Yellow discoloration of the sclera (scleral icterus) appears because unconjugated bilirubin is:", ["Fat-soluble and crosses lipid membranes into scleral tissue", "Water-soluble and filtered into the aqueous humor", "Bound tightly to albumin and trapped in blood", "Deposited only after conjugation by the liver", "Actively pumped into the eye by MRP2"], 0, "Scleral icterus is the first clinical tell of jaundice because unconjugated bilirubin is fat-soluble, so it crosses lipid membranes and stains tissues — the sclera being a sensitive, easily inspected site. The yellow pigment in the eye is fat-soluble UCB that successfully entered cells.\n\nWhy not — Water-soluble and filtered into the aqueous humor: It is UCB's fat-solubility, not water-solubility/filtration, that stains the sclera.  Bound tightly to albumin and trapped in blood: UCB rides albumin but dissociates and enters tissues; it is not trapped in blood.  Deposited only after conjugation by the liver: Scleral staining reflects fat-soluble UCB; it does not require prior conjugation.  Actively pumped into the eye by MRP2: MRP2 pumps CB into bile in the liver; it does not transport bilirubin into the eye.", "basic"], ["On the fractionation rule taught for the workup, an isolated rise in INDIRECT bilirubin (with a normal direct fraction) indicates:", ["Unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia", "Conjugated hyperbilirubinemia", "A pure biliary obstruction", "Dubin-Johnson syndrome", "Primary sclerosing cholangitis"], 0, "In the fractionation rule, indirect bilirubin is the predominant elevation in UNCONJUGATED hyperbilirubinemia; in CONJUGATED hyperbilirubinemia both direct AND indirect rise (some unconjugated precedes conjugation). So an isolated indirect rise points to an unconjugated process.\n\nWhy not — Conjugated hyperbilirubinemia: Conjugated hyperbilirubinemia elevates BOTH direct and indirect, not indirect alone.  A pure biliary obstruction: Biliary obstruction is a conjugated process and raises the direct fraction too.  Dubin-Johnson syndrome: Dubin-Johnson is a conjugated disorder, so its direct fraction is elevated.  Primary sclerosing cholangitis: PSC is an obstructive/conjugated process, not an isolated indirect rise.", "basic"], ["A jaundiced patient has prominent dilated veins radiating across the abdominal wall. This sign and its usual underlying cause are:", ["Caput medusae, from portal hypertension in cirrhosis", "Spider angiomas, from acute biliary tract obstruction", "Palmar erythema, from a chronic hemolytic anemia", "Courvoisier's sign, from an obstructing cystic-duct gallstone", "Xanthomas, from a chronically elevated serum bilirubin"], 0, "Caput medusae — prominent dilated veins on the abdominal surface — reflects portal hypertension in association with liver disease. The other signs are real jaundice-related findings but describe different lesions (spider angiomas, palmar erythema, the painless palpable gallbladder of Courvoisier, dermal xanthomas).\n\nWhy not — Spider angiomas, from acute biliary tract obstruction: Spider angiomas are small skin vessels of chronic liver disease, not abdominal-wall veins.  Palmar erythema, from a chronic hemolytic anemia: Palmar erythema is red palms in severe liver disease, not dilated abdominal veins.  Courvoisier's sign, from an obstructing cystic-duct gallstone: Courvoisier's sign is a painless palpable gallbladder, not abdominal-wall veins.  Xanthomas, from a chronically elevated serum bilirubin: Xanthomas are dermal cholesterol/fat deposits, not portal-hypertension veins.", "advanced"], ["Which laboratory test is the MORE specific marker for biliary obstruction in the hyperbilirubinemia workup?", ["Gamma-glutamyl transferase", "Haptoglobin", "Prothrombin time and INR", "Aspartate aminotransferase", "Albumin"], 0, "Among the additional tests, gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) is the more specific marker for biliary obstruction. Haptoglobin helps diagnose hemolytic anemias; PT/INR and albumin reflect synthetic function; AST is a nonspecific transaminase.\n\nWhy not — Haptoglobin: Haptoglobin helps diagnose hemolytic anemias, not biliary obstruction.  Prothrombin time and INR: PT/INR reflects hepatic synthetic function, not biliary obstruction specifically.  Aspartate aminotransferase: AST is a nonspecific aminotransferase, not a biliary-obstruction marker.  Albumin: Albumin reflects synthetic function, not biliary obstruction.", "basic"], ["A jaundiced patient with right-upper-quadrant pain has an isolated INDIRECT bilirubin rise, splenomegaly, and a low haptoglobin. Integrate these into the most likely mechanism:", ["A pre-hepatic hemolytic process overproducing bilirubin", "A post-hepatic obstruction of the common bile duct", "A canalicular MRP2 transport defect, Dubin-Johnson", "Acute viral hepatocellular injury with mixed bilirubin", "Intrahepatic cholestasis of primary biliary cholangitis"], 0, "An isolated indirect (unconjugated) rise with splenomegaly and a low haptoglobin is the hemolysis signature: red-cell destruction overproduces bilirubin (pre-hepatic), the overworked spleen enlarges, and haptoglobin is consumed binding free hemoglobin. Obstructive and Dubin-Johnson pictures would raise the direct fraction.\n\nWhy not — A post-hepatic obstruction of the common bile duct: A bile-duct obstruction is conjugated and raises the DIRECT fraction, not isolated indirect.  A canalicular MRP2 transport defect, Dubin-Johnson: Dubin-Johnson is a conjugated disorder; it would not give an isolated indirect rise.  Acute viral hepatocellular injury with mixed bilirubin: Hepatocellular injury gives a mixed (direct + indirect) rise, not isolated indirect with low haptoglobin.  Intrahepatic cholestasis of primary biliary cholangitis: PBC is an intrahepatic cholestatic/conjugated process, not pre-hepatic hemolysis.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Discuss the causes and treatments for neonatal hyperbilirubinemia", [["Kernicterus, the feared complication of severe neonatal unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia, is best described as:", ["Bilirubin encephalopathy from fat-soluble UCB entering the brain", "A reversible scleral yellowing that fades with feeding", "Conjugated bilirubin deposition within the renal tubules", "Black pigmentation of the liver seen on biopsy", "Bile-duct scarring diagnosed by an MRCP scan"], 0, "Kernicterus is life-threatening bilirubin encephalopathy: because unconjugated bilirubin is fat-soluble, a high neonatal load crosses the blood-brain barrier and is toxic to the brain. It is a neurologic emergency, not a benign or reversible scleral finding.\n\nWhy not — A reversible scleral yellowing that fades with feeding: Kernicterus is irreversible brain injury, not a benign fading scleral yellowing.  Conjugated bilirubin deposition within the renal tubules: It involves UCB in the brain (basal ganglia), not conjugated bilirubin in renal tubules.  Black pigmentation of the liver seen on biopsy: Black liver pigmentation is Dubin-Johnson, unrelated to kernicterus.  Bile-duct scarring diagnosed by an MRCP scan: Bile-duct scarring on MRCP is PSC, not the neonatal brain injury of kernicterus.", "basic"], ["Physiologic neonatal jaundice arises because, in the newborn, the:", ["Liver is immature and conjugates bilirubin poorly", "The MRP2 canalicular transporter is congenitally absent", "Maternal antibodies destroy fetal UDP glucuronyl transferase", "Bile ducts are blocked by a congenital gallstone", "Toxic copper accumulates in the immature liver"], 0, "Physiologic neonatal jaundice reflects two newborn realities: an immature liver whose conjugating enzymes are not yet fully active, plus high red-cell turnover. The result is a transient, self-limited unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia that resolves as the liver matures.\n\nWhy not — The MRP2 canalicular transporter is congenitally absent: An absent MRP2 transporter is Dubin-Johnson, not physiologic neonatal jaundice.  Maternal antibodies destroy fetal UDP glucuronyl transferase: Physiologic jaundice is enzyme immaturity, not maternal anti-enzyme antibodies.  Bile ducts are blocked by a congenital gallstone: A congenital bile-duct obstruction is biliary atresia, not physiologic jaundice.  Toxic copper accumulates in the immature liver: Copper accumulation is Wilson disease, unrelated to physiologic neonatal jaundice.", "basic"], ["Breast-FEEDING jaundice is distinguished from breast-MILK jaundice in that breast-feeding jaundice:", ["Occurs in the first week from poor oral intake", "Is caused by substances in the milk altering processing", "Reflects a congenital total absence of UDP glucuronyl transferase", "Is corrected only by the Kasai portoenterostomy surgery", "Produces a conjugated hyperbilirubinemia with a grossly black liver"], 0, "Breast-FEEDING jaundice occurs in the first week of life from inadequate intake/mild dehydration and is treated by increasing feeding frequency. Breast-MILK jaundice (later, transient) is attributed to substances in the milk that affect how the liver processes it and is managed by monitoring.\n\nWhy not — Is caused by substances in the milk altering processing: Milk-substance-mediated jaundice is breast-MILK jaundice, not breast-feeding jaundice.  Reflects a congenital total absence of UDP glucuronyl transferase: Absent UGT is Crigler-Najjar, not a breast-feeding-related jaundice.  Is corrected only by the Kasai portoenterostomy surgery: The Kasai portoenterostomy treats biliary atresia, not breast-feeding jaundice.  Produces a conjugated hyperbilirubinemia with a grossly black liver: Breast-feeding jaundice is unconjugated; the black liver belongs to Dubin-Johnson.", "basic"], ["The treatment that converts unconjugated bilirubin to a more water-soluble form so the newborn can clear it is:", ["Phototherapy by photo-isomerization with light", "The Kasai portoenterostomy", "MRCP-guided stone removal", "Anti-copper chelation therapy", "Exchange transfusion for hemolysis"], 0, "Phototherapy works by photo-isomerizing unconjugated bilirubin into a more water-soluble isomer the newborn can excrete without conjugation, heading off kernicterus in physiologic neonatal jaundice. The other options treat different problems (atresia, stones, copper, severe hemolysis).\n\nWhy not — The Kasai portoenterostomy: The Kasai portoenterostomy is surgery for biliary atresia, not a bilirubin photo-conversion.  MRCP-guided stone removal: MRCP-guided stone removal addresses obstruction, not neonatal UCB isomerization.  Anti-copper chelation therapy: Copper chelation treats Wilson disease, not neonatal unconjugated jaundice.  Exchange transfusion for hemolysis: Exchange transfusion is reserved for severe cases; phototherapy is the photo-conversion treatment asked about.", "basic"], ["Crigler-Najjar TYPE II retains partial UDP glucuronyl transferase activity, so its bilirubin can be lowered by an agent that induces the residual enzyme. That agent is:", ["Phenobarbital", "Ursodeoxycholic acid", "Rifampin", "Probenecid", "A copper chelator"], 0, "Crigler-Najjar TYPE II keeps partial UGT1A1 activity, so phenobarbital works — it induces the residual enzyme and lowers bilirubin (the milder, survivable form). TYPE I has complete enzyme absence, so phenobarbital does NOT help; it needs phototherapy plus liver transplant. Rifampin/probenecid raise bilirubin; they do not treat it.\n\nWhy not — Ursodeoxycholic acid: Ursodeoxycholic acid is a cholestasis agent, not the Crigler-Najjar type II inducer.  Rifampin: Rifampin impairs conjugation and RAISES bilirubin; it is not a treatment.  Probenecid: Probenecid competes with conjugation and RAISES bilirubin; it is not a treatment.  A copper chelator: Copper chelation treats Wilson disease, not Crigler-Najjar.", "basic"]]]]], [51, "Pathology of Tumors of the Liver (Lec 51)", [[1, "Discuss the etiological factors, morphology, and diagnosis of benign tumors of the liver and of hepatocellular carcinoma", [["Which lesion is the most common primary tumor of the liver?", ["Cavernous hemangioma", "Hepatocellular carcinoma", "Hepatocellular adenoma", "Focal nodular hyperplasia", "Cholangiocarcinoma"], 0, "Cavernous hemangioma is the most common primary tumor of the liver, typically a <=2 cm red-blue soft nodule under the capsule found incidentally on imaging and often mistaken for a metastasis. HCC is the most common primary liver CANCER, a different superlative.\n\nWhy not — Hepatocellular carcinoma: HCC is the most common primary liver CANCER, not the most common primary tumor overall.  Hepatocellular adenoma: Hepatocellular adenoma is a rare benign tumor, not the most common one.  Focal nodular hyperplasia: FNH is common but ranks below cavernous hemangioma as a primary liver tumor.  Cholangiocarcinoma: Cholangiocarcinoma is a malignancy and only ~1/6 of primary hepatic cancers.", "basic"], ["A 4 cm liver nodule has a central gray-white stellate scar from which fibrous septa radiate, and is composed of normal hepatocytes. The diagnosis is:", ["Focal nodular hyperplasia", "Cavernous hemangioma", "Hepatocellular adenoma", "Fibrolamellar carcinoma", "Nodular regenerative hyperplasia"], 0, "A central gray-white stellate scar with radiating fibrous septa, in parenchyma made of normal hepatocytes, is the signature of focal nodular hyperplasia (FNH) — a benign, poorly encapsulated nodule most common in women aged 30-50.\n\nWhy not — Cavernous hemangioma: Cavernous hemangioma is blood-filled endothelial caverns, not a stellate scar of hepatocytes.  Hepatocellular adenoma: Hepatocellular adenoma lacks the central stellate scar and carries molecular-subtype risk.  Fibrolamellar carcinoma: Fibrolamellar carcinoma is malignant, with oncocytic cells and lamellar collagen, not normal hepatocytes.  Nodular regenerative hyperplasia: Nodular regenerative hyperplasia is diffuse 1-3 mm nodules, not a single scarred mass.", "advanced"], ["Nodular regenerative hyperplasia of the liver is clinically important chiefly because it can cause:", ["Portal hypertension", "Fulminant hepatic failure", "Malignant transformation to HCC", "Kernicterus from bilirubin", "Acute intra-abdominal hemorrhage"], 0, "Nodular regenerative hyperplasia is diffuse 1-3 mm regenerative nodules covering the liver, NOT separated by fibrosis; by altering intrahepatic blood flow it can produce portal hypertension. It is a benign architectural change, not a malignant or hemorrhagic one.\n\nWhy not — Fulminant hepatic failure: It does not cause fulminant hepatic failure; the parenchyma is regenerative, not failing.  Malignant transformation to HCC: Malignant transformation is a beta-catenin-adenoma/HCC concern, not nodular regenerative hyperplasia.  Kernicterus from bilirubin: Kernicterus is unconjugated bilirubin in the basal ganglia, unrelated to this lesion.  Acute intra-abdominal hemorrhage: Intra-abdominal bleed from rupture is the hepatocellular-adenoma complication, not this one.", "basic"], ["The most feared acute complication of a hepatocellular adenoma, making it a surgical emergency, is:", ["Rupture with intra-abdominal bleeding", "Sudden malignant degeneration to angiosarcoma", "Obstruction of the common bile duct", "Spontaneous portal vein thrombosis", "Acute fulminant hepatic failure"], 0, "A hepatocellular adenoma can rupture and bleed into the abdomen, a surgical emergency; this risk (plus the malignant potential of the beta-catenin subtype) drives management. The other listed events are not the defining acute adenoma complication.\n\nWhy not — Sudden malignant degeneration to angiosarcoma: Adenomas can transform to HCC (beta-catenin subtype), not to angiosarcoma, and not acutely.  Obstruction of the common bile duct: Bile-duct obstruction is a cholangiocarcinoma/stone problem, not the adenoma emergency.  Spontaneous portal vein thrombosis: Portal vein thrombosis is not the characteristic adenoma complication.  Acute fulminant hepatic failure: Fulminant hepatic failure is not how an adenoma presents acutely.", "basic"], ["Which hepatocellular adenoma subtype shows loss of L-FABP expression on immunohistochemistry together with steatosis?", ["HNF1a-inactivated adenoma", "Beta-catenin-activated adenoma", "Inflammatory adenoma", "Fibrolamellar variant", "Focal nodular hyperplasia"], 0, "HNF1a-inactivated adenomas lose liver-type fatty-acid binding protein (L-FABP) on IHC and show steatosis — and steatosis is seen ONLY in this molecular subtype, making the L-FABP-loss/fat combination diagnostic.\n\nWhy not — Beta-catenin-activated adenoma: Beta-catenin adenomas show NUCLEAR beta-catenin on IHC, not L-FABP loss.  Inflammatory adenoma: Inflammatory adenomas overexpress CRP; they are not the steatotic, L-FABP-loss subtype.  Fibrolamellar variant: Fibrolamellar is a malignant HCC variant, not an adenoma subtype.  Focal nodular hyperplasia: FNH is a separate benign lesion with a stellate scar, not L-FABP loss.", "basic"], ["A 37-year-old male bodybuilder on long-term anabolic steroids has a 6 cm liver adenoma; IHC shows nuclear beta-catenin. The key implication is that this subtype:", ["Carries a very high risk of malignant transformation", "Is entirely benign and can be safely observed long term", "Shows steatosis and L-FABP loss as its feature", "Overexpresses C-reactive protein from JAK-STAT activation", "Regresses completely once the steroids are discontinued"], 0, "Nuclear beta-catenin (a CTNNB1 mutation) marks the beta-catenin-activated adenoma, which carries a VERY HIGH risk of malignant transformation and often shows dysplasia overlapping with HCC — so its presence is diagnostic and prompts surgery even without symptoms.\n\nWhy not — Is entirely benign and can be safely observed long term: This is the highest-risk subtype, the opposite of safely observed.  Shows steatosis and L-FABP loss as its feature: Steatosis with L-FABP loss is the HNF1a subtype, not the beta-catenin one.  Overexpresses C-reactive protein from JAK-STAT activation: CRP overexpression from IL-6/JAK-STAT is the inflammatory subtype.  Regresses completely once the steroids are discontinued: Stopping steroids does not reliably reverse the malignant risk of this subtype.", "advanced"], ["Worldwide, hepatocellular carcinoma occurs most often on a background of chronic infection with which virus?", ["Hepatitis B virus", "Hepatitis C virus", "Epstein-Barr virus", "Human papillomavirus", "Cytomegalovirus"], 0, "More than 85% of HCC arises in sub-Saharan Africa and Southeast Asia where chronic hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection is endemic; in the US, HCV has driven the rise. Globally, HBV is the dominant viral cause.\n\nWhy not — Hepatitis C virus: HCV is the main driver of the US increase, but HBV dominates worldwide.  Epstein-Barr virus: EBV is linked to lymphomas and nasopharyngeal carcinoma, not HCC.  Human papillomavirus: HPV causes cervical and oropharyngeal cancers, not HCC.  Cytomegalovirus: CMV is not an established cause of hepatocellular carcinoma.", "basic"], ["Aflatoxin B1 promotes hepatocellular carcinoma through which specific molecular event?", ["A G-to-T transversion that inactivates p53", "Stabilization and nuclear translocation of beta-catenin", "Constitutive activation of the IL-6/JAK-STAT pathway", "Amplification of the HER2 growth-factor receptor", "Loss of the L-FABP fatty-acid binding protein"], 0, "Aflatoxin B1 is converted by hepatic CYP450 to an exo-8,9-epoxide that forms a guanine DNA adduct, producing a G-to-T transversion that inactivates p53; about 60% of aflatoxin-linked HCCs carry this p53 mutation.\n\nWhy not — Stabilization and nuclear translocation of beta-catenin: Beta-catenin stabilization is the CTNNB1 driver (~40% of non-HBV HCC), a separate pathway.  Constitutive activation of the IL-6/JAK-STAT pathway: IL-6/JAK-STAT activation is a third HCC driver, not the aflatoxin mechanism.  Amplification of the HER2 growth-factor receptor: HER2 amplification is a breast/gastric event, not aflatoxin-driven HCC.  Loss of the L-FABP fatty-acid binding protein: L-FABP loss defines the HNF1a adenoma subtype, not aflatoxin HCC.", "basic"], ["A 22-year-old with no cirrhosis has a single, well-circumscribed liver mass; histology shows oncocytic hepatocytes growing in cords separated by parallel lamellae of dense collagen. The diagnosis is:", ["Fibrolamellar carcinoma", "Conventional hepatocellular carcinoma", "Cholangiocarcinoma", "Hepatoblastoma", "Focal nodular hyperplasia"], 0, "Fibrolamellar carcinoma — an HCC variant in patients 20-40 with no gender predilection and a favorable prognosis — shows mitochondria-rich oncocytic hepatocytes in nests/cords interspersed with parallel lamellae of dense collagen, typically in a non-cirrhotic liver.\n\nWhy not — Conventional hepatocellular carcinoma: Conventional HCC usually arises on cirrhosis in older patients and lacks the lamellar collagen.  Cholangiocarcinoma: Cholangiocarcinoma is a desmoplastic glandular adenocarcinoma, not oncocytic hepatocytes.  Hepatoblastoma: Hepatoblastoma occurs under age 3 with fetal/embryonal cells, not this picture.  Focal nodular hyperplasia: FNH is benign with a central stellate scar of normal hepatocytes.", "advanced"], ["Which finding is considered the most important precursor lesion of hepatocellular carcinoma in viral hepatitis and alcoholic liver disease?", ["High-grade dysplastic nodules", "Cavernous hemangioma", "Focal nodular hyperplasia", "Nodular regenerative hyperplasia", "Bile-duct hamartoma"], 0, "Among HCC precursors (large-cell change, small-cell change, and dysplastic nodules), high-grade dysplastic nodules — typically once cirrhosis develops — are the most important precursors of HCC in viral hepatitis and alcoholic liver disease.\n\nWhy not — Cavernous hemangioma: Cavernous hemangioma is a benign vascular tumor, not an HCC precursor.  Focal nodular hyperplasia: FNH is benign and not a recognized HCC precursor.  Nodular regenerative hyperplasia: Nodular regenerative hyperplasia causes portal hypertension, not HCC progression.  Bile-duct hamartoma: Bile-duct hamartoma is not the flagged HCC precursor lesion.", "basic"], ["Integrate the epidemiology: a 28-year-old man in Southeast Asia with chronic HBV develops HCC. Compared with a 68-year-old American with HCV-related HCC, the younger patient is more likely to:", ["Have developed HCC in the absence of cirrhosis", "Require cirrhosis as a precondition for the tumor", "Have a fibrolamellar histologic growth pattern instead", "Show an aflatoxin-independent, p53 wild-type tumor", "Present with a benign, self-limited clinical course"], 0, "In high-prevalence HBV regions HCC commonly strikes at 20-40 years and about 50% of those cases occur WITHOUT cirrhosis, whereas in Western HCV-driven disease patients are usually over 60 with cirrhosis in ~90%. Cirrhosis is common background but not required for hepatocarcinogenesis.\n\nWhy not — Require cirrhosis as a precondition for the tumor: Cirrhosis is the ~90% Western/HCV pattern; the young HBV patient often has no cirrhosis.  Have a fibrolamellar histologic growth pattern instead: Fibrolamellar is young-patient and non-cirrhotic, but it is not the typical HBV-HCC pattern.  Show an aflatoxin-independent, p53 wild-type tumor: p53 status relates to aflatoxin exposure, not to this age/virus contrast.  Present with a benign, self-limited clinical course: HCC is aggressive with poor prognosis, never benign or self-limited.", "advanced"], ["A woman on long-term oral contraceptives has a liver adenoma; IHC shows preserved L-FABP, no nuclear beta-catenin, but strong C-reactive protein expression. The subtype and its driver pathway are:", ["Inflammatory adenoma driven by gp130/IL-6/JAK-STAT signaling", "HNF1a-inactivated adenoma driven by L-FABP loss", "Beta-catenin-activated adenoma driven by CTNNB1 mutation", "Fibrolamellar carcinoma driven by a DNAJB1-PRKACA fusion", "Focal nodular hyperplasia driven by an arterial malformation"], 0, "Strong CRP overexpression with intact L-FABP and no nuclear beta-catenin defines the inflammatory adenoma, driven by gp130 (an IL-6 co-receptor) mutations that activate JAK-STAT and upregulate acute-phase reactants like CRP; it is associated with NAFLD.\n\nWhy not — HNF1a-inactivated adenoma driven by L-FABP loss: HNF1a adenomas show L-FABP LOSS, but this tumor has preserved L-FABP.  Beta-catenin-activated adenoma driven by CTNNB1 mutation: Beta-catenin adenomas show nuclear beta-catenin, which is absent here.  Fibrolamellar carcinoma driven by a DNAJB1-PRKACA fusion: Fibrolamellar is a malignant HCC variant, not a CRP-positive adenoma.  Focal nodular hyperplasia driven by an arterial malformation: FNH has a stellate scar and is not defined by CRP overexpression.", "advanced"]]], [2, "Discuss the etiological factors, morphology, and diagnosis of cholangiocarcinoma", [["The majority (about 60%) of cholangiocarcinomas are perihilar (Klatskin) tumors, meaning they arise at the:", ["Confluence of the right and left hepatic ducts", "Ampulla of Vater within the duodenal wall itself", "Distal common bile duct near the pancreatic head", "Cystic duct that drains the gallbladder lumen", "Smallest peripheral intrahepatic bile ductules"], 0, "Perihilar (Klatskin) cholangiocarcinomas, ~60% of cases, sit at the confluence (junction) of the right and left hepatic ducts; intrahepatic tumors are ~10% and extrahepatic/distal common-bile-duct tumors ~20-30%.\n\nWhy not — Ampulla of Vater within the duodenal wall itself: The ampulla of Vater is the distal-most site, not the perihilar confluence.  Distal common bile duct near the pancreatic head: The distal common bile duct is the extrahepatic (~20-30%) location, not perihilar.  Cystic duct that drains the gallbladder lumen: The cystic duct drains the gallbladder and is not the Klatskin site.  Smallest peripheral intrahepatic bile ductules: The smallest ductules are the intrahepatic (~10%) territory, not perihilar.", "basic"], ["Chronic infection with which liver fluke, endemic in Southeast Asia, is a major risk factor for cholangiocarcinoma?", ["Clonorchis sinensis", "Schistosoma mansoni", "Echinococcus granulosus", "Entamoeba histolytica", "Ascaris lumbricoides"], 0, "Cholangiocarcinoma is 30-40 times more common in regions of Southeast Asia (e.g., Thailand) where liver-fluke infestation is endemic, most notably Clonorchis sinensis, which drives chronic bile-duct inflammation.\n\nWhy not — Schistosoma mansoni: Schistosoma mansoni causes portal/peri-portal disease, not the cholangiocarcinoma fluke association.  Echinococcus granulosus: Echinococcus causes hydatid cysts, not cholangiocarcinoma.  Entamoeba histolytica: Entamoeba histolytica causes amebic liver abscess, not bile-duct cancer.  Ascaris lumbricoides: Ascaris can obstruct the biliary tree but is not the classic cholangiocarcinoma fluke.", "basic"], ["On biopsy, cholangiocarcinoma characteristically appears as a well-to-moderately differentiated glandular adenocarcinoma set in:", ["A dense desmoplastic collagenous fibrous stroma", "Blood-filled caverns lined by endothelial cells", "Parallel lamellae of dense collagen bundles", "Sheets of small fetal and embryonal cells", "Normal hepatocytes surrounding a central scar"], 0, "Cholangiocarcinoma resembles adenocarcinoma — glandular/tubular structures lined by cuboidal-to-low-columnar epithelium set in a dense desmoplastic collagenous stroma, with frequent lymphovascular and perineural invasion.\n\nWhy not — Blood-filled caverns lined by endothelial cells: Blood-filled caverns describe cavernous hemangioma, not cholangiocarcinoma.  Parallel lamellae of dense collagen bundles: Lamellar collagen with oncocytic cells is fibrolamellar carcinoma, not cholangiocarcinoma.  Sheets of small fetal and embryonal cells: Small fetal/embryonal cells describe hepatoblastoma.  Normal hepatocytes surrounding a central scar: Normal hepatocytes with a central scar describe FNH.", "basic"], ["A 65-year-old from Southeast Asia with chronic raw-fish exposure presents with right-upper-quadrant pain and jaundice; biopsy shows malignant glands in a dense fibrous stroma with perineural invasion. The most likely diagnosis is:", ["Cholangiocarcinoma", "Hepatocellular carcinoma", "Metastatic colon adenocarcinoma", "Hepatic angiosarcoma", "Focal nodular hyperplasia"], 0, "The liver-fluke exposure (Clonorchis from raw fish), biliary-obstructive jaundice, and a desmoplastic glandular adenocarcinoma with perineural invasion together point to cholangiocarcinoma rather than the hepatocyte-derived or vascular tumors.\n\nWhy not — Hepatocellular carcinoma: HCC arises from hepatocytes and lacks the glandular, desmoplastic, fluke-linked pattern.  Metastatic colon adenocarcinoma: Metastatic colon cancer is possible but is not the fluke-associated primary biliary tumor described.  Hepatic angiosarcoma: Angiosarcoma is a vascular malignancy (vinyl chloride/arsenic), not a glandular adenocarcinoma.  Focal nodular hyperplasia: FNH is a benign lesion, inconsistent with malignant glands and perineural invasion.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Discuss the etiological factors, morphology, and diagnosis of metastatic tumors of the liver", [["The single most common form of malignant tumor found in the liver is:", ["Metastasis from a distant primary tumor", "Primary hepatocellular carcinoma of the liver", "Perihilar Klatskin cholangiocarcinoma of the bile ducts", "Childhood hepatoblastoma of the liver", "Hepatic angiosarcoma of vascular origin"], 0, "Involvement of the liver by metastatic cancer is by far more common than primary hepatic malignancy; about one-third of all carcinomas metastasize to the liver, making metastasis the most common malignant liver tumor overall.\n\nWhy not — Primary hepatocellular carcinoma of the liver: HCC is the most common PRIMARY liver cancer, but metastases outnumber all primaries.  Perihilar Klatskin cholangiocarcinoma of the bile ducts: Cholangiocarcinoma is only about one-sixth of primary hepatic cancers.  Childhood hepatoblastoma of the liver: Hepatoblastoma is a rare childhood tumor, not the most common malignancy.  Hepatic angiosarcoma of vascular origin: Angiosarcoma is rare; it is far less common than liver metastases.", "basic"], ["Which three primary cancers most commonly metastasize to the liver?", ["Colon, breast, and lung", "Prostate, thyroid, and bone", "Brain, kidney, and skin", "Stomach, ovary, and bladder", "Pancreas, esophagus, and larynx"], 0, "The most common primary cancers that metastasize to the liver are colon, breast, and lung; about one-third of all carcinomas reach the liver, which is why a liver mass with a known prior primary is presumed metastatic until proven otherwise.\n\nWhy not — Prostate, thyroid, and bone: Prostate spreads chiefly to bone; this trio is not the classic liver-metastasis set.  Brain, kidney, and skin: These are not the cancers most associated with liver metastasis.  Stomach, ovary, and bladder: These can involve the liver but are not the top three named primaries.  Pancreas, esophagus, and larynx: These are not the classic colon/breast/lung liver-metastasis trio.", "basic"], ["Grossly, metastatic carcinoma in the liver most characteristically appears as:", ["Few large lesions with central necrosis or multiple small nodules", "A single encapsulated nodule with a central stellate scar", "Diffuse 1-3 mm regenerative nodules entirely without fibrosis", "Blood-filled caverns lined by endothelium under the capsule", "A tree-like mass confined to the intrahepatic bile ducts"], 0, "Liver metastases typically present either as a few large lesions with central necrosis or as multiple small round lesions scattered throughout the organ — a multifocal pattern distinct from the solitary or diffuse patterns of the benign and primary lesions.\n\nWhy not — A single encapsulated nodule with a central stellate scar: A single nodule with a central stellate scar is FNH, a benign lesion.  Diffuse 1-3 mm regenerative nodules entirely without fibrosis: Diffuse 1-3 mm nodules without fibrosis describe nodular regenerative hyperplasia.  Blood-filled caverns lined by endothelium under the capsule: Blood-filled endothelial caverns describe cavernous hemangioma.  A tree-like mass confined to the intrahepatic bile ducts: A tree-like intrahepatic ductal mass is intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma.", "basic"], ["A 58-year-old with a malignancy treated a year ago now has hepatomegaly without jaundice; MRI shows multiple liver lesions of varying size, and biopsy cells look morphologically distinct from hepatocytes with atypical nuclei. Integrate these findings — the best diagnosis is:", ["Metastasis from the prior primary tumor", "New-onset focal nodular hyperplasia", "Late-onset hepatoblastoma of the liver", "A fibrolamellar HCC variant tumor", "Benign nodular regenerative hyperplasia"], 0, "A known prior malignancy, multiple varied-size liver lesions, and biopsy cells that are morphologically distinct from hepatocytes (i.e., not a hepatocyte-derived tumor) together indicate metastatic spread from the original primary — the most common malignant liver tumor.\n\nWhy not — New-onset focal nodular hyperplasia: FNH is a single benign nodule of normal hepatocytes with a scar, not multifocal non-hepatocyte cells.  Late-onset hepatoblastoma of the liver: Hepatoblastoma is a childhood tumor under age 3, not a 58-year-old presentation.  A fibrolamellar HCC variant tumor: Fibrolamellar cells resemble hepatocytes (oncocytic); these cells are distinct from hepatocytes.  Benign nodular regenerative hyperplasia: Nodular regenerative hyperplasia is a benign architectural change, not atypical metastatic cells.", "advanced"]]]]], [52, "Pathology of the Exocrine Pancreas (Lec 52)", [[1, "Discuss the etiological factors, pathogenesis, morphology, diagnosis, and complications of acute and chronic pancreatitis", [["On the Robbins pathogenesis flowchart, the three major initiating mechanisms of acute pancreatitis all converge on a single common event, which is:", ["Acinar cell injury that activates digestive enzymes", "Fibrosis and dropout of the pancreatic acini", "Calcified concretions within the pancreatic ducts", "Loss of the endocrine islets of Langerhans", "Glandular metaplasia of the ductal epithelium"], 0, "Duct obstruction, primary acinar cell injury, and defective intracellular transport are the three initiating mechanisms, but the Robbins CAUSES->MECHANISMS->LESIONS flowchart shows all three funneling into acinar cell injury and activation of digestive enzymes, which then autodigest the gland.\n\nWhy not — Fibrosis and dropout of the pancreatic acini: Fibrosis and acinar dropout are chronic-pancreatitis morphology, not the acute convergence point.  Calcified concretions within the pancreatic ducts: Ductal calcified concretions are a chronic, not acute-initiating, finding.  Loss of the endocrine islets of Langerhans: Islet loss is a late chronic-pancreatitis feature, not the acute convergence event.  Glandular metaplasia of the ductal epithelium: Ductal squamous/glandular metaplasia is a chronic change, not the acute mechanism.", "basic"], ["Which laboratory approach does the lecture recommend for the initial diagnosis of acute pancreatitis?", ["Serum lipase, which is preferred over amylase", "Serum amylase, which is preferred over lipase", "Both amylase and lipase together, routinely", "Serum alkaline phosphatase and GGT levels", "Fecal elastase as the first-line test"], 0, "The diagnosis slide states that testing both amylase and lipase is discouraged because it adds cost with only marginal benefit, and that lipase should be preferred over total and pancreatic amylase for the initial diagnosis given its greater specificity.\n\nWhy not — Serum amylase, which is preferred over lipase: Lipase is preferred over amylase, not the reverse; amylase is less specific.  Both amylase and lipase together, routinely: Testing both together is specifically discouraged as adding cost without value.  Serum alkaline phosphatase and GGT levels: ALP/GGT track biliary obstruction, not the primary diagnosis of pancreatitis.  Fecal elastase as the first-line test: Fecal elastase is a chronic-pancreatitis exocrine-insufficiency test, not the acute first-line.", "basic"], ["Which imaging study is identified as the radiographic test of choice for acute pancreatitis?", ["Contrast-enhanced computed tomography scanning", "Plain abdominal radiograph", "Transabdominal ultrasound", "Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography", "Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography"], 0, "Contrast-enhanced CT is the radiographic test of choice for diagnosing acute pancreatitis, with ductal calcifications being pathognomonic; the other modalities have supporting or biliary-specific roles but are not the lecture's test of choice.\n\nWhy not — Plain abdominal radiograph: A plain film can show calcifications but is not the test of choice for acute pancreatitis.  Transabdominal ultrasound: Ultrasound is useful for gallstones but is not the lecture's radiographic test of choice.  Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography: MRCP images the ducts but is not named as the test of choice here.  Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography: ERCP is therapeutic/diagnostic for ductal disease, not the first-line imaging choice.", "basic"], ["A patient with severe acute pancreatitis develops bruising in both flanks. This finding is termed:", ["Turner's sign", "Cullen sign", "Courvoisier sign", "Trousseau sign", "Leser-Trelat sign"], 0, "Turner's sign is flank ecchymosis, while Cullen sign is periumbilical bruising; both signal intraperitoneal or retroperitoneal hemorrhage from severe pancreatitis. The other eponyms belong to pancreatic carcinoma, not hemorrhagic pancreatitis.\n\nWhy not — Cullen sign: Cullen sign is periumbilical, not flank, bruising.  Courvoisier sign: Courvoisier sign is a painless enlarged gallbladder, not flank ecchymosis.  Trousseau sign: Trousseau sign is migratory thrombophlebitis, a carcinoma paraneoplastic sign.  Leser-Trelat sign: Leser-Trelat is eruptive seborrheic keratoses, not a hemorrhage sign.", "advanced"], ["Which noninvasive bedside test has a sensitivity and specificity greater than 90% for acute pancreatitis?", ["Urine trypsinogen-2 dipstick test", "Amylase-to-creatinine clearance ratio test", "Serum amylase level", "Serum alkaline phosphatase level", "Serum total bilirubin level"], 0, "The in-slide MCQ answer: the urine trypsinogen-2 dipstick has greater than 90% sensitivity and specificity for acute pancreatitis and is valued for being noninvasive at the bedside; the other listed tests are less sensitive or nonspecific.\n\nWhy not — Amylase-to-creatinine clearance ratio test: The amylase:creatinine clearance ratio is older and less specific, not the >90% test.  Serum amylase level: Serum amylase alone is less specific than lipase and is not the >90% dipstick answer.  Serum alkaline phosphatase level: ALP reflects biliary obstruction, not a >90% pancreatitis-specific test.  Serum total bilirubin level: Total bilirubin is nonspecific for pancreatitis diagnosis.", "basic"], ["A 48-year-old woman with a long history of alcohol use has epigastric pain, foul greasy stools, and calcifications across the pancreas on plain film. The single most common cause of her chronic pancreatitis is:", ["Long-term alcohol abuse", "Gallstones in the common bile duct", "Hereditary cationic trypsinogen mutation", "Hypertriglyceridemia", "Autoimmune IgG4-related pancreatitis"], 0, "The slide states in a red box that the most common cause of chronic pancreatitis by far is long-term alcohol abuse; the other entities cause chronic pancreatitis but are far less common than alcohol.\n\nWhy not — Gallstones in the common bile duct: Gallstones are the leading cause of acute pancreatitis, not the #1 chronic cause.  Hereditary cationic trypsinogen mutation: Hereditary trypsinogen mutations are rare causes of chronic pancreatitis.  Hypertriglyceridemia: Hypertriglyceridemia is a recognized but uncommon cause compared with alcohol.  Autoimmune IgG4-related pancreatitis: Autoimmune pancreatitis is uncommon and not the most common cause.", "advanced"], ["Which radiographic finding is described as virtually pathognomonic of chronic pancreatitis, present in up to 90% of alcoholic cases?", ["Pancreatic calcifications", "A peripancreatic fluid collection", "Diffuse glandular enlargement", "The double-duct sign", "Splenic vein thrombosis"], 0, "Pancreatic calcifications are virtually pathognomonic of chronic pancreatitis and develop in up to 90% of patients with alcoholic chronic pancreatitis, detectable on abdominal X-ray or CT; the other findings can occur but are not pathognomonic of chronic disease.\n\nWhy not — A peripancreatic fluid collection: A fluid collection suggests a pseudocyst, an acute complication, not the pathognomonic chronic finding.  Diffuse glandular enlargement: Diffuse enlargement is nonspecific and not pathognomonic of chronic pancreatitis.  The double-duct sign: The double-duct sign suggests an obstructing head mass, not chronic pancreatitis calcification.  Splenic vein thrombosis: Splenic vein thrombosis is a complication, not the pathognomonic chronic finding.", "basic"], ["Chronic pancreatitis differs fundamentally from acute pancreatitis in that chronic disease causes:", ["Irreversible destruction of exocrine and endocrine parenchyma", "Fully reversible interstitial edema with no scarring", "Isolated injury to the endocrine islets only", "A self-limited process that resolves without sequelae", "Hemorrhagic necrosis that heals without fibrosis"], 0, "Chronic pancreatitis is defined by prolonged inflammation with irreversible destruction of both exocrine and endocrine parenchyma and replacement by fibrosis; acute pancreatitis, by contrast, can resolve, and the professor stressed that once chronic disease develops there is nothing that can be done to reverse it.\n\nWhy not — Fully reversible interstitial edema with no scarring: Reversible edema without scarring describes mild acute, not chronic, disease.  Isolated injury to the endocrine islets only: Chronic disease destroys both exocrine and endocrine tissue, not islets alone.  A self-limited process that resolves without sequelae: Chronic pancreatitis is progressive and irreversible, not self-limited.  Hemorrhagic necrosis that heals without fibrosis: Chronic disease heals by fibrosis; it is not a fibrosis-free process.", "basic"], ["The weight loss, edema, and foul greasy stools of advanced chronic pancreatitis are best explained by:", ["Pancreatic exocrine insufficiency with fat malabsorption", "Acute hemorrhagic necrosis of the pancreas", "Obstruction of the common bile duct", "Paraneoplastic migratory thrombophlebitis from a tumor", "Systemic inflammatory response with capillary leak"], 0, "Progressive loss of acinar tissue produces pancreatic exocrine insufficiency: digestive enzymes fall, fat is malabsorbed (steatorrhea), and the resulting malabsorption causes weight loss and hypoalbuminemic edema; the other options describe acute or neoplastic processes.\n\nWhy not — Acute hemorrhagic necrosis of the pancreas: Hemorrhagic necrosis is an acute event, not the cause of chronic malabsorption.  Obstruction of the common bile duct: A CBD stone causes obstructive jaundice, not the steatorrhea of exocrine insufficiency.  Paraneoplastic migratory thrombophlebitis from a tumor: Migratory thrombophlebitis is a carcinoma paraneoplastic sign, not a malabsorption cause.  Systemic inflammatory response with capillary leak: SIRS capillary leak is an acute, not chronic-malabsorption, mechanism.", "basic"], ["Trace the complication chain in severe acute pancreatitis: activated enzymes destroy blood vessels and parenchyma, and the patient then develops a systemic inflammatory response. The next integrated consequence at the bedside is:", ["Multiorgan failure with DIC, ARDS, shock, and renal necrosis", "Slow fibrotic scarring with pancreatic calcifications over years", "An incidental cyst lined by glycogen-rich cuboidal epithelium", "Eruptive seborrheic keratoses across the trunk", "A painless palpable gallbladder from ductal obstruction"], 0, "Full-blown acute pancreatitis is a medical emergency: the systemic inflammatory response drives leukocytosis, DIC, ARDS, shock, and acute renal tubular necrosis, the cluster of systemic complications listed on the slide; the distractors are chronic, neoplastic, or paraneoplastic findings.\n\nWhy not — Slow fibrotic scarring with pancreatic calcifications over years: Fibrotic calcification is the chronic, slow course, not the acute SIRS cascade.  An incidental cyst lined by glycogen-rich cuboidal epithelium: A glycogen-rich cuboidal cyst is a serous cystadenoma, unrelated to acute SIRS.  Eruptive seborrheic keratoses across the trunk: Eruptive seborrheic keratoses (Leser-Trelat) are a carcinoma paraneoplastic sign.  A painless palpable gallbladder from ductal obstruction: A painless gallbladder (Courvoisier) is a carcinoma sign, not an acute SIRS event.", "advanced"]]], [2, "Describe the major pathological features of non-neoplastic and neoplastic masses of the pancreas", [["A pancreatic cystic lesion is multicystic, composed of small cysts lined by glycogen-rich cuboidal cells and filled with clear, straw-colored fluid. This lesion is:", ["Serous cystadenoma, which is benign", "Mucinous cystic neoplasm, frequently premalignant", "Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm", "A pseudocyst from prior pancreatitis", "Infiltrating ductal adenocarcinoma"], 0, "Glycogen-rich cuboidal cells, small (1-3 mm) cysts, and clear straw-colored fluid define a serous cystadenoma, which is benign and occurs about twice as often in women; the mucinous lesions instead have columnar mucin epithelium and thick mucin.\n\nWhy not — Mucinous cystic neoplasm, frequently premalignant: A mucinous cystic neoplasm has columnar mucin epithelium and thick mucin, not glycogen-rich cuboidal cells.  Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm: IPMN involves the ducts (main or side branch), not this serous glycogen-rich pattern.  A pseudocyst from prior pancreatitis: A pseudocyst lacks a true epithelial lining; it is a fibrous-walled fluid collection.  Infiltrating ductal adenocarcinoma: Ductal adenocarcinoma is a solid desmoplastic mass, not a clear-fluid serous cyst.", "advanced"], ["Which feature most reliably separates a mucinous cystic neoplasm from a serous cystadenoma?", ["Roughly one-third of mucinous neoplasms progress to invasive carcinoma", "Mucinous neoplasms arise almost exclusively in men", "Mucinous neoplasms contain clear, watery, straw-colored fluid", "Mucinous neoplasms are lined by glycogen-rich cuboidal cells", "Mucinous neoplasms are uniformly benign with no malignant risk"], 0, "The clean discriminator is malignant potential: about one-third of mucinous cystic neoplasm precursors progress to invasive carcinoma, whereas serous cystadenomas are benign; mucinous lesions also favor women, hold thick mucin, and carry KRAS/TP53/RNF43 mutations.\n\nWhy not — Mucinous neoplasms arise almost exclusively in men: Mucinous cystic neoplasms arise predominantly in women, not men.  Mucinous neoplasms contain clear, watery, straw-colored fluid: Clear straw-colored fluid is the serous, not mucinous, picture; mucinous fluid is thick mucin.  Mucinous neoplasms are lined by glycogen-rich cuboidal cells: Glycogen-rich cuboidal cells line the serous cystadenoma, not the mucinous neoplasm.  Mucinous neoplasms are uniformly benign with no malignant risk: Mucinous neoplasms are premalignant, not uniformly benign.", "basic"], ["Mutations in which set of genes are commonly found in mucinous cystic neoplasms of the pancreas?", ["KRAS, TP53, and RNF43", "APC, MLH1, and MSH2", "RB1, VHL, and WT1", "ATP7B, UGT1A1, and ABCC2", "BCR-ABL, JAK2, and FLT3"], 0, "Mucinous cystic neoplasms commonly carry mutations in KRAS, TP53, and RNF43 (slide-verbatim); the other gene clusters belong to colorectal/Lynch syndromes, other solid tumors, hepatic transporters, and hematologic malignancies.\n\nWhy not — APC, MLH1, and MSH2: APC/MLH1/MSH2 are colorectal and Lynch-syndrome genes, not mucinous-neoplasm genes.  RB1, VHL, and WT1: RB1/VHL/WT1 belong to retinoblastoma, von Hippel-Lindau, and Wilms tumors.  ATP7B, UGT1A1, and ABCC2: ATP7B/UGT1A1/ABCC2 are hepatic transporters/enzymes, not pancreatic cyst genes.  BCR-ABL, JAK2, and FLT3: BCR-ABL/JAK2/FLT3 are hematologic-malignancy drivers, not pancreatic cyst mutations.", "basic"], ["A pancreatic fluid collection arising weeks after an episode of acute pancreatitis, walled off by fibrous and granulation tissue without a true epithelial lining, is a:", ["Pseudocyst", "Serous cystadenoma", "Mucinous cystic neoplasm", "Side-branch IPMN", "Cystic neuroendocrine tumor"], 0, "A pseudocyst is the classic non-neoplastic pancreatic mass: a fluid collection that follows acute pancreatitis and is enclosed by fibrous/granulation tissue with no epithelial lining, which is why it is a pseudo-cyst rather than a true neoplastic cyst on the Mayo schematic.\n\nWhy not — Serous cystadenoma: A serous cystadenoma is a true neoplasm lined by glycogen-rich cuboidal epithelium.  Mucinous cystic neoplasm: A mucinous cystic neoplasm is an epithelial-lined premalignant neoplasm, not a post-inflammatory collection.  Side-branch IPMN: A side-branch IPMN is an intraductal mucinous neoplasm, not a non-neoplastic pseudocyst.  Cystic neuroendocrine tumor: A cystic neuroendocrine tumor is a true neoplasm, not a post-pancreatitis collection.", "advanced"], ["On the cystic-lesions schematic, an intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm (IPMN) is distinguished from a mucinous cystic neoplasm by the fact that an IPMN:", ["Involves the main or side-branch pancreatic ducts", "Is a solid, desmoplastic, gray-white mass", "Lacks any connection to the ductal system", "Is lined by glycogen-rich cuboidal epithelium", "Always arises in the tail without duct involvement"], 0, "An IPMN is an intraductal lesion, arising within the main pancreatic duct or its side branches (main-duct vs side-branch types on the Mayo schematic), whereas a mucinous cystic neoplasm forms a discrete cyst not centered on the duct; IPMNs are also mucin-producing, not glycogen-rich.\n\nWhy not — Is a solid, desmoplastic, gray-white mass: A solid gray-white desmoplastic mass is ductal adenocarcinoma, not an IPMN.  Lacks any connection to the ductal system: An IPMN is defined by its ductal connection, not by lacking one.  Is lined by glycogen-rich cuboidal epithelium: Glycogen-rich cuboidal lining is the serous cystadenoma, not an IPMN.  Always arises in the tail without duct involvement: IPMNs are intraductal and not restricted to a tail location without duct involvement.", "basic"]]], [3, "Discuss the etiology, pathogenesis, morphology, and carcinoma of the pancreas", [["A 68-year-old smoker has painless jaundice, weight loss, and a nontender palpable gallbladder. Integrate these findings: the tumor location and the gallbladder sign are, respectively:", ["Head of the pancreas, producing the Courvoisier sign", "Tail of the pancreas, producing the Trousseau sign", "Body of the pancreas, producing the Leser-Trelat sign", "Tail of the pancreas, producing the Courvoisier sign", "Head of the pancreas, producing the Trousseau sign"], 0, "About 60% of pancreatic adenocarcinomas arise in the head, where they obstruct the common bile duct and cause obstructive (painless) jaundice with a painless, enlarged gallbladder, the Courvoisier sign; Trousseau is migratory thrombophlebitis and Leser-Trelat is eruptive seborrheic keratoses.\n\nWhy not — Tail of the pancreas, producing the Trousseau sign: Tail tumors stay silent and do not cause a palpable gallbladder; Trousseau is thrombophlebitis.  Body of the pancreas, producing the Leser-Trelat sign: Leser-Trelat is seborrheic keratoses, not a gallbladder sign, and body tumors rarely give a palpable gallbladder.  Tail of the pancreas, producing the Courvoisier sign: The Courvoisier sign comes from a head tumor obstructing the CBD, not a tail tumor.  Head of the pancreas, producing the Trousseau sign: Trousseau is migratory thrombophlebitis, not the painless-gallbladder sign of a head tumor.", "advanced"], ["Which environmental factor is identified as the strongest influence on the risk of pancreatic carcinoma?", ["Cigarette smoking, which doubles the risk", "A diet rich in dietary fiber", "Moderate consumption of caffeinated beverages", "Occupational exposure to asbestos fibers", "Chronic residence at high altitude"], 0, "Cigarette smoking is the strongest environmental influence on pancreatic cancer risk and roughly doubles the risk; a high-fat diet has been implicated less consistently, and chronic pancreatitis and diabetes are additional risk factors, but smoking is the leading environmental driver.\n\nWhy not — A diet rich in dietary fiber: Dietary fiber is not the implicated factor; a high-fat diet is weakly implicated instead.  Moderate consumption of caffeinated beverages: Caffeine is not identified as a pancreatic-cancer risk factor in the lecture.  Occupational exposure to asbestos fibers: Asbestos is a mesothelioma/lung risk, not the strongest pancreatic-cancer factor.  Chronic residence at high altitude: High-altitude residence is unrelated to pancreatic-cancer risk.", "basic"], ["In the PanIN-to-carcinoma progression model, which molecular event is postulated to occur EARLIEST?", ["Activating mutation of the KRAS oncogene", "Inactivation of the TP53 tumor suppressor", "Loss of the SMAD4 tumor suppressor", "Inactivation of the BRCA2 tumor suppressor", "Amplification of the HER2/neu oncogene"], 0, "On the stepwise PanIN model, telomere shortening and KRAS activation occur early, CDKN2A/p16 inactivation in intermediate-grade lesions, and TP53, SMAD4, and BRCA2 inactivation in higher-grade (PanIN-3) lesions; KRAS is therefore the earliest of the listed events.\n\nWhy not — Inactivation of the TP53 tumor suppressor: TP53 inactivation occurs late, in high-grade PanIN-3 lesions, not earliest.  Loss of the SMAD4 tumor suppressor: SMAD4 loss is a late, high-grade event in the progression.  Inactivation of the BRCA2 tumor suppressor: BRCA2 inactivation is a late, high-grade lesion event.  Amplification of the HER2/neu oncogene: HER2/neu amplification is not the early driver in this pancreatic model.", "basic"], ["Which gross and microscopic description best fits an infiltrating ductal adenocarcinoma of the pancreas?", ["A firm, stellate, gray-white desmoplastic mass", "A soft, encapsulated, well-circumscribed yellow nodule", "A blood-filled cavernous spongy mass", "A thin-walled cyst filled with clear straw-colored fluid", "A fatty, lipid-rich lobulated mass"], 0, "Infiltrating ductal adenocarcinoma forms a firm, stellate, gray-white, poorly defined mass with an intense desmoplastic (fibrous) stroma, the property that makes the gland so hard; the distractors describe benign, vascular, serous-cystic, or lipomatous lesions.\n\nWhy not — A soft, encapsulated, well-circumscribed yellow nodule: A soft encapsulated nodule is not the infiltrative, ill-defined adenocarcinoma.  A blood-filled cavernous spongy mass: A blood-filled cavernous mass describes a hemangioma, not ductal adenocarcinoma.  A thin-walled cyst filled with clear straw-colored fluid: A clear-fluid thin-walled cyst is a serous cystadenoma, not a solid carcinoma.  A fatty, lipid-rich lobulated mass: A fatty lipid-rich mass is a lipoma, not desmoplastic adenocarcinoma.", "basic"], ["A patient with pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma has a rising serum CA 19-9 and is offered a Whipple procedure. Integrate the roles of these two: CA 19-9 and the Whipple procedure are used, respectively, for:", ["Following the treatment response and resecting the tumor surgically", "Screening the general population and palliating bone metastases", "Making the definitive tissue diagnosis and inducing chemotherapy", "Confirming the histologic grade and draining a pseudocyst", "Detecting early curable disease and bypassing the bile duct only"], 0, "CA 19-9 (with CEA) is a serum tumor antigen useful for following a patient's response to treatment but is nonspecific and lacks sensitivity, so it is not a screening or diagnostic test; the Whipple procedure (pancreaticoduodenectomy) is the surgical resection, potentially curative or palliative, while biopsy gives the definitive diagnosis.\n\nWhy not — Screening the general population and palliating bone metastases: CA 19-9 is nonspecific and not a screening test, and Whipple resects the tumor rather than only palliating bone metastases.  Making the definitive tissue diagnosis and inducing chemotherapy: Biopsy, not CA 19-9, gives the definitive diagnosis, and Whipple is a resection, not chemotherapy.  Confirming the histologic grade and draining a pseudocyst: CA 19-9 does not confirm histologic grade, and Whipple is a resection, not pseudocyst drainage.  Detecting early curable disease and bypassing the bile duct only: CA 19-9 lacks the sensitivity to detect early curable disease, and Whipple removes the tumor, not just a bile-duct bypass.", "advanced"]]]]], [53, "Medical Aspects of Pancreatic Disorders I & II (Lec 53–54)", [[1, "List the causes of acute pancreatitis", [["Together, which two causes account for roughly 90% of all cases of acute pancreatitis?", ["Gallstones and chronic alcohol use", "Hypertriglyceridemia and hypercalcemia together", "Post-ERCP injury and abdominal trauma", "Scorpion venom and biliary ascariasis", "Pancreas divisum and autoimmune pancreatitis"], 0, "Gallstones (including biliary sludge and microlithiasis) cause about 30-45% of cases and alcohol another 30-45%, so the two together reach roughly 90%; every other listed cause is a less common 'zebra' contributing only a small fraction.\n\nWhy not — Hypertriglyceridemia and hypercalcemia together: These are metabolic causes but each is uncommon; together they are nowhere near 90%.  Post-ERCP injury and abdominal trauma: Post-ERCP and trauma are recognized but individually minor iatrogenic/structural causes.  Scorpion venom and biliary ascariasis: Scorpion venom and Ascaris are classic but rare zebras, not the dominant pair.  Pancreas divisum and autoimmune pancreatitis: Divisum and autoimmune pancreatitis are uncommon structural/inflammatory causes.", "basic"], ["When hypertriglyceridemia is the cause of acute pancreatitis, the serum triglyceride level is classically above:", ["1000 mg/dL", "150 mg/dL", "200 mg/dL", "350 mg/dL", "500 mg/dL"], 0, "Hypertriglyceridemia-induced pancreatitis is classically associated with serum triglycerides greater than 1000 mg/dL; lower elevations are common in the population and are not the recognized pancreatitis trigger, which is why the test must be deliberately ordered.\n\nWhy not — 150 mg/dL: 150 mg/dL is roughly the upper limit of normal, far below the pancreatitis threshold.  200 mg/dL: 200 mg/dL is a borderline-high value, not the level that triggers pancreatitis.  350 mg/dL: 350 mg/dL is elevated but well under the classic >1000 mg/dL threshold.  500 mg/dL: 500 mg/dL is high but still below the >1000 mg/dL level taught for AP.", "basic"]]], [2, "Describe the history, clinical manifestations, and diagnosis of acute pancreatitis", [["By the lecture's diagnostic rule, a confident diagnosis of acute pancreatitis requires the presence of:", ["Any two of three — clinical presentation, enzymes >3x ULN, imaging", "All three together — clinical presentation, enzymes, and imaging findings", "Characteristic findings of pancreatitis on a contrast-enhanced CT scan", "A serum lipase elevated above the upper limit of normal alone", "Both an elevated amylase and an elevated lipase drawn together"], 0, "Acute pancreatitis is diagnosed when two of three criteria are met: a compatible clinical presentation, lipase or amylase greater than 3x the upper limit of normal, or characteristic findings on imaging; meeting any two suffices, which is why imaging is not strictly required.\n\nWhy not — All three together — clinical presentation, enzymes, and imaging findings: Only two of the three criteria are required, not all three simultaneously.  Characteristic findings of pancreatitis on a contrast-enhanced CT scan: CT findings are one optional criterion; the diagnosis can be made without imaging.  A serum lipase elevated above the upper limit of normal alone: Lipase must exceed 3x ULN, and one criterion alone does not make the diagnosis.  Both an elevated amylase and an elevated lipase drawn together: Pairing amylase and lipase is still just the enzyme criterion — one of the three.", "basic"], ["Why is serum lipase generally preferred over amylase for diagnosing acute pancreatitis?", ["It is more specific and rises earlier and lasts longer", "It rises only when amylase is normal, avoiding false positives", "It is produced exclusively by the pancreatic acinar cells", "It does not need to reach the 3x-upper-limit threshold", "It is the only enzyme that correlates with disease severity"], 0, "Lipase is more specific than amylase (amylase comes from both pancreas and salivary glands) and its elevation occurs earlier and persists longer, making it the better diagnostic enzyme; like amylase, however, it must still exceed 3x the upper limit of normal.\n\nWhy not — It rises only when amylase is normal, avoiding false positives: Lipase and amylase typically rise together; lipase is not gated on a normal amylase.  It is produced exclusively by the pancreatic acinar cells: Lipase comes from several GI tissues (pancreas, intestine, liver, gastric), not the pancreas alone.  It does not need to reach the 3x-upper-limit threshold: Lipase, like amylase, must still be >3x ULN to count toward the diagnosis.  It is the only enzyme that correlates with disease severity: Enzyme level does not track severity; Ranson criteria, not lipase, stratify severity.", "basic"], ["A patient with severe acute pancreatitis develops periumbilical bruising (Cullen's sign) and flank bruising (Grey-Turner's sign). Integrating these findings, they indicate:", ["Retroperitoneal bleeding from pancreatic necrosis, occurring in only ~3% of patients", "A specific finding that by itself confirms the diagnosis of acute pancreatitis", "Resolving disease, since these ecchymoses appear only as the inflammation subsides", "Biliary obstruction that mandates urgent ERCP before any other step", "A benign skin finding unrelated to the severity of the underlying disease"], 0, "Cullen's (periumbilical) and Grey-Turner's (flank) ecchymoses are nonspecific signs that suggest retroperitoneal bleeding in the setting of pancreatic necrosis; they appear in only about 3% of patients and mark severe disease rather than confirming the diagnosis on their own.\n\nWhy not — A specific finding that by itself confirms the diagnosis of acute pancreatitis: Both signs are nonspecific and do not by themselves confirm the diagnosis.  Resolving disease, since these ecchymoses appear only as the inflammation subsides: They mark severe ongoing/necrotizing disease, not resolution.  Biliary obstruction that mandates urgent ERCP before any other step: They signal retroperitoneal bleeding, not a biliary obstruction requiring ERCP.  A benign skin finding unrelated to the severity of the underlying disease: They are markers of severe necrotizing disease, not a benign incidental finding.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Discuss Ranson criteria for acute pancreatitis", [["Which value is one of the Ranson criteria assessed ON ADMISSION?", ["White blood cell count greater than 16,000", "A hematocrit drop of more than 10%", "Serum calcium less than 8 mg/dL", "Blood urea nitrogen rise of more than 5", "Estimated fluid sequestration of more than 6 liters"], 0, "The five admission Ranson criteria are age >55, WBC >16,000, glucose >200, AST >250, and LDH >350; the hematocrit drop, BUN rise, calcium <8, and fluid sequestration are all measured at 48 hours, not on admission.\n\nWhy not — A hematocrit drop of more than 10%: A hematocrit drop >10% is a 48-hour criterion, not an admission value.  Serum calcium less than 8 mg/dL: Calcium <8 mg/dL is assessed at 48 hours, not on admission.  Blood urea nitrogen rise of more than 5: A BUN rise >5 is a 48-hour criterion.  Estimated fluid sequestration of more than 6 liters: Fluid sequestration >6L is a 48-hour criterion.", "basic"], ["Using the Ranson mortality stratification, a patient who meets 7-8 criteria has an estimated mortality of approximately:", ["100%", "2%", "15%", "40%", "60%"], 0, "Ranson mortality climbs steeply with the score: 0-2 criteria carry about 2% mortality, 3-4 about 15%, 5-6 about 40%, and 7-8 criteria approach 100% mortality, which is why the count predicts who needs intensive care.\n\nWhy not — 2%: 2% mortality corresponds to the lowest band, 0-2 criteria.  15%: About 15% mortality corresponds to 3-4 criteria.  40%: About 40% mortality corresponds to 5-6 criteria.  60%: 60% is not a band on the table; 5-6 is ~40% and 7-8 is ~100%.", "advanced"]]], [4, "List the differential diagnosis and complications of acute pancreatitis", [["A pancreatic pseudocyst, a local complication of acute pancreatitis, is best characterized by which feature?", ["A wall of fibrosis/granulation tissue lacking epithelial lining, forming after ~4 weeks", "A true cyst lined by columnar mucinous epithelium forming within 48 hours", "An early peripancreatic fluid collection with no defining wall, usually self-resolving", "Sterile necrotic pancreatic tissue that always requires immediate surgical debridement", "A vascular outpouching of the splenic artery seen on contrast CT"], 0, "A pancreatic pseudocyst is a fluid collection enclosed by a wall of fibrosis or granulation tissue with NO epithelial lining (hence 'pseudo'); it requires about 4 weeks to form, occurs in roughly 10% of patients, and is observed if asymptomatic.\n\nWhy not — A true cyst lined by columnar mucinous epithelium forming within 48 hours: A pseudocyst has no epithelial lining, and it takes ~4 weeks rather than 48 hours.  An early peripancreatic fluid collection with no defining wall, usually self-resolving: That describes an early acute peripancreatic fluid collection, not a walled pseudocyst.  Sterile necrotic pancreatic tissue that always requires immediate surgical debridement: Sterile necrosis is observed and walled off, not debrided immediately.  A vascular outpouching of the splenic artery seen on contrast CT: A splenic-artery pseudoaneurysm is a vascular complication, not a pseudocyst.", "advanced"]]], [5, "Describe the treatment for acute pancreatitis", [["What is the first step in the management of a patient presenting with acute pancreatitis?", ["Aggressive isotonic crystalloid IV fluid resuscitation", "Empiric broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics for prophylaxis", "Immediate surgical debridement of the pancreas", "Total parenteral nutrition to rest bowel", "Urgent ERCP regardless of underlying cause"], 0, "Aggressive isotonic crystalloid fluid replacement (normal saline or lactated Ringer's) is the first step; given in the first 12-24 hours it reduces morbidity and mortality, whereas antibiotics, surgery, TPN, and routine ERCP are not first-line management.\n\nWhy not — Empiric broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics for prophylaxis: Prophylactic antibiotics are NOT recommended; they are reserved for proven infection.  Immediate surgical debridement of the pancreas: Invasive debridement is deferred ~4 weeks to let necrosis wall off.  Total parenteral nutrition to rest bowel: NJ enteral feeding is preferred over TPN, and neither is the first step.  Urgent ERCP regardless of underlying cause: ERCP is reserved for biliary obstruction, not a universal first step.", "advanced"], ["On rounds you are asked the classic board question about pain control in acute pancreatitis. Integrating the exam answer with the evidence, the best statement is:", ["Meperidine is the board answer, but unproven and morphine is fine", "Morphine is absolutely contraindicated, as it causes a fatal sphincter-of-Oddi spasm", "Meperidine is proven superior to morphine in large randomized controlled trials", "Opioids should be withheld entirely so as not to mask findings", "NSAIDs are strictly first-line and opioids are never indicated in pancreatitis"], 0, "The recurring board answer favors meperidine over morphine based on a supposed rise in sphincter-of-Oddi pressure, but no clinical studies actually support this and morphine can be given safely; the question tests recognition of an exam myth versus real-world practice.\n\nWhy not — Morphine is absolutely contraindicated, as it causes a fatal sphincter-of-Oddi spasm: Morphine is not contraindicated; the sphincter-of-Oddi concern is unproven.  Meperidine is proven superior to morphine in large randomized controlled trials: No randomized trials demonstrate meperidine superiority; that is the myth.  Opioids should be withheld entirely so as not to mask findings: Adequate analgesia is appropriate; opioids are not withheld to preserve the exam.  NSAIDs are strictly first-line and opioids are never indicated in pancreatitis: Opioids are commonly used for pancreatitis pain; NSAIDs are not the mainstay.", "basic"]]], [6, "Discuss chronic pancreatitis with regard to the etiology and clinical findings", [["The single most common cause of chronic pancreatitis is:", ["Long-term alcohol use", "Gallstones obstructing the duct", "Hypertriglyceridemia above 1000", "Hereditary cationic trypsinogen mutation", "Autoimmune IgG4-related pancreatitis"], 0, "On the etiology slide, alcohol accounts for ~70% of chronic pancreatitis (the #1 cause), idiopathic/tropical ~20%, and all other causes together ~10%. Notably, gallstone (biliary) pancreatitis is NOT listed as a cause of CHRONIC pancreatitis, even though it is a leading cause of ACUTE pancreatitis.\n\nWhy not — Gallstones obstructing the duct: Gallstones cause acute, not chronic, pancreatitis; biliary pancreatitis is not a listed CP cause.  Hypertriglyceridemia above 1000: Hypertriglyceridemia is in the ~10% 'other' group, not the leading cause.  Hereditary cationic trypsinogen mutation: Hereditary pancreatitis is a rare 'other' cause, not the most common.  Autoimmune IgG4-related pancreatitis: Autoimmune pancreatitis is one of the ~10% other causes, not the leader.", "basic"], ["In chronic pancreatitis, steatorrhea and clinically significant fat malabsorption do not appear until pancreatic function is reduced by more than:", ["90 percent", "25 percent", "50 percent", "10 percent", "75 percent"], 0, "Lamet stressed (repeatedly) that the exocrine pancreas has so much reserve that protein and fat deficiencies do not occur until more than 90% of pancreatic function is lost; only then does steatorrhea and clinically significant malabsorption surface.\n\nWhy not — 25 percent: Far too little loss; the pancreas tolerates much more before malabsorption appears.  50 percent: Half-function loss is still well within the gland's reserve; no steatorrhea yet.  10 percent: Only a small loss; nowhere near the threshold for malabsorption.  75 percent: Three-quarters loss is still below the >90% threshold for steatorrhea.", "basic"], ["A 52-year-old man with a long alcohol history has epigastric pain radiating to the back, greasy foul-smelling stools, weight loss, and new insulin-requiring diabetes. Integrate these findings: the diabetes and steatorrhea share which underlying mechanism?", ["Loss of over 90% of pancreatic parenchyma, destroying exocrine and islet tissue", "Acute autodigestion of the gland by prematurely activated intrapancreatic trypsin", "Gallstone obstruction of the common bile duct causing painless obstructive cholestasis", "A hormone-secreting islet-cell tumor driving a paraneoplastic endocrine syndrome", "An autoimmune attack on the pancreatic beta cells sparing exocrine function"], 0, "Chronic pancreatitis progressively destroys the gland; once more than 90% of parenchyma is gone, the exocrine acini fail (fat malabsorption/steatorrhea) AND the endocrine islets are destroyed (secondary, insulin-requiring diabetes). One advancing fibrotic process explains both deficits in this alcoholic patient.\n\nWhy not — Acute autodigestion of the gland by prematurely activated intrapancreatic trypsin: Trypsin autodigestion is the mechanism of ACUTE pancreatitis, not the chronic exocrine/endocrine loss here.  Gallstone obstruction of the common bile duct causing painless obstructive cholestasis: Biliary obstruction causes cholestatic jaundice, not steatorrhea plus secondary diabetes.  A hormone-secreting islet-cell tumor driving a paraneoplastic endocrine syndrome: A functioning NET gives a hormone syndrome, not this combined exocrine-plus-endocrine failure.  An autoimmune attack on the pancreatic beta cells sparing exocrine function: Type 1-style autoimmune diabetes spares the exocrine pancreas, so it cannot explain the steatorrhea.", "advanced"]]], [7, "Describe the uses of the various tests necessary to diagnose acute and chronic pancreatitis and tumors of the pancreas", [["Why are serum amylase and lipase NOT reliable for diagnosing chronic pancreatitis, and what is the test of choice for pancreatic exocrine insufficiency?", ["Enzymes may be elevated, normal, or low in CP; fecal elastase below 200 mcg/g is the test", "Enzymes are always above 3x ULN in CP; a serum CA 19-9 confirms the diagnosis", "Enzymes are always undetectable in CP; a 72-hour fast is the diagnostic test of choice", "Enzymes rise only with eating; an oral glucose tolerance test is the test of choice", "Enzymes are diagnostic only on tissue biopsy; serum gastrin is the test of choice here"], 0, "In chronic pancreatitis the gland is burned out, so serum amylase/lipase may be elevated, normal, or even low and cannot make the diagnosis (unlike acute, where they exceed 3x ULN). Fecal elastase has become the test of choice for exocrine insufficiency, with values below 200 mcg/g suggestive of pancreatic insufficiency.\n\nWhy not — Enzymes are always above 3x ULN in CP; a serum CA 19-9 confirms the diagnosis: A >3x ULN enzyme rule is for ACUTE pancreatitis; CA 19-9 is a cancer marker, not a CP test.  Enzymes are always undetectable in CP; a 72-hour fast is the diagnostic test of choice: Enzymes are not 'always undetectable'; the 72-hour fast diagnoses insulinoma, not exocrine insufficiency.  Enzymes rise only with eating; an oral glucose tolerance test is the test of choice: An OGTT screens for CF-related diabetes, not exocrine insufficiency.  Enzymes are diagnostic only on tissue biopsy; serum gastrin is the test of choice here: CP is not diagnosed on biopsy in routine practice, and serum gastrin tests for gastrinoma.", "basic"], ["A 68-year-old man with painless jaundice and weight loss has a CT showing dilation of BOTH the pancreatic duct and the common bile duct. This 'double duct sign' should prompt you to assume:", ["A pancreatic-head mass, i.e. pancreatic cancer", "Chronic calcific pancreatitis from longstanding alcohol use", "An insulinoma producing recurrent fasting hypoglycemia", "A benign serous cystadenoma of the pancreatic tail", "Cystic fibrosis with inspissated thick ductal mucus"], 0, "The double duct sign — simultaneous dilation of the pancreatic duct and the common bile duct on CT or MRCP — reflects a mass at the pancreatic head obstructing both ducts; Lamet said patients with that finding can be assumed to have pancreatic cancer, fitting this painless-jaundice presentation.\n\nWhy not — Chronic calcific pancreatitis from longstanding alcohol use: Chronic pancreatitis is marked by calcifications, not the obstructive double-duct dilation of a head mass.  An insulinoma producing recurrent fasting hypoglycemia: An insulinoma causes hypoglycemia, not ductal obstruction or painless jaundice.  A benign serous cystadenoma of the pancreatic tail: A serous cystadenoma is a benign cyst, not a head mass producing the double duct sign.  Cystic fibrosis with inspissated thick ductal mucus: CF gives diffuse tenacious mucus, not the focal head-mass double duct sign in an older adult.", "advanced"]]], [8, "List the various benign and malignant tumors of the pancreas", [["The most common malignant neoplasm of the pancreas — what people call 'pancreatic cancer' — is:", ["Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma", "Insulinoma, a pancreatic NET", "Serous cystadenoma", "Solid pseudopapillary neoplasm", "Acinar cell carcinoma"], 0, "Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma is the most common malignant pancreatic neoplasm and is what is generally meant by 'pancreatic cancer'; it is an exocrine (non-endocrine) tumor that accounts for the great majority of the ~95% exocrine share.\n\nWhy not — Insulinoma, a pancreatic NET: Insulinoma is the most common NET, but NETs are only ~5% of pancreatic tumors, not the leader.  Serous cystadenoma: Serous cystadenoma is a benign cystic tumor, not the most common malignancy.  Solid pseudopapillary neoplasm: Solid pseudopapillary neoplasm is a rare low-grade tumor of young women, not the leader.  Acinar cell carcinoma: Acinar cell carcinoma is a far less common exocrine malignancy than ductal adenocarcinoma.", "basic"], ["Which pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor is paired correctly with its hallmark clinical finding?", ["Glucagonoma — necrolytic migratory erythema with mild diabetes", "Insulinoma — watery diarrhea of 5 liters per day", "Gastrinoma — fasting hypoglycemia relieved by glucose", "VIPoma — recurrent peptic ulcers from excess gastrin", "Somatostatinoma — the Zollinger-Ellison ulcer syndrome"], 0, "A glucagonoma classically produces necrolytic migratory erythema (a cyclic erythematous rash with central healing) along with mild diabetes, stomatitis, anemia, and weight loss. The other options swap each tumor with the wrong hormone syndrome.\n\nWhy not — Insulinoma — watery diarrhea of 5 liters per day: Watery diarrhea ~5 L/day is the VIPoma (WDHA) syndrome, not insulinoma (which causes hypoglycemia).  Gastrinoma — fasting hypoglycemia relieved by glucose: Fasting hypoglycemia relieved by glucose is the insulinoma's Whipple triad, not gastrinoma.  VIPoma — recurrent peptic ulcers from excess gastrin: Peptic ulcers from excess gastrin define gastrinoma (Zollinger-Ellison), not VIPoma.  Somatostatinoma — the Zollinger-Ellison ulcer syndrome: Zollinger-Ellison is the gastrinoma syndrome, not somatostatinoma.", "basic"], ["A patient with recurrent peptic ulcers and diarrhea has a gastrin-secreting tumor. Integrate the anatomy: roughly 90% of these tumors are found within the gastrinoma triangle, whose boundaries are:", ["The cystic/common-bile-duct confluence, the 2nd-3rd duodenal junction, and the pancreatic neck-body junction", "The gastroesophageal junction, the pylorus, and the ligament of Treitz", "The splenic hilum, the tail of the pancreas, and the left kidney", "The ampulla of Vater, the gallbladder fundus, and the portal vein", "The uncinate process, the superior mesenteric artery, and the aorta"], 0, "The gastrinoma triangle, where ~90% of gastrinomas arise, is bounded superiorly by the confluence of the cystic and common bile ducts, inferiorly by the junction of the second and third portions of the duodenum, and medially by the junction of the neck and body of the pancreas — the slide's three labeled points.\n\nWhy not — The gastroesophageal junction, the pylorus, and the ligament of Treitz: These are upper-GI landmarks, not the cystic-duct/duodenal/pancreatic-neck points of the triangle.  The splenic hilum, the tail of the pancreas, and the left kidney: The splenic hilum and tail are the wrong region; gastrinomas cluster near the head/duodenum.  The ampulla of Vater, the gallbladder fundus, and the portal vein: The ampulla, gallbladder fundus, and portal vein are not the triangle's defined vertices.  The uncinate process, the superior mesenteric artery, and the aorta: The uncinate/SMA/aorta describe resectability landmarks, not the gastrinoma triangle.", "advanced"]]], [9, "Differentiate between exocrine and endocrine types of tumors", [["Which statement correctly differentiates exocrine from endocrine pancreatic tumors?", ["Exocrine tumors are ductal/acinar and ~95% of malignancies; endocrine NETs are ~5%", "Exocrine tumors secrete hormones into the blood; endocrine tumors drain enzymes through ducts", "Exocrine tumors are ~5% of malignancies; endocrine NETs make up the other ~95%", "Exocrine and endocrine pancreatic tumors are both islet-cell tumors that secrete insulin", "Exocrine tumors are uniformly indolent while endocrine tumors are uniformly rapidly fatal"], 0, "Exocrine glands secrete a substance out through a duct, so exocrine (non-endocrine) tumors arise from ductal/acinar cells and form ~95% of malignant pancreatic neoplasms; endocrine glands secrete a hormone into the bloodstream, so endocrine NET/islet-cell tumors are rare (~5%) and tend to be indolent.\n\nWhy not — Exocrine tumors secrete hormones into the blood; endocrine tumors drain enzymes through ducts: This reverses the definitions — exocrine drains through a duct; endocrine secretes hormone into blood.  Exocrine tumors are ~5% of malignancies; endocrine NETs make up the other ~95%: The percentages are flipped: exocrine ~95%, endocrine ~5%.  Exocrine and endocrine pancreatic tumors are both islet-cell tumors that secrete insulin: Only the endocrine islet-cell tumors secrete hormones; exocrine tumors are ductal/acinar.  Exocrine tumors are uniformly indolent while endocrine tumors are uniformly rapidly fatal: Exocrine ductal adenocarcinoma is aggressive, while NETs tend to be the more indolent ones.", "basic"]]], [10, "Describe cystic fibrosis of the pancreas", [["Cystic fibrosis of the pancreas is best characterized as:", ["A CFTR mutation on chromosome 7 causing the most common lethal autosomal-recessive disease in Caucasians", "An autosomal dominant disorder of the UGT1A1 bilirubin-conjugating enzyme gene on chromosome 2", "An X-linked recessive disorder of the ABCC2 canalicular membrane export transporter protein, MRP2", "An acquired pancreatic disease caused entirely by years of chronic, heavy daily alcohol intake", "A maternally inherited mitochondrial DNA disease of the pancreatic acinar cell genome"], 0, "Cystic fibrosis is the most common life-shortening autosomal recessive disease among Caucasians (1 in 2000-3000 live births), caused by mutations in the CFTR gene on chromosome 7 that impair chloride/bicarbonate transport and produce tenacious secretions, leading to pancreatic exocrine insufficiency.\n\nWhy not — An autosomal dominant disorder of the UGT1A1 bilirubin-conjugating enzyme gene on chromosome 2: UGT1A1/chromosome 2 autosomal dominant describes a hyperbilirubinemia syndrome, not CF.  An X-linked recessive disorder of the ABCC2 canalicular membrane export transporter protein, MRP2: CF is autosomal recessive (CFTR), not an X-linked ABCC2 transporter defect.  An acquired pancreatic disease caused entirely by years of chronic, heavy daily alcohol intake: CF is inherited, not an acquired alcohol-related disease.  A maternally inherited mitochondrial DNA disease of the pancreatic acinar cell genome: CF is a nuclear CFTR gene disorder, not a mitochondrial disease.", "basic"]]]]]];
// QUIZ_END
